<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-4     11-18 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT GOVERNOR OFFERS PATRIOTS A STADIUM IN HARTFORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Gov. John Rowland has offered to build a
stadium for the New England Patriots as part of a $350 million
development project in downtown Hartford. The team's owner, Robert
Kraft, who has failed to win a stadium deal from Massachusetts,
flew to Hartford this week and spent five hours discussing the deal
with Connecticut officials.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and the governor ate lunch at the executive mansion on
Monday and then, in an extraordinary scene, the two traveled to the
Legislative Office Building and went door to door to answer
questions from legislative leaders, according to people who were
there.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has expressed exasperation with his inability to make a
deal with the Massachusetts Legislature to replace the 27-year-old
Foxboro Stadium, about 30 miles south of Boston. And Rowland has
said his main goal for his second term, which begins in January, is
to revitalize the state's largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials said they were very concerned that their
proposal could be used as leverage by Kraft to win concessions from
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be the bridesmaid at a wedding consummated by
someone else,'' said one legislative leader who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. But state officials said that they saw hope
in the length of the talks, and in Kraft's stated desire to keep
the team in New England despite his apparent stalemate with
Massachusetts officials.
</P>
<P>
   Officials involved in the negotiations cautioned that the
specifics of the deal were not yet set. The $350 million price tag
could include a convention center and possibly other projects,
including a hotel, retail stores and parking.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms being discussed, the Patriots would not have to
pay any money upfront. The state would finance the construction
costs by selling bonds, and the Patriots would use the stadium
rent-free. In return, the Patriots would give the state 10 percent
of all revenue from tickets, parking and concessions. Legislative
and administration officials said that if an agreement were
reached, a special session of the state Legislature would likely be
held in December to vote on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One hurdle for Connecticut is that Hartford, which is 110 miles
from Boston, is a much smaller media market. Boston is the nation's
sixth-largest television market, with 2.2 million households, while
Hartford is 27th, with 910,000, according to Nielsen Media
Research. But state officials who have talked with Kraft said that
because many Patriots season ticketholders live in the suburbs, he
believes that the team would retain a significant part of its fan
base despite the move.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Unlike the National Football League's many mobile franchises,
the Patriots have remained closely identified with the Boston area,
where the team began in 1960 as an original member of the American
Football League. The team's logo is a minuteman _ one of the
Colonial soldiers who once drilled on Boston Common _ and the team
was called the Boston Patriots for its first 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials said the state is demanding an unusually
long commitment from the Patriots, perhaps as long as 30 years. The
planned open-air stadium would seat about 65,000 and sit at the
intersection of Interstates 84 and 91 in the heart of the state
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The site, Adriaen's Landing, on the Connecticut River, was the
planned home of a development project that would include a
convention center and a smaller stadium, for the University of
Connecticut. The university's Huskies would be expected to play in
the Patriots' stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate president pro tem, Kevin Sullivan, who has not
committed to the stadium deal, said a selling point is that it
would be part of a larger plan for Hartford. ``Taken alone, it
would be a gamble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the cost of any needed road improvements
were not included in the package offered to Kraft and would have to
be considered separately.
</P>
<P>
   One official who has discussed the matter with Kraft and spoke
on the condition of anonymity said the discussions appear to be
``on a very fast track'' and are likely to be resolved one way or
the other in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   Because several other big projects Rowland has championed have
fallen through, he has been deliberately playing down the
possibility of landing the Patriots until the deal is sealed,
according to officials who have talked to him.
</P>
<P>
   Just Tuesday morning on a Hartford radio station, Rowland said
of the possibility of luring the team: ``I'm not sure that it's
hope. It's a longshot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
