<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      11-18 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUARD HASN'T RULED OUT LONGSHOT RETURN TO HUSKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The 50-pound weight could have landed anywhere, but it
fell on Lester Towns' foot. Same with Arizona quarterback Ortege
Jenkins, who did his best Kerri Strug rendition to vault into the
Washington end zone in early October. People since have braced
themselves for another gravity-defying occurrence _ the possibility
of the first Husky losing record in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a UW football season full of unexplained phenomena, what's
next? Brock Huard shunning early NFL entry and returning for his
senior year?
</P>
<P>
   Well?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Lambright and his junior quarterback will huddle this
week to discuss that matter alone. They will repeat a conversation
shared 12 months ago, when Huard made the surprising decision to
stick with the college game one more year. This time, farewells are
fully expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty much a conclusion most people have drawn,
considering that a year ago he went through this and he has a
marriage coming,'' Lambright said. ``He's got a few things on his
schedule that would leave us thinking he would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard, as is his custom, would not discuss his future prospects
with the season in progress, other than to confirm that his wedding
to UW basketball player Molly Hills is set for May.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably don't want to hear this, but it's something I'll
think about after we win the bowl game,'' the quarterback said
Tuesday, counting on a victory Saturday over WSU. ``I've not
thought about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet teammates, left equally in the dark on this matter, wonder
if their three-year starter might actually be tussling with this
decision.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Huard isn't exactly closing out his Husky career on an
upbeat note, especially if a season-ending defeat to WSU and the
uncomfortable 5-6 ledger emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Second, some have inferred Huard would have been the third
quarterback drafted last April, behind Peyton Manning and Ryan
Leaf. There could be as many as a half-dozen players rated ahead of
him at the position now in what could be the best group of
quarterback prospects since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   And third, everyone _ his team, fans and media _ has assumed
he's out of here, practically making the decision for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I joke with him and say, `Are you leaving us,
Brock?''' said Towns, a junior linebacker whose play has been
severely curtailed since his offseason weightroom accident. ``He
just says, `No, no, no.' I wouldn't be surprised if he stayed, or
mad at him if he left. But why not use that extra year and become a
more dominant player?''
</P>
<P>
   Said junior defensive tackle Mac Tuiaea: ``To me, it's still a
mystery. He's a good friend, and it's his decision. But I think
Brock is thinking about those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Added junior flanker/kicker Joe Jarzynka: ``I wouldn't be
shocked if he stayed because I know what kind of competitor he is
and how bad it hurts him to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The matter is slightly more complicated this time. Whereas last
year there was a unanimous desire for Huard to return, some fans
have suggested publicly in letters to the editor and calls to the
talk shows that they have grown tired of him. Let the Marques
Tuiasosopo era begin, they say. Time for a different look, they
insist.
</P>
<P>
   Former Husky quarterback Chris Chandler felt this backlash, with
people clamoring for Cary Conklin when Rose Bowls didn't emerge.
Conklin, now the UW tight ends coach, also felt this, his once
loyal followers pining for more of Mark Brunell as Conklin finished
up. It's sort of like becoming enamored with a song when you first
hear it, then listening to it 100 more times and growing weary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that _ that's some fans,'' Huard said. ``The
opinions I care about are my coaches' opinions and teammates'
opinions; they're around here every day. That's what I'm worried
about.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Huard has his in-house backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marques is capable of leading this team, but I never get tired
of Brock with the dedication and leadership qualities he has,''
Tuiaea said. ``I'd welcome him back with open arms.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Tuiasosopo? If Huard came back, wouldn't that limit
the No. 2 quarterback, a big-play guy and the ultimate team player,
to just one year as a starter when his just reward should be more?
</P>
<P>
   Lambright has thought this over. He has a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up looking at: Do you redshirt him?'' Lambright said
of Tuiasosopo. ``He has that year. There's a way of getting your
cake and eating it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Huskies plan for a weekend in Pullman, Huard can't be
faulted if he ponders other destinations. Is it time to move on? Or
should he show his newfound Husky critics that he can help right
this slumping football program? He never forgot the abuse heaped on
that other Husky quarterback in the family, older brother Damon,
when his college career wound down. Should he silence them one last
time or simply wave goodbye?
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't go out on the winning kind of note he hoped; I know
for me, I'd like to come back,'' senior cornerback Nigel Burton
said. ``I wouldn't be surprised at either decision. It's a tough
one and nice one. Do I want to make a million dollars next year or
a couple million a few years from now?''
</P>
<P>
   Jersey No. 7 is still spoken for. His locker remains full. His
name tops the depth chart. But for how much longer?
</P>
<P>
   Lambright offers a weak smile when considering another year of
Huard at quarterback, as if to say he doesn't think it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything like that would be a tremendous bonus,'' the coach
said, ``and a big surprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
