   Latino leadership in the Valley is so stark that the Mexican
American Legal Defense Fund established a Hispanic leadership
development school earlier this year to boost the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   There is a severe underrepresentation of Hispanics in government
roles, said Rodolfo Perez, director of the five-year legal defense
fund program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's alarming. How can you properly serve a community without
proper leadership and representation?'' he asked. &QL; 
COMMUNITY SUFFERS
</P>
<P>
   The people who suffer the most from the lack of leadership are
members of the Latino community, observed Juanita Encinas, who has
had a firsthand view of the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandler community activist noticed the leadership dearth
shortly after Chandler police conducted a five-day immigration
sweep in July 1997, in which many U.S.-born Hispanics were pulled
aside and asked to prove their citizenship. Two children reported
being stopped on their way home from school and warned to carry
birth certificates. A professional golfer complained of being
barred from leaving a grocery store in an upper-middle-class
neighborhood. Teenagers said they were hauled out of a restaurant
by officers who demanded they produce proof of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Days after the raids, rallies were held. Community forums, too.
Calls were &UR; made for public apologies and police reprimands. But
Encinas says with the exception of Chandler City Councilman Martin
Sepulveda, no elected officials initially lent their support.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she says, national organizations, such as the National
Council for LaRaza and the legal defense fund, offered assistance
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge disappointment,'' says Encinas of Servicios para
la Comunidad, a non-profit social-services group in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for such disappointments. &QL; 
NUMBERS AREN'T THERE
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there simply aren't enough Latino elected
officials. Many place the blame on the high costs of campaigning,
low voter turnout in the Hispanic community and fragmentated voting
districts.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Joe Eddie Lopez, D-Phoenix, who is an advocate for
getting more Latinos in both political parties, acknowledged that
convincing Latinos to run for office is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Hispanics don't have the money to run for office or to
provide a living on the $15,000 a year salary we get,'' Lopez said.
``Campaign reform should help because money often is the deciding
factor in elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters this month approved measures that will bring about
campaign reforms in Arizona and will raise legislators' salaries to
$24,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the problem of unfavorable districts and low voter
turnout. Lopez contends that there are still too many districts
that divide the Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   El Mirage and Surprise, two towns with dominant Latino
populations, are in Republican U.S. Rep. Bob Stump's district.
Another Latino haven is in Tempe, also situated in a primarily
Republican district. &QL; 
VOTER APATHY
</P>
<P>
   But even if those issues were addressed, Hispanic voter apathy
hinders the chances of increased representation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, for instance, Phoenix City Council boundaries were
redrawn to increase the chances of Hispanic representation. But
partly because of low voter turnout among Latinos in 1995, an Anglo
candidate won the seat traditionally held by Hispanics. Court
decisions that led to the redistricting were based on the premise
that Hispanics and Blacks needed to be elected to government posts
or the minority groups would lose their political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is competition among ``old guard'' Latinos, the
newcomers and those who have fallen out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   Old guard politicos consist of those who broke open the Latino
political scene in Arizona &UR; _ people such as Alfredo Gutierrez, one
of the first Latinos to win a state Senate seat; U.S. Rep. Ed
Pastor; Al Pena and Tommy Espinoza, who are now with the National
Council for LaRaza, and others.
</P>
<P>
   They were the trailblazers, many community activists say. But
now, they are accused of failing to mentor new leaders and
obstructing those entering the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the rift between Hispanics during Jane Hull's campaign
for the governor's seat earlier this year. When entrepreneur Gary
Trujillo and business owner Ray Arvizu offered to stage a Democrat
Hispanic fund-raiser for Hull, some Hispanics tried to thwart their
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Pena, who ran for Phoenix City Council in 1996,
issued a letter to party officials warning them that Hull was
betraying fellow Republicans by accepting their help.
</P>
<P>
   Arvizu said it's those types of actions that discourage Latinos
from getting active in the political scene. &QL; 
MORE PLAYERS SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more people getting involved. Not the same people over
and over again,'' says Arvizu, who recently started taking a more
active role in politics. ``What's wrong with a bigger pool?''
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre was another person who fought the Latino power brokers
and won. She didn't get their blessing to run for state Senate, but
she made history by winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I have no idea why they wouldn't give me their
support,'' confesses Aguirre, adding that she has no time to ponder
the issue extensively. ``There's so much work for us to do. The
Latino community is grappling with so many issues. There's just no
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the need for more Hispanic representation in
government is the belief that members of other groups simply
haven't fought as hard to meet the needs of Latino citizens. Good
jobs, lower dropout rates, better approaches to immigration _ the
Hispanic community needs strong voices to seek those and other
goals, Latinos say.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To be more effective, Hispanics need to find a way to put on a
united front like other groups do, said John Garcia, an expert on
Hispanic politics at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lack of Hispanic representation has hurt Hispanics. You just
need to look at the numbers to see that no one's looking out for
the Latino community,'' he said. &QL; 
 &UR; Julie Amparano can be reached at 444-8394 or at
julie.amparano &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
