<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURA-RETURN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE VENTURA BACK ON BOULEVARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will move in the ``n'' California, ``a'' national and ``k''
editorial news files.) 
(EDITORS: Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It used to be simple covering politicians on the
run.
</P>
<P>
   You'd wait until their bodyguards jumped out of the dark
government sedans, then look for the shortest, frailest guy. That
was the politician.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura, the governor-elect of Minnesota, jumped out of
the back seat of his sedan in front of Jerry's Famous Deli on the
boulevard in suburban Studio City on Tuesday afternoon and stood
head and shoulders over his bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why the most popular bumper sticker in Minnesota
these days is ``Our Governor Can Beat Up Your Governor.''
</P>
<P>
   On an invite from the Daily News, the former pro wrestler swung
by his old stomping grounds and namesake _ Ventura Boulevard _ on
his way over to taping ``The Tonight Show'' with Jay Leno in
Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for Jesse and me to take a walk down the boulevard
and see what transpired when people saw him. But this being L.A.
and all, by the time Jesse and his bodyguards showed up at Jerry's,
the word had leaked and there were enough media types on hand to
kick off a national political convention.
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, though, Jesse slipped loose of the pack for a
few minutes, and we took a short walk down the Valley's most famous
boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this street,'' he said, waving to a group of young
women who came out of a nearby office building to see the country's
most famous bald politician up close and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to hang out on the boulevard all the time, do a lot of
work out here,'' Jesse said. ``I know the Valley real well. Nice
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he had a chance to talk any further, the crush of TV
cameras descended upon him, with four Minnesota state trooper
bodyguards in hot pursuit, trying to get their charge back in the
car because they were running late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' he said to me, looking over at the front door of
Jerry's deli like a guy who would love not to be himself for a few
hours, and just hang out anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   No chance anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura, of course, is not his real name. James George
Janos is. That name bit the dust the first time he laid eyes on
California's golden Ventura coastline after moving out here in 1975
to kick off his wrestling career.
</P>
<P>
   James Janos faded away, and Jesse Ventura was born. The rest, as
they say, is history. Weird history, but history nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, what'd you think?'' I asked the group of young office
workers watching Jesse's bodyguards whisk him away in a sedan down
Ventura Boulevard to the ``Tonight Show'' studios in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   They all agreed he was big, cute and bald _ and could definitely
beat up our governor-elect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 0024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6006 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COUGARS-SPI &LR;      11-18 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUGARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERCEPTIONS THE BANE OF WSU'S TWO QUARTERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years have passed since Ryan Leaf emerged in the Apple Cup
as the quarterback who would eventually lead Washington State to
the promised land of the Rose Bowl and anoint Cougar coach Mike
Price as one of the top quarterback coaches in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf left for the NFL this year, and WSU has spent an entire
season trying to find its old quarterback magic.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Steve Birnbaum and sophomore Paul Mencke have alternated
series _ even plays _ this season, and neither had a coming-out
party like Leaf did in 1995. Leaf, the season-long backup to Chad
Davis, got his first start in Husky Stadium and completed 23 of 33
passes for 273 yards and three touchdowns in a 33-30 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum and Mencke have looked good in spurts, but both have
been prone to interceptions, fumbled snaps and an inability to
produce scoring plays inside an opponent's red zone. Together, they
have combined for 16 touchdowns but have thrown 24 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have done is they both have started really well,''
Price said. ``Their finish is what is killing us. They are
finishing poorly in the second half when we need to get the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The two quarterback system, which Price said was designed to
maximize the best abilities of both quarterbacks, began when Mencke
replaced Birnbaum in the contest vs. California, the fourth game of
the season. Mencke seemed to energize the team, throwing a 29-yard
TD pass. But both quarterbacks also threw interceptions that were
returned for touchdowns in that game.
</P>
<P>
   The next week against UCLA, Birnbaum started again, but the
Cougar offense failed to mount a scoring drive until late in the
first half in what turned into a 49-17 Bruin rout. For the next
five games, all losses, the quarterbacks were shuffled in starting
roles, in alternating series, and sometimes on alternating plays.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the passing production has improved, but
interceptions and mistakes reached critical proportions. Last week
against Stanford, Birnbaum and Mencke were a combined 17-of-40 for
372 yards and three touchdowns, but Birnbaum had two interceptions
and Mencke three as the Cardinal came back for a 38-28 win.
</P>
<P>
   The two-headed quarterback beast is not Price's brainchild
alone. In fact, this is the first season that Price has turned over
the quarterback coaching duties to an assistant _ in this case, his
son, Eric Price, who is in his first year as Cougar quarterbacks
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two weeks we have been more productive on offense,
but we continue to turn the ball over, which killed us,'' said Eric
Price, who previously served as an assistant coach at Northern
Arizona and Cal Poly San Luis Obispo, and as a graduate assistant
at Miami and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Price admits his abilities have been taxed trying to figure
out which quarterback to use in certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are both different types of quarterbacks, and they both
do things well that are different,'' he said. ``We are trying to
match what they do best.''
</P>
<P>
   Mencke is seen as more of a scrambling quarterback who will try
to make something happen when things break down on the offense,
while Birnbaum is considered more of the classic pocket passer who
excels when the entire offense is clicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just pressing and trying to make things happen,''
Eric Price said. ``It's been pretty frustrating. It's not always
their fault, but they have just pushed it a little bit too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their troubles, both quarterbacks have accepted their
dual roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever coach says ... I'm just excited to go out there,''
Mencke said. ``Whatever we can do to win is what I want to do. If
that means me starting or Steve, or going to the two-quarterback
system, let's do that and get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, both have shown improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing fine in practice, but things are different in
the game,'' Birnbaum said. ``Things are faster, and the receivers
don't get jammed as hard in practice, and that all makes a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Stanford, the offense racked up more yards, more time of
possession and more first downs than the Cardinal, but failed to
score every time it entered the red zone, and was only 4-of-16 on
third-down conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistics are for losers, and we need to concentrate on one
statistic, and that's the scoreboard statistic,'' Mike Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Price hopes this year's experience will help both
quarterbacks in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run it's made them both pretty tough,'' he said.
``They're both winners, they're both good kids, and they have kept
a great attitude throughout the whole season. But those two have
been taking a lot of heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just have to stay positive because they want it so bad
that I think eventually it's going to happen for one of them. After
the season we'll have to evaluate where we are and go into spring
ball with a good attitude and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Price doesn't believe that Leaf's shadow has played a big
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the season for Birnbaum, he was pretty confident,
then things unfolded and it didn't work out for him,'' Eric Price
said. ``But he has stayed positive and each week he's right back in
the offense and he's just so eager to have a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the interceptions have been Birnbaum's fault,
according to Eric Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most unlucky quarterback I've ever seen in my life.
Every time a ball is tipped, it seems like it is picked off or run
back for a touchdown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With both quarterbacks suffering, Eric Price also has taken his
lumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a rough first year for me,'' he said. ``I'm kind
of taking it right along with Mencke and Birnbaum. We're in the
same boat. We're all trying to get the monkeys off our back here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 0025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
