<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMOR FROM THE BENCH AT MICROSOFT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST, MICROSOFT-SUN) 
 (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Microsoft trial is not all fireworks by any
means. There are long stretches of tedium and droning testimony on
the technical details of computing.
</P>
<P>
   To lighten things up, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson began the afternoon session Tuesday by saying that the
court is on ``some e-mail humor list.'' He then read the computer
entry he thought amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Both women and men, it seems, were asked what gender would be
most appropriate for computers.
</P>
<P>
   The women, the e-mail message said, agreed that computers should
be masculine for the following four reasons:
</P>
<P>
   1. In order to get their attention, you have to turn them on.
</P>
<P>
   2. They have a lot of data, but they are still clueless.
</P>
<P>
   3. Most of the time, they are the problem.
</P>
<P>
   4. As soon as you commit to one, you realize that if you waited
a little longer you could have had a better model.
</P>
<P>
   The men, according to the e-mail message, agreed that computers
should be feminine for the following four reasons:
</P>
<P>
   1. No one but the Creator understands their internal logic.
</P>
<P>
   2. The native language they use to communicate with other
computers is incomprehensible to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   3. Even your smallest mistakes are stored in long-term memory
for later retrieval.
</P>
<P>
   4. As soon as you make a commitment to one, you find yourself
spending half your paycheck on accessories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 0028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-YOUNG-NYT &LR;      11-18 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-YOUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERRY YOUNG JR.,   FIRST AFRICAN-AMERICAN COMMERCIAL PILOT 
</HEADLINE>
  ( rl ) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perry H. Young Jr., an aviator whose career spanned more than 50
years and who was the first African-American pilot for a commercial
airline in the United States, died on Nov. 8 at the Horton Medical
Center in Middletown, N.Y. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who lived in Pine Bush, N.Y., had cancer, said his wife,
Shakeh Young.
</P>
<P>
   The historic flight occurred on Feb. 5, 1957. With Young as the
co-pilot, a 12-passenger New York Airways helicopter rose 3 feet,
hovered gently for a moment, then soared straight up from La
Guardia Airport. Nine minutes later, the snub-nose helicopter
landed at Idlewild Airport _ now Kennedy International Airport _
ending the racist notion ``that blacks could not fly,'' said Perry
Jones, former chairman of the Organization of Black Airline Pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point, commercial airlines had refused to hire blacks
in any on-board capacity, even though African Americans had
distinguished themselves as capable aviators during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Young had also been one of the first black
flight instructors in the U.S. Army Air Corps. Assigned to the 99th
Pursuit Squadron, a black unit, he taught more than 150 pilots,
many of whom saw action during the war. The squadron was highly
decorated and went on to become known as the Tuskegee Airmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few of us knew anything about flying _ few blacks did _
and we thought our instructors were going to be white,'' said Lee
A. Archer, 77, who is the only African-American fighter ace, having
shot down five enemy planes during combat. ``When I saw men like
Perry Young, I was surprised and proud. They were like minor gods
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, when the commercial industry was unwilling to
open its doors, Young went to the Caribbean to fly. Over the next
10 years, he was in Haiti, Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands,
operating his own commercial flight service and working as a
contract pilot and flight mechanic. During that time he earned his
helicopter pilot's license.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1956, 17 years after he had earned his first pilot's
license, Young was hired by New York Airways in an aggressive
campaign to break the color barrier in the commercial airline
business. Within months, he rose to captain and flew with the
company for 23 years until it declared bankruptcy in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was both an airplane and helicopter pilot,'' said Jones,
63. ``He would have preferred to fly planes. But at that time, if
your skin was dark, so were your chances of becoming a pilot of any
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   After Young was hired by New York Airways, other men became
emboldened to challenge the status quo. Marlon Green, a former Air
Force captain, took Continental Airlines all the way to the Supreme
Court in 1963, winning a landmark judgment that opened interstate
commercial airlines to black pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Young took his first airplane ride in July 1937 in his hometown
of Oberlin, Ohio, just days after Amelia Earhart had disappeared on
her flight around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   After that first ride, Young began taking flying lessons. He
worked odd jobs while attending courses at Oberlin College, earning
$9 a week to pay for flying lessons that cost $5.25 for 20 minutes.
He earned his private pilot's license in 1939 and dropped out of
college a year later to pursue a career in aviation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not easy,'' Mrs. Young said. ``There was a lot of hurt
but he never wore it on his sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, Young is survived by a son, Perry H. Young III
of New York City; a daughter, Linda Young Ribeiro of Accra, Ghana,
and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
