<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON BASKETBALL TEAM SHOWS NO. 14 RANKING WARRANTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is not every day you wake up and read that the
Washington Huskies are ranked No. 14 in the nation in men's
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been days like this in Seattle since, oh, about
1984, when ethnic food in Ballard was strictly Swedish pancakes and
a good cup of coffee did not come with a decorative dollop of
steamed-milk foam.
</P>
<P>
   Some new trends are worth getting hooked on. Lattes at $2.70 a
pop, but especially a Division I basketball program that finally is
where its determined and talented coach wants it to be, five years
after 5-22.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 Huskies, who opened their season Monday night at Hec
Ed with a win over a scrappy North Carolina-Wilmington team, have
with one win confirmed one important thing:
</P>
<P>
   The sweet taste of last spring's intrepid foray into the heart
of the NCAA tournament has not evaporated from the lips of these
now even deeper, better Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a context clue that tells you the Huskies just might be
aching to make another appearance in at least the Sweet 16 (a tough
task, but let's keep the dream alive). Junior guard Deon Luton says
he spent a good part of his offseason doing dribbling drills.
</P>
<P>
   Luton is the high-flying and explosive scorer who has the
spread-eagle Michael Jordan ``Air'' logo tattooed on his arm. The
fella likes to shake the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to have to handle the ball in the press and
I had some things to work on, so I just incorporated some drills
into my workout routine,'' Luton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. I worked on the drives and the dunks. But
I did the dribbling and ball-handling stuff, too.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of dedication to the basics by key guys like Luton,
Donald Watts, Thalo Green, Dan Dickau, Chris Walcott and big man
Todd MacCulloch (in the best shape of his life) has these Huskies
looking and acting poised and mature.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a bad tangible to throw out there at the likes of
UCLA, Arizona and Stanford _ all Pac-10 opponents with higher
rankings than the Huskies. But maturity, along with talent and
depth, define this No. 14 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we were doing,'' MacCulloch said about the
Huskies' gritty 70-63 win over the NC-Wilmington Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Seahawks were hanging on MacCulloch like Lilliputians
on Gulliver, the Huskies found a way to win, mostly with emphatic
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased,'' Husky coach Bob Bender said Tuesday. ``We're
still a team with a lot to prove. We're not going to go out there
and blow people away. We're a team that will have to find something
within ourselves to pull out games. Like (Monday) night, we shoot
only 36 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one thing this Husky team needs to embrace is complete
dedication to getting the ball inside to MacCulloch. Alone, he can
improve any team's scoring percentage, since MacCulloch has been
the NCAA's leader in scoring percentage the past two seasons. And
MacCulloch seems more than happy to fight off any number of pesky
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to it,'' the 7-footer said after his 20-point effort
Monday left him raked with bloody welts and scratches.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school, they'd yell in to me, `They're doubling.' I
didn't even notice. They'd yell, `They're tripling.' I didn't care.
I'm used to it. I'm confident I can make my shot even with two or
three on me, or I can just kick the ball back out,'' MacCulloch
calmly explained.
</P>
<P>
   While depth might be the Huskies' saving grace on nights when
key guys such as Watts or Luton struggle or there is foul trouble,
that same depth has the potential to take the Huskies away from
their ultimate strength _ the big guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be a priority. When we get into our half-court
set, there has to be better recognition to get the ball in to
Todd,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it is more a sign of the Huskies' strength and depth that
MacCulloch only got six shots from the floor when 14 of his 20
points came from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have added solid freshman point guard Senque Carey
to their lineup, along with a defensive stopper in transfer forward
Greg Clark. Ballard sophomore Michael Johnson got 13 minutes, too.
All of these new bodies added up to a deeper Husky rotation, which
meant the ball was being reversed around the perimeter by a lot of
new combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line, Bender will pare down his rotations
and lean heavily on the group that can best recognize the exact
moment when MacCulloch has positioned himself for the feed.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the season opener was a good win. As early
season polls and predictions go, the ``W'' solidified the Huskies'
presence in the top 25. Although the coach refuses to get caught up
in the hoopla of being ranked up there with the Blue Devils, Tar
Heels, Terrapins, Jayhawks, Bruins and Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except I will say this,'' Bender said. ``I went home (after
the game) and watched ESPN. That was the first time I've ever seen
our highlights on, without it being because we were playing someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   For No. 14 Washington, it's definitely welcome to the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
