<HEADLINE>
NO LOGIC TO BCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (set ital) Streams of unconsciousness while wondering if eight
is enough for UCLA: (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The last thing UCLA needs during USC week is another BCS-related
distraction. But here comes one anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins currently rank second in the BCS (Bowl Championship
Series) poll, and logic says wins over the Trojans and Miami should
get them to the national title game at the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Logic is not, however, a facet of the BCS system. When the rules
were drawn, BCS made preseason classics, like Florida State-Texas
A&AMP;M, exempt from some ranking criteria. It did not, however, add
any kind of qualifier for teams that play a postseason conference
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 BCS team Tennessee (9-0) and No. 3 Kansas State (10-0)
both will play conference title games that will contribute to its
BCS ranking (assuming both teams win out). The biggest impact will
be seen in the strength of schedule component.
</P>
<P>
   That's where UCLA enjoys its current edge. This week's BCS
ranking has UCLA with a 2.24 point edge on K-State in strength of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins' margin was 2.76 a week earlier, before K-State
beat Nebraska. This week, K-State meets Missouri (No. 19 in the BCS
poll), which has the fifth toughest schedule in the nation. If the
Wildcats beat Mizzou, they then advance to the Big XII Title game
against 10-1 Texas A&AMP;M. The Aggies have won 10 straight, are ranked
sixth by the BCS, and have the 15th toughest schedule in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   If K-State wins both of those games, it conceivably could close
the schedule gap with UCLA enough and use its higher rankings in
the human and computer polls to vault into the title game.
</P>
<P>
   There is literally nothing UCLA can do about it, either. It
can't rush out and challenge someone to an extra game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an upside and a downside from a 12th game,'' said BCS
spokesman Charles Bloom. ``Should Tennessee and Kansas State lose
that game, they'll drop in the standings. The upside is that it can
improve their strength of schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has two tough games left, Saturday against USC (20th in the
BCS) and Dec. 5 versus Miami (24th). But wins will not give the
Bruins as much of a boost as K-State wins versus Mizzou and Texas
A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Both USC and Miami also have one other games left, and losses
could indirectly impact UCLA's numbers. On Nov. 28, USC meets Notre
Dame and Miami plays Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   (Paranoid aside: In other words, UCLA's fate may lie in the
hands of USC, since a Trojan win over Notre Dame would be of value;
former USC head coach Larry Smith, now the coach at Mizzou; and
Texas A&AMP;M head coach R.C. Slocum, who once fired Bob Toledo.)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has regular season games left with Kentucky and
Vanderbilt, and is likely to face a rematch with Arkansas (No. 9 in
the BCS rankings) in the SEC title game.
</P>
<P>
   What all this does most is remind one and all that you can't
spell playoff without B-C-S. ...
</P>
<P>
   USC's chances against UCLA this week will likely swing on the
presence and ability of its wide receivers. USC's deep game matured
once Carson Palmer became the starter, and the Bruins have little
pass rush. If Palmer can beat the blitz, USC can beat UCLA. ...
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that Bruinscoach Bob Toledo will undoubtedly
pull another psychological edge out of his trick bag. Toledo
doesn't like just trick plays; he likes to find ways to stimulate
his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, a simple pregame meeting turned into an
emotional catharsis for the Bruins, who went out and throttled
Arizona the next day. Just last week, Toledo dumped all of the
team's troubles on defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti, leading to
one of the better defensive efforts Saturday at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he had the scout team wear purple pants and helmets
with the Washington logo before the Husky game. Before the Arizona
game, amid criticism that the Bruins weren't physically tough
enough, he drew a line in tape on the floor of the locker room and
had players go head-to-head, giving the team an adrenalin rush no
one else could see.
</P>
<P>
   Extra emotional edges aren't necessary this week, but I won't be
surprised if Toledo comes up with one anyway. ...
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time to spruce up the job resume if you'd like to be
a NFL head coach. There could be 14 openings between now and the
start of next season. In order of reassignment: Sure to go: 1. Dick
Vermeil, St. Louis. He never should have left the comfort of a TV
job. 2. Ray Rhodes, Philadelphia. He won't be unemployed long. 3.
Norv Turner, Washington. It's a wonder he's lasted this long. 4.
Ted Marchibroda, Baltimore. Art Modell's honeymoon in Baltimore is
over. 5. Dave Wannstedt, Chicago. The team is improved, but there's
still no long-term answers here.
</P>
<P>
   On the bubble: 6. Pete Carroll, New England, and 7. Dennis
Erickson, Seattle. It's playoffs or ta-ta. 8. Vince Tobin,
Cardinals. There's talent here, but it's poorly coached. 9. Bruce
Coslet, Cincinnati. Name a big win in his career. 10. Bobby Ross,
Detroit. Wayne Fontes, all is forgiven. 11. June Jones, San Diego.
He's just the interim guy for now.
</P>
<P>
   File for future reference: 12. Mike Holmgren, Green Bay. He may
leave for full-power elsewhere. 13. Steve Mariucci, San Francisco.
The front office chaos may drift to the field. 14. Marty
Schottenheimer, Kansas City. Things in K.C. are starting to look
the way they did in Marty's last days in Cleveland. ...
</P>
<P>
   All of this extended basketball-less time has led me to suggest
Donald Sterling reconsider hiring a head coach for his Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips have sucked with a variety of head coaches. Could they
suck worse if they didn't have one? Maybe that's the answer to
their woes. Just hire a team chaperone, designate a tram captain,
and draw straws for starting spots and sub rotation. ...
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait to see the honeymoon pay-per-view video
extravaganza from those crazy kids, Dennis Rodman and Carmen
Electra. . ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
