<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-COSTS-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY FINDS COLLEGE GROWING LESS AFFORDABLE FOR THE POOR
</HEADLINE>
 (See also COLLEGE-SMOKING) 
(rl) 
By WILLIAM H. HONAN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As college costs have risen and federal grants to needy students
have declined over the last two decades, higher education has
become significantly less affordable for students from poor
families, a new national survey shows.
</P>
<P>
   Some academicians who took part in the survey blamed the
higher-education lobby in Washington for the predicament,
maintaining that the lobbyists exercised political triage by
throwing most of their weight behind winning a lower interest rate
on federally backed college loans rather than more money for
federal Pell grants. Loans serve primarily the middle class, while
Pell grants help low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 and 1977, the average Pell grant covered 19 percent of
the annual price of a private four-year institution and 39 percent
of a public four-year institution. But in 1996 and 1997, it covered
only 9 percent of a private college and 22 percent of a public
college, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, over the same period, the maximum Pell grant declined
to 13 percent of the price of a private college, from 35 percent,
and to 34 percent of the price of a public institution, from 72
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The last Congress raised maximum Pell grants to $3,125, from
$3,000, and reduced the interest rate on college loans to 7.46
percent, from 8.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing erosion of Pell grants is partly a result of the
priorities of the higher-education lobby facing the realities of
Congress, said Thomas D. Parker, a senior vice president of the
Educational Resources Institute. The Boston-based institute, a
nonprofit educational research organization, cosponsored the survey
with the Institute for Higher Education Policy, whose headquarters
are in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did get a small expansion of the Pell grants last year,''
Parker said, ``but the higher-education lobbyists in Washington
decided that it's better to accept the fact that it won't be
possible to get much of an increase in Pell grants than to make a
stink about it. They decided to put most of their effort behind
federal college loans, which have a much bigger constituency: the
middle class. The result is that many low-income people can't even
begin to think about going to a four-year college.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Hartle, a spokesman for the American Council on Education,
an organization based in Washington that represents 1,600 colleges
and universities, called Parker ``woefully misinformed'' and said
the Pell grant program had been ``the most important federal policy
objective of colleges and universities for the past 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last two years, the value of the maximum Pell grant
has increased by $425, or 14 percent,'' Hartle said. ``Increasing
the Pell grant by $100 costs $350 million, which is a lot even by
Washington standards, especially when it competes directly with
Head Start, biomedical research and job training.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, entitled ``Do Grants Matter? Student Grant Aid and
College Affordability,'' found that in the six years ending in the
1995-96 academic year, the average net cost of a public four-year
institution rose 28 percent, to $7,829 from $6,140, for
undergraduates whose annual family incomes were $20,000 to $39,999.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also found an overall disparity between the
college enrollment of low-income and high-income students.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Overall enrollments are up and federal funding has modestly
increased,'' said Jamie P. Merisotis, president of the Institute
for Higher Education Policy, ``but these trends mask the fact that
there is a gap of almost 30 percentage points in enrollment between
low-income and high-income students.''
</P>
<P>
   Merisotis said colleges deserved credit for having invested
heavily in financial aid based on need, but added, ``The fact
remains that the prices are still increasing, and the lower-income
students and parents bear the brunt of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about a possible solution, Merisotis replied, ``It's not
just more federal money that's needed, but a different political
attitude about how and why we should be investing in student aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, the schools must keep prices down by improved
cost-management strategies,'' he said. ``For example, some colleges
might consider eliminating a program in electrical engineering that
is high-cost and has very few graduates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
