<HEADER>
A6033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-AUCTION-525&AMP;ADD-N     11-18 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-AUCTION-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED RESULTS FOR CONTEMPORARY ART AUCTION
</HEADLINE>
   ( nk ) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Buyers kept their feet firmly planted on the ground
Tuesday night at Sotheby's auction of contemporary art. While six
or seven people were often seen bidding on a work at once, buying
seemed carefully controlled throughout the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some pieces drew high prices, and records were set for
artists including Richard Diebenkorn, Jeff Koons, Brice Marden and
Martin Puryear. The sale totaled $42.2 million, less than Sotheby's
estimate of $47 million to $65 million. Of the 83 works, 67 were
sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers were selective,'' said Diana D. Brooks, Sotheby's chief
executive. ``They knew what they wanted. But the evening proved
this market is alive and well.''
</P>
<P>
   The salesroom was far more lively than it had been on Monday
night, when the auction house sold Impressionist and modern art
that included 37 works from the Reader's Digest collection.
</P>
<P>
   The highest price paid Tuesday night was for Picasso's ``Nude''
(1909), which shows the artist's mistress, Fernande Olivier,
wrapped in a cloth. Estimated at $10 million to $15 million, it
sold for $11 million to an unidentified buyer. Although a Picasso
would normally have gone into a sale of Impressionist and modern
art, Sotheby's placed it in the contemporary sale because Monday's
auction, which included the Reader's Digest property, was already
too large.
</P>
<P>
   The Picasso was one of 27 works from the Morton G. Neumann
family collection. Neumann, a Chicago industrialist who died in
1985, and his wife, Rose, began buying art in the 1940s. Over the
years, they amassed works by artists including Picasso, Miro,
Dubuffet, Klee and Giacometti. When Mrs. Neumann died this year,
the works went to the their children, who chose to sell a group of
them to help pay estate taxes. Many, including the Picasso, had
been on loan to the National Gallery of Art in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Another painting from the Neumann collection that brought a
strong price was Miro's ``Head of a Smoker'' (1925), one of the
artist's ``dream paintings,'' which shows a head and pipe merging
into a single abstract form. The buyer was David Nahmad, a
Manhattan dealer, who paid $1 million, just at the painting's low
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 and 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   After the the Neumann collection, the sale progressed to
contemporary art from various owners. One of the evening's
liveliest moments came when Richard Diebenkorn's ``Horizon: Ocean
View'' (1992-93) was up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The one contemporary work from the Reader's Digest collection,
the glorious painting of sea and sky incited more excitement than
Monday night's entire sale. Estimated at $1.5 million to $2
million, it sold for a whopping $3.9 million to an unidentified
telephone buyer, leaving seven other serious bidders disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every case, works that didn't sell carried estimates
that were too high. One of the problems, Sotheby's officials said,
was those estimates were placed in July, when both the art market
and the financial market felt more buoyant.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some of the evening's biggest-ticket items went unsold,
regardless of quality. Among them was Jasper Johns's ``White
Numbers'' (1958), an important encaustic-on-linen painting of
numerals in a progression from 0 to 9 repeated horizontally and
vertically in thick, gestural strokes. Sotheby's estimated it would
sell for $7 million to $9 million, but a collective gasp was heard
in the salesroom when bidding failed to go above $6 million. Just a
year ago, a larger version of ``White Numbers,'' from the
collection of Victor and Sally Ganz, fetched $7.9 million at
Christie's, and before Tuesday night's sale, collectors and dealers
said they thought this one should have been priced at $5 million to
$7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Johns was being sold by the Boston collectors Mildred and
Herbert Lee. In the 1960s, Mrs. Lee began buying what were then
considered adventurous works, which are now highly desirable.
</P>
<P>
   ``White Numbers'' wasn't the only Johns owned by the Lees, who
also were selling a 1959 ``Flag,'' a pencil-and-graphite wash on
paper estimated at $500,000 to $700,000. Unlike ``White Numbers,''
it had three serious bidders who wanted to take it home. It finally
sold for $992,500, a record for a Johns work on paper, to Simon de
Pury, the former chairman of Sotheby's in Europe, who now runs an
art investment and advisory business.
</P>
<P>
   Also from the Lee collection was Robert Rauschenberg's ``Dry
Run'' (1963), one of the artist's early silkscreens with overlays
of photographic images. Several bidders showed interest in the
work, which finally went to a representative of Eli Broad, the Los
Angeles collector, for $992,500, a little more than its low
estimate of $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the sale felt very solid,'' said Tobias Meyer, head of
contemporary art for Sotheby's worldwide, who was the evening's
auctioneer. ``For works like the Diebenkorn, we had six or seven
people bidding at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Marden's ``Yellows,'' (1972), a triptych, had lots of bidders
waving paddles. Estimated at $1.5 million to $2 million, it went to
Robert Mnuchin, chairman of the Manhattan gallery C&AMP;M Arts, for
$992,500. Mr. Mnuchin also bought Andy Warhol's ``Four Marilyns''
for $2.3 million, just below its low estimate of $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought some splendid things,'' said a beaming Mnuchin as he
left the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts expressed relief that the market felt more solid
than it had on Monday night. ``There was better property tonight,''
said Diane Upright, a private New York dealer. ``Some of the
estimates were daunting. And buyers were very careful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
