<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON TOPS TEXAS IN DREXLER'S DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The first 6,000 fans to enter sold-out Hofheinz
Pavilion for the Houston-Texas basketball opener last night
received T-shirts commemorating the debut of Cougars coach Clyde
Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the 8,452 in attendance went away feeling as if they
were part of the rebirth of what once was one of college hoops'
most successful programs. Many more may one day say they witnessed
Drexler's first coaching victory.
</P>
<P>
   Gee Gervin, son of former NBA great George Gervin, led Houston
to a historic 71-69 victory against the Longhorns _ who also
happened to be making their debut with coach Rick Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure had a great time tonight,'' said Drexler, who retired
from the Houston Rockets after last season and took the UH job.
``We really wanted to get off to a good start by winning this game.
I was really proud of the players. They played together and stuck
to the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin, a transfer guard from San Jacinto College, scored a
game-high 25 points, including seven of his team's last eight
points as the Cougars held off a Texas rally from 12 down to 70-69
on Ivan Wagner's 3-pointer with 44 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Clack and Gabe Muoneke led Texas with 16 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed with the way we played in the first
half, but we played our way back, and did have a chance at the
end,'' Barnes said. ``We got frustrated at times, but we stayed
together, and I'm proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The game might not have rivaled some of the titanic battles in
Hofheinz 20 years ago when former Houston coach Guy V. Lewis
matched wits with Abe Lemons at Texas and Eddie Sutton at Arkansas
during the height of Southwest Conference basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis said he relishes the rebirth of the program. Last
night's crowd recalled days when Hofheinz regularly sold out when
the Longhorns and Razorbacks visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only thing is we'll be rocking every game this year rather
than just a couple,'' said Lewis, whose teams won 592 games and
played in five Final Fours during his 30-year tenure (1956-86).
``These new (luxury) boxes have really dressed the place up. And on
top of that, it's one more thing that's going to keep the noise
inside. The low ceiling used to keep the noise right on top of us.
Now there's no place for it to go. It's just great.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Houston continued to win after Lewis retired a dozen
years ago, the program never came close to generating Phi Slama
Jama-type enthusiasm that reached its peak when Drexler and Hakeem
Olajuwon helped lead the Cougars to Final Fours in 1982 and '83.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basketball enthusiasm here had dropped to almost nil,''
Lewis said. ``Now, it's amazing. We sold out Hofheinz on a season
ticket basis for the first time in history. And I'm not talking
about padded. People bought the tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The game dominated local early-evening sports talk shows. The
manager of a popular South Main oyster bar patiently explained to a
patron that it was against policy to turn up the sound on the
restaurant's television _ but that they could punch up closed
captioning. Satisfied, the customer said he and some friends would
return _ and this was three hours before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is on a high,'' Lewis said. ``I don't think it's all
that they feel like we're going to win that many games this year,
although they think we'll be improved. But people just feel like
the future is now. We just signed three great players \Rduring the
fall signing period\S and we have our hooks into two or three more.
To go with what we've got, we're going to have top-notch teams.
It's all about enthusiasm for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we could have hired anyone else other than Clyde
who would have brought the enthusiasm back. The guy just wows them.
I've never seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has. But it has been awhile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
