<SLUG> BC-NY-ADELPHI-SETTLE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADELPHI, OUSTED PRESIDENT SETTLE SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: RECASTS lede, ADDS optional material) 
 (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Adelphi University agreed Tuesday to pay a
settlement with its ousted president, Peter Diamandopoulos, that
leaves him with $1.4 million before taxes and resolves all the
suits and countersuits over his removal last year.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also yields $3.5 million for Adelphi from several
sources, which the university said it would use to hire professors
and begin to refurbish its campus here.
</P>
<P>
   Diamandopoulos, whose unusually high pay and benefits led to his
highly publicized downfall in 1997, had sought more than $4.5
million but settled for less than a third of that after refunding
part of his salary and paying rent owed on a luxury condominium in
Manhattan that the university had bought for him, and reimbursing
Adelphi for legal fees and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphi's chairman, Steven Isenberg, said the settlement
``closes the books on what was a difficult and sad chapter in the
life of this university.''
</P>
<P>
   Students and professors expressed relief. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``We just need to get over it,'' said Diane Malinauskas, 21, a
speech pathology major from Glen Cove, N.Y. ``It got to the point
where it was kind of embarrassing to say you went to Adelphi. But
things have turned around. Morale's definitely up.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamandopoulos, who was named president in 1985, had sought to
transform Adelphi from a commuter college into one with an
international reputation, with advertisements that called Harvard
``the Adelphi of Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   But as tuition soared, enrollment dropped and financial troubles
forced layoffs and cuts in programs &UR; .  &LR; Growing dissatisfaction with
Diamandopoulos' personality and policies erupted into an
out-and-out battle three years ago after it was reported that his
$523,000 a year in pay and benefits ranked among the highest for
the nation's college presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by a coalition of critics _ including faculty leaders,
former trustees and administrators, alumni, parents and students _
the state Board of Regents held 27 days of hearings before removing
18 of the 19 trustees for neglect of duty and misconduct in
February 1997. The Regents cited the trustees for granting
excessive compensation to Diamandopoulos, failing to review his
performance and allowing some trustees to engage in private
business with the university.
</P>
<P>
   The Regents appointed a new board, headed by Isenberg, which
dismissed Diamandopoulos. After he sought to stay on as a tenured
professor, the new board went to court to cancel his contract
rights, and he countersued. State Attorney General Dennis Vacco
sued the former trustees for restitution of misspent money, and
they sued the Regents.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Tuesday, in which neither Diamandopoulos nor
the former trustees admitted wrongdoing, settled all the
litigation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the complicated agreement, which was executed on Monday,
the former trustees paid Adelphi $1.23 &UR;  &LR; million and assumed more
than $400,000 in legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Tuesday how the former trustees would divide
their share of the payments to Adelphi. In the group is Hilton
Kramer, an art critic, as well as several wealthy executives,
including Leonard Riggio, chief executive of Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphi received an additional $1.45 million from National
Union, the insurance company that indemnified the former trustees
and officers. Diamandopoulos refunded nearly $650,000 to Adelphi,
paid more than $100,000 in rent on the Manhattan apartment and
dropped claims worth an additional $767,000.
</P>
<P>
   All told, after paying $500,000 in legal bills that it still
owes, the university's balance sheet will be improved by about $3.5
million, Isenberg confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Diamandopoulos was permitted to keep $1.8 million in deferred
compensation and interest, and he received nearly $400,000 more as
a settlement of his counterclaim against Adelphi for breach of
contract. After his reimbursements to Adelphi, he walked away with
about $1.4 million, Isenberg said. But after taxes were withheld,
Diamandopoulos received only about $650,000 in cash, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diamandopoulos, 70, also agreed to vacate the Manhattan
condominium, on East 72nd Street, by the end of the month, Isenberg
said. A broker has been hired to sell it, with an asking price of
$1.45 million. Adelphi had spent a total of $1.3 million to buy,
renovate and furnish the high-rise apartment. Diamandopoulos had
sought to exercise an option to buy it for $905,000.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general and other critics of Diamandopoulos had
attacked his lavish life style as president, and some had
speculated that he used Adelphi's money to amass an art collection
while on frequent trips to Europe paid for by the university. But
Matthew D. Sansverie, chief of the attorney general's Charities
Bureau, said Diamandopoulos had sworn in an affidavit that he, not
Adelphi, had paid for his art collection.
</P>
<P>
   Both Michael N. Rosen, a lawyer for Diamandopoulos, and Stanley
Arkin, who represented the former trustees, said their clients were
pleased with the settlement and remained loyal to Adelphi.
</P>
<P>
   Isenberg noted that since Adelphi named a new president, Matthew
Goldstein, in June, enrollment, which fell 62 percent during
Diamandopoulos's administration, has surged. The freshman class is
nearly twice last year's in number, and total enrollment is up 5
percent, to 4,275.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphi, which has an operating budget of about $76 million,
will use the $3.5 million it received under the settlement to
continue a buyout of tenured professors that has enabled it to hire
13 professors this year and which could result in 40 new hirings
over the next three years, Isenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The money will also allow Adelphi to speed up plans to borrow
$15 million to rehabilitate its five residence halls, add a
computer center to its library and overhaul the interior of its
business school, said a spokesman, Vince Passaro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
