</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-AVALANCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLES LOSE JONSSON, THEN THE GAME, 5-2, TO COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Islanders lost defenseman Kenny Jonsson to a
concussion Tuesday night, then lost to the Colorado Avalanche by
5-2 at McNichols Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson, the Islanders' top defenseman, was injured in the
second period when he was cross-checked in the head by the
Avalanche's Cam Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Russell delivered the blow behind Jonsson's right ear,
Peter Forsberg of the Avalanche elbowed the left side of Jonsson's
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a headache,'' said Jonsson, who has had five
concussions in his career, two in the National Hockey League. ``I
don't think it was a cheap shot.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the 6-foot-3-inch, 195-pound Jonsson
would miss any games, but the loss to Colorado was an indication of
how indispensable Jonsson is to the Islanders. When Jonsson left
the game, the score was tied at 1-1. His presence in the defensive
zone was immediately missed as the Islanders gave up many quality
scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we missed him,'' said Mike Milbury, the Islanders'
coach and general manager. ``Any time he misses is going to be
tough to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson, who missed just one game last season because of the
flu, will be re-evaluated here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to lose him,'' said goalie Tommy Salo, who made
23 saves. ``He's our best defenseman. We need him in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Miller ended his streak of 31 games without a goal at 1
minute 8 seconds of the third period, scoring over a sprawled Salo
to give the Avalanche a 4-2 lead. Claude Lemieux scored Colorado's
fifth goal in the final minute of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who got off to another slow start, were outshot
by 9-3 in the first period but played to a 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche scored first, on a goal by Forsberg at 6:33.
Forsberg, who was fed the puck by Valery Kamensky after winning a
draw, beat Salo with a wrist shot from the slot. The Avalanche is
20-0-7 when Forsberg scores a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mariusz Czerkawski, who scored twice for the Islanders, tied the
score at 16:43. On a two-on-one break, Claude Lapointe made a
cross-ice pass to Czerkawski, who fired wide of the Avalanche net.
The puck rebounded off the back boards and back out to Czerkawski,
who poked it in.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche gained a 2-1 advantage a few minutes after the
injury to Jonsson. Kamensky scored on the power play at 10:45 on
blast from the middle of the right circle. His shot deflected off
Scott Lachance's stick.
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged goals late in the second period. Czerkawski
scored for the second time at 14:01 on the power play to tie the
score at 2-2. But Joe Sakic, the Avalanche captain, restored
Colorado's lead 25 seconds later, ricocheting the puck off an
unsuspecting Salo. Sakic was behind the goal line when the puck
went in.
</P>
</TEXT>
