<HEADLINE>
TROJANS' RECRUITS LEAD ROUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If their first game is any indication, USC's
newcomers won't need any transition period to catch up with the
veterans. Four members of the Trojans' incoming recruiting class
scored in double figures Tuesday as USC rolled to a 101-54 victory
over San Diego State before 2,381 at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Junior college transfer Brian Scalabrine, a 6-foot-9 forward,
lived up to his advance billing with 14 points and nine rebounds in
only 18 minutes. Nearly as impressive was freshman point guard
Brandon Granville, who had 10 points and five assists in his first
college start.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Sam Clancy had 11 points and 10 rebounds and
guard Quincy Wilder added 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, an impressive debut for the youngsters. And a solid
start for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the new guys played well,'' USC coach Henry Bibby
said. ``The new guys are from winning programs and they showed that
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing an outclassed Aztecs team, there were some
jitters among those Trojans making their first college appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous,'' Scalabrine said. ``As good a shape as I'm in,
it was hard to catch my wind. It took me like two or three minutes
once I went to the bench to catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Granville didn't feel any different than when he led
Westchester to the Division I state title, a pretty heady feeling
for someone who wasn't expected to start before the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I wasn't nervous,'' Granville said. ``Coach asked me
before the game if I would be and I told him no. I just tried to go
out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The 47-point victory was USC's largest in a season opener and
matched the worst loss in San Diego State history. Even with the
Aztecs coming off a surprising loss to Nevada at home last
Saturday, Bibby was just happy to get a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last year, I'll take it any way I can get it,'' Bibby
said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Junior forward Jarvis Turner was bothered by back spasms
but scored nine points in 20 minutes.... Point guard Kevin
Augustine played three minutes, despite missing nearly two weeks of
practice after being suspended when he left the team because of
burnout. ``I didn't think I would play at all,'' Augustine said.
``The main thing I talked to coach about was that I need to
continue to work on my conditioning. I'm a ways away as far as
conditioning.''... USC's 22 steals tied a school record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
