<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-CHASE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT DONE YET: GRAF UPSETS A HOBBLED NOVOTNA
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: UPDATES with 2nd round results, Graf beating Novotna; no
pickup) 
 (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jana Novotna may be the defending champion of the
Chase Championships, not to mention the reigning champion of
Wimbledon, but Steffi Graf is the undisputed champion of the
comeback, and Tuesday night at Madison Square Garden, a cramping
Novotna became the latest victim of Graf's latest take-no-prisoners
return to the women's tennis tour.
</P>
<P>
   Now on a two-tournament winning streak since her return from
September wrist surgery, Graf wore her poker face and brandished
her forehand like a bullwhip in the course of a 6-7 (5-7), 6-4, 6-1
victory that improved her record against the third-seeded Novotna
to 28-4. With her defeats of top-ranked Lindsay Davenport and
second-ranked Martina Hingis last week at Philadelphia, the
29-year-old Graf became the first unseeded player to dispose of the
world's top two players in the same event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I played up to my potential, but I've been
wearing down some players and that speaks for itself,'' Graf said.
</P>
<P>
   After scrambling into the final slot at this invitation-only
event for the top 16 women in 1998, Graf turned her attention to
Novotna, who limped into the tournament on a four-match losing
streak and limped away from this match barely able to work her
legs. The first defending champion to falter in the first round
here, Novotna was initially overcome by an onslaught of cramping in
both calves just after winning the first point of her first service
game in the final set. As Graf waited impatiently to put the
finishing touches on the turnaround she had begun in the second
set, Novotna sought treatment from a trainer. Although she returned
to the court and held serve for a 1-0 lead, that was the last game
she would win.
</P>
<P>
   Grimacing and bending and stretching to no avail, Novotna was
merely a pawn for Graf's latest performance in a remarkable
11-match unbeaten streak: At triple match point of this
2-hour-4-minute confrontation between the grande dames of the WTA
Tour, Novotna decided not to waste further time delaying the
inevitable. She simply let Graf's sliced backhand return waft past
her uncontested.
</P>
<P>
   After an unfriendly playing experience in which she was nearly
beheaded by a body-jamming ace from Graf midway through the second
set, getting out of the Garden without terminal injury was probably
Novotna's priority by the end of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, another recent victim of Graf's, has had a disconcerting
week. First she had to cope with the fact that, no matter what she
accomplishes at this year-ending tournament, it will not be enough
to wrest the No. 1 ranking from Lindsay Davenport. So like it or
not, and she doesn't, the record will show she was second best in
1998. And then, as if she didn't have enough pecking-order problems
last night, she had to cope with Patty Schnyder, the Swiss-born
player who had obediently played second fiddle to her until last
month at Munich.
</P>
<P>
   The last time they met, the fuzzy-haired Schnyder, whose five
titles for 1998 earned her the WTA's most improved player award,
dealt Hingis a defeat and a case of leg cramps. This time the
19-year-old Schnyder seemed intent on toppling Hingis again, but
after powering herself to a 6-4 lead, the left-handed Schnyder
wilted just long enough to allow Hingis to regroup and reassert
herself as the steadier playmaker. True, they ran each other
ragged. ``You just have to play and run,'' Hingis said. But in the
end it was Hingis, with a determined glare giving impetus to every
shot she launched, who advanced to the quarterfinal round with a
4-6, 6-0, 6-3 comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strange how the second set was over, 6-0, in like 10
minutes, but then you have to fight for every point in the third
set; it was a little bit nerve-racking to have someone like her on
the other side of the net,'' said Hingis, referring to the pressure
inherent in playing her understudy. ``I was, like, nervous in the
first set. My concentration went up and down like a roller
coaster.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Hingis's black headband felt as tight as a noose in
the opening set, when she went up a break only to instantly
surrender it with a double fault that leveled matters at 3-3. And
after holding for 5-4, Schnyderagain poured on the pressure and
broke Hingis for the set with a rambunctious inside-out forehand
that Hingis somehow dug out of the corner but managed to send only
as far as the net.
</P>
<P>
   But the momentum switched to Hingis's side in the virtually
one-sided middle set, when Schnyder forgot how to aim her missiles
within the boundaries. In the third set, the pair traded breaks in
the second and third games, but once Schnyder allowed Hingis to
wriggle out of a 0-40 deficit as she served in the fourth game, it
was the more famous Swiss player, not the homegrown one, who took
control.
</P>
<P>
   A pragmatist at heart, Hingis said she has already replaced her
chase for the No. 1 ranking with her pursuit of a first Chase
title. ``If you win this tournament, you go better into next
year,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
