<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN WOMEN DEFEAT UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's part of being an up-and-comer, trying to
knock off the queens of college basketball. It allows one to smile
and take quasi-delight even if the result goes in the wrong column.
</P>
<P>
   So while No.14 UCLA wasn't ecstatic over its 113-102 foul-filled
loss to No.2 UConn in front of 5,221 Tuesday at Pauley Pavilion,
there was some reserved pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what we did,'' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said.
``This game shows we can play with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems warped, but in the world of women's basketball, if the
outcome is in doubt in the final five minutes against UConn or
Tennessee or Louisiana Tech, it means your program is close to
arriving at the big time.
</P>
<P>
   And this one was in doubt with four minutes left as UConn's
83-70 lead was cut to 93-89 with 4:40 to play. But the Huskies
(3-0), on the West Coast for the sixth day in a row, scored eight
of the next points to ice the game.
</P>
<P>
   However, UCLA's ability to remain close, and even mount a late
comeback, does validate the preseason prognostications and ease
some of the pain from a 17-point loss to Notre Dame in its season
opener. The Bruins (0-2) were ranked sixth in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   However, just how much is eased will be determined by what the
Bruins do later this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a chance to redeem ourselves after the loss at Notre
Dame,'' UCLA forward Maylana Martin said. ``It wasn't a chance to
get over Notre Dame and make up for that loss, but a chance to get
something back. We expected a lot out of our team and so did other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But before UCLA can jump to elite status it must improve a
defense that was decimated by the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   While the foul-infested game (53 fouls) took away much of the
rhythm and pace, it was UCLA's lack of defense that allowed UConn
to shoot 58 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that damage was done by sophomore Svetlana Abrosimova,
who chimed in with a career-high 39 points on 14 of 17 shooting.
Shea Ralph, who missed last season with a knee injury, added a
career-best 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were led by Janae Hubbard's career-best 29 points
while Marie Philman, Michelle Greco and LaCresha Flannigan each
added 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our (lack of) depth and foul trouble really hurt us,'' Olivier
said. ``We have to do some things different defensively, get a hand
up in the shooter's face.''
</P>
<P>
   What will sit poorly with the Bruins are the missed
opportunities. After UConn pushed a 60-54 halftime lead to 83-70
with 11:29 left, the Bruins pulled within 93-89 with 4:40 left on
Philman's lay-in.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies answered with more open shots and scored eight
of the next 10 points to go ahead 101-91 with 3:12 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I though UCLA played really, really well on offense,'' UConn
coach Geno Auriemma said. ``Obviously, it's important to have our
two best players in a game (late) as crazy as this, where whoever
has the ball last and scores last wins the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
