</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Clyde Drexler got everything he wanted in his University of Houston
coaching debut Tuesday night _ a tight game, a huge crowd and,
finally, a win for his long-suffering alma mater.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After leading from the first three minutes, the Cougars survived
three missed shots by Texas in the closing seconds and escaped with
a 71-69 victory before a sellout Hofheinz Pavilion crowd of 8,452
in the teams' season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler's coaching debut was almost spoiled. Texas, struggling
with 32.4-percent shooting, saw potential game-winning shots by
William Clay, Kris Clack and Chris Mihm miss before Gee Gervin
added the final point of the game for the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty anxious for this night. I'd been waiting for it
the last two months,'' Drexler admitted. ``I live for pressure, and
this game had it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin, the son of former NBA great George Gervin, looked like a
chip off the old ``Ice'' block. A 6-3 junior guard playing his
first major-college game, Gervin coolly led the Cougars with 25
points, including their final eight.
</P>
<P>
   Gervin was 4-of-6 from 3-point range and credited a Drexler
suggestion in helping him reverse a 1-of-9 showing in an 88-80
exhibition loss to the Australian All-Stars last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to just relax and let the game come,'' said Gervin,
who also had three assists and only two turnovers in 36 minutes.
``I took my time, and I was a lot more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad Hendrick scored 17 points for the Cougars, with Kenny
Younger adding 15 points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Muoneke of Cypress Falls and Clack scored 16 each for
Texas, playing its first game with Rick Barnes as coach. Clay added
12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Only 9-of-18 shooting from 3-point range enabled UH to win. The
Cougars hit only 40.6 percent of their field-goal attempts, missed
half of their 20 free throws and committed 18 turnovers. Texas had
a 52-39 rebounding margin, with Mihm (14) and Clack (12) combining
for 26. But the Longhorns also suffered 18 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot play offense any worse than we did,'' said Barnes,
whose team hit only 24.1 percent (7-of-29) of its first-half shots.
``Our offense just didn't get the shots and execute like we needed
to. We needed to penetrate in the middle, and we didn't get the
kind of ball movement we needed. But as bad as we played, we had
three shots to win it at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Drexler liked the way his inside players clustered their zone
defense around Mihm, UT's 7-foot sophomore who blocked seven shots
but missed six of his eight field-goal attempts. The Cougars also
limited Clack to 5-of-19 shooting from the floor but very nearly
let several 12-point leads slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big guys fronted Mihm every opportunity they had to push
him out farther from the basket, and that was a big part of our
game plan,'' Drexler said. ``I'm proud of the way we adjusted when
we lost our big guy, Early Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, charged with much of the job of defending Mihm, suffered
possible torn knee cartilage in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Clay's 3-pointer off the backboard capped an 11-2 UT run that
reduced UH's 61-49 lead to 63-60 with 4:07 remaining. After a
Cougars timeout, Gervin was fouled by Muoneke and made both free
throws, then canned a jumper with one second left on the shot clock
to put Houston up by seven.
</P>
<P>
   After Muoneke sank a 15-footer and two free throws to draw Texas
within 67-64, Gervin answered again, sinking a jumper from the wing
to make it 69-64.
</P>
<P>
   Clay responded with a jumper before Gervin's free throw
presented UH with a 70-66 lead with 1:10 left. But the Longhorns'
Ivan Wagner sank a 3-pointer, his only field goal of the night, to
cut the margin to 70-69 with 44 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   An almost-fatal UH turnover against UT's pressing defense gave
the 'Horns their game-winning chance, but they couldn't get the
ball to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stuck with our game plan, and I was proud of the guys for
sticking together when things got tight and pulling it out,''
Drexler said. ``We're going to have a lot of tight games, and
winning one like this has to help us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
