<HEADER>
A6086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     11-18 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FROM strictly a basketball standpoint, it was hardly Phi Slama
Junior.
</P>
<P>
   No backboard-shaking. No elevating along the baseline. No slam
dunks.
</P>
<P>
   The only Dream player in the house was the locked-out-of-the-NBA
wealthy alumnus relaxing in a front-row seat under the north
basket.
</P>
<P>
   And rather than wearing a red-and-white game uniform, the only
Cougar who could really glide was the head coach in the natty
charcoal pinstriped suit standing in front of the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind any of that. The details can come later.
</P>
<P>
   On the night the Clyde Drexler Era debuted at the University of
Houston, only one thing mattered: The feeling was back.
</P>
<P>
   It was like walking through the door at Hofheinz Pavilion and
stepping into a time machine. Suddenly, it was the '80s again.
</P>
<P>
   You could practically hear the music of Michael Jackson, Cyndi
Lauper and Madonna echoing inside your head. Everybody wore a
Rolex, the price of oil was climbing toward $30 a barrel, the
mechanical bull was bucking at Gilley's, and the most scandalous
thing happening in the White House was a septuagenarian president
who occasionally took a nap in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   And the Coogs won a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, the way it always used to be and the way the
enthusiastic sellout crowd of 8,452 believes it can become again as
Drexler's mere presence and the hustling effort of a young Cougars
team sorted through the ashes of old memories and took a tentative
first step toward relighting the flame Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is euphoria,'' said Drexler as he stood amid a throng of
students and supporters who rushed onto the floor as if the
Cougars' 71-69 victory over Texas had earned them an invitation to
the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive them their overindulgence. When you have been down for
so long and are coming off a dismal 9-20 season, even the first
baby step of progress looks like The Great Wallenda doing a
somersault on the high wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team worked hard and prepared a long time to be ready for
this game and for this night,'' Drexler said. ``We had enough drive
and continued to work hard even when things got tight and they came
back on us at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a young team, and we had to call some timeouts down
the stretch to get them settled down and back into a rhythm that
would keep them into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars almost blew several leads of a dozen points. They
watched Texas snipe away from the outside and slowly climb back.
They saw Ivan Wagner toss in a 3-point prayer from deep in the left
corner that closed the gap to 70-69 with 44 seconds to go. And they
saw a freshman, Jake Ballis, walk with the ball after receiving an
inbounds pass and turn the ball back over to the Longhorns for a
final shot.
</P>
<P>
   William Clay took a jumper for Texas, then Kris Clack tried a
follow from the baseline and Chris Mihm put up a desperate
six-footer that never reached the rim as the Cougars fought and
scrapped and hustled to play those final frenetic seconds of
defense.
</P>
<P>
   It turned into a rugby scrum with William Stringfellow and Kenny
Younger on the floor, and the Cougars managed to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will get better,'' said Clyde's former teammate Hakeem
Olajuwon. ``They are all young players who are still learning about
the game and how to play it. But what I like watching is the way
they are playing so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   That was what mattered to the crowd even more than the 25 points
from Gee Gervin, the 17 points by Chad Hendrick or the 15 points by
Younger.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers are numbers, and there will be higher ones and lower
ones as this season progresses. There will be weeks and months and
years ahead to find out if the former NBA All-Star can make the
successful transition to head coach with no experience. There will
be plenty of time to see if he can manage all the tight situations
when the stakes are higher.
</P>
<P>
   There will be tougher games and bigger hurdles to clear than
this opener against Rick Barnes' first Texas team that is fortunate
to have enough warm bodies to fill the uniforms. The three guys
playing H-O-R-S-E on that Nike commercial with Samuel L. Jackson
could have shot better than the Longhorns. Texas shot 24 percent in
the first half and 32 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   But what mattered wasn't the level of competition, but the fact
that for the first time in a long time, the Cougars were competing.
Hustling, diving, working. Even if they never did dunk the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure had a great time tonight,'' the new head coach said.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
