<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FNB-WOEFUL-BENGALS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flashes of firepower can't rescue Bengals from awful season
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ When it comes to X's and O's, the Cincinnati
offense is a virtual mirror image of the offense used by Denver,
Green Bay, Minnesota and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to W's and L's, the Bengals are in a class by
themselves, a class woefully short of star pupils.
</P>
<P>
   While the leading proponents of the West Coast offense are
gearing up for the playoffs, Cincinnati, 2-8 heading into Sunday's
home game with Baltimore, is gearing down for an eighth straight
losing season.
</P>
<P>
   A rebuilding defense that starts three rookies was expected to
struggle, but the offense has been a year-long disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals are averaging 16.7 points a game and have scored 14
points or less six times, including last Sunday's 24-3 loss at
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Bruce Coslet and offensive coordinator Ken Anderson
have been twin lightning rods for criticism, but Coslet defended
the offensive philosophy and play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We examine what we're doing every week and the plays are there
to be made,'' Coslet said. ``There is no continuity on offense,
there is no rhythm to it. It's hunt and peck, it's all over the
lot. It's not in synch. The plays are there to be made, but for
whatever reason, we're not making the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals will show flashes of firepower, but the flash is
soon darkened by inevitable errors of commission and omission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (potentially successful) plays are there,'' Coslet said.
``We have guys (receivers) open, we have big holes (for backs to
run through), then we have guys breaking down _ missing blocks,
dropping passes, failing to run precise routes and quarterbacks
making some wrong decisions. That's what's plaguing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coslet said he's not trying to put square pegs into round holes,
that the Bengals have the personnel to make the offense work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing the same things that Minnesota, Denver and San
Francisco are doing. If we were doing things differently than
they're doing because I was hard-headed and stubborn, then we'd
have a problem. But we're doing the same things they are, we're
just not executing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those teams do the same things over and over because they're
good at it. We're not good at it. We've been good at in in the past
and we'll be good at it in the future, but we're not good at it
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's play-calling has been criticized and Coslet
understands the frustration. ``It's all in the eye of the beholder
and it's all because we're losing. And I can accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coslet said the talent disparity between the Bengals and their
opponents also has an impact on the play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are (defensive) players you have to account for on every
play,'' Coslet said. ``There were certain things we just couldn't
do against Minnesota because of (All-Pro lineman) John Randle.
There are certain things we won't be able to do against Baltimore
because of (pass-rushing specialist) Michael McCrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just calling these plays out of thin air. It's
tendencies, it's opponents' personnel, it's what we can do. There's
a lot more to it than calling the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end John Copeland, out since rupturing the Achilles'
tendon in his left leg on April 15, was added to the active roster
on Tuesday and is expected to get some playing time against
Baltimore. To make room for Copeland, the Bengals cut offensive
lineman Brock Guttierrez for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Williams writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
