<SLUG> BC-MATT-LAUER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WeeeeeeEEEEEE! `Today' show host up for 4 a.m. siren
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It stinks when you oversleep and have to
suck up to the boss. But it would really stink if you had to grovel
in front of the entire nation.
</P>
<P>
   Behold the Bose Wave clock radio.
</P>
<P>
   The $349 machine, shaped like a cheese wedge, supposedly has
symphonic oomph. At THAT price, it should come with a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wake up right before it goes off,'' says Matt Lauer,
who leaps from the sack at 4 a.m. so that he can arrive at NBC
about an hour later to gear up for Today with co-host Katie Couric.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts out really soft _ weeeeeee _ then gets louder and
louder and louder _ weeeeeEEEEEEEEEEE.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks glance over curiously (he's imitating an alarm clock,
OK?!) as Lauer and I chat at Atlantis Country Club, where he and
Bryant Gumbel, who split Today last year, are playing in the Jay
Robert Lauer Golf Tournament to benefit Hospice of Palm Beach
County. Hospice workers cared for Matt's dad, who died of lung
cancer at his PGA National home in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer, 40, is as gracious as they come. A giddy senior sporting
a golf visor and an ``I LUV MATT'' T-shirt jogs up, and he puts his
arm around her for a photo. He still isn't used to gushing females,
and besides, he just married J. Crew model Annette Roque, 32, last
month.
</P>
<P>
   No, the clock is NEVER on her side of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly wed to a TV producer, Lauer says he didn't collapse
with passion the first time he saw Roque, whom he met on a blind
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those slow-developing things,'' recalls Lauer, a
New York native who says he's ready for kids. ``I don't think I
kissed her for two months.'' (A 7-handicapper and a gentleman!)
</P>
<P>
   What's his secret to wooing so many women?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because we're on so early, and people are in
their underwear or pajamas, and they're just comfortable with us.
We're family.''
</P>
<P>
   And you're free to drop by anytime for a Pop-Tart, dear. I have
some fluffy slippers just for you.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
