<HEADER>
A6244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS19-COX-     11-18 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS19-COX-TAKE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(at)ajc.com x
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that Paula Jones has settled her sexual harassment
lawsuit against President Clinton for $850,000, does that mean she
also will keep the $1 million check presented to her by Abe
Hirschfeld? How does her acceptance of Hirschfeld's million-dollar
offer affect the deal with Clinton, considering that Hirschfeld is
under indictment for income tax evasion?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although there was a splash of publicity surrounding the
transfer Oct. 31 of what appeared to be a $1 million check to Jones
from Hirschfeld, a New York real estate magnate, there was no
actual transfer of funds. In a separate agreement, not made a part
of the filing of the Clinton agreement to pay $850,000 announced
Nov. 13, Jones' lawyers said she renounced any intention to accept
any money from Hirschfeld. In a letter to Clinton lawyer Robert
Bennett, as reported by The New York Times, Jones' lead negotiator,
William McMillan, wrote: ``I further represent to you that the
money from Mr. Abe Hirschfeld is no longer on the table, and that
there will be no payment from Mr. Hirschfeld as a part of the
settlement with Mr. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was concerned over any appearance that
Hirschfeld, who is under indictment on tax fraud charges, was
bailing out the president, the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many (U.S.) World War I veterans are still living?
</P>
<P>
   A: The number is dwindling steadily, but as of mid-November was
about 3,200, according to Tom Thomas of the Department of Veterans
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are U.S. Supreme Court sessions open to spectators?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The public is welcome to attend when the court is
sitting for oral arguments (the next dates are Nov. 30; and Dec. 1,
2, 7, 8 and 9). However, seating is limited and is on a first-come,
first-served basis. Two lines form outside the building, which is
at First Street and Maryland Avenue NE in Washington, across from
the U.S. Capitol. One line is for those wishing to hear an entire
argument; the other for those who want to hear an argument only
briefly. Even when the court is not sitting for oral arguments,
people can visit the Supreme Court building. It's open from 9 a.m.
to 4:30 p.m. Monday through Friday (closed on holidays).
</P>
<P>
   When the court is not in session, lectures are conducted in the
first floor courtroom, every hour on the half-hour between 9:30
a.m. and 3:30 p.m. Information: 202-479-3211 (press 4).
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few days ago, a newspaper item reported the birthday of
Hedy Lamarr, saying she was 85. She was listed as an actress and an
electronic genius. What makes her an electronic genius?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Austrian-born actress, promoted by Hollywood in the 1940s
as ``the world's most beautiful woman,'' is remembered by most
people of a certain age for her scandalous nude run through the
woods in the 1932 Czech film ``Ecstasy''; her six marriages; and
her American debut in the 1938 movie ``Algiers.'' But electrical
engineers also know her as an inventor who, in 1942, patented a
wireless broadcast technology.
</P>
<P>
   The patent, granted to Lamarr and composer George Antheil,
outlined a procedure for shielding radio-controlled torpedoes from
German signal jamming in World War II. The technique called for the
use of devices similar to player piano rolls installed shipboard
and inside the torpedoes. The idea was simple: use the piano rolls
to skip from one frequency to the next in random order, much as a
piano performance moves from one note to the next. The enemy
doesn't know which frequency will come up next.
</P>
<P>
   This concept came to be called frequency hopping and was turned
over to the military during the war. But it didn't make its debut
until the Cuban missile crisis of 1962, when it was used for radio
communications. It led to the modern-day notion of spread spectrum,
or the spreading of a signal among many frequencies to prevent
interference, eavesdropping or jamming.
</P>
<P>
   Lamarr, born in Vienna in 1913 as Hedwig Eva Maria Keisler, at
last report was living in seclusion in Altamonte Springs, Fla. She
was last in the news in April when she sued a Canadian company for
using her name and image on its Internet site without her
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Around 1991, the Central Intelligence Agency unveiled a
sculpture called ``Kryptos'' in the courtyard of its headquarters
in Langley, Va. The sculpture, by James Sanborn, includes a coded
message. Has it ever been decoded? Is it possible to get a copy of
the message?
</P>
<P>
   A: A CIA analyst working on his own time has solved ``the lion's
share'' of it, but it hasn't been completely decoded, CIA spokesman
Mark Mansfield told Q&AMP;A. He said the best way to describe the
sculpture is to say it incorporates natural building materials
native to America and includes an encoded copper screen. When and
if someone completely solves the message, a decision will be made
about releasing it to the public, ``but we're not at that point
yet,'' Mansfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Sculptor Sanborn, of Washington, has created another work with
an encoded message for the University of North Carolina at
Charlotte. ``The Cyrillic Projector,'' an 8-foot-tall bronze
cylinder, was installed in April 1997 in a plaza between two
university buildings. The sculpture is perforated with Cyrillic
letters, the alphabet used in the Russian language. After it was
installed, Sanborn told a reporter that he had given Charlotte ``a
mystery, a puzzle.'' But in that case, he also gave observers a
head start on solving the puzzle by providing a chart to help
decode the message. He described the Charlotte sculpture as ``not
very difficult,'' adding that the work he created for the CIA
headquarters is so hard to break that the CIA ``will never figure
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to the excavation of the tombs of the sons of
Egyptian Pharaoh Ramses II? I recall that work was to begin about
four years ago. Was anything ever discovered? Is excavation still
going on?
</P>
<P>
   A: Egyptologists are continuing their excavations of the royal
tomb known as KV 5 (the fifth tomb beyond the entrance to KV, the
King's Valley). The latest mapping study and excavation project on
KV 5 began in 1989, because the roadway at the entrance to the
valley was being widened and experts didn't want any damage to
occur to the tomb in its path.
</P>
<P>
   A detailed account of the project is in the September issue of
National Geographic. It reports that before 1989, no one had
ventured inside KV 5 since 1825. The tomb has turned out to be the
largest ever found in the Valley of the Kings, according to
National Geographic. The burial place of many of the sons of Ramses
II, it contains at least 110 chambers, with many artifacts and
hieroglyphics promising to captivate excavation officials for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to the Wal-Mart heiress who was in the news
some months ago on a drunk-driving charge?
</P>
<P>
   A: Alice Walton, 49, was cited Jan. 27 in Arkansas with DWI
(driving while intoxicated) and other traffic violations after her
Toyota 4-Runner careened off a road and destroyed a gas meter and
telephone box. When she was taken to a hospital for treatment of a
broken nose, she refused a blood alcohol test. One of four children
of the late Sam Walton and his wife, Helen, and owner of the
investment banking firm Llama Co., she reportedly became
belligerent, telling one Springdale, Ark., officer: ``You know who
I am, don't you? You know my last name?''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than accepting a conventional plea offer to settle the
case, their heiress chose to fight the charges in court, and in May
she was convicted on four counts: driving while intoxicated,
violation of Arkansas' implied consent law, driving without a seat
belt, and failing to maintain proper control of her vehicle.
Although she faced as much as a year in jail and $1,025 in fines,
she got off easier when she was sentenced June 17 in Springdale
Municipal Court: $350 fine, $300 court costs, and 24 hours of
public service. ``She paid up and completed her public service, so
everything's taken care of,'' court spokeswoman Betty Lee told Q&AMP;A.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Walton stepped down as chief executive of Llama Co.
She apparently has moved her legal residence to Texas, which would
enable her to shield her $11 billion in net worth from state income
taxes in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When is Take Our Daughters to Work day scheduled for 1999?
</P>
<P>
   A: It will be April 22. Take Our Daughters to Work day is always
the fourth Thursday each April, said Kelly Parisi of the Ms.
Foundation for Women in New York, the organization that founded the
special day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently mentioned that Toronto's CN Tower is the world's
tallest free-standing structure. Is there a taller structure that
is not free-standing?
</P>
<P>
   A: CN Tower rises to 1,815 feet and 5 inches, according to The
Guinness Book of World Records (1998). It's not a mast with guy
wires to steady or support it, in other words. The world's tallest
structure is a stayed television transmitting tower between Fargo
and Blanchard in North Dakota. Built for KTHI-TV, it is 2,063 feet
tall. Before it fell during renovation work in 1991, the guyed
Warszawa Radio mast in Konstantynow, Poland, held the record of
tallest-ever structure in the world at 2,120 feet tall. It was
first put into operation in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MORE
</P>
