<HEADER>
A6245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN19-COX     11-18 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where do children find their courage?
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ There's something about the courage of children.
Something bold, unapologetic and unself-conscious about it.
</P>
<P>
   The day I met Belynda Denney, then 7, she did something no adult
I know would have the guts to do. She handed Hillary Clinton a
scrawled ``I love you'' note and invited herself to the White
House, just like that.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, The first lady said, ``Come on down.'' Mrs.
Clinton met Belynda, a child ambassador for Children's Medical
Center, while making a campaign stop at the hospital in September
1996. A month later, The first lady gave Belynda, a fourth-grader
at Timberlane Elementary School in Northridge, Ohio, a private tour
of the White House. Belynda made fast friends with Socks the cat,
sat behind the president's desk, and pronounced the White House
``cool.'' Her parents, Bob and Sue, were scared to death by their
brush with greatness; Belynda was unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton thought it was funny that a bald 7-year-old would
just speak her mind and say what she wanted. But that's Belynda,''
said Vicki Giambrone, vice president of marketing and development
for Children's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Belynda died Monday night, just a week shy of her 10th birthday.
She was at home, surrounded by everyone she loved _ and had
commanded to her bedside. She chose the belongings she wanted in
her casket with her: her Tweetie blanket, her teddy bear, her
favorite clothes. Even in her last days, she maintained her
trademark joie de vivre, not to mention her ability to give orders.
</P>
<P>
   During her last hospital visit, her oncologist tried to explain
the results to her parents in the hallway. ``You come in here and
you talk in front of me,'' Belynda said. ``What are my options?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was dying Monday, she told us 'I feel fine','' said
her father, Bob. ``There was never a bad day for her. She had a
wonderful time. In her mind she wasn't different; she just had this
pesty little thing called cancer that made her take a few trips to
the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not surprising Belynda wasn't intimidated by the
White House. What were a few famous folks compared with what she
had been up against? At the age of 6, she was diagnosed with Ewing
sarcoma, a form of bone cancer. At 7 _ the dawning of the age of
self-consciousness _ she became one of two 1996-1997 ambassadors
for Children's Medical Center. She would pose for photos and greet
the public without a trace of embarrassment. ``Belynda wanted to be
the way she was, and she didn't have a problem showing her bald
head,'' Giambrone said.
</P>
<P>
   A little boy came up to her on the playground once, her father
recalled, and asked, ``Are you a girl or a boy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A girl,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then why don't you have hair?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a gene in my body called cancer, and it makes my hair
fall out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, OK,'' the boy said, and went back to his play.
</P>
<P>
   She was a child who showed more courage in nine years than most
of us muster in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belynda wanted to be a teacher, and she fulfilled that dream
because she taught us all so many things,'' Giambrone said. ``She
taught me to speak your mind, to always be looking for the miracles
in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it wasn't only her courage in the face of cancer that struck
me when I met her. It was her joy in the face of life.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to meet the first lady. She wanted to go to the White
House. She giggled. She hugged strangers liberally.
</P>
<P>
   What makes children so curious, so full of life, in the face of
things so frightening.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about that a few weeks ago when 5-year-old Emma
Russell came back to my husband's church for the first time in
seven months. Her hair cropped fashionably short, Emma wore a
black-and-white two-piece vest suit with a panache that put all of
us grown-up women to shame. ``She likes to wear big girl clothes _
nothing frilly,'' explains her mother, Kathleen Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Emma runs around with the other kids at the coffee hour at Grace
United Methodist Church. She comes back for seconds on cookies. She
is, in other words, a full-fledged kid.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago, Emma was diagnosed with a rare, cancerous
kidney tumor and given less than a 50 percent chance to live.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has endured radiation treatments, intermittent
fevers, platelet and blood transfusions, and nearly seven months of
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   She never stopped jumping on the bed. She never stopped begging
to play outside. She cracked up the hospital staff _ and the doctor
himself _ by mimicking her oncologist's accent. The only time she
felt really put out was when she found out she couldn't get her
kidney back. She peppered her father, Steve, with a lot of
questions about that.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she didn't understand what was happening to her. While
making crafts during chemotherapy once, she made her mother a
beaded bracelet. As she placed it on her mother's wrist she said,
``I want you to wear this to remember me in case I die.''
</P>
<P>
   Emma's resilience gave her parents a resilience they never knew
they had. They were rewarded recently with good news: a battery of
tests that all came back clean. If Emma stays cancer-free for two
years, she will be considered cured.
</P>
<P>
   Now they face medical bills exceeding $100,000. Kathleen and
Steve Russell are ``overwhelmed'' _ not by their debts, but by the
generosity of co-workers and friends who have rallied to help. This
Saturday, a garage sale _ children's clothes, books and toys _ will
be held from 8 a.m. to 3:30 in the gym at Grace United Methodist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Emma's parents never gave up because Emma never gave up.
</P>
<P>
   Belynda Denney never did either. Her last words to her
oncologist, as she was leaving Children's Medical Center for the
last time: ``I'm going to hold out for that miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something about the courage of children.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
