<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS19-COX-TAKE2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: operation in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of ``Uncle Sam''?
</P>
<P>
   A: The term is believed to date to the era of the War of 1812.
According to the story, Samuel Wilson, a meat packer in Troy, N.Y.,
was jokingly referred to by his employees as ``Uncle Sam,''
apparently because his company stamped the letters U.S. on food
containers intended for the armed services. The first picture of
``Uncle Sam'' as we know him today appeared in Harper's magazine in
1869. It looked forward to the first of the America's Cup races
between Britain and the United States, which took place the
following year. The cartoon showed Uncle Sam _ top hat, striped
trousers and all _ holding the America's Cup aloft and smiling
confidently while the British symbol, John Bull, glowers menacingly
from across the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several months ago, I read that Pope John Paul II would visit
St. Louis in January. I haven't seen anything since then. Do you
have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The pope will be in St. Louis Jan. 26-27, following a visit
to Mexico City, Bill Ryan of the U.S. Catholic Conference said.
Plans call for the pope to participate in a prayer service at a
youth rally Jan. 26 in Kiel Center. The next morning, he will
celebrate Mass at the Trans World Dome, and later that day will
take part in a prayer service at the Cathedral Basilica of St.
Louis. After that, he'll fly back to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Joe DiMaggio is reported to be seriously ill and in the
hospital. Where can fans send get-well cards?
</P>
<P>
   A: He's at Memorial Regional Hospital, 3501 Johnson St.,
Hollywood, FL 33021. The New York Yankees great, 83, was first
hospitalized Oct. 12 and has been fighting since then to recover
from pneumonia and a lung infection. His condition was described at
first as life-threatening, but then made a brief recovery before
suffering another setback. Earlier this month, Morris Engelberg,
DiMaggio's lawyer and friend, said the Hall of Famer would be in
intensive care for six to eight weeks, then would need
rehabilitation to get over the lengthy hospitalization. DiMaggio's
84th birthday will be Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that an Indiana man, George Bauer,
is suing Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. over tactics the company uses to
collect credit-card debts from bankrupt customers. I'm in that same
situation. The article mentions that Bauer and his attorneys are
asking that the suit become a class-action case. How can I contact
the attorneys involved?
</P>
<P>
   A: The lead lawyer is Daniel Edelman of Edelman and Combs, 135
S. LaSalle St., Suite 2040, Chicago, IL 60603 (312-739-4200).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Jesse Ventura, who ran for governor of Minnesota as a Reform
Party candidate, got lots of publicity after his recent victory. Is
he the first Reform Party candidate ever to win an election?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ventura isn't the first Reform candidate ever to win an
election, but he's the party's first candidate to win a statewide
election, said party chairman Russell Verney in Dallas. The first
Reform candidate to win an election was David Bieler, who in 1997
ran for a county supervisor position in Stafford County, Va. There
have been other municipal and county officials who ran in
nonpartisan races but are aligned with the Reform Party, Verney
said. Reform candidates running in statewide elections across the
United States received more than 2 million votes in the Nov. 3
election, he added. The Reform Party's Mae Schunk was elected
Minnesota's lieutenant governor, by the way, to serve with Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened in connection with Pierre Salinger's
allegation that the Navy was involved in the crash of TWA 800? I
never heard about any final resolution.
</P>
<P>
   A: The whole matter appears to have been dropped after Ian
Goddard, the man who used the Internet to accuse the Navy of
shooting TWA 800 down in July 1996, told CNN that his actions were
``reckless and a mistake.'' Goddard had used the Internet to
release a report, cowritten by Salinger and Mike Sommer, identified
as a former investigative reporter and ABC news executive, claiming
the government was covering up the fact that a Navy missile brought
the plane down. As news reports said at the time, the report
contained few documented facts and was packed with unattributed
quotes, technical jargon and rambling speculation. Salinger never
actually admitted that he was wrong, but he suddenly fell silent
about the claim. He did admit to calling FBI boss James Kallstrom
in October 1996 to say he no longer was investigating the crash.
The FBI confirmed Salinger's call to Kallstrom, but didn't provide
any details.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A TV program about unsanitary conditions at hotels and motels
reminded me that many people died after attending a convention some
years ago at a Philadelphia hotel. Can you refresh my memory about
that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was in July 1976 when an epidemic struck 221 people
attending an American Legion convention at Philadelphia's Bellevue
Stratford Hotel. The mysterious illness came to be known as
Legionnaires' disease. In 1977, scientists discovered the cause of
the pneumonia, a bacterium they named Legionella pneumophila.
Research showed that it commonly occurs in water supplies, and in
the case of the hotel was believed to have occurred when victims
breathed contaminated air coming through the air-conditioning
system. It's now known that the disease can be treated with such
antibiotics as erythromycin and rifampin. In the Philadelphia
outbreak, 34 of those stricken with the disease died.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Former President George Bush and wife Barbara have two sons,
George, governor of Texas, and Jeb, governor-elect of Florida. Do
they have any other children? What do they do?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Bushes had four sons and two daughters. George W. was
born in 1946. Robin, born in 1949, died of leukemia in 1953. John
(Jeb) was born in 1953. Other than George W. and Jeb, none of the
others has shown an interest in politics, and basically they stay
out of the news.
</P>
<P>
   Neil, born in 1955, was embroiled in controversy for a time when
he was a director of the Silverado Banking, Savings and Loan
Association in Colorado, which failed in 1988, costing taxpayers an
estimated $1 billion. Although he never was charged with criminal
wrongdoing, he agreed to pay $50,000 in 1992 to settle a civil
lawsuit lodged two years earlier by the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. Since moving to Houston in 1992, he has established a new
career in international business with Interlink Management Corp.,
consulting on behalf of U.S. and foreign companies working mostly
on overseas ventures. He keeps what a friend called ``a very low
profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin, born in 1956, maintains an even lower profile. Reports
published earlier said he lives in a Virginia suburb of Washington,
is a partner in an investment advisory firm and a franchisee in a
video rental business.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy, born in 1959, was in the news most recently in 1992
when she married Bobby Koch, formerly a top aide to House
Democratic leader Richard Gephardt. It was her second marriage. At
last report, she was working in fund-raising at the National
Rehabilitation Hospital in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard something around Veterans Day about fund-raising
efforts for the construction of a World War II memorial in
Washington. Do you have any information about it? How can I
contribute?
</P>
<P>
   A: Former Sen. Bob Dole announced a drive in March 1997 to raise
$100 million to build the memorial on a 7.4-acre site between the
Washington Monument and the Lincoln Memorial. Private funds will
pay for most of the construction and upkeep for the memorial, which
sponsors hope to open on Veterans Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the memorial's site, design and Registry
of Remembrance, and how you can contribute, call 1-800-639-4992.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported that four U.S. presidents have been
assassinated while in office. How many assassination attempts have
been made on U.S. presidents while in office?
</P>
<P>
   A: Attempts were made against the lives of Presidents Andrew
Jackson (Jan. 30, 1835); Harry Truman (Nov. 1, 1950); Gerald Ford
(twice: Sept. 5, 1975, and Sept. 22, 1975;) and Ronald Reagan
(March 30, 1981). Attempts also were made against Abraham Lincoln
and Franklin Delano Roosevelt when they were presidents-elect, and
against former President Theodore Roosevelt three years after he
left office, when he was campaigning for election again.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Aug. 28, 1965, that Congress enacted a law
making it a federal crime to kill, kidnap or assault the president,
vice president, or president-elect, or to threaten these officials
with bodily harm or death. Before then, it was a state matter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between a stepbrother and a half
brother?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Step'' is the combining form related through the remarriage
of a parent. Your stepbrother, then, is the son of your stepmother
or stepfather by his or her former marriage. A half brother is a
brother through one parent only. In other words, a half brother is
a male offspring having only one parent in common with another
offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm aware of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, but I'm
told that a list has been made of the Seven Wonders of the Modern
World. If that's so, what are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: You may be referring to the septet chosen by the American
Society of Civil Engineers in conjunction with Popular Mechanics
magazine. Here's the group's list of modern wonders, released in
March 1996: the 5-mile-wide, $18 billion Itaipu Dam on the Parana
River on the Brazil-Paraguay border; Toronto's 1,815-foot CN Tower,
the world's tallest free-standing structure; the 51-mile-long
Panama Canal; San Francisco's Golden Gate Bridge; the 31-mile-long
Channel Tunnel, between England and France; the Netherlands North
Sea Protection Works, a network of dams, sluices, canals and dikes
built to protect southwest Holland from flooding on the delta of
the Meuse and Rhine rivers; and the 1,248-foot Empire State
Building, for four decades the tallest building in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
