<HEADER>
A6249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEPHONE-MADNESS19-C     11-18 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEPHONE-MADNESS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hold the phone! A once-easy decision is now almost overwhelming
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Just 20 years ago the choices for a telephone for
your house were simple.
</P>
<P>
   Console, wall, princess. Black, white, pink. Maybe avocado for
the truly adventurous.
</P>
<P>
   But when Linn Hughes and Jim Leonard visited a Beavercreek, Ohio
Best Buy store last week, they found a selection of about 50
cordless phones, 30 corded phones, at least a dozen cellular phone
models and a separate display rack full of telephone/answering
machine combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, of Huber Heights, Ohio, wanted a cordless phone with a
caller ID screen in the handset. ``We've already got a cordless
phone I bought about six months ago,'' he said. ``I want another
one so my wife can have her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, of Beavercreek, also was looking for his second
cordless phone. ``I want a two-line phone with a switch to turn off
the ringer on the second line,'' he said. ``I use the second line
for my home computer most of the time, and I don't need that line
to ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that deregulation has loosened Ma Bell's control of
telephones, the options open to phone users have exploded. And as
the competition grows, the prices plummet.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard settled on a 25-channel cordless phone for about $100,
which he said would have cost about twice as much only a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in the market for a new phone for your home, you can
get one that fits your needs and lifestyle almost perfectly for a
reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
   But because the selection is so vast and confusing, you need to
understand what's out there or you're likely to spend more than you
need to or get less than you want.
</P>
<P>
   CORDLESS PHONES
</P>
<P>
   Until about 10 years ago, almost all home telephones had a cord
that attached the handset to a base.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, however, cordless phones that use radio signals to
connect the handset to the base outsold conventional corded phones
for the first time, according to Jim Barry, a spokesman for the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Americans bought 28.2 million cordless phones last year compared
with 27.8 corded phones, and the gap is likely to widen this year
as people buy second cordless phones for themselves or as gifts.
About 45 percent of all Ameritech phones sold are purchased in
November in December, the heaviest Christmas shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're getting with a cordless phone is convenience,''
Barry said. ``And the technology of cordless phones is getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The first cordless phones on the market allowed users to walk
from one room to the next without dragging a phone cord behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   However, the first phones were prone to interference, had
limited range and lacked security.
</P>
<P>
   They used a simple analog signal to transmit sound from the
handset to the base, and it was common for neighbors to overhear
cordless phone conversations from other homes. Baby monitors also
broadcast across cordless phone lines occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule is you should never say anything over a cordless
phone or a cellular phone that you don't want to see on the front
page of the newspaper,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   Newer phones broadcast on frequencies that are not as crowded,
and they offer clearer signals. Plus many of them use digital
signals: They convert sounds into computer code and transmit the
code between the base and the handset.
</P>
<P>
   Because the transmissions are coded the chance of having
conversations intercepted is lower, but your conversations still
aren't 100 percent secure.
</P>
<P>
   CORDED PHONES
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity of cordless phones, corded phones still
have the edge in dependability and security, Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   Corded phones also are usually significantly cheaper than
cordless models, with many basic models selling for less than $10.
Of course, you can't expect perfect, consistent sound quality from
an $8 phone. Still, a person buying a cordless phone just to reach
several rooms might save money buying two or three moderately
priced corded phones and spreading them around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you prefer cordless phones, you should probably have an
inexpensive corded phone for use during power outages, when the
base unit of a cordless phone won't work. Corded phones get all the
power they need from the phone line, which uses backup power
systems to stay in operation.
</P>
<P>
   Corded phones also offer the most variation in style. While
cordless phones tend to have a streamlined, businesslike look,
corded phones are available in most colors and in novelty shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are headset phones, according to Jeff Small, a
marketing official for Ameritech's consumer division.
</P>
<P>
   Small said people who use headsets at work often like the
convenience of a phone that clips to their belts and has an
earpiece and microphone held in place by a flexible head strap.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get past the corded-cordless division, most phones
operate about the same.
</P>
<P>
   A few phones with old-style rotary dials are being manufactured
as nostalgia items, Barry said, but the tone-producing push button
is the heart of the modern phone.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all cordless phones have number buttons in the handset,
though some have buttons on the handset and the base.
</P>
<P>
   Corded phones often have buttons in the handset as well, but
it's easy to find corded phones with buttons on the base. That
allows you to punch in a number without taking the phone away from
your ear. It also allows larger number keys.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER PHONE FEATURES
</P>
<P>
   According to Small, the most popular extra features for
telephones are call waiting, caller ID and voice mail, in that
order.
</P>
<P>
   Any telephone is compatible with call-waiting service. When
you're on the phone and someone calls, you hear an audible signal.
You may click the receiver button or push ``flash'' to answer the
second call.
</P>
<P>
   You pay extra for call-waiting service, but you don't need
special equipment to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Caller ID, on the other hand, requires an LCD screen for
displaying information about incoming calls.
</P>
<P>
   Both cordless and corded phones can be purchased with caller ID
screens included, or you can buy separate caller ID boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Having the caller ID screen in the handset may be the most
convenient option. Some phones store numbers from caller ID in the
phone's memory for later use.
</P>
<P>
   However, built-in caller ID features raise the costs of
telephones and having a separate caller ID box might be cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Also, what do you do if a built-in caller ID feature stops
working while the rest of the phone is fine? Do you throw the whole
phone away? With separate units, replacing broken components might
be cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   You can have voice mail on any push-button phone, according to
Small. But phones designed to work with voice mail often have
lights that tell you at a glance when you have a message waiting,
and the lights make them much more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Voice mail is particularly useful if you have only one phone
line and have a computer linked to the Internet. Voice mail
automatically ships incoming calls to your mailbox when the
computer is online.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature that is increasingly popular is the two-line
phone, Small said. Many people have added a second line to their
homes, primarily for their computers.
</P>
<P>
   A two-line phone makes it convenient to use the computer line as
a second voice line when the computer is offline.
</P>
<P>
   Other features you might want to consider are storage for
frequently dialed numbers, speakers for hands-free conversation or
an answering machine if you don't want voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   GLANCE BOX
</P>
<P>
   Types of cordless phones:
</P>
<P>
   _ STANDARD CORDLESS PHONES: The first cordless home phones
operated on frequencies of about 43 to 49 MHz and were susceptible
to interference from fluorescent lights, computers and other
devices. Also transmissions at those frequencies usually can't
penetrate walls or other obstructions. Most of the earliest phones
operated on 10 channels _ if they found a lot of interference on
one channel they would automatically switch to the next. Some
discounters still offer 10-channel phones at low prices, but newer
models are superior.
</P>
<P>
   _ 25-CHANNEL ANALOG PHONES: The next step up from the 10-channel
phones offers generally clearer sound quality because it has more
channels to avoid interference. Also 25-channel phones often come
with popular features such as caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   _ 900MHZ ANALOG PHONES: These phones operate at high frequencies
and are less likely to get interference from baby monitors and
similar devices. Their range is also better than older models, and
their signals penetrate obstructions better. You probably will be
able to use a 900MHz analog phone from your yard or even from the
sidewalk a few houses away. Jim Barry of the Consumer Electronics
Manufacturers Association said some phones operate reliably at
three-quarters of a mile. The signal still is broadcast uncoded,
however, so security might be a concern.
</P>
<P>
   _ 900MHZ DIGITAL PHONES: In addition to operating at high
frequency, 900MHz digital phones communicate with their base
through digital signals, which is more secure. The sound quality
may be a little clearer than 900MHz analog phones, but sound varies
from brand to brand. The ranges of 900MHz analog and digital phones
are fairly comparable. Be careful when shopping for 900MHz phones;
it's easy to mistake an analog phone for a digital one if you don't
read the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   _ 900MHZ DIGITAL SPREAD SPECTRUM PHONES: Like all cordless
phones, spread spectrum units can operate on several frequencies.
But when a spread spectrum phone encounters interference on one
channel it doesn't just switch to an adjacent channel: It tries to
find the channel farthest away from the blocked channel. Spread
spectrum technology increases the phone's clarity and range.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2.4GHZ DIGITAL PHONES: Barry said only Panasonic, so far, is
marketing phones that operate at frequencies in the 2.4GHz range,
which is even higher than 900MHz. Panasonic claims its 2.4GHz
phones experience less interference and have twice the range of
spread spectrum phones. At about $250, they're fairly expensive,
however
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
