<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Nov. 18, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STATION-LAUNCH (Undated) _ The first phase of the U.S.-led
international space station begins early Friday in Russia with the
launching of the first station component. ``After years of
discussing, planning and replanning, we're about to launch hardware
and embark on one of the most complex engineering projects in human
history,'' said Gretchen McClain, NASA's deputy associate
administrator for the project. By MARK CARREAU
</P>
<P>
   STATION-RUSSIANS (Houston) _ When it comes to space stations,
Russia's experience is unmatched. And a partnership between the
United States and Russia offers a world of promise _ and problems.
By MARK CARREAU
</P>
<P>
   STATION-FUTURE (Houston) _ An experimental spacecraft and
research laboratory, the international space station promises to be
a little of both as it zips around Earth at an altitude of 250
miles. But achieving the facility's full science and engineering
potential will take time. By MARK CARREAU
</P>
<P>
   STATION-SUITS (Houston) _ Dozens of U.S. astronauts will wear
$10 million spacesuits for spacewalks during the more than six
years it will take to build the U.S.-led international space
station. By MARK CARREAU
</P>
<P>
   STATION-TIMELINE (Undated) _ A timeline that begins with the
Soviet Union's launch of Sputnik I, the first man-made Earth
satellite, to Friday's scheduled launch of the first station
component, a U.S.-financed, Russian-built propulsion and guidance
module called ``Zarya,'' or ``Sunrise.''
</P>
<P>
   FACE-PIES (San Francisco) _ Mayor Willie Brown, in his first
extensive public statements about being pied, said the criminal
justice system should make ``an example'' of the pie-throwers to
discourage similar incidents. By GERGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-CONFUSION (San Francisco) _ When the new anti-psychotic
drug Zyprexa debuted two years ago, several pharmacists reading
those prescriptions mistook it for Zyrtec, an antihistamine. At
least two dozen times, people prescribed Navane for schizophrenia
instead got the high blood pressure medication Norvasc, research
data has shown. Some mix-ups among drugs with similar names have
resulted in deaths. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE (San Francisco) _ A voter initiative to outlaw
same-sex marriage will be on the California primary ballot in 2000.
The initiative would both ban same-sex marriage in California and
prohibit the state from recognizing gay marriages performed legally
in other states. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THANKSGIVING-DINNER (Undated) _ This is the BIG one.
Thanksgiving. Possibly the most anticipated and scrutinized
home-cooked meal of the year. There are even rules for this dinner.
By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIANS-CAPITALISM (San Francisco) _ In Russia, small
businesses are taxed so heavily it stunts their growth, laws
governing business are few, and franchising is virtually unheard
of. But the lack of rules gives hope to a group of Russian lawyers
visiting San Francisco this month. They say they have the
opportunity to create a legal infrastructure that will help
Russia's pioneering entrepreneurs. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX (Las Vegas, Nev.) _ Microsoft President Steve Ballmer
declared this week that the software giant was ``spot on'' in its
business practices and would not back down from the government's
antitrust lawyers. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TARA-LIPINSKI (Albany, N.Y.) _ Tara Lipinski doesn't lead a
normal life. Never has, really. Probably never will. ``Describe
normal,'' Lipinski was saying after another workout on another rink
in another city that isn't home. ``I think my life is very normal
to me. I know in some ways it's different or busier. But I love
it.'' By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Jim Hones has come home to roost
at City Hall, the temporary one in the Veterans Building. He stares
from behind dark glasses from posters on the first floor, and from
photographs arrayed near the Board of Supervisors' meeting room on
the fourth floor. Twenty years later, it's almost unbearable to
look at these photographs of Jones and Jonestown. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
