<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DUMMIES' SERIES SMART FOR NEOPHYTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY   
 c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Among the many computer books out there,
``Windows for Dummies'' has been recommended. I am keeping in mind
that this comes from my ex-boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wisdom Seeker
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SEEKER: Well, he was wrong about everything else, wasn't
he? No, wait! That's what my ex says about me. Your situation is
probably very different from the shrill, shrieking horror of my
life.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, those ``Dummies'' books are a great place to start if
you're totally in the dark. Just make sure they're not too
fundamental for you. Go to the bookstore, plop down with a latte
and a laptop and do some ``browsing.'' Or go to www.dummies.com and
read sample chapters before you shell out 20 bucks for something
you may not even need.
</P>
<P>
   You know, those people have a book for just about everything.
There's even ``Sex for Dummies.'' Hmmmm. I should have bought that
one for that shrew of a ... Sorry! Didn't mean to let my personal
life intrude. It won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have some questions about your collum first
are you a hacker and if you are not how do you know so much about
it.i mean i know your a profeeser or something like that.but you
must know how to hack.By the way please send alot more info on the
hacker stuff.because i am very intrested.thanks
</P>
<P>
   _ AntiUser1
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ANTI: Your teachers must be mighty proud of you.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is there a scanner available that will transmit
text intact? Will a single scanner do both text and graphics?
</P>
<P>
   _ Word for Word
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WORD: In case some brain-dead salesclerk can't give you a
straight answer, just about any scanner you buy can do both. The
scanner simply takes a picture of the page. Character-recognition
software, which ought to come with the scanner, does its best to
recognize letters in that picture and turn them into text in a new
file. A blurry or smudged original means lots of typos, so try to
keep from spilling your tropical drink all over the page before
scanning.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Almost every week you tell us some new ``stupid
software trick'' the Microsoft engineers have put in their
products. Is this why their programs are so ridiculously large?
</P>
<P>
   _ Size Matters
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SIZE: Those little Easter eggs only take up a fraction of
the space in the programs. Microsoft applications are so
ridiculously large because they do about 700 times the number of
things most casual users need. For instance, Microsoft has been
adding on to Word since Bill Gates' acne cleared up, making it
bigger and bigger.
</P>
<P>
   In almost all Microsoft setup programs, there is an option for
``custom'' installation. Use that, and you can pick and choose
exactly how much stuff to install.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of software tricks, you guys aren't playing fair.
You're supposed to be sending me stuff. I'm tired of just giving
and giving and giving. But it was always about you, wasn't it? I
should have seen how selfish you were, but, no, I let you walk all
over me. Well, not anymore. You're not the boss of ... Whoops! Did
it again, didn't I?
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay isn't bitter about
anything. No, really, he's totally over it now. Unless you're a
certain someone, he can be reached at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101, or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
