<HEADLINE>
THE HIGH-TECH TOY BOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By KELLY DeGARMO   
 c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe you're not energized for the holidays, but the toys are.
From Furby and Psycho to Bounce Around Tigger, the hot-selling
playthings are stuffed with electronic guts.
</P>
<P>
   Even the latest board games by Parker Bros., trucks by Tonka and
construction kits from Lego have entered a new dimension.
Everything, it seems, is powered by batteries and electricity. Who
needs parents for meaningful interaction?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the ultimate high-tech wish list for the season:
</P>
<P>
   _The Bounce Around Tigger doll, $30: He giggles, he bounces, he
says: ``Bouncing's what Tiggers do best.''
</P>
<P>
   _Plush Teletubbies aliens, $24.99: Press the tummies of these
PBS television creations, and they come to life.
</P>
<P>
   _Tyco's Blues Clues Sing-Along Blue, $20: Hear the show's theme
song with the squeeze of a paw.
</P>
<P>
   _Barney's Magic Banjo by Playskool, $29: A jammin' instrument
for age 2 and up.
</P>
<P>
   _Rokenbok Expandable Radio Control Building System ($149 set):
Allows kids to build and operate their own vehicles and play
stations. An electricity-driven command deck and control pad put
the player in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   _Follow-the-Lights Talking Phone by Mattel ($28): An
illuminating phone with a mode that helps children learn their
phone numbers. With Disney characters; for children 18 months and
older.
</P>
<P>
   _Hug'n Learn Little Leap by Leap Frog, $35: Winner of the 1998
Dr. Toy Best Product. Teaches phonics, alphabet, counting, colors,
logic and more to preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   _Emiglio the radio-controlled robot, $99: Rolls across the room
to deliver items on his tray, gripped by his spring-loaded hand.
</P>
<P>
   _R.A.D. Robot by ToyMax (about $100): Picks up objects and fires
foam missiles.
</P>
<P>
   _Psycho from Tyco, $60: A vehicle with two huge Gyro-Force rear
tires that runs into the fridge, rolls over and zooms back into
action.
</P>
<P>
   _9.6V Sky Driver from Hasbro ($57): Another terrain-eating
vehicle, which will tumble over grass, dirt and rocks.
</P>
<P>
   _Computer ``soft'' ware: My Interactive Pooh from Mattel, $99;
ActiMates Interactive line by Microsoft, $99 to $115, featuring
Barney, Arthur and D.W. Based on the popular PBS show, Arthur and
D.W. take instructions from a CD-ROM and interact with the official
Arthur Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Low-tech favorites:
</P>
<P>
   _Zoob, any Zoob: The of-the-moment construction toy from
Primordial. The lineup ranges from the Zoob Dude ($6.99) to the
Zoob Toons 120-units kit ($49.99).
</P>
<P>
   _K'NEX: Building sets, transport vehicles, solar power kits and
the ultimate, a K-Force Defense Station ($1.99-$44.99).
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Scarry's Busytown Grocery ($14.99 to $34.99): The
latest train-building set from Brio.
</P>
<P>
   _Dicovery Toys' Giant Pegboard Toy, $13: Boosts fine-motor
skills, available from Discovery Toys at (817) 481-4105.
</P>
<P>
   _Surf Frog toy aquarium from Uncle Milton Industries, $25: Comes
with a coupon for a mail-order tadpole, which becomes a leopard
frog. Available at Store of Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   _Barbie, any Barbie: But especially NBA Barbie, $22.99, and
Happy Holidays Barbie, $33. One dresses in different team jerseys,
the other dons a black velvet ball gown. (And don't forget two new
Barbie CD-ROM interactive toy games, My Very Own Horse, $34.99, and
Barbie Digital Camera, $65).
</P>
<P>
   _Sesame Street Bean Pals, $4.99: A spinoff of Ty Beanie Baby
success; great for stocking stuffers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
