<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TROUBLED MIR TO COME DOWN TO EARTH AS NEW SPACE STATION GOES UP
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-SPACE-1119; SPACE-STATION-1119.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As the new International Space Station goes up, Russian
space officials are trying to decide just when to bring down their
battered but beloved Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities have announced that they intend to bring the
12-year-old Mir station to earth in mid-1999, concluding its
service with a fiery re-entry into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But some Russian officials believe Mir should remain aloft, as a
symbol of Russian autonomy in space, and as a hedge against delays
in completion of the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at Mir's history:
</P>
<P>
   1986 -- Mir's 20-ton central module is launched into orbit; with
an estimated life-span of five years, Mir replaces the series of
smaller Salyut space stations operated by the Soviet Union in the
1970s and '80s
</P>
<P>
   1987 -- The 11-ton Kvant-1 module, with astrophysics and
life-support equipment, is launched and added to Mir.
</P>
<P>
   1989 -- A biological research station, the 20-ton Kvant-2
module, is attached to Mir.
</P>
<P>
   1990 -- The 20-ton Kristall research module is launched and
added to Mir; Soviet authorities shelve plans to launch a Mir-2
space station as talks proceed with international partners on
building an international space station.
</P>
<P>
   1991 -- The Soviet Union collapses; ensuing economic problems
prompt Russia to begin talks with United States on sharing Mir.
</P>
<P>
   1994 -- Russia and the U.S. agree to joint missions aboard Mir,
with NASA paying $500 million to subsidize the Russian program; a
docking module is added to Mir to allow link-up with American space
shuttles.
</P>
<P>
   1995 -- In February, the shuttle Discovery docks with Mir; In
May, Mir expands with the 20-ton Spektr module, carrying Russian
and American research equipment
</P>
<P>
   1996 -- Launch of the 20-ton Priroda research module.
</P>
<P>
   1997 -- On Feb. 23, a flash-fire occurs aboard Mir, the first in
a series of mishaps culminating on June 25, when the unmanned
Progress cargo ship collides with Spektr, nearly forcing the crew
of two Russian cosmonauts and American astronaut Michael Foale to
evacuate Mir.
</P>
<P>
   June 1998 -- The final U.S. mission to Mir as the shuttle
Discovery picks up the seventh and last American astronaut to serve
on Mir, Andrew Thomas, on board since January.
</P>
<P>
   1999 -- Sometime in the summer or fall, after 13 years of
service and clocking more than 2 billion miles, Mir is scheduled to
be pushed into a lower orbit and then disintegrate as it falls into
earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
