<HEADER>
A6481 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-STATION-1119-CO     11-18 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., RUSSIA AND 14 OTHER NATIONS BUILD A SPACE STATION
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-SPACE-1119; SPACE-MIR-1119.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The world's most ambitious construction project begins
Friday(Nov. 20), more than 200 miles above the earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   The International Space Station is scheduled to be assembled
over the next five years at an ultimate cost that could run $40
billion to $90 billion. More than 100 components will be launched
on dozens of flights by and American space shuttles and Russian
booster rockets.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a 460-ton space research station will take shape --
five times larger than the Russian space station Mir. It will be
the third brightest object in the night sky after the Moon and
Venus.
</P>
<P>
   When completed in 2004, as scheduled, the complex will include a
dozen interlocking modules providing living quarters, research
laboratories and support equipment -- interior space equivalent to
two 747 jumbo jets.
</P>
<P>
   THE CONSTRUCTION PLAN:
</P>
<P>
   Friday -- The first space station component, Zarya, (Russian for
``sunrise'') is to be launched aboard a Russian Proton rocket from
Russia's version of Cape Canaveral, the launch site at Baikonur, in
the former Soviet republic of Kazakhstan. Zarya will provide
initial propulsion and power for the station. It was built by a
Russian company under contract to Boeing and financed by NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Early December -- The space shuttle Endeavour will ferry the
Unity module to link it with Zarya. Two astronauts will perform
three spacewalks over five days to connect data and power lines.
Unity, built by Boeing, is a hub unit that will interlock with six
other station components.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-1999 -- Russia is scheduled to launch the main service
module, though the country's economic problems have put the target
date in jeopardy. The module will contain living quarters,
navigation and life-support systems, and rocket boosters to
periodically nudge the station back into its proper orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Through early 2000 -- Shuttle missions and Russian rockets will
transport components to expand the station, including labs, solar
energy-collecting panels, a Soyuz return vehicle, communications
systems and a robot arm.
</P>
<P>
   March 2000-January 2004 -- Labs from Japan and the European
Space Agency will be added, along with U.S.-built living quarters
big enough for a permanent crew of seven.
</P>
<P>
   THE PRICETAG:
</P>
<P>
   Latest estimates put the cost at about $40 billion, more than
half to be paid by the United States. As Russia struggles in its
current economic crisis, Americans may well pay more. If the cost
of operating and servicing the shuttle fleet is included, the total
estimate rises to over $90 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Also joining the project are Japan, Canada, Brazil and 11
nations of the European Space Agency: Italy, Germany, France,
Britain, Belgium, Denmark, the Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden
and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   NASA said earlier this year that American costs would likely be
about $21.3 billion and an independent study commissioned by the
agency suggested in April that United States costs could climb as
high as $24.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The original Russian contribution to the program was expected to
be $8 billion to $10 billion before the current economic crisis.
The other partners' shares amount to about $3.1 billion from Japan;
$850 million from Canada; and $3.8 billion from the European group,
with a separate $550 million from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
