<HEADLINE>
DON'T TAKE THAT $20 BILL TO THE LAUNDRY  
 BIOGRAPHICAL ENHANCEMENT  
 BONDING IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Treasury Department issued a redesigned $20 bill in
September, officials said the new notes would help thwart
counterfeiting by keeping ahead of digital printing technology. But
are they also thwarting digital automation?
</P>
<P>
   Virtually no vending machines that accept twenties accept the
new bills. And it will be well into next year before they do, said
Thomas McMahon, vice president of Washington relations for the
National Automatic Machines Association, a trade group representing
vending-machine manufacturers and owners.
</P>
<P>
   About 100,000 merchandise vending machines accept $20 bills, as
do many change makers and digital vending machines, which dispense
so-called smart cards _ debit cards that can be used to do laundry,
pay highway tolls and use mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told by members they were not given samples early
enough,'' McMahon said. As a result, vending machine manufacturers
are scrambling to refit their machines, which can require fixes
from a simple software patch to an upgrade of the optical device
that reads the bills. Vending-machine manufacturers would have used
the samples to test their machines.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, the Treasury Department invited vending-machine
manufacturers to bring sample machines to Washington to test the
new bills. About 100 companies participated in three sessions held
over the summer, said Edward Sheehan, a spokesman for the
Treasury's Bureau of Engraving and Printing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given the bill-acceptor industry plenty of notice,''
Sheehan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury, he said, insists on maintaining control and would
never have agreed to send out samples of the new twenties before
Sept. 24, when the bills were released to the public. ``If we're
missing one note, there's an investigation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon said that it would take two to six months for
manufacturers to upgrade the machines. On average, the cost for
each machine is $50. He added that he hoped the industry and the
Treasury could work out a compromise before redesigned $1 and $5
bills come out in a few years. ``This is a major issue for us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, just be sure to carry plenty of change.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laurie J. Flynn &QR;
</P>
<P>
   The Name Was Doctored, and So Were the Credentials
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the name isn't the only thing made up about Robert
X. Cringely, the writer and television personality whose newest
series, ``Nerds 2.0.1: A Brief History of the Internet,'' begins on
PBS next week.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Chronicle reported last week that Mark
Stephens, who writes under the Cringely name, had not been a
professor at Stanford University and had not earned a doctorate
there, as he had claimed. He responded in a statement: ``The fact
is I never did finish those final touches on my dissertation and
therefore do not technically have a Ph.D. from Stanford. A new fact
has now become painfully clear to me: You don't say you have the
Ph.D. unless you really have the Ph.D.''
</P>
<P>
   Cringely is often identified as a former Stanford professor in
biographical materials and was described that way on the jacket of
his 1993 book, ``Accidental Empires: How the Boys of Silicon Valley
Make Their Millions, Battle Foreign Competition, and Still Can't
Get a Date.''
</P>
<P>
   But a university spokeswoman said that Stephens had worked as a
teaching assistant and earned only a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for PBS, which runs a column by the writer and
promotes his television work, has now revised his online biography
(www.pbs.org/cringely).
</P>
<P>
   ``As everyone knows, Cringely is a vital part of the Silicon
Valley scene,'' a spokesman for PBS said. ``We feel that the extent
to which he completed his doctoral requirements at Stanford and his
teaching status there do not affect the stature of his television
work.''
</P>
<P>
   A gossip column in the computer trade magazine InfoWorld gave
birth to the pseudonym Robert X. Cringely. Stephens inherited the
job as writer of the column in the mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   The Cringely name was originally added to the magazine's
masthead as a joke earlier in the decade, ``to see how much mail we
got,'' said Sandy Reed, the editor-in-chief. It then became a
byline for the column.
</P>
<P>
   After Stephens was dismissed from the job in 1995, the magazine
sued him for trademark infringement for continuing to use the
Cringely name. He countersued, and in a settlement agreement he was
allowed to continue using the name as long as it was not used in a
competing publication.
</P>
<P>
   The column continues under the Cringely name, but with a
different author. Ms. Reed said the column would spoof the
revelations about Stephens in the upcoming issue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Napoli &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Get the Story on Silicon Real Estate
</P>
<P>
   In what could be the start of a new trend among
computer-industry chiefs, both Cisco's John Chambers and Oracle's
Larry Ellison have invited reporters to their homes for private
tete-a-tetes in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, held on Nov. 6 for some California-style bonding
at Chambers' rambling mansion in the foothills overlooking the
Silicon Valley, the high point was a series of contests.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two dozen reporters were divided into a half-dozen teams,
and each was joined by an executive from Cisco. One task was for
each team to design an egg package that would allow the egg to
withstand being dropped from the roof of Chambers' garage. Two of
the teams flunked this engineering test.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, for his part, invited some 15 reporters to gather last
Wednesday at one of his two houses. (A third home, a palatial
estate in Woodside, Calif., is still under construction.) For this
event, the venue was Ellison's high-tech four-story pied-a-terre in
San Francisco's posh Pacific Heights neighborhood, overlooking the
Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ellison, known for an almost obsessive rivalry with
Bill Gates of Microsoft, conceded that he could not match the
38-car-garage expansiveness of Gates' legendary digital manse on
Lake Washington outside Seattle, the Ellison house does have
noteworthy electronic features.
</P>
<P>
   For example, visitors are greeted at a glass front door that is
made opaque by liquid crystal display technology. At a command from
inside, however, the opacity gives way to a clear pane that reveals
an interior courtyard that has been designed in the style of a
Japanese rock garden.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Markoff &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-15-98 1645EST &QL;
