 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Online shopping becomes practical 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Opening day of trout season, the first football game
of the year and the start of school are all major occasions. But
none of them touch _ for both excitement and panic _ the beginning
of the holiday shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us will end up spending Christmas Eve, elbow-to-elbow,
with other members of the last-minute club. There have always been
alternatives, including using catalogs to order gifts by mail.
Within the past few years, shopping online has become a practical
option.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a veteran online shopper, then you already have a
long list of favorite sites. But if this is the year you will make
your first tentative steps into the world of online commerce, then
may we suggest a cautious entry. Let's take a look today at some
stores you already know, along with an online merchant known for
fast and efficient service. If these first steps prove helpful,
you'll soon be recommending sites of your own.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop, L.L. Bean, didn't invent catalog shopping but
for many years it has been a favorite stop for holiday shoppers.
You'll find the Bean site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .llbean.com/. Once you are there, you'll be able to view any
product in the catalog and, if you like what you see, you can place
your order online.
</P>
<P>
   The Bean site is worthwhile even if you feel more comfortable
ordering from a catalog and dealing with a customer service
representative by telephone. You can get a quick look at what's
available and then, if you like what you see, order a catalog at
the click of a mouse button.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in a metro area, you have undoubtedly shopped at
Macy's. You can have most of that shopping experience online. All
that's missing from the electronic version of the store are the
escalators and the canned holiday music. If you drop in at
http://www.macys.com you'll find the familiar departments of the
store, everything from the jewelry counter to the men's department.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, while browsing the men's department, the Claiborne
Menswear Three-Button ``Bedford'' Sportcoat with Cord Effect at
$152 catches your eye. The next step would be to select a size from
36 to 46 and then click on a button to add the item to your virtual
shopping cart. Then when you're ready to place the order, simply
fill in the charge card information, and your shopping trip is
done.
</P>
<P>
   While you have never gone shopping in a brick-and-stone version
of Amazon.com, this online bookstore is worth a stop. Not
surprisingly, you'll find it at http://www.amazon.com. But you may
be surprised at the massive selection of books and music available
here, along with the speed your order is delivered.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage to this online version of the store is it is a lot
easier to find things than in a regular bookstore. You can search
by author, title or keyword. The savvy folks at Amazon.com know the
holiday business amounts to a disproportionate amount of the year's
revenues. Another nice touch is, once your order is shipped, you'll
get an e-mail telling you to watch for it. Delivery times vary, but
some books arrive in as little as two or three days.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for those of you with the budget of a newspaperman,
there's Wal-Mart. The excellent site at http://www.wal-mart
</P>
<P>
   .com/ does a good job of duplicating the stock you'd find at a
typical Wal-Mart store. And you'll be able to find the closest
Wal-Mart store to your home, or you can send in your resume to work
for the massive retailer.
</P>
<P>
   And Wal-Mart, taking into account the fear some shoppers have of
online shopping, guarantees the store will pay for any fraudulent
credit card charges not covered by the company that issues your
card.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-16-98 1015EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
