<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT17-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Netscape top browser _ for now 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been a neck-and-neck race between Microsoft's
Internet Explorer and Netscape's Communicator for the title of best
browser for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six months, Internet Explorer held the title but
now Netscape has regained the technology lead. That's the opinion
of several Mac reviewers and Walter Mossberg, the esteemed personal
computing columnist for The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   All note, though, Netscape's lead is small and Microsoft has
already said it plans to copy many of the new features added by
Netscape in its next Mac version of Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   However fleeting, Communicator version 4.5 leads for now.
Communicator is really a suite of applications that includes an
e-mail program, newsgroup reader and, of course, the Navigator
browser.
</P>
<P>
   The big reason Communicator has momentarily edged out Microsoft
is a new technology called Smart Browsing. In essence, Smart
Browsing lets you find Web sites and information without typing in
complex Internet addresses. There are two primary parts of Smart
Browsing.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the ability to find sites by typing in common
names. For example, in the narrow location window, type in Apple
Computer and Navigator will take you to the company's home page.
There's no longer any need to type http://www.apple.com.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Browsing isn't perfect by a long shot, but it worked for
me most of the time. When stumped, Smart Browsing will bring up a
search results page.
</P>
<P>
   The other big part of Smart Browsing is a new button at the far
right-hand corner of the title bar. It's called What's Related.
Click on it and the Navigator will present you with a list of
similar sites.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while at the Macsurfer site, I clicked What's
Related. In a split second, it compiled a list of such sites as
MacIntouch, MacFixit and MacCentral.
</P>
<P>
   All of these sites were truly related and worthwhile. They are
presented in a pop-up list when you click on the What's Related
button. You can jump to any site listed by highlighting and
releasing.
</P>
<P>
   Navigator is now part of a large suite of software, which
includes an e-mail program called Messenger. This program too has
been improved. It now lets you quickly view messages without
opening them. The program will also automatically fill in e-mail
addresses from your address book after you type in the first few
letters.
</P>
<P>
   You can check all this out for yourself, for Navigator and its
fuller Communications suite remain free. You can download them from
Netscape's home page at http://www.netscape.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
