 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Amazon Expands For the Holidays  
 By Jamie Beckett   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online bookseller Amazon.com is opening up an Internet boutique,
just in time for the holiday shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, shoppers who go to Amazon.com for the latest
best-seller will have the option of sticking around to buy a
PalmPilot, a digital camera or even a Barbie doll. The Seattle
merchant is expanding _ for the holiday season only _ to offer
toys, games and electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, Amazon.com will redesign its site to permanently add
more than 60,000 video titles to its product line.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the move could help Amazon _ which hasn't yet
turned a profit _ go into the black sooner. ``It's all about
establishing long-term relationships with Internet shoppers,'' said
Jae Kim, an analyst at Paul Kagan &AMP; Associates in Carmel. Winning
online customers is expensive, but Amazon.com can profit by holding
onto customers and persuading them to buy more on the site, Kim
said.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com first moved beyond books in June, when it started
selling music CDs on its site. Within three months of the launch,
music sales topped $14 million, putting Amazon.com ahead of rivals
CDNow and Music Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The wider expansion beginning today had been expected since
August, when Amazon.com made two purchases, Junglee Corp. and
PlanetAll, that it said would help turn it into an Internet
shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Junglee, formerly located in Sunnyvale, makes a database
software program that lets Internet surfers comparison shop.
PlanetAll provides a Web-based address book, calendar and reminder
service to 1.5 million subscribers. At the time, Amazon.com said it
planned to use the technologies to personalize the shopping
experience and to make it possible to buy practically anything at
its site.
</P>
<P>
   But Amazon.com spokesman Bill Curry said yesterday the holiday
store does not use the Junglee or PlanetAll technologies and is not
intended to turn the bookseller into an Internet Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Among items Amazon.com will sell in its gift shop are Dilbert
dolls, Motorola Walkie Talkies, Nintendo video games, Panasonic DVD
players and Sony Walkman stereos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a select list of gifts our customers have told us
they're interested in,'' Curry said.
</P>
<P>
   The online shop will include services such as free batteries and
a gift matcher to help shoppers pick their holiday purchases.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-16-98 2212EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
