<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETFILES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 A Web of Conspiracy Theories  
 By JON SWARTZ   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has all the makings of an Oliver Stone movie.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of unlikely events during the past few weeks that
have conspiracy theorists frothing, a controversial plan to
privatize the Internet domain-naming business takes effect, a key
architect of the plan dies, a congressman launches an inquiry into
the plan, and another key figure behind the scheme mysteriously
resigns (maybe).
</P>
<P>
   The latest wrinkle came last weekend, when a staffer for Ira
Magaziner, President Clinton's Internet czar, said Magaziner will
resign this year to spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   The normally loquacious Magaziner isn't commenting on his
reported departure. Although he routinely uses the speed-dial
button on his phone to answer interview requests, he has been
virtually unreachable by phone and e-mail the past few days. There
has been no formal statement about his apparent resignation.
</P>
<P>
   According to a staffer in his office, Magaziner is in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The public-policy wonk, who also authored theClinton
administration's ill-fated health care plan, was a leading figure
in a controversial plan to transfer Web domain-naming rights from
the federal government to a global, nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Network Solutions, a Virginia company working
under a federal contract, would lose its exclusive right to sell
Web addresses ending in .com, .org, .net, .gov and .edu. Instead, a
worldwide nonprofit group named the Internet Corporation for
Assigned Names and Numbers would decide who could sell domain names
as well as new ones. Network Solutions could continue to sell them,
but so could other firms.
</P>
<P>
   Although the transfer officially took effect October 1, nothing
has really changed. ICANN has said it needs six months to get fully
staffed and running.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Network Solutions continues to control the
multimillion-dollar domain-naming business _ a crucial element in
the fledgling e-commerce field.
</P>
<P>
   So why did Magaziner resign?
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of theories.
</P>
<P>
   One is that Magaziner quit in frustration because the transition
didn't go as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that Magaziner never wanted the transfer to take
place _ that he was acting on behalf of the government, which
wanted to maintain the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another is that Magaziner was ousted because the plan got
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he just wanted to spend more time with his family.
There had been whispers for months that Magaziner was on his way
out.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding the conspiracy theorists is the October 16 death of Jon
Postel, 55, the reclusive technical wizard nicknamed the ``guardian
of the Internet's infrastructure.'' Postel died from complications
following heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   As director of the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority, which
maintains a vast database of all domain names, Postel was another
key figure in the domain-name transition plan.
</P>
<P>
   The same day Postel died, House Commerce Committee Chairman
Thomas Bliley, R-Va., opened an inquiry into the domain-name
transfer. He was responding to complaints that the process was
drafted behind closed doors with minimal public input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned about the manner in which the process of
privatizing the governance of (domain names) has apparently
unraveled,''Bliley wrote in letters to Magaziner and Secretary of
Commerce William Daley. ``A loss of credibility in the Internet
community at large will seriously undermine the ability of (ICANN)
and the stability of the Internet itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Others claim that the process was akin to the movie ``Star
Chamber.'' Issues quietly were discussed among a group of
unidentified people, who posted their conclusions online. ``It was
like a military operation,'' said Naseem Javed, president of ABC
Namebank International Inc., a brand-name consulting firm in
Ontario, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Domain names are the single most important element of
e-commerce, so how come the Clinton administration did such a poor
job of handling this issue?'' Javed said. ``The process was a
laid-back, hush-hush affair that maintained a monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   What really hasn't changed is the role of Network Solutions, a
publicly held company in Herndon, Va., with a market value of $1
billion. Network Solutions is busy expanding into Japan and Germany
_ the next-most-important markets for e-commerce after the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions officials say they support Magaziner's
transition plan. They say competition will fuel growth in the
domain-naming business and that it will benefit everyone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they predict that 100 million domain names will be
registered by 2000. Currently, more than 4 million domain names are
registered, and NSI has registered about 3 million of them. It
currently costs $70 to register a domain name for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, any number of companies will have the right to dole
out names.
</P>
<P>
   Until then ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a damn thing has changed,'' said an angry Eric Gullichsen,
director of Tonic Domain Name Registry. Tonic sells domain names
ending in .to, which is short for Tonga, a country that registers
domain names. ``The transition plan was a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest focus on Magaziner's handling of the transition plan
overshadows his many good works.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime White House adviser is credited with alerting the
Clinton administration to the economic importance of the Internet
and setting an e-commerce policy into motion. He also encouraged
the Clinton administration to rethink its strict limits on the
export of encrypted software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ira heightened awareness of the Net in the Beltway. Without
him, I doubt we would have a law banning new Internet taxes, and a
general hands-off attitude,'' said Erik Olbeter, director of
telecom policy at the Economic Strategy Institute, a think tank in
Washington, D.C. ``He has set the framework for continued strong
growth of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SITE OF THE WEEK: The only thing Americans like more than a good
mystery is pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   A good starting point is Alameda writer Jack Mingo's Whole Pop
Magazine Online (www.wholepop.com). Based on a published book, this
free Web zine is comprised of ``indispensable trivia, worthless
thingamajigs, weird side-trips and preposterous graphics _ all that
cool stuff that pop culture is made of,'' Mingo said.
</P>
<P>
   Interested in a pop quiz on Pop-Tarts or the skinny on why Woody
Allen had a problem with teddy bears? This is your site.
</P>
<P>
   COL. 4 of NETFILES ()
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY
</P>
