<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPAM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING A STOP TO SPAM  
 BY BENNY EVANGELISTA  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a little more than a decade, Sunil Paul has been a space
station designer, a government policy wonk and a guru of the
once-hot ``push'' technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he hopes to become known as the ``spammer jammer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail has been abused and turned into a medium for
spamming,'' said Paul, whose latest startup, Bright Light
Technologies Inc. of San Francisco, is developing programs to fight
unsolicited commercial e-mail, popularly known as spam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most offensive and most obvious way that your
privacy has been violated on the Net,'' said Paul, 33, who is known
for his previous startup, FreeLoader Inc., and for being America
Online's first Internet-products director.
</P>
<P>
   Bright Light, which is on track to market spam-fighting programs
by the end of the year, is a year-old startup that employs tactics
similar to those used by antivirus software-makers. It compiles
lists of known spammers, so they can be blocked by the Internet
service providers before they get to the intended victim.
</P>
<P>
   In a South of Market building, Bright Light has created spam
central, cataloging tens of thousands of known spam e-mail
addresses. The company has set up tens of thousands of e-mail
accounts as ``bait'' for the spammers who send annoying messages
about pornographic sites or get-rich-quick schemes. The e-mail
accounts ``harvest'' addresses of spammers, so Bright Light's
technology can block them.
</P>
<P>
   Paul said he hopes to have hundreds of thousands of spammer
addresses in the databank by the end of the year. The intelligence
center is what Paul calls his ``secret sauce'' for Bright Light's
main product, Spam Wall, designed for Internet service providers
and corporations to use to block spam.
</P>
<P>
   Bright Light already has signed up two major service providers,
Concentric Network and USA.NET, as customers and is working with
AT&AMP;T WorldNet Service and EarthLink Network to help develop the
product.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Plaskon, product management director for the 1.2-million
member AT&AMP;T WorldNet Service, said his company is interested in
Bright Light because its ``very unique product'' seems like a
potentially forceful weapon in the war against spam. AT&AMP;T intends
to use Spam Wall, depending on the results of continuing tests, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working on minimizing spam for two years, and it
seems like it's guerrilla warfare,'' Plaskon said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul got the idea for Bright Light last summer when both he and
his wife, Michelle Odom, were getting spammed at their America
Online addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it was very infuriating,'' Paul said during a
recent interview. ``Somebody out there has figured out who I am and
has sent me stuff that there's no way on Earth I'd be interested
in, and there's nothing I can do about it. If I send them a loud,
obnoxious letter, they love it. It's like, `Great, we know you're
really alive; we'll send you some more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, he said, his wife asked him, ``Can't you do something
about this?''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting spam became another test of his lifelong abilities to
come up with ideas that go against the norm. Even as a teen growing
up in the country music capital of the world, Nashville, Tenn., the
native of India preferred listening to rock.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1987 from Vanderbilt University with a
bachelor's in electrical engineering, Paul hooked on with NASA as a
contractor helping to design the space station. But he said he
became frustrated that ``we would spend a year designing some facet
of the space station and Congress would come along and redesign
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So he joined the Office of Technology Assessment, a
congressional advisory think tank, because ``I wanted a role in
making sure our public policy was guided by informed decision
making rather than politics. Just at that time, ``the Internet
started receiving attention, mainly by policy wonks and engineers,
and I happened to be both,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   He left the OTA in early 1994 to become the first Internet
product manager at AOL, which then had only 300,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one of the first meetings I had about future planning, I
said someday we're going to have to figure out how to get a Web
browser, and everybody's like, `Oh, how are you going to get a Web
browser on 9600 baud, there's no way we're going to have a Web
browser,''' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he left in late 1995, the online service had a
browser, a Web site and 3 million customers
</P>
<P>
   Paul and colleague Marcus Pincus left AOL _ and about $1 million
in unvested stock options _ to co-found FreeLoader Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Their original idea was to develop a Web browser that would
automatically retrieve information from the Web, ``pushing'' to the
desktop instead of requiring the computer user to spend time
``pulling'' it from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   FreeLoader and chief rival PointCast Inc. of Sunnyvale made
``push technology'' the hottest buzz phrase of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Pincus and Paul used the buzz to quickly raise $3.1 million in
investments, generate publicity in publications such as the Wall
Street Journal and become courted by the likes of Yahoo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Just eight months after starting the company, without having
made a dimein profits, they sold FreeLoader for a cool $38 million
to Individual Inc., a news-retrieval service.
</P>
<P>
   The deal seemed a good idea at the time, especially because
rival PointCast had the lead in both product development and
financing. But Individual ended up folding FreeLoader eight months
later after a corporate shakeup.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's own profit from the sale has plummetted with Individual's
stock. The stock options he got in the deal are probably worth
about $3 million to $4 million now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Paul believes that FreeLoader and push technology
failed for the same reason that his latest venture is drawing
attention _ advertisers turned it into a way to shove their
products in front of computer users' faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Push got spammed to death, and the users lost control,'' Paul
said. ``The real reason push never took off is that it didn't
address the needs of real users and instead fell victim to the
needs of advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unchecked, spam could ``snuff the magic out of the
Internet,'' he said. Already, an estimated 10 billion pieces of
spam shoot through the Internet each year, according to industry
experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have never visited a porn site in their lives get
porn spam,'' Paul said. ``A spammer doesn't care whether you're a
kid, whether you're a man or a woman, whether you're black or
white. All that matters is that the cost of sending spam is almost
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright Light may have a good idea, but one analyst who has
followed the electronic messaging industry for 15 years said the
company has to prove it has a product that appeals to a broader
market than just Internet providers.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations already are using some form of e-mail filtering
technology that weeds out spam, said Phil Schacter, a senior
analyst with the Burton Group, a research group based in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they do something to start interesting enterprise
customers, they're looking at a fairly limited market,'' Schacter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, though, remains confident about the market and has rounded
up $5.5 million in investment funding from influential Silicon
Valley venture capitalists like Bud Colligan ofAccel Partners and
Esther Dyson of EDventure Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bright Light is concentrating on spam, Paul said he
sees future business possibilities in other forms of e-mail
monitoring and management for companies.
</P>
<P>
   And if not, Paul said he's always coming up with new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day in the shower, there's at least one or two new
ideas,'' he said. ``The hard part is turning those ideas into
something that can be real.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-16-98 0053EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
