</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-LUCENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T SPIN-OFF LUCENT TECHNOLOGY RIDES INTO HEART OF SILICON
VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By Deborah Solomon   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
 &HT;    Paranoia seems an odd trait for Lucent Technologies _ a $30
billion company with an AT&AMP;T pedigree, a market value of $109
billion and the adoration of Wall Street.
 &HT;    But Lucent knows it faces a herd of up-and-coming competitors
and must stay vigilant to survive.
 &HT;    Keeping tabs from its headquarters in New Jersey is hard,
however, because most of Lucent's potential competitors are here in
the Bay Area.
 &HT;    So the nation's largest telecommunications equipment company,
eager to protect its valuable market share, is setting up shop in
its competitors' own back yard.
 &HT;    The New Jersey company has spent the past year beefing up its
presence in Silicon Valley _ building new facilities, acquiring
local companies, setting up research labs and aligning with local
universities like Stanford.
 &HT;    Lucent is preparing to go head-to-head with local hotshots like
Cisco Systems, Ascend Communications and 3Com Corp. for a share of
a multibillion-dollar industry that will transform the way people
communicate.
 &HT;    It's developing new products and technologies such as wireless
telephone systems at its facilities in the Bay Area and soon will
open a Lucent Venture Fund office in Menlo Park to finance startup
tech companies.
 &HT;    The company now employs more than 3,000 people in the Bay Area
and plans to add several hundred more during the next few years.
That's still a small number when compared with Cisco's 16,000
employees and 3Com's 13,500 employees, but it's more than Ascend's
1,820, and it's enough to show those companies that Lucent means
business.
 &HT;    ``We are very conscious of what Lucent is doing out here,'' said
an executive from one of the area's largest companies.
 &HT;    What Lucent is trying to do is compete in the data networking
business, a relatively new task for the company. Lucent and others
are working to create products that seamlessly integrate voice,
video and data networks.
 &HT;    Data networking products will give companies enhanced services,
such as universal messaging, plus the ability to control all phone
calls, Internet access and video-conferencing from a single
network.
 &HT;    The strategy for developing the products out here, says Lucent
CEO Richard McGinn, is to siphon off some of the creativity, energy
and brain power that's made Silicon Valley the premier place for
innovation. Harnessing what McGinn calls the ``intellectual
horsepower'' of the Valley will help Lucent compete in the brave
new world of telecommunications.
 &HT;    ``The culture of the Valley fits in very well with what we want
to do,'' McGinn said. He cited the area's educated workforce, rich
talent pool and impressive universities as reasons for having a
presence here.
 &HT;    Synergy aside, industry watchers say Lucent needs to be in the
Valley because that's where most of the breakthrough technology is
happening and where customers expect their suppliers to be located.
 &HT;    ``One of the biggest issues for Lucent near-term is the ability
to become a stronger player in data networking,'' said Gregory S.
Geiling, who follows Lucent at J.P. Morgan Securities in New York.
``With the West Coast being such a hotbed of data networking, in
order to be in the flow of information and to have the
relationships with companies and customers, Lucent needs to be out
here.''
 &HT;    Being in Silicon Valley also will allow the company to keep
close tabs on its competitors. Lucent has had explosive growth
since it was spun off from AT&AMP;T Corp. two years ago and is
desperate to sustain that pace.
 &HT;    Revenue has soared from $23.3 billion in 1996 to $30 billion in
1998. The company's market value is $109 billion, and its stock has
defied the recent market downturn. Shares are up more than 90
percent for the year.
 &HT;    Lucent has been so successful because its products run
everything from traditional phone systems to wireless phones to the
Internet. The company is the largest U.S. provider of telecom
equipment, and its customer list reads like a who's who of the
technology and telecom industries _ SBC Communications Corp., Intel
Corp., AT&AMP;T, AirTouch, Apple, Sun Microsystems all use Lucent
products.
 &HT;    But times are changing, and the products that Lucent primarily
focused on _ equipment for circuit-switched telephone systems _ are
going the way of the record player. Lucent says it is committed to
being at the forefront of this new market but faces challenges from
other companies that have been focused on data networking for much
longer.
 &HT;    Lucent's core business, providing equipment to telephone
companies, is a slow-moving one that hasn't changed much in several
decades.
 &HT;    Data networking, on the other hand, moves on Internet time, and
companies that want to survive need to keep pace.
 &HT;    Privately, competitors question whether Lucent can compete in
the fast-moving world of data networking, which spits out products
at a significantly quicker pace than the company is accustomed.
Companies like Cisco refer to Lucent as an ``old world company.''
 &HT;    Industry watchers also wonder whether Lucent, which now has
130,000 employees worldwide, will be able to keep up with the
industry's lightning-fast pace.
 &HT;    ``The big challenge is transitioning to this data networking
base successfully. Product development cycles are a lot quicker,
competition is fierce, and focus on technology is very important.
As they transition to data, they have to be quicker,'' Geiling
said.
 &HT;    Company officials admit that Lucent needs to move at a rapid
clip, but they shake off the notion that it's too mired in its ways
to succeed.
 &HT;    ``Our challenge is to continue to execute with speed,'' said
Carly Fiorina, president of Lucent's Global Service Provider
business, the company's largest division. ``We're limited only by
our own movement.''
 &HT;    To keep up momentum and stay ahead of competitors, Lucent has
acquired several Bay Area companies with a large presence in
markets the company wants to compete in.
 &HT;    But Lucent wants to do more than just absorb other companies'
technology. McGinn has committed $4.5 billion to research and
development this year, and much of that money will make its way out
here.
 &HT;    In February, Lucent quietly opened a division in Milpitas that
was charged with finding ways to deliver more bandwidth to
customers. Nine months later, the division is preparing to ship
wireless antennas that enable customers to make calls, access the
Internet and do video-conferencing using microwave transmissions.
The antenna _ one of the company's most anticipated products _ is
headed to local phone companies, Internet service providers and
anyone else who needs a lot of bandwidth.
 &HT;    The product also is unique in that it was conceived, designed,
built, tested and marketed at the building in Milpitas.
 &HT;    ``We needed to integrate all things together, to take research
and development and sales and fuse it into one team and one
environment,'' said Larry Schwerin, general manager of the wireless
broadband division. While demand for bandwidth is the current rage,
Lucent also wants to develop products that customers don't even
know they want.
 &HT;    The company, which announced more than 30 products this year, is
building a research lab facility in Menlo Park to develop new
ideas.
 &HT;    The 43,000-square-foot building, which will be housed in the
Stanford Research Park, is expected to open next summer with about
125 employees.
 &HT;    The division will focus on developing sophisticated products
that use the Internet to transmit data but are of better quality
and more reliable than what's already available.
 &HT;    ``We're trying to go after things where you can't forecast the
market because it's so new,'' said Ronald Schmidt, who will co-lead
the research lab along with William Coughran Jr.
 &HT;    Analysts say Lucent's timing could not be better. By moving into
the Bay Area, the company is closing a geographic gap and
positioning itself to compete vigorously in the data networking
market.
 &HT;    ``Lucent is one of the largest telecom vendors; they have the
advantage of size; they have good stock currency and are in a great
position if they need to do acquisitions,'' said Geiling.
 &HT;    Philip Sirlin, an analyst with Shroder &AMP; Co. in New York, is a
bit more blunt about Lucent's future. ``They are going to give
Cisco and Nortel a run for their money,'' he said. Lucent ``doesn't
have a choice. Lucent will either be successful in data networking
or they won't be successful. Period.''
 &HT;    
 LUCENT SET TO GO ON BUYING BINGE 
 &HT;     BY DEBORAH SOLOMON 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies has been doing more than just gobbling up
space and talented engineers in Silicon Valley. It's also been
buying local companies with expertise in the markets in which
Lucent wants to compete _ and it's poised to go on an even bigger
buying spree.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lucent bought Livingston, a data networking company
in Pleasanton that makes products that connect computer users to
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition helped fill a hole in Lucent's business
portfolio and gave it access to an even broader customer base.
</P>
<P>
   Three months earlier, Lucent bought Octel Communications Corp.
of Milpitas, a leader in voice mail and messaging. That acquisition
gave Lucent access to large corporate accounts, such as Bell
Canada, Hewlett-Packard and Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   But those purchases may pale in comparison with what industry
watchers expect Lucent to do in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   There is much speculation that the company soon will make
another big acquisition in the data networking or wireless
business, now that it will no longer be penalized for certain
stock-swap takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Under accounting rules, spin-offs are barred for two years from
``pooling of interest'' transactions. It forces companies to take
charges against earnings and sticks them with a big tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   Large deals have been out of reach for Lucent because they would
have been too expensive, but on October 1, Lucent turned 2 years
old and the shackles came off.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area companies such as Ascend and 3Com have been mentioned
as potential takeover targets for Lucent, as have foreign telecom
companies such as Siemens, Alcatel and Nokia. For now, however, the
company is keeping mum on which companies it might be courting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have acquired 10 companies in the past 30 months, and we're
going to continue to acquire firms to add technology, distribution
and new customer groups, in addition to wonderfully talented
people,'' said Lucent CEO Richard McGinn. ``We don't have an
acquisition strategy. We have a business strategy to invest in the
fastest-growing areas, such as hardware and data networking.''
</P>
<P>
   Data networking, with a growth rate of 25 percent a year, is
probably the most obvious target for Lucent acquisitions. Lucent
also would do well to buy businesses with expertise in Internet
protocol routing technology and asynchronous transfer mode. Both
those technologies provide the plumbing for routing telephone calls
and data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent's been rumored to buy almost everybody that's out
here,'' said Gregory Geiling, who follows Lucent for J.P. Morgan
Securities in New York. ``My gut reaction is that any immediate
acquisition would focus on data networking. Lucent is one of the
largest telecom vendors, and they have the advantage of size, they
have good stock currency and are in a great position to do
acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-16-98 0038EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
