<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OLD MASTER'S ENDURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, when the 106th Congress convenes, a remarkable
tableau of history will occur on the Senate floor. Three of the
longest-serving members in the 210-year history of that body, all
in the all-time top 10 in seniority, will take the oath:
</P>
<P>
   Strom Thurmond, South Carolina's gift to gerontology, first
elected in 1954; Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia, elected in 1958;
and Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, sworn in on Nov. 7, 1962,
four months before his 31st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   None of this durable trio shows any sign of quitting. Some
Republicans have murmured that Thurmond, the party's nonagenerian
patriarch, resembles father Anchises in the Aeneid, a burden to his
son fleeing the flames of Troy. A dignified burden, but a burden
nonetheless. Ol' Strom told 'em to take a hike. Byrd, historian of
the Senate, has an almost religious belief in seniority. Kennedy,
reelected in 1994, is campaigning nonstop for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York announced that he
would not run for reelection, ``I called Pat to say we're going to
miss him in the Senate,'' Kennedy said in his Boston office.
Moynihan and Kennedy, two of the few senators who might be
remembered deep into the next century, differ in style and
priorities, but Kennedy praised his colleague's ``courtesy,
understanding, professionalism and good political sense.'' Those
qualities also apply to Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan is 71. Kennedy is 66, a stripling among Senate
sequoias. Next year, he passes in service James O. Eastland of
Mississippi, to become the eighth-longest-serving senator in
history. Thurmond is first and Byrd is fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Kennedy had no local public experience. He's been
working on his equivalency diploma since. Some state reps may know
more about health care, but not many. An alderman or two may be as
versed in education, but their schdeules don't match Kennedy's,
whose daily grind would daunt an aspirant for the Boston City
Council: a medical-care event, then a charity dinner here, a Social
Security forum there. He still listens and learns. This time, they
can't catch him napping if he doesn't sleep.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls his 1962 slogan, ``He Can Do More for
Massachusetts,'' and annotates it with enthusiasm, especially the
National Institutes of Health budget, which he has been milking
like a Guernsey for decades. ``The next century is the century of
life sciences, and 15 percent of research from NIH comes to this
city. Boston is the number one city in the country for
pharmaceutical research.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 elections excited Kennedy. ``Two months ago,'' he said,
``People thought it would take 10 years for Democrats to come back.
Now there's a lot of energy. The House has a better than even
chance of turning Democratic and in the next Senate elections, the
numbers favor us, with 19 of theirs and 12 of ours up, and a large
turnout in a presidential year.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's own presidential run in 1980 ended badly, but in
recent years, he's delivered his own ``state of the union'' address
on ``our agenda,'' on HMOs and AIDS research, on high-tech and
minimum wage, a list for friend and foe alike.
</P>
<P>
   He calls Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle ``indispensable'' in
uniting Democrats, but thinks Majority Leader Trent Lott is
isolated, unable to realize that ``they do best when they show they
can work with Democrats, that in a sense you don't `need' to elect
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was once the GOP's favorite fund-raiser, a hobgoblin to
terrify direct-mail pigeons into digging deep. Newt Gingrich later
served the same purpose for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Having survived Gingrich and many others, the Old Master looks
forward to another eon or two in Congress. In the final session of
the Senate in the 20th century, Kennedy says, ``The numbers haven't
changed, but there's another message: that Republicans are adopting
our issues and may want to work toward a common goal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
