<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BROTHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DYNASTY SIGN IN BUSH SONS' RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They say Texas Governor George W. Bush is the
wiseacre in the family, but it was brother Jeb, the serious one,
who made even his famous father blush the day George W. brought his
girlfriend home to meet the family.
</P>
<P>
   Falling down on one knee, proposal-style, Jeb flung open his
arms and asked the 31-year-old George W. what his nervous parents
would not: ``Brother, did you pop the question, or are we just
wasting our time?''
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than two decades later, the Bush brothers' often
close, sometimes comic, and always competitive relationship has
grown even stronger, friends and family members say, and the
Republican sons of former President George H.W. Bush definitely are
not wasting time.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 3, George W. Bush (who on that did indeed propose to and
marry Laura Welch) was reelected to a second term as governor of
Texas in a longhorn-sized landslide that could propel him to the
top of the GOP presidential pack in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, John Ellis Bush _ Jeb for short _ easily won
Florida's governorship, bouncing back from a 1994 defeat for the
same office in the nation's fourth most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush brothers are expected to make their debut on the
national stage when they attend the annual convention of the
Republican Governors Association, which opens today in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the late 1960s, when siblings Nelson and Winthrop
Rockefeller were simultaneously governors in New York and Arkansas,
have two brothers presided over state houses. And not since
``Kennedy'' became synonymous with political dynasty has one family
shared so much political power and presidential ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know the Bushes say these are no Kennedys, despite the
similarities: the New England prep-school pedigrees, the wealth,
the obsession with sports. What's different, they say, is that the
senior Bush did not push Junior or Jeb into politics; in fact, he
was surprised that his sons chose the hard knocks over the privacy
and security of business careers.
</P>
<P>
   The former president will not discuss his advice to his sons.
Publicly, all he has said since the election is that he's really
proud of their achievements. George W., 52, and Jeb, 45, also are
reluctant to talk about their relationship; they did not answer
repeated requests for interviews for this story.
</P>
<P>
   But family and friends describe a true friendship between two
very different brothers, a relationship that was nurtured by doting
parents during their childhoods in Texas, and that has strengthened
and matured in their pursuits of public office.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nobody helped Jeb Bush more to win the Florida
governorship than did George W., who raised hundreds of thousands
of dollars for him in Texas, screened his television ads, offered
moral support, and made sure lots of family members campaigned in
the Sunshine State. Four years earlier, a deeply disappointed Jeb _
the Bush that bettors believed would win a governor's race in 1994
_ attended George W.'s inauguration in Austin and showed no trace
of hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been competing for generations in this family, but
there's a difference between being competitive and being rivals,''
said William ``Bucky'' Bush of St. Louis, who is a senator's son, a
president's brother, and uncle to two governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``These boys are competitive, but they aren't rivals,'' Bucky
Bush said. ``They weren't raised to have chips on their
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, their relationship has survived personal crises that
make political defeats look pale. (George W. also lost his first
campaign, a bid for a House seat, in 1978.) Robin, the sister born
between them, died of leukemia when George W. was 7 and Jeb was a
baby. George W. was a heavy social drinker until the day after his
40th birthday party when, with a killer hangover, he swore off
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb's Mexican-born wife, Columba, suffered such social ostracism
in Houston, his hometown, that in the early 1980s Jeb moved his
family to Miami. Jeb's family was so wrenched by the 1994 campaign
that afterward Bush converted to Roman Catholicism, his wife's
faith, and sought drug-prevention counseling for one of his
children, according to friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``As George and Jeb have gone through challenging times in their
lives, their siblings and parents have supported them, but I
wouldn't call the Bushes dependent on one another,'' said
Massachusetts native Andrew H. Card, a family friend who served as
President Bush's transportation secretary. ``The boys are very good
friends, but they are also individuals with strong views of their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they are different men. George W. looks like his father
and displays the same restless energy. Jeb more resembles his
mother, and seems to have her calm demeanor and firm resolve.
</P>
<P>
   George W. is the quick, cocky, and hot-tempered one; he was a
curious and incorrigible child who surely spent more hours in the
time-out chair than all of his siblings (including Neil, 43,
Marvin, 41, and Doro, 39) combined.
</P>
<P>
   In her memoirs, former Barbara Bush called George W. ``the son
who pulls no punches and tells it like he thinks it is.'' George W.
attributes those traits to her: ``I've got my father's eyes and my
mother's mouth,'' he has said.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy growing up in Midland, Texas, George W. was a bit of a
bully, according to Bucky Bush, his frequent babysitter, but he was
packed off to boarding school at Phillips Academy in Andover,
Mass., before his considerably younger siblings could encounter
that side of him. He was the absent brother during his years at
Yale and Harvard Business School; George W. didn't settle down in
Texas until his father's political career had moved the younger
children to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb, who also went to Andover but then chose the University of
Texas over the Ivy League, was quiet and studious, a Phi Beta Kappa
like his father, an outstanding tennis player, and a kinder,
gentler contrast ``to his Texas-swaggering, tobacco-chewing,
roughneck-talking, cowboy boot-wearing brother,'' said Card, a
former state representative from Holbrook who is now the auto
industry's chief lobbyist in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb never dated any girl but Columba, whom he met as a
high-school exchange student in Mexico and married right after
college. George W. had the reputation of a partygoer and ladies'
man, which was why the family was so keen to meet Laura, the
librarian he married in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeb was always very disciplined, very focused, and in a
hurry,'' said David Bates of San Antonio, a boyhood friend. ``He
matured quicker than the rest of us, graduated faster, got married
sooner, and was ready to go out in the world and get down to
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeb had played a lot of baseball with his younger siblings, but
when he needed to hit a home run _ to win a statewide race, tailor
a more populist message, become a ``compassionate conservative,''
and reach out to minority voters _ he turned to a brother with
experience. ``George W. was very, very supportive in this
election,'' Bates said. ``The brothers are much closer now than
they ever have been.''
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview after his victory, George W. said, ``I
love my brother a lot. He's going to be a great governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the press after his win, Jeb dismissed any
suggestion of a Bush-Bush ticket in 2000. ``I think he'll impose a
vice presidential nepotism rule,'' Jeb said of his brother. ``If he
doesn't, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a lot of speculation that the Bush brothers
aspire to one of the two highest offices in the land, which, not
incidentally, were both held by their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have played and lost enough tennis in Texas's 90-degree heat
to know there is a very strong competitive instinct in this
family,'' said Marlin Fitzwater, who was President Bush's longtime
spokesman. ``They like to win, but they also know how to lose with
dignity and grace.''
</P>
<P>
   They also know who is the boss. President Bush may be their
political point of light, but Barbara Bush is the one who makes
them stand at attention.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzwater recalls how he and George W. once sneaked out of a
Houston rally for President Bush to smoke cigars. Suddenly spotting
Mrs. Bush coming their way, they instinctively tried to hide the
forbidden tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what are you boys up to,'' Mrs. Bush casually asked,
according to Fitzwater, ``that is making smoke come out of your
pockets?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
