<SLUG> BC-DEMS-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS DOUBT IF GOP CAN MOVE CLOSER TO THE CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats are privately hoping the Republican
makeover, which begins today when the House GOP elects its new
leadership, is not the first wave of a national effort by the party
to move to the political center and reach out to minorities and
women.
</P>
<P>
   A more moderate Republican Party would benefit President
Clinton, Democrats say, if it allowed him to accomplish pieces of
his legislative agenda before his term ends. But it could hurt
Democrats if Republicans succeed in appealing to more voters in the
2000 election, when voters will decide contests for both the White
House and the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans reeling from their worse-than-expected showing
in the midterm election and so much at stake in the next two years,
many Republicans say they have no choice but to change their
messengers and message or risk a return to their minority status in
Congress. Many Democrats are betting that the GOP's efforts will
not succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we recognize that a smarter and more moderate
Republican Party would be more difficult to face in a general
election,'' said Democratic consultant Geoffrey Garin. ``It would
strengthen the Republicans' hand. I don't think there's any
question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garin gave long odds to that possibility. ``If I win the
lottery tomorrow, I'll be a lot richer,'' he said. ``If the
Republicans become more moderate, they will be a lot better. But
the chances of me winning the lottery and them becoming more
moderate are about equal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' first opportunity will come today when they
vote on a replacement for House Speaker Newt Gingrich. The
presumptive successor, Bob Livingston from Louisiana, is known for
his adroit legislative skills and ability to reach across the aisle
and work with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will also decide whether to elevate a woman _
Representative Jennifer Dunn of Washington _ to the number two spot
as majority leader, and the only black Republican in the House _
Representative J.C. Watts of Oklahoma _ to the post as Republican
conference chairman. Both candidates are considered to have a
serious chance of winning, though observers say the races are too
close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Anne Northup, a Republican from Kentucky who has
two adopted black children and garnered about 18 percent of the
black vote in the recent congressional election, has emphasized her
ability to help broaden the party's appeal to minorities in her
candidacy for vice chairman of the Republican conference _ number
six in the leadership hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Democratic leadership did not select a woman for a
top leadership post Monday _ Connecticut Representative Rosa
DeLauro was defeated in a contest to head the Democratic Caucus _
the Republicans are guaranteed to have at least one woman in its
upper ranks. Ohio Representative Deborah Pryce is running unopposed
for reelection as conference secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to win elections, you have to capture the middle, the
center, and I think the Republicans got a wakeup call on November
3,'' said Kenneth Duberstein, a Republican political consultant and
a chief of staff to former President Ronald Reagan. ``Sometimes
there's nothing like a near-death experience to concentrate the
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Mark Sanford, a Republican from South Carolina,
said: ``Necessity is the mother of all invention, and I think the
same holds true for the Republican Party. This is a turning
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanford, elected to Congress during the Republican stampede in
1994, asked: ``Do I think things will change? Yes. And if they
don't, I think we are in real trouble as a party.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, are counting on the GOP conservatives'
prevailing in its showdown with the political pragmatists and
moderates who say the party should try to emulate the success of
Republican governors, whose centrist style of governing has enabled
them to expand their base among women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats such as political consultant Tubby Harrison of Boston
said Democrats benefit from the conservatives' dominance in the GOP
because they can draw sharper distinctions with Republicans in the
absence of having anything else to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats don't really have a message,'' Harrison said.
``The Democrats have stands on particular problems, but there is no
central reason for their existence. The Republicans give them one.
The Republicans say this is what is important, and the Democrats
say we don't want to deal with that, so vote for us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Harrison said a standoff exists between
Republicans and Democrats. ``The Republicans have the ability to do
better, but so do the Democrats. So it's a question of which one
articulates the compelling message.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Duffy, a political analyst at the Cook Political
Report, said Republicans are going through ``the political
equivalent of group therapy.'' She said many have called her to ask
what lessons they can take from the midterm election that gave
Democrats five additional House seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the Republican problems are frankly mechanical, they
are tactical; and those are very easy to fix,'' she said, such as
returning to grass-roots get-out-the-vote efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Their larger problem, Duffy said, is finding a message that's
appealing. ``What they are going through now isn't that much
different from what Democrats went through after 1994, when the
party really had to take a hard look at itself and say, `We can no
longer be dominated by the left,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, a senior policy analyst at the Joint Center for
Political and Economic Studies, a black think tank in Washington,
said: ``There's no magic bullet that is going to attract black
voters or Hispanic voters to the Republican Party. At best, it's
going to be a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Representative Charles B. Rangel, a member of the
Democratic Black Caucus, doubts whether the GOP will make inroads
among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is politically impossible for the Republicans to move to
the center. The people who are in control of the party are small in
number, but they would rather go down the tubes than deal with
us,'' Rangel said, referring to minority groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
