<HEADLINE>
FRESH OR FROZEN TURKEY? THE ANSWER'S IN THE LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is the BIG one. Thanksgiving. Possibly the
most anticipated and scrutinized home-cooked meal of the year.
There are even rules for this dinner:
</P>
<P>
   1. You must serve turkey. It must be cooked until white instead
of pink and moist but not dry.
</P>
<P>
   2. The turkey is to be served with stuffing, which can be made
with anything from apples to oysters as long as it, too, is moist
and not dry.
</P>
<P>
   3. You have to have mashed potatoes and gravy, with lumps in the
potatoes but not in the gravy.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the turkey; the BIG bird.
</P>
<P>
   For best results, use the finest ingredients, advise chefs. But
which is best, fresh turkey or frozen turkey? It all depends on
whom you ask. ``You have to go with the fresh,'' said Bob Briggs,
associate dean of advanced cooking at the Culinary Institute of
America in Hyde Park, N.Y. ``Freezing breaks down cells and when
you thaw (the turkey) out, all that water that comes out of the
package is moisture that was in the bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to mention all the hassles of thawing: the water
collecting in the bottom of the refrigerator, trying to pry out the
frozen neck,'' Briggs said. ``You go to cook it and you find it
isn't thawed completely and you just about have to stand on the
thing to get the bags out of the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all chefs agree. Food safety is the issue that makes
Michael St. John go with the frozen birds. St. John is the
executive chef at The Desmond in Colonie, N.Y., where the kitchen
staff will cook 25 turkeys for the holiday. ``When a frozen bird is
processed, it is killed, cleaned and flash frozen within minutes.
With a fresh turkey, you have raw meat going from the farm to the
warehouse, from the warehouse to the store and from the store to
your home, where it will sit a day or two before you cook it.
``I've had fresh turkey at home a couple of times and I have to
say, I have my concerns about fresh turkeys.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more concerned with the additives in frozen turkeys
than with the food safety issue. According to the U.S. Department
of Agriculture, MSG, salt and sodium erythorbate (a synthetic agent
used in processed meats to preserve color) cannot be used on birds
labeled ``fresh'' or ``minimally processed.''
</P>
<P>
   Frozen birds, however, can be processed with these additives but
the ingredients must be listed on the label. In addition, many
frozen turkeys are ``basted'' or ``self-basted,'' meaning the
turkey has been injected with a solution containing some or all of
the following: edible animal fat, broth, stock, water, spices and
flavor-enhancers. Again, the label must identify the common name of
all the ingredients and the amount of the solution used.
</P>
<P>
   For assurance that the turkey they're serving wasn't being fed
antibiotics or grain treated with pesticides, some people are
turning to organically or naturally raised turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although those practices have been approved for use by the
USDA, there is some controversy about whether or not those are
really good things to put in your body,'' said Eric Paul, meat
manager at the Honest Weight Co-op in Albany. Honest Weight will
sell between 60 and 80 organically raised birds from the Misty
Knoll farm in Vermont for the holiday, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest reason for the popularity of frozen turkeys
is price. They are generally less expensive than fresh.
</P>
<P>
   While you may think you're buying a fresh turkey if it has a
label that says ``never been frozen,'' that may not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   According to the USDA, the term ``fresh'' may only be used on
raw poultry products that have never been stored below 26 F.
Poultry stored at 0 F., or below, must be labeled ``frozen.'' But
there are no rules for labeling fowl stored between 0 and 26 F.To
ensure you get what you want, look for ``fresh'' or ``frozen'' on
the label.
</P>
<P>
   So, which is better? We might as well try to answer the
proverbial ``Which came first, the chicken or the egg?'' Instead
we'll quote the USDA: ``There is no appreciable difference between
a fresh or frozen bird. It is just a matter of preference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
