<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POPE PLANS FOR THE YEAR 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is widely known that many religions have unusual, even
bizarre, expectations for the year 2000. For instance, some
Christian fundamentalists hold that the ongoing US-Iraqi conflict
is the prophesied Time of Tribulation preceding the post-millennial
Apocalypse. But it is less widely known that Pope John Paul II and
the Vatican have been pursuing an ambitious spiritual agenda for
the new millennium, aimed at a purification and renewal of the
Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the pope declared that the year 2000 would be ``a
turning point in human history.'' Four years ago, in a
little-noticed apostolic letter, ``As the Third Millennium Draws
Near,'' John Paul wrote that ``preparing for the year 2000 has
become as it were an (interpretive) key of my pontificate.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope has carefully distanced himself from the millennarian
Christian sects that are fanning apocalyptic expectations for the
year 2000. Indeed, in what almost amounts to a humorous aside, the
1994 letter acknowledges the historical dispute over the year of
Christ's birth _ some scholars believe it may have been 4 B.C. _
and the resulting uncertainty of the precise timing of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Landes, the medieval historian who directs Boston
University's Center for Millennial Studies, calls John Paul ``a
soft millennialist,'' meaning he does not expect any apocalyptic
prophecies to be fulfilled in 2000 AD. On the other hand, says
Landes, ``The pope has undertaken a level of introspection the
Vatican has never seen before. He wants everybody in the church to
embark on a meditation on what the meaning of Christ is and what
the meaning of faith is.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _Under John Paul, the Vatican commissioned an 11-year
investigation into the Church's role in the Holocaust, culminating
in an extraordinary _ and controversial _ statement of
``repentance'' released in March.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _Similarly, a two-decade inquiry into another dark corner of
church history _ the Inquisition _ resulted in a scholarly
conference last month. For the first time, the Vatican opened some
of its Inquisition archives to researchers outside the church.
</P>
<P>
   _Also last month, the pope, a former professor of moral
philosophy, published a sweeping encyclical on ``Faith and
Reason,'' a generally well-received condemnation of
anti-intellectualism in the modern world.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, there is more to come. John Paul has said he would like
to visit Lebanon, Jerusalem, and the rest of the Holy Land _ ``the
places on the road taken by the people of God of the Old Covenant''
_ during the year 2000. For the same trip, he also mentions
visiting Egypt, Mount Sinai, and Damascus, ``the city which
witnessed the conversion of St. Paul.'' Whether geopolitical
realities will allow the pontiff to accomplish this historical
mission, which does not yet figure on his official calendar, is
another question altogether.
</P>
<P>
   On Ash Wednesday (March 8), 2000, John Paul is scheduled to lead
a public ``Request for Pardon,'' highlighted by a Mass procession
to the Circus Maximus in Rome. Catholic officials say John Paul
will use the traditional day of repentance to make a public
confession of sins committed by church members during the past
thousand years. Among the most grievous transgressions, in John
Paul's view, are the 11th-century schism between the Greek Orthodox
and Latin churches, and the 16th century Protestant Reformation:
``Such wounds openly contradict the will of Christ and are a cause
of scandal to the world,'' he writes. ``These sins of the past
still burden us and ... it is necessary to make amends for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's ambitions for a rejuvenated Catholicism are dramatic,
and obviously heartfelt. For me, the pope's physical frailty adds a
layer of tension to his historic demarches. Although it sounds
callous, ``Will the pope live until the year 2000?'' is an
extremely important question in Catholic circles. If, God willing,
he lives and thrives well into the next millennium, he will have
transformed the church as no other pontiff in this century _ or
perhaps in this millennium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
