<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-BUDDHISM-2TA     11-18 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BUDDHISM-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTER FOR BUDDHISM BLOSSOMS IN WESTERN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLEMONT, Mass. _ Susan Patlove and her husband came to this
quiet Mohawk Trail town in the early 1960s to join a new
alternative community.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the community, where the couple raised three children
and still live, shared similar values. The Buddhism came later.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us were Buddhists then, but most of us are now,
although we all practice different forms,'' says Patlove.
``Buddhism is one of the things that happened to our generation,''
said the 51-year-old freelance editor. ``We took
consciousness-expanding to heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddhism _ a philosophy that through meditation cultivates
self-awareness, compassion, discipline, and moderation _ has become
trendy in recent years, the favored faith of celebrities like
Richard Gere, Courtney Love, and members of the Beastie Boys. It
has also been the focus of recent Hollywood movies such as
``Kundun'' and ``Seven Years in Tibet.'' Instruction in arcane
Buddhist meditation techniques, some once confined to remote
Tibetan monasteries, is now almost as easy to find as yoga or
karate training.
</P>
<P>
   But there are few places in the nation where Buddhism in its
major forms and schools of practice has put down roots so deeply
and become such an accepted part of the landscape as in the verdant
hill towns of northwestern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People joke that out here you can probably find more Buddhist
groups than churches,'' says Patlove, a Zen Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Buddhism has found such easy acceptance is the area's
long tradition of religious tolerance, dating to Colonial days when
Quakers and other dissidents, fleeing Boston's regimented
Puritanism, found a haven among the inland hills.
</P>
<P>
   The presence now of five major colleges and universities in
Western Mas-sa-chusetts also fosters open-mindedness. ``There are a
lot of artists and crafts people around here, and they tend to be
open and want to be with like-minded people,'' says Marit Cranmer
of Conway, a weaver who practices a form of Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest in Buddhist meditation in Western Massachusetts
is an amazing phenomenon,'' says Mark Hart of Shutesbury. ``That's
why I settled here.'' A native of Washington state, Hart has a
doctorate in theology from Boston College and at one time
considered becoming a Roman Catholic monk.
</P>
<P>
   Hart makes his living teaching Vipassana, a type of meditation
associated with Theravadan Buddhism of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans usually sample different kinds of Buddhism and then
select the spiritual path that appeals to them the most,'' says
Patlove. ``I like Zen because it's starkly simple and challenging,
but Tibetan Buddhism is attractive to a lot of people because it's
so colorful and artistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Patlove says that becoming a Buddhist was a gradual process that
started with readings and prog-ressed to attending lectures and
then meditation classes. ``It happened slowly during a time of
searching when I was in my 20s,'' she recalls. ``A lot of us were
looking for something, and Buddhism pointed us in a different
direction and gave us a new worldview without contradicting
anything in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Patlove says she grew up in an academic family that wasn't
particularly religious, but occasionally attended Unitarian
services. Her husband, Leslie Patlove, was raised in the Jewish
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Like most American Buddhists, the Patloves neither flaunt nor
conceal their Buddhism. They meditate together for 45 minutes on
weekdays and for several hours with a group on Sundays. ``Many
people I know well have no idea that I'm a Buddhist,'' Susan
Patlove says. ``Sitting quietly with your eyes closed doesn't
attract attention and isn't threatening to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs of Buddhism's spread in Western Massachusetts are
increasingly evident. Stupas, traditional bell-shaped shrines, are
certainly not as common on hilltown skylines as the spires of
Congregational churches. But neither are they that unusual anymore.
Leverett, a small farming town once as thoroughly Yankee as baked
beans for breakfast, now has two Buddhist temple complexes.
</P>
<P>
   The Peace Pagoda, a large domed white stupa decorated with
images of Buddha, stands on a hilltop about a mile from Leverett's
town center. Beside it is a Japanese-style meditation garden
maintained by volunteers. Under construction nearby is a temple
that will contain a prayer hall and living quarters for Buddhist
monks and nuns.
</P>
<P>
   The pagoda was built 13 years ago by monks of the Nipponzan
Myohoji order, founded in Japan after World War II to work for
world peace through prayer and pilgrimage. The order was attracted
to Leverett's rural beauty and tranquillity but was even more
impressed that the town had declared itself ``a nuclear-free
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the pagoda community are currently leading an
``Interfaith Pilgrimage of the Middle Passage,'' in which dozens of
people are spending a year retracing the trans-Atlantic slave trade
route to recall the sufferings of the slave trade. ``Buddhism is
the basis of our activities, and we chant Buddhist prayers on our
pilgrimages,'' says Brother Gyogo Kato, ``but our primary focus is
on peace and justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kato says his community was regarded with some suspicion when it
arrived, but that faded. ``Gradually, we have been accepted, and
now we get a stream of visitors.'' he says. ``The younger
generation is not so involved in mainstream churches and is looking
for alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   At the foot of the hill below the Peace Pagoda is Wat Kiry
Vongsa Bopharem, an ornate white-and-gold temple typical of those
in Cambodia. Redolent of incense, a large shrine room is filled
with images of Buddha and photographs of revered monks and
teachers. The temple has a resident community of three monks and 10
nuns, all Cambodian-born. There are plans to build a large stupa
nearby, a shrine that would also be a repository for the ashes of
deceased Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Cambodian temple, but it's not just for
Cambodians,'' says Kork Ork, a young monk from Amherst who smiles
often and wears an orange robe. ``A lot of Americans come and sit
and meditate with us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A Buddhist family group also meets every Sunday afternoon in the
Leverett Town Hall. Meetings offer a group meditation for adults,
along with what amounts to Sunday school for their children. Hart,
who has two small children, teaches meditation techniques to kids
at the meetings and also discusses basic Buddhist beliefs with
them. ``My own children sometimes sit on our laps when my wife and
I meditate,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
