<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-BUDDHISM-2ND     11-18 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BUDDHISM-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 CHARLMONT, Mass.: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since most American practitioners are first-generation
Buddhists, they have no working model for their religion in family
life. ``There's no blueprint for being a Buddhist in this
country,'' says Susan Patlove. ``It will be interesting to see how
that resolves itself.''
</P>
<P>
   When her children were small, Patlove says, the family always
had a Christmas tree, but considered it more a seasonal symbol than
a religious one. Nominally Buddhist, her children are not as
committed to the faith as the parents are. ``But, they're very
open, and their generation has to evolve, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Evolution is precisely what American Buddhism is going through
now, says Geoffrey Brown of Greenfield, an ordained novice priest
(comparable to a deacon in many Christian faiths) of the Soto Zen
school of Buddhism. ``Soto has its roots in Japan, but we can't
transfer Japanese culture to this country. The soil is different,''
says Brown. ``We have to create our own institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 41, was ordained four years ago by Rev. Issho Fujita,
abbot of the Valley Zendo in Charlemont, the Buddhist community to
which the Patloves belong.
</P>
<P>
   Brown says his ordination was a milestone on a spiritual journey
that began while he was a student at the Putney School in Vermont,
and included Buddhist studies at Columbia University and years of
wandering from one hippie commune to another.
</P>
<P>
   His wife Rebecca, 37, is also a practicing Zen Buddhist. The
couple has an 11-month-old daughter, Sophie. ``We take turns
baby-sitting her while the other one meditates,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has no formal priestly duties, works full time as a
psychiatric nurse in a Greenfield hospital. ``I wear my priest's
robes only in the zendo,'' the meditation hall, he says, ``but I
keep my head shaven like a Buddhist priest to symbolize that I have
renounced worldly values.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Buddhist centers in the area, such as the two in
Leverett, clearly reflect their Asian origins, others are not only
Americanized but even look thoroughly Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Center for Buddhist Studies in Barre _ which
has a large reference library and offers lectures, classes, and
workshops on different aspects of Buddhism _ blends seamlessly into
its small-town surroundings. Offices are in a 225-year-old
converted farmhouse. The white clapboard meditation hall, a modern
building, resembles an old New England meetinghouse, except that
there are cushions on the floor instead of pews.
</P>
<P>
   The center is affiliated with the Insight Meditation Society,
also in Barre. Founded in 1975 by former Peace Corps volunteers,
IMS is one of the oldest Buddhist meditation centers in the
country. It was also among the first to teach Vipassana, also known
as insight meditation, an intense practice intended to heighten
self-awareness and increase self-control.
</P>
<P>
   IMS retreats range in length from 10 to 90 days, during which
participants meditate with closed eyes and in absolute silence from
about 5 in the morning until 9 at night, with only a few breaks to
eat and exercise. ``The crown jewel of the program is the
three-month retreat,'' says Mu Soeng,, the center's director.
``There's always a waiting list, and you have to sign up six months
in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Insight meditation is also taught at the Vipassana Meditation
Society in Shelburne, a 100-acre complex where as many as 150
meditators at a time are in residence. But there, unlike at IMS,
there are no images or shrines to Buddha, and the focus is
completely on the practice and benefits of meditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vipassana's tradition is Buddhist, and we honor the Buddha's
teachings, but the technique is nonsectarian,'' says Luke Matthews,
manager of the center.
</P>
<P>
   The Vipassana Society is constructing a large Burmese-style
pagoda that will be topped by a lotus-shaped gilded stupa. While
the partially completed pagoda's exterior will be colorful and
ornate, the interior is like a beehive for humans. It consists of
meditation cells, small windowless chambers , dimly lighted, where
future Vipassana meditators will spend most of their time during
retreats.
</P>
<P>
   Tibetan Buddhism, which incorporates elements of Hinduism and
shamanism, is, in its original form, the most ritualized and
traditional of all. Shamanism is the belief in good and bad spirits
that can be influenced by priests. Americans often practice a more
simplified version of Tibetan Buddhism based primarily on the
teachings of individual lamas, or monks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dzogchen Community in Conway is housed in a large yellow and
white Victorian building that was once the town grammar school.
Other than the removal of the inner walls of a modular annex to
convert classrooms into a meditation and meeting space, the
building is little changed from the days when it held
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the community are followers of Choegyal NamkaiNorbu,
a Tibetan lama who lives in Italy. He visits Conway, North American
headquarters of his movement, every two years. ``We're not as
traditional or regimented as some Buddhists,'' says Jim Smith, a
50-year-old builder who lives in Amherst, ``and we're really a
practice, not a religion, so you don't have to accept or reject
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the low-profile Dzogchen Community, the Mahasidda
Nyingmapa Center in out-of-the-way Hawley _ whose members are
disciples of another Tibetan lama, Dodrupchen Rinpoche _ proudly
displays its Tibetan connection. The white and gold stupa, the
colorful prayer flags fluttering from a row of poles, and the blue
and yellow wooden temple all stand out vividly against a
pine-tree-covered hillside.
</P>
<P>
   The temple replaced a smaller one destroyed in 1984 in a fire
set by several troubled Vietnam veterans trying to call attention
to their problems. Shocked by the incident, veterans organizations
around the country contributed to a reconstruction fund and dozens
of local volunteers helped put up the new building.
</P>
<P>
   Flooded with sunlight and scented with incense, the Mahasidda
Nyingmapa shrine room is Tibetan in feeling. There are images of
the Buddha and revered Buddhist teachers, and others of dancing
figures representing demons, gods, and goddesses from Tibetan
mythology. Yet the atmosphere is cozy as well as exotic.
</P>
<P>
   David Dvore, a 45-year-old computer consultant from Rowe and a
longtime member of the center, loudly chants in Tibetan as he
prostrates himself before the shrine, touching the floor with his
forehead three times. Then, he leaps to his feet, picks up his
briefcase and _ as the scowling demons look on _ greets a visitor
with a grin. ``Hi, Im Dave,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Many American Buddhist centers emphasize individual meditation.
However, Mahasidda Nyingmapa emphasizes community, much like a
typical small-town church or synagogue. The 50 or so members have
frequent social gatherings, Dvore says, and usually meditate
together on Sunday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhist groups in the hill towns generally go their own way,
Dvore observes, respecting their differences and letting people
come to them rather than proselytizing. ``Buddhism is vast, varied,
and adaptable,'' he says. ``Buddha taught different practices for
different kinds of people. You don't even have to call yourself a
Buddhist if you don't want to. He didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
