<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER SEEDS OF RENEWAL WERE SOWN IN TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night when she was a 15-year-old worried about grades and
boyfriends, Naomi Levy was awakened by her mother and sister. In
her groggy state, Levy thought they were saying, ``The doctor gave
Daddy a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So what?'' Levy replied. ``So what if he got a shot?'' But
what they were really trying frantically to tell Levy was that her
father had been shot in a botched robbery attempt on a Brooklyn
street.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, her father died. For Levy, many other things
died, too _ her religious faith, hopes for future, and confidence
in herself. But it was from that despairing moment that Levy began
a new life &UR;  &LR; whose foundation was built on her Jewish roots.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Levy is a successful and pioneering rabbi who was in the
first group of women admitted into the rabbinate by the
Conservative movement in Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   A mother of two, Levy has turned her story and those of many of
her congregants into a book, ``To Begin Again,'' a treatise on how
God and faith can help people recover from the worst of times. It
deals with a fundamental issue raised by human suffering _ Why
would God allow this to happen?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that wracked Levy after her father's murder _ a
killing that was never solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, his death was the end of everything that had been
sacred,'' Levy, 35, recalled in an interview last week in Boston.
``I completely lost my faith. I was very angry. I stopped praying.
I was going to a private Orthodox high school, but I hated God.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a painfully bleak moment for a young girl who had
wanted to be a rabbi ``ever since I was 3 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in Levy's life came when she was in college at
Cornell University in upstate New York. She came to a new
understanding of God, she says, by studying modern Israeli poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to believe not in a God who prevents all evil, but in a
God who is with us in times of pain,'' said Levy, who resigned as
spiritual leader of Temple Mishkon Tephilo in Venice, Calif., two
years ago to spend more time writing. She became a rabbi in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``If God's job description really was to prevent evil in the
world, then all you need to do is look around you to realize God is
doing an awful job,'' she added. As she studied the great Jewish
philosophers, Levy came to a different belief in the complex
relationship between God and humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith isn't about magic,'' Levy said. ``It isn't about putting
a prayer request here and expecting a direct answer to come out
there. God isn't there to screw up our lives. God is there to help
us when we screw up our lives or our lives become screwed up. God
gives us the capacity to soar beyond any tragedy and to resurrect
our lives and to learn to rejoice again.''
</P>
<P>
   Her new outlook on God not only restored Levy's faith but made
it stronger. ``I wake up every morning appreciating the blessings
God has given me,'' she said. ``It helps me every day.''
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Levy, who was in the first group of women rabbis to
train at the Jewish Theological Seminary in New York, chronicles
the wrenching tales of some of her congregants, such as a woman
raped on her way to Yom Kippur services.
</P>
<P>
   Her congregants, Levy says, helped her realize that ``there is
no way I can ever answer the question of why certain things happen.
But one question I think we can grapple with is how. How can I
carry on with everything that has happened? That is where we can
begin to deal with pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy hopes her book, though steeped in Jewish theology, can be
useful to people of all faiths. ``When something bad happens so
many other pieces of our lives are affected _ our faith, our
relationship with our families, how we look at our work,'' she
said. ``We can't change that one big thing. We can't take back the
death, the rape, the divorce, the job loss. But all the other
ancillary things that are affected we do have power over. We can
start over again. God is our ally in that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
