<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHLESINGER ON JFK `MYTHS'; MRS. STARR REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say the premium cigar craze is finally waning. But you
can't tell that from looking at  &UR; Cigar Aficionado &LR; , the robust (386
ad-laden pages) glossy devoted to the joys of the $10 Macanudo. The
December cover is entrancingly eye-catching with its warm, hazy
illustration of John F. Kennedy relaxing with a fine cigar. But the
``JFK Revisited'' cover story _ Arthur Schlesinger Jr.'s rebuttal
to almost every nasty Kennedy story in circulation _ isn't as
convincing as the cover art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myth breeds countermyth,'' writes Schlesinger, attacking the
revisionist take on Kennedy as an ``incorrigible philanderer, a
reckless risk-taker,'' and a ``bellicose'' Cold Warrior. In his
determined effort to reestablish the myth, Schlesinger insists,
among other things, that JFK: did not steal the 1960 election with
Illinois voter fraud; did not recruit the Mafia to kill Castro; and
was not put in a compromising position by gangster Sam Giancana
(although Schlesinger grudgingly admits Kennedy shared a bed with
Giancana's mistress Judith Campbell). He suggests that the stories
of the late president's sexual conquests were exaggerated and
posits that Kennedy would never have ``Americanized the war'' in
Vietnam. (Calling Oliver Stone.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Schlesinger's timeliest point _ given the results of
this month's Congressional elections _ is his contention that
``history shows no connection between private morality and public
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   In this era of Rat Pack cable movies depicting Kennedy as little
more than a Vegas lounge lizard, it's time for cooler heads to lead
a sensible reassessment. But Schlesinger's hyperaggressive defense
of the Kennedy legacy seems to succeed largely in countering the
foggy anti-Kennedy tales with an equally thick layer of, fittingly
enough, smoke.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of womanizing,  &UR; Mirabella &LR;  offers up an exclusive
interview with Alice Starr, the largely invisible wife of the
independent counsel and Lewinsky report author. There's nothing
surprising or provocative here, as Mrs. Starr stoutly defends her
husband as a rigorously honest man and a loving husband and father
who doesn't bring the stress of the job home at night.
</P>
<P>
   Unfailingly temperate, Starr reserves her harshest words for New
York Times columnist Maureen Dowd (``she doesn't know my husband'')
after Dowd characterized the special counsel as a kind of
prosecutorial Peeping Tom.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Hillary Clintonesque outbursts here about a
left-wing conspiracy out to bury her husband. But that doesn't keep
Mirabella from trying to spin an otherwise arid interview with
repeated comparisons to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hillary Clinton, Alice Starr must defend a husband accused
of being obsessed with sex. ``Like Hillary Clinton, Alice has
always handled the family's finances.'' ``Like Hillary Rodham and
Bill Clinton, Alice Mendell and Ken Starr fell in love almost
instantly.'' You get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   One notable difference is a family friend's suggestion that ``I
don't think that Alice Starr has ever had to put up with
infidelity.'' Touche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Associated Press moved a report that New York's
``Son of Sam'' serial killer David Berkowitz was now saying that
the devil made him do it. A converted evangelical Christian,
Berkowitz _ who pleaded guilty to six murders in 1978 _ says in a
new video that he was a soldier in a ``Satanic army ... determined
to bring New York City to its knees.''
</P>
<P>
   This should all be good news for  &UR; gear &LR; , another of those
proliferating new ``magazines for men'' (read: a pinch of skin and
a smidgen of attitude), which features a story arguing that
Berkowitz was part of a sophisticated satanic cult that planned and
committed the Son of Sam murders.
</P>
<P>
   Mysteries are a weak point. I've never yet been able to finger
the culprit in a Perry Mason episode, so I'm not the best judge of
complicated murder plots. But this story sure does offer the mother
of all conspiracy theories. In one way or another, writer Maury
Terry tries to tie Berkowitz and his cult _ The Process Church of
the Final Judgment _ to Charles Manson, Sirhan Sirhan, and the
horrific 1979-1981 Atlanta child killings.
</P>
<P>
   The final graphs of the story chillingly inform us that the
Process cult under a ```socially acceptable' cover'' is still
around, has amassed a vast real estate empire, and is hoping ``to
inspire Armageddon in time for its professed witching hour _ the
Millennium.'' Kind of strains credulity, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with no actual NBA basketball season to watch, it's at
least time for some hot stove league action. The  &UR; Athlon &LR;   &UR; Sports &LR; 
Pro Basketball Edition is sure to inspire debate with its ranking
of the 50 Greatest Basketball players of all time. The Celtics are
richly rep-resented with Larry Bird (No.6) John Havlicek (11), Bob
Cousy (13), Bill Sharman (26), Dave Cowens (28), and Kevin McHale
(39). Most satisfying to Boston fans will be Bill Russell's
designation (2) as king of the great centers, nipping Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar (3) and the hated Wilt Chamberlain (7).
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious flaw in the rankings is the Chicago Bull
inflation factor. Michael Jordan is a deserving No.1, but Scottie
Pippen seems too high at No.19, and Dennis Rodman at No.47 is as
ludicrous as one of his multihued coiffures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
