<SLUG> BC-BOOK-POISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWENTY YEARS LATER, A SURVIVOR REMEMBERS JONESTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Peoples Temple is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By REN E E GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SEDUCTIVE POISON 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Jonestown Survivor's Story of Life and Death in the Peoples
Temple &QL; 
By Deborah Layton &QL; 
Anchor, 309 pp., $23.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago today, the world first learned of unimaginable
horror in the jungles of Guyana.
</P>
<P>
   There, at a self-styled retreat called Jonestown, hundreds of
people died during a night of madness. Among the dead was Jim
Jones, a preacher-turned-demagogue who convinced the members of his
``Peoples Temple'' that their compound was under attack, and that
the time had come to ``die with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day Jones was prepared for, and had practiced
repeatedly during his ``White Night'' suicide drills. As Jones
rambled on about revolutionary suicide, his followers drank cups of
cyanide-laced punch. Parents fed the fatal potion to their
children, and those who refused were forced to ingest it at
gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Jones would die from a single gunshot, perhaps self-inflicted,
to the head. In all, 913 men, women, and children perished amid the
stench of heat and death.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Layton was a member of the Peoples Temple for seven
years, but she would not die among its followers. Once a member of
Jones's inner circle, she made a harrowing escape months before the
massacre, and was the first to reveal the escalating paranoia and
violence of the man she once unfailingly obeyed and called
``Father.''
</P>
<P>
   In her shattering memoir, ``Seductive Poison,'' Layton recalls
what led her, as well as her brother and mother, into Jones's
terrifying lair, and how she found the resolve to leave. In
riveting detail, Layton unveils the sorrowful story of a family
nearly destroyed by Jones, as well as her own blind faith in
someone who was more madman than messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, every few years there's another discovered cult,
another group of lost believers. But the attention given cults
began with Jonestown. Its name became ``an ominous warning to all
those Americans who sought meaning for their lives,'' in fringe
organizations, writes Charles Krause in the book's introduction.
``Jonestown would demonstrate in bold relief just how dangerous
these groups and their leaders could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause, now a foreign affairs correspondent for ``The NewsHour
with Jim Lehrer,'' was a reporter for The Washington Post when he
arrived in Guyana two days before the massacre. He was on the
makeshift airstrip when temple loyalists opened fire on those who
tried to leave Jonestown.
</P>
<P>
   Five people, including California congressman Leo Ryan, were
killed; Krause was among 12 wounded. It was Layton's testimony
about the horrors of Jonestown that led Ryan's delegation to make
their ill-fated trip. Layton's brother, Larry, was the only person
convicted for the deaths, and he is currently serving a life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   It was Larry Layton Jr. who first discovered Jones in 1968.
Jones was then a charismatic preacher in San Francisco, with a
growing congregation drawn to his fiery sermons denouncing racism,
social injustice, and the Vietnam War. Larry encouraged his
youngest sister, Deborah, to attend one of Jones's serv-ices. She
was moved by the multiracial parishioners, but especially by Jones,
who seemed to be directing his every word toward her.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, Layton was desperately seeking direction. She rebelled
against her parents and experimented with alcohol and other drugs.
Even time in an English boarding school did little to curb her
unruly spirit. But when Layton looked at Jones she saw in his
``clean, radiant, handsome face'' someone ``easy to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Other followers spoke of Jones's healing powers, and his
``family of all races.'' He garnered the enthusiastic support of
then California Governor Ronald Reagan, and of Willie Brown, now
San Francisco mayor, who once called Jones ``a combination of
Martin Luther King, Angela Davis, Albert Einstein, and Chairman
Mao.'' But there were also Jones's dire warnings of a coming
apocalypse, and the ``promised land'' to which he and his followers
would escape.
</P>
<P>
   Layton joined the Peoples Temple, and soon witnessed Jones's
darker side, which became more evident once the Temple moved from
California to Guyana. There were public beatings, and those who
questioned their leader's authority mysteriously disappeared or
suffered sudden, fatal accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Jones controlled every aspect of his followers' existence, from
their sex lives to time spent with those outside the Temple.
Layton's mother, Lisa, would eventually leave her husband and join
the group, in part to be closer to her youngest child. Her mother,
who had escaped Hitler's Germany, would die of cancer _ without
pain medication, which Jones had confiscated for his own uses _
days before the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do not knowingly join `cults' that will ultimately
destroy and kill them,'' Layton writes. ``In their open-hearted
endeavor to find meaning in their lives, they walk blindly into the
promise of ultimate answers, and a higher purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   In reading this chilling memoir, some may desire ultimate
answers to the most obvious question, namely, why any sane person
would join such a group. Layton doesn't cheapen her ordeal, or the
lives of those lost, with throwaway analysis. Perhaps the only
answer lies in the basic human need for fulfillment, sanctuary, and
belonging. And as long as such emotional cravings exist, there will
be shrewd self-appointed saviors promising heaven _ and leading
their followers to hell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
