<SLUG> BC-FOOD-THANKSVIGING-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT A VERMONT RETREAT, IT'S A HOMESPUN HARVEST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST SANDGATE, Vt. _ It's quiet up here on a chilly Sunday in
November. Chickens scramble across the dirt road and a black goat
and his white mate cut stark silhouettes against the mountainside.
This corner of Vermont, northwest of Bennington, is congested with
traffic during the warm months. Now that the tourists are gone, the
natives and ``flatlanders'' are left.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher and Adrienne Kimball don't pretend to be anything
but city folk who weekend here in their country house. Christopher
Kimball, the publisher of Cook's Illustrated and Handcraft
Illustrated magazines and author of ``The Cook's Bible,'' is never
seen around Boston without his trademark bow tie, the perfect
signature to his buttoned-up persona. But up here, giving in to a
``farming bug'' inherited from his mother and grandfather, he is
more easygoing, reserved yet happier in his role as gentleman
farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Kimballs' kitchen, every bowl appears to be in use,
the timer is beeping, pots of root vegetables are vigorously
bubbling on Viking burners, and all four children _ Whitney, 10;
Caroline, 8; Charlie, 3; and 6-month-old Emily _ seem to need
something at once. ``This is what my life is really like,'' Kimball
says.
</P>
<P>
   The midday meal is about to be served, a meal that bears more
than a passing resemblance to the Thanksgiving feast because the
harvest is over and the Kimballs are cooking many of their own
vegetables: potatoes they dug up and are about to garnish with
caramelized onions, which they also grew. They'll mash their own
turnips into the potatoes, though the dish isn't billed that way
when served (the children might not eat them). Sweet potatoes are
glazed with butter and molasses, and buttermilk biscuits _ the same
flaky rounds one of the local women made when Kimball summered up
here as a boy _ are about to emerge from the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball, who began his cooking magazine 18 years ago, celebrates
the home-style food he was raised on and has spent much of his
career perfecting. His just-published ``The Yellow Farmhouse
Cookbook'' (Little, &UR;  &LR; Brown and Co.) is based on this uncomplicated
fare, meals you might find in any American home when Sunday dinners
were served in the middle of the day. The chapters are arranged
according to how a farmer and his family think about the land and
the seasons, as in ``The Root Cellar'' and ``The Chicken Coop.'' In
this household, the harvest feast is a way of life. Variations on
the Thanksgiving menu appear all fall.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball, 47, is the third generation of his family to buy land
and dabble in agriculture. He's the grandson of Dr. Stanley White,
a Washington doctor who had ``two of everything _ like two cows and
two chickens'' on a farm in Leesburg, Va. In the 1950s, Kimball's
parents bought land in this Vermont town, where they raised pigs
and Black Angus. When the marriage faltered many years later,
Kimball's mother, Mary Alice White, bought a farm in Salisbury,
Conn. White's grandchildren call her ``Grandmaw,'' based on her
acronym. Grandmaw _ a doctorate in psychology who spent a good part
of her career at Columbia University _ now raises 150 chickens and
collects freshly laid eggs in her retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' says Kimball, who is famous for his meticulous
recipe testing, ``when I use her eggs in baking, they turn the cake
yellow. The yolks are almost orange colored and they're thicker. I
suspect in the old days they were thickeners.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandmaw will host her son and his family for Thanksgiving, and
the table in Salisbury will boast the traditional American menu:
roast turkey, sweet potatoes, and mashed potatoes. And endless
desserts. ``My mother likes trifle. There are pies. We have pecan
pie, apple pie, and pumpkin pie,'' he says. With seven for dinner,
``it's not enough people to eat all that pie. But she's not unhappy
with the leftovers.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thanksgiving, the Kimballs head up to Vermont to re-create
the meal _ turkey, pies, and all. He roasts turkey the slow way,
unstuffed and untrussed, beginning in a 350-degree oven, then 250
degrees, four hours for an 18-pound bird. He swears by this method,
having made 28 turkeys before settling on it. ``We crave turkey
sandwiches,'' says Adrienne Kimball, 38, who works in Cook's
marketing department.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Kimball has been baking a lot of pies lately. He's
been traveling to promote ``Yellow Farmhouse,'' and the apple pie
he's making uses a mixture of McIntosh and Granny Smith. At home he
prefers Macouns or Northern Spys, both of which he grows on his
land, but those varieties are only available locally. He decided to
develop a pie with apples anyone in the country could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macs have a nice flavor and they cook to applesauce,'' he
says, ``but I don't use a thickener. The Granny Smiths hold their
shape. I like to serve the pie cold and the apples firm up. A
thickener ruins the flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 40 apple trees on the Kimballs' land, and they're
planning to plant more. Kimball, an indefatigable researcher, did a
blind tasting of 17 apples at Cook's Brookline offices and
discovered that new apples were developed by cross-pollination, and
that now genetic engineering has taken over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thinking about abandoning the new disease-resistant
varieties,'' he writes in ``Yellow Farmhouse,'' for ``an orchard of
full-growth old-fashioned varieties _ Freedom, Winter Banana, Blue
Pearmain, and Liberty.'' These are antique cold-hardy apples once
prevalent in New England orchards.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball writes lucidly about the land and the people in West
Sandgate he has followed for 40 years, particularly Junior. Junior
Bentley, who employed the young Christopher Kimball on his farm,
taught him milking and haying. Junior comes to dinner at the
Kimballs' house. ``If we say 6 p.m.,'' says Kimball, ``he pulls his
truck up at 5:59.''
</P>
<P>
   That precision isn't unfamiliar to Kimball, whose philosophy is
to cook scientifically.
</P>
<P>
   He measures everything, from the 1/4 cup of capers he will add
later to veal shanks to the 2 tablespoons of parsley that goes into
the caramelized onions for the potatoes. Adrienne Kimball follows
suit. She weighs the sweet potatoes, first placing a dish on the
scale, then subtracting it from the measurement. She sets a timer
for 17 minutes to cook the quartered potatoes (a master chart in
``Yellow Farmhouse'' gives boiling and steaming times for several
kinds of potatoes cut into various shapes). A measuring spoon adds
the 2 tablespoons of molasses to the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
