<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-AMERICAN-BOS &LR;      11-18 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMISE AS A CENTURY ENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICA 1900 
Narrated by: David McCullough 
Produced by: David Grubin 
On: PBS, 8 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we count down the final days of this dreadful, wonderful,
bloody, inspired century of ours, it's natural for us to start
crystal-balling the prospects for the next 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, we'll come up with more worst-case scenarios than
did our forebears in the year 1900, many of whom looked forward to
the 20th century with unalloyed optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``People felt exhilarated by the possibilities of America,''
narrator David McCullough says in ``America 1900,'' which raises
the curtain in stellar fashion on the 11th season of ``The American
Experience'' series. ``Cynicism and self-pity were not in style ...
On Jan. 1, 1900, most people imagined only good things to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, when cynicism and self-pity are very much in style, that
view could seem hopelessly naive, as out-of-date as the horse and
buggy that was beginning to pass from the scene in 1900. But over
three engrossing and sometimes stirring hours, ``America 1900''
suggests that those alive at the last turn of the century simply
had stronger inner resources.
</P>
<P>
   A resilient faith in a better tomorrow animated the mine workers
who went on strike in 1900 to protest meager wages and hideous
working conditions, the residents of Galveston who doggedly rebuilt
their hurricane-shattered city, the African-Americans who used the
words of W.E.B. DuBois to map a road from vile and
institutionalized racism to social justice, the women who began
forging careers outside the home at a time when they were still
denied the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But then blue-skies optimism was contagious in 1900. Even amid
the hardship and misery that governed so many lives, the future
beckoned. The concept of leisure time, of vacations, began to reach
the middle and working class, and new inventions began to transform
daily life: motion pictures, telephones, phonographs, electric
light, X-rays, indoor plumbing, the automobile.
</P>
<P>
   However, America also had begun succumbing to colonial
temptations little more than a century after winning its own
freedom from colonial rule. Having won control of the Philippines
in the Spanish-American War, the United States moved quickly to put
down an uprising there, as President William McKinley sent 60,000
US troops there.
</P>
<P>
   By exploring that early contradiction between the nation's
ideals and its actions, ``America 1900'' foreshadows some of the
issues US citizens would grapple with in what came to be known as
The American Century.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by David Grubin and skillfully written by Judy Crichton
and Grubin, ``America 1900'' brings the year to life through
marvelous archival images, period music, and portraits of numerous
celebrated and unknown figures, ranging from McKinley and his
firebrand running mate, Theodore Roosevelt, to pioneering
photojournalist Frances Benjamin Johnston and United Mine Workers
organizer John Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the storytelling skills of Crichton and Grubin that
they manage to evoke strong curiosity, and even cliffhanger
tension, about the fates of people long dead.
</P>
<P>
   Will American missionary Eva Price and her family escape the
marauding Boxers of China, whose rallying cry was ``Exterminate the
foreigners''? Will actress Olga Nethersole, star of the scandalous
play ``Sappho,'' be convicted on charges of violating public
decency? Will the mine workers be able to stave off starvation long
enough for their strike to succeed? ``America 1900'' prompts us to
ask these questions, and care about the answers.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary does not belabor the parallels between that turn
of the century and the one just around the corner, preferring to
let us draw the connection ourselves between, say, the state of
race relations then and now, or the dizzying pace of invention in
1900 and our own Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   Like the year 2000, 1900 was an election year. But McKinley
largely let Roosevelt hit the hustings for him because, McCullough
informs us, it was considered ``beneath the dignity of the
president to campaign.'' At times like that, 1900 seems an eon,
rather than a mere century, away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1332EST &QL; 
