<HEADER>
A6631 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-THANKSGIVING-2ND     11-18 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-THANKSGIVING-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WEST SANDGATE, Vt.: ... the potatoes.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing organic about the process, no tossing in a
little something just to see what happens. The results are
delicious: a homespun array of strong tastes that don't overpower
one another, honest ingredients cooked beautifully and nicely
seasoned, a meal you might eat at the table of an off-duty chef.
The tender shanks are served in their own juices, garnished with
capers, anchovies, sage, chopped carrots (each minuscule dice looks
even), tomatoes, and lemon rind. Buttermilk biscuits are as light
as promised. Sweet potatoes spiked with sherry are rich but not too
sweet.
</P>
<P>
   And Kimball turns out to be right about the turnips and
potatoes. You might not guess the dish contains turnips, but you
know at once that it's earthier and deeper-tasting than ordinary
mashed potatoes. Their onion garnish is also made with anchovies,
though you can't taste it. ``I use a lot of anchovies,'' he says,
``just for their flavor and salt.''
</P>
<P>
   At the table, he doesn't taste food the way some cooks do _
curious about how things worked out this time. He picks up his fork
and knife with confidence. Kimball has followed his own recipes,
and he knows they work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Art history to food art
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Kimball was raised in a household where his mother
pushed a button under the dining room table and someone came to
clear the dishes. His grandmother was even more formal. From the
time he was quite young, he was required to wear a jacket and tie
to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   He came to publishing armed with degrees from Phillips Exeter
Academy ('69) and Columbia University ('73), where he studied art
history and was a long-haired member of Students for a Democratic
Society. ``Some people say that was my worst moment,'' he notes.
``Some say it was my finest.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, he thought about a doctorate in oceanic art, but he
changed course because there were no jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He started Cook's Magazine in 1980, publishing it in
Connecticut, where he lived at the time. He wanted a publication
that didn't look or sound like the others on the market, he says,
but ``the food wasn't as good as it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   He sold Cook's Magazine twice (both times, as it turned out, to
S.I. Newhouse Jr.). The first sale in 1983 gave the controlling
interest to The New Yorker, which Newhouse later bought. Then
Newhouse sold that interest to the Swedish company Bonnier in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Kimball sold his remaining equity to Bonnier and left
the magazine. A year later, Newhouse bought the company from
Bonnier and killed Cook's Magazine. Subscribers were given Gourmet.
``Newhouse was never interested in small magazines, just bolstering
Gourmet.'' Kimball says Newhouse also bought Cuisine magazine and
ceased its publication, too.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the Kimballs moved to Boston and bought an old house in
the South End to fix up. Kimball came to run East West Journal,
which badly needed sprucing up. He was hired by Eliot Wadsworth,
publisher of Horticulture magazine. Eventually, Kimball turned East
West around under its new name, Natural Health. He and Wadsworth
and the other investors formed a partnership they named Boston
Common Press. Earlier this year, Natural Health was sold for a
reported $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball never gave up on Cook's. He relaunched it through dogged
perseverance. One day, he did some research and discovered that the
old name was available. ``Bonnier had let the trademark expire,''
he says. ``It cost $175. I sent a check by Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``That was a really good moment,'' he adds, showing some
elation.
</P>
<P>
   He renamed it Cook's Illustrated because there are few finished
photographs _ and no ads or fanfare. Cook's has a devoted fan club
of subscribers interested in the hows and whys of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Though many wonder how he survives without advertisers, others
estimate Cook's Illustrated value at the same $30 million that
Natural Health was sold for.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as publisher of Boston Common Press, he still owns
Handcraft Illustrated and has a few other projects in mind. One is
television. ``People would watch us as we develop the best way to
do recipes. It would be bringing the magazine to life in a
television format.'' This science-of-the-stovetop show will begin
filming next spring, in studios built in the Brookline offices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The real yellow farmhouse
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the few recipes Kimball makes without thinking is
buttermilk biscuits, which he used to eat at the home of Marie
Briggs. She lived in the yellow farmhouse immortalized in the title
of his book. The boy who had to wear a tie for dinner at home was
in his element in the yellow farmhouse, and he writes longingly and
in detail about her midday dinners and the old house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps I remember most fondly the smell of that parlor,'' he
writes, ``the ripe scent of yeast, molasses, fresh bread, green
wood, maple syrup, wood smoke, and pickled meats, a heady perfume
that seeped into the wallpaper and floorboards and that remains
today.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kimball pulls out a bowl to make Marie's biscuits, his
children appear. Caroline glances around and decides on something
more interesting. Charlie, dressed in a cowboy outfit, announces
that he'll put his hands into the biscuit dough. Whitney,
suspecting her father might need help, keeps an eye on her younger
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie pushes a chair up to the counter where a large bowl
holds flour and fat. He holds his hands vertically over the bowl,
ready to plunge them in. Christopher Kimball quickly mixes in the
buttermilk and removes the dough. He begins to roll it out, but
Charlie is champing at the bit to roll, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it nice and light _ not hard,'' says the father. Charlie
follows his instructions. Kimball stamps out biscuits, then Charlie
mimics him.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball moves away to drain turnips and potatoes. Whitney
collects the scraps and rerolls the dough. Charlie watches her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very gently,'' he says. ``Very gently.'' Proud of the moment,
he picks up a handful of scraps and pops them into his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Another Kimball catches the farmhouse bug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
