<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITAL-VANGOGH-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THESE DAYS, VAN GOGH FANS PAY HEAVILY IN TIME OR MONEY
 &HT;    With CAPITAL-ART and CAPITAL-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington, (e)
entertainment and (t) travel categories for release Saturday, Nov.
21.
 &HT;    Cox photos for this story have been placed in the National
folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Advance passes for the National Gallery's Vincent
van Gogh exhibit are long gone, but art lovers still have two ways
to get in: patient determination or cold, hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   Every day before sunrise, bleary-eyed people begin forming a
twisting line that can grow to thousands of people, all hoping for
one of the 2,000 free same-day passes the gallery hands out.
</P>
<P>
   Gallery spokeswoman Deborah Ziska said visitors with the best
chance of seeing ``Van Gogh's van Goghs: Masterpieces from the van
Gogh Museum, Amsterdam'' are those who are in line at the gallery's
West Building by 8 a.m. on a weekday and 7 a.m. on a weekend or
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Since passes aren't handed out until 10 a.m. (11 a.m. on
Sundays), even the first person in line will wait two to four hours
for an allotment of up to four tickets. Those who do succeed must
return later that day for their appointed visiting time.
</P>
<P>
   And for many, the vigil is for naught. Some visitors tell of
joining the line well before dawn, only to be turned away
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   If you would rather spend money than time, the daily Washington
Post and Washington Times newspapers carry numerous classified ads
for advance tickets, all of which were distributed weeks before the
exhibition opened.
</P>
<P>
   Prices vary, depending on whether you want to see the show
during the week or on the weekend, but expect to pay $60 to $100
each.
</P>
<P>
   As for same-day passes, some of those early birds in the daily
line for free tickets work for scalpers, a fact that has provoked
heated debate here.
</P>
<P>
   These tickets are sometimes sold on the street near the museum _
if you trust them to be genuine. Others may be available from
ticket resellers or from hotel concierges, always for what the
market will bear.
</P>
<P>
   As of this week, more than 213,000 visitors have seen the
exhibit, averaging about 5,000 per day, Ziska said.
</P>
<P>
   The 72 paintings will remain at the gallery until Jan. 3. The
show will move to the Los Angeles County Museum of Art before
returning to Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
