u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PERSONAL-CHEFS-B     11-18 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PERSONAL-CHEFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK WHO'S COMING TO MAKE YOU DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ It's not that Pat Kauffman-Lang doesn't like to cook.
As a marketing representative for Bread &AMP; Circus, the supermarket
for health-conscious baby boomers, she not only loves to cook but
she's good at it, especially when it comes to preparing healthy,
low-fat meals.
</P>
<P>
   What Kauffman-Lang lacks is time. She and her husband, a
commercial real estate consultant, work such long hours that they
find themselves too tired at the end of the day to prepare dinner.
So Kauffman-Lang recently turned to a personal chef to make those
healthy meals for them, and feels only a little guilty about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still struggle over it,'' says Kauffman-Lang. ``It feels a
little indulgent having someone come in and cook for me, but it's
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Endlar Lee, on the other hand, has experienced no such
twinges since she hired a personal chef last February. Lee, 36, is
the mother of a 3-year-old daughter and a 5-month-old son and works
full time as an institutional bond broker for a large Boston firm.
Her husband is a pediatrician who, Lee says, ``can't even boil
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee says that if she had known before this year that a personal
chef like Susan Goldstein existed, she would have hired her long
ago. ``I had to ask around quite a while before I found'' Susan,
she says. ``Now I can't imagine not having her cook for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal chefs may be the best-kept secret in the home service
industry these days. The field is considered _ by those in the
know, such as Entrepreneur Magazine _ one of the ``hottest
home-based businesses in 1998,'' with the number of personal chefs
doubling every year (There are more than 2,000 personal chefs in
business nationwide.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, most people don't even know what a personal chef does.
Nor do they realize that such chefs are no longer the exclusive
province of rock stars or Hollywood celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Personal chefs may not have arrived in middle America, says
David MacKay, the executive director of the US Personal Chefs
Association, but they are penetrating major metropolitan areas such
as Boston and many of its more well-heeled suburbs. And they can be
found cooking away in such diverse locations as an elderly widow's
spacious art-filled home in Belmont, a dual-earner couple's
comfortable split-level in Newton, and a tiny apartment turned
condominium on the west side of South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who has worked as a personal chef for a dozen years,
says: ``Five or 10 years ago, my clients considered me a luxury,
not a necessity. But now my clients think of me more as a necessity
than a luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Endlar Lee certainly does. Once a month, usually on a
Wednesday, Goldstein walks into Lee's neo-colonial house in Weston
at 7:30 a.m. with five or six bags of groceries that she bought the
night before. Goldstein, whose business is called Personally
Prepared by Susan, has already discussed the day's menu with Lee by
phone. And by the time Goldstein arrives, Lee and her husband have
departed for work.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein is usually greeted by the nanny, who watches the
couple's children. She ties on a white freshly laundered &UR;  &LR; apron,
takes some pots and pans out of the Lees' cabinets, and gets down
to work.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 p.m., she has prepared anywhere from 10 to 14 meals for
the family: chicken cacciatore, stir fry with chicken and shrimp,
baked stuffed potatoes with vegetables, marinated veal chops for
the grill. She puts them in plastic or glass containers, labels the
meals, and stores them in the Lees' ample refrigerator. Some of
these meals can also go into the freezer, and Goldstein leaves
specific instructions on how to heat up or thaw meals.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein then cleans up her ``mess'' and walks out the door
around 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan is great,'' says Lee during a brief break from her
hectic bonds job.  &UR;  &LR; ``She will cook anything you want and use any
recipe you want. And it's not outrageous in terms of price. I spend
between $300 and $325, including the cost of the groceries, and
that's for 10 to 14 meals.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Lee discovered Personally Prepared by Susan, she used to
boil pasta or stick chicken in the broiler when she came home from
work every evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``As my daughter got older and wanted my attention when I came
home, it became increasingly difficult to turn my back on her and
cook something on the stove,'' Lee recalls. ``And now with two
children, it's even more difficult. If there's nothing prepared, my
husband will eat peanut better and jelly sandwiches, but I get sick
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Ruder, the mother of two preschoolers, also works full
time, in the communications department at Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute. She, too, was sick of eating the same old spaghetti and
meat sauce every night. Seven months ago, her in-laws offered to
pay for a personal chef for the family, and Ruder is still gushing
over the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best gifts we could have received,'' says
Ruder, who doesn't walk in her front door until after 6 p.m.,
having picked up her two sons from day care. ``It has really made a
difference in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, coming home to find freshly prepared baked
chicken with peaches or vegetable stuffed peppers, cooked
Russian-Jewish style and neatly stored in plastic containers in her
refrigerator, allows Ruder and her husband to sit down and eat with
their children. In the days before they had a personal chef, the
couple often didn't get around to cooking for themselves until
after their sons went to bed, around 9 p.m. It was just too
difficult to try to cook their own meals while fixing the boys'
requisite macaroni and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big mac-and-cheese fan,'' Ruder admits. ``And this
feels so much better to me than doing a lot of takeout. There are a
lot of hidden salts and fats and other things in takeout food, and
this gives us control over what we're eating.''
</P>
<P>
   For many people who use personal chefs, that is one of the
biggest selling points of the service. Chefs like Goldstein, who
will travel up to 60 miles, or Laurie Goguen, who is based in
Watertown, customize their cooking to their clients' tastes and
dietary needs.
</P>
<P>
   Goguen, for instance, asks her clients to fill out a lengthy
food preference survey before she begins cooking for them.
Goldstein asks the same questions in person. And both chefs shop
where their clients want them to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Both Goldstein (who charges $35 an hour plus the cost of
groceries) and Goguen (who charges $25 an hour plus groceries) are
experienced chefs. Goldstein, 39, graduated from the prestigious
Culinary Institute of America in New York and worked as a
commercial chef for several years before going into business for
herself. Goguen, 26, taught nutrition cooking classes for a
health-food company before striking out on her own this year.
</P>
<P>
   But, as they and others caution, there are entrepreneurs who don
the personal chef's hat with very little experience or skill. And
getting a referral from the US Personal Chefs Association, a
for-profit operation based in Albuquerque, simply means the chef
has paid $595 to $1,800 for a mail-order training package, and $50
more to sign on as a member of the association.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kauffman-Lang has never heard of the chefs' association. She
hired her first personal chef by word of mouth, through the friend
of a friend. But she says the woman wasn't very clean and didn't
have a large repertoire of dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't trust her alone in my kitchen,'' Kauffman-Lang says.
``With Laurie (Goguen), I leave the door open and give her free
rein in the kitchen. I totally trust her and her judgment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
