<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON WARY OF ROAD AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson is not impressed or comfortable with the fact that
his team is leading the AFC East by one game with six left in the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go look at our schedule,'' said Johnson Tuesday afternoon
before going into a coaches meeting to prepare his Miami Dolphins
for Monday night's game in Foxborough. ``We've got a schedule the
rest of the way that's as tough as anyone's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the road in New England, in Oakland, and finish in
Atlanta. At home we've got New Orleans, the Jets, and Denver. Not
one of those teams has a losing record.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose team beat New England, 12-9, in overtime four
weeks ago in Miami, is aware that the Patriots are banged up but
has no sympathy for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team has injuries at this time of year,'' he said. ``I'm
not even thinking about their situation. All I know is that we
don't play well up there. I've never won a game there. And we don't
play as well on the road as we do at home. So we know how big this
game is on Monday night and we know it is going to be difficult for
us to win up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even thought they haven't been winning, from what I've seen,
their defense has still been playing pretty good. They gave up some
yards to (Doug) Flutie's scrambling in the last game, but our
quarterback (Dan Marino) doesn't scramble,'' laughed Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Sharpe will have the last laugh. Wayne Simmons got cut
Tuesday by Kansas City, and teammate Derrick Thomas has been
suspended one game, after both of them acted like thugs at the end
of the Chiefs' 30-7 loss to the Denver Broncos Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs had five personal fouls in the closing minutes of the
game, 13 penalties in all. Thomas had three personal fouls, and
Simmons triggered some mayhem at the end of the contest with a
personal foul.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs coach Marty Schottenheimer said he was embarrassed by his
team's actions.
</P>
<P>
   According to someone close to the Chiefs, the Kansas City
defensive players were looking to punish Sharpe, the
sometimes-mouthy tight end, for remarks he reportedly made about
them. It is not clear whether the alleged remarks were made to the
media or in private. However, word was around before the game that
they would go after Sharpe if they had a chance. When the game was
out of reach, that's exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, referee Dick Hantak did not take the opportunity
to eject both Simmons and Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs can dump Simmons because he does not hurt them much
under the salary cap. But even if they wanted to get rid of Thomas,
they couldn't, because he has a huge contract, and all of it would
roll forward into next year's salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is the biggest disappointment in the league to date.
After posting the best record in the AFC the previous two years,
the team has fallen apart. In recent years, the Chiefs took in a
lot of players who had bad reputations around the league, and that
appears to be haunting them.
</P>
<P>
   This past offseason, their big free agent acquisition was former
Raider defensive tackle Chester McGlockton. McGlockton was injured
in training camp, underwent back surgery, and returned to the
starting lineup four games ago. The Chiefs have lost all four of
those games. Last year, the Raiders finished 30th _ last _ in
defense, with McGlockton supposedly their best defensive player.
Without him this season, they have been leading the league.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why isn't the league going after the Patriots for not telling
the truth on their Oct. 22 injury report?
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 21, Terry Glenn reportedly was injured in practice. The
league rules stipulate that such an injury must be reported to the
league and the opponent (Miami) by 1 p.m. the next day. Yet when
the Patriots filed their report the next day at 1, there was no
mention of Glenn. It wasn't until three hours later that the
Patriots made the notifications.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots reported the injury, they listed Glenn as
``questionable,'' which means the player has a 50/50 chance of
playing. There have been four games since then, and Glenn hasn't
even dressed for one of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll keeps talking about how the Patriots' offense has
to be better, and he is correct, but the defense hasn't been any
bargain, either. After Sunday's 13-10 loss in Buffalo, they still
have given up more first downs via the pass than any team in the
league, and they are 26th in time of possession, because they can't
get the other guys off the field. What the Patriots have done well
on defense is hold opponents to field goals rather than touchdowns,
even though they have been giving up a lot of yards.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
