<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK UNIT FACES CHANGES IN TIMBER MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston has made a buck off a lot of things over time, from cod
to computers. Add trees to the list.
</P>
<P>
   The city has evolved as the capital of a relatively young and
growing form of investing over the last decade, buying and managing
millions of acres of timberland for institutions across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But changes appear to be taking place rapidly. Forest products
companies have more motivation than ever to sell; publicly traded
real estate investment trusts specializing in timber are around the
corner; and management head-hunting that goes with an emerging
business is rearranging executive rosters.
</P>
<P>
   No company sits in the middle of these developments like the
king of the institutional forest, Hancock Timber Resource Group.
</P>
<P>
   The group, a unit of John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.,
manages about half of all of the $5 billion to $6 billion
institutions have invested in timberland. Three other companies,
including Boston-based Prudential Timber Investments, compete in a
distant second tier of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock was a pioneer in the business in the early 1980s, taking
expertise developed lending to forest products companies and
building it into actual portfolios of property managed for pension
funds and other institutional clients.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock expanded the business with a diversification pitch and
handsome returns. Hancock's timber clients have earned an average
of 16 percent a year over the last five years, in a real estate
category that matches the long-term horizons of its pension
investors.
</P>
<P>
   But Hancock has suffered a big round of management turnover,
losing at least seven executives in the last year. An important
long-term client, the $44 billion State Teachers' Retirement System
of Ohio, decided this month to move its $335 million timber account
and split it between two other firms.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's biggest client of all, the California Public
Employees' Retirement System, has opened its giant $1.2 billion
timber account to new management proposals for the first time in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals from more than a dozen competitors were due in
September, and a spokesman said the pension plan would probably
interview candidates on its short list early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we're focused on the Calpers account,''
said William Coleman, chief executive of Hancock Timber Resource
Group. ``They have asked for proposals for all their real estate
accounts, and now it's Hancock's turn. We've told what we think is
a very good story in response to that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is upbeat news, too. Hancock Tuesday landed a big deal in
Australia, agreeing to pay $352 million for timber rights on
411,000 government-owned acres. A small group of US and Australian
clients put up the money. For Hancock, the deal effectively
replaces the Ohio pension business it just lost and brings the
firm's total assets under management to $3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been looking at the southern hemisphere as a way of
globally diversifying our clients' portfolio,'' said Coleman.
``This deal is really a huge victory for us because we've become
the largest private owner of timber in Australia in a single
transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock has lost a string of longtime timber executives to new
ventures within the last year, including its former leader, Rick
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith left Hancock last year and launched a start-up, Forest
Systems, with the idea of growing an investment company that
actually owned timberland instead of just managing it for clients.
Investors would buy into Forest Systems itself, with hopes that it
would become a publicly traded company before long.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's first piece of business just came in the door. Forest
Systems was the company that won the lion's share of Hancock's Ohio
teachers account. But for now it will only manage $210 million of
the pension fund's property.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hancock alum, Scott Jones, is the chief executive of
Timberland Growth Co., a timber real estate investment trust
waiting to go public. Timberland Growth operates 824,000 acres that
was owned by two forest product companies. Three other former
Hancock Timber executives joined Jones in the new venture earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hancock had the most envied track record in the business, and
individuals with that experience became sought-after for
opportunities as (timber investing) continued to grow,'' said
Jones, who had served as Hancock Timber's director of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said Hancock moved quickly to fill management holes
created by the turnover. He said new Hancock executives tend to
have more global investment and capital markets experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's perfectly natural for the industry to look to us
for talent,'' said Coleman, who joined Hancock in March. ``In a
funny kind of way, we take that as a compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   All the timberland management firms are facing two important new
developments as they compete. The advance of timber real estate
investment trusts, which offer liquidity through shares that can be
easily bought or sold, may catch on. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Timberland Growth and a handful of other companies are going to
find out. Hancock's Coleman agreed there would be ``significant''
securitization of timberland in the future and said his firm was
looking into the possibility of forming a REIT.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, forest products companies that produce things like
paper, hardwood for furniture, pulp, and construction timber are
thinking harder about the possibility of getting cash or stock in
return for their illiquid real estate holdings. Monetizing their
timberland holdings can make financial sense for companies
competing around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Timberland investments could baloon if real estate investment
trusts attract lots of fresh cash and forest product companies
decide its smart economics to sell their property.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, lots of new competitors like Forest Systems and
Timberland Growth make for a crowded field of investment managers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
