<HEADER>
A6651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-18 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HMO BUCK STOPS HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They promised us the moon.
</P>
<P>
   And we wanted to believe we could get it for little or no cost _
that, plus fabulous medical care, delivered by ever-cheerful
doctors and nurses, eager to diagnose and treat every gripe and
groan.
</P>
<P>
   The managed health care industry lured us with an eternity of
sunsets and beaches where everyone ages happily and gracefully,
with access along the way to all the treatments any body would
possibly need.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad fiscal reality is quite different from gauzy, feel-good
commercials. Now, the check is on the table and no one wants to
pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   Take Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, long considered the jewel of
Massachusetts HMOs, which consistently rank among the highest of
quality in the United States. It is the villain of the moment,
having declined to join in a one-year reprieve that would allow
seniors enrolled in Medicare HMOs to continue to chose a plan with
unlimited drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no one villain in this drama. And there are no real
heroes either.
</P>
<P>
   To make a complicated story simple, this is all about passing
the buck.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government does require that seniors are cared for,
and it developed the Medicare program to do that. However, the
federal government does not require Medicare to safeguard seniors
by covering drug prescription costs. Medical costs continue to
increase and reimbursement, including Medicare, is not keeping
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has been the only state in the nation requiring
the HMOS to offer unlimited drug benefits for those enrolled in
Medicare health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs challenged the requirement and won. So, on Jan. 1, the
220,000 seniors and disabled people enrolled in all of the state's
Medicare HMO's will likely face limited drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As the deadline approaches and the politicians scurry to buy
time, the HMOs are engaging in a flurry of gamesmanship. Each one
is trying to make the other look like the bad guy, pledging an
assortment of caps, reprieves, and foundations that are all but
impossible to sort out and understand.
</P>
<P>
   After a public outcry, Tufts Health Plan, Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Massachusetts, and Fallon Community Health Plan said they
would extend unlimited benefits for a year while policy makers
worked out a long-term solution _ but only if Harvard Pilgrim also
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in their cold, corporate heart-of-hearts, each competitor
probably knew Harvard Pilgrim would never sign on. So their
accommodating proposals were at least partly for show.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Harvard Pilgrim says it simply cannot afford to pay the
drug costs. The HMO, which employs more than 4,500 people, says it
lost $22.2 million in the first three quarters of 1998. It blamed
the losses on larger than expected medical expenses, which
outstripped its premium revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated we would be able to control our medical
expenses, more than was the case,'' says Harvard Pilgrim spokesman
Alan Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   To offset the losses, Harvard Pilgrim will increase premiums in
1999 and reduce administrative expenses. This week, it announced it
would eliminate 100 jobs, in a way using its own employees as pawns
in this high-stakes public relations game.
</P>
<P>
   But what about us?
</P>
<P>
   We bought into the HMO commercials because we wanted to believe
what we know cannot possibly be true.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot stay young and healthy forever. We will all grow old,
some more gracefully than others. Medical care costs money and
prescription drugs _ the single largest health-care and unregulated
expense for the elderly _ cost more.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials showing the bliss of healthy seniors jogging
into the twilight will be the ultimate ruse on the baby boomer
generation, if government and business don't join forces to staunch
the bleeding. A bandaid is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SFX-ENTERTAINMENT-2ND     11-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SFX-ENTERTAINMENT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (f and e coding)  
 NEW YORK: ... any more.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All of which raises the question: Why would Sillerman pay $1
billion for all these businesses?
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Sillerman said that the answer, in a
nutshell, is national advertising. Having created the first
nationwide network of amphitheaters with his purchases, he is
convinced he can attract national advertisers who have avoided
concerts and most other live events until now because of the
fractured nature of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he said, credit card companies, apparel makers,
telecommunications firms, and soft-drink bottlers will want to buy
spots at events in every corner of the country or the right to slap
their names on tours and the facilities at which they play. And the
money they pay will be gravy for SFX.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside here is just tremendous,'' Sillerman said.
``There's so much inherent growth that's available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But some entertainment industry veterans suspect
Sillerman's true aim is something quite different, something that
doesn't require him to tightly manage the companies he has acquired
or even do much to attract advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, he's going to flip it'' _ sell SFX to a record
company and media conglomerate like MCA, Polygram, or Time-Warner,
said former Ticketmaster chief executive Frederic D. Rosen, a
longtime industry player. ``Bob's a bright guy, who in his prior
career helped consolidate the radio industry. But his history is
one of consolidating and selling, not consolidating and
operating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sillerman learned the art of buying and selling from his father,
who assembled the Keystone Radio Network when his son was a child.
At Brandeis, the younger Sillerman started a company that sold
fellow students almost anything he could lay his hands on.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was a heady place in the late 1960s, even for those who
did not let drugs and revolutionary rhetoric cloud their interest
in business. ``We were all part of the alternative culture,''
recalled veteran DJ Charles Laquidara. ``It was OK for the Boston
Tea Party or the Phoenix (or a young Brandeis student's company) to
make money because it was going to be part of a new capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Sillerman's case, there was always a twist to the
money-making. His company started serving not as an alternative
kind of business but as a consultant on ``youth culture'' for
corporate advertisers. He began trawling for his first deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although he bought and sold radio stations during the late 1970s
and throughout the 1980s, his ship did not really come in until the
beginning of this decade, and then in a way that left many people
outraged.
</P>
<P>
   Correctly anticipating that the federal government would loosen
restrictions on radio station ownership, he started three publicly
traded companies that bought more than 70 small and mid-sized
stations. He kept large blocks of stock in each firm for himself
and then _ for huge fees _ served as the firms' investment banker,
financial adviser, corporate strategist, and even landlord.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy was a deal shop,'' said Gary Stevens, one of the
nation's largest independent radio brokers, who was stung in an
early transaction with Sillerman, but later made millions selling
him stations. ``His real business was not operating (stations); it
was generating deals to take the fees.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was buying, Sillerman brushed aside complaints of
self-dealing by saying the arrangements had been properly disclosed
in Securities and Exchange Commission filings. Since selling his
radio properties at a tremendous profit, he has declared himself
vindicated and even former critics agree.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everybody in the entertainment industry thinks
Sillerman is out to duplicate his radio success in live
entertainment. Everybody, that is, except Sillerman himself, who
asserted that he is running the company ``as if my now 5-year-old
daughter is going to be operating this business.''
</P>
<P>
   In his interview, Sillerman said he will soon announce a series
of new advertising deals, food concession arrangements, and
ticketing contracts that will show how SFX intends to pay off its
huge debt and make money, both without raising costs to the average
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   But industry veterans warn that there is a fundamental flaw in
his plan: his assumption that SFX will be able to keep any
additional money it makes. Unlike entertainment companies such as
Disney, which owns the movies and theme parks from which it
profits, SFX does not own the bands, theatrical shows, and monster
trucks that fill its venues. These groups once worked for
comparatively modest amounts, but that day is long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Sillerman's proposal to expand advertising, for
example, Irving Azoff, who manages the rock group The Eagles, said:
``If they're going to create new revenue sources, that's great. I'm
going to want 90 percent of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The moon rose high and the house hopped the night of Sillerman's
benefit concert in July. As Rod Stewart prepared for his last
number, his drummer stepped aside for a guest player _ Ron
Perelman. The song was ``We're Havin' a Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Sillerman said he thinks there will be a lot of parties as the
century draws to a close, and that that is good news for SFX.
``There is a general belief,'' he said, ``that the US is going to
be in a party atmosphere for the next two years, so a lot of
entertainers will be touring'' and playing SFX amphitheaters.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent $1 billion, he had better be right, according to
industry executives. If he's not, he may never again be as well-off
as he was that July night. Neither may America's rock and pop
concertgoers, who would have to endure the crumbling of the
entertainment empire he has built.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
