<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6657 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-FUNDS-ART-BOS     11-18 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-FUNDS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.E. FIRMS GARNER $550M IN VENTURE CAPTIAL QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it optimism in the face of adversity.
</P>
<P>
   As US stock markets nosedived and most investors bit their
nails, venture capital funds pumped a record-setting $550.8 million
into 114 young New England companies during the third quarter,
continuing their bets on software, communications, medical
technology _ even retailing and education _ as tomorrow's
money-makers.
</P>
<P>
   That money represented one-seventh of the $3.77 billion that
went to 708 companies nationwide during the July-September period,
also a record.
</P>
<P>
   The total for New England topped the previous high, set during
this year's first quarter, by $16.6 million, according to The
Boston Globe/PriceWaterhouseCoopers Money Tree Survey for the third
quarter of 1998. The national figure was up $70 million from last
spring's high.
</P>
<P>
   Software and computer companies, including a proliferation of
Internet-related companies, captured 65 percent of New England
investment, double what those sectors attracted nationwide. Medical
instruments and devices took third place in the region.
Biotechnology and pharmaceutical companies followed.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick M. Gray, a PricewaterhouseCoopers Technology Group
partner in Boston, said the survey's findings painted ``a rosy
picture'' for entrepreneurs who depend on venture capital to build
what begins as a good idea into a profitable company.
</P>
<P>
   And Gray said this pace should continue, as institutional money
managers, who put money in venture funds, roll over the proceeds of
venture-fund investments made many years ago. Many of those
long-term investments last year delivered annualized returns of
between 25 percent and 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are huge dollar amounts going into venture capital,''
added David Fischer, executive vice president at Silicon Valley
East, a local investment banking affiliate of Silicon Valley Bank
of California. Fund managers in turn are obliged to ``put it to
work,'' he said. ``Investors don't want it just sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   But some venture fund managers, still upbeat about long-term
prospects, said recent uncertainty in financial markets casts a
cloud on whether this momentum can be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things will flatten out a bit,'' said Nicholas
Callinan, in the Boston office of Advent International, a major
venture capital firm. ``That's not to say that things are bad, just
that they won't be as strong as they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is a slowdown, last summer's flow of money should
keep many companies afloat for some time, and the biggest winners
illustrate New England's entrepreneurial diversity:
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicines Co. of Cambridge, Mass. received the largest single
funding in New England during the quarter, $36 million. The company
buys drug ideas from other firms for development and will use its
money to pay for ongoing work on two products, and as ``a war
chest, so if we find another candidate we can buy it,'' said Clive
Meanwell, founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nexabit Networks Inc. of Marlborough, mass., which is
developing high-capacity telecommunications switches and is seen as
a leader among scores of firms in this field, received $25 million.
With Ray Stata, chairman of Analog Devices Inc., as its leading
private investor, Nexabit hopes to have its first products out for
testing this year and widely marketed in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _ OrderTrust LLC of Lowell, Mass. raised the third largest
amount, $22.9 million, from private investors and two venture
funds. The company uses the Internet to process orders for
marketers who sell products delivered by other vendors. SkyMall,
the airline-magazine marketer, and 1-800-FLOWERS, which arranges
floral deliveries nationwide, are clients. OrderTrust controller
David Desrochers said the funding will support growth as the
founders, Timothy and Thomas Litle, explore whether to go public,
remain private, or seek a buyer or a merger partner.
</P>
<P>
   _ HarvardNet Inc. of Portsmouth, N.H., an Internet service
provider in Maine, New Hampshire, and Massachusetts, received $18
million, the fourth largest funding for the quarter. William
Southworth, founder of the five-year-old firm, said the cash is
being used to bolster management, install high-speed data lines,
and build a facility in Boston to house servers holding Web pages
and user software. ``We needed a quantum change,'' he said. ``It
was time to raise some money to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 25 percent of third-quarter investments in New England
were late-stage placements. Some fund managers said this may
reflect the need some companies had for cash after the summer
downturn on Wall Street delayed plans for making initial public
stock offerings to raise money and pay off earlier investors.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff began in mid-July and hit young and technology-based
companies hardest.
</P>
<P>
   Seven New England companies did go public during that time,
though _ six in July and one in September. The largest of these,
Cyberian Outpost Inc. of Kent, Conn., defied the odds, going out at
$18 per share, compared with the company's prediction, in a
registration filing, of between $13 and $15 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet-only computer products retailer's offering on July
31 raised $72 million. ``I say we just made it by a day,'' Cyberian
president Daryll Peck said. ``The following week would have been
too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyberian Outpost shares traded up to 26 on the first day, before
a downward slide that bottomed at 6 3/4 on Sept. 14. As of Friday
shares closed &UR;  &LR; at 16 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the traditional sources of money for venture funds _
pension funds, college endowments, trust-fund managers, and others
who allocate a percentage of assets to these high-risk, high-return
investments _ keep pouring it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more venture capitalists than ever before,'' said
Fischer, at Silicon Valley East.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, venture companies created 140 new limited
partnership funds in 1997, according to Venture Capital Journal, a
magazine that covers the industry. At least as many are expected to
be formed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pieter Schiller, a partner at Advanced Technology Ventures in
Waltham, Mass., said a $175 million fund ATV created this year was
oversubscribed, but was closed at that point to avoid putting too
much pressure on its managers to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``One cannot help but look at the amount of money flowing into
the industry and scratch your head,'' Schiller said. But the effect
is inevitable, he said: ``If you have more people putting money in,
the amount of money being poured into little companies will go
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Matrix Partners, also in Waltham, closed another new fund at
$150 million. ``We could have raised three or four times that,''
Matrix partner Paul J. Ferri said. A third Waltham-based venture
firm, Charles River Ventures, is now closing another $175 million
pool, and many more are in progress.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, even more cash is being made available through
venture funds developed by brokerage houses and marketed to
individuals made rich by the recent stock-market boom.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Wadsworth, a managing director at HarbourVest
Partners in Boston, said those funds have raised new problems
revolving around investor expectations.
</P>
<P>
   These buyers are accustomed to buying and selling quickly on the
open market. Venture fund partnership shares, however, are not
easily traded and don't deliver returns for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole new source of capital that may not be as
long-term in its outlook, may be more volatile, and may dry up when
private equity markets hit a downturn,'' Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe/PricewaterhouseCoopers survey again ranked
California's Silicon Valley as the nation's dominant region for new
companies getting venture funding, with 208 firms there attracting
$1.24 billion. That was about the same amount companies in that
region received during the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But venture funding in the Southeast, which in the past has
threatened to overtake New England and move from third place to
number two, slipped 3.5 percent, to $336.2 million shared among 60
firms. The Los Angeles/Orange County region ran fourth, with $290
million going to 27 companies. Texas was in fifth place with 44
companies sharing $257.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIAL-AROUND-2TAKES-BO     11-18 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAL-AROUND-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USERS OF 10-10 SERVICES CONFUSED BY OBSCURE TERMS? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes 10-10 companies text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theodore Jacobs feels besieged. He gets several direct-mail
pitches a week for 10-10 long-distance telephone services. He only
has to spin the television dial to see more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I am snowed under. It boggles the mind all these
10-10 offers,'' says Jacobs, a retired teacher and part time actor
from Framingham, who so far has not used any of them. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance phone carriers offering 10-10 ``dial-around''
services recently have unleashed an advertising blitz. Trumpeting
their ability to offer lower rates, the 10-10 services seek
cost-conscious callers willing to dial the extra digits to &UR;  &LR; make
interstate and international calls.
</P>
<P>
   With names like Telecom USA, Lucky Dog, and New Dimeline, the
dial-around operators use TV actors such as John Lithgow, Dennis
Miller, and Tony Danza, as well as promotional contests that award
cruises, airline tickets, and other prizes. They hope to get
consumers to bypass their chosen long-distance provider; 10-10
calls are connected through the alternative provider's network. In
the past 12 months, nearly 20 percent of US households have tried
dial-around, according to the Yankee Group, a Boston market
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of 10-10 operators grows, so does confusion over
the myriad terms and conditions of the services. ``Dial- around is
becoming very cluttered,'' says Ken R. Ball, senior vice president
of marketing for Vartec Telecom Inc. of Lancaster, Texas, which
runs the 10-10-811 service, one of 10 major dial-around providers.
</P>
<P>
   Dial-around is one of the latest signs of the constant ferment
in the long-distance phone market. The changes sweeping the $90
billion-a-year industry have made it ever more competitive, pushing
rates ever lower. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, 15 cents a minute was considered a good deal. Today,
service is available for as little as 5 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, per-minute rates for consumers may be on the way out.
Sprint Corp. recently announced a $25 a month calling plan for
unlimited long-distance domestic calls on weekends, although it
will still charge 10 cents a minute for weekday calls. AT&AMP;T Corp.
has said it would match Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it is just a matter of time before the flat-fee
structure adopted by America Online and Internet service providers
becomes a common option for long-distance callers.
</P>
<P>
   While long-distance rates have been declining since the break-up
of the Bell System in 1984, the big push really started with MCI
Communications Inc., which gained millions of AT&AMP;T residential
customers through clever marketing of ``Friends and Family,'' a
pioneering calling plan that provides discounts off standard rates
for frequently dialed numbers. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; MCI's success prompted Sprint and a host of smaller carriers to
roll out a wide range of calling plans &UR;  &LR; with low monthly fees and
drastic reductions off basic per-minute rates. &UR;  &LR; More recently, some
carriers have come out with one-rate plans that offer the same,
discounted rate 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the majority of residential customers _ upwards of 60
million households _ haven't signed up for a low-cost calling plan.
Many of them make few long-distance calls _ less than $20 per
month.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the dial-around carriers. Aiming to capture these
infrequent callers with no strong allegiance to a long-distance
carrier, small long-distance companies jumped into dial-around, on
a regional basis, starting &UR;  &LR; around 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Dial-around companies all pitch simplicity: no sign-ups for
calling plans and no monthly minimums for service. Just dial 10-10,
a three-digit access code, 1, the area code, and the number. The
cost of the call automatically appears on your monthly local phone
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many dial-around services, to the consumer's surprise,
are actually subsidiaries of the established phone giants.
</P>
<P>
   MCI, which started offering dial-around in 1996, last year
elevated it to a national level with hefty television and radio
advertising. The company, now part of MCI Worldcom Inc., was
followed last month by AT&AMP;T's launch of its Lucky Dog 10-10
service, which is now being heavily advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major long-distance companies were losing minutes of usage
to smaller carriers, some offering dial-around, others with prepaid
calling cards, and realized they had to respond,'' said Robert Fox,
telecommunications analyst at Mercer Management Consulting in
Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   And while dial-around is the fastest growing segment of the
long-distance market, it still accounts for only about 3 percent of
the more than $90 billion spent annually on interstate and
international phone calls. Consumers are expected to spend $3
billion on 10-10 dialing this year, double a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The number of long-distances choices today can be mind-boggling,
requiring consumers to shop with pencil-sharp precision.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out the actual costs and savings from a dial-around
service, for instance, isn't so simple. What's rarely understood is
that savings hyped by dial-around carriers are off AT&AMP;T's basic
phone rates, which are the highest available. Heavy users of long
distance _ people who make frequent or lengthy calls _ may be
better off signing up for a calling plan. And, depending on the
time of day or day of the week, some dial-around rates can work out
to be much higher than under calling plans. So it's essential to
know your calling patterns before using dial-around.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, 10-10 services may be most appropriate for
people who make few long-distance calls _ and are willing to pay
for the calls a la carte rather than subscribing to a calling plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers using dial-around are not really saving much money
compared to having a calling plan from a major carrier,'' says
Rebecca Sachs, a spokeswoman for the Telecommunications Research
and Action Center, a Washington-based consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
