<HEADER>
A6663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-VALLEY-BOS &LR;      11-18 1523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-VALLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENERATION OF SWITCH MAKERS GROWS IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When New England telecommunications entrepreneurs are
encouraged to go west, they're not being steered toward
California's Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   They're heading straight to Westford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Route 128 and Cambridge are still attracting
start-ups, but in the $10 billion marketplace to develop the big
iron of the Internet _ the next generation of switches, software,
and high-tech tools for the nation's communications infrastructure
_ several dozen telecommunications firms are planting their roots
in the Interstate 495 communities of Littleton, Tewksbury,
Boxborough, and Chelmsford, with Westford as the epicenter.
</P>
<P>
   With the names Argon, Convergent, Sycamore, Redstone, Castle
Networks, and ArrowPoint, their collective goal is to develop
communications switching systems capable of moving data at
trillions of bits per second and sending a mix of millions of data,
video, and voice ``packets'' to their destinations more quickly and
accurately than today's voice systems.
</P>
<P>
   They were drawn to the quiet community of Westford, 35 miles
northwest of Boston near the New Hampshire border, because of easy
access to I-495, little traffic, low office rents, and a ready-made
work force.
</P>
<P>
   That work force came largely from the former Cascade
Communications Corp., one of the fastest-growing telecom companies
in the mid-'90s. Part of Cascade's success was its ability to
attract experienced electrical engineers who lived in either the
surrounding towns off I-495 or southern New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   So when Cascade was acquired by Ascend Communications last year,
some key employees left to form or join start-ups. In fact, some of
these start-ups are housed in the former Cascade headquarters
building.
</P>
<P>
   The community of 20,000 has felt an impact. Realtors report
housing prices have risen 10 percent annually over the past two
years, and commercial rents, which were under $10 per square foot
three years ago, are now in the $15 to $18 range _ but still well
below the $30 seen along Route 128. And local retailers and
restaurants have seen an increase in business.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike an earlier generation of Route 128 firms that sold
communications and networking products and services directly to
medium and large corporations, the new wave of telecommunications
start-ups are targeting their products to existing telephone
carriers, many of which are not set up to handle today's boom in
digital data.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if the Internet continues to grow at its current pace,
some specialists believe voice telephone traffic will amount to
less than 5 percent of the total communications business by 2004.
That forecast has some of the largest domestic and European
telephone carriers and their traditional voice switch suppliers
scrambling to figure out how to deal with the convergence of data,
voice, and video networks.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Sprint has spent $2 billion to retool its long-distance
telephone network to handle a mix of voice and data more
effectively, while SBC Communications, one of the largest regional
Bell phone companies, said it plans to spend $600 million over the
next three years to transform its network.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, new phone companies, which compete against AT&AMP;T,
Sprint and Bell Atlantic, want to buy the latest Internet switch
technology to gain an edge over their much larger, well-entrenched
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to be the go-to players for the next generation of super
high-speed telecommunications switches are some of the Westford
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a sea change in how telecommunications will be
delivered in the future, and that means developing significantly
better products quickly and at lower prices to a relatively small
group of customers, who will buy large quantities,'' said Tom
Burkhardt, president and founder of Castle Networks Inc. in
Westford, which is building a new switch to bridge the gap between
separate voice and data networks.
</P>
<P>
   Castle is among four start-ups _ the others being ArrowPoint
Communications Inc., Redstone Communications Inc. and Sonus
Networks Inc. _ launched in Westford over the past 18 months,
having received nearly $20 million each in venture capital funding.
A fifth, NextPoint Networks, a software firm, was launched two
years ago and has received $16 million from investors.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Tewksbury, Convergent Networks Inc., formed last May
with $7 million in first-round venture capital, is developing a
switch to move voice traffic over existing data switches. In
Littleton, Argon Networks Inc., formed 18 months ago and now
employing 75 people and $34 million in venture capital, is
developing a high-speed switch aimed at Internet service providers
and telephone carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Further along I-495 in Marlborough is another telecom cluster,
where start-ups Nexabit Networks, Omnia Communications, and
Broadband Access Systems reside.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are seeing is start-ups tackling a piece of the
telecommunications infrastructure they did not handle before, as
the major telephone carriers like AT&AMP;T used to do it all
themselves,'' said Michael Grady, Argon president and cofounder.
``So companies around here are working on bigger, more complex
problems that require more capital and must be solved more
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, a telecom switch start-up must follow a rigorous
timeline: 12 to 15 months to develop its product followed by six to
nine months to market it to some key customers before competition
arrives, and then another six to 12 months to reach profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology changes are moving so fast these days that if you
need two years to develop your product, don't bother, because
you'll miss the time-to-market window when you have little
competition,'' said James Dolce Jr., president of Redstone
Communications Inc., who previously cofounded Arris Networks,
acquired by Cascade before its first anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   And while none of the leaders of these emerging businesses
dreams of becoming industry titans, maybe one will hit financial
pay dirt with an initial stock offering and the others will prosper
when they are acquired by either a big-name competitor or by one of
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisition rumors have already been reported about some of
these start-ups. Argon's Grady declined to discuss published
reports that his company could be acquired by Siemens AG, the
German electronics and telecom company. And earlier this month
Ericsson, the giant Swedish telecommunications equipment company,
said it is looking to acquire start-ups from its new data
networking headquarters in Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be surprised if some of these companies that get $20
million to $30 million in venture capital ultimately sell out for
nothing less than $250 million,'' said Todd A. Dagres, a general
partner at Battery Ventures, a Wellesely venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very large companies are not good at architecting new
products; they are good at adding features to existing products,''
said Edward Anderson, general partner at Northbridge Ventures,
which helped fund three Westford start-ups among a dozen
Massachusetts telecom start-ups. ``But what may take them three
years to design, our companies can do in one-third the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the start-ups: to develop breakthrough telecom
products quickly, working very long hours with colleagues who enjoy
the technical challenges with the ultimate reward of a public stock
offering that makes them a pile of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember telling engineering applicants that if you can't
work 60 hours (a week), don't apply,'' said Cheng Wu, president of
ArrowPoint Communications and a cofounder of Arris Networks.
``Although we probably had people here working 80-hour weeks, we
got our product out on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Those long hours can be punishing on family life. Some firms
provide their employees dinner up to four nights a week,
occasionally with spouses and children at the table.
</P>
<P>
   With salaries averaging $90,000 a year for experienced
engineers, the older, established telecom companies are feeling the
competition, some offering a $25,000 ``retention bonuses,'' stock,
or salary increases to retain talented employees.
</P>
<P>
   Some engineers are in such high demand that they will not even
consider driving down heavily traveled Route 3 toward Bedford,
insisting they would work only close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told the first six engineers that I was thinking of
starting the company in Burlington, they were all ready to quit,
saying they wanted Westford,'' said Rubin Gruber, chairman and
cofounder of Sonus Networks, which last week successfully tested a
combination voice and data switch that works over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber, at 54 the oldest chief executive of the telecom
start-ups, retired three years ago after launching several
companies including Davox Corp. and VideoServer Inc. ``I hated
playing golf, and sitting on the boards of directors of other
companies just did not fulfill me,'' he said. ``This is fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
