<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-CONFUSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELUGE OF NEW DRUGS MAY LEAD TO CONFUSION, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the new anti-psychotic drug Zyprexa debuted
two years ago, several pharmacists reading those prescriptions
mistook it for Zyrtec, an antihistamine.
</P>
<P>
   At least two dozen times, people prescribed Navane for
schizophrenia instead got the blood pressure medication Norvasc,
research data has shown.
</P>
<P>
   And two heart drugs, amrinone for heart failure and amiodarone
for arrythmias, also have been confused, and some patients have
received the wrong one.
</P>
<P>
   Some mix-ups have been fatal. Such was the case with Losec, an
ulcer medication, that was being confused with Lasix, a diuretic.
At least one person died before drugmaker Merck agreed to change
Losec's name to Prilosec in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Today, that drug, one of the most commonly prescribed in the
country, is sometimes mistaken for Prozac, another high-volume drug
that is used to treat depression.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, with Narcan and Norcuron, nelfinavir and
nevirapine, Premarin and Primaxin. With the proliferation of new
drugs on the market, confusion over medications has become a
serious problem, said Bruce Lambert, a professor at the University
of Illinois in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   His database of drug names has grown to more than 1,100 pairs
where one drug was mistakenly dispensed for another, Lambert said
Tuesday. He was attending the American Association of
Pharmaceutical Scientists meeting in San Francisco to discuss the
problem of look-alike and sound-alike drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert told of his recent study in which pharmacists were shown
a list of drug names and then shown another, longer list and then
asked whether any of those on the first list also showed up on the
second. When similarly sounding names were on both lists, the rate
of errors doubled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The take-home message is: We know that similarity increases
the risks of certain kinds of memory errors,'' Lambert said.
``Therefore, we ought to reduce the similarity in drug names
wherever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has taken notice. A year ago,
it began requiring drug companies to get approval ahead of time for
new medication names to make sure they are not too similar to ones
already on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also is about to launch a surveillance campaign to
keep track of problems that crop up because of similar names, as
well as confusing packaging, according to Mike Cohen, president of
the Institute for Safe Medication Practices, a private, nonprofit
organization that tracks prescription errors.
</P>
<P>
   Companies also are becoming more careful. Several have used
Lambert's database to screen names they are considering for new
drugs, he said. The FDA already forbids companies from using names
that sound like the condition the drug is intended to treat, or
that are similar to the medication's generic name.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are concerned because they spend hundreds of thousands
of dollars picking the right name for a new drug, using consultants
and focus groups that help them identify ones the public likes.
Naming drugs has become more of an issue in the past few years as
pharmaceutical companies have begun marketing their products
directly to consumers through big advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notice how many names have Xs and Zs in them,'' Lambert said.
``The branding people believe those letters make the names
distinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lambert has developed a computer program for
pharmacists designed to raise a warning flag when a prescription
for a commonly confused drug name is presented. It is similar to a
program now used to alert pharmacists when a patient is being
dispensed two or more drugs that can be dangerous when taken
together.
</P>
<P>
   With 35,000 drug brand names now registered with the U.S. Patent
and Trademark Office and another 10,000 used as generic names, the
potential for mix-ups is great, Lambert said.
</P>
<P>
   And with doctors' handwriting being what it is, the problem is
by no means rare. Figures reflecting the scope of the problem are
hard to come by, but it is on the rise, Cohen said. He said at
least 4,000 reports of mix-ups had come into his organization since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much worse situation than it was 10 or 15 years ago,''
Cohen said. ``There's a lot more drugs on the market ... and with
the pressures on health professionals because of managed care and
need to control costs, the staffing is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen wants doctors to write on the prescription what it is they
are treating with the drug, so a pharmacist can better figure out
which one they mean. New prescription pads also are being
distributed that have icons representing the heart or kidney or
other body part the drug is supposed to treat.
</P>
<P>
   But he said patients should also be aware of what they were
getting and why and ask their doctors and pharmacists what the drug
should look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done a good job teaching patients what they need to
know to protect themselves,'' Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
