<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-KING-RIGGS-BOS &LR;      11-18 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-KING-RIGGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN KING REIGNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Billie Jean King was borne into the bedlam on an Egyptian
litter by six bare-chested men dressed as Nubian slaves, as Bobby
Riggs appeared in a rickshaw pulled by six women in red T-shirts
that proclaimed them Bobby's Bosom Buddies, as 30,472 spectators in
the Houston Astrodome and a television audience of 50 million
squared off blatantly along gender lines (``Win One for the
Bedroom, Bobby,'' implored one banner), the woman who would become
a legend had a quiet thought:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no turning back.''
</P>
<P>
   She was right. As King and nine other legends of women's tennis
gather this weekend in Hartford, Conn. to celebrate the 25th
anniversary of her triumph in the ``Battle of the Sexes,'' many now
believe _ as King knew all along _ that the match was a turning
point in the movement toward equal opportunity for women not only
in sports but in every facet of American society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood it was about social change,'' she said during a
recent interview. ``That match really got people feeling and
thinking and questioning and asking about themselves and about the
opposite gender. I still get women who come up to me and say, it
changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, as part of the 1998 Phoenix ATP Tour World Doubles
Championship at the Hartford Civic Center, Martina Navratilova and
Chris Evert will lead two teams in an exhibition to commemorate the
historic match. Fittingly, Sunday is the day King will turn 55 _
the same age as Riggs when he lost to her in straight sets 6-4,
6-3, 6-3, on Sept. 20, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs died in 1995 of prostate cancer at the age of 77.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem absurd in 1998 that a tennis match between a
29-year-old in the prime of her career and a 55-year-old far beyond
his could generate such excitement. But in 1973, fresh on the heels
of Title IX and Roe v. Wade, with women earning 59 cents to a man's
dollar and Watergate in full swing, King was yet another threat to
the status quo. Many women thought that was terrific. Many men did
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I daresay there were millions and millions of men and women
watching that match who had no interest in tennis whatsoever,''
said Allen Guttmann, who teaches at Amherst College and is the
author of ``Women's Sports, A History.''
</P>
<P>
   The hype had been building for months. Riggs, a top player in
his day who won Wimbledon in 1939, had long since become the
self-proclaimed clown prince of the sport. As his skills faded his
imagination grew, Riggs made a decent living by betting on himself
to win matches while chained to a Great Dane, or holding a valise.
When he challenged any of the top women tennis players to face him,
$100,000 to the winner, it was just another stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting no part of such nonsense, King turned him down. Several
times. But Margaret Court did not. Apparently succumbing to nerves
and psyched out by the red roses Riggs presented her before the
match in honor of Mother's Day, Court was trounced, 6-2, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't say no'' after that, said King. ``When she lost
badly, then I knew I would have to play. And when ABC said, `We're
going to do it,' I knew that was this was our chance for social
change. Exposure is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rosie Casals, winner of five Wimbledon doubles titles with
King who was in the ABC booth that night and will play this
weekend, put it: ``You knew you were at the top of the top. Howard
Cosell did not do little events.''
</P>
<P>
   While King was largely silent in the days leading up to the
match, Riggs more than made up for it. ``I'll tell you why I'll
win,'' he told Globe writer Bud Collins. ``She's a woman, and they
just don't have the emotional stability.'' But King was winning all
the important skirmishes: the number of sets (five instead of
three), speed of the playing surface, weight of the tennis balls
all favored her youth. Behind the scenes, she was outhustling the
hustler, paying attention to the details while he brayed. ``I was
very scared,'' she said. ``I really needed to win. I just felt like
(a loss) would put us backward. I think it would have given a lot
of people an excuse not to support us.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the match got under way, Riggs led only briefly, quickly
fading in the face of King's powerful volleys. ``She wore him out
in the second set,'' said Casals. ``By the third set, he was
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Women were ecstatic. ``Here we were in the middle of the women's
movement, and there had to be this catalyst, this thing that broke
it all open,'' said Donna Lopiano, executive director of the
Women's Sports Foundation. ``It was like the Berlin Wall. Once one
brick was pushed off, the whole thing came apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Olympic gold medalist Donna de Varona put it: ``We went
right into their sandbox, met 'em face-to-face, and we won. So what
could they say anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   King's battle against Riggs was not her first stand for
equality. In the mid-1960s, she spoke out against under-the-table
payments to ``amateur'' players. In 1970, after several years of
unsuccessful lobbying for prize money comparable to men's, King
helped organize the Virginia Slims professional tour for women. And
it was not her last. She, along with de Varona, founded the Women's
Sports Foundation in 1974, and King remains committed to increasing
diversity and team play in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``All women in sports should bow down to Billie,'' said Tracy
Austin, the two-time US Open champion who also will play this
weekend. ``She really put a lot on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, cautioned King, it is too soon for her or anyone else to
grow complacent. ``The climate and the landscape has changed, but
it obviously needs to change a tremendous lot more. We truly have
to be sure the ABL and WNBA, women's fast pitch softball, make
it,'' she said. ``You really have to give women's professional
sports the same kind of time frame that men's have had to evolve.
People have to be patient. It's very important that people support
these, if people want these opportunities to stay around for their
daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Riggs, who started it all as a hustle and ended up an
inadvertent key player in the women's movement, ``in his later
years, he got the picture of the social change,'' said King, who
became a friend and stayed in touch until the end of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the last things he said to me,'' said King, ``was,
`Boy, we really did make a difference'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
