<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6684 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-18 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLZMAN SPOKE VOLUMES _ SOFTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the people who have ever coached in the National
Basketball Association, no one has ever had a temperament better
suited to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win,'' Red Holzman would say, ``I'm going to go out and
have a steak and Scotch. If we lose, I'm going to go out and have a
steak and Scotch.''
</P>
<P>
   That would make precisely 1,300 steaks and 1,300 Scotches
(assuming, of course, he limited himself to just one of the latter)
during an NBA coaching career that began when he was a 33-year-old
player-coach with the Milwaukee Hawks in 1953 and lasted until the
1981-82 season, when he ended his second stint running the New York
Knicks. Red was very serious about what he did, but he was never
going to get an ulcer, preferring instead to give them, if that's
what it would take to make the team successful. When he left the
bench, it was hardly the end of his contribution to the game he
loved, because for the past 16 years, he had been the Knicks'
``basketball consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Consultant,'' he laughed during a 1987 radio interview. ``A
consultant is a guy you owe money to.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical Red Holzman. He never wanted you to think that he
thought he was important.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always low-key toward everybody,'' wrote Phil Jackson
in his autobiography, ``Maverick.'' ``He had the ability to fade
into the background whenever it was necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything about the public Holzman was understated. Take the
way he called for a timeout, for example. He would rise halfway out
of his seat, casually wave his left hand in the direction of a
player, and then mouth that player's first name once he had his
attention. He looked like an English gentleman hailing a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   He did what he did with so little outward fuss that you could be
forgiven for thinking the team ran on autopilot _ but that would be
a serious miscalculation. The truth is that Red Holzman did a whole
lot of coaching behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight games into the 1967-68 season, he assumed control
of a Knicks team that was widely perceived to be an underachieving
bunch that was taking incessant advantage of Dick McGuire, a noted
nice guy. It took 15 minutes for Holzman to get everyone's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   He called a meeting for 10 a.m. At 10:10, Dick Van Arsdale and
Howard Komives came sauntering in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're fined $10 each,'' Holzman informed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys looked at each other,'' wrote Walt Frazier in his
autobiography, ``Clyde.'' ``You could just about read their lips as
they said to thsmselves, `Hey, what's he think he's doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   At 10:15, the future senator himself arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're fined $15,'' Holzman told Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``From then on the guys knew he meant business,'' wrote Frazier.
``I think he gained instant respect. I know he gained mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The players soon learned that playing for Holzman was at once
simple and demanding. The emphasis was on defense. They were to
``see the ball'' and they were to help each other out. On offense,
they were to make the extra pass.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you say, who doesn't preach that?
</P>
<P>
   What made Holzman special was his ability to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my understanding that Red Holzman possesses more
understanding of human nature than most other coaches do,'' Jackson
tells us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real genius of Holzman lies in his handling of players,''
echoes Bradley in ``Life On The Run.'' (This was, as you see, a
very literary group). ``A comment on a plane or in an airport might
relate tangentially to a previous game, but it is always delivered
low-key.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not afraid to offend his stars and he was completely
comfortable with his black players, neither of which was
necessarily the NBA norm in the late '60s and early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley postulates that Holzman learned a great deal about
coaching during seven summers in Puerto Rico, where he had to deal
with all sorts of playing personalities in all sorts of hostile
environments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the feeling that the Ponce experience has given him
confidence in handling any player in any situation,'' Bradley
wrote. ``It was there he learned to discard his own non-basketball
perceptions when they clashed with a player's in an area unrelated
to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Holzman revealed no company secrets, and he never knocked a
player to the media. You'd ask him a question after a game and he'd
say, ``You saw it; what did you think?'' You came away emptyhanded
but flattered.
</P>
<P>
   He loved to goof on young writers. The first time I ever dealt
with him professionally was after a game in which the Knick bench
had played nobly in defeat. I threw him a softball question, hoping
to extract a few words of praise for Cazzie Russell and the boys.
``He looked at me with apparent disdain. ``They all get in line at
salary time, don't they?'' he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   The man was a classic sideline bench jockey, but the crowd never
knew it because he seldom strayed from his seat. One night he was
on the road and he felt referee Don Murphy was giving the home team
a few too many breaks. ``Hey, Murph,'' Red said, ``you planning on
opening a nice restaurant and bar here when you retire?''
</P>
<P>
   The players talk of him conducting practice in a necktie, and I
can believe it. I don't know if Red Holzman even owned a sports
jacket, because all I ever saw on him was a suit. I always figured
he had 20 suits, 10 black and 10 gray. ``He dresses OK for a
coach,'' Frazier tells us, noting, however, that he wears ``ties
and shirts your cousins give you for birthdays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's looking?'' Holzman would say when queried about his
limited wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   He probably will go down in basketball history as the ``other''
Red, but there is no way to overstate his role in popularizing the
NBA. For it was the 1969-70 Knicks who first connected with the
public at large, and the 1969-70 Knicks were nothing more than Red
Holzman's basketball vision brought to life. As much as people in
Boston don't want to hear it, those Knicks teams of the late '60s
and early '70s brought more attention to the game with their
exquisite brand of team basketball than the 11 Celtics titles of
the Russell years. It was, and is, always all about New York, and
the idea that if a sport can make it there, it can make it
anywhere, to borrow a phrase.
</P>
<P>
   I am going to be deprived of an annual pleasure, which was to go
to Madison Square Garden each year and say hello to Red Holzman. He
died last Friday night, a victim of leukemia. He was 78. I don't
have to ask anyone if he was both a great coach and a great man. I
knew him. I know what I think.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
