<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6688 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      11-18 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND IT TO SIMMONS: HE LOOKS LIKE AN OLD PRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ His nickname at the University of Wisconsin
was ``Touchdown Tony.'' Oh, how the Patriots hope that fits Tony
Simmons in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Especially now, when gloom has descended on Foxborough with the
team 5-5, with talk of a lost season, with talk of a coaching
change at season's end, and with talk of the team moving to another
New England state.
</P>
<P>
   Especially now, when former No. 1 pick Terry Glenn is again
beset by injuries and iffy to return against the Miami Dolphins
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In five games, Simmons has caught two touchdown passes. Among
his 13 receptions are a 47-yarder, a 63-yarder, a 43-yarder, and a
37-yarder. It took Glenn 20 games to catch a 50-yarder, and he has
never had a reception longer than 51 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, who had started three straight games in place of Glenn,
didn't start against the Bills last Sunday because Pete Carroll
wanted Vincent Brisby's veteran leadership on the field. Brisby
tried gallantly to play with a pad around a broken finger but
missed two balls.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons watched as veterans Shawn Jefferson and Ben Coates also
missed passes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the rookie Simmons who caught the ball like a grizzled
veteran, grabbing two passes for 48 yards, including a 37-yard
touchdown _ the only time New England put the ball in the end zone
against the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   It's only been five games, but Simmons appears to be a finely
conditioned athlete _ in track shape, which everyone will tell you
is one step above football shape. It leads you to believe that the
Patriots may have have found something _ a big, durable, tough,
fast receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows that for sure. But Simmons is strength and
conditioning coach Johnny Parker's dream player: a well-conditioned
athlete who is always working toward staying in the best possible
shape.
</P>
<P>
   The irony in his recent emergence is that Simmons played in a
run-oriented system at Wisconsin. Draft gurus across America
thought the Patriots had blown it when they took Simmons in the
second round with the 52d overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   They said he didn't run routes well. They said he had bad hands.
They said he was a ``project.'' They called him a ``track guy,''
which in football means you can't play.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Simmons has shattered all the stereotypes associated
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of confidence in my game right now,'' said
Simmons. ``I'm confident that the ball can be thrown to me and I
can catch it. Right now I'm doing my best and doing what I can to
help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said defenses are playing him as they would most rookie
receivers _ trying to be physical and rattle him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been seeing the same types of coverages, where teams play
a man up and a man behind me, try to catch me, but that's the
defensive plan, and whatever it is, I have to try and defend it,''
he said. ``From the first play, you can tell what they're trying to
do _ or whether it's going to be a long day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a rookie. They have to do something. They try to get me
out of my game. They yell out to me, `You're a rookie, you're a
rookie, you ain't that good.' When they see me play, they try to
instill it in my head that you have to earn your way in this
league.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has responded to the physical abuse on the field by
giving it right back. Simmons often can be seen fighting off his
defender to make separation so he can catch the ball. He's done
that quite successfully. Because he's so fast, he usually does
separate, and because he is so strong in his legs and hips, he can
outleap defenders for ``jump balls,'' much like the Jets' Keyshawn
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons has complete confidence in his speed; in college, he ran
a 4.35-second 40-yard dash and a 10.2 100. He knows few defenders
can keep up with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm faster than some,'' said the Chicago native. ``As
the game goes on, I start to realize whether I'm faster than the
other guy. Sometimes I just come off the ball and rocket off the
ball _ no hands, you can't touch me _ and I'll run past them and
see if they can catch up to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, I played the same way. I got quieter with my hands
when I got here and I was told I had to use my hands more to fight
guys off the line. I haven't got called for them. If a DB is going
to put his hands on me, well, I don't want them on me, so I got to
do what I got to do to get free and to get open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I prove I can get off people and get them away from me,
they'll continue to play bump on me. I know a lot of the DBs
complain to the refs that I'm pushing off. I'm not pushing off. I'm
just playing the game. If they're going to put their hands on me in
the 5-yard range, I'm going to push them off and I have that much
room to do that. I know I can't do that downfield, but I'm going to
take advantage of the space I have.''
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that Simmons is getting more and more comfortable
with Drew Bledsoe. After the 37-yard touchdown pass, the
quarterback pointed to Simmons as if to say, ``Nice job, kid.'' It
was telling that Bledsoe went right back to Simmons after the
rookie was called for ``illegal touching'' (going out of bounds and
coming back in to catch a ball).
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like I had to make up for that play,'' said Simmons,
``but I didn't think I stepped out of bounds. There was no
indication that I had. I asked the ref to explain it and he
couldn't, so I figure that's a phantom call or whatever. I don't
know where they came up with that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Patriots have lost four of their last five, Simmons
has been a bright light for the future. Fans appear more excited
when Simmons goes deep than they do on any other play the offense
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself as the go-to guy,'' said Simmons. ``I'm
just a guy out there playing, but if that's what people want to
call me, then that's the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this is an ongoing process. I have to keep showing I
can do it at this level. My confidence is high right now and I know
I have good skills to play in this league. The more I face some of
these guys, the better I'm going to get. It's fun to play and I
think I'm still on a very good team. We have six more games to show
what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon Glenn may return. Troy Brown is scheduled to be back within
two games. Whither Simmons then?
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots know they can't put him on the back burner, for he
is the hot receiver, the one producing results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
