<HEADLINE>
THANKSGIVING CRANBERRY DESSERT HITS TWO BIRDS WITH A SINGLE CAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not necessary to serve dessert after a Thanksgiving
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Write that down and pass it around the table when the holiday
feast nears its conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says right here I don't have to feed you any dessert. It
was in the newspaper, so it must be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I know as well as you do that if you do save the
clipping, you are going to toss it in the trash bin on or about
Nov. 25. And you are going to bake two pies and buy a gallon of
pumpkin ice cream that nobody wants or needs.
</P>
<P>
   Every year newspaper editorialists feel compelled to remind us
of the true meaning of Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   I'll tell you what it is: It is America's annual guilt trip.
</P>
<P>
   Are you going to cook the feast or will somebody else? If it's a
potluck, who gets lucky and who will be assigned the pot?
</P>
<P>
   Can you put oysters in the stuffing even though you know Aunt
Audrey will turn green, clutch her throat and fall heavily to the
floor? Who is going to be assigned the task of holding Uncle Ned's
head out of the mashed potatoes and gravy after he has killed off
that jug of Gallo blush?
</P>
<P>
   Don't even think about eating in a restaurant on Thanksgiving,
or buying an entire cooked meal from the supermarket. The women in
the party may manage to choke down the food. But they are pretty
sure they are going to be struck with a thunderbolt of hellfire
about the time the check hits the table.
</P>
<P>
   Eating out on Thanksgiving is like cheating _ big time _ on your
income tax. Sooner or later the IRS, or the ghost of John Alden, is
going to catch up with transgressors. And they will spend eternity
chopping turkey gizzards, breaking up day-old bread and boiling
cranberries until they pop.
</P>
<P>
   The modern woman may have been born to be a cop, an astronaut or
a nuclear scientist. But deep down she knows what she is really
supposed to do is cook a big Thanksgiving dinner for all the
relatives. And to complete the meal with two pies and a quart of
pumpkin ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Well, since I know you are going to ignore my good advice, you
might as well prepare a cinch-o dessert for Thanksgiving. And you
won't have to make any cranberry sauce. The berries are in the:
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving Cake
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups raw cranberries
</P>
<P>
   Cream the butter with the sugar in an electric mixer. Beat in
the vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl sift together the flour, baking powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   With the mixer running, alternately add flour mixture and milk
to the sugar mixture and beat until smooth. Turn off the infernal
machine and stir in the cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   Pour this mess into a greased 8-by-8-inch baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 30 to 35 minutes in a preheated, 400-degree oven.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm with either of the following sauces:
</P>
<P>
   Brandy Sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup water
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup cream or low-fat evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve the sugar in the water, without stirring. Cook over low
heat until the sugar is dissolved, then simmer this mixture until
it begins to turn brown. Resist the impulse to stir. If you do, the
sugar will crystallize.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully add the cream, removing from heat if mixture foams up.
Add the brandy (now you can stir). Remove pan from stove and beat
in the butter. Spoon over hunks of cranberry cake.
</P>
<P>
   Butter Sauce
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a saucepan. Blend in the sugar. Stir in cream
and simmer three to four minutes, stirring once or twice.
</P>
<P>
   This will serve eight. If you are expecting 16, double the
recipe, or take a midnight flight to Maui.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
