<HEADLINE>
SIZING UP DOWNSIZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the fall of 1994, two weeks after his divorce became final,
computer engineer Larry Nagel learned he would be part of a
company-wide downsizing at AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Nagel was 48, and his life was a mess: His marriage had fallen
apart, his mother was sick, he was drinking too much, and his
relationship with his boss had deteriorated. Still, Nagel was
stunned.
</P>
<P>
   So was Tom Chase. He lost his managerial job at AT&AMP;T in the
summer of 1994. Within two years, his marriage had ended, his two
daughters had left with their mother, and an intense job hunt,
involving hundreds of resumes and dozens of interviews, had yielded
only a brief stint as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Harvard University who had been regarded as a
creative _ or ``idea'' _ man at AT&AMP;T, Chase is now 53, and says he
will never work for a corporation again.
</P>
<P>
   Chase and Nagel are among six men and women whose stories are
recounted in ``Disconnected,'' a new book by New York author
Barbara Rudolph. Published by The Free Press, a division of Simon &AMP;
Schuster Inc., ``Disconnected'' goes beyond the workplace, into the
protagonists' homes and personal lives. By getting so close,
Rudolph succeeds in exploring the impact of downsizing while
revealing the connection between work and identity and how much
that connection has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph chose American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. workers for her
research because no other company seemed to fit the new work
paradigm as much as the telecommunications giant. Between 1984 and
1985, the company shed 120,000 jobs from its employment roster.
Though AT&AMP;T had been laying off factory workers for years, the new
layoffs targeted white-collar workers for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the summer of 1980, AT&AMP;T had announced plans for a
companywide reorganization that would lead to the establishment of
new domestic and foreign subsidiaries. The announcement came in
response to an earlier decision by the Federal Communications
Commission, which planned to push for deregulation of the telephone
industry with or without congressional legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shape of our future is coming clear,'' then AT&AMP;T chairman
Charles L. Brown said at the time. ``So complex and extensive are
the changes that will be required of us, that we had best get on
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until 1984, with the actual break up of Ma Bell, did AT&AMP;T
begin a massive reorganization involving the first big wave of
white-collar layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is an extreme example of the forces at work in corporate
America,'' Rudolph said in an interview. ``This was a company where
people really did have a job for life. I was bowled over by the
sense of family that people had at the firm. It was quite
meaningful to them, and it seemed to be much more intense than at
other places.''
</P>
<P>
   To dull the impact of job loss, AT&AMP;T and other US companies
created a new workplace lexicon in the mid-1980s and early 1990s,
one that has become an integral part of our vocabulary. ``At
AT&AMP;T,'' writes Rudolph, ```You're accepted for the package' means
you're fired. `You're involuntarily separated' means you're fired.
`Your job won't be there going forward' means you're fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Other euphemisms such as downsizing, right-sizing,
re-engineering, and reorganization joined the list, as companies
searched for ways to lessen what was surely a devastating
experience for American workers. In fact, AT&AMP;T public relations man
Burke Stinson said as much in a telling interview with Rudolph:
``If I tell you it's downsizing,'' he said, ``you won't think
people are getting fired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People really don't have the same narrative in terms of their
working lives,'' noted Rudolph. ``It is no longer a linear
narrative. Instead, many of us are now beginning to think of
ourselves and our work as contingent.''
</P>
<P>
   While the argument has been made that these changes are a
reflection of very powerful economic forces, Rudolph shows us that
there are personal consequences. For Larry Nagel, the consequences
included a failed marriage and, until he was able to move on, an
incredible sense of loss.
</P>
<P>
   Nagel's world had revolved around his career as an engineer,
which was all he ever wanted to be, ``ever since he was an only
child building ham radio sets in Bakersfield, Calif.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a bachelors of science degree and a doctorate in
electrical engineering from the University of California at
Berkeley, he had been a star at Bell Laboratories and a highly
regarded employee at AT&AMP;T. Still, he had his own set of problems.
Each member of his research team was required to review or evaluate
the problems and failings of his department. Nagel was assigned to
document the failings of his own boss, a longtime nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the pink slip finally landed in Nagel's lap, the
explanation was simple: poor teamwork. ``My ears got warm, and I
could feel my skin getting flushed,'' recalled Nagel. ``My heart
was racing and my muscles tensed ... Getting fired completely
blindsided me.''
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks later, just before Nagel was set to leave, the
company offered him work in another section of Bell Laboratories.
But the offer was a demotion. He refused.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Larry Nagel has rebounded. Rudolph tells us
that four months after his layoff, he found work at a New Jersey
start-up that valued him so much it sent out press releases
boasting of its new hire. Less than a year later, Nagel was
promoted. Today, he works as a consultant in a business in which he
is constantly in demand. And, like Chase, he no longer wants to be
a company man.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Tom Chase's story remains unresolved. Rudolph
calls it a life in progress. Chase says he has learned to tackle
one problem at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Chase was very creative and should never have gone to AT&AMP;T
in the first place,'' noted Rudolph. ``He had a flinty
antiestablishment attitude, but that does not keep you in good
standing in a hierarchical organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase has sold his house and moved to a wooded and remote
section of New Jersey. He drives a limousine, does some consulting
work, and is preparing to launch his own home-based business
through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Chase declined to reveal details of
the venture for fear competitors would take his idea. He seems
confident, and feels he will be successful if he can attract the
money to launch his company. He says there is little competition
for what he plans to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Barbara Rudolph got it fairly right in her book,'' he
said. ``She was right. The companies took good care of you ... You
get lulled to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had any advice for young men and women entering
the corporate world, Chase said: ``When you acquire the tools, and
everything you need, just beat it. I did not do it soon enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
