<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SFX-ENTERTAINMENT-ART     11-18 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SFX-ENTERTAINMENT-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SFX CHIEF SPENDS $1B TO BECOME CONCERT KING 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By all accounts it was a golden evening, the night
last July when Robert F.X. Sillerman introduced British rocker Rod
Stewart at a benefit concert Sillerman had organized in the tony
vacation preserve of the Hamptons, where he now makes his home.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long way from when he had hustled discount magazines
and a dating service as a Brandeis student in the late 1960s, and
another step in his transformation from scrappy dealmaker to member
of the monied set. (Among concert guests: billionaire Revlon
chairman Ronald Perelman.)
</P>
<P>
   But then, Bob Sillerman, 50, has a talent for transformations.
He pulled one off recently with, of all things, a string of
mid-sized radio stations, which he sold for an unheard-of $2.1
billion, reportedly pocketing at least $200 million himself. And he
is out to pull off another, this time with live entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 18 months and at a cost of $1 billion _ most of it
borrowed _ Sillerman has basically bought America's rock and pop
concert industry. He has made himself the maestro of the nation's
theatrical touring trade, which brings Broadway shows to places
such as Boston and Washington, Austin and Omaha. And for good
measure, he has sewn up the country's specialized motorsports
business, with events where monster trucks with names like ``Grave
Digger'' crush everything in their paths.
</P>
<P>
   In April, he and the publicly traded company he controls, SFX
Entertainment Inc., spent $90 million in cash and assumed debt to
take over the operations of Boston concert promoter Don Law and,
with them, control of Great Woods, Harborlights, and the Orpheum. A
month later, he spent $10 million more to buy Boston theater
producer Jon B. Platt's firm and, with it, control of the Colonial
and Wilbur theatres and the Charles Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of us, there's not much left here he
doesn't control,'' said Josiah A. Spaulding Jr., chief executive of
Boston's nonprofit Wang Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much left anywhere else, either, and that fact _
together with Sillerman's penchant for picking fights with
competitors _ has set off an unholy uproar. In short order:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (BBOX)The Justice Department has begun an informal review of
SFX's most recent acquisitions with an eye toward possible
antitrust violations. People familiar with the review say the
concern is that the company has cornered so much of the concert
business it could raise ticket prices with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Agents such as Tom Ross, who until he resigned last week
from Los Angeles-based Creative Artists Agency was widely
considered one of the most powerful figures in the music business,
have steered big acts such as Eric Clapton and Celine Dion away
from SFX, fearing it will use its clout to slash what it pays
artists and, possibly, cut agents out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Entertainment executives such as Barry Diller, chairman
and chief executive of USA Networks, have landed in unusually
public and spectacularly bitter clashes with Sillerman. In letters
and public comments last summer, Diller, whose company owns
Ticketmaster, accused Sillerman of exaggerating the number of
tickets that Ticketmaster sells for SFX and of wrongly suggesting
that the ticketing company had offered SFX a bigger cut of ticket
prices, all to promote SFX's new stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Leaders of nonprofit performing arts centers including the
Wang and Washington's Kennedy Center have engaged in a frantic
series of meetings _ the most recent in Hartford two weeks ago _ to
try to figure out what to do if, as most expect, SFX's theatrical
touring subsidiary, PACE Entertainment, raises the price it charges
for shows or begins directing them to SFX-controlled venues.
Although Broadway musicals are only a small part of what these
centers present, according to their administrators, they are among
the few productions that make money and therefore are key to
keeping the facilities solvent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the industry are worried about monopoly,''
said Lawrence J. Wilker, president of the Kennedy Center. ``We use
the surplus (from musicals) to subsidize other art forms. Now that
SFX is in control they are going to want that money, which means
it's going to go out of the community and not be available to us.
It's a real concern.''
</P>
<P>
   A concern, but, as it turns out, not yet a reality. For all the
angst about SFX in the arts and entertainment world, the company
has yet to begin behaving like a behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the firm has raised some concert ticket prices, but
it has lowered others. Nationwide, prices have not risen any faster
this year than in past years, when SFX was not a factor, according
to Pollstar, a concert industry trade magazine. Although the
company is running millions of dollars in the red largely because
of interest costs on its debt, the fees it pays performers are
actually higher, not lower, than the music industry norm, said
Pollstar editor Gary Bongiovanni.
</P>
<P>
   Even regarding issues that are clearly within its control and of
little concern to consumers or antitrust officials _ like whether
SFX consolidates management of the 16 or so firms it has acquired
and cuts staff _ it essentially has done nothing. Although the
company now has 2,000 employees, according to Thomas Benson, SFX's
chief financial officer, it has laid off only about 20 and does not
expect to lay off any more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
