<SLUG> BC-RUSSIANS-CAPITALISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS LEARN ABOUT SMALL BUSINESSES IN THE USA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Small businesses in Russia are taxed so heavily
it stunts their growth, laws governing business are few, and
franchising is virtually unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of rules gives hope to a group of visiting Russian
lawyers who are studying how the United States regulates small
businesses. They say they have the opportunity to create a legal
system that will help pioneering entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have few rules _ not enough, but your country has much
rules,'' said Elena Zhdanova, a lawyer who specializes in tax law
in Moscow. ``We have to find the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the Center for Citizen Initiatives, a San
Francisco-based organization that provides technical aid to Russia,
the program provided the 10-person delegation with fresh ideas on
how to help Russia with its arduous transition to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Substantially funded by the U.S. Information Agency, Citizen
Initiatives has brought more than 1,200 Russian business people to
the United States for training during the past three years. But
this delegation is considered the most likely to effect change in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The group was handpicked by Irina Khakamada, an official of the
newly created Ministry of Anti-monopoly Regulation and
Entrepreneurship Support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to bring young lawyers from all over Russia to
learn about U.S. legislation, and especially legislation for small
and medium-sized businesses,'' said Madina Bikboulatova, director
of the Center for Citizen Initiatives office in Dubna, Russia. ``We
need good lawyers to support and develop small business in
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The group _ nine lawyers and the head of a women's business
advocacy group, ranging in age from 23 to 43 _ maintained a tight
schedule, traipsing between meetings with lawyers, business
agencies and state and local government officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, small businesses account for just 7 percent of the
country's total gross domestic product, according to government
statistics reported last year. In contrast, U.S. small businesses
made up 51 percent of GDP in 1992, the most recent year for which
numbers were available.
</P>
<P>
   Irina Tchitakhova, a delegate from Rostov-on-Don, said it wasn't
that the Russian government didn't care about small business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government can see that small business is a priority,''
she said. ``The government believes (in) the economic benefits of
small business for renewing the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Tchitakhova said, political and economic instability in
the country have made it impossible for businesses to do the
necessary long-term planning.
</P>
<P>
   The visit ended Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
