<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ROCKET TO LAUNCH SPACE STATION'S FIRST COMPONENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid anticipation worldwide, the mammoth first component of the
U.S.-led international space station is poised for launch early
Friday from Central Asia aboard an unmanned Russian Proton rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-story booster is scheduled to blast off from the Baikonur
Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan at 1:40 a.m. EST. The usually reliable,
three-stage Proton is powerful enough to place the 44,000-pound,
41-foot-long, ``Zarya,'' or ``Sunrise,'' control module into an
elliptical orbit varying from 115 miles to 220 miles high.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of discussing, planning and replanning, we're
about to launch hardware and embark on one of the most complex
engineering projects in human history,'' said Gretchen McClain,
NASA's deputy associate administrator for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is high stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Zarya's launching is the culmination of a five-year effort to
fold the economically ailing Russians into a station partnership
that already included the United States, Europe, Japan and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first of 45 launchings, three dozen by the United
States and the remainder by Russia, to fashion a permanently
staffed, seven-person orbiting laboratory that will span an area
equal to a pair of football fields stretched side by side. Dozens
of cargo launchings will also be required to complete the project
by mid-2004.
</P>
<P>
   Built by Russia's Krunichev State Research and Production Space
Center at a cost of $240 million to the United States, Zarya was
designed to furnish electrical power, propulsion and ground
communications during the earliest stages of assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Zarya to a launch accident or a serious malfunction
would set the project back a year while the Russians upgrade a
ground test version for flight, said Randy Brinkley, NASA's space
station program manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not specifically addressed who would be responsible
for paying for the second (module),'' he said. ``The most important
thing is we do have a second control module that could be
launched.''
</P>
<P>
   Introduced by the Russians in the mid-1960s to launch heavy
military payloads, the Proton rocket has more recently become a
commercial satellite launcher. With more than 200 successful
flights, the Proton is considered to have a reliability rating of
98 percent, according to the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   A forecast of subfreezing temperatures and overcast skies at
Baikonur is not a barrier to the launch as it would be to NASA's
space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Russian space agency officials offered final approval
for the Zarya mission earlier this week, allowing the 18-story
Proton to be transported by rail to its launching complex Monday.
The four-hour fuel-loading operation is scheduled for the final
stages of the countdown.
</P>
<P>
   Once launched, the Proton will take just over 9 1/2 minutes to
place Zarya in its initial orbit. The next several minutes will be
followed by the deployments of communications antennas aboard the
module as well as the unfurling of its two 35-foot-long solar
arrays for electrical power generation.
</P>
<P>
   During the following days, Zarya's propulsion system will raise
the module's altitude to 240 miles to prepare it for the arrival of
the station's second component.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. shuttle Endeavour is scheduled to blast off early Dec.
3 with a 36-foot-long, 25,600-pound module called Unity. The $350
million Unity is fashioned with a half-dozen docking ports. Once
joined to Zarya, the two modules will serve as the bridge between
future U.S. and Russian components.
</P>
<P>
   Following a rendezvous with Zarya, the Endeavour crew will use
the shuttle's robot arm to lift the second module from its cargo
bay and position it for mating with Unity. Astronauts will link the
two modules with power and data cables and establish a direct
communications link between the new station and NASA's Mission
Control Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The new station's third major component, the Russian-contributed
service module, has been delayed at least 15 months by Russia's
financial problems. U.S. and Russian officials are hopeful that a
recent $60 million payment from NASA will ensure its launch by
August.
</P>
<P>
   The service module will provide the living quarters for the
station's first resident crew of three in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've faced obstacles and we've gotten through each one of
those,'' McClain said. ``There is no doubt we will have challenges
in front of us, but with our strong partnership we will get through
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
