<SLUG> BC-STATION-SUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREWS DRESS FOR WALKS IN $10 MILLION OUTFITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It will take the world's smallest spaceship, the
spacesuit, to build its largest, the international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of U.S. astronauts will don the bulky $10 million
garments, which NASA calls the extravehicular mobility units, for
spacewalks during the more than six-year assembly period.
</P>
<P>
   Without the suit, the United States and its international
partners could not establish the electrical power, computer data
and communications links to the station's many large components.
</P>
<P>
   At 250 pounds, the stiff but flexible suits were developed by
NASA and its contractor, Hamilton Standard, to protect wearers
against the airless realm of space, temperatures that swing between
250 degrees above and below zero Fahrenheit, and impacts from small
micrometeoroids for up to 7 1/2 hours, while providing only the
most basic of amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Planners estimate that the construction of the space station
will require 1,705 hours of spacewalks. Responsible for about
one-third of that, the Russians will don similar garb developed in
their own country. The station's astronauts and cosmonauts also
will be trained to use one another's spacesuits as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. suit is of an early 1980s vintage, but has been
modified extensively for the tasks of assembling and maintaining
the space station.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is a marvel of synthetic fabrics and materials. Its
basic components include trousers, a top that fits over the upper
torso like a pullover sweater, boots, gloves and a helmet. Oxygen,
communications gear and equipment to monitor the physical health of
the astronaut are mounted in a backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Before climbing into the suit, the spacewalking astronaut will
pull on a set of long underwear laced with spaghetti-thin tubes
through which coolant flows.
</P>
<P>
   The trousers and upper garment are lined with an airtight,
urethane-coated nylon material that enables the suit to be
pressurized without leaking. Layered atop are fabrics of Dacron,
Neoprene-coated nylon, aluminized Mylar and a tough outer covering
of Teflon, Kevlar and Nomex, all for micrometeoroid protection.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. suit is so thoroughly designed for orbital spacewalks
that it could not be used to walk on the surface of the moon or
Mars. Its mobility comes from joints at the waist, shoulders and
elbows. The armor is so stiff that if a wearer fell over on the
moon or Mars, he would be unable to get up without help from a
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Its basic amenities are a bag with 32-ounces of water that can
be sipped through a tube, a fruit bar sheathed in edible rice paper
and an absorbent diaper that will hold up to a quart of urine.
</P>
<P>
   The station spacewalks will be tightly choreographed around
specific tasks to ensure maximum productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get as exhausted mentally as I do physically,'' said U.S.
astronaut Jerry Ross, who will participate in the station
assembly's first three spacewalks. Ross has logged four spacewalks
in five previous flights.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. suits have been enhanced in seven key areas to prepare
them for station work. Probably most important is the back-mounted
jet pack, which will allow the astronauts to propel themselves
through space, in the event that a lifeline is severed. In the
past, spacewalking astronauts have been tethered to the shuttle
during the walks. If the lifeline snapped, the shuttle would
maneuver to pick up the drifting astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   The station protocol will continue the use of tethers, but a
docked shuttle could not respond fast enough to a spacewalker whose
lifeline was severed.
</P>
<P>
   The garment has been modified so it can be stored aboard the
station, undergo minor repairs and be used 25 times before
requiring major overhauls on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts will be able to replace the spacesuits' electronic
displays and life-support elements aboard the station rather than
on the ground. New sizing features permit the arm and leg spans to
be adjusted to fit all but the tallest or shortest astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Electric heaters have been installed in the gloves and boots. In
frigid conditions, a spacewalker can shut off the flow of coolant
to his coldest extremities.
</P>
<P>
   The life-support system components that filter carbon dioxide
from the suit are metabolic rather than chemical. The change eases
servicing between spacewalks because the filter can be recycled by
heating it. The gloves have been extensively modified, as well, to
make the fingers more tactile. Nonetheless, the airtight gloves are
as cumbersome as working with oven mitts.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts who have worn them report that the Russian suits are
similar to the U.S. suits in many regards. The chief difference is
the way the suit is donned. The back of the one-piece Russian suit
swings open so the wearer can climb in or out.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian suit was not designed for extensive refurbishment.
When its major components wear out, the suit is thrown away. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
