<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATION-FUTURE-HNS &LR;      11-18 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATION-FUTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING FOR THE STARS: TIGHT BUDGET INSPIRES SOME CREATIVE
ENGINEERING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An experimental spacecraft and research laboratory, the
international space station promises to be a little of both as it
zips around Earth at an altitude of 250 miles.
</P>
<P>
   But achieving the facility's full science and engineering
potential will take time. For one thing, the station will take at
least six years to build. For another, money once earmarked for
science has been channeled instead to cover construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, almost $500 million in research funds has
been reallocated by NASA to pay for overruns in hardware
development, caused primarily by Russia's financial problems. More
will be necessary as the United States attempts to shoulder
responsibilities that were Russia's before its economic crisis
worsened earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Once the station is assembled, however, NASA plans to spend $2.5
billion on research over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens, I have to be patient and wait for the
infrastructure to develop,'' said Chuck Lloyd, the deputy manager
of NASA's space station payloads office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand I have to take a back seat,'' Lloyd said. ``But
the funny fact of the matter is that, in the end, I take the front
seat, and I stay in the front seat for a very long period of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a couple of intriguing engineering projects, well
outside the realm of traditional laboratory research, have moved to
the forefront, in part because of the station's tight budget. NASA
was forced to pursue them to stem the rising costs associated with
Russia's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Each project could play a key role in future human exploration
of the moon and Mars, goals well beyond the mission of the space
station.
</P>
<P>
   One is TransHab, an inflatable module that may become the living
quarters for up to a half dozen space station occupants and include
novel systems that recycle air and water for the crew. The second
is the X-38, a speedboat-shaped space glider, which NASA plans to
develop into a lifeboat that could bring as many as seven crew
members back to Earth in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   If successful on the station, TransHab could become the habitat
for future manned spacecraft dispatched to the moon or Mars. And
the X-38 may evolve into a crew transport vehicle to carry
explorers from Earth to a larger orbiting spacecraft destined for a
long journey to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``TransHab is basically a space inflatable habitat that could be
used for anything,'' said Donna Fender, who manages the development
project at NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston. ``You could use
it for the space station, to go to the moon or Mars, or wherever
anybody decides to go. Therefore, I can get a two-for-one or a
three-for-one in my agency money.''
</P>
<P>
   The version of TransHab proposed for the international space
station is 40 feet long and 25 feet in diameter. Nearly three times
as long as the aluminum module that NASA originally proposed,
TransHab would offer station crews a three-level habitat. One level
would be sleeping quarters, another a gymnasium and the third, a
large galley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide an environment for the crew that should keep
them very happy for an extended period of time,'' Fender said. ``If
you are going to be up there for a long duration, then I think it's
critical to keep your crews happy. If they are happy, you keep
their minds sharp and productive.''
</P>
<P>
   TransHab is set for launch in 2004 as one of the last components
of the space station, though the plans may change if funds
earmarked for TransHab engineering studies are reallocated to more
immediate needs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a miracle of synthetic fabrics and materials. When
launched, TransHab will be deflated, its outer fabric carefully
packed around its lightweight structural core.
</P>
<P>
   Once it arrives at the station, a shuttle crew will use the
ship's robot arm to lift the module from the cargo bay and attach
it to the orbital outpost. It will be inflated with breathable air.
</P>
<P>
   Working from the inside out, the module comprises three
envelopes of flexible but sturdy fabrics, each surrounding an air
bladder that prevents the inside atmosphere from leaking into the
vacuum of space. The bladders are surrounded by a layer of Kevlar
webbing, the material used in bulletproof vests. The outer layer is
a foot thick and is made primarily of Kevlar to protect the
enclosure from high-velocity micrometeors and man-made space
debris.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers have calculated that this fabric barrier could stop a
projectile of nearly an inch in diameter, traveling at more than
four miles a second. The barrier is designed to absorb the energy
of a projectile by breaking it into smaller pieces, then slowing
their advance.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency calculates that the odds of such a strike are
one every 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The fabric barrier will be surrounded by an additional layer of
insulation to protect the habitat from the wide swings in
temperature to which the station will be exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep stations will be strategically located within the module's
structural core. The astronauts would retreat to the sleep stations
to ride out solar storms with potentially lethal radiation.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's X-38 is undergoing its initial unmanned flight tests at
Edwards Air Force Base, Calif. The spaceship is patterned after
stubby experimental aircraft called ``lifting bodies,'' which were
tested by the Air Force and NASA in the 1950s and 1960s. The
gracefully curved shape of the underbody is designed to provide
lift in the absence of traditional wings, as the vehicle descends
through Earth's atmosphere from space.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's engineers propose that at least one seven-person version
of the spacecraft be docked at the new station in 2003. It would
replace the lifeboat duties performed until then by a three-person
Soyuz capsule.
</P>
<P>
   In case of fire, collision or a medical emergency, the station
crew would go into the rescue craft and undock. A propulsion module
would send the ship and its crew back through Earth's atmosphere
via an automated landing _ one that would not require manual
control by pilots aboard the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery scenario is designed to get the spacecraft to land
within two hours, at a location within an hour of a major medical
facility.
</P>
<P>
   After its re-entry, the spacecraft would deploy a large
rectangular parachute, called a parafoil, to slow and control its
landing. The ship is designed to land on a traditional runway or a
smooth unpaved surface.
</P>
<P>
   The most favored landing sites are in the southwestern United
States, Australia and North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``High tech doesn't have to be expensive,'' said Brian Anderson,
NASA's X-38 manager. Limited to a $90 million development budget,
the X-38 engineering team has relied on combining existing flight
computers, guidance devices and lightweight structural materials to
fashion their creation rather than developing it from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The X-38 and its parafoil have passed their first drop tests, in
which the craft was released from beneath the wing of a high-flying
B-52 bomber to glide to a landing at Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   By early 2001, NASA expects to launch a test version of the
rescue craft in the cargo bay of the space shuttle. It will be
deployed unmanned to determine whether it can make an automated
re-entry and landing.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the first of the rescue vehicles will be
docked to the space station. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
