A6834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TARA-LIPINSKI-HNS &LR;      11-18 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARA-LIPINSKI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOLD LIFE LIVES ON FOR TARA LIPINSKI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Tara Lipinski doesn't lead a normal life. Never
has, really. Probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   Got a problem with that?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's your problem. Not hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Describe normal,'' Lipinski was saying Tuesday night, after
another workout on another rink in another city that isn't home.
``I think my life is very normal to me. I know in some ways it's
different or busier. But I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Being normal is more overrated than the supposed wonders and
deeper meaning of Woodstock. Anybody who puts a premium on being
one of the crowd either hasn't been 16 or has forgotten what it was
like to be that age. People these days have a hard time finding a
happy medium between leading a life of quiet desperation and
appearing on the Jerry Springer show. Lipinski dared not only to
have a dream, but to seeing it through to the end.
</P>
<P>
   At an age when a driver's license is a status symbol, Lipinski
has an Olympic gold medal. Lipinski is the youngest individual gold
medalist in the history of the Winter Olympics. People pay to watch
her do what she loves to do. What she did for free for years _ at a
high cost to her family.
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski is a professional figure skater now. There will be no
more anguishing waits for the long program scores at the world
championships. There will be no rematch between Lipinski and
Michelle Kwan at the 2002 games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is off me,'' Lipinski said. ``I accomplished the
goal of my life. Now I just get to enjoy it and perform. And I'm
still competing, doing shows. It's nice to improve on my skating
and not have to worry about a title.''
</P>
<P>
   The gold-medal dress rehearsals began when Lipinski was 2.
Standing on a Tupperware container, little Tara would drape herself
in ribbons and dried flowers and soak in the cheers of her parents,
Jack and Pat. Tara began roller skating at 3, figure skating at 6.
She was so determined to see how far she could go, her parents
didn't have the heart to tell her no.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that meant Jack would have to live alone, just outside
of Houston, so that Tara and Pat could find the best possible
training environment. Now Tara can call Texas home again. She still
trains in Detroit, but it's different now. She has no Olympics to
consume either her mind or her time.
</P>
<P>
   Does she miss the agony and ecstasy of giving everything she has
to something, not knowing in advance whether it will be worth it?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Lipinski said emphatically. ``You can't get that back.
That's going to be the biggest thing I've ever accomplished. But I
have day-to-day goals.''
</P>
<P>
   So the quest of trying to become a better skater, a better
performer, isn't quite the same when there is no gold standard to
meet. So what? For every Lipinski, there are legions of people
whose shining moment in life is going to be playing on the high
school football team, or sinking the winning shot in a basketball
game nobody else remembers, or setting off the stink bomb that
caused the school to close for an entire afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tsk-tsk at the probability that Lipinski the adult will
never accomplish anything on a par with what she did as a
4-foot-10, 82-pound, 15-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performing is my favorite thing to do,'' Lipinski said. ``To
be here in front of all my fans and show them what I've worked so
hard for for a couple months. Just give them some enjoyment. They
came to see us, so you do the best you can for them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski at her Olympic best was truly a sight to behold. Kwan
was in first place after the short program, and she left only the
narrowest of openings with a smooth, play-it-safe long routine.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote the following words on the day of the long program in
Nagano, Japan:
</P>
<P>
   ``What will unfold in the women's long program today at the
White Ring is only slightly more in doubt than the outcome of a
Cuban election. Kwan, 17, will win the gold medal, unless she
decides at the last moment to spend her entire four-minute program
doing nothing but figure-8s. Lipinski, 15, will have to settle for
the silver, even if she pulls off a quintuple-luzt, quadruple-axel,
triple-flip, double-martini combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski went for the gold with so much a combination of grace
and gusto, the judges had little choice but to do away with the
natural order of things. Before Lipinski literally sprinted off the
ice at the end of her routine, she screamed and thrust her hands
into the air triumphantly. An Olympic moment for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more pressure at a competition like that,''
Lipinski said. ``Here, it's more relaxed and fun and entertaining.
I've got the best of both worlds: I won and I had fun competing.
Now I'm doing shows and doing the other parts that are really
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   She got to visit the White House. She did the Jay Leno-David
Letterman-Rosie O'Donnell circuit. Why would she long to be normal?
Besides, Lipinski's decision to turn pro made it possible to live
under the same roof with her father again _ at least, when she's
not on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly nine months have passed since Tara Lipinski struck gold.
And guess what? The thrill isn't gone, or even faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Lipinski said. ``I think it's going to be here
for the rest of my life. I think I'm still in shock from it. I
couldn't be happier than I am right now. Everything is twice as
good as I thought it would be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
