<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6835 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATION-RUSSIANS-HNS &LR;      11-18 1672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATION-RUSSIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE PARTNERSHIP OFFERS WORLD OF PROMISE _ AND PROBLEMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When it comes to space stations, Russia's experience
is unmatched.
</P>
<P>
   It has launched 10, seven successfully, including Earth's first
in 1971. Mir, its most recent, has logged nearly 13 years in orbit,
despite a major collision, fire and other well-publicized problems
last year. The United States launched one, Skylab, which briefly
housed Apollo-era astronauts a quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States embarked on plans to spearhead the
development of Earth's first international space station, it
elected to brush up on the topic by sending seven astronauts to Mir
for a series of visits. They logged nearly 1,000 days in orbit, the
last 812 of them consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's prowess with space stations, however, exists in the
shadow of its brief and chaotic track record with economic reform.
This discrepancy has imperiled the early development of the
U.S.-led international space station.
</P>
<P>
   In October, NASA won White House approval for a $1.2 billion
plan to reduce U.S. reliance on Russia, a fundamental change in the
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its other space-station partners _ Japan,
Europe and Canada _ are relying on Russia for the station's first
habitable component, the service module. Russia also is to launch a
parade of Progress supply capsules and produce the Soyuz lifeboat,
which will be able to whisk a station crew back to Earth in an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The rockets on the supply capsules will fire periodically to
keep the growing orbital complex circling Earth at safe altitudes
while Progress is docked to the station. The capsules also will
furnish fuel for thrusters on the service module that will perform
the same task when no Progress is docked.
</P>
<P>
   Even at altitudes of 250 miles, the new station will fly through
a thin region of Earth's atmosphere, creating a slight drag that
will cause the orbital laboratory to slowly sink. The propellant is
needed to counteract these forces.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a major financial jolt in Russia prompted a
$22.6 billion global bailout, chiefly through loans issued by the
International Monetary Fund. Within weeks, Russia was forced to
drastically devalue its currency against the U.S. dollar, further
weakening its ability to meet station commitments.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Russian government's wider attempt to impose new
fiscal restraints, it cut funding earmarked for the station this
year from $340 million to $160 million. The amount actually
disbursed by the central government to the Russian Space Agency,
however, was less than 15 percent of the reduced amount by summer's
end.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-summer, NASA administrator Dan Goldin had alerted
Congress that Russia appeared unable to complete work on the
service module in time to launch it as planned in April 1999. He
also warned that there was little work under way on the first of
the half dozen Progress cargo ships or the two Soyuz crew capsules
that the new station will need annually.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the service module, intended to house the first
three-member crew that will staff the new station, was pushed from
April 1999 to July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of the White House, Russia was not expelled from
the project, but NASA was forced to initiate new measures to cope
with Russia's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial was a proposal for direct cash payments
to the Russian Space Agency _ $60 million this year to keep the
service module's launch from sliding beyond July 1999 and another
$600 million over the next four years to improve the prospects for
the production of Progress and Soyuz launches.
</P>
<P>
   Additional hedges against Russia's problems include
modifications to the fuel lines of NASA's space shuttles. At a cost
of $90 million, the alterations will enable shuttles to handle
orbital boosting duties beginning in late 2000, if Progress
production in Russia falters.
</P>
<P>
   A second hedge was to initiate the fabrication of a U.S.
propulsion module that could be docked to the station in early 2002
and subsequently fueled by visiting space shuttles. Initial
estimates place the cost of the new module at $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   Additional U.S. shuttle-supply missions will cost another $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency also anticipates launching a U.S.-built
``interim control module'' carrying enough fuel to meet the new
station's propulsion needs for at least a year. It could be
launched any time after the service module goes up.
</P>
<P>
   None of the new measures, however, eliminates the need for the
Russian service module.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that the timely completion of this important
international project is at risk, should the shortage of Russian
funding continue,'' Goldin told lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin's warning to Congress was based in large part on an
assessment by a panel of experts assembled by NASA in late 1997 to
sort out cost and schedule threats to the project, for which the
United States, as well as Russia, was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule uncertainty associated with Russian
implementation of joint partnership agreements is the major threat
to the international space station program,'' the study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Chaired by aerospace consultant Jay Chabrow, the panel warned
that NASA's costs associated with the station's development were
likely to climb from $17.3 billion to $24.7 billion, largely
because of Russian delays and uncertainties over whether Russia
could provide critical hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants estimated that plans to complete assembly by
2004 could drag out for up to three more years. Lawmakers were not
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians have simply failed to follow through on their
funding commitments, and the Clinton administration brought the
Russians into the project for the wrong reasons, placed the
Russians in the critical path, and routinely let them off the hook
for their failures'' said U.S. Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis.,
who chairs the House Science Committee and is a longtime backer of
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was invited to join the project as a major partner in
1993, two years after the breakup of the Soviet Union and a few
months after Russia signed the Missile Technology Control Regime, a
multinational agreement that restricts member nations from
exporting technologies that could be used to build nuclear
missiles. Clearly, there was concern in the United States that
Soviet arms not find their way into the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   The project's charter members _ the European Space Agency,
Japan, Canada and the United States _ struck their partnership in
1988, when the former Soviet Union still posed a military threat.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the alliance modified to include Russia was an
agreement that each member would contribute hardware and services
at its own expense. When possible, they agreed, members of the
partnership would barter away inequities instead of formally
exchanging funds.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Russia's previous space-station experience, the United
States remained the managing partner for the new enterprise because
of its much stronger economic footing.
</P>
<P>
   Through NASA, the United States will furnish the station's first
laboratory (a 28-foot-long research module), a crew habitation
compartment, an air lock, structural truss and connecting nodes,
power-generating solar arrays, as well as the shuttle assembly
flights, satellite communications, crew training, ground control, a
future seven-person rescue vehicle and the overall management.
</P>
<P>
   The European Space Agency, comprising 11 countries, has pledged
a 20-foot-long research module called Columbus. Europe plans to
install a 33-foot-long robotic arm on Russia's segment of the
station.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has pledged a 33-foot-long habitable laboratory called the
Japanese Experiment Module, along with a 15-foot-long porchlike
platform to hold external experiments. The platform will be
augmented with another robotic arm of just over 38 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Europe and Japan are developing unmanned supply capsules to
augment Russia's Progress ships. Neither will be ready for service
until 2003. A half dozen European supply crafts could boost as much
fuel as 16 Russian Progress capsules.
</P>
<P>
   Canada will make a modest but crucial contribution _ an advanced
version of the 50-foot-long robot arm that it developed to maneuver
large cargo flown by NASA's space shuttle. The device is essential
to the latter stages of construction and the periodic removal and
replacement of small electronics boxes during maintenance and
positioning of large experiments outside the station.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's robotic arm is designed to move along the structural
truss of the station in response to remote commands from the
astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's mission control in Houston is responsible for the ground
supervision of the complex, though in the early stages of
construction, it will exercise that authority through Russia's
control center in suburban Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia plan to alternate commanders once
the international station is staffed in January 2000. Russia's
command role may shrink if the country's role in the partnership
decreases because of economic worries. U.S. astronaut William
Shepherd will be the first commander.
</P>
<P>
   English is the station's official language, though the U.S. and
Russian crews likely will converse bilingually.
</P>
<P>
   When fully assembled, the international station will house seven
men and women.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Europe, Japan and Canada will furnish four
crew members under a flexible formula that will not mean there is
always one from each member country at any one time. Russia will
furnish three crew members.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for its many contributions, the United States has
access to nearly half the laboratory volume of the Japanese and
European science modules, and will get nearly 80 percent of the
electrical power apportioned for research. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
