<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX     11-18 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The world is my oyster on the half
shell
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traveling here, there and yonder, I'm always on the lookout for
a decent place to eat. Along the way I've found a few.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Big Sur, Calif., try the cafe at the state park
headquarters. You'd think the speciality would be burgers and
fries. Instead, it's gourmet all the way. A couple of years ago
when I was there, the resident chef was a graduate of the CIA _
Culinary Institute of America, or something to that effect. For
sure, his secret recipes were to kill for.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Johannesburg, South Africa, the hotel _ I forget the name,
but it's the big one _ where I stayed in 1990 had an excellent
recipe for chicken-fried steak. I should know. I gave it to the
chef, faxed to me directly from my Cousin Booger back in Texas.
Until then, the speciality of the house was ox tail soup, along
with German and English dishes, not the best of combinations. I'm
not saying a good chicken-fried steak can change history. No doubt
Mandela would have been released from prison the very next month,
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Monaco, a sure thing at the outdoor cafe just outside the
Casino du Monte Carlo is a full plate of oysters on the half shell.
Excellent with a glass of the house white wine. The French onion
soup is superb as well. Take time to linger over cafe au lai and
check out the beautiful people. If you should happen to see Sean
Connery strolling by, pretend to ignore him. The waiter may think
you're somebody, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Japan, go with the sushi. Forget that it's raw fish. After
all, you like raw oysters, don't you. Squid is tasty. Octopus is a
bit chewy. Beware those little tables where you have to sit with
your legs folded under you, Indian style. After about five minutes,
you lose circulation in your lower extremities. Difficult for the
digestion.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Moscow, there are no good restaurants. Better you should
figure out a way to eat at Natasha's apartment. She's the ex-wife
of my friend Pavlik. When they were still married, I always stayed
with them. Natasha is half-Georgian on her mother's side, which is
something akin to being half-Italian. My heavens, that woman can
cook. She baked a type of cheese bread I've never found anywhere
else. That was back when she was a housewife. Nowadays, as a result
of the fall of Communism and her marriage falling apart, she has a
successful catering business. Good for her. She deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Italy, if there's such a thing as a bad meal, I couldn't
find it. I'm content to simply eat the spaghetti and then order a
dessert. Sometimes the desserts take half an hour to prepare;
that's how good they are. One that I'll always remember had a
freshly baked muffin as the centerpiece, encircled by fresh fruit,
syrupy sauces and Italian ice cream. Now that I think about it,
forget the spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Lufkin, Texas, my little hometown, you can't do any better
than the Let's Eat! Cafe, located just a couple of blocks behind
the newspaper office. It's the very soul of soul food. Sister
Sharon does the cooking. Meat dishes vary daily from roast beef to
smoldered pork chops to fried catfish. It's turnip greens or
collard greens, depending on whether it's Tuesday or Wednesday.
Yams are on the menu most every day. Comment heard from a fellow
diner who had been raised on soul food: ``This is so good it makes
you wanna slap your grandmaw.'' Best place I know _ in Europe or
Asia or wherever in the world _ for hot water cornbread. Makes me
wonder why I ever left home.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
