<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIATIVE WOULD OUTLAW GAY MARRIAGE IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A measure that would outlaw same-sex marriage in
California will appear on the primary election ballot in 2000, an
issue that is certain to incite heated debate.
</P>
<P>
   The California Defense of Marriage Act qualified easily with
482,044 signatures declared valid out of the 677,512 submitted,
Secretary of State Bill Jones said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, sponsored by Republican state Sen. Pete Knight
of Palmdale and organizations such as the Traditional Values
Coalition, would ban same-sex marriage and prohibit the state from
recognizing gay marriages performed legally in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for gay rights and other likely opponents of the
ballot measure face an uphill fight if votes in Hawaii and Alaska
are any indication. Two-thirds of the voters in both states passed
anti-gay-marriage measures on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown that a majority of Californians oppose
legislation legalizing gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot initiative approved in Hawaii authorizes state
lawmakers to write a law prohibiting same-sex marriages, while
Alaskans voted a gay-marriage ban into their constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Gay-rights groups promised to fight the measures in the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1516EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOBBYISTS19-COX     11-18 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBYISTS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOBBYISTS LAMENT LACK OF RESPECT
 &HT;    520&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the American League of Lobbyists, persuasion is
a way of life. Now the group faces a daunting task _ persuading the
public that lobbyists deserve respect.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of the professional group's 508 members, 62 percent
of respondents agreed that ``the lobbying profession is unfairly
maligned because of a general lack of public understanding.'' Five
percent disagreed, and the remaining 33 percent were either
uncertain or didn't respond.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the press reports ``fairly'' on lobbying or
lobbyists, 76 percent of the professional persuaders said ``no,''
and 19 percent said ``yes.'' The rest didn't respond.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the league's members _ mostly senior-level managers of
lobbying efforts at corporations, unions, associations or
multi-client ``contract'' shops _ have other consolations: 65
percent reported earning more than $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, any group, whether it's a business
association or organized labor, would tend to believe it's not
treated fairly,'' the league's president-elect, Kenneth Feltman,
said Wednesday. ``On the other hand, there's no doubt that many
contract lobbyists are irritated when the news media blithely
dismiss them as 'hired guns.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the survey shows we have some additional educational
and outreach responsibility to work not just with Congress and the
administration, but with the media,'' said Feltman, who is
executive director of the Employers Council on Flexible
Compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lobbying is good for America,'' said the survey's instigator,
Deanna Gelak, chief lobbyist for the 103,000-member Society for
Human Resource Management. ``The stereotypical picture of lobbyists
who spend most of their time schmoozing with legislators and giving
out campaign contributions is all wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   When the league asked its members to identify the single factor
that ``most frequently changes the vote of a member of Congress,''
only 5 percent chose ``campaign contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   More popular choices were ``good information ...effectively
presented directly to the member of Congress'' (35 percent);
``grassroots'' lobbying by people from the member's constituency
(30 percent) and ``good information ...effectively presented to
staff'' (25 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the campaign contributions are related to
the ability to meet directly with members of Congress,'' said Larry
Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics,
a nonpartisan group in Washington that analyzes the role of money
in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to get into a congressman's office is to give him
a check with his campaign committee's name on it,'' Makinson said.
``It doesn't just get you access. It also gets you a sympathetic
ear.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that even though the lobbyists didn't stress the
usefulness of campaign contributions, half of them said they or
their clients have a political action committee (PAC), and 70
percent said they give contributions personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish everyone had a lobbyist, but the reality is not
everyone can afford one,'' Makinson said. ``Those with more money
can have more influence.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   However, contract lobbyist James Albertine said, ``Spending a
lot of money doesn't necessarily mean you're the most powerful
lobbying group.''
</P>
<P>
   He was backed up by Evelyn Dubrow, retired lobbyist for UNITE,
the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deny that when my union wants to get legislation
considered, it often goes first to members (of Congress whom) its
PAC has helped,'' Dubrow said. ``But I don't think money is the
most important thing to members of Congress. What they want most is
votes, so groups with members in their districts can find a way to
meet with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
