<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITAL-ART-1STLEDE-$     11-18 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITAL-ART-1STLEDE-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With CAPITAL-VANGOGH and CAPITAL-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington,
(e) entertainment and (t) travel categories for release Saturday,
Nov. 21.
 &HT;    server.
 &HT;    Corrects date to 1988 in graf 15.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the art world's fervor over the traveling
Vincent van Gogh exhibition, it's easy to forget that the capital
has a wealth of other treasures to offer, including temporary
exhibitions rivaling the van Gogh show in quality.
</P>
<P>
   Hours spent in the iffy pursuit of van Gogh passes might better
be devoted to enjoying the National Gallery of Art's immense
permanent collection. Housed in two separate buildings on the
National Mall, it includes other van Gogh paintings among thousands
of works that span the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, one rare find is Leonardo da Vinci's ``Ginevra de'
Benci,'' the only painting by the famed Florentine artist in the
Western Hemisphere and one of only three portraits of women
(including Mona Lisa) painted by da Vinci.
</P>
<P>
   Another gem, commanding its own room at the gallery, is Augustus
Saint-Gaudens' memorial to Gen. Robert Gould Shaw and the
Massachusetts 54th Regiment, the African-American unit that
inspired the Civil War movie ``Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   If your goal in Washington is not just van Gogh bragging rights,
but a memorable aesthetic experience, here are some other good
bets:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gifts to the Nation from Mr. and Mrs. John Hay Whitney. Van
Gogh's 1989 ``Self-Portrait'' is a highlight of this donation from
one of the finest American private collections of modern art.
</P>
<P>
   While this exhibition is small _ only 16 paintings _ it is
replete with significant works by artists including Henri Matisse,
Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Georges Braque, Raoul Dufy, George
Bellows, Thomas Eakins, Edward Hopper, Henri Rousseau and James
McNeill Whistler. It is on view through Jan. 3 at the National
Gallery's East Building.
</P>
<P>
   _ Impressionists in Winter: Effets de Neige. This exhibit at the
Phillips Collection in Northwest Washington brings together 62
Impressionist winter landscape paintings.
</P>
<P>
   On view through Jan. 3, it focuses on the ``snow effect'' works
of Claude Monet, Camille Pissarro and Alfred Sisley and others.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Phillips Collection is a privately owned museum,
there is an admission charge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whistler's ``Harmony in Blue and Gold: the Peacock Room.''
Once the dining room of a wealthy shipowner in London, Whistler's
only existing interior design has been reassembled in a permanent
display at the Freer Gallery of Art, also on the National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   A lattice of intricately carved gold shelving surrounds the
room, and rich green walls are accented by golden depictions of
peacocks. Oval lamps appear to grow from a ceiling of lush
blue-green patterns of peacock feathers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chuck Close. If ``so what?'' is the first thing you say after
glancing at this 80-painting retrospective at the Hirshhorn Museum
and Sculpture Garden, then ``wow'' will almost certainly be the
last.
</P>
<P>
   At a distance, Close's monumental mug shots of his friends and
family look like unflattering eight-foot photographs. But closer
inspection reveals tiny strokes of acrylic on canvas, meticulously
applied in some cases with an airbrush, in others with the artist's
own fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Close's early photo-realistic style turned more abstract in
1988, when a blood vessel in his spinal column ruptured, leaving
him mostly paralyzed from the neck down. The faces of his later
subjects emerge from a colorful mosaic of circles, rectangles,
triangles and ovals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's working 100 years later (than van Gogh), and you can't
help but notice how his art is very expressionistic,'' Linda
Powell, the museum's director of education, said of Close. ``He
moved from photo-realism to a more expressionistic and vibrant
palette.'' The exhibition continues through Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Philippe Halsman: a Retrospective. This show at the National
Portrait Gallery near the Mall trace-- the career of the longtime
Life magazine photographer. Among the approximately 80 vintage
prints from the 1930s through the 1970s are images of Albert
Einstein, Marilyn Monroe, and Salvador Dali that have become modern
icons. The exhibition continues through Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The museums don't end there. From other branches of the
Smithsonian Institution such as the National Museum of American Art
to private museums such as the Corcoran Gallery, interesting
collections abound in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian spokeswoman Mary Combs said tourists need to give
themselves plenty of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``One technique families use is to split up,'' Combs said. ``The
ones who want to go to the National Gallery can go, and everybody
has a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1520EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0154 </DOCNO>
