<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KID-DISEASE-RPT-COX     11-18 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KID-DISEASE-RPT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPEATING FOR ALL NEEDING
 &HT;    PHOTOS ARE AVAILABLE TO GO WITH THIS STORY
 &HT;    TYLER ULM'S FAMILY DEALT WITH A DISEASE THEY HAD NEVER HEARD OF
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyler Ulm's 3-year-old body is covered with bright red patches
of raised skin. Every toe on his left foot has been amputated. His
right knee, stripped of its original muscle, is so weak and stiff
that he drags the leg when he walks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to Tyler's parents, his infirmities are miracles, his
never-ending physical therapy a joy. They realize how lucky he is
to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Tyler contracted meningococcemia, an uncommon and brutal
disease that kills up to 60 percent of its victims. What seemed
like the stomach flu in the afternoon began destroying his skin and
muscles by nightfall. His hold on life grew so shaky that a
hospital chaplain twice prepared Tyler's parents for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The boy fought off the disease in three days. The work to repair
its damage may last for decades.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be dealing with this the rest of his life one way or the
other, whether it be physical or emotional,' said his father,
Dayton, Ohio resident Jamie Ulm.
</P>
<P>
   Meningococcemia is an especially pernicious disease because it
begins innocently. By the time anyone realizes what's happening, it
can be too late. That is almost what happened to Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   On May 23, at the end of a long stay with relatives in
Cincinnati, the boy developed a high fever and began vomiting. His
parents say they took him to Children's Hospital Medical Center in
Cincinnati and were assured that he simply had the flu.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 p.m., small red spots broke out on Tyler's body. They
looked like chicken pox, hardly an alarming disease for a child.
Tyler's parents put him to bed without worry.
</P>
<P>
   But later that night, about 1:30 a.m., Tyler's mother checked on
him. What she saw made her breath catch in her throat.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's lower legs had become a mass of dark purple bruises.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Mark McGwire had taken his baseball bat and was
practicing his home-run swing on (Tyler's) legs,' recalled Jamie
Ulm.
</P>
<P>
   It was awful. My mom and dad both said that if they weren't
there that night, they would have swore that we beat him.'
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to them, meningococcemia had reached its end game.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is similar to meningitis, but it attacks the
bloodstream instead of the tissue covering the brain. Both
conditions are caused by bacteria that reside in the throat and
nasal passages of a small portion of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria can be spread by close, prolonged contact. Most of
the time it doesn't cause any problems, but for reasons no one
understands, it occasionally becomes a monster.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Brilli, a Children's Hospital physician who is
conducting a national study of the disease, said meningococcemia
annually strikes 2,000 to 3,000 Americans, most of them children
(Ohio health statistics do not separate meningococcemia from
meningitis). Various studies put its fatality rate at 20 to 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with flu-like symptoms: fever, nausea, a stiff neck,
severe headaches and drowsiness. It quickly grows much worse.
</P>
<P>
   The disease chews up the lining of veins and arteries, causing
blood clots. The surrounding tissue is starved of oxygen and begins
to die. That is what caused the horrific bruises on Tyler's legs.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Ulm called Children's Hospital when he saw the marks, and
45 minutes later, Tyler was in its intensive care unit. Doctors
gave him antibiotics to kill the bacteria and drugs to make his
heart beat stronger. They put him on a respirator to support his
lungs and force oxygen to his starving tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's life was in doubt for the first two days. But at last,
doctors stopped the bacteria's attack.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler then went to Cincinnati's Shriners Hospital for Crippled
Children. The hospital specializes in burn victims, and Tyler had
lost so much tissue that he was treated as if he had been in a
fire.
</P>
<P>
   He endured a dozen surgeries in less than two months. Surgeons
excised the dead tissue, amputating his left toes, cutting away
large muscles in his legs and removing smaller ones in his arms.
They took a muscle from his belly to support his right knee. They
performed numerous skin grafts, turning Tyler's small body into a
scarlet patchwork.
</P>
<P>
   They also put Tyler in a pressure suit - essentially, a
neck-to-ankle Ace bandage that prevents scarring. He wears it 23
hours a day, shedding it onlyto take a bath.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ordeal, the boy was an ideal patient.
</P>
<P>
   Kids do great with everything,' said Dr. Glenn Warden, chief of
staff at Shriners. People say, Gee, I feel sorry for these kids,'
(but) kids are perfectly wonderful ... much better than adults.'
</P>
<P>
   By early September, the doctors had finished their repair work.
Tyler came home to Dayton and plunged into a five-day-a-week
rehabilitation at The Children's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Physical therapist Dorie Marek started one recent session by
putting Tyler on his back and stretching his legs. She was trying
to increase the flexibility of both muscle and skin.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's reconstructed right leg is so weak and stiff that he
doesn't like to put any weight on it, so Marek has devised drills
that force him to do so, from walking up stairs to kicking a soccer
ball with his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have told the family that Tyler's rehabilitation could
last until he is 21 or beyond. As he grows, his many skin grafts
could split, or his muscles could stiffen again. He may even lose
that stubborn right leg - Jamie Ulm said it doesn't seem to be
growing properly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no doubt Tyler is fortunate. Warden said other
children who have faced meningococcemia ended up losing several
limbs. And Tyler shows no sign thus far of the learning
disabilities and psychological disorders many young survivors of
this disease develop.
</P>
<P>
   For a child who has withstood so much, Tyler seems as normal as
can be. He loves race cars, Nintendo, soda pop, cookies and
irritating his younger sister. His parents hope to start him in
preschool before the year is over.
</P>
<P>
   As Tyler settles into his dramatically altered life, Jamie Ulm
said he wants other parents to be aware of the warning signs no one
detected in his son's case.
</P>
<P>
   If we could just get one family to catch this early, that would
be more satisfaction than somebody dumping a pickup full of $100
bills in our front yard,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
