r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIBLE-HISTORY-HOMOPHO     11-18 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-HISTORY-HOMOPHOBIA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBLE DOESN'T CONDONE SLAVERY, ANTI-SEMITISM -- OR HOMOPHOBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Recently, at a fund-raiser for a national organization dedicated
to overcoming racial and religious bigotry, the speaker linked
anti-Semitism to intolerance against homosexuals.
 &HT;    Afterward, a friend noted sadly, ``I'm worried he brought up the
gay issue. It might offend some contributors.''
 &HT;    ``Let it offend them,'' I responded, ``maybe they need to be
offended.''
 &HT;    In the weeks since Matthew Shepard died -- apparently the victim
of a brutal gay-bashing -- liberal pundits have blamed his murder
on ``the climate of hate'' created by the religious right.
 &HT;    This analysis is wrong. The religious right did not create the
current ``climate of hate.'' If you want to blame religion for
antigay violence, blame Christianity. Liberal, conservative,
Protestant, Catholic -- it does not matter.
 &HT;    Although Jesus never mentioned homosexuality, his followers
developed an anti-homosexual ethic. Beginning with Paul, who
condemned either homosexuality in general or homosexual
prostitution specifically, homophobia contaminated Christianity
from almost its inception.
 &HT;    Throughout much of history, the church proclaimed homosexuality
inimical to faith. Often it ignored or silenced -- and only rarely
affirmed -- its gay and lesbian children. From Augustine through
Aquinas to Protestant reformers, homosexuality was seen as
``unnatural'' and the source of idolatry, deception, and
corruption.
 &HT;    When antigay picketers held up ``God Hates Fags'' signs at
Shepard's funeral they did not represent only the contemporary
religious right. Rather, they embodied a history of horror directed
against homosexuals by the church -- part of a western society's
collective inheritance.
 &HT;    Not every Christian, of course, is homophobic. Rather, all
Christians -- and nearly all Americans -- are influenced by antigay
biblical interpretations. As one professor noted regarding a course
she taught, ``Almost every student described feeling fearful and
uncomfortable about talking to gays and lesbians.''
 &HT;    Students far from the religious right -- such as those in her
liberal classroom -- still snicker about ``the sin that knows no
name.''
 &HT;    Some of my gay and lesbian friends struggle with this heritage.
As Christians, they honor the Bible, trying to live as God would
have them. As homosexual people, they feel the weight of tradition
against them.
 &HT;    The struggle? To believe in a God whose people reviled and
persecuted them.
 &HT;    Of course, others have suffered similar biblical fates.
African-Americans were told the Bible cursed them to be slaves;
women were taught their intrinsic inferiority and wifely
submission; Jews became demonic ``Christ- killers.''
 &HT;    In each case, Christianity developed elaborate theological
systems based on a few biblical texts to keep people subject to the
cultural status quo and male authority.
 &HT;    Powerful though they were, these interpretations are just that:
interpretations. Gay Christians know they have been oppressed by
what people have said about the Bible -- not the Bible. It presents
a different message -- that of a loving God.
 &HT;    The straight community often fails to recognize the difference
between the text and interpretation. Instead, heterosexual
Christians enshrined their prejudices as ``biblical'' and reading
into the Bible ideas not contained therein.
 &HT;    For example, the story of Sodom and Gomorrah is not -- as
commonly believed -- about homosexuality. It is about inhospitality
and violence. English mistranslations aside, the Bible never
actually uses the word ``homosexual.''
 &HT;    The Bible does not condemn what we know as homosexuality --
especially if a monogamous partnership. Tradition does, but most
Christians do not believe tradition infallible. Thus, rejecting bad
tradition in favor of biblical fidelity should be a compelling task
for believers.
 &HT;    Since the 19th century, many Christians have used biblical
criticism to keep the church from misinterpreting its scripture. As
a result, biblical arguments no longer justify slavery. Sermons no
longer identify Jews as the cursed children of Cain. Churches admit
women to full participation in ministry, not some second-class
status.
 &HT;    At some point in history, however, Christians believed these
offensive things -- as many still believe that homosexuality is an
``abomination'' against the Lord.
 &HT;    Homophobia is so pervasive that even those victimized by similar
biblical interpretations fail to recognize it. Only in the last two
decades have churches seriously engaged these issues. This has been
a slow, painful process -- not unlike the arguments surrounding
slavery and women's rights.
 &HT;    One day, as did abolitionism and feminism, the argument for full
inclusion of homosexuals in church and society will win. We will
look back and wonder why it was so hard to see gays and lesbians as
people -- not sinners.
 &HT;    For Matthew Shepard, however, the day did not come soon enough.
His broken body, hung as Jesus on the cross, gives the rest of us
courage to bear the pain of change.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
