<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6942 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPCL-MENTAL-RESEARCH-     11-18 1782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-MENTAL-RESEARCH-II-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... its description.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I understand that my condition may improve, worsen, or remain
unchanged from participation in this study.'' A later sentence
added that ``I understand that because of the withdrawal of active
medication, I may become worse during this study and that either a
relapse of my initial symptoms or new symptoms may occur.''
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA officials painted a less uncertain picture in court
depositions and the published literature. They cited earlier
studies showing that 60 to 75 percent of schizophrenic patients
taken off medication experienced a relapse. They said medication is
withdrawn in order to study factors that can predict which patients
might relapse and which ones might be able to safely stay off drugs
known to cause troublesome side effects.
</P>
<P>
   In a revealing admission, the official who headed UCLA's human
subject protection board at the time of the study said in a
deposition that such details as relapse rates were kept out of
consent forms because they were ``overly frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   The official, Dr. Dorothy Rosenthal, was asked by Aller's
attorney if such information would deter patients from entering
such experiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Correct,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on his experience, Aller, now 35, said he had no
idea researchers expected to see him get worse. ``I thought they
cared about me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As his parents, Robert and Gloria, saw their son descend into
psychosis, they began to ask for his medical records and sought to
determine the true purpose of the study.
</P>
<P>
   When his parents finally convinced him the researchers did not
have his interests at heart, said Aller, ``I couldn't believe they
wanted relapse.'' He left the study in 1991 and is doing well on a
new schizophrenia medication.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio LaMadrid thought the UCLA researchers cared about him
too, especially when they provided weekly lunches, holiday parties,
and free care as part of the package, recalled his brother,
Laurence LaMadrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge social component,'' said Laurence, who stayed
in contact with his brother during his time in the study. ``It was
almost a fraternity.''
</P>
<P>
   When researchers told Antonio he was being transferred from the
Aftercare Clinic after several years, citing drug use, he was
devastated, Laurence recalled. Soon afterward, Antonio committed
suicide by jumping off a 12-story UCLA building.
</P>
<P>
   Although Antonio's participation in the withdrawal phase of the
study had ended about three years earlier, he had continued to be a
patient at the clinic. But court depositions in the lawsuit filed
by the LaMadrid and Aller families against UCLA show that he had
not been seen by a physician in his last year at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA spokesman Warren Robak said he could not comment on either
case because the families have not given written permission waiving
patient confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Keith H. Nuechterlein, the UCLA clinical psychologist who headed
up the study, said that while the consent form did not specify
relapse rates, such information was raised in conversations with
patients and family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel that the amount of information that was
available _ when considering the oral and written informed consent
_ was always very complete,'' said Nuechterlein. The study,
designed to better understand the early stages of schizophrenia,
continues to be federally funded, although the
medication-withdrawal phase ended several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1994, OPRR found that UCLA had failed to fully disclose
the risk of medication withdrawal in the schizophrenia study; UCLA
changed its consent form in response. OPRR also concluded that even
though UCLA said it provided much of the information orally, that
``cannot take the place of the written informed consent which ...
regulations require prior to participation in such research.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuechterlein said he expects the standards for informed consent
to continue to evolve, ``as we try to understand how to really make
sure our patients in studies, and their family members, truly
understand, and are making good, sensible decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   A Globe review of symptom-exacerbation studies from institutions
around the country found a pattern similar to that at UCLA:
researchers telling patients one thing in consent forms and
planning to do another.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bronx Veterans Affairs Medical Center, for instance,
researchers gave schizophrenic patients the drug L-dopa, used to
treat Parkinson's disease but known to induce psychotic symptoms in
people with mental illness. But researchers told patients that ``we
think by giving you this drug and evaluating your response to it,
we may be able to tell if your regular medication is safe for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   In their 1987 published report, the researchers noted that while
most patients recovered from psychotic symptoms after the L-dopa
was stopped, ``a few patients did not.... It seems likely that
L-dopa played a role in bringing on relapse in these few patients
or caused some form of sensitization to psychosis.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Bronx VA acknowledged in a 1994 letter to
mental health advocate Vera Sharav that at the time of the 1987
study it was standard practice not to spell out the risks in
consent forms. They said if the study were still going on today,
the consent form would be worded more explicitly.
</P>
<P>
   At University Hospital in Cincinnati, where in 1983 Shalmah
Prince sought treatment for an impending manic phase of her manic
depression, she was shepherded into a study involving medication
withdrawal and an injection of apomorphine, but the consent form
never disclosed all the risks.
</P>
<P>
   In a court deposition in the lawsuit that Prince eventually
filed, which was dismissed last year because the statute of
limitations ran out, one of the researchers, Dr. David Garver,
explained the failure to disclose risk this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that the consent form signed by the plaintiff does
not discuss a risk associated with a drug-free period. However,
this risk would seem to be self-evident even to a person without
medical training. If therapeutic drugs are of benefit to control a
patient's disease or disorder, it should be clear that withholding
such treatment may lead to a worsening of the patient's symptoms
until treatment is reinitiated.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say that the omission or minimizing of risk in
consent forms during the 1980s was in keeping with standards of the
day and that procedures have vastly improved. But more recent
examples of questionable consent still exist.
</P>
<P>
   In its 1994 and 1995 review of 125 contemporary studies, some
involving the mentally ill and some not, the President's Advisory
Committee on Human Radiation Experiments found that nearly half of
all consent forms were ethically unacceptable or questionable, for
failing to disclose risks or other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In its continuing investigation of the University of Maryland,
OPRR found inadequate disclosure of research risks in studies
continuing into the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   An example of lack of candor on the part of researchers doing
challenge studies comes from consent forms in which psychotic
symptoms are described as a side effect rather than the aim of the
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symptoms are expected. They are not unintended side
effects,'' said Donald Rosenstein, a specialist on psychiatric
research at the National Institute of Mental Health, testifying
before the National Bioethics Advisory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people, including investigators, can get
confused about that,'' Rosenstein said. ``In symptom-provoking
studies, the whole point is to elicit symptoms that are
characteristic of the condition under study.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`I don't remember
</P>
<P>
   what I signed'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in psychiatric studies that don't provoke symptoms,
however, true informed consent can be elusive.
</P>
<P>
   When Andrew Brownstein entered a National Institute of Mental
Health program in Washington, D.C., in 1994, he was asked to sign a
sheaf of consent forms at a single sitting without having time to
read them. Some were for studies of potentially therapeutic drugs,
but others were for spinal taps and brain scans that would do
nothing to improve his condition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In the case of Brownstein, as in others, the sheer volume of
material raises the question: Could he possibly know and understand
what he was agreeing to?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big, big black notebook,'' said Brownstein, who has
bipolar disorder, in recalling what a researcher gave him the first
night he was on the ward. ``There were so many consent forms
presented to me I don't remember what I signed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 13 months he was there until he left in 1995, Brownstein
underwent seven spinal taps, including one that was so
excruciatingly painful that he suffered a severe headache for
several days. He was also enrolled in studies of experimental
medications that might be therapeutic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful,'' he said of the headache. ``I think it knocked
me down for four or five days.''
</P>
<P>
   In an investigation prompted by Brownstein's testimony to the
National Bioethics Advisory Commission last year and concluded in
September, OPRR validated Brownstein's complaints. In response, the
National Institute of Mental Health changed its informed-consent
process.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Dr. Trey Sunderland, chairman of NIMH's institutional review
board, which is charged with protecting subjects of research, said,
``We are constantly trying to improve informed consent.'' He
acknowledged it was ``an error'' to ask Brownstein or any other
patient to sign consents for multiple protocols at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent a year and a half now, changing our policies
and, I think, making them better,'' Sunderland said. But he added
that NIMH's review board is ``not a policing organization. We're a
supervisory organization. We've tried to make it absolutely clear
to our investigators what we expect and what OPRR expects.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Brownstein, the consent process was part of an
experience that made him feel like a guinea pig, rather than
someone in need of care.
</P>
<P>
   As he was about to be discharged, a doctor said ```Andy holds
the record. We have done more procedures on him in 13 months than
we have done on people here a much longer time. His veins were
good, his arteries were good, his spine was good,''' Brownstein
recalled. ``That didn't make me feel proud at all. I wasn't trying
to set any records.''
</P>
<P>
   The final insult came the next day, as Brownstein left the
facility. He recalled the doctor saying to him, ``Thanks for your
time, and thanks for your body fluids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That sums it up,'' said Brownstein. ``It was very cold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
