<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPCL-MENTAL-RESEARCH-     11-18 1822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-MENTAL-RESEARCH-II-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... medical record.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite his state of mind, and over his mother's objections,
Post was asked to sign up for a protocol that involved stopping his
antipsychotic medication and taking three intravenous ``amphetamine
challenges'' so researchers could study the involuntary muscle
movements that are sometimes a side effect of antipsychotics.
</P>
<P>
   The medication was stopped to stir the involuntary hyperkinetic
movements, and the amphetamine was given to study whether it would
moderate the movements _ even though the stimulant was also known
to induce psychotic symptoms in people with mental illness,
according to the research protocol given to patients and their
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give him amphetamine, he's going to go through the roof,''
his mother, Beverly Post, remembered telling the researchers. She
adamantly objected to their plan to give her son, then 27, the
psychostimulant. ``He is a hyperactive person. He has been that way
all his life.''
</P>
<P>
   But armed with Neil Post's signed consent forms, the researchers
proceeded. After the second infusion of amphetamine, Post became
even more restless, unable to sleep, and verbally abusive,
according to his medical record. His reaction was so acute that the
third infusion was never given. His behavior alternated between
``modified catatonia'' and ``belligerent excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Post, now 41 and with a new diagnosis of autism, recalled he
didn't like the pills he was asked to take or the brain scans and
other procedures he was asked to undergo in his two years in
research. It was a painful period he'd rather not discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he'd rather talk about making music, particularly
playing the steel drum. He is a member of Potential Unlimited, a
nationally known group of performers with developmental
disabilities. He also plays lead pan, as the lead steel drum is
called, for the Rhinebeck Central High School steel drum band in
New York, where he now lives, near his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hart, a University of Maryland spokesman, said he cannot
comment on Post's care because ``we're always concerned about
issues of patient confidentiality.'' Hart said the Maryland
researchers are not available to comment.
</P>
<P>
   OPRR this year found the Maryland research center failed to
fully disclose the risks of medication withdrawal, both in the
1980s and today, and continues to have an open case against the
facility. It also cited the center for signing up people for too
many protocols at once. The investigation was prompted by testimony
that Beverly Post and another mother, Janice Becker, gave before a
presidentially appointed ethics commission last year, about their
children's experiences at the center.
</P>
<P>
   But Hart said that the federal agency also found ``we're doing
things the right way.'' The institution has ``suffered a lot,'' he
said, as a result of comments that cannot be countered because of
confidentiality restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's assistant dean for research, Anne Newman Hirshfield,
said in a statement that ``we must stress that the OPRR's thorough
audit did not reveal significant instances of noncompliance with
regulations nor inadequate protection of human subjects. Several
areas were identified where we could improve our practices, and we
have implemented those suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that at her institution, ``we consider the protection
of human subjects of utmost importance. Therefore, we were
especially gratified that the Maryland Psychiatric Research
Center's additional protections for human subjects were considered
by the OPRR compliance site visitors to be `innovations (that) have
the potential to significantly enhance the informed-consent
process.'''
</P>
<P>
   In institutions across the country, others in a similarly
fragile mental state have been asked to sign up for studies
involving agents known to cause psychotic symptoms, according to
the Globe's review of the scientific literature.
</P>
<P>
   At the Illinois State Psychiatric Institute, for instance, 20
patients who were hospitalized for ``acute exacerbation'' of their
symptoms were described as having given ``informed consent'' to a
study. That research used intravenous methylphenidate, or Ritalin,
to make ``possible the study of psychosis under controlled
laboratory conditions,'' according to the researchers' published
reports in 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Half the patients experienced ``moderate to marked
deterioration,'' they noted, and two others became so psychotic
they could not finish the study.
</P>
<P>
   And at Hillside Hospital, a division of Long Island Jewish
Medical Center in New York, in long-running, federally funded
research that ultimately enrolled 70 people newly diagnosed with
schizophrenia, patients described as ``acutely psychotic'' were
said to give informed consent to ``challenges'' using Ritalin,
according to research reports in the 1990s. Family members also
reportedly gave consent. The medical center refused the Globe's
request for copies of the consent forms.
</P>
<P>
   Some Long Island mental health advocates apparently were never
told of the study, even though it had been ongoing for a decade and
all newly admitted schizophrenic patients at one time were being
asked to consent. Arnold Gould, who has a son with schizophrenia
and who founded the Long Island chapter of the National Alliance
for the Mentally Ill in 1980, said he does not recall hearing about
the long-term study, even though the group meets regularly at the
hospital. He doesn't think that researchers deliberately hid this
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I didn't ask the right question,'' Gould said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Researchers defend methods
</P>
<P>
   in challenge studies
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers involved in challenge studies say they can tell the
difference between psychotic patients who are able to give informed
consent and those who cannot, and that they also try to obtain
consent from family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask them questions, present information, and ask them to
explain to you their understanding of what has been communicated,''
said Dr. Jeffrey Lieberman, who headed up the Hillside Hospital
study and is now a professor at the University of North Carolina in
Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have psychotic symptoms, it doesn't mean incompetence.
They can still have the necessary cognitive wherewithal to
understand what is being communicated to them and to determine the
meaning of things on a factually-accurate basis, even though they
are undergoing symptoms that affect their attention and judgment.
It is a matter of magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Appelbaum of the University of Massachusetts Medical
School, who has not done challenge studies himself but has
researched the ability of psychotic patients to consent, said
patients who are having psychotic symptoms often can function
``quite well'' in many areas of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have delusions and odd ideas about the CIA
investigating their backgrounds, or the FBI trailing them on the
street,'' he said. ``But that doesn't prevent them from
understanding what they need to buy at the supermarket that night
to make dinner, from understanding what is being proposed regarding
their entering into a research study.''
</P>
<P>
   Such statements fail to ring true for people who know firsthand
what psychosis feels like, and for ethicists who say researchers
have an inherent conflict when it comes to judging capacity to
consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick enough to be in the hospital. I was in danger. I
was in no frame of mind to be making such a major decision about my
health,'' recalled Patricia Reynolds, who has bipolar disorder, or
manic depression, and was asked while she was having a major
delusional episode to enroll in a University of Cincinnati
treatment study in which some subjects received placebo pills
rather than medication. ``I had signed the papers because my
ability to make a reasonable, rational decision had been altered.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said she left the hospital when she ``realized that I
was being treated like a laboratory rat.''
</P>
<P>
   In any situation where acutely psychotic patients are asked to
sign up for a study when they are expecting treatment, ``you'd be
deluding yourself if you were looking for real consent,'' said
Alexander M. Capron, a University of Southern California professor
and member of the National Bioethics Advisory Commission, which is
renewing calls for research protections for the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Ethicists have a term to describe this problem with the way
research is conducted: therapeutic misconception.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost becomes impossible for patients and doctors to
distinguish between therapy and experiments. They look at it as all
part of treatment. That's a problem,'' said George Annas, chairman
of the health law department at Boston University School of Public
Health. He served as consultant to the 1970s national commission
that first called for special research protections for the mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians who are doing this stuff don't think they're doing
bad things to people,'' he said. ``I don't think there are bad
people here. They want to do good. Patients want doctors to make
them better.''
</P>
<P>
   But when scientists get caught up in the lofty goal of advancing
research to benefit humankind, Annas said, ``they forget about the
humans right in front of them. They're overly enthusiastic. They
can't do both _ research and protect human subjects. They just
can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Katz, a professor emeritus of law, medicine, and psychiatry
at Yale who has served on national commissions examining ethical
concerns raised by Tuskegee and the human radiation experiments,
said the problem is a longstanding one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conflict ... is between the advancement of science and
protecting the inviolability of subjects of research,'' he said.
``Scientists do have a tendency to make concessions ... of not
protecting fully the inviolability of subjects of research. That is
a conflict that has been with us since the beginning of medical
science.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Consent forms fall
</P>
<P>
   short of full disclosure
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if the competence of a mentally ill patient were not an
issue, some consent forms clearly fail to fully disclose the risks
and goals of the research. This has been documented by OPRR
investigations and emerges clearly in comparisons of some consent
forms with scientists' research protocols and their accounts in
subsequent publications.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at UCLA, Bronx Veterans Affairs Medical Center, and
the University of Cincinnati, have acknowledged in letters and
sworn testimony that they have withheld information from mentally
ill subjects, either because the researchers did not want to
frighten the subjects out of participating, or because they thought
the information was unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The consent form that UCLA researchers asked Gregory Aller and
Antonio LaMadrid to sign, for instance, was fairly innocuous in its
description:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
