<SLUG> BC-JELL-O-HOLIDAYS-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIGGLE ALL THE WAY: FESTIVE JELL-O MOLDS ARE PERENNIALS ON HOLIDAY
TABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans get jiggly with it during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Kraft survey found that 75 percent of us include a
Jell-O concoction on the feast table at Thanksgiving. It seems that
amid the heaviness of the turkey, the stuffing, the mashed potatoes
and the gravy, celebrants want a dish that's lighter to the tooth.
</P>
<P>
   There's also, no doubt, a connection that all of the meal's
components, including the Jell-O, can be classified as nursery
foods _ easy-to-eat foods that we can handle from the cradle to the
grave.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of the holidays, we're sharing favorite Jell-O
recipes submitted by Star-Telegram readers.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY-CREAM SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   2 3-ounce packages strawberry Jell-O
</P>
<P>
   2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   2 10-ounce packages frozen strawberries, slightly thawed
</P>
<P>
   13- to 15-ounce can crushed pineapple, well-drained
</P>
<P>
   2 large bananas, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve Jell-O in boiling water. Add strawberries, pineapple,
bananas and lemon juice. Pour half of mixture into a 9-by-13-inch
glass dish. Refrigerate to set. When set, spread sour cream over it
and pour the remaining Jell-O mixture on top. Chill and serve. May
be made a day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 182 calories, 5 grams fat, 29
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 10 milligrams cholesterol, 42
milligrams sodium, 26 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kitty Wooten, Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ANGEL SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   8 1/4-ounce can crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   Boiling water
</P>
<P>
   2 3-ounce packages lime Jell-O
</P>
<P>
   2 3-ounce packages cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   2-ounce jar pimentos, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Drain pineapple and reserve liquid. Add enough boiling water to
pineapple juice to make 2 cups liquid. Mix Jell-O with hot liquid
and stir until dissolved. Set aside to cool but not thicken. Whip
cream cheese until soft.
</P>
<P>
   Add pimentos, celery and pecans to Jell-O and mix well. Add
pineapple and mix well. Put in refrigerator to thicken but not set
(a half-hour to an hour, depending upon refrigerator). When
thickened, fold in whipped cream and spoon into a 2-quart mold.
Chill to set.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 316 calories, 22 grams fat, 22
grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 40 milligrams cholesterol,
201 milligrams sodium, 63 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cynthia Becker, Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MARVELOUS FRUIT MIX-UP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce package Jell-O, any flavor
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup thawed nondairy whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   11-ounce can mandarin orange sections, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   15 1/2-can crushed pineapple in syrup, drained
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve gelatin in boiling water. Add ice cubes and stir
constantly until gelatin starts to thicken, 3 to 5 minutes. Remove
any unmelted ice. Add whipped topping, blending until smooth. Stir
in oranges, marshmallows, walnuts and pineapple, reserving some
fruit for garnish, if desired. Pour into serving bowl or individual
dessert glasses. Chill until set. Garnish with reserved fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 150 calories, 5 grams fat, 23
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, trace cholesterol, 24
milligrams sodium, 29 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rebecca Ayala-Torrez, Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WALDORF MOLD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce package Jell-O (mixed fruit or lemon, orange, or
orange-pineapple)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup diced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced red apples
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve Jell-O and salt in boiling water. Add cold water and
vinegar. Cool until thick. Fold in celery, apples and walnuts. Pour
into 1-quart mold. Chill until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 294 calories, 20 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 43 milligrams cholesterol,
116 milligrams sodium, 62 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara G. Rubin, Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LEMON FLUFF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce package lemon Jell-O
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce carton nondairy whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   12-ounce carton small-curd cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Combine first four ingredients. Mix and bring to a boil. Mix
well and cool for a few minutes. Add in last three ingredients and
refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 341 calories, 21 grams fat, 29
grams carbohydrates, 12 grams protein, 27 milligrams cholesterol,
95 milligrams sodium, 55 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Janet M. Harvey, Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CINNAMON APPLESAUCE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cinnamon candy (Red Hots)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups applesauce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce package wild cherry or raspberry Jell-O
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Add cinnamon candy to boiling water and stir until candy is
dissolved. Reheat to boiling and add Jell-O. Remove from heat and
add applesauce. Chill. Top with whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 371 calories, 1 gram fat, 79
grams carbohydrates, 15 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 78 milligrams
sodium, 2 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deann Jacobson, Benbrook, Texas
