<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOT 'IM OUT FOR ABUSING THE MILITARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As long as Congress is geared up to put Bill Clinton's feet to
the fire in impeachment hearings, here's a suggestion: Instead of
impeaching the president of the United States for his tawdry sexual
proclivities and his pathological aversion to the truth _ both of
which were well-known to voters before they elected him not just
once but twice _ why not impeach Clinton for a high crime and/or
misdemeanor that amounts to something?
</P>
<P>
   Why not impeach the president for aggravated incompetence in his
role as commander in chief of the nation's armed forces?
</P>
<P>
   If members of the House Judiciary Committee truly want to
examine Clinton's fitness for office, why don't they start by
taking a look at the stunt he pulled last weekend _ ordering
military strikes against Iraq and then changing his mind at the
last minute?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rehashing Clinton's intimate moments with Monica
Lewinsky, why doesn't the committee investigate Clinton's chronic
recklessness in cavalierly deploying U.S. troops to far corners of
the globe for purposes that have nothing to do with national
security? Why don't these congressional patriots who seem to equate
sex acts with acts of treason set aside Ken Starr's salacious
account of Clinton's private life and demand that the president
account for his outrageous misuse of America's fighting forces?
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde swear in
some military experts who can explain to the country what happens
to morale when soldiers are constantly alerted to expect imminent
combat and then told time and time again to stand down because the
alert was just another false alarm?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Hyde and these other politicians who are screaming for
impeachment could ask the military experts what happens to
preparedness when troops are shipped off to distant outposts for a
one-year tour of duty only to have the tour extended and extended
and extended _ with no clearly defined mission to carry out and no
clue when their thankless assignment might end.
</P>
<P>
   Security-conscious members of Congress are well aware that
morale and readiness have plummeted during Clinton's presidency;
that professional soldiers are abandoning their military careers
for better jobs elsewhere; and that America's enemies and potential
enemies are patiently biding their time until they are confident
that they have nothing to fear from the world's lone remaining
superpower.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant fighting force that President Bush deployed with
such spectacular results in the Persian Gulf War has deteriorated
on Clinton's watch to the point that it's fair to wonder if this
president keeps letting Saddam Hussein off the hook because of a
philosophical antipathy for military action _ or because the
commander in chief knows that the United States is no longer
equipped to carry out significant military objectives.
</P>
<P>
   You want to impeach Bill Clinton? Let's impeach him for the high
crimes and misdemeanors of squandering our nation's status as the
world's boldest defender of freedom; of destroying the morale of
the world's greatest soldiers; of kowtowing to a two-bit dictator;
of abdicating U.S. leadership to appeasement-minded pacifists such
as U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insists that this was the last time he intends to let
Saddam slither out of the bull's-eye. If the Iraqi dictator breaks
his promise to cooperate with U.N. weapons inspectors one more
time, Clinton says, well, no kidding, really, we're gonna let him
have it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope he means it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton says that this time was Saddam's last chance. OK. Will
the next time be Clinton's last chance to prove that he's up to the
job that the polls say 70 percent of Americans want him to keep,
despite his detractors' efforts to take it away from him?
</P>
<P>
   One more capitulation to Saddam might have plenty of Americans
thinking that the president should be impeached _ not for having
sex and lying about it, but for felonious failure to do his job.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
