<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crab appetizer should fill the bill come holidays
 &HT;    By Marsha Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a long wait for Cele Bullis of Gainesville, Ga., who
wrote in July asking for a recipe for a crab appetizer she had
enjoyed at Winston's restaurant in Roswell, Ga., which is now
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Few responses came, and none claimed to be Winston's formula.
Most were similar to this one, sent by Judy Abbott of Acworth, Ga.,
who said she tried them at a clambake in Fairview Park, Ohio.
``They were delicious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullis, meanwhile, doesn't believe Winston's recipe included
cheese, unless it was cream cheese, so we'll keep looking and hope
that in the meantime, she, and you, will enjoy this one. It's easy
to make and freeze, just waiting for drop-by company during the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Crab Canapes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 48 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1jar Old English Cheddar Cheese Spread
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon seasoned salt
</P>
<P>
   17-ounce can crab meat
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   3cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   6English muffins
</P>
<P>
   Melt cheese spread and butter in small saucepan. Set aside to
cool. In a small bowl, mix seasoned salt, crab meat, mayonnaise and
garlic. Add to cooled cheese mixture. Split six English muffins.
Divide crab mixture onto muffin halves. Freeze on a cookie sheet
for 20 minutes, then cut into quarters and freeze until ready to
bake and serve. Bake at 425 degrees for 12-15 minutes and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per piece: 53 calories, 2 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 60), 3 grams carbohydrates, 14 milligrams
cholesterol, 133 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sandra Watts of Doraville is hoping someone has a recipe for a
cake such as the one her mother made every Christmas without
benefit of a recipe. She called it Lemon Cheese Cake, even though
there is no cheese in it. Four layers were frosted with a mixture
of egg yolks, sugar and lemon juice, among other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
