<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Side dishes that put bird's nose out of joint so good the bird
wHeadline goes here on so many lines
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the curtain goes up on the Thanksgiving table, the turkey _
all golden brown and succulent _ usually steals the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But, like a catchy show tune that you can't stop singing, it's
often the supporting cast _ the side dishes _ that you remember
long after the feast is over.
</P>
<P>
   Many Thanksgiving cooks have learned the hard way not to tamper
with the traditional favorites that everyone expects and looks
forward to all year.
</P>
<P>
   So while you leave Mama's sweet potato casserole or Aunt Pearl's
ambrosia safely on the menu, what better time is there to add a bit
of excitement to your table than by adding a few new players to the
regular cast of side dishes? Some may very well end up being scene-
stealers and future family favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Start your search with http://food.epicurious.com. Click on
``Thanks for Everything,'' and then ``Thanksgiving Menu Maker'' and
behold hundreds of imaginative, contemporary variations on hors
d'oeuvres, appetizers, soups, salads, stuffings, sauces, chutneys,
relishes, potatoes, sweet potatoes, rice, vegetables, breads and
desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Under ``hors d'oeuvres'' we found this intriguing but simple
recipe for Broiled Oysters With Hazelnut Pesto.
</P>
<P>
   And look what they've done to brussels sprouts and roasted red
onions (recipes follow).
</P>
<P>
   In the holiday spirit of overindulgence, here are some other
places to visit to search out side dishes.
</P>
<P>
   If you find the recipes at Epicurious a tad exotic, call up
http://www.kitchenlink.com/cgi/sgbrdautoframes?board. It's a long
address, but you will find yourself in the Thanksgiving side dishes
and stuffings section of the Holiday Cooking Club
</P>
<P>
   There is a list of variations on comforting, familiar recipes
submitted by readers, with not a gourmet chef in sight.
</P>
<P>
   And for total Thanksgiving recipe overload, check out
http://www.racersworld.com/(tilde)deb/tg/tgrecipes.htmlcompany for
dozens of links to companies, magazines, Web sites and places like
the California Sweet Potato Council, all offering hundreds of
Thanksgiving side dishes.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Broiled Oysters With Hazelnut Pesto
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 15-20 minutes Cooking time:
2-3 minutes for each pan
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups packed fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup (about 5 ounces) hazelnuts, toasted and husked
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup plain dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup water
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) butter, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   30fresh oysters, shucked, shells reserved
</P>
<P>
   Combine basil, hazelnuts, bread crumbs, cheese, 1/4 cup water,
lemon juice and garlic in food processor. Blend until mixture is
finely chopped. Add butter and process until smooth paste forms.
Season pesto to taste with salt and pepper. (Can be made to this
point 2 days ahead. Cover and refrigerate. Bring to room
temperature before continuing.)
</P>
<P>
   When ready to assemble, preheat broiler. Arrange oysters in half
shells on 2 large baking sheets. Top each oyster with 1 1/2
teaspoons pesto. Working in batches, broil until pesto begins to
brown, about 2-3 minutes. Place 3 oysters on each plate and serve.
_ Bon Appetit, November 1997
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 261 calories, 12 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 63), 13 grams carbohydrates, 74
milligrams cholesterol, 473 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Brussels Sprouts and Roasted Red Onions
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 65
minutes
</P>
<P>
   4pounds medium red onions (about 9)
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4pounds brussels sprouts
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup water
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Trim onions, keeping root ends
intact, and cut each lengthwise into 6 wedges, keeping wedges
intact. In a large bowl toss onions with oil and salt and pepper to
taste. In 2 shallow baking pans arrange onions in one layer and
roast in upper and lower thirds of oven 25 minutes. Carefully turn
onions over and switch position of pans. Roast onions 25 minutes
more, or until just tender and some edges are golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Trim brussels sprouts and have ready a large bowl of ice and
cold water. In a large saucepan of boiling salted water, cook
sprouts until just tender, 8 to 10 minutes, and drain in colander.
Transfer sprouts to ice water to stop cooking and drain in
colander. Vegetables may be prepared up to this point 1 day ahead
and chilled separately, covered.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, stir together mustard and water. In a 12-inch
heavy skillet, cook onions and sprouts in butter over medium-high
heat, stirring, until heated through. Stir in mustard mixture and
salt and pepper to taste. _ Gourmet, November 1997
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 155 calories, 4 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 39), 22 grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams
cholesterol, 59 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
