<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     11-18 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A microbrew `lite' that's lovely
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There were people who thought Greg Kelly had rocks in
his head, leaving a management job with Guinness to start a
microbrewery in Atlanta. Maybe he did and maybe he didn't. What can
be said with certainty now is that he has stones in his beer.
</P>
<P>
   Stones and fewer calories, too. Kelly's Light may be the first
microbrewed ``light'' beer in the Southeast _ less filling and
tastes, if not great, pretty darned good for what it is. It's also
a bold, innovative step for Atlanta Brewing Co., best known for its
flagship Red Brick Ale.
</P>
<P>
   From its origins in Northern California two decades ago, craft
brewing has been a reaction against the blandness and sameness of
mass-market beers. The early craft brewers wanted to re-create
traditional, full-flavored styles, not make Lite beer.
</P>
<P>
   So did Kelly when he founded Atlanta Brewing Co. in 1993. But
Kelly's Light is a stone-brewed beer, reviving a primitive method
to produce a thoroughly contemporary beer. In Europe, before
technology had advanced beyond wood kettles, white-hot stones the
size of small boulders were somehow hoisted and immersed in the
beer, bringing it to a boil without the use of flames. The Germans
still call this stein (stone) brewing.
</P>
<P>
   Today no one worries about setting a metal brewing tank on fire,
but stone-brewing survives in Germany as a means of quickly
caramelizing fermentable sugars. A method that had to have been
cumbersome has been made easier by modern machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, at the International Brewers Conference in Atlanta,
Kelly and his head brewer, Brian Buckowski, happened to attend a
presentation on the ancient art by Chuck Skypeck of Baltimore's
Brimstone Brewery. ``Greg said, `Hey, we could do that, don't you
think?' '' Buckowski says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they could. It's not fair to ask a person who doesn't
drink light beer what he thinks. But say this much: Buckowski has
worked a minor miracle with this exceptionally clean-tasting brew.
It actually tastes like beer, even if it's not as assertive as some
of us would prefer. This is an ale that has the crispness of a
lager, with a nice, dry finish.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly had been talking about brewing a ``light'' beer for a long
time. A salesman by training and instinct, he knew that many people
would never take to hoppy ales or full-bodied lagers. Traditional
or not, those beers are alien to what many people know. For them,
beer means the neutered stuff they drink from a pop-top aluminum
can or long-neck bottle. This is what the marketing people at the
big breweries have conditioned Americans to think is beer.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, most Americans thought bread was the white
sandwich kind _ degerminated, soft as Charmin _ and anything
heartier than Roman Meal a little weird. Sourdough? Pumpernickel?
Coarse whole grain? Nope, not for us.
</P>
<P>
   I call Lite drinkers the White Bread crowd. They don't really
like beer to begin with, which is no crime. But it's the old story:
They want to fit in. You want to tell them to order a Coke or
ginger ale and not worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   Buckowski's challenge was to brew a light beer that had fewer
calories (98 per bottle), but still had taste. He started by
brewing a lager, using traditional lager hops. Not satisfied, he
tried an ale, using the Ahtanum hop that made Red Brick Summer Brew
a winner. Then he stone-brewed the same beer, using flat,
2-foot-by-6-inch slabs shipped from Ireland. Secured in a canister,
the superheated stones sat in the brew kettle through the full
boil. The result was as zesty as a light beer can be.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a light on the rocks. But what really separates this one
from the others is that it's brewed entirely from malted grains _
95 percent barley and 5 percent rye. None of the corn or rice found
in mass-market beers.
</P>
<P>
   I've always said that if I were stranded at a party where the
only choices were Coke and a Lite, I'd go with the Real Thing. Now
I think I just might ask for a Kelly's.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet persistence pays off. When Dogwood Brewing first fired its
kettle on Chattahoochee Road (Atlanta, Ga.) in 1996, it was one
microbrewery among many. Founder Crawford Moran, a one-time
graduate student in English, began with an English-style pale ale.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later Dogwood is still small, still has no budget
for advertising, but it's slowly becoming Atlanta's premier
producer of bottled beer. Its stout made the Journal-Constitution's
10 Best in Atlanta last year, its pale ale was voted best in
Atlanta by readers of Southern Draft and its summer brew this year
was a delicately spicy Belgian White Ale that compared with any.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it was easy to overlook what Dogwood was accomplishing.
A chance sampling of Dogwood Pale Ale changed that. Moran and head
brewer Matt Speece have not only reformulated the beer, increasing
the amount of Cascade hops, but are also dry-hopping it. Whole hops
are put into the brew during the final brewing stages, imparting a
more floral aroma and more pronounced taste.
</P>
<P>
   None of Atlanta's three breweries makes a pale ale with this
much character. From one style to another, Dogwood keeps getting
better.
</P>
<P>
   And now it has added to its lineup a winter ale made from
barley, wheat, oatmeal and rye. It is not brewed to any one
particular style, but if you're a fan of porters with a slight
smokiness, this is one you'll love.
</P>
<P>
   It's another reason many folks are becoming fans of Dogwood.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
