<HEADER>
A7035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TDAY-USA-COX     11-18 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TDAY-USA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It doesn't matter where you hail from, traditions _ and the
memories they bring to mind of food, family and friends _ make a
holiday special
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Bonnie Kin was growing up in western
Pennsylvania, she always knew Thanksgiving was drawing near when
her mother would retrieve the antique food grinder from the top
shelf of the cupboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was used to grind cranberries for her famous cranberry
salad,'' explains Kin. ``My three brothers and I took turns
grinding the cranberries the night before Thanksgiving every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This tradition continued even after Kin and her brothers grew up
and scattered, and when her mother died seven years ago, Kin
inherited the grinder.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Kin's daughter, Ashley, 10, ``solemnly stands at the table
each Thanksgiving eve turning the handle of the old grinder year
after year.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fresh cranberries, the salad isn't significantly
different from many others _ chopped celery and nuts, Jell-O and a
mold. But it's the turning of the handle year after year that
endears and endures, like so many Thanksgiving traditions.
</P>
<P>
   When we asked readers _ especially those who've moved here from
other regions of the country _ to share their Thanksgiving recipes,
we found the menu sacred; the variations subtle. No wild rice
souffles from Minnesota or lobster stuffing from Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Folks around here _ whether they are from here or not _ stick
with turkey and dressing, cranberries and pumpkin pie.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that for many the standard menu is but a
starting point. Joseph Brady of Roswell, for instance, often serves
venison and duck along with the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``My version of my mother's English-style dressing goes well
with all the richer meats,'' said Brady. His mother was
English/Irish and raised in Chicago, his father from Savannah, Ga.
The dressing relies heavily on apples, prunes, sherry and French
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Bautsch of Marietta prefers a dressing rich in pork
sausage and turkey giblets, as her in-laws in New Orleans prepare
every year. ``I had never had anything but regular corn bread
dressing growing up, and this was a big surprise the first
Thanksgiving we had with my husband's family 34 years ago,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Susan Kendall of Marietta, Ga., oysters are the key to a
good dressing. She remembers visiting her grandparents in
Hagerstown, Maryland as a child. Her grandfather was a friend of J.
Millard Tawes, who was governor of Maryland for 12 years and owner
of an oyster farm and packing house in Crisfield. Each
Thanksgiving, the Tawes sent her family fresh oysters along with a
gallon tin of shelled oysters.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Thanksgiving, there would be oysters on the half shell,
oyster dressing and scalloped oysters,'' said Kendall, who
continues to make oyster dressing each year, without the help of a
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Another Marylander sent us a recipe for peas and carrots in
brown gravy. ``It wouldn't be Thanksgiving for my siblings and me''
without the dish, said Roseanne Bourgeois of Grayson, Ga. She
traces the dish back to her mother's Polish roots.
</P>
<P>
   For Pat Hawthorne of Fayetteville, Ga., who hails from Brooklyn
via Wisconsin, it wouldn't be Thanksgiving without mashed
rutabagas, which she always called turnips until she moved to the
South and we set her straight. They are boiled and then mashed in
turkey stock, cream, nutmeg, salt and butter.
</P>
<P>
   But like Kin, it's cranberries that define Thanksgiving for
Debra Swiggum of Lawrenceville, Ga. She and her family moved to the
Atlanta area eight years ago from Wisconsin, and at that time they
started a new tradition _ her husband cooks the Thanksgiving meal.
</P>
<P>
   There's one exception. Swiggum makes the desserts _ a pumpkin
pie and a cranberry cake with warm brown sugar sauce. ``I grew up
in a small town surrounded with many cranberry bogs from small
family-owned businesses to the larger Ocean Spray,'' she said. ``So
cranberries were plentiful and very fresh. In fact, every year, my
mother sends me two boxes, farmed locally.''
</P>
<P>
   And many of those tart, crimson jewels end up in a spongy yellow
cake that soaks in the sweet, warm sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although our tradition of having the entire meal made by my
husband is relatively new,'' said Swiggum, ``this cake reminds us
all of home in Wisconsin, having dinner at Grandma's house.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
