<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TDAY-USA-RECIPE1     11-18 1555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TDAY-USA-RECIPE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thanksgiving U.S.A.
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ OK, so here's a radical idea for Thanksgiving. How
about roast turkey?
</P>
<P>
   To suggest otherwise would be sacrilege. We know that, of
course. So when we asked folks to send up their regional variations
on this national meal, it came as no surprise that we received
fairly traditional recipes _ though many with touching personal
stories. Recipes of memories, in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Rodgers, author of ``Thanksgiving 101,'' said that as he's
traveled the land teaching cooking classes on the holiday meal,
he's been struck by the similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain icons on the Thanksgiving table _ Jell-O
salad, green bean bake, canned cranberry sauce, pumpkin pie,'' he
said. ``Stuffing is the main place where differences occur. In
California, people make it with sourdough bread. In Seattle, a lot
of people prefer whole wheat bread. In the South, of course, corn
bread is de rigueur. In Pennsylvania, I've had stuffing made of rye
bread, and in some Italian communities, I've had stuffing that is
made with no bread at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For our part, we've given you four choices for dressing, along
with 11 other recipes that are all regional variations on our old
favorites. So, if you've had exactly the same thing for the past
umpteen years, why not try a dash of Nevada or a pinch of Wisconsin
this year?
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Leroy's Turkey Recipe
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Resting time: overnight (in refrigerator)
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2-2 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Reader Randa Warren shared this ``foolproof'' method for
roasting a turkey that a friend of hers (Leroy) in Aspen, Colo.,
taught her. It's roasted at high heat, so it cooks quickly, but a
salt treatment the night before helps keep it moist, juicy and
well-seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   1fresh turkey, 12 to 15 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1to 1 1/2 cups salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup warm bacon fat or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Boiling water
</P>
<P>
   The night before serving, salt turkey heavily inside and out.
(Heavily enough that you can scrape your fingernail through the
salt.) The next morning, preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash the bird
thoroughly inside and out with cold water. Have warm bacon fat (or
oil) ready and spread heavily over entire turkey. Place turkey in
deep roasting pan, put in oven and roast at 450 degrees for 1 hour.
Then remove from the oven and fill the pan with boiling water to
the level of the wing elbow. Cover with aluminum foil, seal edges
and return to oven for an additional 1 to 1 1/2 hours, or until an
instant-read meat thermometer registers 180 degrees in the thickest
part of the thigh. Time will vary depending on size of turkey.
Allow to cool slightly before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 374 calories, 48 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), no carbohydrates, 139 milligrams
cholesterol, 313 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Oyster Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Susan Kendall of Marietta remembers oyster dressing from her
Thanksgiving jaunts to her grandparents' home in Hagerstown, Md.
She still makes oyster dressing every year and ``even my husband
likes it, and he's from Chicago, where oysters are considered
slimy, suspicious things.'' So go ahead and try it. You'll like it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   3pints oysters
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   12cups fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon poultry seasoning
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Drain oysters, reserving 1/2 cup
liquor. Coarsely chop oysters if they are large and set aside. In
large saucepan or Dutch oven, melt butter and cook chopped onions
over medium heat about 5 minutes until tender; remove from heat.
Stir in oysters and reserved liquor, bread crumbs, chopped celery,
salt, pepper, thyme and poultry seasoning. Spoon into greased
13-by-9-inch pan, cover with foil and bake 1 hour, uncovering the
last 20 minutes to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 315 calories, 15 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 31 grams carbohydrates, 103
milligrams cholesterol, 1,128 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   English-Style Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Brady of Roswell likes to serve this English-style
dressing, a version of his mother's recipe, which relies on prunes,
apples and sherry for a rich flavor that can complement turkey,
duck and game.
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1medium Spanish onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   2ribs celery, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   20pitted prunes, sliced in half
</P>
<P>
   3Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1/2loaf French bread, cubed and dried
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup dry sherry (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon dried sage
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons dried parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3cups turkey, chicken, veal or beef stock, or some combination,
divided
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees. In a large iron skillet melt the
butter over medium heat. Add the onion and celery and cook until
transparent. In a large mixing bowl combine the prunes, apples,
bread, sherry, eggs, sage, thyme, parsley, salt and pepper. Add the
onion and celery and 1 1/2 cups of the stock. Pack into the skillet
and bake about 40 minutes, basting with the remaining stock as
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 202 calories, 5 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 27), 33 grams carbohydrates, 52 milligrams
cholesterol, 253 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Corn Bread Dressing
</P>
<P>
   With Sausage and Giblets
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Michele Bautsch of Marietta recommended this rich, dark dressing
that her kinfolk in New Orleans prepare. Our testers agreed that
it's delicious, and easy to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound pork sausage, browned and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   2packages (6 ounces each) corn bread mix (any kind with no
sugar), cooked according to package directions (ours used 1 1/3
cups milk)
</P>
<P>
   3large onions, 2 chopped, 1 halved
</P>
<P>
   3ribs of celery, 2 chopped, 1 halved
</P>
<P>
   3ounces turkey giblets
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups water
</P>
<P>
   1cup milk
</P>
<P>
   4large eggs, slightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1can (15 ounces) chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter a 13-by-9-inch baking dish.
Brown sausage in a heavy skillet. Remove sausage from pan and
crumble into a large bowl. Discard the fat from the skillet but do
not wipe out. Crumble corn bread and add to sausage. In this same
pan, saute chopped onions and chopped celery until onion is
transparent. Add to the sausage in the large bowl. In the meantime,
simmer the turkey giblets, the halved onion and the halved celery
rib in the water. Cover and cook until tender, about 20 minutes.
Remove giblets, chop and add to the sausage and vegetables. Discard
onion and celery. Stir in the milk and eggs until well-blended. Add
the chicken broth and stir until evenly moist. Pour into baking
dish. Bake for about 45 minutes, until dressing is set and golden
brown on top.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 251 calories, 10 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 28 grams carbohydrates, 158
milligrams cholesterol, 641 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Macadamia Nut and Ginger Stuffing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   We found this Hawaiian-style dressing on the Internet
(http://www. epicurious.com) and couldn't resist adding it to our
regional lineup. The sweet egg bread is a nice departure from white
bread and corn bread. Serve this for the adventurous crowd.
</P>
<P>
   6cups 1/2-to- 3/4-inch cubes Hawaiian bread (sweet egg bread),
crust trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1pound sweet Italian sausage, casings removed
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup minced peeled fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped, drained canned water chestnuts
</P>
<P>
   1cup coarsely chopped dry-roasted macadamia nuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup (about) canned low-salt chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   3large eggs, beaten to blend
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place bread cubes on baking sheet.
Bake until dry and firm, stirring occasionally, about 18 minutes.
Do not toast. Transfer to very large bowl. Melt butter in heavy
large skillet over medium-high heat. Add sausage, shallots and
ginger. Saute until sausage is cooked through, breaking up meat
with back of spoon, about 10 minutes. Transfer to bowl containing
bread cubes. Mix in green onions, water chestnuts, macadamia nuts,
parsley and orange peel. (Can be made 1 day ahead; cover and
chill.)
</P>
<P>
   Butter 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking dish. Mix enough chicken broth
into stuffing to moisten. Season with salt and pepper. Mix in eggs.
Transfer stuffing to prepared dish. Cover with foil. Bake 45
minutes. Uncover and bake until golden brown on top, about 10
minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 408 calories, 14 grams protein, 25 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 32 grams carbohydrates, 149
milligrams cholesterol, 518 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
