<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Food on film: Feast your eyes on these
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Thanksgiving and Christmas on their way, our thoughts turn
naturally to food, glorious food. Here are a few of the movies'
most memorable meals _ from fabulous feasts to less delectable
chow-downs.
</P>
<P>
   NOURISHING
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Babette's Feast'' (1987): It turns up in every food-movie
roundup, but how could it not? This Oscar-winning film celebrates
the transforming power of art, rendered in mouth-wateringly
gastronomic terms. In the late 1800s, a Frenchwoman (Stephane
Audran) finds refuge from the political upheavals in Paris by
relocating to a remote Danish village. When she wins the lottery,
she repays her benefactors with a repast to remember.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Eat Drink Man Woman'' (1994): A warm, scrumptious comedy
about food and family, fathers and daughters. A master chef seeks
to reconnect with his daughters through the bountiful banquet he
prepares for them every Sunday. It starts out as a kind of
ritualized forced feeding, but things change as the daughters come
to understand their loving if autocratic parent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Soul Food'' (1997): Pretty much the same idea as ``Eat Drink
Man Woman'' _ food and family in one big stew _ but put through an
African-American filter. Irma P. Hall is the matriarch who fixes
the yummy Sunday dinner that holds the family together. But when
she falls ill, it's up to her children to fix the meal. And
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   BIZARRE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Beetlejuice'' (1988): A fancy dinner meant to show off the
haunted-house merits of their new home turns into a free-for-all
when everyone (including guest Robert Goulet) is seemingly
possessed by the spirit of Harry Belafonte. All together now:
``Dayo! Daaaa-Yo! Daylight come and me wanna go
</P>
<P>
   home!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Ref'' (1994): Cat burglar Denis Leary gets more than he
bargained for when he kidnaps a squabbling yuppie couple (Judy
Davis and Kevin Spacey) on Christmas Eve. Including Christmas Eve
dinner a la Davis. Meaning, a traditional Scandinavian banquet in
honor of an obscure Scandinavian saint, with everyone wearing
elaborate ``crowns'' of lighted candles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Delicatessen'' (1991): Savory sick humor is the point in
this dazzlingly perverse French black comedy. Set in some near
future where eat-or-be-eaten is the rule of thumb (and thigh and
shoulder), the plot focuses on one suspiciously well-stocked deli
where the butcher-landlord and his tenants have devised their own
system for dining in.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Cook, the Thief, His Wife and Her Lover'' (1989): Peter
Greenaway serves up an opulently lush banquet of human depravity in
this tale of a monstrous mobster (Michael Gambon), whose libidinous
wife (Helen Mirren) gets, um, fed up with his abuse. What follows
is as repellent as it is compelling _ a movie that offers food for
thought aimed at our gag reflex.
</P>
<P>
   SEXY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Tom Jones'' (1963): Perhaps the single sexiest
eat-drink-man-woman scene in all of cinema takes place in Tony
Richardson's marvelously bawdy romp. Albert Finney and Joyce Redman
devour oysters, chicken and you-name-it before devouring each
other. Perils of Filmmaking Note: One of the oysters Redman ate
turned out to be bad and she was sick for days.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Like Water for Chocolate'' (1992): Magical munchies from
Mexico are at the heart of this tale of sauces and sorcery. When a
mother decrees that her youngest daughter, Tita (Lumi Cavazos),
must devote her life to taking care of her, the girl becomes
something of a kitchen magician, channeling her feelings into the
food she prepares.
</P>
<P>
   I THINK, THEREFORE I EAT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``My Dinner With Andre'' (1981): Theater director Andre
Gregory and playwright-actor Wallace Shawn are the two and only
performers in Louis Malle's comedy of table manners. Actually, it's
little more than two hours of dinner chat about the meaning of life
and other small matters. But after all is said and done and
consumed, you may find their ramblings surprisingly touching.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
