<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In `Armageddon,' the sky is falling, but it's nothing to worry
about
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   It's the end of the world as we know it, and producer Jerry
Bruckheimer feels fine. Unlike the relatively somber ``Deep
Impact,'' his gung-ho tale of a Texas-sized asteroid menacing Earth
is like a patriotic video game played by cowboys. The movie never
lets the threat of global annihilation get in the way of the
MTV-edited fun. To its credit, you can see most of its reported
$165 million budget in the special effects and mammoth sets. And
the photogenic Ben Affleck and Liv Tyler star as young lovers in
the middle of the madness. But it's up to Bruce Willis, of course,
to save the planet. He ought to try saving Planet Hollywood first.
Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
