<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-WITHDRAWAL-111     11-18 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WITHDRAWAL-1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS TROOP WITHDRAWAL NEARS, WEST BANK ISRAELIS AND ARABS AWAIT
NERVOUSLY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KADIM, West Bank _ Hava Miller came to this high hilltop with
four other families 14 years ago as a pioneer, simply searching for
``a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she is about to be a reluctant pioneer in the precarious
Middle East peace process and its untested Wye Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old's community, the Israeli Jewish settlement of
Kadim, will likely find itself surrounded by areas controlled by
the Palestinian National Authority within just a few days.
</P>
<P>
   It will be one of the first steps of the Wye peace plan.
Residents wonder whether it will be harder for their children to
get to school an hour away -- a bus trip already escorted by army
patrols. Will their water lines be cut off? Will their community
shrink out of existence as newcomers are scared off?
</P>
<P>
   These are not the extremists who have been staging protests and
threatening to topple the Israeli government if land is ceded.
</P>
<P>
   While the Israeli government encouraged settlements in order to
strengthen its claim to disputed land, the residents of Kadim came
for affordable housing and government tax breaks. They do not say
they came here because God promised them the land, as do others,
and some might leave if compensated -- as a recent poll showed many
of the 170,000 Israeli settlers would.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye Memorandum, which was signed in Washington last month,
outlines the withdrawal of Israeli troops from more West Bank land
captured in the 1967 war. The first phase switches 2 percent of the
West Bank from Israeli to Palestinian control and switches other
land from partial to full Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   The maps of the exact tranfers are not public yet. Political
leaders have been meeting with settlers, tweeking the maps with
public input similar to how school districts regularly make
adjustments in their school zones.
</P>
<P>
   But most expect Kadim to be an island of Jews among
Palestinian-controlled lands when it becomes a first step under the
Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye deal has been on-again, off-again, almost daily since it
was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a good day. The Israeli parliament ratified Wye
the night before and meetings started in the long-delayed talks
over the final boundaries of Israel and the Palestinian Authority,
the hardest issues in the Oslo peace process. The Israeli cabinet
votes on approving the first steps of the withdrawal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But, on the dry ground of the rocky, hilly, West Bank, people
are nervous. Near the Palestinian town of Anata, Palestinian
Rasmiya Ifhidat, 43, watched a bulldozer, guarded by two Israeli
army patrols, cut a road through her land.
</P>
<P>
   The road is intended to make post-Wye life easier for Jews who
live in the West Bank, but it leaves her land as a small island
between an Israeli army base and the new highway. In tones of
desparation, the widow said Israelis have warned that they will
knock down a house her family had started to construct. Currently,
22 relatives live under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Further north, the Israeli army evicted several Jewish settlers
from a hilltop they had taken with trailers -- an attempt to expand
their hold on the disputed land. Just days ago, Israel's Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon had urged settlers to ``seize'' any land they
could before the withdrawals happen.
</P>
<P>
   But, they are not capturing any hills near Kadim.
</P>
<P>
   There are 40 families here now, in small stucco houses with
Spanish tile rooves. They are nestled among pine and fruit trees,
and an olive orchard with a Palestinian farmer who is still allowed
to come in and harvest.
</P>
<P>
   They are mostly secular Jews, many of whom work in high-tech
jobs in cities within an hour's drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the most negotiable settlement in the whole thing,''
said Rick Wienecke, a sculptor who lives in Kadim, noting that the
community is small, moderate and without political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing a building with Wienecke's studio is a chicken
incubating company, owned by an Israeli but run by four
Palestinians. They swap tools with the Israelis and get along, even
as their views differ.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, for example, believe the Jews can keep living
here, but under the rule of the Palestinian Authority, rather than
the Israeli government. The land used to belong to Palestinians and
should be returned, they say. Miller says she would leave if forced
to live under Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
   But, in day-to-day life, this basic disagreement rarely
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This specific settlement is different from the others,'' said
Rida Amriyeh, a Palestinian who buys chickens at the incubator.
``It was always totally peaceful . . . maybe they are a minority.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
