</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JAPAN-1119-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BEGINS ASIA TRIP CHIDING JAPAN TO HEAL ITS ECONOMIC
WOUNDS
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ President Clinton called on Japan to ''take decisive
steps'' to clean up its $1-trillion banking crisis and stimulate
its moribund economy, just hours before arriving here for a
U.S.-Japan summit.
</P>
<P>
   As independent counsel Kenneth Starr takes the stand before the
House Judiciary Committee in Washington on Thursday, Clinton will
be here, in the capital of the world's second-largest economy.
He'll be discussing ways Japan, the region's closest U.S. ally, can
help pull itself, and East Asia more generally, out of a financial
crisis that has shaken markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also expected to pressure Japanese Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi to make good on earlier promises to open markets here
to increased U.S. exports and to accelerate deregulation across a
host of key industrial and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's slumping economy has dampened demand for American goods
and services in this country. One result, a rising trade imbalance,
expected to top $60 billion -- in Japan's favor -- this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a prelude to the likely focus of the summit, Clinton implored
the Japanese government to ''promptly and effectively'' implement a
broad plan for driving the country out of seven years of stagnation
that is hurting the region as well as U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing is more important to restoring stability and growth in
Asia than efforts to restart Japan's economy,'' Clinton said in
White House remarks Wednesday, before departing for Tokyo. ''It has
long been Asia's engine of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan has pledged programs to help its banks rid themselves of
an estimated $1 trillion in bad debts that have caused a chronic
credit squeeze that is starving the Japanese economy. Japan has
also promised to inject tens of billions of dollars into public
works and to provide billions of dollars more in tax relief, but
U.S. officials have expressed concern that the pledges might not
materialize quickly enough, or substantially enough, to pull Japan
out of recession.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to discussing how Japan can promptly and
effectively implement its commitment to banking reform, stimulate
consumer demand and growth, deregulate key economic sectors and
open its markets to fair trade,'' Clinton said. ``Just as the world
looked to us in America six years ago to put our economic house in
order, today nations look to Japan to take decisive steps to help
the Japanese people, to restore growth in Asia and around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economy is expected to contract by more than 2
percentage points this year, and economists predict it will grow
little, if any, next year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. dissatisfaction over Japan's economic policies have
strained relations between the United States and Japan, the
cornerstone of U.S. economic and strategic interests in the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ''On macroeconomic policy we have been somewhat at odds, and
rather publicly, with the Japanese government over the past year,
and the result has been a measure of
</P>
<P>
   frustration in (the U.S.) Treasury (Department) and a measure of
resentment in Japan at the frequency and specificity and often
public character of advice,'' from Washington, said former U.S.
Ambassador to Japan, Michael Armacost. ''So there's some
bridge-building to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was due to arrive in Tokyo early Thursday morning (EST),
for a busy schedule spent meeting with Emperor Akihito and Empress
Michiko at the Imperial Palace, holding a business roundtable with
Japanese and American executives and conducting a televised town
hall meeting to communicate directly with the Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening Clinton is scheduled to meet with Prime
Minister Obuchi before joining him for a state dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to meet with Obuchi most of the day on
Friday, in a wooded retreat near the foot of Mount Fuji, the
highest mountain in Japan and the best known natural symbol of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is the first stop on a five-day Asia swing that will also
take Clinton to South Korea, for talks likely to focus on security
issues surrounding Communist North Korea, and the island of Guam.
</P>
<P>
   He will remain in South Korea until Monday morning. His visit
will include talks with President Kim Dae Jung, a joint news
conference and a roundtable discussion with Koreans. He also will
visit with U.S. troops at the Korea Training Center and at the Osan
Air Force Base. Clinton returns to Washington Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the White House on Wednesday, Clinton warned of a
''provocative missile program,'' in North Korea, which fired a
medium-range test missile through Japanese air space earlier this
year, sending relations between Japan and North Korea near a
generational low.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered, then aborted, U.S. air strikes over the weekend
against Iraq, to pressure that country to cooperate with a United
Nations program to inspect and dismantle its weapons of mass
destruction program.
</P>
<P>
   He'll spend much of the coming days discussing the need to
strengthen a U.S.-brokered freeze on North Korea's alleged nuclear
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Iraq's weapons of mass destruction have dominated recent
headlines, we must be no less concerned by North Korea's weapons
activities, including its provocative missile program and
developments that could call into question its commitment to freeze
and dismantle its nuclear weapons effort,'' Clinton said. ''This
trip will give us an opportunity to address this critical issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
