<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7077 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THANKSGIVING-ARIZONA-     11-18 3402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIVING-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL CHARRO CAFE ADDS SOUTHWESTERN FLAVOR TO THANKSGIVING DINNER  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - In some ways, the Thanksgiving dinner that
Carlotta Flores cooks for her family in Tucson is like that of her
childhood memories.
</P>
<P>
   There are the two dressings, and always the mashed potatoes, and
an overflowing colorful abundance of Mexican and American foods.
</P>
<P>
   Carlotta Flores and her husband, Ray, and their family operate
El Charro Cafe in Tucson, which is the oldest Mexican restaurant in
Arizona owned by the same family. Carlotta's great-aunt, Monica
Flin, opened it in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   She was a pistol, Monica Flin. She drank martinis out of
teacups. Carlotta remembers that Monica loved to hunt and that
during quail season, wearing a dress and big hat, she would take
her guns and have someone drive her out to join the men who were
quail-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she loved bingo and she loved to smoke,'' Carlotta said.
``And makeup, she loved makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica's culinary legacy is lovingly explored in Carlotta's new
cookbook, ``El Charro Cafe: The Tastes and Traditions of Tucson,''
published by Fisher Books in Tucson ($24.95). Carlotta selected a
Thanksgiving menu from the cookbook for Arizona Republic'' readers.
</P>
<P>
   There are pumpkin tamales, of course, and two types of
dressings, cooked outside the turkey. One is made with
jalapeno-cheese bread and one is a picadillo, an easy-to-make
ground beef hash with sweet and sour overtones, which has become
traditional at Mexican weddings. Monica always made the picadillo
at Thanksgiving, Carlotta remembers.
</P>
<P>
   When Carlotta was a child, her great-aunt closed the restaurant
only on Christmas Day. So, on Thanksgiving, the family ate at the
restaurant. The children worked with the adults all day to prepare
the feast and helped set the table with Monica's own china, silver
and linens. Other Tucson families joined them and were served
family style, each with their own turkey. Monica always sent them
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, El Charro is closed on Thanksgiving. Carlotta makes a
great abundance of food for anywhere from 25 to 55 people. Her
daughter, Candace, director of special events for the restaurant's
catering division, said one of the family jokes is that everybody
wants to be there at Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always another plate,'' Carlotta said. ``There's
always lots of food.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica made lamb as well as turkey for the holiday, Carlotta
said. Other kinds of meats are on the modern menu, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband's not a turkey lover, so it wouldn't be unusual to
do a pastrami for him,'' Carlotta said.
</P>
<P>
   One of her kids wants green beans with french-fried onions;
another likes pearl onions in cream sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Ejotes con Crema y Almendras, String Beans with Cream and
Almonds, from the cookbook, suggests an updated combination of
both. Green beans are cooked, seasoned, napped with sour cream and
sprinkled with a little Mexican or feta cheese, and slivered
almonds. The basic idea can be adapted to other vegetables or
combinations, too, Carlotta says. She includes low-fat variations
with many recipes, reflecting the many low-fat options on El
Charro's menu.
</P>
<P>
   Calabacitas, Carlotta's take on the favorite squash and corn
dish reminiscent of succotash, is also on her suggested menu. She
likes to use zucchini, pattypan or yellow crookneck squash,
separately or in combination.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Mashed Potatoes are served with two salsas, Red and
Green, nestled in wells. The potatoes are mashed and whipped with
15 ounces of evaporated milk and a couple of tablespoons of butter.
Then, a cup of diced, roasted fresh green chiles are folded in. The
flavor is especially good with roasted turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Carlotta rewrote this cookbook from an earlier version she
published herself that had even more family history in it. It's a
well-conceived portrait of a landmark restaurant and a valuable
addition to the written food history of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   El Charro's influence has moved far beyond the state's borders.
Carlotta credits Monica with invention of the chimichanga, the
topopo salad and even the cheese crisp. And El Charro Cafe is the
only restaurant still known to make carne seca in the old way,
drying in the sun 500 pounds of beef daily that are hoisted in a
vast cage above the roof. Because you probably don't want to
sun-dry hundreds of pounds of beef in the sky above your house, you
can't exactly duplicate El Charro's carne seca at home. However,
Carlotta gives a recipe for a good facsimile.
</P>
<P>
   Now nationally famous, the chimichanga at El Charro is made with
the 18-inch white flour tortillas found only in southern Arizona.
The topopo is more of a Tucson dish, served in many Mexican
restaurants there as well as a few in the Valley, such as Los
Olivos in Scottsdale. Monica was inspired by a Mexican volcano to
create the cone-shape mound of salad lined with chicken and cheese
strips.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese crisp is the litmus test for Arizona's Mexican
restaurants, because it's one of those deceptively simple things
that can be sublime or terrible. The local open-face version of the
quesadilla is one of those big flour tortillas crisped in the oven
or on a griddle and covered with melted cheese. And, if the menu
says ``cheese crisp'' instead of ``quesadilla,'' it's not a chain.
</P>
<P>
   The giant flour tortilla may be the basis for much of the
Mexican-American cuisine of southern Arizona, but for Thanksgiving,
Monica, and later Carlotta, always picked up football-shape rolls,
bolillos, at a bakery. These are basically French bread rolls,
Maximilian's gift to Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   These days, there is more than one El Charro. Three are at
Tucson International Airport and one is on the east side of Tucson
at 6310 E. Broadway Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   The historic downtown location, 311 N. Court Ave., is in the El
Presidio Historic District and is on the National Register of
Historic Places. The black basalt building was built by Monica's
father, Jules Flin, a young French stonemason who moved to Tucson
in 1860. The eight children he and Carlota Brunet, who was also of
French descent, had were bilingual, then trilingual.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the restaurants, Carlotta now operates a factory,
which makes eight kinds of tamales, minichimichangas, chilaquiles,
red and green chili sauces, and four salsas. Most is sold in bulk
to restaurants, although the salsas are sold in gift shops, too.
The sauces are the secrets to her food, Carlotta said. They are her
way to assure the same taste, the consistency, in all her
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Next, this dynamo is looking north. Carlotta said she is
scouting Tempe and downtown Phoenix for the next possible El Charro
spots.
</P>
<P>
   And the world is going to look at Carlotta. The ``Los Angeles
Times'' wrote about her new cookbook for el Dia de los Muertos. And
QVC, the shopping channel, is interested in packaging the salsas
with the cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   History is still being made. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SALSA DE CHILE COLORADO &QL; 
(From ``El Charro Cafe'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per 1 tablespoon serving: 5 calories, 0.1 g
fat, 0 cholesterol, 1 g carbohydrates, 0.1 mg fiber, 0.1 g protein,
9 mg sodium, 53 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   12 dried red chiles
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts boiling water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup garlic puree
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chiles in cold water and remove stems. Cook in boiling
water until tender, about 15 minutes. Remove chiles and reserve the
cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Place a few of the chiles in a blender or food processor with
1/2 cup reserved liquid, and blend to a paste. Remove to bowl.
Repeat with remaining chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large skillet. Add garlic puree and flour,
stirring until flour browns. Add the chile paste, stirring
constantly until it boils and thickens. Season with salt. Thin
slightly with cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic puree: To make 1/2 cup garlic puree, peel four whole
heads (the entire thing, not four cloves) of garlic by smashing the
cloves with the side of a wide knife; the peels will slip off
easily. Put garlic in blender or food processor with 1/4 cup water,
and puree to the consistency of applesauce. Store in a tightly
closed jar in refrigerator and use within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 8 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RELLENO DE JALAPENO (Savory Jalapeno Stuffing) &QL; 
(From ``El Charro Cafe'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per 1/2 cup serving: 203 calories, 8 g fat, 8
mg cholesterol, 27 g carbohydrates, .1 mg fiber, 6 g protein, 439
mg sodium, 34 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   3 loaves commercial jalapeno-cheese bread, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups warm water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound crumbled tomato-and-basil feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Garnish: Strips of roasted red bell peppers, jalapeno slices
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In large skillet, melt margarine. Saute onion and celery,
stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lightly toast slices of jalapeno bread on cookie
sheet in oven. Cut into cubes. Combine cubed jalapeno bread and
water in large bowl. Fold in crumbled feta cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly add moistened bread to celery-and-onion mixture in
skillet, stirring constantly over low heat about 5 minutes to blend
flavors. Add additional margarine, if needed. Stir again. Turn into
a greased casserole dish and garnish the top with roasted peppers
and jalapeno slices, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Cook and bake for 20 minutes. Uncover and continue baking until
browned, about another 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: Crumbled, cooked chorizo adds another spicy touch to
this recipe. Mix 1 1/2 cups of cooked and crumbled chorizo into
stuffing before turning mixture into casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EJOTES CON CREMA Y ALMENDRAS (String Beans With Cream and Almonds) &QL; 
(From ``El Charro Cafe'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 210 calories, 15 g fat, 25 mg
cholesterol, 16 g carbohydrates, 4.4 mg fiber, 7 g protein, 328 mg
sodium, 61 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1 1/2 pounds fresh green beans or 2 cans (16 ounces each)
French-style green beans
</P>
<P>
   6 green onions
</P>
<P>
   \ cup garlic puree
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt (omit if using feta cheese)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup crumbled Mexican or feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup silvered almonds
</P>
<P>
   If using fresh green beans, snap off the ends, string them if
necessary and slice length-wise. Steam or boil until partially
cooked and tender-crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Mince green onion, reserving 1 tablespoon green tops for
garnish. In large skillet, heat oil and saute onion with garlic.
Add beans and salt and pepper and saute until warmed through. Over
low heat, add sour cream a little at a time, stirring carefully
until mixture is thick enough to coat beans. Add crumbled cheese;
stir. Adjust seasoning to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Serve topped with reserved minced onion tops and slivered
almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic puree: To make 1/2 cup garlic puree, peel four whole
heads (the entire thing, not four cloves) of garlic by smashing the
cloves with the side of a wide knife; the peels will slip off
easily. Put garlic in blender or food processor with 1/4 cup water,
and puree to the consistency of applesauce. Store in a tightly
closed jar in refrigerator and use within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CALABACITAS CON QUESO &QL; 
(From ``El Charro Cafe'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 211 calories, 7 g fat, 7 mg
cholesterol, 21 g carbohydrates, 5.2 mg fiber, 287 mg sodium, 33
percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1 white onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   10 medium squash, cut into 1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   3 tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup garlic puree
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh Anaheim chiles, roasted, peeled, chopped
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can whole kernel corn, drained
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound longhorn cheese, shredded
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat oil and saute onion, squash, tomatoes
and garlic puree. Add water, cover and cook over low heat 20
minutes. When squash is tender, add chopped chiles and corn, and
stir lightly. Taste, and season with salt and pepper. Cook 5
minutes more. Turn off heat. Immediately sprinkle with cheese, then
cover for a few minutes so cheese melts. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic puree: To make 1/2 cup garlic puree, peel four whole
heads (the entire thing, not four cloves) of garlic by smashing the
cloves with the side of a wide knife; the peels will slip off
easily. Put garlic in blender or food processor with 1/4 cup water,
and puree to the consistency of applesauce. Store in a tightly
closed jar in refrigerator and use within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: If you have any leftover Calabacitas, puree it, then
blend with 3 cups beef stock, a little milk and seasonings to your
taste, and you will have Sopa de Calabacitas. For vegetarian
Calabacitas soup, use all milk (1% or condensed skim milk) instead
of beef stock.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PICADILLO &QL; 
(From ``El Charro Cafe'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 327 calories, 20 g fat, 68 mg
cholesterol, 18 g carbohydrates, 2 g fiber, 20 g protein, 443 mg
sodium, 55 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds lean chopped or ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup garlic puree
</P>
<P>
   1/2 white onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups diced cooked potato
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tomato, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup raisins, soaked in hot water until plump
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup ketchup mixed with 1/2 cup water (optional)
</P>
<P>
   6 green olives, pitted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced unpeeled apple
</P>
<P>
   Heat skillet and add salt, water and ground beef. Stir and
separate beef and brown it quickly. Add garlic puree, onion,
potato, celery, tomato, raisins, vinegar, ketchup, olives, sugar,
cinnamon and apples. Cook until flavors blend, about 15 minutes,
stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic puree: To make 1/2 cup garlic puree, peel four whole
heads (the entire thing, not four cloves) of garlic by smashing the
cloves with the side of a wide knife; the peels will slip off
easily. Put garlic in blender or food processor with 1/4 cup water,
and puree to the consistency of applesauce. Store in a tightly
closed jar in refrigerator and use within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CARLOTTA'S ROASTED TURKEY &QL; 
(From Carlotta Flores)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving of turkey with skin and gravy:
647 calories, 36 g fat, 244 mg cholesterol, 2 g carbohydrates, 0.4
g fiber, 73 g protein, 738 mg sodium, 52 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   12- to 16-pound turkey (reserve neck and gizzard for gravy,
below)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup salt mixed with 2 tablespoons ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs
</P>
<P>
   1 medium apple, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped garlic mixed with 4 tablespoons vegetable
oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup melted margarine
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 475 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the turkey inside and out, remove any remaining quills,
and pat dry. Season the bird inside and out with salt and pepper
mixture. Place onion, celery and apple in turkey cavity; drizzle
garlic/oil mix over the ingredients in cavity. Pat outside of
turkey, under wings, on legs, underside of bird and breast with
melted margarine.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap foil around the tips of legs. Place turkey on rack in a
roasting pan to allow air circulation, making sure pan is big
enough to hold turkey. Roast turkey in preheated oven at 475
degrees for approximately 35 minutes or until it starts to brown.
Reduce heat to 375 degrees and cover loosely with foil. Baste often
with the natural juices of the turkey and cook for about 1 1/2 to 2
hours or until pop-up thermometer pops, or until thermometer
(placed in thickest part of the breast) reads 175 degrees. Transfer
turkey to platter, cover and let set for 30 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: Turkey breasts can be cooked in a separate pan, with
the same process as the turkey, only place the vegetables under the
breasts on the rack, and bake until ready. At times Carlotta has
barbecued the breasts to have a different flavor of the turkey at
the table. She bastes the breasts often, as they tend to dry out if
not handled with a little more care than the whole turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Carlotta keeps a squeeze container of melted margarine to
help with the basting process because she feels the margarine adds
to the overall browning of the turkey with a moistness that is
welcomed by her family.
</P>
<P>
   For gravy: Combine 4 cups water with rinsed and chopped turkey
neck and gizzard. Add 1 celery stalk cut in half; 1 onion,
quartered; 1 tablespoon salt; 1 bay leaf; and 2 garlic cloves. Cook
for about 1 hour, then add 2 cans (14.5 ounces each) low-sodium
chicken broth. Cook half-hour more, strain, and proceed with your
favorite gravy recipe, using the turkey stock for your gravy base.
</P>
<P>
   Carlotta uses Wondra flour for her gravy and has Kitchen Bouquet
on hand in case she thinks the gravy lacks flavor. At this point,
she adds strained chipotle paste (2 to 4 canned chipotle peppers,
pureed) and a 14-ounce jar of warmed prickly pear jam or jelly to
the gravy to give it added zing!
</P>
<P>
   She also dices fresh parsley and adds to the gravy boat.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TAMALES DE CALABAZA (Pumpkin Tamales) &QL; 
(From ``El Charro Cafe'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 264 calories, 9 g fat, 6 mg
cholesterol, 44 g carbohydrates, 2.8 mg fiber, 303 mg sodium, 30
percent calories from fat. &QL; 
Masa:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups pre-mixed masa (if fresh masa is available, use it
and omit chicken broth)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups warm chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups (16 ounces) canned pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   1 can (5 ounces) evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped pecans or raisins (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Dried cornhusks
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple Chutney:
</P>
<P>
   1 jar (16 ounces) pineapple preserves or jam
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh orange zest
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whole-cranberry sauce (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   For masa: Using a large bowl and an electric mixer, whip
vegetable shortening until fluffy, about 5 minutes. Beat in sugar,
salt and baking powder. Add pre-mixed masa and broth alternately,
beating until well mixed. Let stand at room temperature 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For filling: In a saucepan, combine pumpkin, milk, sugar,
cinnamon and nutmeg. Over medium heat, bring to a boil and cook for
1 minute. Remove from heat. Stir in vanilla extract, coconut,
pineapple, and pecans or raisins, if using. Set mixture aside to
cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Soak cornhusks in hot water about 30 minutes to
soften. Remove and wipe off extra water. Separate cornhusks. In
center of each husk, spread about 2 tablespoons masa. Spoon 1
tablespoon filling lengthwise down center of masa. Fold husk over
filling to encase it. (Use 2 husks if necessary.) Fold bottom,
pointed end up, over enclosed filling. Place tamales, open end up,
in a steamer basket or Dutch oven fitted with a rack. Do not crowd.
If necessary, place extra husks among tamales to keep them upright.
Place a layer of husks over tamales; cover and steam about 1 1/4 to
1 1/2 hours. Check water level every 30 minutes so pot doesn't run
dry. Add boiling water if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, open husks and top with 2 tablespoons of warm
pineapple chutney.
</P>
<P>
   For chutney: Place pineapple preserves or jam, fresh orange zest
and cranberry sauce, if using, in a microwave-safe dish and heat.
Stir to blend. Add coconut. Use immediately or keep in refrigerator
for up to 1 week. Reheat before using.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SALSA VERDE DEL MERCADO &QL; 
(From ``El Charro Cafe'')
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per 1 tablespoon serving: 3 calories, 0 fat,
0 cholesterol, 1 g carbohydrates, .1 mg fiber, 33 mg sodium, 15
percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped fresh Anaheim chiles, roasted and peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place chile and broth in blender and blend until smooth. Pour
into saucepan and heat slowly over medium heat. Bring to a boil,
then reduce heat and simmer 10 minutes. Taste and add salt. Cool.
Cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 cups. &QL;
</P>
