<HEADLINE>
MAYOR WANTS JUSTICE FOR ACCUSED PIE-THROWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown said three people accused of
plastering him with pies should face ``whatever justice is
appropriate'' to discourage more such attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects are charged with battery and misdemeanor assault on
a public official. Four days before the Nov. 7 attack on the mayor,
San Francisco Supervisor Gavin Newsom was struck by a pie during
his election-night victory party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unpleasant experience,'' Brown said Tuesday. ``They
should be used as an example so that the conduct ceases to occur. I
don't want anyone else victimized.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 64, hurt his right ankle and bruised his right knee when
he tackled one of the pie throwers and held him on the ground until
the police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Brown told a news conference that the ankle was severely
sprained and would cause discomfort for four to six weeks. The
mayor said he had agreed to increased police protection and would
make it easier for his bodyguards to do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've interfered more than I should have,'' he said, noting he
has at times gone without a bodyguard against the advice of the
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They promised to do the job as discreetly as possible,'' he
said. ``But they hope to not allow anyone to get that close to me
again.''
</P>
<P>
   John Shanley, spokesman for District Attorney Terence Hallinan,
said the three defendants are scheduled for trial Jan. 8 on the two
misdemeanor charges, which carry a maximum sentence of one year in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Shanley said that depending on the severity of the mayor's
injuries, the charges could be bumped up to felonies. He said
investigators from Hallinan's office would interview the mayor and
would seek his medical records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a closed deal,'' Shanley said. ``A serious injury
would warrant felony charges. People shouldn't interpret the
misdemeanor charges as us not taking it seriously. We take this
case very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever justice is appropriate for people who assault people
in a cowardly way,'' Brown said when asked if the charges against
the pie throwers should be felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Members of group calling itself the Biotic Baking Brigade have
said they hit the mayor with pies to call attention to his policies
on homelessness. The pies were intended to make a statement through
humor and were never meant to hurt anyone, members of the group
have said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor defended the right to protest. However, he said, ``the
right to protest stops at another person's physical presence. You
don't have the right to punch me in my face with your fist or a
pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he was struck with a tin pie plate in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half an inch lower and it wouldn't have been an ankle injury,
it would have been an eye injury,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
