<HEADER>
A7150 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-ROBOTS-2TAKES     11-18 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-ROBOTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB ROBOTS OFFER HAND-ON EXPERIENCE FROM AFAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Wis., Va.)  (Eds: Please note subslug for CIR-PAINTING-ROBOT)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The artist dipped his brush into a can of red paint. With one
motion, he swiped a thick, fierce stripe across the middle of the
canvas: a gooey, abstract landscape in primary colors. It had been
a long afternoon, and the floor was covered with drips and splats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good thing I don't have to clean up,'' the painter (this
reporter) thought as he logged off. Such is the luxury of painting
with a Web robot, a remote telerobotic device that is operated via
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, an aspiring Jackson Pollock in Brooklyn (or
anywhere on the planet) can make a masterpiece using PumaPaint, a
six-foot, one-armed, 500-pound robot at Wilkes University in
Wilkes-Barre, Pa. yugo.mme.wilkes.edu/ villanov/).
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. Click on one of the four paint-bucket icons
_ each representing a different color _ click again to dip the
brush, roll the mouse to move it. A live, though slow and choppy,
video clip shows the PumaPaint robot responding, reproducing your
strokes on an actual canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Leave an e-mail address and Matthew R. Stein, the associate
professor who started offering the robot's services this summer,
will send you your masterpiece for no charge, at least for the time
being. It's point and paint.
</P>
<P>
   From San Francisco to Japan, Web robots run the gamut, from the
sublime (painting) to the mundane (toy trains). One allowed
students to interact with robots at the site of the Titanic
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Another was developed so NASA scientists could control the
Pathfinder mission on Mars from around the world. In fact, the Web
robot world is mature enough to have critical mass: in October, the
first international conference in the field was held in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Web robots' roots date to the early days of the Internet, when
academics in England pointed a digital camera at a coffeepot and
updated images to the Web every few minutes. Soon, Web-cams grew
more interactive, allowing surfers to aim them in different
directions and at varied subjects: street corners, animals and,
yes, bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   If Web-cams took the central nervous system of the Internet and
gave it eyes, then Web robots have completed the body. With the
increased sophistication of Internet programs like CGI, which is
used to update Web page information rapidly, and Java, which can
relay tiny packets of information between computers, it became
easier for a home PC to issue complex commands to a machine
somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the first two Web robots started up almost
simultaneously (although independently) in 1994. One was a
six-legged robot bearing a camera at the University of Western
Australia, the other a robot arm with a camera that dug buried
artifacts out of a sandbox at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   A third Web robot, called the Tele-Garden, achieved a measure of
Internet fame in 1995 for its founder, Ken Goldberg, an associate
professor of engineering who was behind the 1994 Berkeley project.
</P>
<P>
   The Tele-Garden (telegarden.aec.at) is a six-foot-wide planter
in Austria that can be seeded using a robotic arm. More than a
half-million commands were sent to the robot in the first six
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our objectives is to explore the attention span of Web
surfers,'' Goldberg wrote via e-mail. ``When you plant a seed, it
takes several days to see a result. Those who stick around create
an interesting community, or culture, that's based on patience and
a bit of caring. But we don't intend the Tele-Garden as a utopian
vision of the future of gardening but more as a dystopian reminder
about the pleasures of real gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   For his most recent Web robot, Goldberg created an art project
entitled ``Dislocation of Intimacy.'' In October, a black steel box
at a San Francisco gallery was connected to the Internet. Visitors
to the site (www.dislocation.net) could control motors, lights, and
two fans within the box, causing the box to appear as if it were
breathing. An electronic camera updated the results every two
seconds to the Web. At the same time, visitors to the museum could
see the results in person.
</P>
<P>
   Humanizing the Net with this sort of interactive art is also the
ambition behind PumaPaint, the Web robot at Wilkes University.
Stein, an associate professor of mechanical engineering, initiated
the project after creating an online telerobotic exercise between
his students and a group at the University of Wisconsin. Then,
Stein said in a telephone interview, ``I became curious about what
we as a community of Web surfers would do with a blank canvas and
the ability to paint it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to PumaPaint have left everything from smiley faces to
a surprisingly discernible portrait of Vincent Van Gogh. Randy
Robertson, a PumaPainter in Virginia, wrote via e-mail that the
device offered him more than just a good time. He felt as though he
had glimpsed a Jetsons-like future, when workers might be able to
manufacture goods at a factory from the comforts of their own home.
</P>
<P>
   ``As applications like PumaPaint are developed,'' Robertson
wrote, ``the advantages of rural relocation will greatly outweigh
the disadvantages.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrinking the global village has been on the minds of web robot
developers like Roland Siegwart of the Swiss Federal Institute of
Technology in Lausanne, Switzerland. Siegwart has focused his work
on creating mobile robots that might one day roam the halls of the
museums or the streets of New York. On his current site, users
guide five miniature vehicles named Alice through a city-like maze
(dmtwww.epfl.ch/isr/asl/projects/alicepj.html).
</P>
<P>
   Web robot developers remain a small but dedicated group.
Siegwart invited two dozen leaders in the field to convene at the
conference in Canada in October. Those attending, including Stein
and Goldberg, as well as Web robot developers from Germany and
Japan, presented their recent findings about robot Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Y. Taylor of the University of Western Australia said
that a survey of users showed that 95 percent of his Web robot
visitors were male. The majority of visitors stayed for just a
brief period of time, though some remained for hours. Many users
reported being frustrated with the time delay, a problem that will
presumably will ease as bandwidth on the Internet increases over
time.
</P>
<P>
   At Carnegie Mellon University, a popular web robot named Xavier
has provided lessons about how humans interact with remote
machines. Xavier www.cs.cmu.edu/Xavier) is a mobile robot that can
be deployed throughout a university building. Using a
text-to-speech program, Xavier can be instructed by a Web surfer
to, for example, go down to the X-ray lab and tell a knock-knock
joke.
</P>
<P>
   Though surfers have enjoyed the novelty, there have been
problems. Batteries in Xavier can die out. Worse, the radio
communication system used for robot is limited in bandwidth, thus
limiting the potential interactivity. Surfers can get an e-mailed
report that their mission had been completed, but they are unable
to witness the punch lines being delivered.
</P>
<P>
   A list of other Web-robot sites can be found at the site 
dir.yahoo.com/ComputersandInternet/Internet/InterestingDevicesConnec
tedtotheNet/Robots/
</P>
<P>
   For now, the experiments are mostly recreational in nature, but
developers hope to one day perfect practical applications.
``Telerobotics has a fairly long history in hazardous environments
i.e. nuclear, space and undersea,'' Taylor wrote, ``Web
telerobotics can be used in all of these at lower cost than
traditional techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, kinder, gentler robots like PumaPaint await
your instruction _ 24 hours a day, seven days a week. Soon, Stein
might have to invent another robot: one that mops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
