<HEADLINE>
Q &AMP; A: PARTITIONING A HARD DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What does it mean to partition a hard drive? Is it advisable
to do so?
</P>
<P>
   A. Partitioning your hard drive means dividing one large space
into smaller units, or partitions. Think of a lovely old house that
was once a four-story single-family dwelling in the early part of
the century. Now envision that the house is sold a few decades
later, and the new owner puts up walls and doors and turns the
single-family dwelling into eight apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they are all part of the same big drive, each new
partition is assigned its own drive letter under Windows; if you
divide a Macintosh drive, you see separate icons on the desktop for
each partition.
</P>
<P>
   Partitioning is best done when you initially format a new hard
drive; to do it later is time-consuming because you must first save
and then reinstall all your files and programs.
</P>
<P>
   Why would you want to divide your hard drive? One of the main
reasons is that partitioning a multigigabyte hard drive can make it
work faster. When you are working on a file in a particular
segment, the computer doesn't have to look all over the hard drive
for the file's data, just in that one area.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to:
</P>
<P>
   Questions
</P>
<P>
   Circuits
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036-3959
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
