<HEADLINE>
NEW SHOW'S LOSS IS SAD COMMENTARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - I first read about Keith Olbermann jumping ship from
MSNBC to Fox Sports News last week in the sports section of the
newspaper. I read a follow-up story in the features section.
</P>
<P>
   Fitting, because for his fans, his quitting as host of ``The Big
Show'' resonates across all sorts of boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   True, he is merely jumping from one cable network to another
after making a name for himself at a third _ ESPN, where he was
co-host of the ``SportsCenter'' highlight show. But Olbermann is
someone who can talk about most anything intelligently, the sort of
quasi-Renaissance man who puts a lie to the myth that sports guys
can't cover anything not involving first downs and three-point
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Others came before him in that regard, of course. Bob Costas'
star never shined so brightly, for my money, as when he hosted
``Later,'' a late, late-night talk show. Costas has a nearly
encyclopedic knowledge of pop culture, and he brought it to bear in
a smart, understated way _ nothing like the 38-ounce Louisville
Slugger he hits baseball fans over the head with when he's calling
games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Monica, Monica, Monica
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But hopes were so high for Olbermann. Not only was he
intelligent in his sports work at ESPN, he also had a nice little
smart-aleck streak. He seemed a natural to move on to a wider
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   So when he began ``The Big Show,'' which was to be a news show
with the Olbermann twist, at MSNBC last summer, the future looked
bright. It took him a while to get his MSNBC legs, but he improved.
He always entertains. Don't get me wrong, I'm not saying he's
George Will or Sam Donaldson. I'm saying he's better.
</P>
<P>
   Then a funny thing happened in the White House, and, soon,
Olbermann might as well have been host of ``The Big Lewinsky Show''
because that's just about the only subject he ever covered.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that he did a bad job of it. It's just that when it
comes to topics, Olbermann is like a shark. He has to keep moving
to survive. Sticking him with one subject was a losing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   He says now that the Monica Lewinsky quagmire was ``tangential''
to his leaving MSNBC, but no one much believes him _ especially
after he made comments such as this during the commencement address
at his alma mater, Cornell, in May: ``There are days now when my
line of work makes me ashamed, makes me depressed, makes me cry. .
. . About three weeks ago, I awakened from my stupor on this
subject and told my employers that I simply could not continue
doing this show about the endless investigation and the
investigation of the investigation, and the investigation of the
investigation of the investigation.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Uh-oh, another logo
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the thing is, he was right. Not just about the Lewinsky
story but about the way so many stories are covered. You can't
watch television news stories without first seeing a splashy logo _
``White House in Crisis'' or ``Showdown With Iraq'' or some such.
And a logo is a guarantee the story will be done to death.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet that when the people who design these things sit down
to eat in the morning, they intone in a James Earl Jones baritone,
``English muffin vs. Bagel: The Battle for Breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Every news show, be it ``Talk Back Live'' or ``Burden of Proof''
or ``News Chat,'' is now basically the same. They line up a couple
of ``experts'' who think Bill Clinton is a cloven-hoofed satyr and
square them off against a couple of others who spend their spare
time shining Clinton's halo. (The characters change, but the format
doesn't; when things heat up with Iraq, simply substitute ``Saddam
Hussein'' for ``Bill Clinton'' in the preceding sentence.)
</P>
<P>
   We don't learn anything. Nothing we can't learn from throwing
two dogs one bone, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the maddening thing for Olbermann was that, despite
the American public's well-documented distaste concerning the
Lewinsky affair, the story was a ratings booster for his show.
</P>
<P>
   So now he's back in sports, where the headlines change hourly.
It's honorable, I suppose, that unlike so many TV types who would
give up a knuckle for a Nielsen point, he can walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for us he felt like he had to. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
