<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONITORS GET SKINNIER, AND A PHONE FOR YOUR TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ The Comdex trade show is the largest gathering
of computer buyers and sellers in North America. In an annual
ritual that dates back to the earliest days of the PC industry,
more than 200,000 people are gathered here in the desert to see the
latest technologies put on display by hundreds of companies.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, it seems as if everything at Comdex is shrinking,
except for the hotels, room rates and cab lines. Many of the bigger
names in the computer industry have pulled out of Comdex or reduced
their presence in an effort to save money and avoid being lost in
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The computer giants IBM, Compaq and Dell limited their presence
to private hotel suites or meeting rooms _ Apple has never been a
big player at Comdex _ as did the major chip makers Intel and AMD.
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of the big PC names, the show seems a bit
thin, a bit flat, a bit smaller than in years past. And that's
perfectly appropriate, because the computers themselves are getting
smaller, cheaper, thinner and flatter.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, consumer electronics companies like Sony,
Panasonic, Philips and Toshiba have expanded into some of the space
the big computer companies vacated, bringing with them not only a
fresh collection of computers but also an invigorating infusion of
electronic toys including smart telephones, digital cameras, stereo
speakers and a diverse array of hand-held gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many of the big computer companies that skipped
Comdex announced that they would resurface at the annual Consumer
Electronics Shows here in January, the better to show off their
low-cost computers and peripherals that they hope will impress the
home audience. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about the trends of the show itself. People come here
to see today's and tomorrow's hot products, and to try to predict
where the fast-paced computer industry is headed in the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   Several trends were apparent. The Internet is the driving force
for the industry today. Several companies, including Dell and
Compaq, will soon begin offering desktop PCs that are prepared at
the factory for high-speed (big bandwidth) connections to the net
through cable modems or a new type of phone connection called DSL,
for digital subscriber line.
</P>
<P>
   These new types of connections are many times faster than
dial-up modems or even ISDN, and, besides reducing the frustrations
of slow access to the Web, they create the opportunity for new (to
consumers, at least) applications like video conferencing.
</P>
<P>
   Mobility is going to be a major theme in the year to come,
ranging from smaller and lighter notebook computers to the creating
of all sorts of devices for retrieving information on the go,
including electronic mail and web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Portable computers are proliferating, in a wide range of sizes,
shapes, weights and prices. Some of them are being used as
replacements for desktop PCs, but most of the action here was in
the so-called companion PC categories.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Kaldor, an analyst at International Data Corp., noted that
he has in his kitchen an oven, a toaster oven, a microwave and a
toaster. All of them perform some specialized variation on the
general function of heating food.
</P>
<P>
   He sees it as logical, then, that some consumers might have a
desktop computer, a notebook, subnotebook or ultraportable
computer, and some sort of Palm Pilot-like hand-held computer.
</P>
<P>
   In the smaller category, several companies have been
demonstrating the new class of ``Jupiter'' notebook computers,
which are based on the latest version of the Windows CE operating
system, code-named Jupiter. They are useful only if one already has
a desktop computer to feed it files and applications.
</P>
<P>
   These machines typically cost less than $1,000 and weigh about 2
pounds. Of the ones I saw, I liked Hewlett-Packard's Jornada, NEC's
MobilePro 800 and Vadem's Clio.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Jupiters have a slightly smaller keyboard, about 90 percent
the size of a regular notebook keyboard, but they are still very
useable for word processing, browsing the Web, handling electronic
mail, and doing other basic tasks. Battery life is said to be more
than twice that of conventional notebooks (some claim to work 10
hours on a charge), and, unlike portables based on Windows 98, they
switch on and off instantly, eliminating the annoying wait for
Windows to boot.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do work in cramped spaces, like airline seats, and
who do not mind giving up some of the functionality of Windows 98,
the Jupiters are ideal.
</P>
<P>
   For those who decline to give up their true Windows
applications, but who still want a light notebook, there were
several options in a category now generally called ultraportable or
super-slim notebooks. Two that I saw and liked were the Sony Vaio
505FX, which is the latest version of the original super-slim
computer, and the Toshiba Portege 3010CT.
</P>
<P>
   The Portege 3010CT weighs just less than 3 pounds and is the
size of a stack of paper three-quarters of an inch thick. The
$1,999 computer, which will be in stores in December, comes with a
266-megahertz Pentium processor with MMX technology, 32 megabytes
of RAM, a 4.3-gigabyte hard disk, a 56K modem, an external diskette
drive and a 10.4-inch active matrix TFT screen.
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba asserts it will run 4 hours on a battery charge. It has
a Universal Serial Bus port and two Type II PC card expansion
slots, which allows for the attachment of an optional, external
CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   The trend to thinness was also apparent in desktop computers.
Toshiba's Equium 100, which costs about $3,000 for a basic version,
consists of a thin Pentium II computer with an attached, 15-inch
flat panel display that pivots to either landscape (wide) or
portrait (tall) positions. The entire computer takes up less than
10 inches of desk space from front to back, basically half the
space of a conventional 17-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Flat-panel monitors are everywhere. If money were no object,
flat-panel displays would replace most conventional, cathode ray
tube monitors overnight. But since money is an object, especially
in this town, most people here could only gaze enviously at Nokia's
new 800Xi display, an 18-inch model that will go on sale next month
for about $3,400. It is a bright, crisp and sturdy analogue
display, comparable to a 20-inch conventional monitor, and it
offers a wider and therefore better viewing angle than other flat
panels I've seen.
</P>
<P>
   For fans of flatness, there are affordable alternatives. Several
companies were showing off flat computer speakers, which are less
than one inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite was a $129 set of Berwin flat-panel speakers from
Kwong Quest. The twin flat panels are approximately 5 inches wide
and 7 inches tall each, and about half an inch thick. A subwoofer
cube, about four inches square, completes the set.
</P>
<P>
   A conclusive recommendation will have to await the chance to
test these stylish beauties far away from the din of Comdex, where
the background noise is about 100 decibels, with gusts up to 150
decibels when nearby booths launch into their usual garish skits or
decide to demonstrate their new speakers and sound cards.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is here with a new cell phone so small and lightweight
(2.7 ounces) that it can be clipped to a scarf or necktie. Destined
to be the new status totem of the ``mine is smaller than yours''
crowd of cell phone users, the StarTac V3620 is about the size of
an inch-thick stack of business cards.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to cost $500 to $700 when it becomes available
early next year. The V3620 packs a lot of features into its
diminutive form, including a built-in digital answering machine (a
chip, actually) that stores either four minutes of messages or, in
a clever twist, up to four minutes of dictated notes, or some
combination of voice mail and dictation.
</P>
<P>
   One might use it, for example, to record the location of one's
rental car in the vast parking lots around this convention center.
</P>
<P>
   There were many more interesting products being demonstrated
here that will not be available to the public until later next
year. This column will discuss some of these prototypes next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1652EST &QL; 
