<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-SAFETY-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF TRUCK INSPECTION OFFICERS KEEPS TEXAS ON DANGEROUS COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by TRUCKS-SAFETY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARLAND, Texas _ The 18-wheeler just wouldn't stop, despite the
red lights flashing and siren blasting on the highway patrol car
riding close behind it.
</P>
<P>
   The truck continued for a mile or two, gradually slowing.
Finally, when it was down to a crawl, the driver jumped out and
threw a log in front of the rear wheels, stopping the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No brakes,'' the driver said sheepishly, shrugging as the two
troopers approached. He was driving a fully loaded pulpwood hauler
_ 40 tons of truck and cargo.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was outrageous, said Capt. Larry Marshall,
commander of the Texas Department of Public Safety's regional Motor
Carrier Bureau in Garland.
</P>
<P>
   But the most unusual aspect, he said, is that the truck with the
faulty brakes was pulled over at all.
</P>
<P>
   Texas leads the nation in fatalities involving large trucks, yet
almost all big trucks get a free pass through the state.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is so short on officers assigned to inspect commercial
trucks that fewer than one of every thousand on the road each day
face inspection, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Of trucks that are pulled over for inspection, one in three has
safety defects so serious _ such as bad brakes, bald tires or
unsecured loads _ that the vehicle is immediately ordered out of
service until repairs are made, said Maj. Lester Mills, director of
the state Department of Public Safety division responsible for
truck safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're hitting the bad characters, but when you pull
over a truck and inspect it, 50 or 60 more drive by that don't get
looked at,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to safety defects found during inspections, one in
six drivers is not allowed to continue because he or she is not
qualified, said Capt. Bob Burroughs at the DPS Motor Carrier Bureau
headquarters in Austin. The most common reason a driver is
disqualified is for driving more than the 10 consecutive hours
allowed by federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The state has 371 DPS officers assigned to truck safety
inspections, but they are responsible for more than 1 million
commercial trucks and 32,000 trucking companies, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only other state our size _ California _ has at least
three times as many officers inspecting trucks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is purely financial, said David Willis, president of
AAA's Foundation for Traffic Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has given a higher priority to the problem than
Texas has, and it spends a lot more money on truck inspections,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   California receives the same amount of federal funds for truck
inspections that Texas does _ $3.955 million this year, said Dick
Henderson, director of governmental affairs for the Commercial
Vehicle Safety Alliance in Washington, a coalition of truck safety
enforcement agencies in the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is that Texas doesn't add state funds to
that,'' he said. ``California contributes another $6 million to $8
million a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem in Texas is the huge increase in truck
traffic since Congress approved the North American Free Trade
Agreement. The flow of trucks along the state's major north-south
highways _ including Interstate 35W through Tarrant County _ has
tripled, state officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that new trade from Mexico has to come through the big
metropolitan areas of Texas _ San Antonio, Austin, Dallas-Fort
Worth and Houston,'' Burroughs said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the state's urban areas, which have the most trucks, also
have the fewest inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not where we need to be, especially in the inner-city
areas where people are not looking at trucks much. Some of those
might never be inspected because we concentrate on rural highways,
not cities,'' Burroughs said.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are short-handed, DPS officials say, they leave
urban vehicle inspections to city police departments. But in the
Metroplex, only Arlington, Dallas, Garland, Irving and Plano have
police officers certified to inspect trucks. In Arlington, two
officers are assigned to truck inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big gap in our coverage,'' Mills said, ``and all we
can do is try to have some enforcement presence out there and hope
that, for the most part, truckers will voluntarily comply with the
safety standards.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   An overweight rock hauler with faulty brakes, whose driver ran a
red light, was blamed in a December 1994 Southlake accident that
killed a pregnant woman and seriously injured her 3-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   A Dallas woman lost her husband and her father-in-law in 1993
when a novice truck driver who had been on the road for 22 hours
ran over the men's car with his tractor-trailer in Mesquite. Police
said he misapplied the brake, causing the truck to jackknife.
</P>
<P>
   Safety defects are the most common cause of fatal accidents
involving commercial trucks, highway safety experts say. And the
problem is growing.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 486 people _ one of every 10 killed in Texas traffic
accidents that year _ died in collisions that involved large
trucks, the DPS reported. That was an increase of 36 from the 450
killed in accidents involving large trucks in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Why do other drivers share the road with so many unsafe trucks?
</P>
<P>
   Truckers complain that pressure from shippers to keep goods
moving, as well as the high cost of maintaining their vehicles,
sometimes forces them to delay repairs and drive unsafe vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the time, truckers are just barely making it,'' Leslie
Marion, a Memphis, Tenn., trucker, said recently while refueling
his rig at a popular Weatherford truck stop along Interstate 20.
``It takes time to keep one of these trucks fixed, and you really
need to go over it carefully after every trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even at big companies like the one I drive for, the
pressure is there to keep going, take another load, and don't stop
for anything. I've been driving for 30 years, and it gets harder
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Texas has fewer truck inspectors than the federal
government would like, the state is in compliance with the
regulations covering oversight of commercial vehicles, said Dave
Martin, regional director of the Federal Highway Administration's
Office of Motor Carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Because Texas leads the nation in truck-related traffic
fatalities, the state is part of the federal agency's Big 10
project, a concentrated effort to reduce truck fatalities by 20
percent during the next 10 years in the 10 states with the highest
number, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the list, in order according to the number of 1997
fatalities, are California, Florida, Georgia, Ohio, North Carolina,
Pennsylvania, Illinois, New York and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given all of those states some additional grant money
so they can try to reduce fatalities, and we have encouraged them
to work more in the high-traffic corridors through the Dallas-Fort
Worth and Houston areas,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   But in Tarrant, Denton and Cooke counties _ the entire area from
the south Tarrant County line to the Oklahoma border _ the DPS has
assigned five motor carrier officers.
</P>
<P>
   Included in that territory is a 120-mile stretch of Interstate
35/35W, the nation's busiest north-south trucking route, and
shorter sections of Interstates 20 and 30, two of the nation's
busiest east-west truck routes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Stewart and his four co-workers, the truck inspection
troopers assigned to the area from the Hurst DPS office, say they
sometimes believe that they aren't making a difference in weeding
out unsafe vehicles and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   On a good day, Stewart and his partner can inspect about 10
trucks, he said. Statewide, about 350 trucks are inspected daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of trucks out there that we just can't get
to,'' he said. ``While we're inspecting one, dozens more with the
same problems are driving by. They're everywhere, and they carry
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's saving us is that the vast majority of trucks and
drivers are safe and conscientious,'' Stewart said. ``We're out
looking for the ones that aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The DPS plans to ask the Legislature next year for money to hire
57 more troopers to police the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Fines for safety violations can be $1,000 or more per
infraction, but most of that money goes into the state's general
fund, not toward the program that is supposed to keep dangerous
trucks off the road, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the DPS must make do with the officers it has,
Burroughs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're No. 1 in fatal accidents, and we always want to see that
situation get better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be comfortable until we put ourselves out of
business, but that is an unrealistic goal.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
