<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-680-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED INSTALLS PASSENGER-FRIENDLY EQUIPMENT AT DOMESTIC AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (fb)  
 By JANE L. LEVERE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airlines is installing new customer-friendly equipment at
a number of U.S. airports as part of a $200 million, three-year
program to improve airport processes and make travel easier for its
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   At San Francisco International Airport, the carrier is currently
testing a small, mobile check-in podium that it deploys when there
are long lines at check-in counters, flights are canceled or other
bottlenecks with passengers occur. Custom-made for United, the
equipment is battery-powered and has access to the carrier's data
base by radio frequency.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, a subsidiary of the UAL Corp., is now trying out
four of these units in San Francisco, and will introduce others in
the first quarter of next year at Los Angeles International
Airport, Chicago O'Hare International Airport and La Guardia
Airport in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime late this year or early in 1999, United will put up
large video screens in gate areas that will flash information on
flight delays and cancellations, and alternative plans travelers
may make. For example, Greg Couper, United's director of customer
services planning, said that if a United flight were canceled, the
screen could list other flights offered by AMR's American Airlines,
Delta Air Lines or Continental Airlines where passengers could be
accommodated. These screens will be installed first at O'Hare, then
at other airports that have not yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, since the beginning of November, United has installed
metal templates on X-ray machines at O'Hare and Los Angeles that
measure whether a piece of luggage is small enough to be carried
on, rather than checked. If the luggage is too large, customer
service agents posted at the machines will take it from the
traveler and check it.
</P>
<P>
   Couper said United would install templates on X-ray machines at
as many as 50 additional domestic airports within the next several
months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Torture Test
</P>
<P>
   The December issue of PC Computing magazine contains the
publication's first ``hand-held PC torture test,'' with editors
rating 13 machines for performance, battery life, usability, and
survival through baking, freezing, dropping and dousing with
coffee, cream and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine gave 3Com's Palm III Connected Organizer, with an
estimated price of $369, its highest rating of five stars, praising
its design, usability, battery life and price. This machine's
disadvantages, the magazine said, are a screen that can be
difficult to read and awkward data entry from the touch screen.
</P>
<P>
   Four-star ratings went to Casio's Cassiopeia E-10 palm-size PC;
Compaq Computer's C-Series 2010C; Hewlett-Packard's HP660LX Palmtop
PC; IBM's Workpad PC Companion; Philips Electronics' Nino 300, and
Psion's Series 5.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also discusses the next generation of hand-held
equipment, including Qualcomm's new pdQ Smartphone, an all-in-one
digital phone and pen-based organizer that will offer paging,
E-mail and World Wide Web browsing; a shirt-pocket size device from
Symbian that will let users browse the Web and read E-mail and
files, and a machine from Bluetooth that will allow wireless
communication via radio frequency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Update
</P>
<P>
   Radisson Hotels Worldwide, a unit of the Carlson Companies, is
giving travelers who book a reservation on the company's Web site
(www.radisson.com) 2,000 miles in American Airlines' frequent-flier
program. Reservations must be made by Feb. 28, 1999, and travel
completed by March 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Hilton Hotels Corp. is installing 24-hour automated business
centers, operated by Business Anywhere USA, at up to 100 of its
U.S. hotels by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
   Ritz-Carlton Chicago has a ``compcierge'' to help guests with
computer-related problems on weekdays from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.,
including providing surge protectors, universal power converters,
power plugs and outlets, and other devices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
