<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCKS-MAINTENANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCK MAINTENANCE OFTEN GETS BACK SEAT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TRUCKS-SAFETY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ After trucker Tom Angerer made the down
payment on his shiny new black 18-wheeler, he had $30 left in his
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just like most of the other guys who get started in this
business as owner-operators,'' he said. ``I put all I had into the
truck, then went on the road to try to make some money so I could
feed my family and make the payments on the rig.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance, he said, had to take a back seat.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the problem with many 18-wheelers plying the
highways and byways of the United States, safety experts say. One
in three big rigs inspected on Texas highways is considered so
unsafe that it is ordered out of service until repairs are made.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the repairs can be as simple as spending five minutes
with a wrench to adjust the brakes. For others, it might mean
spending $3,600 or more to replace all 18 tires.
</P>
<P>
   Owner-operators often must make difficult choices when it comes
to keeping their vehicles in good shape, drivers said.
</P>
<P>
   ```Do I buy new tires this week and skip the mortgage payment on
my home, or do I try to make another run or two on these old tires
before spending more money on the truck?' That's the question a lot
of us have to ask ourselves,'' said Angerer, a Seal Beach, Calif.,
resident who regularly hauls commodities into the Fort Worth area.
</P>
<P>
   Many truckers have a difficult time making it financially,
Angerer said, although he said he has been driving long enough _ 25
years _ that those days are behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drive the newest and best vehicle on the road, and I keep it
up immaculately,'' he said. ``I've learned the secret: If you make
enough money, you can afford to play the game right.''
</P>
<P>
   One-truck operations often are lax in their maintenance,
primarily for economic reasons. But such problems also occur among
trucking companies with many vehicles, said Bill Webb, spokesman
for the Texas Motor Transportation Association, which represents
23,000 trucking companies _ including owner-operators _ doing
business in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people doing things well, but there always
will be those who try to cut corners,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brakes are probably the biggest safety issue, Webb said. It's
not uncommon for an inspector to find that a significant number of
the brakes on a truck are out of adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want those trucks off the road if they shouldn't be on the
road,'' Webb said. ``We believe in enforcement if it's fair and
consistent, and for the most part it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government sets inspection criteria for large trucks
and buses, and it certifies officers who do the inspections, said
Randy Moseley, a safety investigator for the Federal Highway
Administration's regional Office of Motor Carriers in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The most thorough roadside check, a Level 1 inspection, takes
two officers, Moseley said. The officers crawl over, under and
through the truck and the trailer, looking for bad brakes, bald
tires, loose lug nuts, cracks in the frame, improperly secured
loads and other infractions, said trooper Don Stewart, one of five
Hurst-based truck inspectors for the Texas Department of Public
Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also take a look at the driver,'' he said. ``Is he
medically qualified? Is his logbook up-to-date? Has he been driving
longer than the maximum 10 (consecutive) hours allowed by law?''
</P>
<P>
   When troopers find violations serious enough to take a truck or
a driver off the road, the driver is usually cited and the truck
must be parked, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day, three Hurst troopers conducted random
inspections of trucks on Farm Road 156 just north of Northeast Loop
820, ordering them into a Texas Department of Transportation
maintenance yard, away from traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The first one inspected, a flatbed semi-trailer truck hauling a
backhoe, was ordered off the road because of its weight: 92,000
pounds. The maximum allowed without a special permit is 80,000
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to leave it parked until he gets a permit,''
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver also was issued a citation, which carries a minimum
fine of $1,000, the trooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Heller of Cedar Rapids, Iowa, who drives for a large
company, said the inspectors are ``too strict on us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many regulations that an inspector could go out
there and find something to write up on every truck here,'' he
said, referring to the dozens of trucks parked at a Weatherford
truck stop while he was refueling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even got written up once because my fire extinguisher wasn't
in working condition,'' he said. ``That might be important on a
gasoline truck, but I'm hauling groceries.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller, who has been driving 14 years, said he has ``just about
had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't enjoy it anymore,'' he said. ``I'll just do it
until I make enough money to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
