<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREATEST-ACCOMPANIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST CALL WARREN JONES THE PIANO MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of folks camm him the world's greatest accompanist.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a title that Warren Jones, 46, accepts _ at least
not without an argument.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``accompanist'' part he objects to.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so he plays the piano while the reigning superstars of the
voice world _ Marilyn Horne, Kiri Te Kanawa, Carol Vaness, Hakan
Hagegard _ stand in front of the piano and sing.
</P>
<P>
   But don't call him an accompanist _ or a ``collaborator.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does one call a pianist who does what he does?
</P>
<P>
   ``How about `pianist'?'' Jones says. ``A violinist who plays in
an orchestra is still a violinist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to be perplexed at the mania to categorize pianists
_ as nightclub pianists, or chamber music pianists, or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth music fans first got to know Jones when he appeared
with bassist Samuel Ramey in the first performance on the Cliburn
Foundation vocal recital series at Ed Landreth Auditorium in
February 1992. The pair returned in the Cliburn series to the
Meyerson Symphony Center in Dallas in January 1995, when Jones
stunned the audience by performing the entire recital, including
the encores, from memory. Any doubts that he is a singer's greatest
partner _ or whatever you call it _ were erased at that point. He
doesn't always play from memory, and that in itself is not a sign
of musical greatness anyway. But in Jones' case, it reflects the
extraordinary knowledge and involvement he brings to a performance.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' background is somewhat unusual for someone so deeply
involved in classical music. The son of a filling station owner in
the small town of High Point, N.C. (there's still a definite
Carolina inflection in his speech), Jones had begun studying the
piano at age 5 with a teacher in Thomasville, N.C. Early on, he
displayed extraordinary talent, including perfect pitch and easy,
flawless memory.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones didn't see a live opera until he was 16. Touring in
Europe that year as pianist for a choir of teen-agers, he stumbled
into a performance of ``Lucia'' in Florence, Italy. He was
astounded by the whole spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Jones worked at the family gas station before
moving away to attend the New England Conservatory, already with a
strong inkling that he would never be a soloist. He was good enough
to perform a Mozart concerto with Arthur Fiedler and the Boston
Pops, but he says, ``I knew I didn't have the peculiar personality
for the solitude that a soloist experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   After several years as assistant conductor of the San Francisco
Opera and then of the Metropolitan Opera, Jones began performing as
a pianist with singers. Eventually, that became his main job.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Jones tours regularly with several renowned singers,
but only those he respects and who regard him as an equal partner.
He teaches piano at the Manhattan School of Music and appears
annually with a favorite chamber music group in San Antonio. He
served on the jury of the Van Cliburn Piano Competition in Fort
Worth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to be the best of his kind _ whatever it's called _ has
also involved learning some nonmusical lessons, Jones admits,
particularly when it comes to working with some of the most
finicky, notoriously temperamental performers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always had an overwhelming desire to be right,'' he
says. ``But I have learned that I am not always right. I have
trained myself to say, `Let's try that.' And, when I'm flexible, my
partner is flexible, too.'' .MDBR/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
