<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7194 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GAME-SICKNESS-750     11-18 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAME-SICKNESS-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL QUEASINESS IN VIRTUAL REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Jannick P. Rolland was participating in a test of the
physical side effects of head-mounted video devices intended for
surgeons. The experiment went fine, and she could see and function
in the augmented reality the gadget presented. Test done, she
picked up a can of soda and brought it to her lips. Well, actually
to her forehead _ she tipped the can back and nearly poured soda
down her face.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rolland, then a researcher at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill, had just proved that technology is
unpredictable. As the makers and users of technology like virtual
reality systems and pulsating graphics on Web pages are
discovering, interactive cyberenvironments can make you try to
drink with your forehead or throw up or, in rare instances, cause
more serious trouble, like epileptic seizures.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last December, several hundred people in Japan,
most of them children, were happily watching their favorite cartoon
on television one minute and hospitalized with seizures the next.
One sequence of the show, called ``Pocket Monsters,'' which is a
cartoon based on a Nintendo game, showed alternating flashes of
blue and red light that induced nausea and dizziness in thousands
and seizures in others predisposed to so-called photosensitive
epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year's incident, several Japanese television stations
have adopted strict standards for television programs. When the
show, then called ``Pokeman,'' made its debut in the United States
last September, the harmful episode was discarded and all others
scrutinized. ``Before it aired in the U.S., every series, every
episode was reviewed frame by frame,'' said Alfred Kahn, chief
executive of 4 Kids Entertainment in New York, the U.S. distributor
of the show.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident underscored the problem: Technology can make
you sick. The kinds of problems it can cause, however, predate
modern technology. It has long been known that certain lighting
effects can trigger seizures in people with photosensitive
epilepsy. The first documented case occurred in 125 A.D., when a
Roman, Apuleius, noted that a person had an epileptic seizure when
a potter's wheel was rotated in front of his eyes. The flickering
light produced by the rotation triggered the seizure.
</P>
<P>
   How interactive technology makes people ill and what can be done
about it are problems that makers of games, for instance, have to
confront.
</P>
<P>
   Video game manufacturers are well aware of the problems that
interactive technology can cause: joystick thumb, eyestrain,
migraines and other kinds of headaches, fatigue, motion sickness
and seizures. For the past several years, game manufacturers like
Nintendo, Sega and Sony have included warnings with their
documentation to alert users to the dangers that lurk behind the
fun. Web sites with flashing lights and strobe effects might cause
similar problems, but none have been documented.
</P>
<P>
   The head of an industry association for video and computer
games, Douglas Lowenstein, said seizures were rare. Lowenstein,
president of the Interactive Digital Software Association in
Washington, said, ``There have been at most only about 50
documented cases of video-game-induced seizures in history.''
</P>
<P>
   There is concern beyond the video game industry. Perhaps because
of the incident in Japan, officials at the Epilepsy Foundation, in
Landover, Md., report a heightened awareness among companies and
consumers alike. ``We've gotten calls from advertising companies
saying they want to use an effect in an ad, asking for some
guidance,'' said Peter Van Haverbeke, a spokesman for the epilepsy
group.
</P>
<P>
   Van Haverbeke said he had also received calls from people
concerned about the flashing visual displays that now adorn many
Web pages. ``As people go online more and more to purchase from
online catalogs, one could imagine that the technology to attract
attention would be put to greater use,'' Van Haverbeke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that people with epilepsy understand their
risks, which are minimal,'' said Dr. Eli M. Mizrahi, a professor of
neurology and pediatrics at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston
and chairman of the Epilepsy Foundation's advisory board. He said
only those people with photosensitive epilepsy, which accounts for
about 2 percent of epilepsy patients, were at risk and that such
people should beware of rapidly flashing and intense light. ``It's
also important that people with epilepsy not be afraid of
technology,'' he said
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A far more common malady, experienced most often in the
simulated environments of virtual reality, is motion sickness. It
is caused by what virtual reality experts call scene delay _ a
discrepancy between visual cues and the movement perceived by the
inner ear. ``Scene delay is one of our really big problems because
of the enormous amount of computation that the computer has to make
each time the subjects move their heads,'' said Donald E. Parker, a
researcher at the University of Washington's Human Interface
Technology Laboratory in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the queasiest stomachs are produced by large-format
films, like those in Imax theaters, where the screens are often 70
feet wide and 100 feet high. Such movies, which often focus on
high-altitude, high-risk undertakings, specialize in giving the
audience the illusion of participation. ``People joke that the
movies are only 40 minutes long because no one can take it for
longer than that,'' said Judith Rubin, a publicist with the Large
Format Cinema Association, an industry group based in Stockton,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``These movies have the ability to make you nauseated in a way
that real life would make you nauseated,'' said Byron B. Reeves, a
communication professor at Stanford University who studies
physiological and psychological effects of interactive media and
television. ``Visual cues and peripheral vision are disturbed
enough to upset one's sense of balance, inducing nausea, much as a
bobbing sailboat would.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous stomach-jolting film was ``Energy!
Energy!'' which was shown at the 1982 World's Fair in Knoxville,
Tenn. The film included an aerial shot above the Manhattan Bridge
that induced vertigo in most of the audience. ``People were
literally throwing up in the theater,'' said Bayley Silleck, a
filmmaker in New York who was one of the film's directors.
</P>
<P>
   Such a large-scale outbreak of inner ear imbalance caused by a
movie has not recurred, partly, experts say, because audiences have
become more accustomed to viewing such films. Still, milder
queasiness is common. For example, a large-format film about Mount
Everest released last spring in Imax theaters contains a dramatic
rock-climbing vignette that had many of those in the audience
averting their eyes to save their stomachs. ``You're seeing what
the climber is seeing as you look down and that has made people
kind of gasp,''' said Lori Rick, director of marketing for
MacGillivray Freeman Films, which produced the distributed the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Still worse are the virtual reality experiences that resemble
amusement rides and are called motion simulation films. Two popular
ones are the Star Tours ride at Walt Disney World and Back to the
Future: The Ride. In these rides, sight is tightly coupled with
motion as viewers' seats lurch and roll with the action on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the industry,'' Ms. Rubin said, ``lots of people tell
you out of the side of their mouth that they hate getting into
those simulators.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are symptoms like those experienced by Dr. Rolland,
who is now an assistant professor in the School of Optics at the
University of Central Florida in Orlando. She nearly dumped a soda
on her face after she used a video see-through display mounted on
her head because her hand-eye coordination went out of synch.
</P>
<P>
   The augmented reality system allowed surgeons to see a
three-dimensional X-ray view of bones, organs and tissue that
appeared to be superimposed on the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Testing showed the need for careful scrutiny of potential side
effects. ``It showed us that the body had adapted to the point
where it's miscalibrated to the real world,'' Dr. Rolland said. Her
findings led to a new approach toward designing such systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you connect more of the body to the computer, the chances
for physiological reactions increase,'' said Frank Biocca, director
of the Media Interface and Network Design Laboratory at Michigan
State University in East Lansing, who collaborated with Dr. Rolland
on the University of North Carolina experiment.
</P>
<P>
   In the extreme, someone leaving a virtual environment can fall
or even experience an inversion of the visual field. Biocca said a
test pilot who had been in a flight simulator was driving his car
when he suddenly saw the world upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If exposure is sufficiently long, people adapt, then you get
post-exposure effects due to the adaptation itself,'' said Parker,
of the University of Washington. ``It's very comparable to being on
an oceangoing vessel and coming back and having the wobbles. It's
been observed since the Romans were shipping people around and
trying to keep their legions well enough to fight when they got off
the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Biocca, who devotes much of his work to spotting negative
physiological and psychological reactions to interactive media,
like computer games and simulations, said more research on their
effects was needed. Biocca pointed out that there was a wide range
of issues that arise from using interactive devices. ``With more
information, we can be more precise about where exactly the
problems are, if there are any,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, of Stanford, said he was more concerned about less
visible symptoms. ``What constitutes a physical effect?'' he said.
``We generally think of throwing up or having your eyesight
impaired. But there are numerous, more subtle changes. Your heart
rate can change; electrical activity in your brain can change.''
</P>
<P>
   As high-definition television sets begin to show up, researchers
are beginning to pay attention to their possible physical effects.
Reeves said he was interested in looking into the possible effects
of viewing a very large picture, which is commonplace in the new
format, in the average-size living room. ``Big really makes a
difference,'' he said. ``Rocket ships are bigger, monsters are
bigger. It just fills a room more.''
</P>
<P>
   Biocca said most people born since the early 1950s would spend
as much as seven years of their lives watching television. For
children born today, ``as new interactive media replace the
telephone, the television set and other amusements, if you combine
all those media, you may get a situation where people are inside
these environments for as long as 15 to 20 years of their lives,
over a 70-year life span,'' he said. ``There has to be some
consideration of the long-term psychophysiological effects.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way to understand the long-term effects of such
technologies will be over time. ``There are no potential animal
models for studying the human effects of media like TV and virtual
reality,'' Biocca said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals can be used to test some lower-level perceptual
phenomena,'' he continued, ``but can't be used to test more subtle
social and psychological effects.'' For that, the only study
subjects are humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
