<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-BIDEN11-19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIDEN WARNS LAWMAKERS TO HEED PUBLIC'S VIEWS ABOUT CLINTON
 &HT;    370 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers who want to remove President Clinton from
office must ``bend over backwards'' to show the American people the
impeachment proceedings are fair, Sen. Joseph Biden said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior member and former chair of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, Biden, D-Del., said though lawmakers are elected to
exercise their own judgment and not shift with the political winds,
they still should take seriously the views of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're trying to decide whether an offense is a breach of
the public trust, it is important to know what the public thinks,''
he said at a National Press Club luncheon. ``If the American people
don't think they have made a mistake in electing Bill Clinton, we
in Congress had better be very careful before we upset their
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden said the best way to ensure the inquiry is conducted
properly is for lawmakers to proceed in a manner that is fair and
consistent with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Democrats and Republicans to disregard their party
affiliation, and he warned them not to base their decision on
whether they agree with Clinton's political or personal views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should they fail to do this, the risk they face is the chance
that they will inflict more damage on our system of government and
induce more cynicism and disgust with politics than anything
President Clinton has done thus far,'' Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's comments come amid continued bickering in Congress
as independent counsel Kenneth Starr prepares to present
allegations against the president at impeachment proceedings
Thursday. While Democrats are complaining about plans to call
additional witnesses, Republicans are warning them not to launch an
attack against Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who want to vote against impeachment should not think
it is an approval of the president's actions, Biden said. Other
alternatives to impeachment exist, including criminal charges once
the president has left office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to impeach, even failure to proceed with criminal
action, does not mean the president has not paid for his immoral
behavior,'' Biden said. ``He has already been sentenced to a
hundred years of shame in the history books, which is not an
insignificant penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
