<SLUG> BC-CIR-BIG-CARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCLING THE (STATION) WAGONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan and Dean sang its praises, and it was once the chosen method
of transportation for summer vacations, tailgate parties and
surfing pilgrimages.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was back when when surfing meant waves, not Web
sites. The American station wagon, the family-packed Sherman tank
of the interstate highway, isn't seen much on the road these days,
thanks to the proliferation of minivans and the almost
dainty-sounding sport utility vehicles. But these classic machines
of yesteryear can still be found cruising the infobahn if you're
looking for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Online Home of the Station Wagon (www.stationwagon.com) has
scads of material for serious wagon wonks, with such regularly
updated sections as Station Wagons in the News, which tracks press
sightings on the subject, and a hefty collection of Web links to
pages celebrating wagons of all kinds. The site contains a Facts
and Trivia page, a Frequently Asked Questions area and a section
where interested parties can buy and sell station wagons.
</P>
<P>
   One of the subsets of the station-wagon faithful is the
wooden-body crowd, who revel in the glory days before auto makers
built cars with all-steel bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The 1953 Buick Roadmaster is often cited as the last of the
``woodies.'' The National Woodie Club, at
www.classicar.com/clubs/woodie/woodhome.htm, offers a site to
discuss the distinctive cars, dispense tips, recruit new members
and announce events. There's even a poetry page on the site
featuring a heartfelt composition called ``My Old Dodge Woodie.''
</P>
<P>
   Referred to as ``cargo ships'' by the Webmaster of the Land
Yacht Marina site, (members.aol.com/landyacht9/cargo.html) station
wagons also have their own section in the Marina. The page displays
many lovingly photographed wagons from many different years and
makers and serves up plenty of links, lore and facts.
</P>
<P>
   The main Land Yacht Marina site
(www.voicenet.com/perches/landycht.html), as one might guess from
the name, is an electronic monument to the glory days of large
cars, some of which seemed bigger than many New York City
apartments. Those fuel-hungry eight-cylinder behemoths that once
threatened to shove the pocket-size Pintos and Pacers off the
asphalt are back in style here. Billing itself as ``a friendly port
of call for all devotees of the great American land yacht, the
long, cushy and powerful road cruisers of the '50s, '60s and
'70s,'' the Land Yacht Marina rounds up a generous helping of
big-car bytes with an engaging sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Another motoring monolith that has inspired a great number of
Web odes is the Volkswagen microbus. Thom's Vintage VW Bus Site
focuses only on models that were made from 1949 to 1967
(www.vintagebus.com).
</P>
<P>
   Comprehensive in its scope, the Vintage Bus site has more than
15 different sections, including a FAQ, galleries devoted to
photographs and art, wiring diagrams and technical specifications.
It even has a Hall of Shame with pictures of rusted and abandoned
microbuses.
</P>
<P>
   As the real things are a rare sight these days, Vintage Bus just
might be the best way to remember the noble Volkswagen van. It
definitely beats being stuck behind one for 10 miles of two-lane
highway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
