u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BATTERY-ART-2TAKE     11-18 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BATTERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE BATTERY GOES, SO GOES THE ... 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Wis., Nev., Calif., Mo., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're on a cross-country flight and your tray table is a nest
of spreadsheets and scribbled notes, raw material for a
due-yesterday report that you are banging out on your laptop
computer. Then, somewhere over Ohio, the computer's batteries give
out.
</P>
<P>
   Or you're attending your child's school musical and when Junior
finally takes center stage, the camcorder sputters, flashes a ``low
batteries'' message, then goes dark.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the time your car gets a flat tire on some remote
stretch of highway and you reach into the glove compartment for
your cellular telephone. There is no dial tone. The phone's
batteries are as flat as your punctured radial.
</P>
<P>
   Batteries _ cells, packs and button-size disks that people can't
live without _ are dying like flies. Or so it seems when you need
them. And people in the electronics industry agree that batteries
are a weak point in portable technology. A common consumer
complaint is that they don't last long enough, or they don't last
as long as battery manufacturers suggest they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like driving a car and never really knowing when you are
going to run out of gas,'' said Christopher Policano of New York,
whose work in public relations requires him to carry a pager, a
cellular phone and a personal digital assistant to keep track of
appointments and contacts. ``I always have a beeper on and it is
interesting to me that I can buy the same kinds of batteries and
one set will last a couple of weeks and another set will get me a
low cell signal on my beeper after just two days. I don't
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Batteries, which have been around since the era of steam
engines, are practically everywhere, in the low- and high-tech
devices we carry on us, from pocket radios to palmtop computers.
They are also in devices we carry inside us, like cardiac
pacemakers and ultratiny hearing aids, and in devices we hardly
notice, like smoke detectors and keyless hotel door locks, and in
devices we hardly ever see, like interplanetary probes hurtling
through deep space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you imagine Christmas morning with all the types of toys
and devices and having all of them plugged into the wall?'' said
Paul Cheeseman, vice president of technology for Rayovac, a battery
maker based in Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 to 15 years there have been significant
advancements in some batteries, especially alkalines, the most
popular type, and newer types of rechargeable ones, including some
alkalines. But in an industry that has $4.3 billion in annual sales
in the United States alone, those improvements have lagged far
behind the blazingly fast evolution of the electronic components
that drive the most popular high-tech devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battery is not keeping up,'' said Ken Hawk, founder and
chief executive of 1-800-Batteries, a mail-order and online battery
retailer in Reno, Nev. He said manufacturers are increasingly
introducing products like DVD players and Pentium II-powered
laptops that are making higher and higher energy demands on
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the disparity, say battery makers and retailers,
is that batteries are the products of chemistry while
microprocessors, on the other hand, are the offspring of physics.
And while the microprocessor industry has steadily found ways to
greatly shrink the size of chips and boost their performance
(Moore's Law states that chip power doubles every 18 months),
battery manufacturers have been hard pressed, after more than two
centuries of working at it, to improve at anywhere near that rate
the battery's electrochemical process that produces electricity.
</P>
<P>
   While batteries will improve, and there are always new
developments on the horizon, no eight-day, one-ounce laptop battery
is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Batteries are a lot more complicated than they seem,'' said
Hawk, who ought to know. His company sells 7,000 kinds.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, all modern batteries, whether primary (the
disposable kind ) or secondary (the rechargeable kind), generate
electricity by use of an electrochemical reaction. This is
accomplished by inserting two electrodes _ one positive (a cathode)
and one negative (an anode) _ into a material called an
electrolyte, which helps the flow of energy between the electrodes.
The electrolyte can be a liquid, as in many rechargeable batteries,
or a solid, in the case of ``dry cells.''
</P>
<P>
   When a battery runs down, the anode and the cathode, which go
through electrochemical changes as the battery produces
electricity, reach a state in which they can longer pass electrons
between them. The voltage drops. The battery dies.
</P>
<P>
   But that explanation is deceptively simple. For example, the
common AA alkaline battery, the kind that would commonly power a
portable cassette player, contains more than two dozen components
and materials, requires 40 manufacturing steps to assemble and
involves more than 15 different chemical and electrochemical
reactions to produce one spark of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   And rechargeable batteries that typically power high-drain,
high-tech devices like mini disk players and hand-held televisions
are even more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The first practical battery is believed to have been developed
in the 1790s and first documented in 1800 in a letter to the Royal
Society in London. A chain of advances in battery technology in the
19th century yielded zinc-carbon batteries. These batteries, cheap
and low-powered, are still in limited use (and likely to come in
devices in which batteries are included).
</P>
<P>
   Zinc-carbon batteries have given way to alkaline batteries; they
use an alkaline electrolyte, which reduces corrosion and gives a
longer life.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, batteries do not store electricity.
They store energy, which is translated into an electric current by
chemical reactions in the batteries, using over the years
substances like manganese dioxide, zinc, nickel, lithium salts,
hydrogen-absorbing alloys and potassium hydroxide.
</P>
<P>
   It is the recalcitrance of chemical reactions that makes
improvement in batteries difficult. Changes in materials _ new
combinations of more refined chemicals _ have produced improvements
by making battery components lighter, thinner and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   A result has been stronger and longer-lasting batteries, said
Linnea Brush, senior research analyst for the Darnell Group, a
publishing and market research company in Norco, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-like circuitry is even showing up in some batteries,
particularly those high-end rechargeables that power some laptop
computers, camcorders and cellular phones. These so-called smart
batteries started coming into use in the mid 1990s. They perform a
range of duties, from keeping the battery from being improperly
charged to reporting its energy levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pay a little more, but smart batteries take the guesswork
out,'' said Ms. Brush, who added that the use of these batteries is
growing at an annual rate of 47 percent worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But most batteries remain, as Ms. Brush called them, ``dumb.''
And problems more often arise with these rechargeable batteries
when they are used in electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One puzzling problem is variability. How to know how long a
charge will last? While batteries are extensively tested against
standards set by the American National Standards Institute, a
nonprofit, nonregulatory body in Washington, battery makers are
reluctant to guarantee that a given battery will work for a given
number of hours.
</P>
<P>
   Battery manufacturers often speak of their battery's capacities
in terms of voltage and milliampere-hours, which is practically
meaningless to most consumers. Sometimes battery potency simply
comes down to a marketing claim like ``longer lasting.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, many battery makers and retailers say, a mountain
of variables makes it next to impossible to predict the battery
life in the myriad of modern devices that routinely gobble them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People use things differently,'' said John Grady, general
manager for technology for Eveready Battery Co., based in St.
Louis. A major influence on how a battery will perform is whether
the device, a cellular phone, for instance, is used continuously or
intermittently, as when a motorist uses it only to call for help.
In the case of a cellular phone, continuous use is generally more
taxing on batteries.
</P>
<P>
   But choose the wrong batteries and even that truism can be spun
on its head. High-power batteries, like nickel cadmium ones, are
best suited for short bursts of energy. For more sustained power,
high-energy batteries, like nickel metal hydride and lithium ion,
are better suited, Ms. Brush said. Mix them up and disappointment
is very likely to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Other variables include the design and efficiency of the device
being used and the conditions under which they are used. Heat, for
example, like the kind produced in many laptops, is a well-known
slayer of batteries, battery makers say. So are digital cameras,
which have earned a reputation for quickly depleting batteries
because of their high-power demands.
</P>
<P>
   After buying an Apple Quick Take 200 digital camera last year,
Andy Baird, an interface designer for the Educational Testing
Service in Princeton, N.J., said he was forced to become a
self-taught batteries expert to slow his camera's ravenous
consumption of batteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can get a lot more usefulness out of their batteries if
they know a little about the kinds of batteries there are and how
they should be used,'' said Baird, who publishes a battery guide at
members.home.com/andybaird/batteries.html.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests, for example, that frequent users of digital cameras
should use nickel metal hydride or high-capacity nickel cadmium
batteries and save money by recharging them. He cautions, however,
that alkaline and especially lithium batteries should be kept as
emergency back-ups because they maintain their charge for many
years, unlike rechargeable ones, when they are not in use. For the
occasional birthdays-and-holidays-only photographer, Baird suggests
sticking with lithium batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Even though batteries do not change as much as other aspects of
high technology, there are at least two significant developments on
the horizon. One is a new variation on lithium ion batteries, the
most sophisticated and expensive of rechargeable batteries. It is
the lithium ion polymer rechargeable battery.
</P>
<P>
   This battery promises to be powerful, yet lightweight and
environmentally safe. Its designers note that the battery's body is
thin and flexible unlike conventional batteries and it manages at
least 500 charge and discharge cycles. Most of all, Ms. Brush said,
the lithium ion polymer battery is much safer than its predecessor,
which has been known to ``vent flames'' while recharging.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Carcone, vice president of the Sanyo Energy (U.S.A.)
Corp., said lithium ion polymer batteries will appear sometime next
year. Yet another battery, the zinc-air cell, is lighter and has a
higher energy density than the lithium batteries, Ms. Brush said,
but it is aimed at computer manufacturers and is not generally
available to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Duracell introduced an improved alkaline battery
called the Duracell Ultra that the company says is 50 percent
longer lasting than its previous alkaline batteries. (It's also 20
percent more expensive. A four-pack of AA Ultra costs about $5.)
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Eveready, whose strategy is to shy away
from rechargeable batteries and concentrate on making disposable
batteries that can handle high-tech devices, introduced its
highest-capacity battery, the Energizer Advanced Formula. Grady
said it represents a 100 percent performance improvement over
Energizer's standard batteries in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The battery industry is highly competitive, with each advance by
a manufacturer often matched or surpassed by others. And that,
battery makers agree, is likely to continue for some time because
battery dependency is likely to continue to grow in coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on widespread use of solar-powered personal stereos,
telephones and computers anytime soon, battery developers say. If
something uses electricity and it is mobile, it probably runs on
batteries, from a musical greeting card to the Space Shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The average household bought 36 batteries in 1997, 40 percent
more than it did a decade earlier, according to a recent A.C.
Nielsen study of American buying habits. And quite naturally, the
study found, battery purchasing peaks during the winter holiday
season to power gifts for which batteries are often not included.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for batteries, especially in all their many new
shapes and permutations, has strained traditional retailers like
supermarkets to keep in stock all the kinds of batteries consumers
say they need.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reach more consumers, Rayovac and
1-800-Batteries announced last month an exclusive agreement to
create a telephone ordering help line for consumers who have
difficulty finding batteries and accessories in traditional stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming increasingly harder for stores to stock the
growing array of batteries for today's sophisticated electronic
devices, resulting in disappointed consumers and lost sales,'' said
Dave Jones, Rayovac's chairman and chief executive, in a company
statement. ``The hotline and Internet sales are a win-win for
all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Hawk said, ``everybody needs batteries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
