<HEADER>
A7220 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SHOGO-GAME-NYT &LR;      11-18 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SHOGO-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGST AND ANGER JAPANESE-STYLE, WITH A WINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.D. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shogo calls to mind the old advertising slogan for Reese's
Peanut Butter Cups: Two great tastes that taste great together.
Take the game play of a first-person shooter like Unreal or Quake.
Add the narrative and esthetic conventions of Japanese animation.
Swirl together and voila, a pulse-pounding blast-o-rama with giant
robots, huge-eyed heroes, omnipotent corporations and
interplanetary war, interwoven with romantic themes and family
psychodrama.
</P>
<P>
   As Sanjuro Makabe, a soldier employed by the United Corporate
Authority, your mission is to quash a rebellion on the planet
Cronus, where your last mission went disastrously awry, claiming
the lives of your girlfriend and your brother. (In the world of
Japanese animation, otherwise known as anime, siblings are always
assigned to the same military unit; families stick together, even
on commando missions.)
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, you blame yourself, and all of this guilt and angst
justifies the destructive spree that is soon to follow; Shogo's
designers have gleefully embraced Japanimation's singular
combination of high-tech violence and unabashed melodrama. ``I've
lost too much to this war,'' Sanjuro declares as the story opens.
``My brother Toshiro. Kura, the woman I loved. Baku, my childhood
friend. I can't bring them back _ but I can avenge them. Every
rebel CMC soldier and fanatical Fallen terrorist I wipe off the
face of Cronus brings me one step closer to peace. That, and
Kathryn, Kura's sister, whom I've been dating for the past several
months. ... It's kind of complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, the plot twists and swerves through anime's
conventional roller coaster of sudden revelations and wrenching
moral choices. In the 40 or 50 hours it takes to complete this
game, you discover the truth (gasp!) about your girlfriend's death,
the United Corporate Authority's nefarious motives (no!) and the
identity of Cronus' mysterious rebel leader (it can't be!).
</P>
<P>
   All the while, there's a full-scale war in progress. So you're
piloting a 40-foot transformable robot under heavy fire while you
make these decisions. But that's anime: Sturm und Drang in the
cockpit of a cutting-edge vehicle. From ``Speed Racer'' to
``Robotech,'' Japanimation has never been a stranger to camp.
</P>
<P>
   And it's high camp, as opposed to American cartoons, whose
lantern-jawed heroes have no idea how ridiculous they look running
around in tights. Anime knows it's overblown, and viewers are in on
the joke. That's why Astro Boy is more fun than Superman. And
that's why anime conventions frame the first-person shooter more
cleverly than the cybergoth esthetic. Anime winks at the viewer,
and a Japanimation video game winks at the player. It says: This
stuff doesn't really make sense, but doesn't it look cool?
</P>
<P>
   There is no real logic in piloting a big robot that has hands
and holds guns. But your MCA (mobile combat armor), a 40-foot
mechanical exoskeleton, doesn't have rocket launchers attached. It
picks up a gun that fires rockets. It walks, even though that makes
no sense either, especially since the vehicle transforms into a
hovercraft.
</P>
<P>
   But that's beside the point. Anime is not about function. It's
all about style. It's about the dark cloud swirling over the raised
fists of a demonic villain. It's about the action heroine's perfect
spiky hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   In Shogo, you see the same stylistic flourishes. ``Instead of
putting the camera in a standard Hollywood place, we might stick it
way under their chin, creating this huge angle,'' said Shogo's
producer, Jason Hall. ``Or like, a lot of times in anime, before a
character destroys another character, they always hit this pose,
and there's a sound, and a little gleam off their sword or
something. So even though it doesn't make sense, we wanted to put
in the poses. And _ this is a perfect example _ when things are
about to explode, the bigger the explosion, the longer they just
sit there and glisten.''
</P>
<P>
   The anime conventions are so over the top _ and so pitch perfect
_ that they throw computer game conventions into high relief. They
set off the cartoonishness of first-person shooters, with their
hyperbolic explosions, surreal lighting effects, landscapes
littered with gigantic firearms and cairns of conveniently placed
ammunition. Dressed up as anime, the first-person shooter becomes
high camp as well. Shogo plays the genre for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   On a military installation, for instance, you run into a crying
woman. She says she lost her kitty cat. Could you please help her
find it? You don't really have time for this because you're on a
seek-and-destroy mission behind enemy lines. But you agree because
this woman controls a crucial access gate. So she hands you the
kitty cat's favorite squeaky toy, and pretty soon you're running
around the military base squeezing this doll that screams, ``Magic
claw! Magic claw!''
</P>
<P>
   Every time you do that, enemies can hear you. So you end up
switching between weapons and the squeaky toy, trying to run down
this cat. Enemy robots turn to face you. Switch to pulse rifle and
blast them to smithereens. Grab the squeaky toy and sprint down the
alley (``magic claw!''). More enemies round the corner. Switch to
laser canon (boom! boom! boom!). Whip out the squeaky toy (``magic
claw!''). Sprint for the cat in John Woo slow motion.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to take Quake seriously after this. But it also makes
you realize that the genre's limitations may be its great strength.
First-person shooters are like sharks. They have stopped evolving
because they work so well. Of course, the production values keep
getting better _ you can always pump up the resolution as
technology improves. But the underlying game play has become a
formula. And that formula is not going to change significantly
because it hits gamers in the right spot (whatever that spot may
be).
</P>
<P>
   We tend to think of this design straightjacket as a liability.
But it may in fact be an asset because it makes the first-person
shooter into a kind of blank canvas for anyone who wants to
experiment with esthetics. If the game mechanics are identical
under the surface, it gives you the opportunity to test the limits
of the skin, the visual surface, and how much difference that can
make.
</P>
<P>
   If enemies are enemies, does it matter what they look like? Does
it make a difference if the enemies are human? What if they're
aliens? What if they're demons from hell? What if they're foreign
soldiers? What if they're terrorists? Cops? Pets? Kids? Because
these images are not structural decisions. They're esthetic
decisions. So the question is: If the basic code is held constant,
do the surface decisions matter, and how much, and to whom?
</P>
<P>
   When does it stop being the same game?
</P>
<P>
   (Shogo; Monolith Productions; CD-ROM for Windows 95; $49.95;
rated M for mature, ages 17 and up.)
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
