<HEADER>
A7224 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-QUAKE-CHAMPION-2T     11-18 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-QUAKE-CHAMPION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAIL-BITING TIME IN THE GAME ARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kurt Shimada is shaking with joy, disbelief and
a twinge of guilt. Moments ago, in the preliminary round of the
computer game championships, he didn't just beat but demolished
Dennis Fong, who happens to be the Michael Jordan of computer
games.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt is unprepared for this good fortune. ``Dude, I'm totally
shaking,'' says this terribly nice 15-year-old, who turns savage
when wielding a mouse-controlled virtual rocket launcher in a game
called Quake II. ``I thought I was going to get spanked.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Professional Gamers' League championships, a
three-day competition to determine the king of the keyboard
jockeys. Until Kurt Shimada came along, Fong had seemed invincible.
But the challenger's victory in the early round has set the stage
for the pair to meet again in a heavyweight showdown here at
Club-i, a downtown cybercafe, amid about 150 spectators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A professional computer game league may sound a bit
contradictory in terms, but there is more than $100,000 at stake
here in cash and prizes _ which makes these games very serious
business. The final match is the culmination of a four-month
regular season, with the earlier rounds having been played entirely
over the Internet. Some 1,700 contestants worldwide were pared down
to 32 finalists in three different games: Quake II, a Quake II team
competition and Starcraft, a strategy game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quake II, a post-apocalyptic shoot-'em-up, is considered the
marquee event, a meeting of the best action players akin to the top
card on fight night. Whether playing over the Internet or here in
the championship, the players sit at separate computers.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting is done by the avatars they control in a virtual
arena on screen. The idea is to roam the arena, more like an
abandoned building, picking up weapons and then hunting down and
killing the other avatar. It's called a ``death match'' _ and it is
where reputations are made and lost. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Fong, 21, has owned these competitions,
earning $100,000 a year in endorsements alone. But the chance for
fame and money has brought talented foes like Kurt Shimada, whose
aim with a weapon called a rail gun is legendary and who is thought
to have a real chance to dethrone Fong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Computer game fans can't contain their excitement over the final
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is incredible,'' says Serena Wong, owner of the Club-i,
as she considers the prospect of a Shimada-Fong final death match.
</P>
<P>
   The Total Entertainment Network, a San Francisco-based Internet
game company, created the Professional Gamers' League (www.pgl.com)
last year, and this is the third championship (a ``season'' lasts
three months). The league is slowly gaining credibility among
gamers and sponsors; it has attracted $2 to $3 million in
sponsorships from high-tech companies that subsidize the contest,
fly out the finalists and pay for the prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Lundberg, executive producer of the league, said he thought
it had the potential to become enormous, because it allowed anyone
to play, whether they are ``weak, short, tall or handicapped.''
There is, however, one clear sticking point: The games are far less
enjoyable for spectators than for players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the final rounds here, the players sit on an elevated stage,
cordoned off from the fans by a rope. Some spectators crane their
necks to watch them, which isn't particularly riveting, since even
in the heat of a pitched battle, only the players' fingers move.
</P>
<P>
   So most spectators watch the frenetic avatars on a big-screen
monitor that hangs from the ceiling, although it is only possible
to see one player's perspective at a time.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the fans _ mostly high-school and college
students _ don't seem to mind a bit. They gasp and scream when
players score a kill. ``Great shot!'' rings out in the room at one
point, as if Evander Holyfield had just hit Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   The die-hard fans can learn about their favorite players from
another trademark of the sporting world: player trading cards. The
cards, which are handed out at the door, include action photos,
biographical information and player aliases like Lord-187,
Mastakilla and the Insane Frog. On the card for Fong, whose
nickname is Thresh, it notes that his hometown is Berkeley, Calif.,
and his favorite weapon is a rocket launcher. His central
processing unit speed? A healthy 400 megahertz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of parents, too, who flew in to watch their
sons take a shot at the title. They seem nervous and hopeful. ``My
guy is Lord-187,'' says Mike Buxton of his 15-year-old son, Mark,
who has come here from Clearwater, Fla. ``On the plane over here, I
told him that no matter what happens, `You're a winner.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tempting as it might be to stereotype the players as
mouse-toting recluses, they don't fit into one mold. True, they are
mostly adolescent boys _ all the competitors in the championship
are males _ and many seem thinner than a PC modem card. But there
are also some good athletes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They come to the tournament with their own equipment: keyboard,
mouse and the ever-important mouse pad. (``You wouldn't go to a
tennis tournament without your own racquet,'' a player explains.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And they are exceedingly friendly. While the games themselves
might be highly violent, the players are more cordial to one
another than combatants in a senior croquet tournament. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say there is no competitive spirit. Players love
to trash-talk over the Internet; during games, the good ones are
quick enough to type in taunts to one another, like ``Come and get
me'' and ``I own you,'' as well as some expletive-charged
epithets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They don't at all like to lose. Iain Girdwood, also known as
TillerMan, appeared quite dejected when he lost both of his first
matches in the preliminary round of the strategy game category,
called Starcraft. Girdwood had been flown in from Scotland to
compete and had been widely considered the favorite in that game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a loser,'' he says, wasting no words. ``Put that in your
article.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The contest occurs against the backdrop of a raging debate here
over whether great video gamers are born or made.
</P>
<P>
   Some players say it is necessary to practice hour upon hour to
become a professional. Those who disagree say Fong is the best
evidence that there is something else is involved in greatness
besides mere practice. In awed tones, some speak of ``Thresh ESP.''
They say Fong has such acute senses he can tell whether another
player is in the Quake II maze even without seeing the player.
</P>
<P>
   Fong himself just shrugs, unable to explain his knack. But
clearly, he has something going for him. He has won the two
previous PGL championships, has netted a red Ferrari in a separate
tournament and in all has taken home hundreds of thousands of
dollars in cash and prizes. He has been written about in countless
national and international magazines.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me know if you want to talk to him,'' says Peter Kim, a
24-year-old friend and business associate of Fong. ``I'm his
agent.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Shimada, whose nickname is Immortal, is a high-school
sophomore from Pleasanton, Calif. He started with Sega in fourth
grade and graduated to computer games when he was 10. He and Fong
have become friendly, despite their rivalry. Nowadays, he says he
practices for only a couple of hours a day. His secret? ``I just
take it one match at a time,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The final game takes place two days after Kurt's initial victory
over Fong, on a Saturday afternoon. The winner will walk away with
$8,500 in cash and a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd is hyped up, which may explain why fisticuffs briefly
broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immortal has great aim, but you can't count Thresh out,'' says
a fired-up Robert Villasana, one of the PGL announcers. ``It's that
close.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kurt says he is feeling good, noting that he has the odds in his
favor. When the king and the kid sit down for the final contest,
Fong will have his work cut out for him. Since the champion had
come through the loser's bracket in the double-elimination
tournament, he would have to beat Kurt twice consecutively to
retain his title.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Kurt sn't sure how he feels about the idea of
dethroning Fong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' he says. ``I want to win really
bad. But he's my friend. I don't want to take everything from
him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he need not have worried. Despite the excitement
engendered by the early upset, it isn't even a contest.
</P>
<P>
   Fong, who _ Thresh ESP notwithstanding _ says he put in hours of
practice after losing to Kurt in the early round, jumps out to an
early lead, and then absolutely crushes the young gun. The final
score is Thresh 46, Immortal 0. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Fong pumps his fist in the air, gives a jubilant
smile and lets out a relaxed exhale. ``I honestly didn't think I
could take him,'' he confides. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, the two players shake hands and exchange supportive
words. Fong tells Kurt not to worry about his future as a
competitive gamer. ``Nobody has aim like him,'' he says.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then Fong is engulfed by well-wishers, several of whom ask him
to autograph his trading card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard so much about him, I just had to see him,'' says
Aaron Melius, who drove more than an hour to attend the match and
is waiting for Fong to sign the card. ``He's the gold standard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
