<HEADLINE>
GEEK NOTES: HI-TECH NEWSWATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Israel)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holiday Shopping on the Web? Probably Not
</P>
<P>
   Americans who let their keyboards do the walking when they go
shopping remain a decided minority, two studies have found. Based
on a survey of 2,500 households, the San Francisco-based marketing
firm Odyssey estimates that 88 percent of all U.S. households won't
buy anything through the Internet this year. Even 57 percent of
families with online access will pass on cyber shopping. ``For all
of the hoopla surrounding E-commerce it is still a retailing method
in its infancy,'' said Nick Donatiello, Odyssey's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Another study by the Boston Consulting Group for Shop.org, an
association of online retailers, used data from 127 vendors and
other sources to calculate that Americans spent $4.4 billion buying
stuff through the Net during the first six months of this year.
That sounds impressive but it represents less than 1 percent of
total retail spending in the country during that period.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with technology consumers' reluctance to send their
credit-card numbers through the Internet are obvious limits to
expanding Internet shopping, both reports indicate. But both
Donatiello and David Pecaut, a senior vice president at Boston
Consulting, say that retailers themselves are often a large part of
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Donatiello is critical of retailers who offer
their goods on the Web at conventional store prices but then tack
on substantial delivery charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that people will just suck up the shipping is just
not so,'' he said. ``That's a cost of doing business like real
estate.''
</P>
<P>
   Pecaut added that many companies still haven't adequately
addressed privacy issues or adopted a ``Good Housekeeping type of
seal of approval'' for their payment systems to ease worries about
security.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ian Austen
</P>
<P>
   Let Your Microphone Be Your Mouse And Sit Back and Relax
</P>
<P>
   It's handy, it's dandy and it's at least four tools in one. No,
not a new Popeil Pocket Fisherman, but a device for your computer
that is a new example of convergence, the morphing of several
separate consumer electronic devices into one.
</P>
<P>
   Called Speech Mike, this slender and ergonomically correct
hand-held device by Philips Electronics is at first glance a
microphone for personal computers, which might be especially useful
as voice-recognition and other speech applications become more
widespread in homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mullen, a Philips spokesman, said the microphone, which
is connected by a cord to a serial port, gives users a ``kick your
feet up laid back'' option to huddling over a computer to speak to
it. It also has a built-in speaker so users can discreetly listen
to the computer from a distance.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Mullen noted, the Speech Mike has a built-in
trackball with left and right click buttons so, again at a
distance, users can control their computers, including browsing the
Internet or given a presentation. The device can also be placed on
a flat surface for use as a conventional mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Speech Mike has been sold only online since the summer, but
is scheduled to arrive on retail shelves early next year and cost
about $70, Mullen said. The Speech Mike Pro, for about $150, will
offer six programmable keys, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mouse is a tool of the '80s, much less the millennium,''
Mullen said. ``This is a tool people are going to be more
comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   Program Notifies You of E-mail As Long as You're Not on the
Phone
</P>
<P>
   Are you eager to know when an important e-mail has arrived but
frustrated at having to repeatedly dial into your Internet service
to check for messages? If so, Mailpush Express might calm your
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   The service, offered by New Email Communications Systems, gives
e-mail users with dial-in modems a feature that's standard
equipment for those constantly connected to the net by T1 lines or
cable modems _ a new mail notice that pops up on their computer
screens. Mailpush's trick is that it works even when its users are
offline.
</P>
<P>
   Users must first register e-mail services vital statistics,
including their password, on NECS' website
(www.express.mailpush.com) before downloading the company's $19.95
software. After that, Mailpush computers automatically check-in
with the customer's ISP every 10 minutes. When the hunt finds new
mail, a phone call to the customer's computer turns on a green mail
logo in their Windows task bar and, if the computer has a sound
card, sets off a voice prompt. To actually read the e-mail, the
customer still must connect dail in to the service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get used to having it, it's a very addictive
service,'' said Zvika Eadan, general manager of NECS, which is
based in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   At least he hopes so, since there is also a monthly charge to
use the service, which Eadan estimated would be about $3.
</P>
<P>
   The system is not flawless. If the modem's phone line is being
used for conversation or faxing, the Mailpush prompt cannot get
through. Also, the current system does not work with popular
Web-based e-mail services, like Yahoo, although NECS plans to
introduce a program for Microsoft's Hotmail shortly.
</P>
<P>
   While Mailpush is just becoming available in the United States,
Eadan said the company had about 12,000 customers in Israel. To his
surprise, a large portion of them are not hyperactive e-mail
addicts but people who get one message every few days. Those long
dry spells had meant that many of them had lost interest in
checking in for messages.
</P>
<P>
   Can't Get Enough Talk on TV and Radio? Try Tuning In to the Web
</P>
<P>
   Talk shows are undeniably successful staples of television and
radio. So it's not surprising that Talkspot is attempting to adapt
the format for the Web. Following the lead of Web-based audio
services offering music, Talkspot (www.talkspot.com) offers four
channels aimed at different tastes that are delivered using Real
Audio.
</P>
<P>
   The topics are familiar to even a casual talk show listener:
astrology, politics (mostly conservative), parenting advice, weight
loss and, on Channel Z, off-color shock jock humor ``where
everything is politically incorrect and proud of it!''
</P>
<P>
   James Golden, Talkspot's vice president for programming and host
of two shows, acknowledged that one potential attraction of Web
talk was that it cannot be curbed by the FCC. ``Much of Channel Z
pushes the borders,'' said Golden, a former producer of Rush
Limbaugh's radio show who appeared on air under the name Bo
Snerdly. ``However, we have standards here too. We do not encourage
the gratuitous use of dirty words.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the site have the option of receiving audio only or
logging into Web pages that display graphics related to a program's
topic along with a primitive video image from the studio. Below,
the page displays a text-based chat room that is mined by the
on-air hosts for comments. As in conventional broadcasting,
listeners can also pitch their views or question guests through
toll-free phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Talkspot is the creation of Ken Williams, the founder and former
chief executive of Sierra On-Line, an interactive gaming service.
His new company plans to sustain its site through advertising and,
according to Golden, plans to offer up to 100 different channels,
mostly from outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sony Offers On-Line Juke Box With Unlimited Play in 24 Hours
</P>
<P>
   The jukebox is back _ on the Internet. Sony Music Online's new
site _ a partnership with RealNetworks Inc. _ has a ``pay as you
play'' structure, allowing users to choose songs and play them
through their computers. The songs selected from the site
(www.sonymusic.com/jukebox) can be played an unlimited number of
times in a 24-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   Users with credit cards can purchase ``tokens'' at 10 for $2.50,
22 for $5 or 50 for $10. The songs (about 200 online currently; up
to 500 promised in the future) are all from the Sony catalog, and
range from pop favorites by Michael Jackson and Bob Dylan to
chestnuts from Mott the Hoople's ``All the Young Dudes'' and
``Nature's Way'' by Spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The site will allow Sony to track users according to time of
day, music type and ZIP code. Sony's vice president for new
technology and business development, David Waldman, said that the
data would be used to determine listening patterns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles Bermant
</P>
<P>
   Another Case of Users Being Way Ahead of the PC Industry
</P>
<P>
   The computer industry has recently been pushing to make its
products also serve as TV sets. Windows 98 was designed to help
support TV drivers and Panasonic and Compaq have just released a
tuner card that even allows PCs to display High Definition
Television programs. Their customers, however, may have already
found a less complicated, often cheaper, answer.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 10,000 homes by Media Matrix, a company that tracks
computer use, discovered that 47 percent of computer users run
their Windows-based PC and have on a television in the same room at
the same time. That's up from 40 percent in a similar survey last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
