<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWDEPUFF-GIRLS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Sugar, spice and Chemical X, that's what Powerpuff Girls are made
of 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have children, you watch Cartoon Network. There are other
kid-centric cable channels you probably check out with your
darlings, such as Nickelodeon or _ have mercy on your soul _ the
Disney Channel. But neither of those has animation on demand, 24-7,
and you, as a parent, never know when you'll need an emergency
cartoon injection to distract your children so you can read a book
or enjoy a parental nerve-calming beverage.
</P>
<P>
   Because you are forced to watch, you appreciate CN's mix of
classic 'toons (''The Tex Avery Show, Scooby-Doo),'' but long for
the new stuff, like ``Johnny Bravo'' or ``Cow and Chicken.'' The
new shows _ especially the network's most popular series,
``Dexter's Laboratory'' _ maintain an arch consciousness that winks
at our cartoonish expectations even as a new generation of bad guys
survives multiple dynamite explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoon Network's latest offering, ``The Powerpuff Girls,''
debuting at 7 tonight, is perhaps the best of the new 'toon breed.
(Sincere apologies go out to rabid fans of the sweet but hopelessly
innocuous ``Rugrats'' on Nickelodeon.) ``TPG'' concerns three
superpowered sisters _ Blossom, Bubbles and Buttercup _ who were
created in the lab by their ``father,'' Professor Utonium, in an
attempt to produce the world's first ``perfect'' little girls. The
prof accidentally added Chemical X to his mixture of sugar, spice
and everything nice, which caused the newly created girls to fight
crime with superhuman powers in addition to their daily Everygirl
routines. Rather serious biogenetic ethical issues aside, this
accidental creation is a blessing for Townsville, USA, which needs
help fighting evil beings like Fuzzy Lumpkins, Him, Roach Coach,
The Boogie Man (a disco-dancing villain) and Mojo Jojo. The show is
perfectly explained by its catch phrase: ``The Powerpuff Girls:
Saving the world before bedtime!''
</P>
<P>
   Like live-action TV shows, cartoons often need time to find
their groove _ witness the Disney Channel's ``Rolie Polie Olie,''
which gets better every week. ``The Powerpuff Girls'' seemingly
will have no such growing pains. From the beginning, the roles are
clear (Blossom is the leader, Bubbles the tomboy, Buttercup the
Barbie-saves-the-whales goody-two-shoes). The humor is right on,
too: silly enough for kids and clever enough for parents. The cute
stuff _ one gal throws Powerpuff punches in her sleep; they fly
through the house to escape getting ready for bed _ is never
cloying. There's even one ``very'' sly, very adult joke in this
week's episode, just as the professor goes off on a date with Ima
Goodlady. (Trust me, the kids won't get it, and it happens so fast,
I had to rewind the tape twice to figure it out.)
</P>
<P>
   This is creator/writer/producer Craig McCracken's second
breakout hit for Cartoon Network, although he only served as art
director for ``Dexter's Laboratory.'' The 27-year-old took the idea
for ``The Powerpuff Girls'' from his student short, ``The Whoopa--
Girls.'' The series' title may be a little more benign, but the
finished product is not.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7280 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDICIARY-IMPEACH-HNS     11-18 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDICIARY-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
   CURTAIN RISES ON IMPEACHMENT HEARINGS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid bitter partisan rancor, the House on Thursday
opens long-awaited impeachment hearings against President Clinton
for alleged perjury and obstruction of justice in the Monica
Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr was scheduled as the day's
lone witness before the House Judiciary Committee. The majority
Republicans may meet Friday to decide whether to call additional
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Alternating scenarios with different configurations of witnesses
have marked the confused Republican planning for the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., and other
Republicans have urged Judiciary Committee Chairman Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., to call other key figures in the Lewinsky matter,
including Clinton's personal secretary Betty Currie, White House
lawyer Bruce Lindsey and presidential confidant Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible witness urged by some Republicans was John
Huang, former Democratic National Committee fundraiser who was at
the center of congressional probes into financing Clinton's 1996
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   After opening statements by Hyde and Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich.,
the top Democrat on the committee, Starr gets the floor for up to
two hours to address the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Starr then will be questioned by Republican committee lawyers,
White House lawyers and then each of the committee's 37 members _
21 Republicans and 16 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is expected to go well outside the four corners of
Clinton's efforts to hide his 18-month relationship with Lewinsky
and instead will try to show that Clinton's conduct in the Lewinsky
affair was part of a wider pattern of presidential obstruction of
Starr's investigation, which began in 1994 as a look at Bill and
Hillary Clinton's roles as investors in the ill-fated Whitewater
land development scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told reporters he wouldn't stop Starr from ranging beyond
the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I?'' Hyde asked. ``Because the Democrats would like
that? The Democrats want to stick to Monica Lewinsky. We want to
look at everything. That's the big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Democrats left no doubt they intend to shift
attention away from Clinton's behavior and focus their fire on
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr's conduct and the actions of his staff bear directly on
credibility of the inquiry itself,'' said Jim Jordan, spokesman for
Judiciary Committee Democrats. There are serious questions about
the investigation and about how the issue ended up in Starr's
office in the first place, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said Democrats would ask Starr about allegations that he
or his aides threatened Lewinsky; leaked grand jury materials; were
in contact with lawyers representing Paula Jones in her sexual
harassment civil lawsuit against Clinton; and started investigating
the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship before obtaining court
authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charged that the last-minute uncertainty about the
witness list illustrated how Republicans were in disarray in the
face of polls showing little public enthusiasm for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``thought they were going to ride this impeachment
horse all the way home, (but) the horse is now in terrible shape,''
said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a Judiciary member. ``They've got
two choices: They can shoot it and send it to the dog-food factory,
or they can paint stripes on it and tell everyone its a zebra... I
don't think they know yet what they're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, at least, Republicans said they would focus on
Starr's Sept. 9 report to Congress citing 11 grounds for
impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to hearing Ken Starr's side of the
investigation,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, a Judiciary
member. ``The administration and its spokespeople have savaged Ken
Starr daily and ... he has not been allowed to speak publicly about
what he has found. So, for the first time he will be able to speak
for himself and speak candidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith dismissed Democratic plans to put Starr on trial Thursday
and charges of faulty GOP leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence Ken Starr will successfully keep the focus
on whether the president committed impeachable crimes,'' he said.
``I'm sure the Democrats would like to change the subject, but
there's only one subject at hand: Whether the president committed
these crimes or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Other GOP members of the committee expressed concern about
Starr's ability to withstand the expected Democratic barrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough forum for Starr,'' said Hutchinson.
``The Democrats are champing at the bit for this opportunity and
it's going to be hard for him to look good.''
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the White House on Wednesday conceded defeat
in its effort to expand the time its lawyers would have Thursday to
question Starr. After receiving Hyde's initial offer of 30 minutes,
White House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff on Tuesday insisted the time
be expanded to 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde turned down the request. On Wednesday, Ruff sent Hyde a
letter saying ``we will proceed within the time allotted'' even
though in his view 30 minutes ``is not consistent with the standard
of fairness that the committee has sought to achieve.'' The
president's personal lawyer, David Kendall, will use that slot to
question Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told reporters Wednesday he would be ``liberal and
tolerant'' in extending the White House's cross-examination period,
``if they're on a line of questioning and they need more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, the committee's chief counsel, Tom Mooney,
wrote to Ruff imploring him to respond to a list of 81
Lewinsky-related questions sent by Hyde to Clinton on Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a promise to get the answers back to the committee by
Nov. 13, the White House has failed to forward them, Mooney wrote.
``We are dismayed that you have missed your own self-imposed
deadline,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week Starr has delivered additional boxes of
evidence to the committee. One set involves Kathleen Willey, the
former White House volunteer who claimed Clinton kissed and groped
her during an Oval Office encounter in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The other involves Webster Hubbell, former Justice Department
official and close Clinton pal indicted last week for lying to
Congress and federal banking regulators about work he did for the
now-insolvent Madison Guaranty Savings &AMP; Loan, owned by Clinton
Whitewater partner James McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Hubbell and Willey documents could prove to be wild
cards in the hearings, though it was unclear whether either case
would come up at all.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday will mark only the third time in U.S. history that the
House Judiciary Committee has conducted an impeachment inquiry into
the actions of a president. The previous occasions were the 1867
and 1868 proceedings against President Andrew Johnson and the 1974
hearings on President Nixon's role in the Watergate scandal.
</P>
</TEXT>
