A7321 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIAL-AROUND-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     11-18 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAL-AROUND-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... consumer group.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She warns consumers to make sure they understand the particulars
of individual dial-around services, which now come with a wide
array of terms and conditions. Some are better for longer calls but
worse on short calls. A few dial-around carriers push very low
rates but require minimum calling times. Some have higher weekday
daytime rates and others special promotions, in which calls made
before Jan. 1 are cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 15-minute weekend call between Boston and Los
Angeles costs $1.94 using 10-10-321 (12 cents for the first minute
and 13 cents for each additional minute). But it would cost only 99
cents with 10-10-220 (which bills 99 cents for the first 20
minutes, then 10 cents for each additional minute).
</P>
<P>
   The same weekend call using an AT&AMP;T Simple Minute Plan (10 cents
a minute no matter how long the call), costs $1.50.  &UR;  &LR; However, AT&AMP;T
and MCI are promoting calling plans charging 5 cents a minute on
Sundays. So the bi-coastal call, if made on Sunday, would total
only 75 cents, but the calling plan carries a $4.95 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   For callers who make infrequent daytime weekday calls, but stay
on the phone a while, dial-around can be less expensive. For
example, a 30-minute weekday call with 10-10-321 (27 cents for the
first minute and 28 cents a minute afterward) &UR;  &LR; costs  &UR;  &LR; $8.39. But
with 10-10-220, it costs only $1.99. AT&AMP;T will charge $7.50 under
its Simple Minute Plan for the same call.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Jacobs, who spends about $45 a month on long-distance calls
to the West Coast and Washington, D.C., through an AT&AMP;T calling
plan, says he fears that dial-around services have too many hidden
charges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Consumers should not be misled into believing that quick-fix
`10-10' numbers are a substitute for researching which
long-distance plan offers the best savings,'' adds Scott M.
Stringer, a New York State assembly member from Manhattan. He plans
to file legislation in Albany requiring that all 10-10 services
play a recorded message before each call is connected, providing
full disclosure of rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee Group estimates that nearly 40 percent of all
dial-around users are in the 45- to 64-year-old age group and about
25 percent of the callers have incomes under $25,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular of the dial-around services is 10-10-321 from
Telecom USA, a subsidiary of MCI. &UR;  &LR; That service is also the most
expensive among dial-arounds for calls shorter than 20 minutes. Its
time-of-day rates, which vary on weekdays and weekends, are
slightly lower than AT&AMP;T's basic rates, but signficantly higher
than either Lucky Dog or New Dimeline, which charge 10 cents a
minute for interstate calls any time.
</P>
<P>
   For calls up to 20 minutes, Telecom USA's newest dial-around
service _ 10-10-220 _ charges 99 cents for a 20-minute call, or a
low 5 cents a minute. However, if you dial the wrong number or get
an answering machine, you still spend 99 cents.
</P>
<P>
   MCI's success with 10-10-321 prompted AT&AMP;T, which had once
dismissed the dial-around business, to hastily enter the market
last month with the introduction of its Lucky Dog 10-10-345
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did not think customers would spend the time to dial
the extra digits,'' says Howard McNally, president of Lucky Dog,
the AT&AMP;T subsidiary whose 10-10 rates are low enough to siphon
customers from the company's established calling plans.
</P>
<P>
   Adds his boss, C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T chairman, ``We were
simply late.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
