</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV22-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POLITICS, THE NAME OF THE GAME IS OFTEN THE NAME ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 22)   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chances are the contest for the presidency in 2000
will be a showdown between the son of a former U.S. senator,
wearing the Democratic label, and the son of a former U.S.
president, wearing the Republican insignia.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans long ago severed our ties with English royalty and
rejected the granting of titles of nobility. But we continue to be
enthralled by political dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in a name?'' the fair Juliet asked an ardent Romeo.
``That which we call a rose by any other name would smell as
sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Juliet's concern was the bloody rivalry between her family, the
Capulets, and Romeo's family, the Montagues, in Italy nearly 700
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since there was no America then, she could not have imagined the
kind of politics in which the name of the game very often is the
name itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming presidential showdown, the two leading
contestants, Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee and George W. Bush of
Texas, are attractive, talented baby boomers whose fathers preceded
them as victors at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father and namesake, Vice President Al Gore served in
the House and Senate. Governor Bush's father also was a congressman
and served in such important appointive posts as Republican Party
chairman, CIA director and U.S. envoy to China before becoming
Ronald Reagan's vice president in 1981 and president in 1989.
President Bush's father, Prescott Bush, was a senator from
Connecticut in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes. There are few more important legacies in politics
than a strong bloodline.
</P>
<P>
   In this century, our two most illustrious dynasties have been
the Roosevelts and the Kennedys. It would appear, however, that
they may be joined by the Bushes, whose current generation also
includes the governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 3 election saw three other prominent families replenish
their hold on public office.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio Robert A. Taft III was elected governor. In Colorado and
New Mexico two young men bearing the name of one of Arizona's most
distinguished families, Udall, were elected to Congress. In
Indiana, Evan Bayh, a former governor and son of onetime senator
and presidential hopeful Birch Bayh, was elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Taft's great grandfather, William Howard Taft, and his
grandfather, Robert A. Taft, both were embroiled earlier in the
century in ideological battles that threatened to tear the
Republican Party to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1912, when William Howard Taft was nearing the end of his
four-year term as president, his onetime mentor and close friend,
Theodore Roosevelt, challenged him for the GOP nomination. Taft won
that fight, but Roosevelt ran on the Progressive ticket and split
the Republican Party. The result: Democrat Woodrow Wilson won the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, Taft's son Robert, an Ohio senator known
universally as ``Mr. Republican,'' launched his third bid for the
presidency. But his staunchly conservative, isolationist policies
were anathema to moderate Republicans, who persuaded the popular
Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower to run.
</P>
<P>
   In a bitter showdown, Eisenhower won the GOP nomination and the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The Udall prominence in Arizona began with Levi Udall, who
served as chief justice of the state supreme court. His eldest son,
Stewart, served in the House in the 1950s. When John F. Kennedy was
elected president, he became Interior secretary and held that post
for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   When Stewart Udall moved to the Cabinet, his brother Morris, a
former professional basketball player known as ``Mo,'' won the
seat. He later became chairman of the House Interior Committee and
an unsuccessful aspirant for the Democratic presidential nomination
in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stewart's son Tom is a congressman-elect from New Mexico
and Mo's son Mark enjoys similar status in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   After a successful eight-year tenure as governor of Indiana,
Evan Bayh will take over a Senate seat previously held by
Republicans, including Dan Quayle. Bayh could one day become a
presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   New York Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's announcement
that he will retire in two years has sparked speculation that one
of the contenders for his seat will be Housing Secretary Andrew
Cuomo, whose father Mario served three terms as governor and whose
wife Kerry is a Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   There now is a Kennedy in the Senate, in the House and in the
lieutenant governorhip of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   But being the son or daughter of a distinguished family does not
guarantee success at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, Hubert Humphrey III, son of the former vice
president and 1968 Democratic presidential nominee, won the party's
gubernatorial nomination this year over the sons of two of his
father's closest allies, former senator and 1984 presidential
nominee Walter Mondale and former governor and U.S. agriculture
secretary Orville Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   But being nominated is not the same as being elected. When the
votes were counted in Minnesota, neither Humphrey nor his
Republican opponent, Norm Coleman, had the governorship. The winner
was Jesse Ventura, a colorful onetime professional wrestler who ran
as a tax-cutting, antigovernment libertarian.
</P>
<P>
   Dynasties, like everything else in our lives, eventually die
out.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Roosevelt family produced two of the most dynamic
presidents in our history, Republican Theodore and Democrat
Franklin, none of the current generation is active in public
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Other dynasties have all but vanished: the Lodges of
Massachusetts, the Stevensons of Illinois, the Longs of Louisiana,
the Byrds of Virginia and the Talmadges of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But in politics a rose by any other name still does not smell as
sweet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
