<HEADLINE>
KEY EVENTS IN CLINTON INQUIRY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)    &HT;    WASHINGTON _ Key events in the investigation of allegations that
President Clinton tried to cover up his sexual misbehavior at the
White House:
 &HT;      
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Nov. 29, 1993: &LR;  President Clinton meets privately near Oval
Office with Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jan. 20, 1994: &LR;  Robert Fiske appointed as independent counsel
to investigate Whitewater land dealings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; May 6, 1994: &LR;  Paula Jones files a sexual harassment lawsuit
alleging her career as a state clerk suffered when she rebuffed a
crude sexual advance by Clinton when he was governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aug. 5, 1994: &LR;  A a panel of three federal appeals court judges
appoints Kenneth Starr to take over Fiske's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nov. 15, 1995: &LR;  Clinton and White House intern Monica Lewinsky
begin a sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; May 27, 1997: &LR;  The Supreme Court rules Jones can pursue her
sexual harassment lawsuit while Clinton is in office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dec. 5, 1997: &LR;  Lewinsky named on a list of potential witnesses
in Jones' lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dec. 19, 1997: &LR;  Lewinsky subpoenaed to appear at deposition for
the Jones suit and to turn over gifts from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jan. 7, 1998 &LR; : Lewinsky signs affidavit for Jones case saying
she had no sexual relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jan. 12: &LR;  Linda Tripp gives Starr's office secretly taped
conversations with Lewinsky, who confided in Tripp about her affair
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   J &UR; an. 16: &LR;  Starr authorized to investigate Lewinsky matters.
Prosecutors confront Lewinsky and unsuccessfully seek her
cooperation. Tripp briefs Jones' legal team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jan. 17: &LR;  Clinton testifies in Jones' lawsuit and denies a
sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jan. 26: &LR;  On national television from the White House, Clinton
says: ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman. ... I
never told anybody to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jan. 27: &LR;  Starr opens a grand jury inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; March 15: &LR;  Willey appears on CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes,'' saying
Clinton fondled her during 1993 meeting adjacent to the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; April 1 &LR; : Jones' lawsuit is dismissed by U.S. District Judge
Susan Webber Wright.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; July 17: &LR;  Prosecutors issue subpoena for Clinton's testimony
before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; July 28: &LR;  Lewinsky is given immunity from prosecution in
exchange for her agreement to testify.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; July 29: &LR;  Clinton agrees to testify from the White House, and
prosecutors withdraw the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aug. 6: &LR;  Lewinsky testifies to the grand jury for six hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aug. 17: &LR;  Clinton undergoes more than four hours of questioning
before a federal grand jury. He says in a nationally broadcast
speech, ``I did have a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky that was not
appropriate. ... I misled people, including even my wife. I deeply
regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aug. 20: &LR;  Lewinsky testifies again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sept. 9: &LR;  Starr delivers to the House of Representatives 36
boxes of documents outlining what he calls ``substantial and
credible information ... that may constitute grounds for
impeachment'' of the president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sept. 11: &LR;  The House votes to release Starr's report to the
public. The White House issues a rebuttal in advance of the
release.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oct. 8: &LR;  House votes to authorize an impeachment investigation
by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oct. 20: &LR;  Three judges of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
hear arguments in Jones' appeal for reinstatement of her lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nov. 3: &LR;  Republicans in mid-term elections lose five House
seats to the Democrats. Exit polls show almost two-thirds of voters
don't want Clinton impeached.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nov. 9: &LR;  House Judiciary Committee holds hearing at which
scholars offer contrasting view of what constitutes an impeachable
offense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nov. 9: &LR;  The Supreme Court refuses to shield Clinton's closest
adviser, Bruce Lindsey, from prosecutors' questions about his
conversations with the president. The court also refuses to shield
Secret Service officers, several of whom already testified, from
being asked what they overheard while protecting the president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nov. 13: &LR;  Clinton agrees to pay Jones $850,000 to drop her
sexual harassment lawsuit. Starr delivers material to House about
his investigation of the Willey incident.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nov. 17: &LR;  Starr delivers material to House about his
investigation of Webster Hubbell, who investigators suspect took
money from presidential supporters to remain silent about Clinton's
role in Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
