<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      11-18 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: SPOLETO FESTIVAL USA; GLIMMERGLASS OPERA PREMIERE;
MORE THAN A MUSE TO PICASSO; CAROL BURNETT TROVE TO UCLA; AMERICAN
ACADEMY OF ARTS AND LETTERS CENTENARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., S.C.)  (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winter hasn't arrived yet, but in Charleston, S.C., spring _ in
the form of the Spoleto Festival USA _ is just around the corner.
Nigel Redden, the general director of the 23rd festival, from May
28 to June 13, is already announcing its highlights, including the
opening attraction, ``Il Trittico,'' Puccini's triple bill of
one-act operas. The first weekend will also bring the U.S. premiere
of Kurt Weill's opera ``Die Burgschaft,'' and the festival has
commissioned a new work by the performance artist Laurie Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Upper Registry
</P>
<P>
   Where can you find ``Central Park'' (note those quotation marks)
next summer? Try Cooperstown, N.Y., where the Glimmerglass Opera
will offer the world premiere of a work of that title. Consisting
of three one-act operas unified by their setting, it opens July 24.
The librettos are by the playwrights Terrence McNally, Wendy
Wasserstein and A.R. Gurney, and the scores are by Robert Beaser,
Deborah Drattell and Michael Torke. The production, directed by
Mark Lamos, is headed for the New York City Opera in the 1999-2000
season. The Glimmerglass season opens on July 1 with a new staging
of Mozart's ``Abduction From the Seraglio,'' followed by a new
production of Verdi's ``Rigoletto'' and Monteverdi's rarely staged
``Ritorno d'Ulisse in Patria.''
</P>
<P>
   More Maar
</P>
<P>
   Before Dora Maar became model and muse for Pablo Picasso after
their meeting in 1936, she was an established photographer and an
acknowledged member of the Surrealist movement. In Paris on Friday,
Dora Maar's photographs will be auctioned at Drouot-Montaigne. Next
Thursday, her paintings will be sold at an auction called
``L''Atelier de Dora Maar.''
</P>
<P>
   Gift of Laughter
</P>
<P>
   Carol Burnett has donated 145 videotapes to UCLA containing some
290 episodes of ``The Carol Burnett Show,'' which was broadcast on
CBS from 1967 to 1978 and won 25 Emmy Awards. She also donated
scripts and music from the show and other Burnett vehicles, like
the musical ``Once Upon a Mattress.''
</P>
<P>
   Time's March
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an exhibition beginning Thursday, the American
Academy of Arts and Letters will celebrate its 100-year history and
its collection. On view in the show, ``A Century of Arts and
Letters: The Centennial Exhibition of the American Academy of Arts
and Letters,'' are a Mark Twain manuscript; correspondence from
Tennessee Williams and Dorothy Parker; paintings by Childe Hassam
and William Merritt Chase; and letters to the academy from Thomas
Eakins, e.e. cummings and Gore Vidal rejecting election to
membership. The exhibition at the academy, on Audubon Terrace at
633 W. 155th St., continues through Dec. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
