<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHARTON-PLAY-TEX     11-18 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHARTON-PLAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE AMERICAN EXPATRIATE PLAYS ANOTHER: GAYLE HUNNICUTT AS EDITH
WHARTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Edith Wharton was little more than a name in
an American Lit textbook to Gayle Hunnicutt when the latter was a
Kappa Kappa Gamma at Texas Christian University during the
mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton, who lived from 1862 to 1937, was an American who
resided mostly in Europe while writing incisive novels about the
Manhattan upper class she was born into. Hunnicutt, Fort
Worth-born, left TCU for UCLA and Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   At UCLA, Hunnicutt was coached and encouraged by legendary
director Jean Renoir _ who may or may not have counseled her to
mask her natural warmth with patrician aloofness. In any case,
Hunnicutt adopted that device in some film portrayals, and it
served her well. Her initial Hollywood phase (1968-73) paired the
Texas newcomer with such stars as George Peppard (''P.J.''), James
Garner (''Marlowe'') and Michael Sarrazin (''Eye of the Cat'').
</P>
<P>
   A move to London in 1969, with then-husband David Hemmings,
slowed her Hollywood output, but the 1980s found Hunnicutt in at
least one memorable big-screen opus: ``Target,'' in which director
Arthur Penn cast her as the abducted wife of Gene Hackman and
mother of Matt Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   SUNRISE, SUNSET: Gayle Hunnicutt is back on campus portraying
Edith Wharton in a sagacious and witty play titled ``The Life and
Loves of Edith Wharton.'' It was performed at TCU on Nov. 15 at 8
p.m. as part of a regional conference.
</P>
<P>
   The show will travel to the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New
York Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   A key element of the play is Wharton's friendship with author
Henry James, also an American who spent the bulk of his creative
life abroad. Portraying James and other men (and women) in
Wharton's life is English actor Frank Barrie, an alumnus of the
Bristol Old Vic and of the National Theatre under the artistic
directorship of Sir Laurence Olivier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank and I go back to 1977, when we did `Twelfth Night' and
`The Admirable Crichton,' '' Hunnicutt said. ``I always asked Frank
to come to shows I've been involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   She asked him to have a look at ``Edith Wharton at Home,'' an
earlier play in which Hunnicutt starred. The look led to ``The Life
and Loves of Edith Wharton,'' which Barrie wrote _ working from
research and a first draft by Katrina Hendry. It premiered in 1994
at England's Chichester Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie is also the director of ``Life and Loves.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrie prowled the stage one afternoon last week, stroking his
chin like a road company Sherlock Holmes as he visualized various
ways to reblock his staging. He concluded:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to busk it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Wing it, he meant, like the buskers who entertain for theater
queues in Britain.)
</P>
<P>
   Barrie and Hunnicutt are superb together in ``Life and Loves''
(which also played in Austin early this month). The loving
friendship of Wharton and James is realized particularly well. In
addition to their literary link, the two shared a devout and
unabashed snobbery about their native country. Consider this
exchange in the play:
</P>
<P>
   EDITH: ``The American landscape has no foreground.''
</P>
<P>
   HENRY: ``Yes, and the American mind has no background.''
</P>
<P>
   Married since 1978 to English journalist Simon Jenkins,
Hunnicutt works regularly in her second homeland. A particularly
important project for her was the 1972 dramatization of Henry
James' ``The Golden Bowl,'' which Hunnicutt did for BBC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``That production really launched my career in Britain,'' she
said. ``Later I spent my honeymoon night at Lamb House in Rye,
where James wrote `The Golden Bowl.' So I seem to have the links in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although James was Wharton's literary mentor, he was not her
equal in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was known as the master, but he didn't sell very well,''
Hunnicutt said. ``And Edith sold phenomenally well. She was a
best-selling author from the very beginning of her literary career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end of her life she was sometimes known as `Miss'
Edith Wharton. She was very offended by that. She so did not want
any touch of spinsterhood to be attached to her reputation. She so
wanted people to know she had had a sexual life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Edith's sexual self was not as Mrs. Edward Wharton. It was
as the lover of Morton Fullerton, an awakening that occurred when
the novelist was 46.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very odd to live to age 46, and have been married since
you were in your 20s and are a virgin,'' Hunnicutt said. ``We do
very much touch on that in the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting when you read her novels to understand how
anyone could write so profoundly about the human heart and human
relationships who had come from such a strangulated world of that
old Dutch New York side, who looked down on the Astors and the
Vanderbilts as the nouveau riche.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much the world she writes about. She was Edith
Newbold Jones. The expression, `keeping up with the Joneses,' comes
from her family.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
