<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Nov. 19. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-REPUBS (Washington) _ Congressional Republicans select
their leaders: Livingston as speaker; Armey as majority leader, on
a third ballot; and Delay, who was unopposed, as whip. By Katharine
Q. Seeley.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ On the eve of the high-stakes
appearance of Kenneth Starr before the House Judiciary Committee,
House Republicans are expressing anguish, doubts and outright
opposition to the panel's inquiry, which the public overwhelmingly
wants it to end. With only an 11-vote margin in the current
Congress, which will dwindle to six votes in the next Congress, it
would take only a few other Republicans among those who say they
are wavering to kill any chance of impeaching Clinton. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ (Washington) _ After stepping back from a massive bombing
campaign of Iraq, the United States and Britain are redoubling
their support for Iraqi opposition groups as an alternative means
of ousting the Iraqi dictator, but administration officials say the
existing dissident organizations are weak, divided and, in many
cases, thoroughly penetrated by Iraqi agents. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PHARMACEUTICALS (Beijing) _ Imported Western
pharmaceuticals have taken China by storm, straining pocketbooks as
they hold out promises of cure. Sales have been bouyed by a new and
unlikely symbiosis: Western drug companies have been aggressively
courting China's doctors and hospitals not only with new pills but
also with gifts, money and even kickbacks, practices that are often
banned in the United States. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   LIVENT (New York) _ Livent Inc., the Broadway theater company,
filed for bankruptcy protection Wednesday, just six months after
the company was taken over by Michael Ovitz, the former Hollywood
talent agent. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
