<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-KURDS-NYT &LR;      11-18 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-KURDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY, TURKEY AT ODDS OVER EXTRADITION OF KURDISH REBEL  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Italy's refusal to extradite a Kurdish rebel leader
wanted by Turkey has soured relations between the normally close
allies, and as government leaders in Rome and Ankara traded angry
words Wednesday, the United States added to the pressure by also
calling for extradition of the Kurd, Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he should be extradited and brought to justice,''
the State Department spokesman, James Rubin, said in Washington
Wednesday. ``And we hope a way will be found to extradite him to
Turkey, consistent with international and Italian law.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema has been in a quandary over what
to do with Ocalan, leader of the separatist Kurdistan Workers
Party, since he was arrested last week trying to enter Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Italian law forbids the extradition of prisoners to countries
that have a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But D'Alema, a former Communist, is also under pressure from
leftists in his coalition to grant Ocalan political asylum. He has
not ruled it out, saying instead that if Ocalan's pledges to
renounce terrorism are sincere, Italy will consider his case.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey views Ocalan as a terrorist. Wednesday, Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz told the Turkish Parliament that if Italy fails to
extradite Ocalan, ``not only will it remain as a stain on their
record but they will become accomplices to every murder ever
committed'' by the Kurdistan Workers Party.
</P>
<P>
   Yilmaz added, ``No government of the Turkish republic would ever
forget this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night D'Alema sternly rebutted Yilmaz. Calling the
comment on Italy ``unacceptable,'' D'Alema said: ``Italy does not
justify terrorism and will not be an accomplice to it. Those who
dare to make this link are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan, who is being held in an undisclosed hospital near Rome,
was adding his own form of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have abandoned terrorism and are ready for a peace
accord,'' he wrote to the daily newspaper La Repubblica in answer
to the newspaper's written questions. ``My presence here testifies
to a change in the strategy of the Kurdish national movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Angry demonstrations for and against Ocalan have spread across
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year-old Kurd set himself on fire Wednesday in Rome. In
Moscow on Tuesday, two supporters of the rebel leader set
themselves on fire; one died. The other protester in Moscow and the
man in Rome were hospitalized. Kurdish demonstrators in Turkey also
set themselves on fire this week.
</P>
<P>
   Passions also run high on the other side. In Brussels, Turkish
demonstrators set fire to two houses in a neighborhood with many
Kurdish residents. Italian television Wednesday night showed
Turkish demonstrators in Istanbul holding rallies, burning Kurdish
flags and calling for a boycott of Italian goods, including Versace
and Armani designer clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Italy, which exported $3.14 billion worth of goods to Turkey in
the first nine months of this year, could ill afford such a
boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Any hope the Italian government harbored that Germany would take
Ocalan off its hands, moreover, has dimmed. Germany, which issued a
warrant for Ocalan's arrest on homicide charges in 1990, has not
requested his extradition, which Italy could more easily grant
because Germany has no death penalty. But Germany has a huge
Turkish population and a strong Kurdish one, and is apparently
reluctant to make a move that would inevitably generate fresh
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night D'Alema hinted that he felt isolated and would
welcome some support from his European colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about Italy and Turkey,'' the prime minister said.
``It involves all of Europe, from which we expect total solidarity.
We've already gotten signs of encouragement, and we are expecting
more tangible political gestures.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GATORS-COX     11-18 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GATORS AND SPURRIER
 &HT;    ATTN: SPORTS EDITORS
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE _ Imagine being a traffic cop at rush hour in
Manhattan or a commodities trader during a big sell-off on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Now double this amount of anxiety and you have an idea of what
it's like to be near Florida coach Steve Spurrier every time the
Gators have the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very stressful time,'' receivers coach Dwayne Dixon
said. ``And you do it about 70 times every game.''
</P>
<P>
   The process starts and ends with Spurrier, who, even before the
play is over, is thinking about his next call. Once he knows the
down and distance, he quickly decides on a formation and a play.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier then verbally gives the call to backup quarterback
Billy Young, who sends in the information to quarterback Doug
Johnson using strange-looking hand signals. Meanwhile, Dixon
handles substitutions by telling which players to go in and holding
up a card with a number to tell which player/players to come out.
</P>
<P>
   All this, in about 15 seconds. That way, Johnson has time to
change the play at the line of scrimmage _ with Spurrier's help, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty chaotic,'' said Young, who's been sending in the
signals the past two seasons. ``When I first started, it was pretty
intense because everything was going so fast. Now that I've done it
a while, it doesn't seem like it's too fast; it's just the way we
do things.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier prefers to look at the system as organized chaos. He
says for it to work, one thing must happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's crucial is the quarterback knows the plays,'' Spurrier
said. ``Once we get started, he can anticipate what's coming next.
That's what's been happening with Doug the last few games.''
</P>
<P>
   The art of sending in plays from the sideline takes on a more
special meaning Saturday when the fourth-ranked Gators travel to
No. 5 Florida State, with a shot at the national title possibly on
the line. Because these teams know each other so well _ this will
be their seventh meeting in the past five years thanks to a pair of
rematches in the Sugar Bowl _ trying to make sure the defense also
doesn't know the signals is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   This issue was avoided last year when Spurrier rotated Johnson
and Noah Brindise at quarterback, eliminating the need for Young as
the middle man. Even so, Johnson suspected FSU's cornerbacks had
stolen their audible calls, so with FSU leading 29-25 late in the
game, Johnson used a hand signal for Jacquez Green to run a curl _
then deftly added another hand motion to change it to a
curl-and-go. The play resulted in a 63-yard pass that set up Fred
Taylor's winning touchdown in Florida's 32-29 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go to some phony audibles if we think the other team
knows our signals,'' Spurrier said. ``I don't know how much they
(FSU) know our signals. Obviously, we have been playing them for
nine years now and our signals haven't changed much.''
</P>
<P>
   But expect the Gators to tweak their signals Saturday. They
could have two players signal in the plays (one would send in
``dummy'' signals), or they could have more players stand near
Young to block the view from the FSU sideline, or they could add
different signals for just this game.
</P>
<P>
   All of which adds some pressure to Young, a 5-foot-8 junior who
is UF's fourth-string quarterback. With some of the weird motions
he has to make, he had better have a good memory and a small ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put in a funny signal for LSU last year, and my mom saw it
and thought I was brushing my teeth,'' Young said. ``My friends
think I'm doing aerobics.''
</P>
<P>
   The process doesn't end after Young has signalled in the play.
Spurrier studies the defensive alignment once his team reaches the
line of scrimmage and will either motion for Johnson to run the
play or yell for an audible. Actually, Dixon is the one yelling
because his baritone voice is much louder than Spurrier's
high-pitched Tennessee twang, which will come in handy Saturday at
deafening Doak Campbell Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you can do that a lot easier at home or at stadiums
like Vandy, that are real quiet,'' Spurrier said of his sideline
audibles. ``But, shoot, we yelled a bunch of them in at the
Superdome (in '96 when Gators beat FSU 52-20 to win the national
title).''
</P>
<P>
   Once the audible is yelled in, Spurrier can relax. For about
three seconds. Then the pressure-packed process starts all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
