<HEADER>
A7565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GODOT-THEATER-REVIEW-     11-18 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODOT-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WAITING FOR GODOT': TIPTOEING MOURNFULLY THROUGH A CEMETERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at the end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Vladimir and Estragon of Andrei Belgrader's
elegiac new production of ``Waiting for Godot'' are so aware of the
proximity of death that it seems at times as if they're tiptoeing
between cemetery plots.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's bleak masterpiece is in fact partly a meditation on
the tragic brevity of life: ``They give birth astride of a grave,
the light gleams an instant, then it's night once more,'' goes the
haunting line spoken by the slaveowner Pozzo to the famous hobos
trapped in that notorious no man's land, waiting day after day for
the redeemer who never comes.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Shalhoub and John Turturro, playing Vladimir and Estragon
in the Classic Stage Company's solemn revival of this actors'
favorite, which opened Wednesday night, take these words as gospel.
As a result, this ``Godot'' is one mournful waiting room. Their
tramps are conscious at all times of the gravity of their
existential plight: no statement is expressed without careful
forethought, no action undertaken that does not imply sober
contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   When, for instance, Turturro's Estragon attempts the task of
removing his tight boot, his acrobatics are as painstakingly
plotted as those of a Cirque du Soleil contortionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting for Godot'' unfortunately can invite a certain
sobriety. It's an elliptical tragicomedy that wrestles with really
Big Questions, like the meaning of everything; think of Nietzsche
and Einstein up there, doing two and a half hours of stand-up. The
danger for actors is becoming too enamored of the play's
big-picture concerns about existence, when it's the challenges of
everyday existence, like finding a pair of comfortable boots, that
are what keep us entertained, if you will, that keep us from
thinking too much about life's essential absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   Shalhoub and Turturro, thoughtful, sensitive stage actors who
have found success on television and in the movies, seem humbled by
Beckett's mysterious play. In Belgrader's reverential
interpretation, they display the symptoms of a severe case of
significance. It's not fatal to the production: both deliver
admirably pared-down portrayals, devoid of famous-actor's ego. But
the quasi-religious tone does tend to s-s-l-l-o-o-w-w things down
quite a bit, especially in a protracted first act that almost seems
a real-time re-enactment of the tramps' eternal vigil.
</P>
<P>
   When they pick up the pace in the second act, when at last Didi
and Gogo, as they call one another, embrace and gaze into each
other's eyes and really converse, ``Godot'' not only quickens, it
becomes sharper and more amusing. For although Belgrader is intent
on a faithful reproduction, his overly academic approach up to then
has taken a lot of the snap out of the play and makes that barren
country road, adorned by a single naked tree, seem a pretty windy
place.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Godot'' is the first offering by Classic Stage under its
new artistic director, Barry Edelstein, who directed a much-admired
``All My Sons'' for the Williamstown Theater Festival and the
Roundabout Theater Company. Clearly, Edelstein is making a
statement, setting off with a play that ranked in a recent Royal
National Theater poll as one of the most important dramas of the
20th century. And he is to be commended for beginning his tenure by
attracting such a first-rate cast, which also includes Christopher
Lloyd as Pozzo and Richard Spore as the human workhorse, Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his stellar players should all take deep breaths and relax.
``Waiting for Godot'' does not have to be a portentous event. As
was demonstrated recently in a cheeky and fully alive version of
the play by the Studio Theater in Washington, ``Godot'' can seem as
biting and fresh as improvisational comedy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Joy Zinoman, the Studio's director, took liberties
with the text that got her into hot water for a spell with
skeptical representatives of Beckett's estate _ the actors' ad-libs
sparked a public debate over how much control a dead playwright's
agents can exercise over how his plays are interpreted _ but she
did not alter its meaning. What she did was in full service of the
master of the absurd, reinforcing the lasting relevance and
elasticity of his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrader, of course, takes a more conservative approach here,
more reserved by far than, say, the Mike Nichols 1988 all-star
version for Lincoln Center Theater with Robin Williams and Steve
Martin. But his scrupulous efforts at deriving meaning sap the play
of a good portion of its humor and theatricality. Why, for example,
would he have Spore try to make sense of Lucky's amazing nonsense
aria? The emaciated Spore, tethered to the rope carried by Lloyd,
is a freakish fright of a Lucky, an apparition conjured in one of
those hallucinatory episodes of ``Twin Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, Lucky's monologue of gobbledygook, prompted by
Pozzo's command that he ``Think!,'' is delivered in a burst of
energy, gushing forth like the contents of a broken fire hydrant.
It's the only way that it's funny. Here, Spore labors over every
word of the speech, as if trying to divine some rationale for it,
and it falls completely flat. By the end, Shalhoub and Turturro
become our surrogates, gesturing madly at Lucky to get on with it.
No one in the audience would disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd, with those wild eyes and the voice of the leader of a
chain gang, can be a wonderfully menacing presence on a stage, and
his gargoyle-like Pozzo is definitely the sort of bully that
Vladimir and Estragon would be cowed by. But as with Spore, there
is no lightness of being in his performance; the underlying
music-hall smoothness of Pozzo _ he's costumed here as a ringmaster
_ eludes Lloyd, who is playing someone close to his evil character
in ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit?''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with these maddeningly half-realized creations, Shalhoub
and Turturro are pressed to fully occupy the play's emotional
center. Given time, they begin to find their way toward one
another. (They could even pass for brothers).
</P>
<P>
   Shalhoub's placid Didi is the more refined of the two, with the
suggestion of education in his clipped delivery and his more
decisive manner: it is he, after all, who gets the message from
Godot to wait, for reasons forever unknown, on this road halfway to
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Turturro, so expert at wired outsiders, like the angry,
cast-aside contestant in the movie ``Quiz Show,'' here strips away
the bravado and plays Gogo as a blue-collar naif, with the trace of
a New York accent and an unassuming air. This simplicity is the
most rewarding aspect of this ``Godot.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Shalhoub, he's at his best when he's treating Beckett's
language as an actor's fuel, and not as if it had been inscribed on
tablets and handed down from the mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WAITING FOR GODOT'
</P>
<P>
   By Samuel Beckett; directed by Andrei Belgrader; production
supervised by David Esbjornson; sets by Andrei Both; costumes by
Elizabeth Hope Clancy; lighting by Michael Chybowski; production
stage manager, Amy Patricia Stern; general manager, Jason Loewith.
Presented by the Classic Stage Company, Barry Edelstein, artistic
director; Beth Emelson, producing director. At 136 E. 13th St.,
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: John Turturro (Estragon), Tony Shalhoub (Vladimir),
Christopher Lloyd (Pozzo) and Richard Spore (Lucky). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
