<SLUG> BC-AMNESTY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Juveniles receiving abusive justice, Amnesty International says
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Georgia and across the country, juvenile justice
systems routinely violate the rights of children in custody,
inflicting beatings and other cruel punishments, Amnesty
International said in a report issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The international human rights group said federal, state and
local governments in the United States have drastically stepped up
the severity of punishments imposed on offenders under 18 in the
last generation.
</P>
<P>
   Society should focus instead on prevention, education and
rehabilitation, the group said, along with the head of a Georgia
advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many children are incarcerated when other action could or
should have been taken,'' said Pamela Johnson of the Amnesty
International's Southern Regional Office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The report, titled ``Betraying the Young: Children in the U.S.
Justice System,'' is part of Amnesty's yearlong, worldwide campaign
focusing on issues in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia ranks among the worst states for juvenile justice, but
no state in the country provides the proper programs well, said
Richard L. McDevitt, president of the Georgia Alliance for
Children.
</P>
<P>
   McDevitt called Georgia's juvenile justice system
``state-sponsored child abuse'' and ``an incubator'' for adult
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``To prevent adult crime, you have to start with juveniles,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the U.S. Justice Department reported it found ``a
pattern of egregious conditions violating the federal rights of
youths'' in Georgia's detention centers. Among other problems, it
said, youths were routinely abused and lacked proper educational
facilities and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The state agreed in March to spend $65 million over the next
three years to relieve overcrowding and improve education and
programs for mental and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
