<SLUG> BC-WAART-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIANS TAKE PART IN A SHOWER OF STRAUSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)  (js) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is it related to the shower of Leonid meteors, this
odd confluence of dubious works by Richard Strauss? Edo de Waart
and the Sydney Symphony Orchestra presented the ``Symphonia
Domestica'' at Carnegie Hall on Tuesday evening, a day before
Christian Thielemann and the New York Philharmonic were to begin a
run of performances of the ``Alpine Symphony'' at Avery Fisher
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect Straussians tend to melt before the homely pieties and
calculated impieties of the ``Domestica,'' but even they have
little but scorn for the grandiosity of the ``Alpine.'' This flawed
Straussian has always regarded the ``Alpine'' with a perverse
fondness and taken the ``Domestica,'' when necessary, through
gritted teeth. (Tortured memory has gone so far as to imagine the
clanging of actual pots and pans in the percussion, and its failure
to appear always provides some relief.)
</P>
<P>
   Atypically, a listener was tempted to wish for a less
adventurous program from the Sydney Symphony: one of the Beethoven
symphonies it played over the weekend at the Tilles Center in
Brookville, N.Y., perhaps, in view of its captivating performances
of two Beethoven symphonies recorded live in June by the Australian
Broadcasting Company.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra did offer Beethoven of a more discreet kind _ the
Second Piano Concerto, with Christian Zacharias as soloist _ and
the crisp performance bore out the promise of those recordings.
Zacharias fitted in comfortably, coloring a fine, unbroken line
with an imaginative array of touches and sonorities.
</P>
<P>
   It was an excellent idea, too, to bring along an Australian
work, if a piece inspired by Les Baxter, Henry Mancini and John
Barry (and surely Bernstein's ``West Side Story,'' though the
composer doesn't say so) can be so described. Graeme Koehne's
``Elevator Music,'' his program note suggests, seeks to restore the
good name of ``music which serves to give pleasure to `ordinary'
people,'' and it makes for a pleasant enough way to spend 10
minutes. It also affords a thorough workout for the orchestra, and
here, as in the Beethoven, the Sydney players, obviously well
trained by de Waart, their chief conductor, produced an impressive
corporate sound.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the Strauss with its greater extremes and individual
demands did weaknesses show: a shrillness in the highest string
playing; thin and wavering tone from several soloists. Still, there
was nothing so bad that it might not have been concealed by a
cannier, not to say better, choice of repertory.
</P>
</TEXT>
