<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-MAGAZINES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forbes examines 'promise and threat' of the Internet
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Given the recent resurgence of Internet stocks,
Fortune (Dec. 7) displays good timing with a package of stories on
what it calls ``the promise and threat'' of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine starts by declaring the Internet ``will empower
consumers like nothing else ever has,'' and cites this as evidence:
``Already 16 percent of car buyers shop online before showing up at
a dealership, and they aren't comparing paint jobs _ they're arming
themselves with information on dealer costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' point is while the Internet is good for consumers, it
makes life harder for businesses, and the latter needs to learn to
deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Discount broker Charles Schwab is one business that has embraced
the Internet. In three years, it has gone from handling no
transactions over the Internet to handling trades on $4 billion
worth of securities a week, according to Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   All the world's a stage
</P>
<P>
   The story lines in the Nov. 23 issue of Business Week run from
Hollywood to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The cover report is about Steven P. Jobs' efforts to turn Pixar,
the animation studio, into the ``next Disney.'' In the same edition
is a report card on Asia. Business Week's conclusion: A complete
recovery is months away, and some countries are doing better than
others, but the ``region's harrowing economic free fall is nearing
bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately speaking
</P>
<P>
   Forbes (Nov. 30) is out with its list of the biggest private
companies in the United States, based on revenue. There are no
changes at the very top, with Cargill No. 1, followed by Koch
Industries and Atlanta's United Parcel Service. Forbes' list of 500
companies includes 17 based in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Worth a second look
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit a brick wall at 125 miles per hour, you have to
pick yourself up and go around it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's money manager Gavin Rankin's comment on dealing with the
thrashing the collapse of the Russian economy has given to
Lexington Troika Dialog Russia, last year's hottest mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   That story, and another offering advice on mortgage refinancing,
make the December issue of Money worth reading for more than just
the retirement planning guide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
