<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PAYHIKE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta gives non-union workers pay raise
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Non-union Delta Air Lines workers will get an 8
percent pay boost on Jan. 1, but the raises will be partly offset
by the termination of a profit-sharing plan for those workers.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, Atlanta's largest private employer, also has
offered to restore a 2 percent pay cut for unionized pilots 16
months ahead of schedule. Pilots would continue to receive
profit-sharing payouts at 6 percent of salary.
</P>
<P>
   The moves were announced Wednesday in what Chief Executive Leo
Mullin called ``significant and positive changes to (Delta's)
compensation program.''
</P>
<P>
   They follow a $1 billion profit in the fiscal year ended June
30. Mullin and other top executives already have received hefty
bonuses for the strong financial results, which capped a rebound
from hard times earlier in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Wage boosts have been scarce for Delta's non-union workers in
the '90s, although the profit-sharing plan was added in 1995 and
produced payouts of 6 percent of base pay in the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said profit-sharing will be scrapped for non-union workers
at the end of this year, with a final payout covering the first
half of the current July-June 1999 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Jan. 1, profit-sharing will be supplanted by a 6
percent wage hike, with an additional 2 percent boost added for an
8 percent net wage increase.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot pay changes are structured differently because of the
union contract, but they are intended to have the same effect.
Delta's Air Line Pilots Association unit has been seeking a
midcontract pay boost for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ALPA leaders must approve the company's offer and will take it
up next month, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, in an employee memo, said the conversion of
profit-sharing to a pay boost provides more security for most
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recession is a real possibility, and such economic conditions
can alter the value of variable compensation elements such as
profit-sharing,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Extra boosts will go to flight attendants and mechanics who
``have fallen below competitive compensation,'' according to the
memo. It said the changes will leave those workers, along with
reservationists and airport agents, at the top of the industry
based on top-of-scale wage rates at major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, high wages have helped Delta remain the
least-unionized major airline. But two unions are courting flight
attendants, and one of them, the Transport Workers Union, also is
trying to organize ramp workers and mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of employees know the reason this came about was
the organizing efforts,'' said Jeff Osborne, a TWU organizer. He
said the plan amounts to only a 2 percent boost for non-union
workers, once profit-sharing is eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne said workers are concerned about other issues, such as
retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
