<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN LEADERSHIP SELECTS FIRST AFRICAN AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. J.C. Watts, a former University of Oklahoma
star quarterback, made history Wednesday by becoming the first
African American elected to the House Republican leadership, giving
the GOP its long-sought chance to claim it is a party of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, a telegenic, high-octane orator, defeated Rep. John
Boehner, R-Ohio, a low-key political insider who has served for
four years as chairman of the Republican Party Conference, the
fourth-ranking leadership post.
</P>
<P>
   The 121-to-93 vote for Watts was a startling upset in
Wednesday's secret-ballot Republican leadership elections.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the party conference, which consists of all 223
House Republicans, endorsed Appropriations Committee Chairman Bob
Livingston of Louisiana, 55, to become the 51st House speaker,
replacing Newt Gingrich of Georgia, who announced two weeks ago he
was stepping down in the wake of the GOP's disappointing election
results.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who spoke briefly to the conference, left for a
Florida vacation with his wife Marianne before most of the votes
were cast. The formal election for House speaker takes place in
January when the 106th Congress convenes, but since the Republicans
have a majority, Livingston's victory is assured.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker-elect promised afterward to cut taxes and save the
Social Security Trust Fund, which could go bankrupt in the 2030s as
the bulk of baby boomers retire.
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``We want the American people to know they're
going to get good, clean, honest government from us. ``We may have
slipped,'' he added, referring to the GOP's loss of five House
seats Nov. 3. ``But we haven't fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts said he, too, looked forward to the next Congress. ``I'm
excited about everyone working together as a team to make sure that
we cut people's taxes, that we strengthen our national defense,
that we strengthen Social Security, we continue working on a health
care system to make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   The 223 Republican House members who convened in the Cannon
House Office Building to select their leaders also reelected House
Majority Leader Richard Armey of Texas after a cliff-hanging three
rounds of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, majority leader since the Republicans took over the House
in 1994, defeated Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma on the third
ballot in a 127-to-95 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Because no one got the 112-vote majority needed to win on the
first ballot, two more rounds of voting ensued, each time
eliminating the lowest scorer. A late entry, Dennis J. Hastert,
R-Ill., the chief deputy whip, was the first to fall, followed by
Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, the first woman to run for majority leader, had faced
opposition among some conservatives because while she is against
the use of federal funds for abortions, she is also pro-choice. She
said later she did not think that position hurt her bid against
Armey. But she said the 11th-hour candidacy of Hastert siphoned
votes away from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have minimal disappointment,'' she said, although she added,
``I would have loved to have put my shoulder to the wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said the Republicans ``decided to continue with Dick Armey
for very good reasons'' _ they wanted ``continuity and stability.''
She added she was glad she ``took the risk at cracking this glass
ceiling.'' Dunn said she does not fear any political retribution
because she challenged the majority leader. ``I really do not
expect any negatives on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Largent, a Bible Belt conservative and former former Seattle
Seahawks wide receiver, said he was ``not accustomed to losing,''
and would ``continue to fight for the things we believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans said the three rounds of voting signaled less
than a ringing endorsement for Armey. ``It shows that there are
some people in our conference that were looking for change,'' said
Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C. ``Now it's time to repair the breach.''
</P>
<P>
   In another leadership coup, Thomas M. Davis of Virginia replaced
John Linder of Georgia as chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Campaign Committee, the House GOP's fund-raising
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Linder had been tapped by Gingrich to head the committee, but he
was swept from office by Republicans seeking a change. In toppling
him, Davis had a strong assist from Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the
Republican whip, or chief vote counter. DeLay was re-elected
without opposition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., predictably won reelection as
chairman of the conference's 42-member Republican Policy Committee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., became vice chairwoman of the
Republican Conference, a slot vacated by Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep. Deborah Pryce, R-Ohio, won her uncontested post as
secretary of the Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hastert retained his leadership post as chief deputy whip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
