<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BROTHERS TAKE SPOTLIGHT AT GOP GOVERNORS MEETING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush basked in renewed
national media attention Wednesday and picked up a qualified
endorsement for a presidential campaign from his younger brother,
the governor-elect of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, joining his Texas brother for the first time since
both scored gubernatorial election victories Nov. 3, said he was
encouraging George W. Bush to run for the White House if he could
resolve family considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush brothers grabbed the spotlight on the opening day of
the Republican Governors Association's annual meeting, bantering
with each other and with reporters in a news conference that ended
only when security officers helped the Texas governor elbow his way
out of a crowded room.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush's comments were the strongest that any member of the
Bush family has yet made in support of a potential presidential bid
by George W. Bush, who has said he has not yet decided whether to
seek the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an uncivil age that we live in. It's pretty intense
politics these days,'' said Jeb Bush, who will become Florida's
chief executive in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (the Texas governor) has got two teen-age girls who I think
are really cool, and having their father run for president is
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeb Bush added: ``If he gets through that, and he decides to
do it, I've encouraged him to. I think he would be an awesome
candidate. I'm going to vote for him .... If he announces his
candidacy, we won't have a family vote. Everybody will be lined up
to help him.``
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine Republican governors and governors-elect, some of
whom also are considered potential presidential contenders, were
expected to attend their annual conference, which runs through
Friday. But if any governors whose last name wasn't Bush were
seeking media attention, they were in the wrong place Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes' news conference was the major event. Several dozen
reporters, photographers and TV camera operators representing most
of the country's major news organizations were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to introduce my little brother to the Texas press
corps. It looks like some others came along,'' George W. Bush
deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   At previous governor conferences, Bush usually has held informal
briefings with the handful of Texas reporters attending and private
interviews with selected national reporters. But, now that he is
considered the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination in 2000, the demand was too great this time, spokeswoman
Karen Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush's office had been bombarded with ``dozens'' of
requests for media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   With each Bush brother sitting _ apparently accidentally _ in
front of the other brother's state flag, the first question and
many that followed were, not surprisingly, about the presidential
race. And George W. Bush's responses were equally not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made up my mind yet,'' he said. ``Right now I'm
working on my (second gubernatorial) inauguration speech, and I've
got an agenda that I've got to get through the legislative
session.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature will convene Jan. 12. Bush will be
inaugurated for his second term Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say this. (For) someone who is running for
president, it would be wise for them to knock on Jeb Bush's door.
Florida's an important state,'' the Texas governor added.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said his main consideration in deciding on a
presidential bid was whether he wanted to take his family through
the grind of Washington politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although his father, George Bush, was elected president after
years of national public service, the Texas governor added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't grow up every day wanting to be president of the
United States. I grew up wanting to be (baseball star) Willie
Mays.``
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, 52, said it was a ``big deal'' to see his
younger brother, 45, elected governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how proud I was to see him walk into a
Republican governors' meeting,'' he said. ``This guy's a good guy,
and I love him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush's election, the Texas governor added, will make Florida
a better state.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor also couldn't resist a little fraternal
teasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling him what to do for 45 years, and he hasn't
listened yet,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, who called his father a great president, said he
developed a ``rather thin-skinned reputation'' for defending ``my
dad's honor'' during the elder Bush's unsuccessful re-election race
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like to see him get attacked. I found out it's a lot
different, though, going from loyal son to candidate and, now,
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
