<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7587 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDICIARY-IMPEACH-1ST     11-18 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDICIARY-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAIN RISES ON IMPEACHMENT HEARINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: New grafs 3-4 with witnesses; editing to conform)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid bitter partisan rancor, the House on Thursday
opens long-awaited impeachment hearings against President Clinton
for alleged perjury and obstruction of justice in the Monica
Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr was scheduled as the day's
lone witness before the House Judiciary Committee. The majority
Republicans may meet Friday or later this month to decide whether
to call additional witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., late
Wednesday announced that in addition to hearing Starr's testimony,
the committee would issue subpoenas for closed-door depositions
from White House lawyer Bruce Lindsey, Clinton lawyer Robert
Bennett, and two figures in a related matter: Clinton's alleged
kissing and groping of former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   One is Daniel Gecker, a Richmond, Va. lawyer who represented
Willey and undertook an unsuccessful effort to secure tabloid and
book deals for Willey. The other is Nathan Landow, a wealthy
Maryland developer and Democratic fundraiser. Willey has alleged
that Landow urged her to keep silent about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a final list,'' said Sam Stratman, spokesman for
committee.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Starr gets the floor for up to two hours to address
the committee after opening statements by Hyde and Rep. John
Conyers, D-Mich., the top Democrat on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Starr then will be questioned by Republican chief counsel David
Schippers and his Democratic counterpart Abbe Lowell. Then each of
the committee's 37 members _ 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats _ will
question Starr for five minutes each. At the tail end, David
Kendall, Clinton's lawyer in the Lewinsky matter, will get to
question Starr for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is expected to go well outside the four corners of
Clinton's efforts to hide his 18-month relationship with Lewinsky.
He will try to show that Clinton's conduct in the Lewinsky affair
was part of a wider pattern of presidential obstruction of Starr's
investigation, which began in 1994 as a look at Bill and Hillary
Clinton's roles as investors in the ill-fated Whitewater land
development scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told reporters he wouldn't stop Starr from ranging beyond
the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I?'' Hyde asked. ``Because the Democrats would like
that? The Democrats want to stick to Monica Lewinsky. We want to
look at everything. That's the big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Democrats left no doubt they intend to shift
attention away from Clinton's behavior and focus their fire on
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr's conduct and the actions of his staff bear directly on
credibility of the inquiry itself,'' said Jim Jordan, spokesman for
Judiciary Committee Democrats. There are serious questions about
the investigation and about how the issue ended up in Starr's
office in the first place, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said Democrats would ask Starr about allegations that he
or his aides threatened Lewinsky; leaked grand jury materials; were
in contact with lawyers representing Paula Jones in her sexual
harassment civil lawsuit against Clinton; and started investigating
the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship before obtaining court
authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Alternating scenarios with different configurations of witnesses
have marked the confused Republican planning for the hearings,
prompting Democrats to charge that the last-minute confusion about
the witness list illustrated how Republicans were in disarray in
the face of polls showing little public enthusiasm for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``thought they were going to ride this impeachment
horse all the way home, (but) the horse is now in terrible shape,''
said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a Judiciary member. ``They've got
two choices: They can shoot it and send it to the dog-food factory,
or they can paint stripes on it and tell everyone its a zebra... I
don't think they know yet what they're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, at least, Republicans said they would focus on
Starr's Sept. 9 report to Congress citing 11 grounds for
impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to hearing Ken Starr's side of the
investigation,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, a Judiciary
member. ``The administration and its spokespeople have savaged Ken
Starr daily and ... he has not been allowed to speak publicly about
what he has found. So, for the first time he will be able to speak
for himself and speak candidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith dismissed Democratic plans to put Starr on trial Thursday
and charges of faulty GOP leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence Ken Starr will successfully keep the focus
on whether the president committed impeachable crimes,'' he said.
``I'm sure the Democrats would like to change the subject, but
there's only one subject at hand: Whether the president committed
these crimes or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Other GOP members of the committee expressed concern about
Starr's ability to withstand the expected Democratic barrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough forum for Starr,'' said Rep. Asa
Hutchinson, R-Ark. ``The Democrats are champing at the bit for this
opportunity and it's going to be hard for him to look good.''
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the White House on Wednesday conceded defeat
in its effort to expand the time its lawyers would have Thursday to
question Starr. After receiving Hyde's initial offer of 30 minutes,
White House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff on Tuesday insisted the time
be expanded to 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde turned down the request. On Wednesday, Ruff sent Hyde a
letter saying ``we will proceed within the time allotted'' even
though in his view 30 minutes ``is not consistent with the standard
of fairness that the committee has sought to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told reporters Wednesday he would be ``liberal and
tolerant'' in extending the White House's cross-examination period,
``if they're on a line of questioning and they need more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, the committee's chief counsel, Tom Mooney,
wrote to Ruff imploring him to respond to a list of 81
Lewinsky-related questions sent by Hyde to Clinton on Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a promise to get the answers back to the committee by
Nov. 13, the White House has failed to forward them, Mooney wrote.
``We are dismayed that you have missed your own self-imposed
deadline,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week Starr has delivered additional boxes of
evidence to the committee. One set involves Willey. The other
involves Webster Hubbell, former Justice Department official and
close Clinton pal indicted last week for lying to Congress and
federal banking regulators about work he did for the now-insolvent
Madison Guaranty Savings &AMP; Loan, owned by Clinton Whitewater
partner James McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Hubbell and Willey documents could prove to be wild
cards in the hearings, though it was unclear whether either case
would come up at all.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday will mark only the third time in U.S. history that the
House Judiciary Committee has conducted an impeachment inquiry into
the actions of a president. The previous occasions were the 1867
and 1868 proceedings against President Andrew Johnson and the 1974
hearings on President Nixon's role in the Watergate scandal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
