<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7607 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METEOR-WHOOPS-BOS &LR;      11-18 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METEOR-WHOOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERROR SENDS METEOR VIEWERS TO WRONG PART OF THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showers and storms of meteors, it seems, may be a lot like snow
storms and rain showers: Awfully hard to predict. Astronomers who
forecast a &UR;  &LR; storm of Leonid meteors, according to preliminary
reports, may have been a half-a-world off in predicting where the
storm would be the heaviest.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of astronomers from the United States, Canada and other
nations traveled to remote and harsh locations in Asia, including
the Gobi desert in Mongolia, in hopes of catching the peak of an
expected dazzling storm that happens only once in 33 years _ and
sometimes not that often. But it looks like they could have spared
themselves money and time if they had stayed closer to home: The
most spectacular meteor displays may have occurred somewhere over
the Atlantic ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the world's most skilled astronomers had analyzed
centuries' worth of records to prepare their forecasts. Just a few
days ago, they acknowledged that they might be way off in
predicting how many meteors might be seen during the peak, but they
were pretty sure about where and when the peak would be.
</P>
<P>
   If the early reports are right, just the opposite occurred. They
were close on their predictions on the number of meteors at the
peak _ perhaps as many as 1,000 to 2,000 per hour, well within a
predicted range of 200 to 10,000. But they were way off on the time
and location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Predicting meteor showers is really a crapshoot,'' said Donald
Yeomans of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory, who is considered one of the world's best at
calculating such things. Like most in the field, he was confident
that Asia would be be the best viewing spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out'' on exactly what did happen, Yeomans
said in an interview Wednesday, but the preliminary reports &UR;  &LR; 
strongly suggest that the forecast was about as far off as those
weather reports that have people shoveling six inches of ``partly
cloudy'' off the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody is really complaining about it _ except, of
course, the legions of would-be skywatchers who were stuck under
solidly overcast skies during the whole show. That includes most of
New England.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who could see the sky at all, few were
disappointed. Although the peak was in the ``wrong'' place,
virtually every part of the world, at some point, was showered with
meteors at a rate of 100 to 400 per hour. While that's no more than
are seen in some other, lesser meteor showers, it is more than
forecast for this year outside the Asian sites.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ecstatic eyewitness reports flooded the Internet
and radio programs around the world. Observers on different
continents, many of them experienced skywatchers who have weathered
many a meteor shower, said the displays surpassed any meteor
activity they had seen before.
</P>
<P>
   The highest numbers of meteors were reported in the Eastern
Atlantic: in Portugal and at the Canary Islands observatory at La
Palma. A team of professional astronomers from the United Kingdom,
observing at La Palma, reported that as dawn broke on Tuesday
meteors were raining down at a rate of almost one per second, or
nearly 3,600 per hour _ although less than an hour elapsed before
the display was washed out by morning twilight.
</P>
<P>
   A group of observers from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena, Calif., watching from the nearby mountains, said that
even with half the sky obscured by clouds they saw somewhere
between 600 and 1,000 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Green, who has been compiling information from viewers
around the world for the International Astronomical Union's central
clearinghouse for astronomical information in Cambridge, Mass.,
said Wednesday early reports do indeed suggest that predictions of
the peak were off by 12 hours or so, and that Asia missed out on
the highest levels of showers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Considering the amount of money and effort spent to send
scientists to far-flung places that turned out to be relative duds,
he said, there may be a lesson to be remembered next year, whose
Leonid shower is expected to be comparable to this year's _ and
perhaps be the last such Leonid storm for centuries to come:
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not be quite as bold next year,'' Green said,
``about predicting what will happen and when.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
