<SLUG> BC-OFF-LABEL-MEDICINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW USES FOR OLD DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dozen years ago, when word got out that men taking minoxidil
to control their high blood pressure were growing extra hair on
their heads _ and elsewhere _ doctors began writing prescriptions
to get the drug compounded in formulations that could be rubbed
directly on the body.
</P>
<P>
   Tablets were mashed and bulk powder ordered to be mixed with
propylene glycol and alcohol so that the solution could be applied
topically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only had one patient who ever took minoxidil for blood
pressure, but I mixed up a lot of the topical preparation to grow
hair. We mixed it however the doctors ordered,'' says Dan
Fuchshuber, a North Texas pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   So much of the topical solution was being prepared that
pharmaceutical giant Upjohn reportedly obtained a patent for
topical minoxidil and filed a lawsuit against some pharmacies that
were known to do a lot of custom compounding. This was shortly
before the company launched Rogaine,its popular hair tonic, now
sold over-the-counter.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of off-label drug use, where male pattern
baldness is treated with high-blood-pressure medicine, labor is
induced with ulcer drugs and acne medicine is prescribed for women
worried about wrinkles. And it's all legal _ and ethical.
</P>
<P>
   Although drug companies can't advertise or sell drugs for
purposes other than those for which they have been federally
approved, once the U.S. Food and Drug Administration approves a
drug as safe and effective for one indication, doctors can legally
and ethically use the drug for any purpose in the patient's best
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Antihistamines are widely used off-label.
</P>
<P>
   Benadryl, for example, causes so much drowsiness that when it
went over-the-counter about six years ago, diphenhydramine, the
popular antihistamine's active ingredient, almost immediately took
over the market as the active ingredient in sleep aids including
Sominex, Nytol, Compoz and most pain medications with a PM suffix,
such as Excedrin PM, Fuchshuber says.
</P>
<P>
   Antihistamines have been widely used as tranquilizers since
diphenhydramine was first introduced in 1945, notes Fort Worth
allergist Bob Lanier. Diphenhydramine became very popular in French
prisons, where it was used to calm down difficult-to-control
inmates, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the older tranquilizers we still use today, all the
old tricyclics, actually developed from antihistamine drugs,''
Lanier says.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier notes that there is a long tradition of using drugs
off-label because they have to be approved within such a narrow
framework. Sometimes drugs are prescribed for beneficial side
effects that are discovered. The classic example is amantadine,
developed and used since the 1960s for the treatment of Parkinson's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we had that terrible flu epidemic in 1968,'' says Lanier,
``and the only people who didn't get extremely ill with the flu
were those taking the Parkinson's drug.''
</P>
<P>
   It took more than 20 years, but Symmetrel, whose active
ingredient is amantadine, was approved by the FDA in 1991 for the
treatment of type A influenza strains. Flumadine, a closely related
drug, has also been approved to fight the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the drugs used for children today are used
off-label, never officially approved by the Food and Drug
Administration for use in children. In fact, most drugs are
approved only for use in middle-aged men because they were the only
ones included in drug trials until about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some other popular drugs originally approved for one medical
purpose and now widely used for another include:
</P>
<P>
   Retin-A: developed to treat acne, now used against wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Depo-provera: developed to treat endometriosis, now approved for
birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Taxol: developed for breast cancer, now used more in bladder
cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Premarin: developed for use in estrogen replacement therapy
primarily to prevent hot flashes, now used to protect
post-menopausal women from osteoporosis and heart disease, and
being tested against Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Thalidomide: first developed as a sedative and used to treat
morning sickness, then taken off the market; recently approved for
the treatment of leprosy and for the severe mouth ulcers that
people with AIDS often get.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
