<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMEY-KEEPS-JOB-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PULLS THROUGH ON THIRD BALLOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Ron Hutcheson 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving kept his
job Wednesday as House Republicans prepared for life without
Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Republicans picked Rep. Bob Livingston of Louisiana
to replace Gingrich at the top of the leadership team dominated by
Sun Belt lawmakers. Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma was elected
chairman of the Republican conference, becoming the first
high-ranking African American in the House Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, a former star quarterback at the University of Oklahoma,
will rank fourth in the next Congress, behind Livingston, Armey and
GOP Whip Tom DeLay of Sugar Land, who was unopposed for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans emerged from the closed-door session determined to
get back on track after setbacks in the Nov. 3 elections. The loss
of five GOP House seats triggered Gingrich's resignation and
touched off a leadership scramble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We muffed our message a little bit in the last elections, and
the American people held us accountable,'' Livingston said. ``As
Abe Lincoln said, a slip is not a fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, who faced three challengers, struggled through three
rounds of balloting before winning a majority of the 223 Republican
votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Irving Republican captured 100 votes _ 12 short of the goal
_ in the first round, compared with 58 for Rep. Steve Largent of
Oklahoma, 45 for Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington and 18 for Rep.
Dennis Hastert of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   With Hastert out of the race, Armey fell short again in a second
ballot that eliminated Dunn from the competition. He finally beat
Largent, 127-95, in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I pray for humility, and all of a sudden I had 222
people helping me with it,'' a relieved Armey joked. ``I was in a
horse race with three thoroughbreds and one Texas quarterhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Largent, a former star receiver for the Seattle Seahawks
football team, fell back on a sports analogy in explaining the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Largent has been too slow and too small his whole life,
and this is just one more occasion,'' he said, repeating a
criticism that he disproved as a football player.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers attributed Armey's victory to the good will he
has generated as a leader of the GOP revolution that captured a
House majority in 1994. He also benefited from a desire for at
least some stability after Gingrich's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reputation for reaching out to all members of the
conference _ conservatives and moderates alike _ gave him a track
record to build on,'' Rep. Lamar Smith of San Antonio said.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, whose district includes the northeast corner of Tarrant
County, had strong backing from Rep. Joe Barton of Ennis and Rep.
Kay Granger of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dunn and Largent joined Armey in a post-election show
of unity, some critics were not as willing to forgive and forget.
Armey, whose job as legislative leader often puts him between
warring moderates and conservatives, has come under fire from both
factions for his handling of the GOP agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have a track record of not learning from past
mistakes. We'll see if he does this time,'' said Rep. Joe
Scarborough of Florida, a conservative who has been one of Armey's
harshest critics.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing mood was more optimistic. The newly elected
leaders said they intend to rally rank-and-file lawmakers behind a
targeted agenda of tax cuts, a strong national defense, Social
Security protection and education support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't betray our philosophy to win applause, nor abandon
good policy in search of praise,'' Livingston told his colleagues.
``We must cooperate to move forward. But we will never capitulate.
In short, we will never, never, never give in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most rebellious Republicans said the hotly contested
leadership races eased long-standing tensions within the party.
Others said Gingrich's departure will help them stay focused on
issues rather than personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, instead of sweeping things under the rug, we're
really listening to each other,'' Rep. Matt Salmon of Arizona said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's ascension to the top job will not become official
until the full House ratifies the decision in a party-line vote
when the 106th Congress convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said his tough re-election fight taught him some valuable
lessons for the next Congress. He said one Georgia lawmaker
complained that Armey had not spoken to him in his four years as
majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine that? That's nobody's fault but my own,''
Armey said. ``Today, I sat down next to him and I said, `Say, did I
ever welcome you to the party?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hutcheson, (202) 383-6101
</P>
<P>
   rhutcheson &LR; krwashington.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
