<HEADLINE>
DEARTH OF WORKERS PLAGUES RETAILERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   AND JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tammy McMaster could sense that stores were desperate
for sales clerks to work during the holidays. So she made her move.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the 19-year-old reasoned, she had worked a full year
for The Body Shop and deserved a $1-an-hour raise. When her
supervisor refused, she clomped across the mall's glazed floor in
her clunky shoes to the Talbot's Kids store and got a job there.
The Body Shop quickly hired her back _ and gave her the raise.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment at its lowest level in decades, retailers
can't remember a holiday season when it was more difficult to find
clerks to prepare for the rush of shoppers. The problem is
national, but it is particularly acute in Massachusetts, where the
jobless rate is a full percentage point below US unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the tight labor market, retailers are being
forced to boost wages, offer signing bonuses, health benefits and
paid vacations _ even to seasonal and part-time workers. But that
may not be enough during the holiday weeks. Inexperienced, albeit
energetic workers have no trouble landing a job _ or playing one
retailer off against another with the bargaining skills of a
seasoned executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good year to do it,'' McMaster explained as Sunday
shoppers at the Burlington Mall sniffed The Body Shop's ointments.
``You can go through this whole mall, and there are (help wanted)
signs everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Shopkeepers are loath to snatch employees from each other. But
this holiday season demands that they use extreme tactics to
attract _ and keep _ workers in a job market flush with better
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all desperate,'' said Skip Coppola, general manager
for the Faneuil Hall Marketplace in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers in the historic shopping area have been grumbling that
Finagle-A-Bagel's offer of a ``signing bonus'' for new hires is
siphoning workers off for tasks no more skilled than slapping a
schmear of cream cheese on a bagel.
</P>
<P>
   The $50 bonus, unheard of for food service crews, is an
acknowledgment of the high cost of turnover in retail and
food-service businesses. Sign-on bonuses are aimed at retention,
since they are paid only after the worker stays on the job for
three months.
</P>
<P>
   For Finagle-A-Bagel, the two-week-old policy at the store has
produced a stack of applications from which to choose. It brings 10
prospective workers a week through the door, compared with two
applicants at another downtown Finagle-A-Bagel, company officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   To outbid competitors, retailers this season are paying seasonal
workers well above the minimum wage of $5.15 an hour, once the
standard for temporary or part-time help.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's, which is in the midst of adding 1,000 seasonal workers
to its 3,000-person work force in Massachusetts, is paying sales
clerks 50 cents an hour more this year than last, or between $6.50
and $7.50 an hour, said Elliott Tobias, vice president of human
resources for the New England region. And Macy's competitors are
shocked by the department store's steep sign-on bonus: Last
weekend, Macy's raised the bonus by $100, to $300, in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are using any strategy that will work to get a
larger pool of candidates for work,'' said Connie Doty, director of
jobs and community services for the city of Boston. ``There are a
lot of jobs that go wanting at the very low end.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with a tight labor market, needless to say, is that
the quality or experience of applicants has, well ... ``I need to
phrase this as diplomatically as possible,'' said Leslie Fay, who
sells beaded jewelry from her pushcart in Faneuil Hall. She
explained that applicants are unschooled in ``the basics'' _ like
getting to work on time.
</P>
<P>
   Fay, who needs just one employee to help her through the
holidays, has had no luck. ``I'm working more right now than I
typically do for the simple reason we can't find anyone to hire,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially tough for small operators like Fay to find help
when national chains such as Sunglass Hut, KB Toys and August Max
Woman are advertising signing bonuses, generous benefits packages
or large employee discounts this year for seasonal workers.
</P>
<P>
   KB Toys uses a 25 percent discount on store merchandise as a
tool in tripling holiday staffing to almost 30,000 nationwide. It
also runs an &UR;  &LR; ``Elves Wanted'' campaign _ displayed on billboards,
T-shirts worn by sales staff, and blimps. The toy company uses the
campaign to lure parents, grandparents, aunts and uncles who are
customers and ``already know something about toys,'' said Gerry
Murray, a vice president at headquarters in Pittsfield.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers with trendy merchandise, such as The Gap or Banana
Republic, get more mileage out of employee discounts, said John
Macht, a retail consultant and former Jordan Marsh executive.
``There's certainly some kind of pecking order going on in terms of
where they choose to work,'' he said. ``There's more selectivity on
the part of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin Carter ``knew it would be easy'' to find a sales job at the
Burlington Mall. So, she quit her job scooping ice cream at
Brigham's and began the search for her first retail job.
</P>
<P>
   The mall-savvy 18-year-old, who will start college in January,
picked up applications at Macy's, Sears and Lord &AMP; Taylor. But,
``they just didn't offer what Filene's offered,'' she said, folding
a gray sweater outfit for a Filene's customer. Stray glitter under
her left eye reflected the store's flourescent lighting as she
explained Filene's had the best benefits for part-time workers,
including health coverage 60 days and a week's paid vacation after
a year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``When labor markets heat up at the bottom, companies end up
improving job quality,'' said Paul Harrington, a Northeastern
University labor professor. ``They invest in the work force with
training and equipment and then wages have to be higher so you
attract a different kind of worker.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside of a tight job market is that it provides experience
to young workers who might otherwise be turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh out of high school, Steve Castelli was among 325 people
hired by the newly opened Rain Forest Cafe, a retail-restaurant
establishment at the Burlington Mall with a Disney-like cacacophy
of jungle drums, roaring tigers, and a long line of kids waiting
with their parents for a table.
</P>
<P>
   The Rain Forest Cafe was a big step up for Castelli, whose prior
experience was cleaning up around a health club and a friend's
house. ``I never thought I'd be doing this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, an Aldo shoe store the size of a postage
stamp was &UR;  &LR; jammed with customers trying on platform boots. Store
manager Mary Roberts was &UR;  &LR; too busy rushing around to talk much; at
3 p.m., she had given up on taking a lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry I didn't have more time,'' she said. ``If you know
someone looking for a job, let me know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
