<HEADLINE>
THE WORKS OF EDITH WHARTON: MANY AND VARIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edith Wharton was nothing if not prolific. When she died at age
75 in 1937, she left uncompleted her 16th novel _ ``The
Buccaneers'' _ in addition to which she had published eight
short-story collections, seven novellas (not including ``Ethan
Frome,'' considered here as a novel), two volumes of poetry, three
travel books, and four full-length nonfiction works including ``A
Backward Glance,'' her 1934 autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel was ``The Valley of Decision'' (1902), now
considered an apprentice work. Wharton's reputation was established
with her second novel _ ``The House of Mirth'' (1905), still
regarded as a masterpiece. (It made the recent, much-publicized
list of the 100 best 20th-century novels in English as selected by
the Modern Library board.) It concerns Lily Bart's effort to rise
in society and raises the novel of manners to the level of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton's most-read work is the short novel ``Ethan Frome''
(1911), her least typical tale, dealing not with New York society
but with New England rustics. Its resolution is tragic, and many
consider it Wharton's highest achievement. Others rate ``The Custom
of the Country'' (1913) as her best work. Its protagonist is the
anti-heroine Undine Spragg, who uses men as steppingstones to power
and wealth but is ultimately frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   The other Wharton work to make the notorious ``Best 100'' is
``The Age of Innocence,'' which treats ironically the effect of
money and class on character. It is her most skillfully constructed
work, but she is otherwise less consistent than her model, Henry
James.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton's other novels, variable in quality, include ``The Fruit
of the Tree'' (1907); ``The Reef'' (1912); ``The Marne'' (1918);
``The Glimpses of the Moon'' (1922); ``A Son at the Front'' (1923);
``The Mother's Recompense'' (1925); ``Twilight Sleep'' (1927);
``The Children'' (1928); ``Hudson River Bracketed'' (1929); ``The
Gods Arrive'' (1932). ``The Buccaneers'' was issued in its
unfinished form in 1938 and republished in 1995, having been
``completed'' by other hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madame de Treynes'' (1907) and ``Summer'' (1917) are
outstanding novellas; and ``Old New York'' is the collective title
for four novellas issued together in 1924. One component _ ``The
Old Maid'' _ is especially admired. As adapted by Zoe Akins, it
became first a Pulitzer Prize play, then a classic movie with Bette
Davis. Larry Swindell, (817) 390-7731
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
