<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-POLICIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CORPORATE POLICIES AIRED AT CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Business leaders representing more than 150
corporations met Wednesday to discuss the need for socially
responsible corporate policies and practices in the United States
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Business for Social Responsibility, the conference
brought together representatives from five continents to discuss
the challenges companies now face as they expand operations around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a bottom-line interest in making sure that the markets
we serve are economically healthy and growing,'' said keynote
speaker Henrique de Campos Meirelles, president and chief operating
officer of BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a packed crowd, Meirelles noted that BankBoston
reacted to poverty, unemployment, and disinvestment in Boston's
urban areas by establishing a Community Banking Group in 1990.
Since then, the group has grown from seven branches in inner city
neighborhoods to a network of 46 branches in three states.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Gail Snowden, group executive of the
Community Banking Group, the project created a real estate lending
unit and began financing urban development projects.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, Meirelles said, BankBoston has expanded its
outreach to include a relatively new plan to assist women who wish
to launch their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our involvement in community development has been effective
because it is essential to who we are,'' noted Meirelles. ``Having
a community investment policy woven into the fabric of your
business will differentiate you from your competitors.'' Founded in
1992, Business for Social Responsibility is a national business
association with more than 1,400 members and affiliates.
Collect-ively, the organization's members and affiliates employ
more than 6 million workers around the world and have annual
revenues totaling more than $1.5 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which ends Friday, will feature such speakers as
former Prime Minister Shimon Peres of Israel; Mads Ovlisen,
president and chief executive of Novo Nordisk A/S; Arnold Hiatt,
chairman, The Stride Rite Foundation and chairman of Business for
Social Responsibility; Eileen Fisher, president and chief executive
of Eileen Fisher Inc.; and Tazeem Nathoo, interim chief executive
of Vancouver City Savings Credit Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
