<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STARR'S TURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of complaining that Ken Starr's
initial referral was ``only about lying about sex,'' Democrats on
the House Judiciary Committee now insist the impeachment hearings
be limited to sex, the whole sex and nothing but the sex.
</P>
<P>
   When Chairman Henry Hyde steered the inquiry beyond President
Clinton's Lewinsky perjuries, Democratic Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt had a hissy fit. Stick to the sex (which turns people off)
or we walk, was his message. Hyde called that bluff; the boycott
threat was hastily withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume Starr uses his opening time to show how Clinton
exhibited a four-year ``pattern and practice'' of abusing his power
by withholding evidence and tampering with witnesses _ from hushing
up Web Hubbell to coaching forgetfulness in Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers and committee partisans will try to change
the subject to Starr's leaks, expenses and prosecutorial hardball,
as if he and not the president's lawbreaking were the impeachment
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has undermined the rule of law with his
repeated trivialization of the oath, power abuse beyond ``lying
about sex'' has to be shown before a consensus could form for
removal.
</P>
<P>
   In the matter of Kathleen Willey, the committee needs to know
all the grand jury knows about possible witness intimidation. More
important than who lied about sexual harassment in the Oval Office
is whether the power of the White House, buttressed by private
snoops, was subsequently brought against an individual accuser. The
committee cannot settle a she-accused-he-denied dispute, but it is
duty bound to find out what power, if any, was used to shut her up
after the alleged event.
</P>
<P>
   The committee should grill Starr on other investigations long
overdue for a criminal information. Now is the time to expose the
Clinton manipulation of the FBI in Filegate, as well as White House
influence on Justice Department persecution of Travel Office
employees standing in the way of political patronage. And has Starr
solved the mystery of the reappearance in the first lady's upstairs
office of her long-missing Whitewater billing records?
</P>
<P>
   We have just learned that Starr has been taking the testimony of
John Huang, the Riady family's man at Commerce and the illegal DNC
fund-raising operation. That's in connection with the Riadys'
hushabye payment to the jail-bound Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   The committee should call Huang, give him use immunity and find
out how Clinton illegally raised millions from Asian sources, which
was soon followed by good news for the Riady clan: a flip-flop of
Clinton policy toward most-favored-nation trade.
</P>
<P>
   If Judiciary is unwilling to look into this, it does not take
seriously its impeachment responsibility. That's because the word
in the Constitution that comes before ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' as a cause for impeachment is ``bribery.''
</P>
<P>
   Huang, a secret participant with Indonesia's James Riady and
Bruce Lindsey at meetings in the Oval Office, knows what policy
advice was solicited and how much hard and soft cash was solicited.
Clinton's Justice Department has avoided questioning Huang for two
years. Why can't we know what Starr has learned _ and why must
Congress depend on the independent counsel for part of the story
when Huang and Lindsey are available to the committee?
</P>
<P>
   The courts have ruled that Clinton cannot cloak the
taxpayer-paid lawyer Lindsey with executive privilege; if Clinton
repeats his unlawful stonewalling order, that would become an
impeachment count.
</P>
<P>
   Looking into illegal foreign fund-raising that borders on
bribery, of course, is not as offputting to the public as delving
into private lives. That's why Clinton partisans want a
``Monica-only'' inquiry into sex lies.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should press Starr to reveal the status of all his
court-assigned investigations. The public's need to know of any
White House abuse of power now outweighs a prosecutor's obligation
to indict lesser figures later.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should the committee rely on any independent counsel as its
only source of information. The unpublicized Select Committee on
Chinagate has yet to share its secret findings with Judiciary.
Before a vote is taken on impeachment, Congress should find and tie
up Starr's loose ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
