<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APEC-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE SUBSTANTIAL COMES OUT OF APEC MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Hopes that a summit of Asia-Pacific
leaders would launch concrete measures to hoist the battered region
out of financial freefall faded Wednesday, as leaders endorsed a
modest set of recovery plans, a half-baked trade deal, and a vague
commitment to study the controversial question of regulating world
capital flows.
</P>
<P>
   The rainbow of Malay batik shirts sported by the 21 leaders of
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation nations added a rare bit of color
to a day of long-winded platitudes and blurry proposals. The APEC
leaders added little to the 16-month-old debate of how to rescue
what was the world's fastest-growing region from a downward spiral
that has eviscerated currencies, bankrupted companies, and thrown
tens of millions of people into poverty.
</P>
<P>
   A political dogfight sparked by Vice President Al Gore's vocal
support for protesters demanding more democracy here and across
Asia distracted from APEC's economic agenda. But there is no
indication that leaders would have approved more radical plans even
without the diplomatic ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, APEC summiteers have walked away with
concrete schedules and individual action plans for liberalizing
trade in specific areas. That may be because when APEC held its
first summit in 1993, Asian economic growth was strong, so
cooperation was easy. But at a time of recession and political
foment, it is hard for nations to agree on how to navigate a way up
from down.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, leaders proclaimed victory, even if in muted
tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a successful meeting,'' said Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad. ``Whether it is successful later on, we
will have to see.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior US official who spoke on condition of anonymity
acknowledged that ``meetings don't solve problems. What solves
problems is work.'' He reasoned that ``there's nothing we can do
about the basic fact that this meeting took place in the context of
a political crisis in Malaysia and a rather formidable financial
crisis that has now spread from Asia to a more global scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the official asserted that the ``centerpiece of this
meeting was an agreement on consensus for strategies for strong,
credible recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading the communique, however, reveals that most of those
strategies are ones that APEC is merely endorsing, not ones that it
initiated. One is a $10 billion US-Japanese proposal to inject
capital into credit-strapped Asian banks and corporations to spur
investment and growth. Another is the tripling by the World Bank
and the doubling by the Asian Development Bank of lending to create
social safety nets, a rarity in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   US officials also cheered themselves that a nine-sector trade
liberalization deal remained intact, even though only 16 economies
signed on and one key nation _ Japan _ did not give full approval.
The deal will now be passed to the 124-nation World Trade
Organization to gain more support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ideal is alive and well and getting its passport in shape
to get to Geneva,'' another US official said, referring to the
trade organization's headquarters. ``We have 16 economies that have
booked to travel with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, taking the deal to a world forum may be the most
appropriate thing to do. As Asia's recession has affected &UR;  &LR; world
markets, the need for global, not just regional, cooperation has
become painfully apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, an ongoing debate over whether capital flows and
financial markets should be regulated or monitored will be studied
by APEC, but even Malaysia's Mahathir _ the world's most vocal
proponent of capital controls _ said Wednesday that such issues
must be addressed by a larger world community, such as the G22
group of nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with something that involves all the countries
in the world,'' said Mahathir, surprising those who thought he
would push Asia to endorse its own capital controls like those he
imposed here Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   However, the admission that there must be wider participation
beyond Asia on trade and financial systems raises the question of
APEC's relevance as a solo body. The leaders' declaration on
capital flows was also almost verbatim from a statement two weeks
ago by the G7 group of industrialized nations, calling into
question what original thinking APEC leaders did on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say APEC acts as a united catalyst, bringing to a
global forum issues endorsed by a region that accounts for 55
percent of world economic output. But others, especially APEC
business delegates, wish the group would have also taken specific
regional action on trade and business development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is most people are disappointed,'' said Robert
Lees, secretary-general of the Pacific Basin Economic Council, an
association representing 1,100 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's communique also praised China for not devaluing its
currency and endorsed International Monetary Fund austerity
measures that others have criticized as the wrong prescription for
certain Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Clinton, who skipped the APEC summit
because of the Iraqi crisis, is expected to arrive in Japan today
for a two-day visit, where he will urge the world's second-largest
economy to do more for Asian recovery. He then goes to South Korea,
where he will examine economic reforms undertaken after a
staggering financial collapse and $60 billion IMF bailout a year
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNEY-HITLIST-HNS &LR;      11-18 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNEY-HITLIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TEENS SUSPENDED OVER `DEATH LIST' THAT INCLUDED BARNEY,
DICAPRIO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTI MUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUGAR LAND, Texas _ Barney the purple dinosaur, Big Bird and
actor Leonardo DiCaprio were on lists that recently led Macario
Garcia Middle School in this Houston-area suburb to suspend two
13-year-old boys.
</P>
<P>
   School authorities do not think the lists were anything other
than pranks in which the teens were naming people they disliked _
in fact, each boy's name was on his own list _ but the youths were
suspended late last month.
</P>
<P>
   With a series of violent attacks in schools nationwide this
year, school officials do not consider such pranks funny.
</P>
<P>
   The principal at Garcia Middle School on Wednesday sent out a
letter with some details of the incident, reassuring parents that
the school _ part of the Fort Bend Independent School District _ is
safe for their children.
</P>
<P>
   The teens were suspended for three days after school district
police confiscated the lists of names. The lists, made
independently of one another and not connected, were labeled ``The
List'' and ``A Death List.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Barney and Big Bird, the lists also named eight to 10
peers _ classmates the boys admitted to police they didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   The two boys, whose names were not released, told the
investigating officer they never had any intention of killing or
harming any of those on their lists, said Fort Bend ISD spokeswoman
Mary Ann Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Although district officials view the lists as a prank, it was a
serious enough prank to be deemed disruptive behavior punishable by
three days of suspension, Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think school safety is at the forefront of all of our
minds,'' said Fort Bend ISD Area III Superintendent Betty Baitland.
``We are very careful with everything we see and hear in schools
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, five teen-age boys in Burlington, Wis., were
arrested and charged with conspiracy to commit murder after a plot
to systematically shoot and kill classmates and administrators
unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   This followed more than a year of school campus horror stories
in which teachers and students were killed and wounded in violent
outbursts by young people in schools around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While the lists at the Sugar Land-area school are being viewed
as non-threatening, concerned parents just finding out about the
incident have been calling for more information, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The boys turned over their lists to a district policeman Oct. 22
after the officer heard rumors and asked the pair for them. The two
were suspended from Oct. 27-29.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia Middle School Principal Jeryl Jean Kyle could not be
reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the letter sent home to Garcia Middle School parents
Wednesday, she has likened the lists to a past middle school fad
involving so-called ``slam books,'' in which pupils were asked to
write things _ usually most unflattering _ about classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something administrators worked very hard to stop,''
Baitland said. ``It was so hurtful.''
</P>
<P>
   In her letter to parents, Kyle said a youth who saw his name on
one of the lists contacted police Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Although no criminal intent or illegal act occurred, she said in
the letter, the pupils were ``given appropriate school disciplinary
penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Simpson said, the two boys saw school counselors
and the parents of one of the boys said he would get outside
counseling as well.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators sought legal advice on just how much they could
tell the parents of those children named on the lists. Parents were
called several days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you notify a parent of something like this, the first
thing they want to know is who wrote the list,'' Baitland said.
``There are some real privacy issues. We had to get some legal
opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   The administrator said they were able to give those parents
whose children were on the lists the first names and the first
letters of the last names of the two authors.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle assured parents that their children are safe at the middle
school, and that police found ``no motive, weapons, plans or intent
to harm anyone on that list.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel things are safe and secure at Garcia,'' Baitland said.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Land is an affluent community of 44,000 people about 15
miles southwest of downtown Houston. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
