<HEADLINE>
GOP SHUFFLES HOUSE LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The post-election mutiny against Speaker Newt
Gingrich and his leadership team came to fruition Wednesday with
Gingrich formally ousted, his top lieutenant narrowly surviving,
and the first black Republican grabbing power in the House GOP
hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling their management team for the last House session of
the century, Republicans unanimously endorsed Representative Bob
Livingston of Louisiana to replace Gingrich and stopped just short
of dumping the No. 2 in the leadership, Majority Leader Richard K.
Armey of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The 223-member GOP caucus also effectively fired their
conference chairman, Representative John A. Boehner of Ohio, and
replaced him with Representative J.C. Watts, Jr., of Oklahoma, a
charismatic orator who became the first black lawmaker to hold a
national GOP leadership position.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Watts _ and the insurrection against Gingrich and
Armey _ underscored the deep unrest within the Republican caucus
after Democrats unexpectedly picked up five seats in the midterm
elections and sliced the GOP's slender majority to 11 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Watts overthrew Boehner, 121-93, he said the shift
in power ``helps us all take a serious look within ourselves and
see where do we go from here and how do we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts, a Christian conservative and former professional football
player who has refused to join the liberal Congressional Black
Caucus, responded lightheartedly when he was asked about the
historic nature of his election to the No. 4 spot in the House GOP
leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to Disneyland and celebrating!'' said Watts, who won
the position on his 41st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, 55, a 20-year House veteran who will relinquish his
powerful chairmanship of the Appropriations Committee when the
106th Congress convenes in January, delivered the message of change
that many GOP members apparently yearned for after Gingrich's
four-year tenure as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his GOP colleagues who were elected to leadership posts
Wednesday, Livingston was nominated on a voice vote for the
speaker's job. The full House will elect him in January, barring
the unforeseen and extremely unlikely possibility that the 211
House Democrats persuade at least six Republicans to join them in
blocking Livingston's election.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich began the closed-door elections by handing a gavel to
Livingston as a symbol of the stunning transition of power. He then
left Capitol Hill for a Florida vacation with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Newt stood before you with the contract, I stand before
you with a new covenant to enact our agenda and build our bases,''
Livingston told the GOP rank-and-file moments later. He was
referring to Gingrich's Contract with America, the policy
centerpiece of the Republican revolution in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas was the only top member of
Gingrich's leadership team who dodged a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiercest race, Armey scarcely withstood a multipronged
attack from Representatives Steve Largent of Oklahoma, Jennifer B.
Dunn of Washington, and J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, a draft
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, 58, who was criticized with Gingrich for failing to heed
warnings from many GOP lawmakers that they were not adequately
communicating the Republican agenda before the midterm elections,
needed three ballots to survive but finally prevailed in a
head-to-head showdown with Largent, 127-95.
</P>
<P>
   After each round, the candidate with the fewest votes was
knocked out, first Hastert, then Dunn, and finally Largent.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's near-defeat was seen by many members as a powerful
warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message that we're tired of business as usual,''
said Representative Matt Salmon, an Arizona conservative who
supported Largent. ``Ultimately, he won, but he was sent a message
that to be successful, you've got to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, more relieved and contrite than joyful, indicated he
received the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate enough that I have been provided an even more
keenly honed opportunity to learn and understand the needs and
interests of this majority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston also discerned a need for change. Referring to the
election setbacks, he told his colleagues, ``We lost focus, we
forgot to say what we stand for, who we are, what we want to do. We
didn't run out of ideas, we simply neglected to run on our ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Largent, 43, who became a Hall of Fame football receiver despite
his modest size by NFL standards, said he ``has been too slow and
too small my whole life, and this was just one more occasion. But I
will tell you that I'm not accustomed to losing, and I don't like
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Largent pledged to work with Armey and the other Republican
leaders, as did Dunn, who lost her bid to become the highest
ranking woman House leader in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to sweep up the residue and bring unity
back to our team,'' Dunn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
