<HEADLINE>
KERRY TESTS WATERS IN GRANITE STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ As he works the breakfast crowd at Yoken's, a
pit stop on the presidential primary trail, Senator John F. Kerry
is looking for signs to help him make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Dutifully, he shakes the hands of the 100 or so members of the
Chamber of Commerce who have come to hear him speak. Cheerfully, he
makes small talk from table to table, though the hour is still
early. With enough encouragement at enough places like this, Kerry
could move ahead with a presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was his second trip across the border into campaign
2000 terrain, but he is no closer to making a decision. In fact, he
said, he may not register his yea or nay until February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really in the thinking stage,'' he said. ``I can't shed
any greater light on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends, advisers, and aides are egging him on, rooting for the
go sign. From week to week, his friends go back and forth, first
predicting he will run, then backing off, then changing their minds
again.
</P>
<P>
   In his own mind, there are numerous hurdles that need to be
cleared. He still owes $1 million from his super-expensive 1996
Senate race. He and his wife, Theresa Heinz, have to decide if they
want to give up their lives as they know it. And he worries that a
compressed presidential primary process might not allow enough time
for voters to get to know him.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry will visit Atlanta Thursday, raising money to help retire
his loans. Friday he will meet with veteran political hand John
Sasso in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday night, he will be at the Wang Theatre in Boston,
trying to raise even more money with the help of a few famous
friends _ Robin Williams, Shawn Colvin, and James Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to test the waters in Iowa, another presidential
proving ground, and travel to California in December for private
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next months are pretty key,'' he said, aware that other
candidates are already raising money, locking up crucial support.
``You've got to get going at some point so as not to be left in the
dust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I've really been burdened by the debt issue,
and we're trying to get rid of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife has also signaled some reluctance toward the
roller-coaster, non-stop craziness of a national campaign run. He
said they have had ``chats'' about the possibility of his jumping
into the Democratic fray, but they have not had the serious
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said it's sort of ridiculous. That's her expression,''
Kerry said, referring to comments she made recently in New
Hampshire about his potential presidential bid. ``Later, she made
it clear that she was talking about the hurdles you have to get
over on a personal level to be able to decide to do this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If he does get in, Kerry says, both he and his wife would be
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   And he added that if he decides to run, he could run well. He
said he has a fund-raising base of $14 million to $16 million, and
one of the largest direct-mail lists in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Kerry said, his toe-in-the-water testing has
yielded an encouraging response.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sort of curiosity about the possibility,'' he said.
``I don't find doors slamming shut.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
