<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST PEACE WILL NOT COME CHEAP .. GUESS WHO'S GOING TO PAY FOR
IT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Clinton is promising Israel and the
Palestinian Authority to pick up much of the bill for their new
land-for-security plan. But buying peace will not be cheap, or
easy.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican leadership change means that congressional
scrutiny could be more acute than originally anticipated. Israel's
new aid request raises potential diplomatic problems, as the United
States runs the risk of subsidizing roads to Jewish settlements in
the West Bank. And greatly increasing aid to the Palestinians poses
financial and political difficulties, U.S. officials say.
</P>
<P>
   As the Clinton administration weighs the Israeli and Palestinian
requests, it is striving to insure that the entire aid package
strengthens rather than further complicates its role as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is expected to seek up to $1
billion for pulling Israeli forces out of the West Bank, over and
above the $2.9 billion in military and economic aid already
earmarked for Israel this fiscal year. The new request comes just
as Congress has reduced assistance to Israel for the first time in
decades, cutting its yearly economic support check to $1.08
billion, from $1.2 billion, the beginning of what was announced as
a 10-year phase-out of nonmilitary aid.
</P>
<P>
   And Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, says he believes he
has a green light to solicit as much as $300 million in new U.S.
assistance _ a big jump in U.S. aid to Palestinian-controlled Gaza
and the West Bank, which has been kept at $75 million annually for
the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, congressional approval did not seem much at
issue. The house speaker, Newt Gingrich, and the minority leader,
Dick Gephardt, had signaled readiness to provide substantial new
assistance. But the Appropriations Committee chairman, Rep. Robert
Livingston, now assured of becoming Gingrich's successor, was one
of the few congressional leaders who has publicly questioned
economic aid to Israel. Congressional critics of Arafat, meanwhile,
are likely to try to continue to block direct bilateral-style aid.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has not yet disclosed the full scope
of its new appropriation request, which represents the fulfillment
of a pledge by the president to help underwrite the costs of the
interim peace accord negotiated last month in Wye, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration is considering the details of a package
which will address Israeli security requirements relating to Wye
and Palestinian economic needs,'' Jim Foley, a State Department
spokesman, said last Friday. ``We are planning to consult with the
Hill on this package.''
</P>
<P>
   While the expected U.S. aid package will spotlight the large and
widening gap between aid to Israel and aid to the Palestinians,
irking some of Arafat's supporters, Palestinian economic officials
hope it will institutionalize U.S. economic support of the kind
Egypt has enjoyed since its 1979 peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
