<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-AID-2NDTAKE-N     11-18 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-AID-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JERUSALEM: with Israel.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the Oslo agreement in 1993, the United States announced a
five-year, $500 million economic aid package for the West Bank and
the Gaza Strip: $375 million in grants from the Agency for
International Development and $125 million in loan guarantees for
new local U.S. business ventures from the Overseas Private
Investment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The promised AID money was mostly spent _ the bulk of it on
wells, sewage systems and other water installations _ but OPIC has
provided just $6 million in the last five years. ``We cannot
undertake any assistance without a willing private investor,'' said
Lawrence Spinelli, a spokesman for the investment corporation.
</P>
<P>
   From all international sources, the Palestinian Authority was
promised $4.2 billion in foreign assistance in the five years
following Oslo, but received just $2.5 billion, most of it from
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same five-year period, Israel collected $15.3 billion
in military and economic support from the United States,
Palestinians note.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration will gather international donors in
Washington later this month to present a new aid pledge for
Palestinian-controlled areas. The Palestinians hope the meeting
will nearly double international aid outlays, to $800 million or
$900 million yearly, said Anis al-Qaq, who supervises Palestinian
aid receipts as deputy minister of planning and international
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The most contentious financing issue is the widening network of
bypass roads, circuitously linking isolated Jewish settlements in
Palestinian-governed territory and Israeli-controlled fragments of
the West Bank with each other and with Israel proper.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote to approve the Wye withdrawal pact, the Israeli
Cabinet gave the go-ahead for 12 new bypass routes serving
settlements that will now be left as enclaves within autonomous
Palestinian territory. The proposed 1999 budget, now being debated
in the Israeli Parliament, had already called for a tripling of
annual spending on bypass roads, to $28 million.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the hearts and often even the periphery of local towns
and villages, this emerging parallel road system enables Israeli
motorists to traverse the West Bank with little or no contact with
Palestinian residents. The roads also speed access to and from
Israeli military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend the bypass roads are leaching money away from
public works within Israel's borders and entrenching settlements
they oppose. A recent opinion poll commissioned by Washington
showed most Israelis opposing further spending to support Jewish
settlements deep inside the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The road-building program is even more politically fraught for
the Palestinian Authority. The bypasses almost invariably involve
expropriations of Palestinian property, followed quickly by home
demolitions, the forcible expulsion of local residents and angry
street protests led by Arafat's Palestinian opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military officers persuaded the Netanyahu government
last week to hold off on one planned route through a Palestinian
refugee camp, warning that land seizures there could provoke
violence and disrupt the Wye-mandated troop redeployments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Netanyahu has said that it is ``as clear as daylight''
that putting into effect the new peace accords would accelerate
land seizures for new bypass projects.
</P>
<P>
   In what it called an ``interim'' financing step, the Israeli
government has authorized $60 million for immediate redeployment
expenditures: $24 million to the defense ministry for withdrawing
troops and relocating military bases, $24 million to the ministry
of national infrastructure for bypass roads and $12 million to the
ministry of public security for ``civil defense'' programs in the
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to remember is that redeployment is not in the
budget,'' said Raanan Gissin, a spokesman for the ministry of
national infrastructure, which under the hard-line leadership of
Ariel Sharon greatly expanded roads and security installations for
the settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Since Israel's jurisdiction over those areas is not recognized
by the United States or any other foreign government, U.S. policy
precludes financing roads or any permanent Israeli installations in
the West Bank _ a restriction considered doubly important as
Washington tries to play the honest broker in talks between the
Israelis and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet enforcing this could be problematic, U.S. officials concede.
</P>
</TEXT>
