<HEADLINE>
SUNNY DAY REAL ESTATE BREAKS THROUGH CLOUDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The four-year moratorium on the media is over, and
members of the recently reunited Sunny Day Real Estate are finally
talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more of a story now,'' says guitarist Dan Hoerner,
from a tour stop in Orlando. ``Back in the day, we just wanted to
play and not really worry about doing the band as a career. Now
we've gotten back together and there's something to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the group had granted one interview, which came
during a 1994 tour in support of its debut release, ``Diary,'' on
the Sub Pop label.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed likely, though, that even with press attention, Sunny
Day would always remain low-key. Unlike Sub Pop counterparts such
as Nirvana and Mudhoney, who became media darlings during the
grunge era, Sunny Day was forging a name for itself in the
emotional-rock genre.
</P>
<P>
   But immediately following the release of the group's self-titled
second album _ commonly referred to as ``the pink album'' because
of its pink cover _ the members went their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just infighting,'' Hoerner says of the breakup. ``It
was little, bitchy, ridiculous things that you develop over tours
and over the course of not really knowing what you're doing and
getting in overwhelming situations.''
</P>
<P>
   During the three-year split, Hoerner fled to his farm in eastern
Washington and singer Jeremy Enigk released ``Return of the Frog
Queen,'' a solo album he composed, which was backed by a 21-piece
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In the strangest of moves, bassist Nate Mendel and drummer
William Goldsmith joined Dave Grohl's Foo Fighters _ a media
darling if ever there was one. But during the recording of the Foo
Fighters' second album, ``The Colour and the Shape,'' Goldsmith
learned that Grohl, Nirvana's ex-drummer, had recorded new drum
lines. An irate Goldsmith quit the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got screwed over in the recording,'' Hoerner says. ``He got
all his drum tracks recorded over after he worked his ass off to
put them down. He made the choice and walked away from it and I am
extremely grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith's departure from the Foo Fighters helped pave the way
for the long-awaited Sunny Day reunion. (Enigk and Hoerner had
already been working together again).
</P>
<P>
   The missing piece, of course, was Mendel. The trio had waited
six months for him to join them in the studio, but it never
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the Foo Fighters, we're like a goldfish compared
to a whale. Nate wanted to play the music of Sunny Day, but
couldn't walk away from the money of Foo Fighters,'' Hoerner says.
</P>
<P>
   The band recruited Jeff Palmer, formerly of San Francisco's
Mommy-heads, to play bass and recorded ``How It Feels to Be
Something On.''
</P>
<P>
   The album is the last the group owed Sub Pop as part of its
contract, which raises the question of whether this is a permanent
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're totally going for it,'' Hoerner says. ``We just really
want to make music. I think we're all looking forward to getting
into the studio and making the next record.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
