<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ A near doubling in the shipments of
Boeing aircraft abroad narrowed the September trade deficit to $14
billion, down nearly $2 billion from the record gap in August. But
the aircraft sales appeared to be a one-time statistical oddity,
and Commerce Department numbers reveal that the huge falloff in
exports to the Pacific Rim, combined with a growing inflow of
steel, toys and electronics, are beginning to take a larger toll on
American jobs and corporate profits. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
