<HEADLINE>
FERRY LINKS KEY WEST, FORT MYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects spelling of Fort Myers in lede item)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Florida Keys are getting easier to reach from the state's
west coast.
</P>
<P>
   A new high speed ferry from Fort Myers to Key West is expected
to begin service this month. The one-way service covers 134 miles
in just three hours, cutting traveling time by many hours when
compared to driving.
</P>
<P>
   The new ferry service will be operated by Buquebus, which also
operates high-speed ferries in Europe and South America. Two
round-trips a day are planned, with prices expected to be $55 for
coach and $75 for first-class service.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry will leave from Fort Myers' Harborside and arrive at
the foot of Grinnel Street in Key West. Food and beverage service
will be available.
</P>
<P>
   For vacationers, the new service offers new opportunities to
combine a holiday in two very different and enjoyable parts of
Florida. For more information, call 941-461-0999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Florida deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One way to save on a Florida vacation is to use the free green
Traveler Discount Guide to Florida. The guide provides auto
travelers with low rates on hotels and resorts. The guide is free
at some 12,000 locations, or may be ordered by calling
800-332-3948. A $3 shipping charge is made on telephone orders for
the first guide, with a cost of $1 for each additional guide;
credit cards are accepted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skiers heading for the French Alps can stay in accommodations as
low at $45 a night per person. Among packages offered by New
Frontiers is a week at Val Thorens that includes a six-day ski
pass, meals, taxes, and service charges, starting at $699 a person.
Air fare is available starting at $288 from New York. For
information, call 800-366-6387.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Airways is offering a variety of winter vacations in
Greece, with flights leaving from Boston. Among packages are one to
Athens from $769; Athens plus Santorini from $935; and Athens plus
Istanbul from $1,059. The packages include air fare, hotels,
breakfasts, transfers, and sightseeing. For information, call Orbit
Travel at 800-283-7277.
</P>
<P>
   A long weekend in Stockholm is available through March 25 for as
low as $498 a person, including air fare, hotels, breakfasts, and
taxes. The package is for four days and three nights in Stockholm.
An add-on trip to beyond the Arctic Circle, including a stay in the
famed Ice Hotel, is also available. The trips are from Newark to
Stockholm via SAS Scandinavian Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Priceless Ireland at Prices You Can Afford'' is a brochure
from the Irish Tourist Board featuring nine value vacations to the
west of Ireland, through April. Vacations range from a four-day
exploration for under $500 to a seven-day escorted tour of some of
Ireland's most sacred and historic sites for $1,072. The packages
include air fare, accommodations, a rental car, and breakfasts. For
a copy, call 800-SHAMROCK.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Study in England
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An educational experience for all ages is being offered by
Cambridge University in England. The 15th annual study program will
be held July 18-31 and includes seminars ranging from Thomas Hardy
and the Crusades to politics today. Students live in private rooms
with baths, and all courses have field trips and are available for
credit. For information, write to Joann Painter, Office of
Cooperating Colleges, 714 Sassafras St., Erie, PA 16501; or
telephone 814-456-0757.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Caribbean flights
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TWA will begin new services to the Caribbean from Boston and New
York. From Boston, TWA will begin five flights weekly to San Juan
on Feb. 3. The Puerto Rico service will leave Boston at 8:55 p.m.;
return flights will leave San Juan at 6:55 a.m., arriving in Boston
at 10:13 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   From New York, the airline will offer nonstop service from John
F. Kennedy Airport to Nassau daily except Wednesdays beginning Feb.
11. And TWA will offer service to Puerto Plata in the Dominican
Republic, and to St. Martin on Dec. 17. Both flights will be from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sailing guide
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A free sailing guide to more than 1,000 sailing schools,
community sailing programs, and sailboat rental operations
throughout the United States is available by calling 800-535-SAIL.
The guide offers information on participating in Discover Sailing's
free half-hour introductory sails at more than 300 schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Palace by night
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Hampton Court Palace in London can tour the palace
by lantern light through Dec. 22. The tour ranges from the Tudor
kitchens to Henry VIII's State Apartments on to the Haunted
Gallery, where the ghost of Catherine Howard, Henry's fifth wife,
is said to run screaming along the corridor. Tours are offered
Tuesday, Saturday, and Sunday evenings. For information, call
800-806-7187.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For visually impaired
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York's Hotel Delmonico on Park Avenue has opened the
Lighthouse Suite, the first suite specifically geared for people
who are visually impaired. Among room features are large-print
books and magazines, a large numerical clock, large dial
telephones, high-contrast handles and pulls on furniture, and
black-and-white decor with red accessories to provide the highest
visual contrast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For men only
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A ``for men only'' spa program has opened at the Jalousie Hilton
Resort and Spa on St. Lucia. Male spa-goers now make up 30 percent
of all spa visitors, and the Hilton has developed special
treatments, from facials and sea salt body scrubs to sulfur mud
baths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
You pick the time
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A nice feature of the Sheraton Center Toronto Hotel is its
``clean at your convenience'' program that lets guests choose when
they wish to have their room cleaned and refreshed. A doorknob card
allows guests to check off their desired cleaning time, with a
choice of four periods. Adding to the program is that mini-bar
staffers will do their checking and restocking during the selected
period, rather than interrupting guests at another time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ski guides
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ski Europe'' and ``Ski America'' by Charlies Leocha and a team
of skiers are two of the best books for checking out ski resorts.
The reviews are candid, and provide complete information on
terrain, lessons, child care, and other winter activities. A nice
feature is a profile on the each resort's personality. The books
are available from World Leisure Corp., Box 160, Hampstead, NH
03841; telephone 617-569-1966.
</P>
</TEXT>
