<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMEY11-19-COX     11-18 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMEY11-19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMEY RE-ELECTED HOUSE MAJORITY LEADER
 &HT;    765 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican U.S. House of Representatives members on
Wednesday re-elected Rep. Dick Armey of Texas as House majority
leader and tapped Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the sole black
Republican in Congress, to help GOP lawmakers deliver a unified
message during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Armey fended off three challengers to retain the No. 2 position
in the House, but his duties and visibility may be vastly curtailed
under new House Speaker Bob Livingston, R-La., who was acclaimed
Wednesday as the successor to Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich announced his resignation Nov. 6 after being blamed for
losses in the Nov. 3 election that shaved the already-thin majority
in the House and left Republicans with 223 seats to Democrats' 211.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappiness with the election results claimed two more victims
Wednesday as Republicans picked their leaders. A 130-77 vote dumped
the GOP campaign committee chairman, Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., in
favor of Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   And Republican Conference Chairman John Boehner, R-Ohio, lost
that No. 4 seat to Watts in a 121-102 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Texans survived the leadership shake-up. Majority Whip
Tom DeLay of Sugar Land was unopposed for re-election to the No. 3
job in the House, and Armey of Irving was able to stave off his
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   With the mix of new and old leaders, ``we have a good
combination of continuity and fresh faces,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas. ``This vote has re-energized Republicans and reflects a
more accurate image of us as a party.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes may not be over, however. Gingrich had ceded much of
the day-to-day running of the House to Armey, who also became
Republican lawmakers' lead spokesman at weekly news conferences and
Sunday talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is expected to take back some of the power Armey had
enjoyed, and the Texan said Wednesday he could live with that.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich ``had an awful lot of authority that he more or less
handed over to me,'' Armey said in an interview after his
re-election. ``If Bob wants to pull some of this authority back as
speaker, I'm perfectly content to have him do that because, quite
frankly, I think I took on too much in this work. I had the
responsibility while (Gingrich) retained the authority, and it
turned out to be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the authority Armey wielded over legislation came from
Gingrich's usurpation of the powers that traditionally belonged to
House committee leaders. Livingston was one of those leaders, being
Gingrich's hand-picked head of the House Appropriations committee.
</P>
<P>
   As speaker, Livingston is expected to return control to
committee leaders, which will be good news for another Texas
Republican, Rep. Bill Archer of Houston, who will return for a
final two-year term as chairman of the tax-writing Ways and Means
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   For rank-and-file Republicans, they're hoping the new team will
cure what they saw as a lack of both substance and style in the
current team. Unhappy GOP members complained that Gingrich, Armey
and other leaders failed to deliver a GOP election platform on tax
cuts, Social Security and education. And when the leaders did speak
out, insurgents complained, they looked and sounded terrible.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, one of Armey's challengers, former football star
and conservative Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla., campaigned in part on
his telegenic good looks. Another challenger, moderate Rep.
Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., gave Republicans the opportunity to promote
a woman in House leadership. Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., went on
the ballot Wednesday as a last-minute candidate who could appeal to
both conservatives and moderates.
</P>
<P>
   The election of majority leader went to three ballots, with the
lowest vote-getter dropping off at each round. Hastert fell first,
then Dunn, and finally Largent as Armey won, 127-95.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Armey's re-election, House members were complaining
about his public appearances: ``He's lousy on TV,'' said Rep. E.
Clay Shaw, R-Fla. ``It's something we have to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey blamed his bad TV presence on a Washington press corps
that is obsessed with personalities, not policy: ``You put Dick
Armey on a Sunday morning show and ask him to talk about IMF reform
or tax cuts (or) bankruptcy reform,'' he said, ``and you get a
pretty clear and concise message.''
</P>
<P>
   As for House business, Armey said he can work past the
sometimes-strained relations between Livingston and him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do fine,'' Armey said. ``Bob and I have a long and
colorful history. Fundamentally, Bob Livingston and Dick Armey are
legislators, and we will work well on that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
