<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-ARMEY-HNS &LR;      11-18 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ARMEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMEY SURVIVES CHALLENGE TO HOUSE POST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas survived
a strong challenge Wednesday as Republicans elected their new
leadership team, including the first black GOP member ever to hold
a top post.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the only black Republican in
Congress, won the No. 4 spot in his party hierarchy by beating John
Boehner of Ohio 121-93 for chairman of the GOP House caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other black lawmaker, former Rep. William Gray, D-Pa.,
had ever held a top leadership job in Congress. Gray was majority
whip from 1989-91 when he resigned from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Armey was re-elected to a third term as the No. 2 leader, but it
took three ballots for the Texan to gather a majority of votes. He
beat out Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma on a final ballot of
127-95.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Republicans chose Rep. Bob Livingston of
Louisiana as the new House speaker to replace Newt Gingrich of
Georgia who was pressured into resigning after the GOP lost five
seats to the Democrats in this year's mid-term election.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Sugar Land, Texas, was
re-elected without challenge to his No. 3 post, joining his fellow
Texan Armey of Irving as the only members of the old leadership
team to survive the election fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Both Watts, a former quarterback at the University of Oklahoma,
and Largent, a former pro football star, were backed by
conservative members who tried unsuccessfully last year to remove
Gingrich from the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Matt Salmon, one of the leaders of that failed coup, said
Watts prevailed in his race and Largent turned in ``a good
showing'' against Armey because ``people were ready for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey faced two challengers because he was generally blamed _
along with Gingrich _ for not accomplishing much in Congress this
year and for failing to develop a unifying message for Republicans
to take to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Dunn of Washington, another Armey challenger, drew
support from the more moderate wing of the caucus, but was
eliminated on the second ballot after tallying only 49 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said he was grateful to be returning next year to his old
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that ... I have been provided an even more keenly honed
opportunity to learn and understand the needs, the interests of
this majority as we go forward,'' he said shortly after his
election.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton of Ennis, who helped rally votes for Armey,
cautioned his fellow Texan to become more in touch with the
concerns of his party colleagues, especially the conservatives, in
the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dick needs to listen to the rank and file very
closely,'' Barton said.
</P>
<P>
   Watts said his addition to the leadership team would send a
message of inclusion to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for the Republican Party for America to know
that we're a party of men and women, and red, yellow, brown, black
and white Americans,'' the ex-quarterback told reporters. ``I think
we want to say to everybody that you're welcome in the Republican
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The leadership elections ended two weeks of what one member
referred to as ``a back-stabbing, dirty campaign'' by some
candidates to unseat Armey, Boehner and John Linder of Georgia, who
lost his position as chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee to Tom Davis of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   As they emerged from their meeting room, Dunn was the first to
call for members to put the leadership elections behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to sweep up the residue and bring unity
back to our team,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Livingston a short time later. He
said Republicans would quell their internal spats in an effort to
``work hard'' for the good of the country even if it means reaching
out to the Democrats and the president to get things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the American people to know that they're going to get
good, clean, honest, efficient government from us,'' Livingston
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we're all going to have to work together. We have a
slim majority.''
</P>
<P>
   After the election reverses, Republicans hold an 11-seat edge,
with 233 members to 211 for the Democrats. Rep. Bernard Sanders of
Vermont, the lone independent in Congress, usually votes with the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In brief remarks to reporters, Livingston said that Republicans
should be looking ahead with confidence to 2000 and the possibility
of winning the White House and gaining back seats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We muffed our message a little bit in the last elections,'' he
acknowledged. ``The American people held us accountable. But as Abe
Lincoln said, a slip is not a fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're going to pick ourselves up and move ourselves
forward, and advance the Republican agenda because that agenda is
what's good for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said preserving Social Security and passing tax cuts
would be at the top of that legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Although elected to his new position by his Republican
colleagues, Livingston, 55, will still have to be confirmed as
speaker in a vote by the full House when it convenes in January.
But that will be only a formality.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., met with Livingston
to discuss not only management matters related but legislative
issues that they might be able to work together on next year.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt among Republicans about who is in charge,
they were erased Wednesday when Gingrich rose to praise Livingston
during the caucus and urged members to unite behind him. In a
gesture of support, Gingrich handed Livingston a gavel and then
left on a long vacation trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, who was chairman of the Appropriations Committee
before ascending to the speakership, is a conservative like
Gingrich but is considered to be much more pragmatic in his
approach to getting legislation through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Where Gingrich tended to stress ideology over compromise,
Livingston is expected to emphasize deal-making, an art that won
him the respect of Democrats on the Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
