<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, Nov. 19, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at 206-448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Undated) Fourteen years and many billions of
dollars after President Reagan called on the country to build a
permanently manned space station, what is billed as the most
ambitious and difficult undertaking since the building of the
pyramids is about to begin. America's Cold War warrior, though,
could never have imagined when he issued his challenge in 1984 that
the first piece of the space station would be built by Russia and
launched from the republic of Kazakhstan, a country created with
the breakup of the old Soviet Union. When a Proton rocket blasts
off shortly before midnight Thursday (Seattle time), it will not
only mark a new chapter in the space age, but a grand opportunity
for The Boeing Co. to establish itself as the world's leader in the
space business. Boeing is the prime contractor for the space
station.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-LEADERSHIP-DUNN (Washington, D.C.) Jennifer Dunn's rapid
rise through the GOP leadership hit a wall yesterday as her fellow
House Republicans overwhelmingly rejected her candidacy for
majority leader. Republicans accepted Dunn's argument that a
``fresh face'' was needed to diversify a GOP leadership team that
had consisted exclusively of white men. But instead of adding a
woman to the top echelons of leadership, the Republicans made the
surprise move of elevating the lone black GOP congressman, J.C.
Watts of Oklahoma, to the post of conference chairman. Dunn now
resumes life as a rank-and-file member of Congress, pledging to
continue to work to reach out to women voters.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS (Seattle) Injuries are forcing the Seahawks to
juggle their offensive line, which means that Sunday in Dallas a
rookie (Todd Weiner) will line up across from Leon Lett, the
Cowboys' Pro Bowl defensive linemen. Not a pretty scenario for a
struggling offense and a team that has to win.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL-COLUMN-THIEL (Seattle) On ``the astonishing deadness of
Husky and Seahawk crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
