</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAM-ROCK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ALL THAT GLITTERED WAS GLAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A great scene occurs at the beginning of Todd Haynes' new movie,
``Velvet Goldmine:'' A pack of teen-age glam-rock fans, all vibrant
and sparkly in glitter makeup, high heels, flashy clothes and long
hair, run laughing through staid, gray London.
</P>
<P>
   They are clearly having the time of their lives, reveling in
their youth, their ability to shock, their sheer otherness.
</P>
<P>
   They adjust their makeup and crowd into a hall to hear the
sparkly, vibrant, campy music of Maxwell Demon (the alter ego of
Brian Slade), who comes onstage in a shower of feathers and squeals
and theatrical sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Velvet Goldmine'' gets a lot wrong _ Ewan McGregor's
Michigan-street-kid accent, for starters _ but for these few
minutes, at least, it's rock 'n' roll nirvana, and a piece of
history. Between 1972 and 1975, glam was the music of choice for
hundreds of thousands of young English rock fans _ and a few
American ones.
</P>
<P>
   The major guiding force, of course, was David Bowie, whose
theatrical live presentations and concept LPs, such as ``Diamond
Dogs,'' were loved by fans and critics.
</P>
<P>
   But right behind him (at least in England) was the art-pop of
Roxy Music, the teen heartthrob/sugar-metal of Marc Bolan's T. Rex,
the stompalong party anthems of Slade and Sweet, the more
aggressive, wise and cynical Mott the Hoople, and Gary Glitter's
campily updated take on Vegas-era Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Here was something totally different amid 20-minute
progressive-rock workouts by Yes and Jethro Tull, Led Zeppelin's
blues-based hard rock, and the folk of Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Guitar-based _ but not full of long, bombastic solos _ melodic
and given to catchy, sing-along choruses, glam could be seen as an
antidote to all of the above. Here was youth and fun and the first
blush of young lust, wild clothes and long nights of mirth-making.
Here was the party.
</P>
<P>
   As with punk (which drew from it and followed it) you didn't
have to be a virtuoso to play it. The songs were most often
concerned with being young and carefree, the romance of love and
club life (in Roxy's case), of violence and decadence and life on
the road (Mott) and related topics.
</P>
<P>
   It is in portraying the heady rush of glam that ``Goldmine''
flourishes: The era was all about the right image as much as the
actual music, although the music was frequently wonderful. Glam
could seem as much a fashion show as a musical movement, although
the music influenced even nonglam acts, like Elton John and the
Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   And because it was so campy and cute _ and the music so much
more purely pop than the boogie and prog-rock filling stadiums at
the time _ glam never caught on in America.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Bowie, who became a huge star, glam in America
consisted of bands getting one or two hit singles, such as Mott's
``All the Young Dudes.'' American hard rock fans simply wanted the
more macho, harder, deadly serious fare of Aerosmith and Black
Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'70s, glam had faded. Bowie went underground to get
his life together in Berlin; little girls grew up and got tired of
Marc Bolan (who died in an auto crash in 1977); Ian Hunter left
Mott; and Roxy Music broke up. Then punk came along and captured
the interest and imagination of a new generation of teen-age rock
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way, glam became part of the mainstream. Mott fan
Mick Jones co-founded the Clash; Roxy's sound was a huge influence
on the New Romantic movement of the '80s and, to a lesser extent,
the Cars. Joan Jett covered Glitter, and Quiet Riot had two big
hits with Slade songs, ``(Mama Weer All Crazee Now'' and ``Cum on
Feel the Noize).''
</P>
<P>
   And glam's still around: Marilyn Manson dresses up his sound and
his image to remind us of David Bowie circa 1972. English bands,
such as the London Suede and Pulp, draw on Roxy Music as a major
influence. Glitter's ``Rock and Roll Part 2'' (the one where
everybody goes ``Hey!'' over and over) is heard at basketball and
hockey games everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in England, there is talk of a ``glam revival.'' But as
glam was never a major movement here, the chances are far slimmer
that Americans will embrace it. But that's OK. Glam was about a
moment (pre-AIDS, pre-anti-drugs) when we liked our rock stars to
be flamboyant. On its own, it couldn't and wouldn't work in these
more conservative times, but its influence will never really
disappear. Dave Ferman, (817) 390-7839 dfer\Nstar-telegram.com]
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
