<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHARTON-PROFILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITH WHARTON: A LIFE NOT SO INNOCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edith Wharton was born into the society she would write about.
Her wealthy parents moved in the highest New York circles, and they
afforded their daughter a private education in the United States
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   She was born Edith Newbold Jones in 1862. At 23, she married the
considerably older Theodore Wharton, a fellow blueblood, who proved
to be neurotic and alcoholic. After only a few years, and with the
marriage possibly having never been consummated, Edith left him.
But divorce was out of the question, and she remained forever
``Mrs. Wharton.''
</P>
<P>
   She began writing short stories, and her first submissions to
women's magazines were anonymous. But after Henry James encouraged
her, she began signing her stories and made her hardcover debut at
37, just before the century's turn, with the story collection
titled ``The Greater Inclination.''
</P>
<P>
   Five books later and securely established, Edith Wharton moved
permanently to France in 1907, returning only occasionally to
America for brief visits. What the American literary community
learned about Wharton during her years of living abroad was mainly
what she chose to reveal. Confident that her celebrity would
endure, she left letters and other papers ``for my biographer,''
and was certain that she had accomplished an immaculate deception.
</P>
<P>
   Several earlier Wharton biographers never caught on, but R.W.B.
Lewis did a more thorough investigation, found other papers and
decoded information about a long love affair initiated soon after
Edith took residence abroad. The man in question was a man of
letters _ Morton Fullerton, himself unhappily wedded _ and their
secret liaison endured until Fullerton died in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' biographical study of Wharton won the Pulitzer Prize and
National Book Critics Circle Award for 1976. In its aftermath,
scholars have correlated Edith Wharton's life with her more
renowned works, particularly ``Ethan Frome'' (paraphrasing her own
unhappy marriage) and ``The Age of Innocence'' (the affair with
Fullerton).
</P>
<P>
   Edith Wharton died in 1937. She is buried at Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-FILMS-2TAKES-$     11-18 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIM, SHOCKING, DIDACTIC, A NEW NEW WAVE ROLLS IN  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 22)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
Phillip Lopate's collection of film criticism, ``Totally, Tenderly,
Tragically,'' has just been published by Anchor Books. 
 By PHILLIP LOPATE  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days a mood of optimism and brash confidence has once
again taken hold of French filmmaking. A new generation of films _
``My Sex Life,'' ``Irma Vep,'' ``The Dreamlife of Angels'' and ``I
Stand Alone'' _ is causing an international stir with its
uninhibited depictions of contemporary society, and taking festival
prizes and even finding American distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Some are calling it the new New Wave, the Next Wave or the
Re-New Wave; others, more skeptically, a hype-created ripple.
</P>
<P>
   The original Nouvelle Vague, or New Wave, of the 1960s looks, in
retrospect, like a miracle, with Jean-Luc Godard, Francois
Truffaut, Eric Rohmer, Claude Chabrol, Alain Resnais, Louis Malle,
Jacques Rivette, Agnes Varda and Jacques Demy all re-inventing
cinema as free expression. Even if such a national renaissance
cannot expect to be repeated in a half-century, there is no
question that French filmmaking is undergoing a resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   The old New Wave was a band of brothers: Parisian
film-critics-turned-directors who started out as friends and
collaborators (whatever fallings-out later occurred). But the
current crop of auteurs tends to be more fragmented and tribal.
</P>
<P>
   To oversimplify: one tribe (Arnaud Desplechin, Olivier Assayas,
Mathieu Amaric) consists of Parisian, largely Jewish, intellectuals
making realistic, urbane, analytical films about the lives of
graduate students, wannabe writers and professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Another tribe (Erick Zonca, Gaspar Noe, Mathieu Kassovitz, Bruno
Dumont) focuses more somberly and often angrily on the working
class _ dropout youths from the provinces or the housing project
neighborhoods or suburbs, who either get into trouble or get
trapped on the assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most gifted of the lot is Arnaud Desplechin. His
first feature, ``La Sentinelle'' (released here last month), was a
fascinatingly layered drama about a medical student finding a
severed head; his attempt at identifying it leads to a hornet's
nest of issues about loyalty and politics at the end of the cold
war.
</P>
<P>
   Besides writing extraordinarily eloquent dialogues, Deplechin is
a stickler for physical gestures and will film multiple takes until
he gets exactly the right shrug or cigarette angle he is looking
for. His second feature _ and so far the masterpiece of the new New
Wave _ is ``My Sex Life (or How I Got Into an Argument),'' a
three-hour, richly novelistic comedy about several brainy,
competitive, neurotic philosophers.
</P>
<P>
   The charmingly hangdog Mathieu Amalric plays Paul, a perpetual
student who can't seem to finish his doctorate and keeps
vacillating among three women. Amalric, whom the New York Times
film critic Janet Maslin described as ``his generation's
Jean-Pierre Leaud,'' projects a shy, likable warmth,
self-deprecating intelligence and decency even when he is playing
lecherous Peter Pan characters who resist growing up. (Amalric's
own feature, ``Eat Your Soup,'' was praised by Godard as the best
film he'd seen in years.)
</P>
<P>
   Fellow filmmakers were drawn to him. ``I think it's because I
wasn't an actor at the start that I got used so much; I know I have
very little range,'' Amalric said in New York recently, with a
puckish smile. ``I mostly work for filmmakers who speak in the
first person, and who can imagine me as their alter ego.''
</P>
<P>
   Where did this ``first person'' style come from? One of the less
desirable effects of the original New Wave's aura was its tendency
to eclipse the very talented generation of filmmakers that
immediately followed. Maurice Pialat, Andre Techine, Chantal
Akerman, Bertrand Tavernier, Jean Eustache, Philippe Garrel, Benoit
Jacquot and Jacques Doillon, all labored in the shadow of the New
Wave's glamour, creating a daring, often brilliant body of work
without ever achieving name art-house status.
</P>
<P>
   But the personal, intransigently marginal filmmaking of
(especially) Eustache, Garrel, Ms. Akerman and Doillon had a
greater influence on the younger filmmakers than did their New Wave
elders.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Eustache's ``Mother and the Whore'' (1973), a
three-hour film about an overeducated, underachieving guy torn
between two women, has haunted much of the French cinema that
followed, setting a reproachful standard for honesty and intensity.
Its archetypal French film plot, of extracting oneself from an old
love and immersing oneself in a new, had an obvious influence on
Deplechin's ``My Sex Life'' and Garrel's ``Birth of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from the other camp, Gaspar Noe has said: ``I love
Eustache. He came from the lower class, and he had some anger,
something existentialist, almost Dostoyevskian, that is totally
missing in the other French directors.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Wave opened the door to a fresher, more casual
filmmaking approach: real locations, improvisations, jump-cuts,
hand-held camera, self-reflexive distancing jokes. Today's younger
filmmakers take this vocabulary as a matter of course; their shocks
come from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Gaspar Noe's ``I Stand Alone'' is an act of aggression against
audiences: its protagonist, an unemployed butcher, kicks his
pregnant wife in the stomach and either slits his daughter's throat
(or fantasizes doing so) while spewing racist, homophobic,
incestuous thoughts on the soundtrack. All in the service of what
the filmmaker calls ``a cinema of catharsis.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this brutality is undercut by jarring sound effects,
supergraphic titles and a sly, over-rhetorical expressionism. Noe
says that the deadpan comedy in Leonard Kastle's 1970 cult classic,
``The Honeymoon Killers,'' served as his model.
</P>
<P>
   A slight, polite, head-shaven young man, Noe was delighted that
a man fainted at this year's Toronto Film Festival screening, and
chagrined that the New York Film Festival audience seemed to take
his shock treatment in stride. Callowly provocative as his
worldview sometimes seems, he has a filmmaker's instinctive touch:
a genius for arresting compositions and poetically grim locations.
</P>
<P>
   Noe professes little use for the films of his contemporaries
Assayas and Desplechin, much less Rohmer, with their (to his mind)
privileged, boringly bourgeois characters. He much prefers the
stark, harsh portrait of a racist delinquent in Bruno Dumont's
``Life of Jesus,'' which won le Prix Jean Vigo for best first
feature in 1997, or Mathieu Kassovitz's lacerating if sophomoric
``Hate,'' about disaffected multicultural youth, or this year's
surprise debut hit Erick Zonca's ``Dreamlife of Angels,'' which
follows the dead-end lives of two young working-class women.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Lumpen types are more naked, you can see their scars more
easily. I don't think I could ever shoot a movie about high
society,'' says Noe.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Assayas, at 43 the veteran of the Parisian group, rolls
his eyes at Noe's comments; he's heard it all before. ``I respect
his and his friends' filmmaking, but what I don't like is their
saying that the reality they're depicting is the only reality. I
don't like the sanctimonious aspect of their discourse. To my mind,
modern alienation, the pain of everyday life, the lack of meaning,
is as strong and disturbing for the petit bourgeoisie as for the
working class.''
</P>
<P>
   Assayas has evoked that pain most powerfully in his 1994 film
``Cold Water,'' about middle-class youth in the 70s who lash out at
inner emptiness with drugs, stealing and self-destructive behavior.
The remarkable 20-minute party scene in which they trash a suburban
home is one of the apotheoses of recent French cinema, and a
triumph of Assayas' patient, observantly mobile camera.
</P>
<P>
   He followed it up with the comic, wildly satiric ``Irma Vep''
(1996), starring the Hong Kong actress Maggie Cheung, about a film
production that also gravitates toward chaos.
</P>
<P>
   But in his most recent film, the soon-to-be-released ``Late
August, Early September,'' Assayas opts for a more thoughtful,
mature focus, as he charts a circle of friends turning 40 and
facing career disappointments, aging and death. There is nothing
``privileged'' or ``safe'' about the raw feelings and economic
struggles of this group on the precipitous verge of middle age,
still trying to construct authentic selves.
</P>
<P>
   An important filmmaker who bridges the Parisian and the
proletarian group is Claire Denis. She is a good friend of Assayas,
and her movies (like ``No Fear, No Die'' and ``I Can't Sleep'')
treat the problems of African guest-workers or Algerian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In these subtle, empathetic films, Ms. Denis uncovers the
growing pains of a new, multicultural French society, without the
blunt didacticism of other, politically progressive filmmakers who
are trying to speak out against the National Front's brand of
racism.
</P>
<P>
   Issues of class, cinematic style and genre can't help
intersecting. The bruised, proletariat characters in last year's
``Life of Jesus'' _ as inarticulate as cows in the field _ are
served well by a bleakly minimalist Bressonian style. Paradoxically
the audience for such movies is almost entirely the educated middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the film theorist Stanley Cavell once
observed that one of the reasons the characters in witty talking
comedies were nearly all middle-class was that the middle class had
the leisure to converse. Another key dividing line in French cinema
today is the degree to which the pervasiveness of American
filmmaking is resisted or embraced.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, even as the French film industry began to
speak out against the market domination of Hollywood, many French
film school graduates became enamored of the jazzy rhythms and
darkly smirking attitudes of Quentin Tarrantino, David Lynch and
other American independent filmmakers. As one of these graduates,
Gaspar Noe, said, ``I feel more in common with Todd Haynes' `Velvet
Goldmine' or Todd Solondz's `Happiness' than I do with most French
filmmakers.'' His new motion picture, ``Enter the Void,'' will be
shot in English.
</P>
<P>
   His friend Mathieu Kassovitz has also moved, temporarily, to
Hollywood and is trying to mount an English-language production.
The Parisian tribe of Deplechin and Assayas would seem to be
clinging to a more self-consciously French style, with their
slower, talkier, more character-driven and nuanced chamber dramas.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the two esthetics is hilariously sent up in
Assayas' ``Irma Vep,'' when a young French journalist interviews
Maggie, the beautiful Hong Kong actress who is about to star in an
art-film remake of the 1915-16 classic ``Les Vampires.''
</P>
<P>
   The journalist says he can't stand these precious French art
films; the only motion pictures that are truly alive are the Hong
Kong and Hollywood action flicks. His harangue is actually a
paraphrase of opinions expressed by Mathieu Kassovitz in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But when I asked Assayas whom he was satirizing he said:
``Myself! He's like a monstrous version of myself as a young man. I
began in film criticism, I wrote the issue on Hong Kong movies for
Cahiers du Cinema and then I found, to my horror, that people were
using Hong Kong action films to trash the values of the other
moviemakers whom I loved _ like Bergman and Rohmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most of the original New Wave directors are still
alive and working, though their avuncular expressions no longer
shake the world as they did when they were Young Turks. Rohmer's
most recent, ``Tale of Autumn,'' is the wise, delicately witty work
of a septuagenarian; Resnais' latest, ``Same Old Song,'' is
sublimely mellow, melancholy, lyrical; Godard continues to stretch
the boundaries between fiction and essay-film with his video
series, ``Histoire(s) du Cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   The patriarchs are busy commenting, kibitzing, appreciating (and
sometimes, no doubt, wishing ill to) the younger filmmakers who
have inherited their mantle, and who basically ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   Both the new Parisian and the provincial-working-class camps
have surprisingly much in common: a sexual frankness; an emotional
grittiness; an openness to Cassavetes-inspired, informal camera
work, a resistance to the frothy lure of ``Gallic charm,'' which
many Americans still expect from French movies.
</P>
<P>
   France has continuously been one of the great national cinemas _
which means that at no time in the last hundred years have
impressive movies not been made there. But American audiences don't
always get the chance to see French quality films because of the
vagaries of distribution.
</P>
<P>
   During the 80s, there was a near-blackout; now, thanks partly to
the promotional hype surrounding this new New Wave, that situation
may be rectified. If so, it is hype in a worthy cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
