<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GLITZ, GLAMOUR PUT GLOSS IN YULE
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This holiday season, go for the glitz and the glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the perfect time of the year to go a little over the
top,'' says Jerry Bolduan, a contributing editor to Martha Stewart
Living magazine. ``If last year you decorated with just flowers or
fruit, mix flowers, fruits and foliage this season. And use twice
as many flowers.'' But he warns, ``this is not inexpensive to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For more glitz, he suggests silver or gold accents. John Loring,
design director for Tiffany &AMP; Co., agrees that ``the holidays cry
out for glitter.'' He says: ``Don't forget silver tinsel and plenty
of lights on the tree. Three strings won't do.''
</P>
<P>
   To add a special glow and warmth to any holiday setting, Atlanta
interior designer Melissa Galt uses candles. ``I love to group
candles in odd numbers for greater impact,'' she says. ``For
example, place one candle on one end of the mantel, three on the
other end, perhaps five on a coffee table.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
