<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin at last gelling with her `ER' co-stars
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes a village to save an ``ER,'' something the NBC drama
finally gets through its pointy head tonight (10 ESTon NBC) to
produce its most gripping episode of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It's classic ``ER.'' The show has spent most of this season
idling in a frustrating neutral _ focusing too much on perky new
intern Lucy Knight (perky Kellie Martin) and pushing plots along as
though someone forgot to take the safety off the County General
gurneys.
</P>
<P>
   But tonight ``ER'' gets back to its whiz-bang roots: dying kid,
lots of operating room heroics by lots of different docs, tension
between characters that becomes its own subplot and an ending that
leaves things profoundly unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   And while Martin again gets too much face time _ there will come
a point tonight when you'll wish you could reach right through the
TV screen and put a sock in her mouth _ her character finally
becomes part of the ensemble. She's not just there to bug Dr. John
Carter (Noah Wyle), though she does plenty of that. She's finally
there to make his character grow up into something else.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other plot lines this season that have strolled casually
through the back door, things hop tonight from the start. A little
girl is wheeled into the ER with a bleeding spleen, an injury she
got with her father in a car accident. She needs a blood
transfusion, and the only one who can be located quickly with her
rare blood type is her father. But he splits the hospital without
anyone knowing it: He'd kidnapped the girl from his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   While the battery of regulars work like mad to keep the girl
alive, Carter and Lucy head out into the cool Chicago night to find
the father. Their amateur sleuthing is often as much a competition
between them as it is a search for the girl's dad. Carter is as
controlling as Lucy is headstrong, and it's when they finally meet
in the middle that they both become something new and interesting.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for TV's best drama, which until tonight hasn't
seemed new or interesting all year.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   The one about turkey
</P>
<P>
   More people are watching ``Friends'' this season than last.
There's a good reason: While much of TV's best returning shows
aren't clicking this season, ``Friends'' is.
</P>
<P>
   Or, rather, has been.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's Thanksgiving episode (8 o'clock ESTon NBC) is
serviceable _ and sometimes even outright funny _ but not nearly as
inventive as we might like.
</P>
<P>
   The gang relives a string of Thanksgiving memories, all full of
sight gags that for the most part would be better left to the
memory of Lucille Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ones you won't want to miss: Chandler (Matthew Perry)
in the '80s with his hair coifed into a Flock of Seagulls do,
Monica's (Courteney Cox) return to her fat years and Rachel
(Jennifer Aniston) with her old nose.
</P>
<P>
   The Ross-Emily plot does finally get a rest. And we hope it's
over and done with.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
