<HEADLINE>
MIT MEDIA LAB TO DEVELOP PROGRAM FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Media Lab, where academics develop everything from
personalized news broadcasts to wearable computers, is among the
most famous research centers at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now MIT is set to open a kiddie version of the Media Lab, thanks
to a $27 million grant from the chairman of Japanese video game
maker Sega Enterprises Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The cash grant, one of the largest ever received by the
university, comes from Isao Okawa, chairman of Sega and of its
parent, CSK Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than games, however, the center's researchers will
develop new technologies aimed at enhancing the social activities
of children and teenagers, such as storytelling, dance, music, and
visual arts.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Media Lab's efforts among children have focused
primarily on the development of ``intelligent toys'', such as Lego
blocks containing computer chips that control mechanical operations
like turning wheels and triggering camera shutters. In 1990, the
MIT Media Lab received a $3 million grant from Sega's rival,
Nintendo, to study how video games can be a learning tool for
children. However, Nintendo reportedly is no longer a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Now the school wants to help children experience computers in
more social environments. The latest venture is based on Okawa's
views that digital technologies offer a chance to make fundamental
changes in education _ or, as the school puts it in a press
release, to ``rethink the nature of childhood itself.'' Okawa has
funded children's conferences on similar themes.
</P>
<P>
   A more formal research agenda will be drawn up by Mitchel
Resnick, a computer scientist at the Media Lab who also leads
efforts to create intelligent toys.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Resnick said &UR;  &LR;  the center's main &UR;  &LR; goal &UR;  &LR; is to
``find out how new technologies might enter the lives of children
in more meaningful ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The new institute, to be known as the Okawa Center, will be
affiliated with the Media Lab. It will be housed in a new building
to be built next to the Media Lab, near Kendall Square, that is
expected to open in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Another building will be torn down to make room for the new one,
said an MIT spokeswoman. The new facility will be designed by a
Tokyo architectural firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
