<SLUG> BC-BBA-MVP-GONZALEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ GARNERS SECOND MVP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe now Juan Gonzalez will get some respect. For the second
time in three years, he has been voted the American League's Most
Valuable Player, and it wasn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   The man who had the most RBIs in the AL in 49 years and led the
Texas Rangers to their second AL West title in three seasons easily
won over a star-studded field in the voting announced Wednesday by
the Baseball Writers Association of America. The Texas outfielder
received 21 first-place votes and seven seconds for 357 points.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra was a distant second with
232 points, including five firsts, seven seconds, and seven thirds.
The 1997 AL Rookie of the Yeear will receive a $75,000 bonus
because of his high finish.
</P>
<P>
   In third place was Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter with 180
points, including two firsts, six seconds, and three thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Red Sox players received votes. Free agent first
baseman Mo Vaughn finished in a fourth-place tie with Seattle's Ken
Griffey with 135 points. Closer Tom Gordon got 27 points, Cy Young
Award runner-up Pedro Martinez 1.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez batted .318 this year with 45 home runs and a league
high of 50 doubles. His 157 RBIs were the most in the AL since Ted
Williams and Vern Stephens each had 159 for Boston in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of support for Gonzalez was somewhat surprising. In
1996, he barely nosed out Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez,
290-287. Rodriguez would have won had he received the vote of a
Seattle writer.
</P>
<P>
   This time Gonzalez had no such competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I felt more comfortable this year because of my
numbers and my team,'' he said via teleconference from his home in
Puerto Rico. ``We won the division title, and that was a plus for
me. To finish first in a field like this is a great honor for me. I
give a lot of credit to Nomar and the rest of the guys behind me in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for me has always been to stay healthy,'' added
Gonzalez, who played in a career-high 154 games. ``When I'm
healthy, I'm able to put up the best numbers that I can. I have a
trainer who goes with me everywhere, and that really helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing I had going for me was the great chemistry
inside the lines and inside the clubhouse. We're like a family.
Everybody works so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was on fire early in the season. He had 101 RBIs by the
All-Star break, and at the end of July, he had 116 RBIs in 105
games, posing a threat to the major league record of 190
established by the Cubs' Hack Wilson in 1930. But in the final two
months, opponents pitched around him, and even though his average
went up, his power totals leveled off. Gonzalez was also bothered
by hamstring pulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed that I didn't get the record,'' he
said. ``I knew when I drove in 101 RBIs in the first half, I had a
great chance for the record. In the second half, I had Rusty Greer
hitting in front of me, and they'd rather pitch to him. It made a
difference. He wound up having more opportunities than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez already has the respect of home run king Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great, great hitter,'' McGwire said in a recent
interview. ``But the sad thing is, if somebody said, `Who was the
MVP in the American League in 1996?' I'd bet nobody really knows.
It's Juan Gonzalez. Year in and year out, he puts up the numbers.
It just seems he doesn't get the notoriety that he should.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he still thinks he can break the RBI record, the
29-year-old Gonzalez said, ``It's not impossible. I just need to
stay healthy and keep working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said the thought of being the first Latin American
player to win the MVP Award twice is pleasing. But he has another
goal _ for Dominican slugger Sammy Sosa of the Cubs, author of 66
homers and a major league-leading 158 RBIs, to win the National
League MVP Award today. Sosa is considered the front-runner, ahead
of the Cardinals' McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd vote for Sammy,'' Gonzalez said. ``It would be a special
moment if two players from Latin America could win the MVP Award
the same year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy had great numbers and a great year. No one should forget
that both he and Mark McGwire broke Roger Maris's (home run)
record. Mark did hit 70. My feelings go towards Sammy because of
Chicago winning the wild-card race.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
