<SLUG> BC-EMELLE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fiery deaths put commune in spotlight
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMELLE, Ala. _ They call this place the Holyland, but Tuesday
evening one building on this religious commune became a hellish
deathtrap for four small children.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left of a dormitory that housed 78 people is a
smoldering tangle of burned mattresses and charred iron bed frames,
and four red flags marking where the two boys and two girls, aged 3
to 5, died.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year-old girl knocked over a lamp, causing the fire at the
commune in this remote farming community near the Mississippi
border, said Sumter County Sheriff Johnny Hatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids didn't know what to do, and by the time the adults
saw what was going on, the place was in flames,'' Hatter said. Two
mangled, ash-covered buckets, evidence of an effort to stop the
fire, lay in the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Holyland, an Apostolic, self-reliant community, was started 20
years ago by Luke Edwards, a 72-year-old preacher who has been
accused of running a cult and building a business empire by making
poor blacks work for him for little pay. Edwards, who lives in a
modest trailer at the front of the 54-acre property where some 150
people live and work, was not available for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Most Holyland residents shied away from the media, but Denise
Chapman, 41, who has lived here 18 years, defended the community as
a haven for poor and troubled African- Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, 99 percent of our church in Meridian (Miss.)
was on welfare,'' she said. ``We pooled our resources and now no
one is on welfare. I came from Michigan an ex-drug addict. They
changed my life. I'd probably be dead now.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the members are not from the area, and many are troubled
youths from cities as far away as Chicago, sent here by their
parents to straighten them out.
</P>
<P>
   The community raises its own food and livestock, schools the
children and provides medical care. It is part of a
multimillion-dollar operation called Reach that owns four
restaurants, three motels, three stores, a slaughterhouse, an
airplane, and three limousines. A 1997 Associated Press story said
the empire was started by church members who used food stamps to
buy food wholesale and used it to open the first store.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has been hit with repeated lawsuits, child labor fines
and claims by his daughter and some former members of sexual
improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   Hatter said he is not familiar with any troubles with the place,
except for the occasional teen trying to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had reports of kids knocking on neighbors' doors trying
to get away,'' he said. ``And kids have stolen cars, trying to get
back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Clement Scott, a pilot from Tuskegee who teaches some of the
kids how to fly, laughed at suggestions that Holyland was a cult.
He was at the site Wednesday to see if he could help his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what they are doing here,'' he said. ``It's not a cult,
it's just people working for the whole group. They're doing good
things here. I've never had anybody try to recruit me. And look,
they don't even have a gate. People can come and go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
