</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich leaves capital as successor nominated
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newt Gingrich left town quietly Wednesday after
urging Republicans to rally around his presumptive successor as
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and his wife, Marianne, boarded a plane for an
undisclosed location in Florida late Wednesday morning shortly
before his Republican colleagues in the House made Rep. Robert
Livingston of Louisiana their nominee for speaker. The full House
will elect the speaker when it convenes on Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief address to GOP House members, Gingrich said he told
them, ``It's been a great emotional experience for Marianne and me
to have had these years working together with our team.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said Livingston will ``make a great successor.'' Other
Republicans said the speaker made a plea for party unity, saying it
is the only way Livingston will succeed with the party's narrow,
six-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston launched a challenge to Gingrich Nov. 6, three days
after Republicans suffered a loss of five seats in the House in the
midterm election. Before the day was out, Gingrich announced he
would not seek another term as speaker and also would leave the
House.
</P>
<P>
   He has not revealed the terms of his departure, but his aides
have said Gingrich does not intend to take his seat in the 106th
Congress. Once he has vacated his seat, the governor will issue a
call for a special election.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich did not elaborate Thursday on what he plans to do after
he leaves Congress, except to tell CNN it will be a ``public life
on the outside,'' where he said he will be making speeches and
``talking about where we need to go as a country.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker is not expected to return to Washington until Dec. 8
for the lighting of the Christmas tree on the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
