A7833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-BAXTER-COLUMN19-C     11-18 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BAXTER-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP takes larger step southward
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One reason for the restlessness among congressional
Republicans, it was widely said last week, is a desire for a
leadership less dominated by Southern white males. So much for
that.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled a bit, but Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas held
on to his post in Wednesday's House caucus elections, joining
Speaker-elect Bob Livingston of Louisiana and whip Tom DeLay of
Texas to leave the party's top three positions in SWM hands. The
election of Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma and Rep. Tillie Fowler of
Florida to party posts did add some racial and gender diversity to
the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But if anything, the former University of Oklahoma wishbone
quarterback's defeat of Ohio Rep. John Boehner in the race for
conference chair bumps up the Southern male part of the quotient a
few more degrees, while the success of Fowler, daughter of the late
Georgia state Sen. Culver Kidd, in the race for vice chair gives
the leadership an even more Southern stamp.
</P>
<P>
   This should not be too surprising. The SWM critique somewhat
misses the point of how so many Republicans got to Congress in the
first place. Also, it gets a bit mushy when Newt Gingrich, an SWM
born in Harrisburg, Pa., is replaced as speaker by Livingston, an
SWM born in Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, an SWM born in Cando, N.D., struggled a bit but managed
to avoid being smitten by the sword that Gingrich fell on. Not so
for Georgia's John Linder, born in Deer River, Minn., who took the
fall for the party's disappointing showing this month and lost his
job to Virginia's Tom Davis, an SWM born in Minot, N.D.
</P>
<P>
   As this birthplace tour is intended to illustrate, the old
regional generalities are being replaced by more modern means of
political location.
</P>
<P>
   Airports, for instance: Livingston and Armey both represent
districts that have grown around large metro airports, as did
Gingrich before he moved to the newly created 6th District. This is
not coincidence, but a natural process of leaders rising out of
places where their party's voters have accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's district outside New Orleans and Armey's outside
Dallas combine a solid base of Republican suburbia with a stretch
of conservative rural counties, which could also describe those in
Georgia represented by Linder, Bob Barr and Mac Collins. Or, for
that matter, the district outside Seattle represented by Rep.
Jennifer Dunn, who fell short in her bid for majority leader
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There's no more representative example of the new post-regional
geography than Florida, and that state's GOP chairman, Tom Slade,
has announced he's challenging Jim Nicholson of Colorado for the
party's national chairmanship _ the next test of how restive the
party is after the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia GOP Chairman Rusty Paul said Wednesday he thinks the
Republican National Committee is about evenly split among those who
want to dump or keep Nicholson and those who haven't made up their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this: The Republican base is furious,'' Paul
said after a blistering state executive committee meeting over the
weekend. That base _ which includes quite a few SWMs _ isn't going
to wait long for the new leadership team to turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
