A7835 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-LINDER19-COX     11-18 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LINDER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Linder's loss of rank linked to poor GOP performance at polls
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Linder became the second Georgian to fall
from the GOP leadership ranks when House Republicans on Wednesday
gave Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia Linder's job.
</P>
<P>
   Davis won a two-year term as chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, which Linder ran for the past two years.
Davis easily defeated Linder, 130-77.
</P>
<P>
   Critics and supporters of Linder alike agreed that the Georgian
carried ``too much baggage,'' in Rep. Nathan Deal's (R-Ga.) words,
following the GOP's unexpected loss of five seats in the
congressional midterm election. The NRCC recruits candidates and
raises money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to accept some of the blame, whether it was justified
or not,'' said Deal, who voted for Linder.
</P>
<P>
   Davis got help from Rep. Tom DeLay (R-Texas), the House Majority
Whip, who put his vote-counting operation to work for the
Virginian.
</P>
<P>
   Linder campaigned hard for another two years as chairman,
boasting of his success in raising money. One critic, Rep. Joel
Hefley of Colorado, said Linder had ruffled some feathers in his
quest for campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linder raised a lot of money, but he didn't do it with any
grace and he threatened us no matter how much we gave. If we gave
$50,000, he wanted $100,000. If we gave $100,000, he wanted
$200,000,'' Hefley said.
</P>
<P>
   Linder, 56, easily won a fourth term in Congress on Election
Day. But in the wake of the GOP's disappointing performance, he
immediately came under fire.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich told Linder he would have to run for his
post, rather than be appointed by the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's own decision to step down temporarily took the
focus off Linder, but did not satisfy the thirst for change in the
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There clearly was a desire for change and I was a perfect
target for that,'' Linder said following the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In Davis, the Republicans chose a more moderate politician who
represents a suburban Washington district. Davis, 49, also is a
prolific fund raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a broad-based party. We have a great message. We need to
look at more messengers. We're looking at keeping our party base
broad and open to all who share our philosophy,'' Davis said after
his victory. He was first elected in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Linder, who probably will retain his seat on the powerful Rules
Committee, said he knew faced his long odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by fighting the fight and being able to talk to 180
people, I think I cleared the air about what the committee did and
did not do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a trying two weeks, Linder even managed a joke.
With more time on his hands the next two years, he said, ``Maybe
I'll get a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
