<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOPLEADERS19-COX     11-18 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPLEADERS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watts chosen for fourth-ranking slot in House
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans gave their only African-American
member the fourth-ranking slot in the House hierarchy Wednesday as
they chose some new faces and some familiar ones as leaders in the
next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts (R-Okla.), a former All-America quarterback,
became the first black man to hold a Republican leadership position
in the House when he defeated Rep. John Boehner (R-Ohio) for
Republican Conference chairman, whose job is to promote the party's
agenda and keep members informed about legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner had sought a third two-year term as chairman, but he
absorbed some of the blame for the Republicans' ineffectiveness
over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, who won 121-93, said his election sends a message of
Republican inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for the Republican Party for America to know
that the Republican Party _ that we're a party of men and women,
and red, yellow, brown, black and white Americans,'' said Watts,
who turned 41 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Newt Gingrich stepping down at the end of the current term,
Republicans unanimously chose Rep. Bob Livingston of Louisiana as
their candidate for speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, the House Appropriations Committee chairman, pledged
to work with Democrats, but also sought to reassure his
conservative colleagues. ``We will do so to advance Republican
principles'' of less government, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, 55, still must be elected by the full House, but
that is considered a formality. He identified his top priorities as
preserving Social Security and cutting taxes, an agenda quite
similar to Gingrich's.
</P>
<P>
   While Watts was claiming a victory for diversity, another
aspiring leader who campaigned on that theme fell short in her bid
to become majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jennifer Dunn (R-Wash.) finished third in the balloting.
House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas won a third term over
Rep. Steve Largent, another football-playing Oklahoman. On the
third ballot, after Dunn had been eliminated, Armey defeated
Largent, 127-95.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Texan Tom DeLay, the House majority whip, also earned
another two years from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.), chairman of the National
Republican Congressional Committee, did not fare as well, losing
his post to Rep. Tom Davis (R-Va.).
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's challenge to Armey opened up her position as
vice-chairman of the conference. Republicans chose Rep. Tillie
Fowler, a six-year member of the House, as Dunn's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler, a Georgia native, is the daughter of the late Democratic
state Sen. Culver Kidd of Milledgeville.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining members of the leadership team stayed the same.
Rep. Chris Cox (R-Calif.) will remain chairman of the Republican
policy conference and Rep. Deborah Pryce (R-Ohio) will stay on as
Cox's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
