<SLUG> BC-DORMITORY-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR CHILDREN DIE IN COMMUNE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMELLE, Ala. _ Four small children died in a fire that destroyed
a dormitory at a religious commune whose founder has been praised
as a self-help visionary and scorned as a cult leader.
</P>
<P>
   The fire Tuesday night at a 54-acre compound called ``Holyland''
was apparently caused by a 10-year-old girl who knocked over a
lamp, said Sumter County Sheriff Johnny Lee Hatter. The lamp
ignited bedsheets, and the fire reduced the wooden building to
little more than ashes and the charred remains of metal-frame beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went up fast from there,'' Hatter said in an interview.
``All that was left was the rubble, and we've been digging through
that all day.''
</P>
<P>
   As investigators sifted through the building's remnants
Wednesday, four red flags marked the spots where the searchers
found the children, two boys and two girls ages 3 to 5.
</P>
<P>
   Their identities were not immediately released and it was not
known if they were among the children of Holyland's 72-year-old
founder, Luke Edwards, who by some accounts has fathered more than
a dozen children with members of his flock. Edwards has acknowleged
fathering 18 children _ nine each by his first and second wives _
but denied fathering children out of wedlock. He could not be
reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all in mourning, but we will rebuild,'' said Martin
Crawford, an Edwards assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Hatter said an initial investigation of the fire showed there
was no foul play involved. However, a spokesman for the fire
marshal's office said it was too early to determine whether any
laws were broken. Hatter said the building had smoke detectors, but
no sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   The building was one of seven wooden structures, three mobile
homes and several sheds that dot the property along with rusty
earth-moving equipment. At least one other fire has occurred at the
western Alabama commune near the Mississippi line. A nursery and
preschool building were destroyed in 1993. No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports indicated the fire was being treated as
suspicious, but Hatter said that was not the case. He also said the
controversies surrounding Edwards would not color authorities'
treatment of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't had no problems at all with him,'' the sheriff said.
``To me it's just a business he's running.''
</P>
<P>
   Few others who know Edwards are so sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, Edwards's unique approach to self-help _ an
unorthodox blend of business savvy, low-cost labor and
old-fashioned begging _ has earned him publicity and a decidedly
mixed reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Some praised him as a religious entrepreneur who moved his
congregation of poor blacks from welfare to work. But others
derided him as a self-interested charlatan who built a cult-like
organization from the sweat of his followers, who they say are
forced to travel the country panhandling.
</P>
<P>
   Holyland has been a magnet for reporters in recent years, drawn
by a business empire worth an estimated $6.5 million as well as by
$1.3 million in court judgments, child-labor fines and claims of
sexual improprieties by former residents.
</P>
<P>
   A Detroit auto worker turned Pentecostal preacher, Edwards took
over a church in Meridian, Miss. more than 25 years ago. He never
went beyond the fourth grade, but his followers call him ``the
bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that nearly his entire congregation received food
stamps, Edwards devised a plan in the early 1970s to use government
aid as a financial stepping stone. He opened food pantry in the
church and received authorization to take food stamps. Goods were
purchased at wholesale and sold to church members at retail prices.
</P>
<P>
   The profits formed the building blocks of his later
acquisitions. In a few years, the organization started buying land
across the border in Alabama under its not-for-profit corporate
arm, REACH Inc., which stands for Research, Education and Community
Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Now REACH owns three motels, four restaurants, a small
slaughterhouse, three stores, a cattle feedlot, a hog farm, an
airplane, 2,800 acres of land, several limousines and two garages,
according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The Holyland's businesses are not its only money maker. There is
also the group's system, known as ``The Route.'' Vanloads of adults
and children are sent on the road for weeks at a time to ask for
money outside stores nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
