<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds to review slavery course
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Federal officials want to determine whether a
community college noncredit course violated civil rights laws by
teaching that most black people during the Civil War were happy
under slavery.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina advisory committee to the U.S. Commission on
Civil Rights voted Wednesday to request that the federal commission
schedule a public forum to examine the course and its sponsor, Lt.
F.C. Frazier Camp 668 of the Sons of the Confederate Veterans in
High Point, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should have to prove beyond the shadow of a doubt
that they are not a hate group,'' said Richie Everette, the branch
president of the NAACP in Randolph County.
</P>
<P>
   He said he recently attended one of the classes, and that he was
treated cordially by the dozen white students. Still, he said the
group sponsoring the course should ``open its doors'' by inviting
blacks to participate in its military re-enactments.
</P>
<P>
   The final class in the weekly 2 1/2-hour course, ``North
Carolina's Role in the War for Southern Independence,'' is
scheduled for today at the Archdale campus of Randolph Community
College. But the controversy that erupted this week amid criticism
from civil rights leaders and skepticism from historians promises
to intensify under federal scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Voting to request that the federal agency hold a forum in the
next few weeks, state advisory committee Chairman Wyatt Kirk said,
``We are going to try to put to rest distortions and percep-
tions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Frances Berry, chairwoman of the federal Civil Rights
Commission, asked Wyatt to gather information about the course
during the North Carolina panel's quarterly meeting Wednesday in
Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia A. Daniel, the college's vice president for education
programs, told committee members that she was not qualified to
debate the historical accuracy of whether black people enjoyed
slavery. She defended the college's decision to offer the course,
saying administrators approved it under the same guidelines they
authorized other nonacademic credit continuing education courses,
such as ones titled ``Creating Racial Unity'' and ``Angels Right on
Schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to enter the theological debate (whether there)
are angels among us?'' said Daniel. ``I haven't met many this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Taught for the first time this semester, the Civil War course is
part of the college's series of courses about North Carolina's
place in history, Daniel said. A course slated to start in January
will examine the role of civil rights in the state. Tuition for the
Southern history course is $40 per student, which covered
instructors' salaries and materials, Daniel said. Instructors are
not employed by the college. A few in the audience complained that
the civil rights panel should focus on what they consider more
critical issues for blacks, such as police brutality, crime and
housing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
