r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     11-18 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SHOULD BITE CASH BULLET ON GONZALEZ NOW, NOT LATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The one thing the Rangers do not want to know _ never want to
find out _ is how much two-time American League MVP Juan Gonzalez
is worth on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Advice to general manager Doug Melvin: Do not go there. Not if
you want to keep your job.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the smartest thing the Rangers can do in the next
few months is spend a little money _ oh, maybe $75 million, give or
take Fort Knox _ to tie up the best player in franchise history for
the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   It's the classic, pay me now, or pay me later.
</P>
<P>
   Get it on paper ASAP and consider the $75 million another
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably sit down and put our club together here for
next year,'' Melvin said yesterday, ``then take a look at it. We've
talked about it within the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Mark McGwire or Sammy Sosa, who should be announced
today as the National League MVP. Forget publicity hogs Ken Griffey
Jr., Mike Piazza and Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   The best hitter in baseball works the night shift at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez stamped himself as the premier hitter of the '90s by
winning his second Most Valuable Player award in three years
yesterday, to go along with two home-run championships captured
earlier in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think Juan gets a little bit overlooked,'' Melvin
said. ``There's been a lot of talk about Griffey, a lot of talk
about some of the other players. I think the way Juan performed
this season and what he set out to do should put to rest some of
the criticism that was thrown in his direction earlier in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was the most valuable player. I didn't think it
was a surprise at all that he won.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come as a surprise to the Baseball Writers of America,
either. The 28 baseball writers with MVP votes made Gonzalez a
runaway winner. Three-fourths of the voters _ 21 writers _ gave
Gonzalez their first-place votes and the not-so-magnificent-seven
who didn't (shame on them) made him their second choice.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first Latin American player in baseball history to win
the MVP award twice, which may speak to the same bias to which
Melvin is alluding. But that's another column for another time.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, just put yourself in Melvin's seat and try to
figure out what you're going to have to offer to get Gonzalez's
signature on a long-term contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the facts:
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who just turned 29, is under contract this season, and
the Rangers have another option for the year 2000, both at around
$7 million a year. Sure, by today's standards, that's a steal for
the Rangers, but you, as Melvin, don't have to feel a bit guilty.
In 1994 and '95, when Gonzalez was injured parts of both seasons
and limited to 46 homers in two years, he was overpaid. That's the
way these long-term deals work.
</P>
<P>
   By 2001, the Rangers have to have Gonzalez signed to an
extension or he can become a free agent. Piazza's contract with the
Mets _ seven years, $91 million (an average of $13 million a year)
_ is the current slugger's financial ceiling. Vaughn, according to
media reports, has a six-year, $72 million offer on the table from
the Angels. But the contract that knocked the socks off every GM in
baseball was the one singles-hitting Jose Offerman just signed with
Boston for four years, $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's worth that,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates asked,
``what's Mo Vaughn worth? What's Juan worth?''
</P>
<P>
   And those are 1998 dollars. What will Gonzalez be worth two
years from now, in baseball's rapidly escalating economy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' Melvin exclaimed. ``That's hard for me to say. I can't
win in that situation, if I say what he's worth and put a figure on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Logic says Gonzalez, if he were on the open market today, would
zoom past Piazza and stretch the ceiling to $14, maybe $15 million
a year. He could easily be the first $100 million baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were smart enough in January 1994 to sign Gonzalez
to a five-year contract with two option years that has prevented
that from happening. Now the smart thing to do is sign him to a
five-year extension at $15 million a year and never look back. It's
the kind of decisive, money-saving deal Tom Hicks has made dozens
of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play with Texas,'' Gonzalez said yesterday from San
Juan, Puerto Rico. ``It's a great place to play baseball. They have
great fans. I'd feel much better to play my whole career in one
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that a five-year extension will take Gonzalez to the end of
his career, by any means. Seven years from now, Gonzalez will have
just turned 36 and, if he has remained healthy, be somewhere close
to 500 career home runs.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, is another story for another time.
</P>
<P>
   Today's story is Gonzalez, which means it's time for the Rangers
to take care of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Before they find out things they really don't want to know.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
