r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GONZALEZ-MVP-TEX     11-18 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GONZALEZ-MVP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ WINS SECOND AL MVP AWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Rangers outfielder Juan Gonzalez has been named the
American League's most valuable player for the second time in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who won a tight race for the award in 1996, was the
overwhelming winner this time, receiving 21 of 28 first-place votes
from the baseball writers. Boston Red Sox shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra was a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the most excited person in the whole world right now,''
Gonzalez said yesterday from Puerto Rico, where he celebrated with
a small group of family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who will receive a $250,000 bonus in addition to the
trophy, is the 23rd player in major league history to win two MVP
awards. He is the first Latin American player to win the award
twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa can make it a clean sweep for the
region by winning the National League award, which will be
announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of the other 22 are in the Hall of Fame. Cal Ripken,
Barry Bonds and Frank Thomas are still active; Robin Yount and Dale
Murphy aren't yet eligible for enshrinement.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris, whose single-season home run record was broken this
season by Mark McGwire, is the only two-time MVP who is eligible
for the Hall of Fame but not in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This says Juan is one of the elite players,'' said Rangers
manager Johnny Oates. ``To be elected two out of three years, that
says he's among the best of the elite. That's quite an
accomplishment. What he does, he does very well, and that's drive
in runs.''
</P>
<P>
   His number of runs batted in proved to be the difference.
Gonzalez led the American League with 157 RBI, the most by one
player since Boston's Ted Williams and Vern Stephens drove in 159
in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   He had 100 RBI at the All-Star break, creating speculation he
would challenge the all-time single-season record of 190 set by
Cubs outfielder Hack Wilson in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also hit a career-high .318 with 45 home runs, 110 runs
scored and a league-leading 50 doubles. His batting exploits helped
the Rangers win their second West Division championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll remember most us winning the division title,'' said
Gonzalez, who has played eight full seasons with the Rangers.
``When you win the division, that's a great moment for the whole
team and the whole organization. Then, 157 RBI was amazing. There's
been a lot of years where nobody drove in more than 150 RBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said he was also proud of staying injury-free. This was
the first time in four years that he did not spend time on the
disabled list, allowing him to set a career high with 606 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked in spring training about playing every day,'' Oates
said. ``That's what I'm most excited about, his dedication and hard
work being rewarded like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The voting was done by 28 baseball writers, two in each American
League city. Ten players were named on each ballot. Gonzalez
received 21 first-place and seven second-place votes for a total of
352 points.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra received 232 points, followed by Yankees shortstop
Derek Jeter (180). Red Sox first baseman Mo Vaughn and Mariners
outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. tied for fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez edged Seattle Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez by
three points to win the award in 1996. That year he hit .314 with
47 home runs and 144 RBI to join Jeff Burroughs as the only Rangers
to win the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time I felt more comfortable than in 1996,'' Gonzalez
said. ``The first time was too tight. Now I feel great. I'm in
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians outfielder Manny Ramirez, New York Yankees
outfielder Bernie Williams, Chicago White Sox outfielder Albert
Belle, Rodriguez and Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez rounded out the
top 10.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth time in club history that the Rangers have
had two players in the top 10. The others were Burroughs and
pitcher Ferguson Jenkins in 1974; Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro in
1993; and Gonzalez and Rodriguez in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez receives a $50,000 bonus for being in the top 10.
Reliever John Wetteland got an eighth-place vote and starter Rick
Helling got a 10th place vote, marking the first time in club
history that four Rangers received most valuable player
consideration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
