<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-INJURIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR PUTS THE SPOTLIGHT ON BRAIN INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confronting Traumatic Brain Injury
</P>
<P>
   William Winslade
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Press, $27.50
</P>
<P>
   ``On September 7, 1943, when I was not quite two, I fell from a
second-story porch and landed headfirst on the concrete pavement.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the opening words of William Winslade's book, which
illuminates an underappreciated public health problem: traumatic
brain injury.
</P>
<P>
   After his accident, Winslade was in intensive care in a Chicago
hospital for five weeks. No one could predict whether he would live
or die _ or whether he would suffer lifelong mental, emotional and
physical disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   He survived, and thrived. Today, he is the James Wade Rockwell
Professor of Philosophy in Medicine at the Institute for the
Medical Humanities at the University of Texas Medical Branch in
Galveston, and he teaches preventive medicine and community health,
psychiatry, and behavioral sciences.
</P>
<P>
   But so many others don't do well.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, 75,000 to 100,000 people die of brain
trauma each year. An additional 70,000 to 90,000 are left
permanently impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``On any given day, we have 25,000 to 40,000 people in a
persistent vegetative state. We can't help them. It's a fate worse
than death,'' Winslade says. ``We rescue people from the brink of
death with the jaws of life, so the fatalities are down, but the
devastation is up.''
</P>
<P>
   Winslade works with the Transitional Learning Community in
Galveston, where more than 600 head-trauma patients have undergone
physical, speech, recreational and occupational therapy, and have
relearned the practical skills necessary for independent living
over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are killing 40,000 a year in car accidents, and most of
them die of brain injuries. Gunshot wounds, falls and sports
injuries account for most of the others,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet traumatic brain injury seldom comes to mind when we list
major public health problems,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   His book calls for policy changes to lower the incidence of
traumatic brain injury. He wants to raise the minimum driving age
and make driver's-license tests more challenging. He is lobbying
the Texas Legislature for a graduated licensing system, which would
limit the privileges of our youngest drivers, such as requiring
that they drive with an adult in the car for the first six months,
drive only during daylight hours, drive only if no other teens are
in the car, or observe a midnight driving curfew.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that 7 percent of licensed drivers are 16 or 17
years old, yet they account for 14 percent of traffic fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people do you know who have failed their driver's
tests?'' he asks. ``Very few, because the standards are so low. We
should make driver's tests harder. Driving a car is not a
constitutional right. We need to rethink what's important to us.
Too often, we start our kids driving as young as possible because
it's more convenient for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Winslade says cars worry him more than guns; a car is 2 tons of
steel going 90 mph with other people in the way. He believes that
it was stupid to raise speed limits, and he wants more speed checks
and more law-enforcement officers patrolling the highways.
</P>
<P>
   He also would require bike and motorcycle helmets, air bags and
seat belts. He wants to tax automobile licenses and driver's
licenses, guns, and alcohol to help cover the costs of treatment
and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   And, he's calling for a ban on professional boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Winslade's goals are to make brain-injury prevention part of the
education of every student before the student is old enough to get
behind the wheel of a car, and to get traumatic head injury
recognized as a public health problem.
</P>
<P>
   This book should go a long way toward those goals.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
