A7853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      11-18 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   France: British Agent Freed
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ An appeals court rejected a British extradition request
for a former British secret agent and ordered him freed. The agent,
David Shayler, was arrested on Aug. 1 in Paris as he reportedly
considered releasing information on a British plot to kill Moammar
Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   France: Strike Grounds Air France
</P>
<P>
   Air France flight attendants grounded more than half of the
state-owned airline's flights on Tuesday and Wednesday in a strike
for higher wages and longer rest periods between flights. Air
France said it expected traffic to return to normal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Queen Goes to Market
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Queen Elizabeth II took a turn around the City of
London financial district for what aides called her first all-day
visit to London's equivalent of Wall Street. Asked whether she was
fazed by the markets, Naomi Hill, a trader at Merrill Lynch, said
after chatting with the queen, ``She was totally knowledgeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal: Ban on Meat Exports
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission banned the export of beef and cattle
from Portugal after a sharp rise in mad cow disease this year.
Sixty-seven cases have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Djibouti: Reaction to Eritreans
</P>
<P>
   Djibouti has closed its embassy in Asmara and broken off
diplomatic relations to protest an Eritrean allegation that it
sided with Ethiopia in a six-month border conflict. Eritrea fought
a 30-year war against Ethiopia, gaining independence in 1993. But
the border between the two has not officially been declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
