<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-LEADERSHIP-DUNN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNN LOSES BID FOR TOP LEADERSHIP ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Jennifer Dunn's rapid rise within the GOP came
to an abrupt halt Wednesday as her fellow House Republicans
overwhelmingly rejected her candidacy for majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accepted Dunn's argument that a ``fresh face'' was
needed to diversify a GOP leadership team that previously had
consisted exclusively of white men. But instead of adding a woman
to the top echelons, the Republicans made the surprise move of
elevating the lone black GOP congressman, J.C. Watts Jr. of
Oklahoma, to the post of conference chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, a 57-year-old Bellevue Republican who gave up a junior
leadership post to run for majority leader, now returns to life as
a rank-and-file House member.
</P>
<P>
   She accepted her defeat with grace. She congratulated the
victor, incumbent Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, and pledged
to continue to work on broadening the party's appeal to women. Dunn
also said she was pleased even to have been taken seriously as a
candidate for a position that no woman has ever held, and said she
hopes her effort will make it easier for other women to rise in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic day for the Republican Party,'' Dunn told
reporters minutes after her loss. ``We have broken yet another
glass ceiling _ the first time ever a woman has run for a top
leadership position. It's a great groundbreaker for women.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Republicans chose Appropriations Committee
Chairman Bob Livingston, R-La., as their nominee for House Speaker.
If elected by the House in January _ pretty much a foregone
conclusion because Republicans hold a majority _ Livingston will
replace Newt Gingrich. Gingrich decided not to seek another term as
speaker after his party suffered the unexpected loss of five seats
in the House in this month's election.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also re-elected Tom DeLay of Texas as majority
whip. But they ousted John Boehner of Ohio as conference chairman,
replacing him with Watts.
</P>
<P>
   Armey won re-election after three rounds of voting by the 223
Republicans elected to the next Congress. In the first round, Armey
won 100 votes to 58 for former Seattle Seahawk Steve Largent, 45
for Dunn, and 18 for Rep. Denny Hastert, R-Ill. Hastert then
dropped off, and in a second round of voting Armey won 99 votes to
73 for Largent and 49 for Dunn. Dunn then dropped off, and Armey
ultimately defeated Largent of Oklahoma, 127 to 95. (Not all
Republicans voted in each round.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hastert's entry hurt us, because when all the talk about him
came about, that kind of froze members from making commitments
because they didn't know what the field would be,'' said Rep.
Richard ``Doc'' Hastings, R-Wash., who was Dunn's top vote-counter.
``But Jennifer is still a senior member of the Ways and Means
Committee, and, let's face it, she is still a very good spokesman
for our party, and she will be sought after by various media who
ask her opinions on things. I don't think that will be diminished
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's supporters offered a variety of other theories to explain
her defeat. Top among them was that she was running against an
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick (Armey) had used his position to ingratiate himself with
an awful lot of people around the country, and it's hard to
dislodge that,'' said Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash. ``It was a
question of whether Dick should be punished for the election losses
or not, and although people wanted to flirt with that
(possibility), in the end they didn't want to enforce it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested that perhaps Dunn, who had held the
sixth-ranking leadership post, might have aimed too high in running
for the No. 2 job, and might have waited too long to declare her
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer did a great job, and I supported her vigorously, but
we're a small state and Armey had a running start,'' said Rep. Jack
Metcalf, R-Wash. ``If she had run for a lesser office, she probably
would have made it. This was no repudiation of her _ this was just
a reinforcement of support for Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Dunn supporters quietly blamed her loss on her compromise
position on abortion _ she supports abortion rights but is not a
vocal champion of the cause and opposes federal financing of
abortions. That position has managed to alienate supporters and
opponents of abortion rights, because both sides believe Dunn isn't
entirely with them.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's campaign, although failing to win votes of a majority of
House Republicans, dramatically increased her national prominence.
She was profiled on NBC News and in the Washington Post and New
York Times; she was interviewed on a variety of television shows
and by numerous newspapers; and she was mentioned as a possible
vice-presidential nominee in 2000 by U.S. News and World Report.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's political future is uncertain. The next major political
races in Washington state are in 2000 for U.S. Senate and governor.
But Republican Slade Gorton has told friends he plans to seek
re-election to the Senate and Democrat Gary Locke appears likely to
be difficult to beat for the governorship.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said she will focus on trying to cut taxes and save Social
Security as a member of the House Ways and Means Committee, and
will ``work as a member of our broad Republican team to reach out _
particularly to women _ through a national campaign, communicating
our positive vision to every American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's next,'' she said. ``I don't know what
will happen. I have no thought that they will create a new position
(for Dunn). But it's such an inside game. You don't have to be part
of leadership to do what you're here to do _ I'm here to make a
difference and I expect to do that one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dunn said she doesn't regret her choices this year, which
included forgoing a race for U.S. Senate against incumbent Democrat
Patty Murray to focus on a career in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have minimal disappointment, because I would love to have
put my shoulder to the wheel. I'm a very good manager and I love to
do that kind of work,'' she said. ``But I don't have any regrets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
