<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD BOB? I DON'T THINK SO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The announcement came breathlessly Wednesday afternoon.
It sounded like the flip side version of ``The Midnight Ride of
Paul Revere.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ``The British are coming!'' we were warned that ``The
Patriots are leaving! The Patriots are leaving!''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone really think that &UR;  &LR; Bob Kraft _ a man with an ego
bigger than the Citgo sign in Kenmore Square _ wants to be owner of
the Hartford Patriots? Think he wants to be our football Harry
Frazee? Think he wants to stroll the dead streets of America's File
Cabinet, gladhanding the poor souls who could not support a major
league hockey team, the Forever .500 Whalers?
</P>
<P>
   I don't care what he signs or doesn't sign. Kraft knows that
Hartford, Conn. is a yahoo sports town. He knows moving to Hartford
means he'll immediately lose half of his Greater Boston fan base.
Patriot fans will drive to Providence, R.I., but thousands will
drop out before they make the 100-mile trek to the picturesque
intersection of Interstates 84 and 91.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, Bob. Hartford? You can't do better than Hartford?
Hartford is populated by Jet fans and Giant fans. This is where you
want to build a fan base for the Patriots? Why not try New Haven or
Kennebunkport? Both are in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know him know that ``Live Shot'' Kraft can't stand the
anonymity of Hartford. He can't be Jerry Jones Jr. in Hartford.
Hartford has no mass media for him to cultivate. Hartford has no
Sunday night sports TV war, no big-time media consultants with
their own radio shows.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft was willing to make his team worse because of his hatred
for Bill Parcells, but will he actually move it because of his
hatred for House Speaker Thomas Finneran?
</P>
<P>
   Don't the Hartford yahoos know they are being used? Again.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft no doubt will try to make Finneran the bad guy as he puts
the loaded gun to the head of state taxpayers. Finneran certainly
makes it sound like a personal matter when he tells the Salem
(Mass.) News, ``I'm going to give tax breaks to some fat-ass
millionaire and screw our kids?'' (The speaker said he was talking
about Oakland's Al Davis and Baltimore's Art Modell.)
</P>
<P>
   Is it personal?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that repeated,'' said Finneran from his office
Wednesday night. ``I don't know if that's Mr. Kraft's
characterization. We've agreed to disagree. If it was personal, I
don't think you'd see a $52 million proposal sweetened to a $57
million proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   You may think Finneran is wrong. Many do. You may think he has a
personal agenda. Many do. But the speaker is prepared to take the
heat for Kraft's potential departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already been identified as the bad guy consistently for
the past two or three years,'' Finneran said, ``but when you ask
people what they admire in public leaders, they say they admire
those who articulate principles in the face of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he feel about being marked as the man who would drive
the Patriots out of Massachusetts?
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some who say that,'' said Finneran, ``but I
think many will say, `Thank God for people of conscience and people
of principle who won't flinch under pressure.' This is nothing but
economic bullying.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran said he is disappointed by reports the team is leaving.
``I had been cautioned by people for many months and years not to
fool myself that there would be any reciprocity of loyalty between
fans and owners. These owners gouge our fans, overpay their
employees, then the solution is to turn to the taxpayer and say,
`Save us from ourselves.' It just doesn't pass a rational economic
analysis. To do what the owners request is to create precedent that
is very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker can be sanctimonious (the ``guardian at the gate''
comes to mind), and his words won't fly well on the sports pages.
But football fans tend to forget that there is a segment of the
population that favors Symphony Hall and the Museum of Fine Arts
over Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Legislature revisit the issue when Kraft again folds
his paper house of Hartford?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said the speaker. ``We have never closed the
door up here. It's not my style, and I don't think it's appropriate
to say we'll never revisit this. The burden is on all of us to be
prepared to listen to other ideas. But the essential principle for
us is not to create precedent we can't live up to. When you ask
taxpayers to come into a partnership, you have to treat them as a
partner and not someone to be plundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope was that there'd be some type of reciprocity and that
the loyalty and commitment to the fans would be a factor. It
clearly has not been a factor. This has reduced itself to a Jerry
Maguire-type status.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Maguire didn't have the same hammer as Bob Kraft. Jerry
had only one wide receiver to shop. Kraft can say, ``Show me the
money!'' and threaten to move his team.
</P>
<P>
   But he won't. Just as Finneran won't be bullied or threatened,
Kraft won't be reduced to owning the Hartford Patriots. Hartford
doesn't cut it for King Kraft. He wants the citizens of
Massachusetts to kiss his ring. He wants to be Big Man on Campus in
(itals)Boston(unitals). Not Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
