<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FORT WORTH PAST IS IN SAX MAN'S `FUTURE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the 1940s in Fort Worth, and little Billy ``Tom'' Robinson
is sitting in a car, waiting for his dad, Ellis. Dad's a plumber;
he's in somebody's house, finishing a job or collecting money.
Whatever. Billy is studying people: the movement of their bodies,
the way they walk and the sway of their shoulders all suggest music
to him.
</P>
<P>
   Billy hears music everywhere (especially when mockingbirds
chirp; he's fascinated by how they never repeat themselves) and at
the Jamboree Dine and Dance, the little joint Mom and Dad run
downtown, where musicians come and go. During the day, Billy
sometimes goes inside to try his hand at boogie-woogie piano.
</P>
<P>
   Time passes, and Billy takes up the tenor saxophone, learns from
guys like Thomas ``Red'' Connors and Dewey Redman and Dallasites
James Clay and Buster Smith, keeps on listening to the mockingbirds
and watching people, keeps hearing melodies, starts to go out to
quiet places and play duets with the mockingbirds. He also notices
the colors of leaves in the fall; the different colors set against
one another, the different hues of yellow and green, suggest chord
changes, different intensities of sound.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 1964, and Robinson has moved to San Francisco to try to
make it in jazz. There's a cave near a landmark called Seal Rock,
and that's where you can find him, far away from the smoky clubs
and the nascent hippie movement, practicing in the cave and
outside, on a cliff, experimenting with sounds and chord changes
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Between then and now Robinson, 59, has played with legends
(Archie Shepp and Charles Mingus). He has also recorded several
solo CDs, the latest being this year's excellent ``A Short Turn to
the Future,'' which includes five of his own tunes and a version of
Duke Ellington's ``In a Sentimental Mood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Future'' is a rare treat for Fort Worth jazz fans, a gem of a
CD from a man who stands tall in the city's jazz history _ and
certainly deserves to be mentioned among such Cowtown sax titans as
Ornette Coleman, the late, great Julius Hemphill, Redman, and King
Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson isn't as well-known as those men _ not through any lack
of talent, but rather because he largely opted out of being in New
York, the epicenter of the jazz world. Robinson moved to Montreal,
Canada, in the early '70s, after marrying a Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   He liked it. Montreal and now Ottawa, where he has lived for
years with his second wife, are nice, safe places, and he took to
them. He taught jazz improvisation at two universities and has also
studied psychology, lectured, recorded, and played festivals and
universities; New York is a place to go now and then, not a place
to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about where you live,'' he says. ``It's about what
you have going on and keeping your family safe.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Robinson has merged his playing and his studies in
psychiatry at the University of Ottawa to develop a music-therapy
system he calls Audio-Neural Musichiatry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about how you can take records and manipulate the mind
with them, by duplicating mental processes and emotions with
voicings and tone textures and the dynamics of tones,'' he says.
``They can also affect the sense of equilibrium. You have a thought
memory and an emotional memory. When you play rhythms and melodies,
people relate to them in a balance sense. Music can stimulate your
sense of balance and cause you to remember emotional experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   A book Robinson wrote on the subject will, he says, be out next
spring. ``Future,'' however, is here now, and although you'll
probably have to order it to get it, it's well worth the search.
They say it's always a good idea to stop and smell the roses. Billy
Robinson has been doing it all his life, and listening to the
mockingbirds, too, refusing to hurry or worry about how famous he
might have been.
</P>
<P>
   And if he gets his way, he'll be bringing his music back to
Texas soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intentions are to come back to America and play more, by
all means,'' he says. ``I'm an American. I want to establish a
musical relationship with America. I want to establish a
relationship with my home state and my hometown.'' Dave Ferman,
(817) 390-7839 dfer &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
