<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7930 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      11-18 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS AWAIT DECISIONS BY FOUR SUPERSTARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually, one of the dominoes will fall first. It could be
Albert Belle. Or Bernie Williams. Or Mo Vaughn. Or Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   There is no 24-second clock forcing anyone to make a move until
they're good and ready. In the meantime, millions of dollars are
stacked like cordwood, waiting to be awarded like dowries at the
end of that peculiar mating ritual between free agent superstars
and the baseball teams coveting their services.
</P>
<P>
   These are courtships carried on in relative secrecy, especially
those in which the occupants of Yawkey Way are involved. So far,
the Red Sox have parted ways with Vaughn, made an offer to
Palmeiro, and put the full-court press on Belle. But as of last
night, they remained on hold on all fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman, the one free agent they have signed, was due in
town today for formal introductions with his new club.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Wednesday afternoon, the Red Sox had not made an
offer to Belle, but neither had their only rivals for the slugger's
services, the Yankees, who spent the day wooing free agent
outfielder Brian Jordan. And Jordan, a candidate to replace free
agent Bernie Williams as the Yankees' center fielder, emerged from
his meetings in Yankee Stadium, only to add to the confusion,
saying he'd been told repeatedly by Yankees officials that their
first priority was to re-sign Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, meanwhile, was supposedly planning to pay a visit to
Boston sometime this week, but neither his agent, Scott Boras, nor
club officials would confirm Wednesday whether a meeting has been
scheduled. Boras, who has not returned repeated phone calls to his
office, has been asked by general manager Dan Duquette not to talk
about his negotiations with the Sox. Team spokesman Kevin Shea gave
it his best ``I don't know'' response.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, Palmeiro Wednesday night was being wined and dined
by team owner Peter Angelos and GM Frank Wren as the Orioles
attempt to retain their 34-year-old first baseman, who offered to
have a similar meeting with the Sox but was told that wasn't
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   A Red Sox offer to Belle could come as soon as Thursday. CEO
John Harrington, the man who pulled the plug on Vaughn, must decide
whether he wants to pay Belle, who is earning $11 million a year
now (including his $5 million buyout on a five-year deal), an
average salary at least equal to the $13 million a year the Mets
are paying catcher Mike Piazza. Belle has three years remaining on
his deal with the White Sox and probably will want at least another
three years tacked onto that by the Red Sox, who were willing to go
no more than five years (plus an option) with Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, meanwhile, went another day without accepting the
Angels' six-year, $72 million offer. His agents have been talking
with that other team in southern California, the Dodgers, who need
to move some more salary before they can take on Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and Palmeiro's destinies do not appear to depend on what
course Belle and Williams choose, but there's no doubt that what
Belle does, presuming he is the first to make a move, will define
the field better for Williams. The loser in the Belle sweepstakes
is almost certain to turn its attention to Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
