<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-BATS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WCC MAKES THE SWITCH TO WOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 &HT;     c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The West Coast Conference has decided to switch from using
aluminum bats to an NCAA-approved wooden composite bat for the 1999
season in a move that will affect the Pacific-10, Western Athletic
and Big West conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our presidents have decided,'' WCC commissioner Michael
Gilleran said on Wednesday, ``is that we're going to use a wood or
a wood composite bat. We're going to notify our nonleague
opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, the NCAA Baseball Rules Committee voted to alter bat
specifications for the '99 season. That paved the way for
conferences to switch to bats made of wood or, like the WCC is
doing, wood composite.
</P>
<P>
   Safety was the main concern, although the abundance of scoring
in the College World Series _ capped by USC's 21-14 win over
Arizona State in the championship game _ also was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Gilleran said it was a ``prudent'' decision.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the New Jersey Athletic Conference, which announced
the switch to wood on Tuesday, WCC teams will no longer play teams
that use aluminum. That means Pepperdine and Loyola Marymount could
have games removed from their upcoming schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Loyola Marymount coach Frank Cruz said his players have been
using wooden Louisville Slugger bats during the fall-league season
and in practice. He said LMU has yet to order any of the wooden
composite bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially it's going to hit us,'' Cruz said. ``It's going to
make a dent.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Muldoon, director of publicity for the Pac-10, said the
conference hasn't made a decision to drop aluminum. But it is a
move that seems to be imminent. Stanford baseball coach Mark
Marquess has spent the last week calling Pac-10 coaches about the
possibility of dropping aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   A UCLA baseball coach who didn't want to be identified said he
couldn't comment on the issue, even when he was asked if the Bruins
are using wooden bats in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Farrell, commissioner of the Big West, said that
conference hasn't made an official decision on switching to wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're examining that possibility,'' he said. ``(The WCC
decision) obviously has a schedule impact for all the schools in
our conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hurd, a WAC associate commissioner who oversees baseball,
said the WAC is adopting a wait-and-see attitude toward dropping
aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not addressed (switching to wood) from a league
standpoint,'' Hurd said. ``I don't know the time involved will
allow that happen (for the '99 season). We have discussed it, but
we never did adopt a conference policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The WCC's decision to drop aluminum is another blow for Van
Nuys-based Easton Sports, the nation's leading aluminum bat
manufacturer. Easton filed a $267 million restraint-of-trade
lawsuit against the NCAA on Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Easton, the chairman for Easton Sports, has said that the
NCAA's safety concerns regarding aluminum bats are overblown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
