<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      11-18 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HEARING OPENS, VOTE EXPECTED TO WIDEN SCOPE OF INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With high drama and potentially grave consequences,
a bitterly divided House Judiciary Committee will open hearings
Thursday on possible impeachable offenses stemming from President
Clinton's sexual affair with a former White House intern and other
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr is scheduled as the only
witness, presenting his case against the president. According to an
advance copy of his testimony, Starr will allege Clinton ``misused
his authority and power as president'' to stymie Starr's
far-ranging grand jury investigation and the recently settled
sexual-harassment lawsuit brought by Paula Corbin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's partisan clashing grew increasingly hostile
Wednesday night as they wrangled over a Republican decision, in the
final hours before Starr was scheduled to appear, to expand the
scope and duration of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Committee &UR;  &LR; Chairman Henry J. Hyde issued a list of future
witnesses, including White House deputy counsel Bruce R. Lindsey,
one of Clinton's closest confidants, and Robert Bennett, Clinton's
lawyer in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The move was assailed by committee Democrats as a ``fishing
expedition'' with the makings of ``a gotcha game.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a lightning rod for critics who have accused him of
trying to bring down Clinton over a private, consensual affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky, intends to testify that the case against the
president ``is not a private matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence further suggests that the president ... misused
his authority and power as president and contravened his duty to
faithfully execute the laws,'' Starr plans to say, according to his
prepared testimony. ``That too is not a private matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Starr hearing will be a pivotal passage in the proceedings,
as Clinton's foes and supporters jockey before a Congress that is
wary of the volatile case and a public that polls show is weary of
the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Only twice before in the nation's history has a president been
the target of a congressional impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   However, the panel's GOP majority is expected to prevail
Thursday when the committee votes on whether to issue subpoenas for
Lindsey, Bennett, and two individuals who are familiar with former
White House volunteer Kathleen Willey: Democratic fund-raiser
Nathan Landow and Willey's lawyer, Daniel Gecker. Willey has
accused Clinton of groping her near the Oval Office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The new witnesses were expected to be questioned first in
private depositions, according to the Associated Press. Republicans
would then decide whether to summon them, or additional witnesses,
at public hearings, committee officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gecker and Landow are expected to be called early next
week, followed by Lindsey and Bennett during the first week of
December, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prepared testimony includes detailed arguments to
support his claim that there is ``substantial and credible''
evidence that Clinton committed 11 impeachable offenses stemming
from the Lewinsky matter, including perjury, witness tampering, and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short,'' Starr plans to say, ``the evidence suggests that
the president repeatedly used the machinery of government and the
powers of his office to conceal his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky from the American people, from the judicial process in the
Jones case, and from the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hyde's approval, Starr plans to range beyond the Lewinsky
and Willey episodes to discuss the Whitewater real estate deals,
the improper use of FBI files by White House political operatives,
the firing of White House travel office personnel, and allegations
that Clinton's friend, Webster L. Hubbell, may have accepted ``hush
money'' to shield the president from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans said they are expanding the inquiry to
support Starr's contention that Clinton has engaged in a pattern of
deception beyond the alleged coverup of his illicit affair with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said it appeared the
Republicans were off on an unfair, unconstitutional ``partisan
adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have rediscovered all of their old bad habits and since
they don't like where it's going, they're going to try to find
something else,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde acknowledged the widening gulf between the two sides. ``The
Democrats want to stick to Monica Lewinsky,'' he said. ``We want to
look at everything. That's the big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In lurching toward looking at ``everything,'' Hyde risks
inciting the wrath of a growing number of House Republicans who
favor swiftly ending the proceedings and sanctioning Clinton short
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde, who has said he hopes to resolve the impeachment issue
by the end of the year, blamed the White House in part for
prolonging the inquiry. He said Clinton's lawyers could have
expedited the process by admitting in a sworn affidavit to the
allegations in Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said lawyers have yet to complete
answers to 81 questions from Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some cooperation from them is very desirable,'' Hyde said.
``It would be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats, who are poised to counterattack Hyde and
Starr in the nationally televised hearing, expressed outrage at the
Republican move to broaden the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat who sits
on the Judiciary Committee, said the move was ``nothing less than a
desperate attempt to resuscitate a failing effort to impeach the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan called it a ``a recipe for a protracted inquiry, which is
exactly what the American people don't want.''
</P>
<P>
   For Starr, whose favorable rating in the most recent public
opinion poll was only 18 percent, Thursday's hearing poses the
biggest test of his career as he tries to make his case in a
two-hour speech before the committee. Starr then faces questioning
from the 37 committee members, including some Democrats who hope to
turn the hearing into an examination of Starr's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Charles F. C. Ruff said the president's
legal team would abide by a Republican-controlled schedule that
gives him 30 minutes to question Starr, although Ruff said in a
letter to the committee that the restriction ``is not consistent
with the standard of fairness that the committee has sought to
achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself was thousands of miles away on a trip to Asia.
Privately, White House officials expressed confidence that Clinton
would emerge relatively unscathed, noting that Starr is on the
defensive and that Republicans are so divided that they are ousting
House Newt Speaker Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Starr sent a report to Congress that said Clinton
may have committed impeachable offenses in the Lewinsky case, in
which the president denied under oath that he had a sexual
relationship with the former intern. When Lewinsky later testified
that she had oral sex with Clinton, the president said his denial
had been ``legally accurate'' but acknowledged that his
relationship with Lewinsky was ``wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7948 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-625(2TAKES)-N     11-18 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR TO CITE PATTERN OF OBSTRUCTION; WIDENING INQUIRY SEEN
</HEADLINE>
   (htv) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, will insist
in the House impeachment hearings on Thursday that President
Clinton not only obstructed justice by covering up his affair with
Monica Lewinsky, but repeatedly threw up ``roadblocks and hurdles''
that slowed the prosecutor's other investigations.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr's prepared testimony for the House Judiciary
Committee's first hearing was made public Wednesday night, Rep.
Henry Hyde, the chairman, announced that Republicans would supboena
four new witnesses in the investigation of Clinton amid signs that
the committee majority is now seeking to broaden the inquiry far
beyond the Lewinsky matter to show a larger pattern of obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also sought a Justice Department report on campaign finance
investigations concerning Clinton, and the department indicated it
was likely to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   In his prepared statement, Starr ran through a litany of the
investigations he has conducted since he was first charged with
examining the president's failed Whitewater real estate venture,
and said ``The pattern of obstruction of justice, false statements,
and misuse of executive authority in the Lewinsky investigation did
not occur in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   He complained, ``We have been forced to go to court time and
again to seek information from the executive branch and to fight a
multitude of privilege claims asserted by the administration _
every single one of which we have won.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Starr announced in his prepared testimony
that his investigations have exonerated the Clinton administration
from any wrongdoing in the firings of seven employees in the White
House travel office and into whether White House officials used
confidential FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   As for Whitewater, Starr said he had drafted an impeachment
referral in late 1997 that outlined allegations that Clinton had
testified falsely at the trial of Jim McDougal and Jim Guy Tucker.
But Starr said he never sent the referral because he said the
evidence did not meet the standards required.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Starr's testmony dealt with the Lewinsky matter, on
which he refered 11 potential articles of impeachment to the House
in September. Starr summed up his view of the president's hostility
to his investigation in these terms:
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next several months, it became apparent that the
strategy to win had many prongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, the president denied the truth publicly and
emphatically. Second, he publicly promised to cooperate with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third, the president deflected and diverted the investigation
by telling aides false stories that were then relayed to the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourth, he refused invitations to testify to the grand jury
for over six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifth, his administration delayed the investigation through
multiple privilege claims, each of which has been rejected by the
federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixth, surrogates of the president attacked the credibility
and legitimacy of the grand jury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventh, surrogates of the president attempted to convince the
Congress and the American people that the matter was unimportant.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said Republicans wanted to take depositions from Bruce
Lindsey, the Clinton confidant who is deputy White House counsel
and from Robert Bennett, Clinton's private attorney in the sexual
harassment case brought by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   He said the committee would also question Daniel Gecker, the
lawyer for Kathleen Willey, a White House volunteer who has said
the president made a sexual advance to her, and Nathan Landow, a
Democratic developer and fund-raiser close to the White House who
counseled Ms. Willey on whether she should testify in the Jones
case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Clinton's 1996 campaign finance practices, Hyde wrote to
Attorney General Janet Reno, seeking unrestricted access to a
memorandum from Charles LaBella, the former top prosecutor for
campaign finance abuses, in which he recommended that an
independent counsel be named to investigate the president and Vice
President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, obtained by The New York Times, Hyde said that
because he wanted to wrap up his impeachment inquiry expeditiously,
``I do not believe that the committee can or should wait for you to
finish your preliminary inquiry of possible crimes of the president
or your campaign finance investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde once again said that he intended to finish his
investigation by the end of the year. But Democrats and the White
House accused the Republicans of ranging far beyond Starr's charges
of 11 possible impeachable offenses in the Lewinsky case and of
trying to start a battle over attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to pick a partisan food fight they've been
reduced to picking up Ken Starr's leftovers,'' said Jim Kennedy. a
White House spokesman. ``They are even trying to out-Starr Starr by
breaching the attorney-client privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is an impeachment in search of a crime, and
in another 48 hours we will be reopening the Vincent Foster case,''
said James Jordan, the spokesman for Democrats. And Rep. Martin
Meehan, a committee Democrat, said the fast-moving events meant
``this is going to be a long involved process.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department officials said that the department is
likely to cooperate with Hyde's request for the memo written by
LaBella. It must first, however, obtain judicial approval to
disclose grand jury informaiton in the report. The Justice
Department could go to court to seek permission as early as
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The activity and partisan positioning came on Wednesday, a day
before Starr will take center stage before Congress, set free for
the first time in his four year investigation of the president to
give a wide-ranging public presentation of his case against the
president. In his prepared testimony, obtained Wednesday night,
Starr argued that his case against Clinton has nothing to do with
sexual liaisons and he protested that his office had taken no
pleasure in investigating the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The propriety of a relationship is not the concern of our
office,'' Starr says in his written statement. ``No citizen who
finds himself accused in a sexual harassment case, or in any other
kind of case, can lie under oath or otherwise obstruct justice, and
thereby prevent the plaintiff from discovering evidence and proving
her case.''
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of his prepared statement, Starr subtitled the
final section ``Reflections.'' In it, he defended the work of his
office over nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lewinsky investigation, Starr said neither he nor his
staff ``relished'' the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff and I agree with the sentiments expressed by Chairman
Hyde in the Nov. 9 hearing when he said, `I'd like to forget all of
this,''' Starr said, adding: ``I mean, who needs it?''
</P>
<P>
   He also detailed his legal background, dating back to his
position as a law clerk in 1973 and attempted to joke about his
lack of political acumen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person is, of course, deeply affected by his or her
experiences,'' Starr said. ``For my part, my experience is in the
law and the courts. I am not a man of polls, public relations, or
politics, which I suppose is obvious at this point. I am not
experienced in political campaigns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
