<HEADLINE>
WARREN DOWNPLAYS SEAHAWKS REUNION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys running back Chris Warren's former
teammates check on him occasionally with long-distance phone calls.
Cortez Kennedy wants to know how he likes Dallas. Darryl Williams
and Michael Sinclair call up to chat about life.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, Warren said, rarely turn to how or why his eight-year
career with the Seattle Seahawks came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, with the Cowboys playing host to the Seattle
Seahawks on Sunday, Warren must relive his final days in Seattle.
It's OK. He understands that people want to know if he harbors any
bitterness toward his old team, if he has circled Nov. 22 in red on
his calendar, if he is looking for revenge against the club that
did not re-sign its all-time leading rusher.
</P>
<P>
   His answers?
</P>
<P>
   No, no and no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, they wanted a change,'' Warren said yesterday. ``I was
out. Ricky \RWatters\S was in. It's something you have to respect
and be professional about. If I was bitter, that would take away
from my game and it'd be falling right into their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson would not discuss the details
that led to the change. But Erickson said he has watched Warren
this year and is ``happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Warren did a lot of things for this franchise and for me
personally,'' Erickson said. ``I know him well, and I think he will
come out and play a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said he doesn't expect Warren to play
more than usual. Warren will spell starter Emmitt Smith, and he'll
return kickoffs. He might return punts in place of Deion Sanders,
who has a sprained big toe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ``a 100-yard game would be incredible,'' Warren said. ``But
I'm not putting my eggs in that basket.''
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Two players with sprained big toes, Sanders and center Clay
Shiver, did not practice yesterday. Sanders is expected to start
Sunday, coach Chan Gailey said, but Shiver might be sidelined for
the second consecutive game. Right guard Everett McIver returned to
practice yesterday for the first time since spraining his right
knee Oct. 4. Gailey said he will wait until at least Friday to
announce who will start, McIver or rookie Flozell Adams. Cornerback
Kevin Smith practiced and showed no ill effects from a separated
left shoulder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
