A7960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-REPORT-ART-425&AMP;     11-18 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING EXPORTS TRIM U.S. TRADE DEFICIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rl) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton left for Japan Wednesday
declaring that ``our workers and our farmers pay the price'' for
declining U.S. exports to Asia, the Commerce Department reported
trade figures suggesting that the price is not rising as quickly as
many feared.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments abroad of Boeing Co. aircraft nearly doubled,
narrowing the September trade deficit to $14 billion, down nearly
$2 billion from a record monthly deficit in August. But the plane
sales appeared to be a one-time statistical oddity, and the overall
figures showed that the huge falloff in exports to the Pacific Rim
_ combined with growing imports of steel, toys and electronics _
were beginning to take a larger toll on jobs and corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The figures underscored the political imperatives behind the
dual messages that Clinton is expected to deliver in Japan and
South Korea: that the United States wants to help the Asian
economies, but not at the cost of absorbing more and more of their
products.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the slight improvement in the recent month's figures,
for the first nine months of 1998 the U.S. trade deficit has been
running about 50 percent higher than it was a year ago, when the
Asian crisis was in its early months. That widening deficit poses
what Secretary of Commerce William Daley recently called ``a
political problem of enormous magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton said: ``Nothing is more important to
restoring stability and growth in Asia than efforts to restore
Japan's economy. But it has been stalled for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time he cited South Korea's giant
conglomerates, the chaebol, saying that their resistance to
economic liberalization had to end.
</P>
<P>
   In both Tokyo and Seoul, Clinton's aides say, he will raise the
subject of soaring shipments of foreign steel to the U.S. market,
an issue that has mobilized unions and steelmakers alike. The
companies point to a first wave of layoffs in the steel industry as
an indicator of what will happen to other U.S. industries as the
full effects of the Asian crisis begin to be felt broadly in
American manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that the import explosion here has yet to really
occur,'' said Allen Sinai, chief global economist of Primark
Decision Economics in Boston. ``The aircraft-export days are
numbered for us. And when the Asian economies begin to do better
with their production, the flood of cheaper imports will be
noticeable, even on lean-and-mean American companies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To be sure, cheaper imports also offer advantages for U.S.
consumers and companies. They lower the cost of production,
particularly for automakers and construction companies that can buy
parts or steel more cheaply. Many are now searching the world for
such deals, gradually relying on more foreign suppliers. That often
contributes to restraints in prices, allowing the kind of
interest-rate cuts that the Federal Reserve announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The figures released Wednesday show how much of the current
trade problem is rooted in Asia. The deficit with China for
September, $5.9 billion, is larger than that with Japan for the
month, $5.1 billion. Together, the two countries have surpluses in
the trade of goods with the United States amounting to nearly $89
billion since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   American car exports to Japan _ the subject of the Clinton
administration's big confrontation with Tokyo three years ago _
amounted to $79 million in September, and $709 million since the
beginning of the year. These paltry results provide vivid evidence
of how the economic downturn has wiped out any advantages from the
1995 agreement with the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   After Asian nations, the biggest trade deficits were with Canada
and Mexico, the two other members of the North American Free Trade
Agreement, totaling a little more than $6 billion for September,
and $24.4 billion since the beginning of the year. The United
States continues to run a small surplus with Brazil, which received
a $41.5 billion IMF bailout last week. Trade with Brazil, however,
is expected to turn into deficit as the Brazilians slip deeper into
recession.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said that exports in September increased
to $77.1 billion, from $75.4 billion in August, but the entire
difference was attributed to the aircraft sales.
</P>
<P>
   Imports edged down to $91.2 billion from $91.3 billion in
August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
