</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DREPUNG, Tibet -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- TIBET-MONSTERIES,
11-17 -- Monks descend the stairs at Drepung Monestary, once
claimed to be the world's largest monastery with 10,000 monks.
Today there are only 600. Over the last four years, Chinese
authorities have carried out a campaign to tighten control over
Tibetan monasteries, which Beijing has come to see as nests of
opposition to Chinese rule over this devout Himalayan region (Seth
Fasion/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AL KHADR, West Bank -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- ISRAEL-WESBANK,
11-17 -- Jamilee Ali from the Palestinian village of Al Khadr
covered her face and wept at the uprooting of a fig tree by
Israelis constructing a road to Efrat. The new road through the
valley on the edge of Al Khadr, southwest of Bethlehem, is supposed
to connect the northern end of the fast-growing Jewish town of
Efrat to the Jerusalem-Hebron highway. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KRASNOYARSK-26, Russia -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- RUSSIA-NUKE,
11-17 -- A worker at Krasnoyarsk-26 stares at a dismantled control
boards which once operated one of the nuclear reactors. Once
considered a bastion of privilege for the Soviet Union's scientific
elite, it is now an impoverished ward of the state. (James Hill/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
