<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 11/18/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW ORLEANS -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- GOVS, 11-18 -- In their
debut appearance as heirs to the latest American political dynasty,
Gov. George Bush of Texas, right, and his brother, governor-elect
Jeb Bush of Florida, at the opening of the Republican Governors
Association's annual convention Wednesday in New Orleans. Not since
1967 -- when Nelson Rockefeller was governor of New York and his
brother Winthrop was governor of Arkansas -- have two brothers
occupied governor's mansions. (Lee Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) BEIJING -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CHINA-PHARMACEUTICALS, 11-18
-- Parents of patients leaving Beijing Children's Research
Hospital, where many of them buy expensive drugs from the West.
Chinese doctors prescribed hundreds of millions of dollars worth of
expensive Western medicine last year. The underlying motive being
that cash-strapped Chinese hospitals are allowed to sell medicines
their doctors prescribe at a profit, and the profit is far greater
when doctors prescribe expensive Western drugs. (Elisabeth
Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) YONKERS -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- UN-CHILD SUPPORT, 11-18 --
Audrey Camp Nekunam, 71, in her one-bedroom apartment in Yonkers
which is furnished with the few remaining pieces her husband left
after leaving. Divorce is rarely simple, nor is it always fair. But
spouses of UN staff members have found it is uniquely devastating.
(Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo) Attention eds: Story now
skedded as U.N.-DIVORCE.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SYCAMORE, Ill. -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- SMOKING-PARIAHS,
11-18 -- There are few riddles in life more enigmatic than the
spell that smoking can cast, even to smokers like Jan Binder who
has walked the horror chamber of nicotine. Binder smoked a
cigarette in her home in Sycamore on Tuesday. (Lloyd Degrane/New
York Times Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- MIDEAST-AID, 11-18 -- Israel
and the Palestinians are seeking U.S. money to put their
land-for-security plan into effect. Aharon Domb, left, and Pinkhas
Valershtein, leaders of the settlers movement Yesha, look over West
Bank maps showing the effects of redeployment. (/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- BISHOPS-ABORTION, 11-18
-- In a pointed statement that calls Roman Catholic politicians to
heed the teachings of their faith, the nation's Catholic bishops
declared they had a pastoral responsibility to speak out to public
officials who support abortion rights and euthanasia and urge them
``to a change of heart.'' Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston discussed
the statement with reporters Wednesday in Washington. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- IRIS-OPERA, 11-18 -- Fiora
Contino, left, and Karen Notare, will take part in the centennial
celebration of the work,''Iris,'' at Alice Tully Hall in New York
City. One hundred years ago Sunday, Pietro Mascagni's opera
``Iris'' had its premiere at the Teatro Costanzi in Rome, the same
theater in which, eight years before, his first and most famous
opera, ``Cavalleria Rusticana,'' received 60 curtain calls at its
premiere. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- GODOT-THEATER-REVIEW, 11-18
-- Tony Shalhoub, front, and John Turturro as Vladimir and Estragon
in the Classic Stage Company's solemn revival of ``Waiting for
Godot.'' Shalhoub and Turturro, thoughtful, sensitive stage actors
who have found success on television and in the movies, seem
humbled by Beckett's mysterious play, and deliver admirably
pared-down portrayals, devoid of famous-actor's ego. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1998 --FALL-ANTIQUES-SHOW , 11-18
-- This armoire was carved in Wisconsin by an anonymous Swiss man
and was being sold at the Fall Antiques Show in New York for
$7,500. Miniseries and documentaries have long extolled the
immigrant experience in the United States. But few if any scholars
have addressed the connection between immigration and America's
aesthetic history. Luckily, until that time, the antiques show in
New York will have to do. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN FRANCISCO -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CIR-QUAKE-CHAMPION,
11-18 -- Denis Fong, center, was headed for another victory in a
Quake tournament in San Francisco during the Professional Gamers'
League championships. Fong, 21, also known as ``Thresh,'' is
considered by his peers as the Michael Jordan of computer games.
(Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- HILLARY, 11-18 -- As a
withering year draws to a close with her husband's threatened
impeachment, Hillary Rodham Clinton prevails above the American
landscape in all her signature duality. President Clinton and his
wife took part in an event at the White House where President
Clinton announced funding for after-school programs earlier this
month. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CONGRESS-REPUBS, 11-18 --
Rep. Bob Livingston, elected by Congressional Republicans as
speaker of the House, jokes with Rep. Dick Armey, who was
re-elected majority leader, during a break in Republican caucus in
Washington on Wednesday. At right is Rep. J. C. Watts, elected to
head the Republican Conference. Looking on at left is Rep. Jennifer
Dunn who lost in her bid for majority leader. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- LIVENT-ASSESS, 11-18 --With
a mountain of debt, its stock frozen and shareholders clamoring for
redress, Chapter 11 reorganization buys the Livent, Inc., the
troubled company behind the musical ``Ragtime,'' breathing space to
try to get its house in order and keep its creditors at bay. Garth
Drabinsky, chairman and chief executive of Livent, at the Ford
Center for the Performing Arts in Manhattan. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ABOARD USS DWIGHT D. EISENHOWER -- Nov. 18, 1998 --
IRAQ-3, 11-18 -- The USS Dwight D. Eisenhower, background, and the
British navy's HMS Cumberland patrol the waters of the Persian Gulf
on Tuesday. After stepping back from a massive bombing campaign of
Iraq, the United States and Britain are redoubling their support
for Iraqi opposition groups as an alternative means of ousting
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein. (Shawn Eklund/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ABOARD USS DWIGHT D. EISENHOWER -- Nov. 18, 1998 --
IRAQ-2, 11-18 -- From left: Lt. Marcel Leblanc, from New Orleans,
La., Lt. Matt Bartel, of Barrington, R.I., and Lt. Jason Nargi, of
Burlington, Vt., copy down combat Search and Rescue (SAR)
information during a pre-flight briefing aboard the USS Dwight D.
Eisenhower while the aircraft carrier sailed in the northern region
of the Persian Gulf on Sunday. (Shawn Eklund/New York Times
Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PHOENIX -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- BOOK-DALAILAMA-AZR, 11-18 --
Psychiatrist Howard Cutler poses in his Phoenix condominium. Behind
him is a 16th century tanka, or Tibetan painting. Cutler wrote a
book with the Dalai Lama called ``The Art of Happiness: A Handbook
for Living.'' (Photo by Paul F. Gero/The Arizona Republic)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT, 11-18 --
Many woodworkers frown upon the use of stain for coloring wood.
They feel that it is too often used to disguise inferior and
uninteresting wood to make it appear more like high-quality walnut
or mahogany. Still, many professional cabinet makers and furniture
craftsmen find that there are a number of legitimate reasons to
color wood with stain. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- NY-COP-CARS , 11-18 -- One
of the components of the city's visual signature will soon go the
way of all things. One by one, the NYPD's familiar patrol cars,
Chevrolet Caprices painted white and a custom shade that the
department calls ``grabber blue,'' are being replaced by lily-white
Ford Crown Victorias. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CIR-GEEK-NOTES, 11-18 --
Called Speech Mike, this slender and ergonomically-correct
hand-held device by Philips Electronics is a microphone for
personal computers as well as a trackball. It allows the user to
sit in a more relaxed posture while using voice recognition
software or surfing the internet. It is scheduled to arrive on
retail shelves early next year and cost about $70. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON-- Nov. 18, 1998 -- IMPEACH, 11-18 -- With the
impeachment hearings set to begin Thursday, House Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde was in the spotlight while talking to
reporters Wednesday. The committee is to call Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel, for questioning on Thursday. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- CONGRESS-ARMEY, 11-18 --
Newly reelected House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, right,
appearing before the press with the two house members who had
challenged him for his leadership position, Rep. Steve Largent,
R-Ok, left, and Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wa. Armey won on the third
ballot. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- NY-HOTEL-SPA-2, 11-18 -- The
lobby of the new W, a business hotel and spa set to open on Dec. 1
within the shell of the modestly drab Doral Inn in New York's
Midtown. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- NY-HOTEL-SPA-1, 11-18 --
What does your hotel lobby grow? At the new W, a business hotel and
spa set to open on Dec. 1 within the shell of the modestly drab
Doral Inn in New York's Midtown, herbs are sprouting behind the
front desk. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- BATTERY, 11-18 --Batteries --
cells, packs and button-size disks that people can't live without _
are dying like flies. Or so it seems when you need them. And people
in the electronics industry agree that batteries are a weak point
in portable technology. A common consumer complaint is that they
don't last long enough, or they don't last as long as battery
manufacturers suggest they should. (David Corio/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DREPUNG, Tibet -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- TIBET-MONSTERIES,
11-17 -- Monks descend the stairs at Drepung Monestary, once
claimed to be the world's largest monastery with 10,000 monks.
Today there are only 600. Over the last four years, Chinese
authorities have carried out a campaign to tighten control over
Tibetan monasteries, which Beijing has come to see as nests of
opposition to Chinese rule over this devout Himalayan region (Seth
Fasion/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AL KHADR, West Bank -- Nov. 18, 1998 -- ISRAEL-WESBANK,
11-17 -- Jamilee Ali from the Palestinian village of Al Khadr
covered her face and wept at the uprooting of a fig tree by
Israelis constructing a road to Efrat. The new road through the
