<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ARMEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN IN THE NEWS: DICK ARMEY, AN IDEOLOGUE WITH SWAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Leader Dick Armey, a man from North
Dakota with Texas in his swagger, cannot help indulging in a hokey
fishing tale or two when he is in a cheery mood. But seldom do they
blossom into allegory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about the poor bass,'' Armey told reporters back in
September. ``Put yourself in his place. You go into Denny's and you
sit down and somebody puts your hamburger in front of you and you
pick it up and take a bite. All of a sudden somebody grabs you by
the mouth, drags you around the store, drags you outside, pulls the
hook out of your mouth and throws you back into Denny's. That is
what the poor fish goes through.''
</P>
<P>
   For Armey, the past three weeks have been no different. Many of
his Republican colleagues aligned against him, eager to yank him
out of the leadership position he has held since 1995. But
Wednesday, after weeks of intense lobbying for a second chance at
the post of majority leader, Armey was re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   It was far from a runaway victory; members voted three times in
Wednesday's in-House election before the ballots finally sifted out
the three other challengers and fell conclusively in Armey's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of us provided for the other a merry chase,'' said Armey,
who represents suburban Dallas, after the secret votes were
counted. Summing up the rigors of the challenge he faced, he added,
``I have an even more keenly honed opportunity to live and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 4, the day after the congressional midterm elections, it
looked as if Armey would not survive the wrath of his Republican
colleagues, who blamed their House leaders for ending up with a net
loss of five seats. Few of them could forget the sight of the
majority leader, on national television, sweeping aside dire
predictions of Republican losses with braggadocio just hours before
the polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich resigned his post almost
immediately, and two other leaders were ousted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Armey rallied, spending days on the phone and calling into
action allies to help sway disillusioned members his way. The power
of incumbency and his years of experience helped bolster his
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Born on July 7, 1940, in Cando, N.D., Richard Keith Armey worked
as a grain elevator operator and a telephone lineman before he
traded in blue collar work for a degree from Jamestown College and
a Ph.D. in economics from the University of Oklahoma. He and his
wife, Susan, have five children from previous marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Armey is an ideologue who dislikes the current tax rate and the
International Monetary Fund as much as he does the Washington
cocktail circuit. (He reluctantly bought a tuxedo this year, which
he pairs with armadillo-skin cowboy boots.) An architect of the
Contract With America, he has fought against abortion and gun
control, and championed school vouchers, which permit tax dollars
to travel to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   When asked amid the Lewinsky scandal what would happen if he
ever found himself in President Clinton's position, Armey thought
of his wife and replied, ``I would be looking up from a pool of
blood and hearing, `How do I reload this thing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Although he emerged victorious Wednesday, it has been a rocky
year and a half for Armey. In July 1997, Armey attended a meeting
of Republican rebels who sought to oust Gingrich. He told Gingrich
about the plot, then disavowed any role in it. That left members on
both sides distrustful.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early in the year, he faced a brief challenge to his
position from Rep. Bill Paxon, R-N.Y. In the end, it was Paxon who
backed down and later retired.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, his allies reminded colleagues that Armey had
campaigned hard for them, and is capable of learning from his
mistakes. Although the vote was close, 127-95 in the third ballot,
the argument worked.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin of Louisiana, who supported Armey,
said the narrow vote carried a warning. Armey, he said, needs to
bid farewell to the new style of firebrand Republican governance
and develop a less abrasive leadership style.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to receive it as a stern message that members want
him to work with Livingston,'' Tauzin added, referring to the new
speaker of the House, Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La. ``This took a
lot of assurances that Armey would be very much a team player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
