<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; COMDEXDIARY &LR;  _ It's 8 a.m. at the Luxor Hotel and Casino, a glass
and steel pyramid whose excesses might embarrass even a pharaoh. A
few slot machines ring out, but not too many people have started
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pyramid Cafe just off the gaming floor, Martin Sacks sits
at the head of a table of a dozen staffers from International
Microcomputer Software Inc., or IMSI, a $63 million Novato company
that makes a variety of software packages mainly for business users
and designers.
</P>
<P>
   While others gripe about the Comdex noise and clutter, Sacks
relishes the show's throbbing energy. ``Comdex is awesome,'' he
says at the breakfast table, ``because it's the one opportunity to
see where you are. You're talking to customers. You're seeing the
competition. You live in the cocoon of your office, and this is a
good slap-across-the-face reality check.'' By Dan Fost
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AOL _ &LR;  America Online and Netscape Communications reportedly
are in talks to integrate Netscape's Web browser into AOL's online
service instead of or in addition to Microsoft's browser. By Jon
Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PERSONAL TECH PACKAGE &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GREETING &LR;  _ Holiday greetings have come a long way since 1843, when
Londoner Sir Henry Cole got fed up with writing annual letters to
friends and relatives and commissioned an illustrator to design
what would be the first Christmas card.
</P>
<P>
   Today, anyone with a PC and an Internet connection can send a
colorful, card, complete with animation and sound, anywhere in the
world in a matter of minutes by using e-mail. And inexpensive
software lets you create professional-looking cards from scratch,
complete with personal photos, and print them out in elegant color.
By David Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A  &LR; _ Question: Over the past couple of years, I've
accumulated a lot of free CDs that either arrived in the mail or
came with PC magazines _ you know, demo software, AOL connection
software, stuff like that. Rather than throw them out, I've taken
to using them as cup covers to keep my coffee hot. Now, though, I'm
starting to think that there may be chemicals in the CDs that could
hurt me. Is there anything hazardous about them? Columnist David
Einstein has the answer
</P>
