<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE SURGES SPUR WIDE GAINS AS DOW CLIMBS BY 54.83  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c. 19988 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Late-session surges drove stocks to broad gains
Wednesday as investors more thoroughly digested the Federal
Reserve's decision the day before to cut interest rates for a third
time in seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a heightened degree of confidence that the Fed is
doing the right thing,'' said Frederick Taylor, chief investment
officer at United States Trust Co., predicting that the economy
would ``barely'' grow next year while profits modestly fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrials finished with a gain of 54.83 points,
to 9,041.11, a level just 3.2 percent below its mid-July record.
The blue-chip gauge was down 19.3 percent from that record at the
end of August.
</P>
<P>
   Even better was Wednesday's performance of the Nasdaq market,
which climbed 18.92 points, just more than 1 percent, as various
Internet and other technology raced ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape jumped 10 to 39\ and America Online jumped 8], to 83}
on talk of an alliance between the two companies. Ebay soared 18~,
to 147{, Amazon.com 15{, to 164 and Yahoo 13], to 190[.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings of these current darlings may be skimpy or nonexistent
but according to one school of thought, their corporate fortunes
would probably suffer far less than other businesses from recession
or deflation.
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks, by contrast, were mostly lower Wednesday. Cutting
the prime rate in response to the Fed rate reduction may have been
a factor, but a bigger reason seemed to be disclosure of steeper
costs associated with the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan eased 1, to 105~, Bankers Trust 1[, to 67 7/16.
American Express, on the other hand, jumped 2}, to 102[ to account
for about one-fifth of the Dow's rise.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market was mixed, with short-term rates edging higher
and longer-term rates a bit lower as traders and investors
continued to bet on another round of interest-rate reductions at
the next meeting of the Fed's policymaking committee on Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I expect the Fed to ease again,'' said Robert
Stovall, president of Stovall/Twenty-First Advisers. The central
bank might hold off then if stocks are then at or near new highs,
especially if holiday shopping is strong, he added, but ``more
easing is needed to prevent a liquidity squeeze from grabbing
capital markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Stovall also cited the Wall Street maxim, supported by history,
that any time the Fed cuts rates two or more times in sequence,
both the stock and bond markets will advance over the following 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Another optimist Wednesday was Clare Zempel, chief investment
strategist at Robert Baird in Milwaukee, who said: ``The broad
stock market has considerable room to rise.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the relationship of yields on three-month Treasury
bills to the earnings yield _ the inverse of the more common
price-earnings calculation _ for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, a ratio
now at its lowest level since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk-reward relationship is decisively on the side of
reward,'' Zempel said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Dow stocks with sizable gains Wednesday were 3M, 2 7/16,
to 82 1/16; Merck, 2\, to 149|; General Electric 1}, to 91}; and
Wal-Mart, 1}, to 73].
</P>
<P>
   Because of the uncertainty of the general earnings outlook,
``people are looking for the steady growers,'' said John Silvia,
economist at Scudder Kemper Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup, which reported higher earnings, climbed 15/16, to
56 7/16. Daimler-Chrysler, in its second day of trading on the New
York Stock Exchange, rose 1[, to 85.
</P>
<P>
   The strength in drug stocks went well beyond Merck.
Warner-Lambert rose 3\, to 77 15/16 while gains for Bristol-Myers,
Lilly and Schering-Plough reached 2 points or more.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems closed down 1/16, to 66|, after trading as high
as 69 13/16. The stock had added 3~ Tuesday as it won a licensing
suit against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 51 issues hit new yearly highs
and 32 sank to new lows but declining issues slightly outnumbered
advancing ones, 1,545 to 1,514. Volume was a moderate 652.5 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 added 5.16 points, or 45/100ths of 1
percent, while the small-cap Russell 2000 gained 69/100ths of 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, two of the most closely watched markets these days
posted gains. Brazil's main index climbed 2.60 percent while
Japan's Nikkei 225 gained 1.29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose 2.30 percent in Mexico, 64/100ths of 1 percent in
Hong Kong and 30/100ths of 1 percent in France but fell 52/100ths
of 1 percent in Britain and 37/100ths of 1 percent in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
