<HEADER>
A7989 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON &LR;      11-18 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A Low-Tech Use for Free CDs  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Over the past couple of years, I've accumulated a lot of
free CDs that either arrived in the mail or came with PC magazines
_ you know, demo software, AOL connection software, stuff like
that. Rather than throw them out, I've taken to using them as cup
covers to keep my coffee hot. Now, though, I'm starting to think
that there may be chemicals in the CDs that could hurt me. Is there
anything hazardous about them?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  CDs, both the music and software kind, start out as
piece of plastic coated with a thin, reflective layer of aluminum.
After a disc is replicated from a master disc, it's given a coat of
protective lacquer that's hardened using ultraviolet light. So, no,
there's no hazardous material involved, and you can continue to use
your novel cup covers.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the tip on what to do with unwanted CDs. By the way,
have you ever thought of using them as coasters? That way you could
have one below the cup and one on top.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know if Syquest is ever coming back? They have a Sparq
One unit of mine that was to be replaced. I can't get a phone
number to call and their Web site is down. I certainly hope they
come back. I need that unit. Can you help me contact them?
</P>
<P>
   A: For readers who don't know, Syquest is a maker of removable
disk drives that has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy. It's also in
the process of selling itself to an unnamed buyer. That means it
could make a comeback under new management. In the meantime, it's
offering limited technical support, which you can reach at (510)
226-5400. It seems to me like getting a defective drive replaced
would fall into the category of limited support. Especially if the
drive was under warranty. And they must certainly have products to
spare, since they couldn't sell enough of them to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every once in a while my computer will freeze up and tell me
that it's suffered a ``general protection fault.'' What is this, in
language I can understand, and is there anything I can do to
prevent it from happening?
</P>
<P>
   A: Windows uses general protection faults (GPFs) as a protective
measure to prevent programs from overlapping each other within the
main system memory (aka RAM). When an application you're running
tries to allocate space in memory that's unavailable, the result is
a GPF, halting the offending application in its tracks. Sometimes,
the application can be closed and then restarted, but sometimes
your entire system must be restarted.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody gets GPFs occasionally, so I wouldn't worry. If you
find that a particular application causes them, you might want to
remove and reinstall it. Also, you can reduce the risk of GPFs in
general by not having lots of applications open simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I use the Microsoft Office Shortcut Bar quite a bit to switch
between programs. The trouble is, I have to load it manually every
time I start Windows. Is there a way to have this toolbar
automatically loaded onto the desktop every time I boot up?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Indeed there is. After loading the shortcut bar, click on
the left-most icon, then choose Exit from the menu that appears.
This will close the shortcut bar, but before that happens, you'll
see a dialog box giving you the option to have the shortcut start
automatically every time you start Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 78-year-old father is losing control of his hands and it's
difficult for him to type. Is speech-recognition software advanced
enough for this feature to really help him? He doesn't want to mess
around with spelling, punctuation, etc. Also, like most of us, he
is impatient and wants to be able to dictate normally, not one ...
word ... at ... a ... time. Could you recommend any solutions and
also let me know what, if any, upgrades I'd need for my computer to
make the software work?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Until 1997, commercially available speech recognition
software used what was called ``discreet'' technology _ which
required users to pause between words. Now, however, several
affordable programs are available that use ``continuous speech''
recognition, letting you talk to the computer just as you would to
a person.
</P>
<P>
   The three leaders in the field are Naturally Speaking from
Dragon Systems, ViaVoice from IBM and VoiceXpress from Lernout &AMP;
Hauspie. These programs come in different versions aimed at
different kinds of users, from individuals at home to professionals
in corporations. A program that meets the needs of dad should cost
you less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering hands-free dictation, the newest
programs let you use voice commands to fix spelling and punctuation
errors, and generally do anything to the text that would normally
require a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Strike a blow for individualism and use an e-mail program that
doesn't have Microsoft or Netscape in the name. Try Eudora Light,
which you can get at &LR;  www.eudora.com,  &LR; or Pegasus, a really
powerful program available at  &LR; www.pmail.usa.com. &LR;  Both are free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
