<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      11-18 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL TO BRING PATRIOTS TO HARTFORD SAID `REAL CLOSE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The state of Connecticut is trying to lure the New
England Patriots to downtown Hartford with a $280 million publicly
financed stadium package, a proposal so sweet some said team owner
Robert Kraft would be unable to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is real close,'' said one person involved in the
talks between the team and Connecticut officials. ``But no one has
given anyone a time ultimatum. ... They need to know very
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the proposal, Kraft's team would play
rent-free in a new 65,000-seat open-air stadium to be built by 2001
and paid for entirely by bondholders, taxpayers and football fans.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials, who have been meeting for weeks on
finalizing an offer to the Patriots, said Wednesday the deal could
be announced as early as Thursday. The agreement would not allow
for any ``wiggle room'' for the Patriots to back out of it,
according to a source with knowledge of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Governor John Rowland, who has spearheaded the attempts to lure
the Patriots away from Foxborough, abruptly cancelled plans
Wednesday to attend the National Republican Governors Conference in
New Orleans so he could meet with business and legislative leaders
and brief them on the proposal. Rowland needs to quickly complete
the deal so he can call the Legislature back for a vote authorizing
stadium construction bonds before the session ends Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said talks were continuing, but there was no
agreement as of Wednesday night. Patriots spokesman Stacey James,
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Boston, the finger pointing has already begun over
the prospect of having the team leave Foxborough. But part of the
nastiness that has characterized the negotiations between Kraft and
local politicians was also evident Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sending him a sympathy card,'' Mayor Thomas M. Menino said
of Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   And House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, the man who has almost
single-handedly blocked a publicly-financed stadium deal for the
last two years, was quoted in the Salem Evening News as saying,
``I'm going to give tax (breaks) to some fat-ass millionaire and
screw our kids?'' Finneran admitted he used those words at a
Peabody dinner event Tuesday night, but said they were spoken in a
conversation about other NFL owners.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless a certain resolve also settled on the State House,
with Governor Paul Cellucci, attending the governor's conference in
New Orleans, wanly urging voters in a press release to complain to
their representatives for not getting a deal done here and blaming
the House in advance should the team leave.
</P>
<P>
   Said Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, who struck a $72
million land and infrastructure deal with Kraft last February that
Finneran blocked: ``This day did not have to come.''
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Martin Meehan (D-Lowell), who has been dealing
with NFL franchise relocation issues on the House Judiciary
Committee, said the league has no way of stopping Kraft from moving
the team and likely would not try because of the national
perception of the stadium ``fiasco'' here.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that this has become personal,'' Meehan said,
``I don't think that's healthy in economic development projects.
... I believe they are going to leave and reach an agreement in
Hartford. It doesn't make any sense for them not to move to
Hartford at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, there is a string of other time-sensitive
development issues associated with the huge $1 billion convention
center, housing and retail project known as Adriaen's Landing along
the Connecticut River, which is putting pressure on securing the
centerpiece of the deal: a new stadium for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   With the clock ticking, Rowland Wednesday canceled his trip and
privately apprised about 30 legislative and business leaders of the
proposal in a surprise two-hour meeting at the Governor's Mansion
in West Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut House Speaker Tom Ritter and Majority leader David
Pudlin, both Democrats, attended the meeting, showing bi-partisan
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been anyone that has come out so far to say we
shouldn't pursue the opportunity,'' said Larry Perosino, a
spokesman for the House Democrats. Given that support, any bond
issue would likely be approved, especially in light of the state's
budget surplus, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The business community, led by Phoenix Home Life Mutual
Insurance Co. chief Richard Fiondella, is also behind the prospect
of revitalizing downtown and there is expected to be a bidding war
among the city's largest insurance companies for securing naming
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland told reporters after Wednesday's meeting that Kraft
would not be allowed to negotiate with other states if he signs a
tentative agreement on the Hartford deal.
</P>
<P>
   Public funding, which would top $370 million including
infrastructure, would be paid for over time by the team's payroll,
sales and usage taxes, in addition to the 10 percent ticket tax,
those familiar with the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the flurry of activity between the team and
Connecticut officials in recent weeks is that utility officials met
with Hartford Mayor Michael Peters Nov. 2 to figure out a way to
replace the steam plant on the site where the stadium would be
built at the crossroads of Interstates 84 and 91.
</P>
<P>
   And there finally appears to be a critical mass of will power,
effort and money in Hartford which could lure the team away from
Foxborough once and for all. Right now, Connecticut is the only
state Kraft is talking to, after he dismissed as inadequate a
proposal by the Massachusetts House last summer offering $57
million in infrastructure and walked away from talks with Rhode
Island last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Finneran defended his offer as more than enough and
blamed Kraft for being greedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very consistent with the trend in professional sports.
It's all about money,'' Finneran said. ``They don't care who they
bully and pillage. And unfortunately it's the taxpayers and other
jurisdictions that continue to fall over.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his comments about a ``fat-ass millionaire,'' Finneran
said he was referencing Al Davis, the general manager of the
Oakland Raiders, and Art Modell, who moved the Cleveland Browns to
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff writer Anthony Flint contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
