<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-GINGRICH-FUNDS-44     11-18 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GINGRICH-FUNDS-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT GINGRICH, GOP LACKS MASTER FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Newt Gingrich stepping down from Congress, the Republican
Party is losing its top fund-raiser, a man who, by party accounts,
raised more than $60 million for office-seekers this year and
masterminded a strategy that helped Republicans take over Congress
in 1994 and retain control ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Ronald Reagan was president has the Republican Party
had a fund-raiser with as much star power and willingness to dazzle
donors as Gingrich. Without him, the party is left with no one in
its leadership ready to step into this role and with no obvious
candidates in the wings as the party prepares for the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that because of Newt's fund raising, his
decision to step down has to be greeted with a level of ambivalence
by the party,'' said Ralph Reed, a Republican strategist based in
Atlanta. ``You are losing someone who has probably raised, over the
last four years, conservatively, a quarter of a billion dollars for
the party and those things are hard to replace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has not decided what he will do next; and whether it is
teaching, espousing his philosophy or resuming a position at GOPAC,
his former political organization, he might well continue to do
some fund raising. It is clear, however, that he will no longer
serve as the party's top money man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a while before anyone can fill Newt's fund-raising
shoes,'' said Mark Braden, a Washington lawyer who represents
Republican candidates. ``Fund raising is a combination of sitting
in the right chair in Congress and being in the right places in the
campaigns. Newt was extraordinarily good at giving the `red meat'
speech to the faithful. I don't see anyone who can walk in and fill
that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to calculate exactly how much Gingrich has raised.
The party estimates that he raised $60 million for the National
Republican Congressional Committee in the midterm elections;
Gingrich's office says that for House candidates and other
Republican office-seekers, the total comes to $76 million.
</P>
<P>
   His own campaign war chest _ this year it came to $7 million _
is always one of the fattest in Congress. And in the 1996
presidential election year, Gingrich is credited by the party with
raising close to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., who is to become
the next speaker, is a more modest fund-raiser: His campaign war
chest totals just under $1 million and he gave away around $2
million to Republican candidates over the last four years. By his
staff's count, he made ``dozens'' of campaign fund-raising
appearances for candidates this year, raising around around $1
million for them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the party's best-known politician, Gingrich had a reputation
as someone who was not uncomfortable asking for money and who could
deftly separate donors from their dollars. He embraced fund raising
with a passion, understood its strategic importance and, despite
his consistently high negative ratings, was a celebrity outside the
Beltway who whipped up enthusiastic crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either directly or indirectly, Newt raised around two-thirds
of the $90 million that we raised this year,'' said Ted Maness
executive director of the National Republican Congressional
committee. ``He will be missed. This committee will try to expand
the base of people we use for fund raising. But it will take a
while to replace him. People who attended his speeches were
spellbound. He had that effect on our donors.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich raised money through fund-raisers that benefited other
Republican candidates as well as from the use of his name, voice
and likeness on telemarketing calls and direct mail solicitations.
In the last election, he traveled to 189 congressional districts in
48 states, 15 states in the last week alone.
</P>
<P>
   He also dipped into his own campaign funds, as well as into his
leadership political action committee, the Monday Morning Pac, to
give to other Republican candidates _ $896,437 in 1998. In
addition, he put $500,000 of his campaign money into a last-minute
television issue-ad blitz, which later came under fire, on behalf
of Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond fund raising, Gingrich was perhaps even more important to
House Republicans as a financial strategist who developed a game
plan in the early 1990s that is credited with putting the party on
solid financial footing and getting money to House Republican
challengers prior to the 1994 elections, a critical factor in the
Republican victory.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1992, when the party's congressional fund-raising
committee was nearly $5 million in debt and Republicans were out of
power, Gingrich promoted a ``share-the-wealth'' plan in which
Republican incumbents in safe districts were pressed to send
campaign funds to support fledging Republican candidates. He helped
create the ``Incumbent Protection Fund'' which, despite its name,
shifted millions _ $10.6 million by 1996, for example _ from
Republican incumbents to challengers. In the last year, he upped
the ante, pressing House committee chairmen to bring in $100,000 to
the party's televised campaign efforts and $50,000 for incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1998 midterm elections, the congressional committee
raised $81 million by September 30; for the entire two-years of the
1996 mid-term cycle, the committee raised $93 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also used the power of the speaker's office _ which
gave him ``make it or break it power'' over nearly every piece of
legislation _ to draw money from Washington's corporate lobbyists
and their political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt was an entrepreneur who found creative and untried new
ways to maximize the financial resources of the party,'' said Reed,
the Republican strategist. ``He worked the K Street lobbyists and
he turned the unused checkbook balances of safe incumbents into
assets for the broader party. These are innovations that will be
part of politics of the future, but they were not done until
Newt.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Gingrich would be stepping down as Speaker in the
year 2002, under term limits, the National Republican Congressional
Committee had already begun use other Republicans as fund-raisers,
Maness said.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to Gingrich say they do not expect him to retire
completely from the money circuit. Richard Galen, executive
director of GOPAC, said: ``His star is tarnished as speaker. But
not as Newt Gingrich.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
