<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUGGENHEIM-MUSEUM-     11-18 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUGGENHEIM-MUSEUM-ART-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM PROPOSES A NEW BRANCH ON MANHATTAN'S RIVERFRONT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL and CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum is quietly
developing plans for a large new branch to be designed by the Los
Angeles architect Frank Gehry and built at the Hudson River on Pier
40 off Houston Street, said people who were consulted on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed museum, part of a growing empire of Guggenheim
outposts, including those in Spain and Germany, would be built on
state land in the middle of a new shorefront state park, a
10-minute walk to Chelsea or SoHo, Manhattan's two major art
centers.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first major museum building to rise in the city
since the Whitney in 1966 and perhaps the biggest change in the
West Side skyline since the $500 million glass-sheathed New York
Convention Center opened in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Like all projects affecting the ecology of the Hudson River, the
museum would face extensive federal, state and local review.
Approval from the Army Corps of Engineers would be required if the
building were to extend beyond the pier and into the river.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry also designed the striking and highly acclaimed $100
million museum that the Guggenheim opened a year ago in Bilbao,
Spain. The museum, with its rakish silhouette, sweeping curves and
titanium skin, attracts more than 1.4 million visitors and millions
of dollars in the last year to the old Basque riverfront city.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed new museum in Manhattan could cost four times as
much, with some prospective donors already offering support, people
at the museum said. It would allow the Guggenheim to exhibit more
of its permanent holdings of modern art as well as new collections
and to expand its programming greatly, beefing up areas like
photography, architecture and video.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry and Thomas Krens, the Guggenheim's director, declined to
discuss the project Wednesday. Other officials at the museum said
it was simply an idea in the early stages of development. Gehry,
however, has already produced architectural drawings for the
building.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has also assembled figures on the project's economic
benefits, claiming that in the first two years of operation, the
new museum would generate $1 billion in tax revenues, extra tourism
and employment for the city and state.
</P>
<P>
   City and state officials said they had not yet been consulted,
although Krens was said to have held a preliminary discussion about
it with Gov. George E. Pataki in East Hampton, N.Y., last summer.
Zenia Mucha, a spokeswoman for the governor, did not respond to
calls about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Pier 40 is, at nearly 15 acres, the largest pier jutting into
the Hudson on Manhattan's West Side, sitting amid the new five-mile
Hudson River Park established by the state legislature and signed
into law by Pataki on Sept. 8. Work on the 500-acre park, which
runs from Battery Park City to 59th Street, has just begun and is
scheduled to last until 2003 at a cost of up to $390 million. Pier
40, on state-owned land, is now occupied by a three-story 2,200-car
garage, in the shape of an oblong donut, which also has soccer
fields on the roof and some areas for community use inside.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear how the museum would fit into the lengthy
sliver park and the anticipated commercial development planned for
as many as 19 renovated piers within the park area.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders questioned about the museum's plan said it was
the first they had heard of it and that they would not want the
museum to supplant or dominate an important segment of the park.
</P>
<P>
   The park, now controlled by a 13-member state-city trust, grew
out of the long-disputed highway plan Westway, the
multibillion-dollar sunken roadway that was to have run along the
Hudson, but which was defeated in a concerted campaign by local
opponents who cited environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   People who have spoken with Krens said that the project has
already been promised substantial private support from at least one
trustee of the Guggenheim, Peter B. Lewis. Lewis, the new chairman
of the Guggenheim Foundation and chairman and chief executive of
the Progressive Corp., a Cleveland-based insurance company, made an
unrelated cash pledge of $50 million to the Guggenheim in April.
Reached by phone, Lewis said he would not discuss the new project.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has long been close to Gehry, who worked for more than
five years with Lewis on a $30 million house in Cleveland before
the project was shelved several years ago. It was Gehry who
introduced Krens to Lewis, who became a trustee of the Guggenheim
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   If the new museum is built, people at the museum said, the
Guggenheim would probably close its six-year-old branch on the
corner of Broadway and Prince Street in SoHo. The outpost in SoHo
has been a financial drain on the institution, reportedly incurring
losses close to $40 million up to now.
</P>
<P>
   Under Krens, who has led the museum for 11 years, the Guggenheim
has embarked on a series of bold expansions. Besides Bilbao, which
has been hailed by critics as one of the most important works of
architecture in the 20th-century and has already generated $219
million of revenue as well as $35 million in new tax revenue for
the long-neglected industrial city on the Nervion River, it also
opened a 7,000-square-foot exhibition space in Berlin on the ground
floor of the Deutsche Bank on the Unter den Linden, near the
Brandenburg Gate.
</P>
<P>
   Besides these projects Krens has had ambitions for a Guggenheim
presence in cities like Paris and Salzburg. But neither of the
sites he had in mind for these cities has worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Krens announced that the Guggenheim was planning
to open three new museum sites in Venice. (The museum already
operates the Peggy Guggenheim Collection in the Plazzo Venier dei
Leoni on Venice's Grand Canal.) But progress on these projects is
moving slowly, Guggenheim officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Floating an unusual $54 million bond issue, Krens also directed
a sweeping $58 million renovation and expansion of the museum's
landmark Frank Lloyd Wright structure on Fifth Avenue at 89th
Street. And he opened the Guggenheim branch in SoHo in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the new branch in Manhattan have been so closely held
that they did not come up on Monday night at a small private dinner
of Guggenheim trustees and patrons to mark the election of Lewis as
foundation chairman, one participant said.
</P>
<P>
   Krens was said to have broached the plan last summer with Pataki
at the East Hampton home of Ronald O. Perelman, chairman of Revlon
and the former president of the Guggenheim. Perelman would not
discuss it, said a spokesman, Jim Conroy.
</P>
<P>
   The state's economic development arm, the Empire State
Development Corp., has not been advised of any plans, said a
spokesman for its chairman, Charles A. Gargano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2159EST &QL; 
