<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREETING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Ho, Ho, Ho, Holiday Greetings Go High Tech  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Holiday greetings have come a long way since 1843, when Londoner
Sir Henry Cole got fed up with writing annual letters to friends
and relatives and commissioned an illustrator to design what would
be the first Christmas card.
</P>
<P>
   Today, anyone with a PC and an Internet connection can send a
colorful, card, complete with animation and sound, anywhere in the
world in a matter of minutes by using e-mail. And inexpensive
software lets you create professional-looking cards from scratch,
complete with personal photos, and print them out in elegant color.
</P>
<P>
   For those who conduct most of their business and much of their
personal correspondence via e-mail, electronic cards are becoming
acceptable alternatives to the traditional paper kind.
</P>
<P>
   They're certainly more convenient, since they require no
envelopes, stamps or trips to the post office. And in many cases,
they're absolutely free.
</P>
<P>
   Selections of e-cards you can personalize and send at no charge
can be found at a number of Web sites, including
 &LR; www.egreetings.com, &LR;   &LR; www.bluemountain.com, &LR;   &LR; www.e-cards.com &LR; 
and &LR;  www.giftrap.com. &LR;  Greeting card leader Hallmark
 &LR; (www.hallmark.com), &LR;  also offers some free e-cards, as does
 &LR; www.greeting-cards.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In general, free e-cards aren't as lavish as expensive cards
that you can buy in a store. Hallmark, however, is an exception,
boasting some beautiful free cards on its site.
</P>
<P>
   If you want really high quality e-cards _ many of which have
animation and sound _ you'll have to pay from $1 to $3 or more per
card. Hallmark has a great lineup of quality cards, as does its
chief rival in the greeting card business, American Greetings
( &LR; www.americangreetings.com, &LR;  or keyword ``greetings'' on America
Online).
</P>
<P>
   When you send an electronic greeting, in most cases the card
itself stays on the site where it was created. An Internet link is
e-mailed to the recipient, who can use the link to view the card.
Cards also can usually be downloaded and printed.
</P>
<P>
   E-cards do have some drawbacks, the biggest of which is that not
everyone has e-mail. And among those who do, there are still many
traditionalists who like to send cards through the mail and hang
cards they receive over the fireplace so everyone can see how many
friends they have.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't fancy the idea of e-cards, consider software that
can take the trouble out of holiday greetings.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hallmark and American Greetings are in this part of the
business as well, with the Hallmark Connections Greetings 99 from
Microsoft ($29.95) and American Greetings CreataCard Gold from
Mindscape ($49).
</P>
<P>
   Other leading programs include Print Shop Signature Greetings
from Broderbund ($19.95) and Print Artist Cards Plus from Sierra
($29.95).
</P>
<P>
   All of the programs give you a wide selection of predesigned
cards that you can personalize, as well as letting you create cards
from scratch. You can add photos or graphics to your cards, and
print them on a decent color inkjet printer at a quality that
rivals store-bought cards.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most of the programs let you e-mail cards directly
from your computer using your own Internet account. That gives you
the advantage of using an e-card Web site, without the cost for
sending a really good card.
</P>
<P>
   The Print Shop and American Greetings programs are the easiest
to use, and the most well-thought-out of the ones listed here.
Their interfaces are simple and direct, and they guide you
logically through the process of selecting, customizing or creating
a card.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft program is, as you might expect, rather
Windows-like. That means there are lots of dialog boxes and option
menus, which add up to too much complexity for what should be an
uncomplicated task.
</P>
<P>
   Least user-friendly of the bunch is Sierra's Print Artist
program. It utilizes a tool bar with 28 little icons and works like
a desktop publishing program, giving you options for stretching,
aligning and coloring photos and graphical images.
</P>
<P>
   That's way too much for all but the most ambitious computer
fanatic. For the rest of us, it's just a turn-off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
