<HEADER>
A8004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BISHOPS-ABORTION-400&AMP;     11-18 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-ABORTION-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS TAKE BOLDER STAND IN BATTLE AGAINST ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:: Mass., Md.)   (af)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's Roman Catholic bishops declared
Wednesday that they have a pastoral duty to speak out to persuade
public officials who support abortion rights, and Catholic
officials in particular, to undergo ``a change of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishops' statement, which describes abortion, euthanasia and
physician-assisted suicide as fundamental threats to the health of
civil society, is addressed to all Catholics, urging them to
register their opposition to those issues by speaking out and
voting.
</P>
<P>
   It mentions priests, religious teachers and parents, but the
statement devotes far more of its attention to what it says are the
moral responsibilities of political leaders, especially Catholic
leaders, to work against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, the statement represents an unusually bold stance
for the bishops to take with politicians of their own faith in a
nation where Catholic politicians like President Kennedy once felt
impelled to declare that they would not take their political
positions directly from church authorities.
</P>
<P>
   It also suggests at least the possibility of a greater political
role for the bishops as the nation heads into the 2000 presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s the question of what a Catholic politician was
obligated to do on this issue was the focus of a public debate
between Cardinal John O'Connor, archbishop of New York, and former
Gov. Mario Cuomo, who said he personally opposed abortion but was
obligated by law to uphold the right to it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the statement _ adopted by a vote of 217-30 at the
semi-annual meeting of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops
_ is a nuanced document, which underwent a number of revisions
during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It declares, for example, that opposition to abortion and
euthanasia ``does not excuse indifference'' to issues of poverty
and violence, but it also says that ``being `right' '' on other
social issues never excuses ``a wrong choice'' on abortion and
euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tough language, the statement seeks no
ecclesiastical sanctions against officials who do not follow church
teachings on abortion or the other issues, a point emphasized
repeatedly by leading prelates in interviews after the vote. But it
does urge the bishops to speak out to politicians, particularly on
the issue of abortion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``As chief teachers in the church,'' the bishops state, ``we
must therefore explain, persuade, correct and admonish those in
leadership positions who contradict the Gospel of life through
their actions and policies.'' The statement, titled, ``Living the
Gospel of Life: A Challenge to American Catholics,'' also says that
``no appeal to policy, procedure, majority will or pluralism ever
excuses a public official from defending life to the greatest
extent possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal William Keeler, archbishop of Baltimore, said the
document was intended to promote a ``theology of persuasion'' and
was also intended to generate a reflection by all Catholics on the
church's teaching against abortion and euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   Although individual prelates, like O'Connor, and groups of
bishops have spoken out in support of anti-abortion legislation and
occasionally criticized politicians who support abortion rights,
never has the bishops' conference declared its members to have an
obligation as teachers of the faith to speak directly to Catholic
politicians on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also contains a stern pastoral warning by the
bishops to Catholic elected officials about the spiritual dangers
of continuing on a course at odds with church teachings against
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge those Catholic officials,'' the statement says, ``who
choose to depart from Church teaching on the inviolability of human
life in their public life to consider the consequences for their
own spiritual well-being, as well as the scandal they risk by
leading others into serious sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Bernard Law, archbishop of Boston and chairman of the
bishops' Pro-Life Committee, which wrote the 26-page statement,
said, ``I think what is new is this is the first time the bishops
as a body have addressed the issue in this way.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal said the statement, which was in the works for two
years, was released after the 1998 congressional elections so it
would not be seen as linked to that election.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the document originated in the bishops' frustration at
the failure of a national effort to ban a late-term abortion
procedure called by its opponents partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But some bishops voiced reservations about how the document
would be be applied by members of the conference and perceived by a
wider public. One prelate said the statement might trigger an
``anti-Catholic'' backlash if people thought the bishops were
attempting to dictate public policy to legislators.
</P>
<P>
   That the bishops will take differing tacks in how they act on
the document was indicated in what some of them said after the
vote. In a news conference, for example, Law said that three
Massachusetts politicians, all Catholics _ democratic Sens. Edward
M. Kennedy and John Kerry, and Republican Gov. Argeo Paul Cellucci
_ were wrong in their support for a legal right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's press secretary, Eileen Hoffer, said in response that
the governor ``respectfully disagrees with the cardinal on the
matter of a woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``The governor respects the teachings of the
church but feels that the matter of choice is a private matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry did not respond immediately to being singled out by Law.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Kennedy said that he had ``great respect for
Cardinal Law and the Catholic conference but he continues to
support a woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy has spoken out in the past, suggesting that leaders of
the Catholic Church were wrong to expect public officials of any
faith to advocate a ban on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1984, Kennedy, in an address entitled ``Faith and
Freedom,'' defended the positions of Cuomo and Geraldine Ferraro,
the democratic candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo and Ms. Ferraro both are Catholics and both were involved
in a debate at the time with O'Connor over the moral obligations of
Catholic candidates and officeholders. O'Connor contended then, as
the bishops did Wednesday, that Catholics as public officials have
an obligation to act on the moral teachings of the church.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops' statement also condemns the use of violence or the
threat of violence as a means of promoting ``the cause of life,''
which some bishops said they appreciated in light of the fatal
shooting last month of a Buffalo, N.Y., doctor who provided
abortions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
