<SLUG> BC-COMDEXDIARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wheeling and Dealing at Comdex   By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Las Vegas &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's 8 a.m. at the Luxor Hotel and Casino, a glass and steel
pyramid whose excesses might embarrass even a pharaoh. A few slot
machines ring out, but not too many people have started gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pyramid Cafe just off the gaming floor, Martin Sacks sits
at the head of a table of a dozen staffers from International
Microcomputer Software Inc., or IMSI, a $63 million Novato company
that makes a variety of software packages mainly for business users
and designers.
</P>
<P>
   As IMSI's chief executive, Sacks wants a rundown on how Comdex
is treating his company, which paid half a million dollars _ for
booth rental and equipment and staff per diems _ to be there:
What's the reaction to IMSI's products? Who have the executives had
meetings with? Who will they meet with today?
</P>
<P>
   While others gripe about the Comdex noise and clutter, Sacks
relishes the show's throbbing energy. ``Comdex is awesome,'' he
says at the breakfast table, ``because it's the one opportunity to
see where you are. You're talking to customers. You're seeing the
competition. You live in the cocoon of your office, and this is a
good slap-across-the-face reality check.''
</P>
<P>
   A day with Sacks, from sunup to well past sundown, reveals the
pulse that makes Comdex a trade show too big to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Even as companies scale back their presence at the show, they
still send representatives. With an entire industry gathering in
one place, Comdex spawns deals that are consummated for weeks and
months to come.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 8:45 &LR;   &UR; a.m. &LR;  Sacks has wolfed down half a grapefruit and a bowl of
corn flakes, and he hops in a cab to get to Las Vegas Convention
Center for the start of his second day at the show.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks, 38, a tan and athletic South African, is on a mission at
this particular Comdex. IMSI faltered in the past two quarters
after seven years of nonstop growth. Last week, the company laid
off 20 people _ the second such layoff this year _ as it moves to
delivering its software over the Internet and invests more than $1
million in new equipment to manage that business.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks isn't gambling in the casinos, but he's betting that the
Web holds the key to future growth, and he plans to scour the show
looking for partnerships that fit with IMSI's new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Internet use has reached critical mass, Sacks says. ``It's time
for us to make the leap.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9:35 a.m &LR; . Sacks jumps out of his cab two blocks from the Las
Vegas Convention Center, where traffic is at a standstill. He walks
briskly toward the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin, slow down!'' calls public relations manager Patricia
Roche, struggling to keep up with her long-legged boss.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks can't stop. ``This is Comdex, guys,'' he calls
good-naturedly over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He spends a moment inside studying a map of the show floor, and
he's off. It's still a quiet time on the floor, as only exhibitors
are allowed in. He heads straight for the Microsoft Partner
Pavilion, checking out other software companies' displays.
</P>
<P>
   Still moving, he pauses at Symantec's booth. ``I check the
karma, see what they're pushing, what they're not pushing,'' he
says. Symantec just bought an IMSI competitor, so he sizes up how
well the new offerings are displayed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10:05 a.m. &LR;  He crosses the hall and leads an Oklahoma-style
land rush into another wing of the show. He pops in on different
booths, looking for friends, striking up partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most interesting stuff is with the smaller companies,'' he
says. ``If IBM or Toshiba do something, you hear about it. With the
smaller companies, you have to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 minutes, he's ready to go. He takes out his mobile
phone and calls a van he's hired for the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, I missed a meeting, and I figure it cost us
$60,000,'' he says. ``We didn't do the deal. Since then, we have a
driver at our disposal.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10:35 a.m. &LR;  The van pulls up at the Sands Hotel, which has two
floors of Comdex booths. IMSI's booth is on the second floor,
staffed by upbeat workers in matching white shirts promoting the
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The IMSI booth is pushing two products: a Web site,
 &LR; www.arttoday.com, &LR;  that the company acquired just last month, and
a software product, MasterClips Image Server, featuring more than 1
million pieces of clip art.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks heads straight into a meeting with representatives of a
foreign government's military operation, who have bought an IMSI
application for computer-assisted design.
</P>
<P>
   He then chats up the Australians at the booth next door, asking,
``Is there any way we can work together?'' They listen to his
pitch, and in a common trade show ritual, they exchange business
cards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 11:35 a.m. &LR;  Back at his own booth, Sacks schmoozes with Jeff
Bianco, president of GraphicCorp, a Los Angeles company that
provides many of the clip art images. Reflecting the challenge of
IMSI's new Internet business model, the two men kick around ideas
of new ways to pay for and distribute the artwork.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1:05 p.m. &LR;  In one of the booth's makeshift conference rooms,
Sacks huddles with Gordon Doran, a Scottish executive with the
Walnut Creek office of LightWork Design, which is selling 3-D
images to IMSI for resale. They discuss the final stages of a
product announcement due for release by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Every conversation is carried at a higher-than-normal volume,
because of the constant crowd noise that fills the room.
</P>
<P>
   As he leaves, Doran voices a common Comdex sentiment: ``This is
the show from hell. This is unbelievable, this place.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1:30 p.m. &LR;  IMSI sent out for sandwiches, and Sacks is about to
eat his _ and give a reporter a PowerPoint presentation _ when
longtime IMSI Vice President Marty Shapiro pokes his head in.
``Someone from Corbis is here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Bill Gates' company,'' Sacks says. ``I'd better talk to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacks gets to eat eventually. One reason he doesn't pass up any
opportunity to meet or talk, he says, is cost: For a five-day show,
at 10 hours a day, the money IMSI spent on its Comdex presence
works out to $10,000 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3 p.m. &LR;  Sacks heads into a meeting with men in suits, somewhat
of an anomaly at the trade show. The meeting is confidential and
lasts a long time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5:30 p.m. &LR;  Sacks prowls the show floor and ultimately hooks up
with a friend, the president of another small software company, and
they talk in a quiet spot near a food court.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6:30 p.m. &LR;  Finally leaving the hall, the IMSI workers happily
walk past a taxi line where people will wait an estimated 90
minutes. Instead, the IMSI van arrives, and a dozen people squeeze
in for the ride back to the Luxor.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks stays in the van, though, and heads to the Mirage casino,
where he's having a dinner that's part business and part social.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 11:30 p.m. &LR;  Sacks is tired, but he's changed into jeans and is
ready for one final adventure: the Leonid meteor shower.
</P>
<P>
   The ballyhooed storm is peaking Tuesday night. Sounds good to
Sacks, who has fond memories of watching Halley's comet from the
cockpit of a 747.
</P>
<P>
   He takes a ride to a spot about 30 miles west of the city, far
enough so the bright lights don't interfere with the stargazing.
</P>
<P>
   The desert is cold at night, and he leans on the warm hood of
the car. The sky is filled with stars, but his small party sees
only a handful of meteors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2 a.m. &LR;  Sacks checks back in to his room at the Luxor. He's
tired, but already thinking about the next day. In less than six
hours, he'll convene another breakfast staff meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
