r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-SFCHRON &LR;      11-18 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Netscape May Land AOL Deal   By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
America Online and Netscape Communications reportedly are in talks
to integrate Netscape's Web browser into AOL's online service
instead of or in addition to Microsoft's browser.
</P>
<P>
   The potential deal, reported in yesterday's Wall Street Journal,
could severely undercut Microsoft's leverage in the Internet
market. Quoting anonymous sources, the newspaper speculated that as
part of the deal, AOL might buy an equity stake in Netscape and
pick up a board seat with the Mountain View company.
</P>
<P>
   AOL currently gives its 14 million subscribers access to the Web
through Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser under an exclusive
contract that expires January 1.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL, based in Dulles, Va., may see Microsoft as a growing
competitor. Microsoft is attempting to turn its faltering MSN from
an Internet service provider into an all-in-one ``portal'' site
that would rival AOL for content, Web access and electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Another reason AOL may want to distance itself from Microsoft
is the U.S. Justice Department's antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which claims Microsoft improperly leveraged its
dominance in operating systems to make strides in the Internet
market, has pitted the software giant against AOL and Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Senior Vice President David Colburn has testified that AOL
chose Microsoft's Internet Explorer as its Web browser because
Microsoft promised to promote AOL on its Windows operating system.
Microsoft claims it won the deal solely on technical merit.
</P>
<P>
   Still another theory: AOL may be courting Netscape to squeeze
better contract terms out of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   An AOL-Netscape deal ``would be a big win for Netscape,'' said
analyst Jim Balderston of Zona Research in Redwood City. ``If they
land the AOL deal, it could change the perception that Netscape is
dead in the water and re-establish it as a vibrant player in the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL and Netscape officials had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good relationship with AOL and feel confident the
software we offer them provides distinct and unique advantages to
AOL customers,'' said a Microsoft spokeswoman who didn't want her
name used. ``Besides that, we have no comment on rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of an AOL-Netscape deal come hard on the heels of a rare
legal drubbing for Microsoft. A federal judge in San Jose on
Tuesday ruled that Microsoft must alter Windows 98 and other
products to comply with Sun Microsystem's version of the Java
programming language.
</P>
<P>
   AOL shares, which split yesterday, climbed $8.38 to $83.75.
Netscape stock jumped $10 to $39.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
