<SLUG> BC-GOP-HOUSE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP Election Day loses cost Boehner high-ranking House post
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Festering anger among House Republicans over
Election Day losses apparently cost U.S. Rep. John Boehner his job
in party leadership at the same time two higher-ranking members
were returned to power.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the first day of the GOP's three-day
organizational conference, Boehner of West Chester was replaced as
conference chairman by a hot, young political star, Rep. J.C. Watts
of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, who becomes fourth in command in the House as Conference
Chairman, is the GOP's first black House leader. He defeated
Boehner 121 to 93 in a secret-ballot vote.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner issued a statement Wednesday evening, but declined to
talk with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race began as a contest between allies, and ended as a
contest between allies,'' the statement said. ``J.C. Watts is a
tremendous spokesman for the vision, values and ideas we share as
Republicans, and his presence in the leadership will be a
tremendous boost for our cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference chairman runs party meetings and also manages a
$1.1 million budget that is used for a wide variety of
communication operations that includes preparing internal party
documents such as talking points as well as mass-appeal messages
for the public. The job comes with a staff of two dozen, a suite of
offices, and a much-prized office in the Capitol Building.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner held the job since Republicans took control of Congress
in 1994, but the alliances he developed during years of
cross-country fund-raising for Republican congressmen failed to
protect him from the anti-leadership fervor that drove House
Speaker Newt Gingrich to resign within days of the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote held before the Boehner-Watts race, Republicans
elected U.S. Rep. Bob Livingston of Louisiana to succeed Gingrich
as Speaker. But in a twist, Republicans re-elected a pair of Texans
in the second and third place leadership slots.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Richard Armey defeated two challengers, and
Majority Whip Tom DeLay was unopposed. Armey faced the most
impassioned critics of any of the GOP leaders and needed three
ballots to draw the 113 votes required to claim victory.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's survival, however, diminished Boehner's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's head had to roll,'' said U.S. Rep. Mark Foley of
Florida, who had campaigned for Boehner.
</P>
<P>
   One of Boehner's close friends in the party, U.S. Rep. David L.
Hobson of Springfield, said he spoke with Boehner Tuesday night and
Boehner knew he'd be more vulnerable to defeat if Armey won. But
Boehner still encouraged him to vote for Armey, Hobson said.
</P>
<P>
   For Boehner, the opposition primarily was intangible. Most
members said there was no specific objection to the job Boehner has
done, unlike Armey whom one congressman called ``a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble was a deep-seated desire among disappointed
Republicans to punish the leadership team that let Democrats gain
five seats in the House in a year when Democrats were damaged by a
presidential scandal. Coupled with that was the allure of electing
an energetic new face to the leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   ``John had the misfortune of facing a very talented guy,'' said
U.S. Rep. Jerry Lewis of California, a Watts supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he decided to run for Conference Chairman, Watts,
41, had been pegged as a future leader in the party. A former
University of Oklahoma football star whose up-by-his-bootstraps
success story embodies the Republican ideal, Watts was a featured
speaker at the 1996 Republican National Convention, and the
following year gave the Republican response to President Clinton's
State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking Boehner's job, he promised to bring in outside
consultants to help hone the Republican message, and pledged to
arrange meetings with subcommittee chairmen to better integrate
policy development with the communications arm of the party.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to save Boehner's job had a decidedly Buckeye flavor,
with U.S. Rep. John Kasich of Westerville calling members of the
Budget Committee that he runs, U.S. Rep. Rob Portman of Cincinnati
also making calls, and Hobson delivering the closing nomination
speech for Boehner just before the vote Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big loss for the conference and a big loss for
Ohio,'' Hobson said. ``This doesn't reflect on the job he did, it's
just that people wanted a change and John's race was the last race
where they felt they could make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing a member of the senior leadership team cost the state
some prestige, and carries some practical changes as well. The Ohio
delegation loses an assured ear among the top decision makers in
the House, and loses a powerful vote in the party's Steering
Committee, which determines committee chairmen assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hobson's own future in the House is a matter for some
speculation. Hobson's close friendship wi
</P>
</TEXT>
