<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOB-LIVINGSTON19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House Speaker-elect Livingston looks back on his home district
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Communities in U.S. House Speaker-elect Bob
Livingston's district tend to boast about two things: how close
they are to New Orleans and how far they are from New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fitting dichotomy for a conservative district that feeds
off a town that doesn't do much conservatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although only a short drive from the famous attractions of New
Orleans, Slidell has a character and appeal all of its own,'' the
city says in its promotional material. ``Thanks to Lake
Pontchartrain, which separates these two cities, Slidell has
escaped the problems which trouble many large metropolises without
being isolated from the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It's code, says political scientist Wayne Parent of Louisiana
State University, for a district that's easy to pigeonhole: largely
suburban, middle to upper-middle class, white and Protestant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is made up of people who fled New Orleans,'' Parent said.
``They were fleeing what they perceived as crime and all the things
that go along with the big city. Early on I'm sure there were some
racial white-flight things going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who sent Livingston to Washington tend to be folks
who view government as something that is inflicted. People like
Buddy Comeaux, whose furniture and appliance store is down the
block from the high-rise that houses Livingston's district office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government intrusion is the most important thing,'' Comeaux
said. ``It's terrible. I'm expecting somebody from the government
to come in and say that I haven't granted credit equally to my
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Comeaux, fresh from a government probe of an ex-employee's
sexual harassment claim, said he sees government nonsense every day
when he drives down Veterans Highway, a suburban strip a tad past
its prime.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is drive down any street in America today,
and you will see way too many disability parking spaces,'' he
groused. ``You see all kind of foolishness like that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few doors down, baseball card store owner Frank Lucito, a
registered Democrat who votes Republican, also wants government to
spend less and stay off his back. And Lucito, proving that one
man's pork is another man's sirloin, is hopeful that Livingston can
bring home the bacon. ``If it's like the things I've seen on
television, we may get something here, a contract here or there for
the state or whatever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal, Comeaux says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that we have to grovel to get our own money back,
but I guess we do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers show that Livingston's district is the state's
wealthiest and most educated. ``And it's probably the whitest
district in Louisiana,'' said David Duke, the former KKK official
elected in September as chairman of the GOP in St. Tammany Parish,
which is in Livingston's district.
</P>
<P>
   St. Tammany is the only Louisiana parish in which registered
Republicans outnumber registered Democrats. At party headquarters
in Covington, Duke continues to espouse the
right-of-right-of-right-of-center politics that has made him a
political lightning rod.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana and national GOP, Duke believes, ``have joined
with the enemies of our heritage who are transforming our great
nation into a Third World reservation of the New World Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, who scores well on conservative group's vote
ratings, is part of the problem, according to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a strong conservative, and we wish him well. But for us
he leaves some things to be desired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Duke again has a title that entitles him to be
quoted irks local Republicans like Ron Besson, chairman of the West
Jefferson Parish Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think David Duke represents the people of St.
Tammany,'' he said. ``To the average voter there, I think David
Duke is an embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but Duke claims enough popularity around here to have had
a direct role in allowing Livingston to be in position to ascend to
the nation's most powerful job elected on a less-than-statewide
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Livingston thought about joining the legion of
legislators-turned-lobbyists. Duke, who has run well in this part
of Louisiana in his gubernatorial and U.S. Senate elections,
planned to seek Livingston's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been the odds-on favorite,'' Duke said. He added
that then-Speaker Newt Gingrich, fearing a Duke victory, encouraged
Livingston to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Even the opposition found an upside to Livingston's ascension.
Louisiana Democratic Chairman Ben Jeffers said that if the House
speaker has to be a Republican, he might as well be a Louisianan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City of New Orleans and the State of Louisiana should
benefit from having the speaker of the House of Representatives
here as a resident,'' Jeffers said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
