A8014 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOV-BROTHERS-BUSH19-C     11-18 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOV-BROTHERS-BUSH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governors Bush greet the press
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The governors Bush, brothers-in-lawmaking whose
realm includes one-eighth of all Americans, went directly to center
stage Wednesday as the nation's 31 GOP governors gathered here.
</P>
<P>
   For George W., it marked the first toe in the national political
water since a landslide re-election solidified his position as the
top contender for the GOP presidential nomination in 2000 _ though
he insists he remains undecided about his ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help it,'' Bush said of his front-runner status at a
joint news conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Governors Association meeting also gave Jeb Bush,
Florida's governor-elect, a national press audience to announce his
endorsement of his big brother _ if George W. decides a
presidential race is where he wants to take his wife and teen-age
twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he gets through that and decides to do it, I've encouraged
him to,'' Jeb said. ``I think he would be an awesome candidate. I'm
going to vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor steadfastly stuck with his
I-haven't-made-up-my-mind line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next question,'' Jeb chimed in, trying unsuccessfully at one
point to bail his brother out of a line of questions about a White
House race.
</P>
<P>
   Are you confident you can do the job, a Washington reporter
asked George W.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me well enough to know the answer to that is yes,''
he replied.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor continued to insist that his decision will be
based on what's best for his family and how a presidential race _
and a national office _ would affect his wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   In a roundabout way, he recently got a small taste. It came
during a public event Saturday in the Texas House chamber as his
father, former President George Bush, was subjected to screaming
protesters blaming him for suffering in Iraq. The governor, Texas
first lady Laura Bush and their daughter, Jenna, were with the
former president when he spoke at the Texas Book Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that doesn't bother me,'' the Texas governor said when
asked if moments like that give him pause about a presidential
race. ``I think it really disturbed a lot of people in the
audience. I think my daughter was a little shaken by it all, but it
doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he later told daughter Jenna, a 10th-grader, that
``those kinds of things happen when you've got somebody you love in
the public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how his daughter would react if protesters blamed him for
thousands of deaths, Bush said, ``I don't think she'd like it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like I didn't like it in 1992 when my dad was running for
president. As some of you may remember, back in those days I
developed a rather thin-skinned reputation. I don't think it was
deserved, but, nevertheless, I developed it because sometimes I
defended my dad's honor in the political process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Bush-Bush press conference was moved to a larger
room to accommodate the large press throng, certifying that the
brothers are big news in The Big Easy. It's a result of a
combination of things: who their dad is; what George W. might
become; and the fact that, as a Reform Party member, the
governor-elect formerly known as ``The Body,'' Minnesota's Jesse
Ventura, is not here.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to New Orleans, Bush of Texas knew what he and
Jeb would face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody is going to try to elbow their way in to
have a picture with me and my brother,'' he said last week. ``Kind
of the debut of the two elected governors with the same last name
from the same family. I think people are going to want to see Jeb
and I interact with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   They interacted Wednesday as politicians and brothers. ``I've
been telling him what to do since _ how old are you?'' George W.
said to Jeb.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot younger than you,'' replied Jeb, seven years younger.
</P>
<P>
   As George W. droned on with his theory that it's difficult for
Congress to set a national agenda, Jeb wedged in with: ``Can I
disagree on one thing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just make sure it is a minor point,'' cautioned big brother.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeb got the last word when George W. said, ``I didn't grow
up wanting to be president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did,'' said Jeb.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
