<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF DEION IS COWBOYS' MVP, FORGET A LONG PLAYOFF RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All hail to Deion. Notice please, the feet-kissing frenzy that
has engulfed a segment of local star-on-the-helmet-gazers. And from
that same group also comes word that the coronation committee has
met and voted. Deion is hereby proclaimed ``King of Football.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Best-Dressed in North Texas?
</P>
<P>
   The Deion Fan Club squealed with its loudest glee after that
wild one the other day in Tempe, Ariz., a game that in their
gooey-eyed estimation proved a point.
</P>
<P>
   See there, they told us, The Blessed One is player of the year
in the NFL, Defensive player of the year in the NFL, and most
certainly, the one player the Cowboys could not do without.
</P>
<P>
   Something about what Jake, the Arizona Snake, did with Deion in
the game, and then what Jake accomplished when Deion was on the
sidelines, sitting it out with a toe ache.
</P>
<P>
   But in telling that Tempe story, why not tell it all? And the
truth shall be along shortly. But first ...
</P>
<P>
   Through 10 games this season, Sanders is the Cowboys' MVP. Don't
take my word for it. Just ask him. He'll tell you.
</P>
<P>
   From here, however, project the Cowboys through the final six
regular-season games, which would be the end of December. At that
time, if Deion is still being touted as the Cowboys' most valuable,
then it's a team that will be making a quick January exit. There
will be no playoff payoff.
</P>
<P>
   When January arrives, the real MVP had better come from an
assortment of Emmitt, Larry Allen, Troy, Michael, even Ernie Mills
or Billy Davis, which is not an outrageous theory any longer. Or
put Chan Gailey in there as MVP.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs are going to be about offensive production. This is
a Cowboys' season that has been about offensive production all
along, except Troy Aikman's absence for five games caused a long
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Deion is going to be a big factor in the playoffs, but success
won't hinge on a cornerback-punt returner. It's going to come down
to how many holes the line opens for Emmitt Smith, and what he does
with those holes. Or how many weapons besides Michael Irvin does
Aikman have in the passing game, which at the moment is several.
</P>
<P>
   Winning in the weak NFL of today is about offense. Winning in
Tempe last Sunday was about five red-zone touchdowns in five trips.
</P>
<P>
   Denver is not the league's best team because of its defense _
does Denver even have a defense? In a shaky NFC, Minnesota is tops
among a jello group, but name one Vikings defensive starter. See
there. If those two teams meet in the Super Bowl, the final score
will be 60-50, and I'm guessing Denver will have the six-oh.
</P>
<P>
   The second-best thing about the game in Tempe was the Cowboys
showed their first sign of offensive dominance under Gailey. The
best thing was the W, although the finish came with a heart attack
attached.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yeah, about that Deion factor, or nonfactor, last
Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   When Jake Plummer put on a Joe Montana show, bringing back the
Cardinals from deficits of 28-0 and 35-14, the We-Love-Deion club
says The Snake prospered because Sanders was on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   No, he wasn't. Not the whole time. Deion was back at his corner
when Plummer whipped the Cardinals on a 70-yard scoring drive,
cutting the Dallas lead to 35-28. Deion was also out there when
Plummer rallied the Cardinals from their own 22 to the Dallas 5,
and did so in exactly 43 seconds. You do remember what happened
from there.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Sanders was limping, but as usual, Plummer didn't throw in
his direction anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith was bounced around in the Plummer passing spree, but
Kevin was also playing injured. Since the Cowboys were desperate at
cornerback, Smith gamely stayed in despite a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   When Sanders was out, Charlie Williams tried to hang in as his
replacement. Williams was toasted more than once, but he's not even
a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Plummer had the same second-half success against
Sanders-Smith as he did against Smith-Williams. Jake threw for 314
yards in the second half, and 124 of it came in the final four
minutes when you-know-who had returned.
</P>
<P>
   For one game anyway, it was Jake Plummer who looked like the
``King of Football.'' Deion is what he is _ the MVP thus far of the
Cowboys. For the future good of the team, that needs an offensive
change, starting Sunday vs. Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, let the slobbering continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
