<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSU'S COOPER STEELS HIMSELF FOR MICHIGAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now a short break from the buildup to the USC-UCLA game.
</P>
<P>
   There are actually some other rivalry games this week, and some
major eye-twitching by coaches worried about the devastating effect
a loss will have on, among other things, recruiting, booster
support and job security. And not necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Take Ohio State coach John Cooper. (Please.) He's 1-8-1 against
Michigan, having lost in 1990, 1993, 1995 and 1997 when a victory
would have earned a Rose Bowl berth, and in 1996 when a victory
would have brought a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Cooper's secretly pleased that the Buckeyes'
national-title hopes were dashed by Michigan State, because it
deprived Michigan of ruining his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get away from it,'' Cooper told reporters this week.
``You guys don't let me forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an old Cooper stand-by, to blame the media. But even he
admitted that his record against Michigan dogs him ``about 365 days
a year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, (the fans) have been pretty nice, I guess,'' Copper
added. ``There are negative comments... that people make, but
that's not going to change. Some people would not be pleased if we
won every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Down in the panhandle, the Florida-Florida State game has BCS
implications, with both teams ranked in the top five. The schools
fight each other in the talent-rich Sunshine state for recruits, so
this game means just about everything to both programs.
</P>
<P>
   Local legends Bobby Bowden and Steve Spurrier were both crying
the blues this week, but for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden's still trying to get over the loss of starting
quarterback Chris Weinke, and lamenting his team's 17-point
``victory'' over Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst I felt after a game since N.C. State,'' Bowden
said, referring to FSU's lone loss this season on Sept.12. ``It's
because we looked so futile on offense... with the biggest game of
the year coming up. We really have got to go back to square one
offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   And then you have the surly Spurrier, who couldn't resist
alluding to the Seminoles' penchant for knocking quarterbacks out
of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have mentioned in the past that (knocking out the
opponent's QB) is their goal,'' Spurrier said. ``I'm not going to
put words in their mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   You just did, coach.
</P>
<P>
   If Ohio State and Florida lose Saturday, get ready for plenty of
alibis.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson search begins: Last week, the New Orleans Times-Picayune
reported that Clemson athletic director Bobby Robinson spoke with
Cincinnati athletic director Bob Goin to get information about
Tulane coach Tommy Bowden. Goin was in the Florida State athletic
department when Bowden was on his father Bobby's staff at FSU.
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches being mentioned in connection with the Clemson job
are former head coach Danny Ford and Mississippi coach Tommy
Tuberville.
</P>
<P>
   We want a refund: A few weeks ago, Kansas State installed goal
posts made by Merchants Environmental Industries of Chicago. The
goal posts were guaranteed to be indestructible.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. While it took Wildcats fans more than 30 minutes to
finally snap off the crossbar and uprights after Saturday's
Nebraska game, the goal posts in one end zone failed to live up to
the Chicago company's claim.
</P>
<P>
   The company has sent a replacement to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Gator Bowl bound: Georgia Tech can secure a Gator Bowl berth
with a victory over Wake Forest as the ACC's second team. Who will
they play? The Jacksonville, Fla.-based bowl is hoping for another
Notre Dame loss, which would mean the Irish would be out of the BCS
picture and in the Gator Bowl's to play Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Aloha Buffs? The Aloha Bowl is hoping it can pair Colorado
against USC in its Dec.25 contest but doesn't like the idea of
waiting until the Buffaloes play Nebraska on Neb.27 or the Dec.5
Big 12 title game to offer an invitation, which gives fans less
time for travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   Family man: Colorado was not a bowl team last season for the
first time since 1988. After Saturday's 37-8 win over Iowa State,
coach Rick Neuheisel said, ``I spent Christmas Day at home last
season and it stunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the back of the room, he saw his wife, Susan, and
their three boys. Neuheisel quickly audibled: ``Sorry, honey. I
didn't mean it quite like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Subliminal message: As Texas went its through its walk-through
Friday at Texas Tech, the Jones Stadium scoreboard kept flashing
the 1997 score _ Texas Tech 27, Texas 10 _ and a picture of Red
Raiders running back Ricky Williams. Tech won 42-35.
</P>
<P>
   Fast fact: Missouri has lost three games this season _ all to
opponents that, at the time, were in the Top 10 (Texas A&AMP;M, Ohio
State, Nebraska). Not that it was any surprise, because Missouri
has a 34-game losing streak to Top 10 teams dating to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Fast fact, the sequel: Miami has blocked 30 punts in 42 games
under coach Butch Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Finally: Texas running back Ricky Williams needs 62 yards in the
Longhorns' season finale against Texas A&AMP;M on Nov.27 to pass Tony
Dorsett as Division I-A's all-time leading rusher. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
