<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS ENDORSE LIVINGSTON, EJECT OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct name of the Cannon Office Building, update
throughout and incorporate addend)  
(htv) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After two weeks of bloodletting over their
leadership, House Republicans sent a mixed message Wednesday about
the image they want to project in the coming 106th Congress: they
kept some leaders and threw out others, producing a team with a
strong conservative cast that includes the party's first black
leader.
</P>
<P>
   In what was a foregone conclusion, the party unanimously
endorsed Rep. Robert Livingston of Louisiana as its nominee for
speaker. He will replace Newt Gingrich, who resigned under pressure
after the party lost seats in the Nov. 3 midterm elections.
Livingston is to be elected speaker by the whole House on Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans kept Dick Armey as majority leader after an intense
four-way struggle and Tom DeLay as majority whip. Both men, who are
strong conservatives, are from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But they ejected John Boehner of Ohio as Republican Conference
chairman, replacing him with J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the first
black Republican in a leadership role in modern times. And they
repudiated John Linder of Georgia as chairman of the National
Republican Congressional Committee, replacing him with Thomas Davis
of Virginia. Both Boehner and Linder bore some blame for the
party's midterm stumble, in which it lost five House seats.
</P>
<P>
   The party put two women in its lowest leadership positions.
</P>
<P>
   The voting by secret ballot Wednesday took place behind the
closed doors of the ornate caucus room in the Cannon Office
Building. Emerging midway through the day, Livingston stood with
some of his new team, including Armey, with whom he and DeLay have
had frosty relations.
</P>
<P>
   Setting a tone of low-key conciliation, Livingston pronounced
his party ``united,'' adding: ``We're all going to have to work
together,'' a daunting task that will entail ``reaching out to
Democrats,'' given the party's narrow six-vote majority and the
strength of its ideological wings on the left and on the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the American people to know that they are going to get
good, clean, honest, efficient government from us,'' Livingston
added. ``We muffed our message a little bit in the last
elections,'' he conceded. ``We may have slipped, but we haven't
fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's priorities, he and others made clear, would be to
save Social Security and enact tax cuts before the elections in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats sitting on the sidelines gloated that the Republicans
had failed to make a clean sweep of their leadership and put a
fresh face on their party. ``On the issues, there is no difference
between Newt Gingrich and the new Republican leaders,'' said Roy
Romer, general chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The most intense action of the day came during the protracted
four-way race for majority leader, the No. 2 in command. Armey won
a majority of votes only after a third ballot, and seemed somewhat
the bloodier for it. A relieved Armey described the ordeal as a
``merry chase.''
</P>
<P>
   But his closest challenger, Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma, an
ardent conservative and charter member of the revolutionary class
of 1994, brooded after the battle: ``Steve Largent has been too
slow and too small his whole life, and this is just one more
occasion,'' he said, a reference to criticism early in his football
career, which was rocky in the beginning but culminated in his
induction into the Hall of Fame. ``But I will tell you that I'm not
accustomed to losing, and I don't like to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Also spurned for majority leader was Rep. Jennifer Dunn of
Washington, the first woman to aim for a top leadership position,
who declared that even her attempt to run for office was a
milestone.
</P>
<P>
   And a fledgling effort to draft Dennis Hastert of Illinois as
majority leader fell flat. In the first round of balloting, Armey
won 100 votes, Largent 58, Ms. Dunn 45 and Hastert 18. With no one
winning a clear majority of 112, the person coming in last,
Hastert, was dropped and a second ballot was held. On the second,
Armey won 99, Largent 73 and Ms. Dunn 49. On the third, Armey won
127 and Largent 95.
</P>
<P>
   Once Hastert and Ms. Dunn were eliminated, the moderates had no
one to support. They have never liked Armey, but some said
Wednesday that they found Largent too inflexible and inexperienced
and had no choice but to support Armey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There clearly was an anti-Armey sentiment in the conference,
and people felt it was time to get rid of him,'' said one moderate
who did not want to be identified. ``But in the end, the moderates
just couldn't go with Largent. It was more like going with the old
devil we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all moderates agreed. ``He'd look you in the eye and act as
though he was listening to you, then do the opposite,'' said one,
reflecting a ``complete puzzlement'' as to how Armey got elected.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio of New York, who ran Armey's campaign, said the
Texan won in part because there was a change above him, a change
below him and people wanted a steady hand at the tiller.
</P>
<P>
   After retaining Armey, the party ousted two other incumbents
from its hierarchy. In what some described as a burst of
indignation, Republicans rejected Boehner as conference chairman.
The chairman is responsible for presenting the party's message to
the public and communicating leadership decisions and party policy.
</P>
<P>
   Watts blamed the leaders directly for the party's losses in the
midterm elections. ``I'm a public relations major,'' he said. ``And
one of the things I found out in public relations is it's very hard
to P.R. a bad product. And we had a very bad product as Republicans
coming down the stretch. And whether it was true or not, the
perception was the presidential problems and Monica Lewinsky became
our agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But this criticism was mild compared with what Boehner said on
the Sunday after the Nov. 3 elections. He went on television and
placed the blame for Republican losses foursquare at the feet of
Gingrich. ``The problems, in terms of managing the House, were
mostly in the speaker's office,'' Boehner said on the ABC News
program ``This Week.'' And, he said, the resignation of Gingrich
represented ``enough change.''
</P>
<P>
   But after voting Wednesday to retain Armey, some Republicans
said they were desperate to present some change in leadership and
took it out on Boehner. Watts beat him, 121-93.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for chairman of the campaign committee, Davis beat
Linder 130 to 77. Davis is a fiscal conservative but one of the few
prominent Republicans who supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I was chosen this year tells you a lot about how
we've listened to voters,'' Davis told reporters. ``Two years ago,
I wouldn't have been electable in this conference.''
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the leadership ladder, Tillie Fowler of Florida
was elected vice chairwoman of the Republican Conference and
Deborah Pryce was retained, unchallenged, as secretary of the
conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
