<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-CATHOLICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC LEADERS DECRY RACISM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's Catholic bishops deplored racism
Wednesday as a sinful scar on religious and secular life, urging
local dioceses help end it within the church and across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In their fall session, the bishops also adopted a statement
relating church teaching to personal and public behavior. Titled
``Living the Gospel of Life: A Challenge to American Catholics,''
it condemns abortion, physician-assisted suicide, capital
punishment and other attacks ``on innocent human life.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was adopted after extended discussion, including
calls from a liberal bishop that a document ``on life'' should also
specifically oppose ``weapons of mass destruction.'' The statement
was not adopted until a sentence was added condemning violence
against abortion clinics and physicians who do abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic elected officials are the statement's most direct
target. It advises them to espouse church teaching in speaking and
voting on related legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call on them to reflect on the grave contradiction of
assuming public roles and presenting themselves as credible
Catholics when their actions on fundamental issues of human life
are not in agreement with church teaching,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Joseph A. Fiorenza of Houston said most Catholic leaders
in his region conform to the statement's call for a ``consistent
ethic'' of human life. The church views and teaches that life is
``a continuum that applies from conception through birth to natural
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishops have charted a centrist course this week, balancing
competing voices and interests in the conference and in the 60
million-member American church. Tuesday, they elected Fiorenza, a
moderate and a longtime advocate of racial justice, as their
president. Bishop Wilton D. Gregory of Belleville, Ill., was
elected conference vice president, becoming the first black to hold
that post. Their elections sounded a conciliatory note in sharp
contrast to the social discord portrayed in the discussion on
racism.
</P>
<P>
   Racism is not an individual problem, the bishops said in an
informal report presented by Bishop Curtis Guillory, auxiliary
bishop to African-Americans in the Diocese of Galveston-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Dismantling racist attitudes in a democracy where citizens once
purchased blacks as slaves, forced Indians onto reservations and
denied equal education to Hispanic immigrant children calls for
systematic solutions, the bishops said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race is the number one socially defining issue in the United
States,'' the report stated. Despite progress, churches remain
segregated, stereotypes are taken as accurate and racism breeds
violence, Guillory said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racial incidents still remind us it is a scar on society and
the church,'' the bishop said. Earlier this year in Jasper, Texas,
49-year-old African-American James Byrd Jr. was beaten, chained to
the back of a pickup and dragged to his death. A few weeks ago in
Virginia, a black man was burned and beheaded. There are 140
Internet sites pushing racial hatred, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's three bishops and Los Angeles Cardinal Roger Mahony
linked the statement on ``the sanctity and dignity of human life''
to the racism discussion. ``The racism discussion comes in on the
dignity aspect,'' Guillory said. Fellow Bishop James A. Tamayo,
Houston diocesan auxiliary to Hispanics, added that respecting that
dignity means removing barriers created by ethnicity, gender or
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The national bishops published a statement in 1979 calling
ending racism. Three years ago Houston's three bishops issued a
pastoral letter, ``Many Members, One Body,'' urging parishes cease
allowing ethnic differences to divide people.
</P>
<P>
   The national church and the Houston diocese are increasingly
diverse and multicultural. Among ethnic groups there are an
estimated 3.4 million African-American Catholics, 22 million
Hispanics, 2 million Asians and 500,000 Native Americans. Among the
Houston diocese's 1.2 million Catholics, a figure including those
not registered with a parish, there are 500,000 Hispanics, 80,000
blacks, 73,000 Asians, and a small number of Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Houston bishops issued their letter, workshops have
been held in about 50 percent of the diocese's 160 parishes to
teach reconciliation, Guillory said. Those workshops explore
stereotypes, build trust and link ethnically diverse people.
Parishes have exchanged pastors for Sunday worship across racial
lines. Some churches ``twin'' with others, he said, so that a
mostly white suburban parish may operate an outreach in a Hispanic
inner-city one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
