<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILGRIM-ENTERGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA COMPANY MAKES BARGAIN DEAL FOR PILGRIM N-PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: La.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEC Energy has agreed to transfer its Pilgrim nuclear power
plant in Plymouth to a Louisiana utility in a complex
cash-and-financing transaction, according to people familiar with
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to be announced Thursday, will make New
Orleans-based Entergy Corp. one of the largest new operators aiming
to sell generation services as New England states open power
markets to competition.
</P>
<P>
   While hardly lucrative for BEC, the parent of Boston Edison Co.,
the agreement will clear the way for the local utility to pursue
plans to expand its electricity marketing-and-distribution
businesses, or to sell itself outright.
</P>
<P>
   BEC has already sold its nonnuclear generating assets as part of
the state's electricity deregulation plan passed last year. Under
the legislation, designed to lower electricity prices,
investor-owned utilities are selling their plants to outside
companies like Entergy, which will compete to provide homes and
businesses with power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; People familiar with the matter said that under an agreement
signed by executives of both companies Wednesday night, BEC would
transfer Pilgrim to Entergy in return for $80 million to $90
million in cash, depending on audits of the assets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Entergy will receive as much as $266 million in new
BEC borrowings to cover the costs of cleaning up the plant when it
ceases operations, scheduled for 2012.
</P>
<P>
   The deal doesn't come close to covering the $650 million book
value of &UR;  &LR; Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   But with deregulation plans removing nuclear rate guarantees,
analysts had grown concerned whether BEC could operate Pilgrim
profitably at all, let alone sell it for anywhere close to its face
value.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with similar difficulties, other nuclear plant operators
in the region have failed to find any buyers and have closed
facilities outright, such as the Maine Yankee reactor in Wiscasset,
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   But people familiar with the thinking of BEC executives said the
company was pleased to avoid that outcome and to strike a deal that
will keep the 670-megawatt Pilgrim facility &UR;  &LR; in operation. Its
continued power supply will also keep prices stable in the region,
an important factor as BEC shifts to become a distribution and
marketing organization.
</P>
<P>
   While other utilities are scrambling after gas-fired power
plants, Entergy is pursuing a contrarian strategy to take advantage
of its relatively strong record as a nuclear operator. Entergy's
five other reactors have never been on the federal government's
``watch list'' of the worst-run nuclear facilities. In 1997 the
plants operated at 90 percent of their total capacity, compared
with an industry average of 73 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim's staff of about 675 will become Entergy employees, and
people familiar with the deal said Entergy doesn't anticipate
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   However, these people said Entergy won't recognize contracts
covering about half of Pilgrim's work force and instead plans to
begin negotiations with their union, the Utility Workers Union of
America, to reach new agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The union had previously filed a complaint to the National Labor
Relations Board against BEC, charging the company hadn't bargained
in good faith over the terms of the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   As previously reported, Entergy was bidding for Pilgrim against
a competing offer from AmerGen Energy Co., a joint venture of Peco
Energy Co. in Philadelphia and British Energy PLC.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the discussions said the key to Entergy's bid
was its treatment of the cleanup costs at Pilgrim, which are
similar to those facing all nuclear plants licensed to run for 40
years after their start date.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim's license expires in 14 years, at which time BEC
estimates it will cost $620 million to clean up radioactive
materials there.
</P>
<P>
   But Entergy executives believe they can achieve the same results
for just $585 million by coordinating efforts with cleanups at the
five other nuclear reactors they own, in Louisiana, Mississippi,
and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Charges collected from ratepayers to cover the cleanup now stand
at just $180 million, and won't top $200 million before the sale of
Pilgrim is expect to close in early 1999. To make up the
difference, BEC will also provide Entergy with up to $266
million &UR;  &LR; that the Boston utility plans to borrow, said people
familiar with the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   That will increase the size of the cleanup fund to $466 million.
Entergy then plans to earn enough by investing that money to cover
the remaining costs of the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   BEC also expects to receive credits from a nuclear-insurance
fund in coming years that it values at $31 million, said people
familiar with the matter. After the sale BEC will have about 2,250
employees, far fewer than its headcount of 4,800 in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy closed Wednesday at 29 3/16, down 5/16. BEC was off 1/16
at 40 15/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
