<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG THEATER COMPANY MOVES TO A NEW STAGE: BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for light rewrite and addition of 4 grafs at end; in 10th
graf, corrects Drabinsky's age from 48 to 49)  (mk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Livent Inc., the Broadway theater company, filed for bankruptcy
protection Wednesday, less than six months after Michael Ovitz,
once widely considered the most powerful person in Hollywood, took
over the company.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ovitz, former president of Walt Disney Co.,
and his new management team filed a lawsuit against the company's
founders, the impresario Garth Drabinsky and his partner, Myron
Gottlieb.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses the two men of having misled Ovitz, who
invested $20 million in Livent, by hiding the fact that the company
was losing millions of dollars on its expensive productions of
musicals like ``Ragtime,'' ``Showboat'' and ``Phantom of the
Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also contends that Drabinsky and Gottlieb gave
themselves more than $7.5 million in ``kickbacks'' by funneling
company money to another corporation in Toronto that Gottlieb
owned.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz and Livent's new managers maintain that Drabinsky and
Gottlieb had ordered the company's accountants to manipulate the
financial books so that more than $60 million of extravagant
spending on advertising, salaries for the shows' huge casts and
elaborate sets were hidden and never cut into the profits the
company reported in its financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit further contends that in an effort to keep the
matter covered up, Drabinsky and Gottlieb tried to gain the
cooperation of Livent's senior financial executive, Gordon
Eckstein, by offering him greatly increased compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The company's severe financial straits are already taking a toll
on the many productions that the company now has in major cities in
North America. On Tuesday night, the cast of one of its productions
of ``Ragtime,'' which has been touring the United States and is now
playing in Minneapolis, was told that the rest of the tour,
including stops of several weeks that had been scheduled for
Seattle and Boston, had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the allegations, Drabinsky and Gottlieb, who were
suspended from their jobs in August and formally dismissed
Wednesday by the company's board of directors, said in a statement
that Ovitz and Roy Furman, Livent's new chief executive and a
former Wall Street investment banker, were trying to blame them for
their own poor business decisions and miscalculations.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb said they would vigorously defend
themselves against the allegations. In addition, Drabinsky filed
his own lawsuit against Ovitz, Furman and other Livent executives
charging that they had acted together ``in a conspiracy to injure
him.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time that Drabinsky, 49, a man known for his
artistic vision, abundant confidence and high-spending ways, has
built a sprawling entertainment company, only to be dismissed
because of accounting issues.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Drabinsky, a former entertainment lawyer, founded
Cineplex Odeon in Toronto and built it into an 1,800-screen chain
across the United States and Canada. But in 1989, MCA, one of the
company's big investors, dismissed him amid questions of his
accounting practices. Critics had accused the company of
understating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb said in their statement Wednesday: ``This
is a sad day for live theater and a sad day for Livent
shareholders. New management is facing the consequences of their
actions of recent months. Rather than growing the company, they
have wasted resources on accountants and lawyers in a protracted
campaign to inflict injury to our reputations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of nurturing the creative potential of the company,
they have diminished it. Instead of focusing on growing the company
and building shareholder value, they have relentlessly focused on
discrediting us.''
</P>
<P>
   They added that Ovitz and Livent had filed the suit against them
on the same day that the company filed for protection from
creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy act ``to
deflect attention from their own ill-conceived decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy filing Wednesday in Manhattan will give the
company many months to reorganize its finances while it continues
to produce shows. With the protection from creditors that comes
with filing for a reorganization under Chapter 11, Livent will not
have to make scheduled payments of interest and principal on almost
$200 million of debt until it can renegotiate the terms with its
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   The debt, which was mostly used to pay for the construction of
new theaters in New York; Chicago; Vancouver, British Columbia, and
Toronto, is now consuming most of Livent's cash, leaving the
company unable to keep up with its daily expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The company is scrambling to arrange some new short-term
financing so that it can meet its payroll and other day-to-day
costs.
</P>
<P>
   After months of delay, the company also released corrected
financial statements Wednesday for 1996, 1997 and the first two
quarters of 1998. They show that Livent's entire equity has been
eaten up by its bills. That means that the company's debts are now
greater than the value of its theaters and other assets.
</P>
<P>
   The corrected statements were the first financial details that
Livent has released since Aug. 10, when it said it had discovered
serious accounting irregularities and was suspending Drabinsky and
Gottlieb while it investigated the scope of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lack of financial information, securities
regulators in the United States and Canada suspended trading in
Livent's stock. It is not clear whether, with the release of the
corrected financial statements, the regulators will now let the
stock trade again.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the civil suits and countersuits, Livent is under
investigation by securities regulators in both the United States
and Canada. The Royal Canadian Mounted Police have begun a criminal
investigation into the company's activities.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of their own investigation, Ovitz and his managers
in their suit detailed a trail of unusual business transactions
that they say were handled by Drabinsky, a lawyer, and Gottlieb, an
accountant. With the transactions and secret side deals attached to
some Livent contracts, Ovitz's lawsuit says, the two men were able
to enrich themselves by millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the lawsuit says, the two men told the
company's accountants to hide the millions of dollars the company
was losing on shows either by shifting the costs to other accounts
so that they never affected the bottom line or by excluding the
amounts entirely from the company's official set of books.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky had directed the company's accountants to keep a
separate set of ledgers from the company's official books so that
he could track Livent's ``real'' expenses, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says that Drabinsky and Gottlieb were able to make
improper payments of more than $7.5 million to themselves by asking
an engineering company working on a theater construction project to
inflate the bills it sent to Livent. The engineering company, the
suit says, would then pass the amounts to Drabinsky, Gottlieb or to
a Toronto company, King Commodity Services Ltd., which is
controlled by Gottlieb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
