<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT DEAL WITH PATRIOTS `POSSIBLE,' VP KRAFT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  BOSTON _ Amid reports that an agreement in principle could be
imminent between the Patriots and the state of Connecticut, the
prospect arose that an era could be ending for the Boston area's
haunted football franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president Jonathan Kraft said Wednsday night,
``There's no deal as we talk right now.'' Asked if there might be
Thursday, he said, ``It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the deal told the Globe Wednsday night that the
new facility, which would be located in downtown Hartford, would
include more than $100,000 earmarked toward improving the road at
the junction of Interstates 84 and 91 to allow better access.
</P>
<P>
   Tailgating and guaranteed exiting from the stadium within one
hour would be added enticements for current season ticket-holders
to make the 2 1/2-hour drive 10 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sources also say current season ticket-holders would be
accommodated while the team explores a season ticket base with
residents of the Greater Hartford area. It was also learned that
there would be no personal seat licenses sold and the revenue
stream would be expected to come from ticket sales, luxury boxes,
and premium-type seating.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Revolution, also owned by the Krafts, would
remain in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   While it had been thought that the Patriots might stay at their
current practice facility in Foxborough and play their games in
Hartford, that would not be the case because a new practice
facility would be built near Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Despite strong media reports, the league remained cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no announcement,'' said NFL spokesman Greg
Aiello. ``There are two issues here. First of all, any move would
require a three-quarters vote of the other NFL owners, and
secondly, a move by the Patriots to another New England site would
be viewed as positive by the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The league also confirmed that nothing could stop the city of
Boston from building a stadium and luring an expansion franchise if
the Patriots moved. But that, too, would require a three-quarters
vote, and team owner Bob Kraft, a powerful member of the expansion
committee, probably would not allow such a thing to happen.
</P>
<P>
   There are no territorial rules in the NFL; therefore, there
could be 10 teams in Chicago or eight in Boston as long as the
league owners approved by a three-quarters vote.
</P>
<P>
   In a July interview with the Globe, commissioner Paul Tagliabue
spoke positively of a possible move to Hartford by the Patriots if
they could not resolve their longstanding problems regarding
building a facility in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 20, 1993, Tagliabue said Foxboro Stadium was ``an
unacceptable venue for the long-term future of the Patriots.'' And
about a month later, the state of Connecticut was trying to float
$252.1 million in bonds to fund a new stadium for the Patriots.
Five years later, the plan has resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest relocation report regarding the Patriots, who
at various times in the past have been rumored to be headed for
Memphis, Nashville, Birmingham, Ala., and, most recently, St. Louis
and Providence.
</P>
<P>
   During their nomadic formative years, the Patriots at various
times called Boston University's Nickerson Field, Fenway Park, and
Harvard Stadium home before settling in to
Schaefer/Sullivan/Foxboro Stadium in 1971. But those were mere
neighborhood shifts compared to this proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Some close to Kraft can't imagine him moving the franchise out
of the Boston area, considering that he was born and raised in
Brookline, has been a season ticket-holder, and prevented it from
moving to St. Louis by purchasing it from James Busch Orthwein for
almost $200 million in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Kraft has attempted to find a permanent home for the
Patriots in a facility that would meet NFL standards for the new
millennium. Time and time again, he has been rebuffed, starting in
South Boston, where residents protested the prospect of disrupting
their neighborhood as much as they did a proposed 70,000-seat
waterfront stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's frustration with House Speaker Thomas Finneran has led
to this situation. In reality, the difference between the
Finneran/House infrastructure proposal and the Kraft/Senate
proposal is about $15 million in the public assistance the owner
would receive to build a new stadium. But so far, nobody in
Massachusetts is budging.
</P>
<P>
   So as early as Thursday, Kraft might have to sign an agreement
in principle with the state of Connecticut or lose out on a viable
option.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' staff spent most of their time Wednesday
scrambling for answers regarding the media reports.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the players seemed caught in an awkward spot.
</P>
<P>
   From a purely personal viewpoint, Drew Bledsoe would be quite
upset if the Patriots moved to Hartford because he and his family
are building a home in Medfield, where they wanted to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Now that move may be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult for myself and for our players who have
settled into this area,'' said Bledsoe. ``When you sign to play for
a team, you hope it's the only team you ever play for so you can
put down roots and stay in one place. From that standpoint, it's
tough, but I understand in my conversations with Bob what he's had
to go through to get a stadium built in this area, and if this is
going to happen, then you can't blame him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said it would be a sad day if the Patriots moved,
because of the fan base they've built in southeastern Massachusetts
and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends who come in here to play against us and they're
amazed at the fan support we receive here,'' said the quarterback.
``We have a great following of fans who really support us and give
us quite a home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``our facility is the laughingstock of the
league. It's not a major league facility. And it's amazing to me
and to a lot of people that we can't get $1 of public money
allocated toward a new home for our team. It's tough to see other
cities allocate money for stadiums when here in New England, we
have an owner who is willing to build the stadium himself with help
from the state for the infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said a perfect example of the rabid fan support was that
the Atlanta Falcons couldn't sell out their own facility, the
Georgia Dome, but when they came to Foxboro Stadium this month, the
place was jammed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the frustrating thing,'' said Bledsoe. ``I think teams
in other areas of the country would love to have the support we do.
That part is already in place. But if we have to move, we have to
move if it means the franchise can flourish with a new facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Browne, the NFL's senior vice president of communications
and government affairs, said Wednsday night that the league would
be willing to comment only when there is an agreement. Browne did
not seem concerned about the Patriots moving out of a major TV
market like Boston, nor did Tagliabue appear concerned about that
in July.
</P>
<P>
   While the Kraft years have probably been the best in Patriots
history in terms of on-field success, they also have been
turbulent. There was the acrimonious departure of coach Bill
Parcells to the New York Jets after the 1997 Super Bowl. More
recently, high-profile players such as Dave Meggett and Ben Coates
have faced sexual assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kraft bought the team, he's been trying to get out of
Foxboro Stadium. At first, he hoped the Patriots would be part of a
Boston megaplex deal. When that fell through, Kraft was assured by
then-Governor William Weld that he would be accommodated for having
prevented the franchise from moving out of the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
