<HEADLINE>
THE THREE WHO WILL QUERY STARR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-REPUBS) 
(Eds: bylines at end of articles) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Schippers
</P>
<P>
   David Schippers, who will lead the questioning of Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr for the Republicans in Thursday's Judiciary
Committee session, has made much of being a lifelong Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the former prosecutor was harsh in his comments
about the president last month when he outlined the Republicans'
case to the committee. He said there was ``substantial and
credible'' evidence that Clinton lied under oath and that the
nation's judicial system might have been harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If lying under oath is tolerated and, when exposed, is not
visited with immediate and substantial adverse consequences, the
integrity of this country's entire judicial process is fatally
compromised, and that process will inevitably collapse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, 68, made his mark as the chief federal prosecutor in
Chicago. He has been in private practice since 1967 and is a
longtime friend of Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who is the chairman of
the committee.
</P>
<P>
   _ NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Abbe David Lowell
</P>
<P>
   Abbe David Lowell, the chief lawyer for the Democrats on the
Judiciary Committee, is a Washington insider with a firm grasp of
Congress and politics. He built his reputation defending Democratic
politicians like former House Speaker Jim Wright, who resigned in
1989 amid accusations of ethical violations.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, 46, was born in New York City, reared in Westbury, on
Long Island, and received his undergraduate and law degrees from
Columbia University. He is a partner in the Washington law firm of
Brand, Lowell &AMP; Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   In an argument to the Judiciary Committee last month, he held
that the president's having an improper sexual relationship and
lying about was not an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an attempt to organize his staff to spread
misinformation about the progress of the war in Vietnam,'' he said.
``Or about a break-in of the Democratic headquarters at the
Watergate, or even about how funds from arms sales in Iran were
diverted to aid the contras in Nicaragua.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, the president's chief private counsel, has waited
a long time for an opportunity to confront Starr. Kendall, 54, has
represented Clinton in Whitewater matters for nearly five years but
has rarely appeared in public to defend the president. His chief
weapons have been legal briefs and scathing correspondence to the
Office of Independent Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall endured months of criticism for his handling of the
Monica Lewinsky investigation, urging the president to remain
largely silent while mounting a vigorous counterattack against
Starr. But Clinton remains in office and Starr must now defend his
investigation before Congress and a special master appointed by the
judge supervising the Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall made his reputation in death-penalty and First Amendment
cases after compiling a gilded resume: Rhodes Scholar, Yale Law
School, a Supreme Court clerkship. But it will be as the
president's lawyer in only the third presidential impeachment
inquiry in U.S. history that Kendall will long be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN M. BRODER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
