<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-MUSIC-ALBUMS19     11-18 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-MUSIC-ALBUMS19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Whitney we know and love
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``My Love Is Your Love''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney Houston. Arista. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Whitney's new effort is mostly like old times.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Whitney Like You've Never Heard Her Before,''
proclaims the sticker on Whitney Houston's first studio album in
eight years. Such false advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The singer-actress's return to recording something other than a
soundtrack is actually, often pleasantly, familiar. Pulling from
the gospel roots she displayed breathtakingly well on the
``Preacher's Wife'' soundtrack, Houston joins Lauryn Hill on a
cover version of Stevie Wonder's ``I Was Made to Love (Him),'' a
reworking that's as memorable as her take on ``I Will Always Love
You'' on ``The Bodyguard'' soundtrack. And ``It's Not Right But
It's Okay'' is as sister-girly as all that was ``Waiting to
Exhale,'' the movie and soundtrack featuring Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are such by-the-numbers big ballads as ``I Learned
From the Best,'' ``You'll Never Stand Alone'' and ``When You
Believe,'' her overemoted duet with fellow pop diva Mariah Carey.
You have to expect those exercises in riffs and octaves from a
Grammy favorite who made her rendition of ``The Star-Spangled
Banner'' a top seller. The surprise comes when the often
predictable rapper Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott, as guest
producer, tastefully reveals Houston as a sensual being on ``Oh
Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   And leave it to Houston's most familiar collaborator, producer
Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds, along with Daryl Simmons, to draw out
one of her most stirring vocal performances on ``Until You Come
Back.'' Proof that Whitney like we've heard her before is really
quite fine.
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   Success expands Jewel's sweet tooth
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirit''
</P>
<P>
   Jewel. Atlantic. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: I'm OK, you're OK, Jewel's OK. OK?
</P>
<P>
   A pure product of what Joni Mitchell called ``the star-making
machinery,'' 24-year-old vocalist Jewel Kilcher has enjoyed a
peculiarly accelerated career. When her first album, ``Pieces of
You,'' was released in 1995, she flaunted a vagabond image and
talked about sleeping in her car. As her new album arrives, she's a
multi-platinum Lilith Fair alumna who is already the subject of a
best-selling parody (a spoof of her poetry collection, ``A Night
Without Armor'').
</P>
<P>
   No wonder she dedicates ``Spirit'' to her mother, who is also
her manager. But such success exaggerates Jewel's gifts as a
songwriter. She is unbearably trite in the winsome way that only
introspective college-age guitar strummers can be. ``If I could
tell this world one thing,'' she sings in an ever-soothing voice,
``it would be that we're all OK.'' Next stop: ``Oprah.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the advantage of stardom is that you get to spend
lots of money on your records, and ``Spirit'' is resplendent in a
subdued folk-pop-country way. The seductive studio craft lends a
sense of significance to what is ultimately pretty innocuous.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Human Being''
</P>
<P>
   Seal. Warner Bros. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   No one else projects romantic anguish amid such lush upholstery
as Seal. Like Sade, another celebrated English mononym, he has
become a global soul-soother by evoking not ache's desolation but
its multi-hued cornucopia of emotion, its limitless swank. ``Human
Being,'' the latest album from the Grammy Awards mainstay, feels
like the aural equivalent of a ride in a late-model BMW through
some deserted city of the heart. The production is immaculate, the
music a slick urban noir soundtrack that ripples with hints of
techno and trip-hop, its somber themes offset by an insistent
rhythmic pulse and Seal's soaring appeals. Class act that he is,
the vocalist connects even without the luxe trappings. ``Lost My
Faith,'' which briefly matches Seal with an acoustic guitar, boasts
the old-school folkie grit of Otis Redding _ grit with a little
extra polish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Salesman and Bernadette''
</P>
<P>
   Vic Chesnutt. Capricorn. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Partnered with the protean Nashville ensemble Lambchop, whose
horn arrangements sprawl from English Beat-style exuberance to the
ragged dirge of a New Orleans funeral procession, Athens-based Vic
Chesnutt finds the coherence lacking in his previous effort (1996's
major-label debut, ``About to Choke''). As ever, he populates his
songs with a gallery of amusingly observed characters (``a man
dripping with Vitalis,'' a ``self-ordained Faustian'') and treads a
shaky tightrope between the absurd and the profound (he's a Flying
Wallenda of deceptively casual couplets). What's new is how the
songwriter happens onto a surprising Al Green falsetto in the
beseeching ``Maiden'' and, in the brooding, Dylanesque folk-rock of
``Parade,'' truly paints a masterpiece, evoking an existential
sadness that may be one of the forgotten qualifiers of great art.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   TECHNO
</P>
<P>
   ``OK''
</P>
<P>
   Talvin Singh. Island. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his techno-ambient brethren, Talvin Singh is a
cross-pollinator. But this British-born producer brings something
new to the usual mixture of sample loops, synth washes and digital
rhythms: the hot mystique of his Indian heritage. Overlain with
such traditional Indian instruments as sitars and tablas, Singh's
debut album can transport you from the heart of Bombay to a London
rave in a split second. Sometimes, the instruments switch purposes.
The gorgeous keyboard layers of ``Traveller'' bring to mind a
sunrise over the Ganges, while the rat-a-tat tablas on ``Eclipse''
are every bit as intense as the most cutting-edge drum-and-bass
track.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
