<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING OF LIVE HIV VACCINE ON TERMINALLY ILL PROPOSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Researchers from the University of Massachusetts and
Harvard University are proposing to inject live but genetically
disabled AIDS virus into a group of terminally ill cancer patients
to see if the approach might be feasible as a vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, discussed publicly at an AIDS meeting Wednesday, is
the latest wrinkle in a long-running debate about human tests of a
live-virus vaccine against the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that some AIDS researchers and funding
agencies have been cool to the proposal, Dr. John Sullivan, an AIDS
researcher at UMass Medical School in Worcester, said he and
Harvard researcher Ronald S. DesRosiers are scheduled to discuss
ethical issues raised by the proposal with officials at the US Food
and Drug Administration next month.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said testing potentially hazardous drugs or vaccines in
terminally ill patients has ample precedent, adding that cancer
specialists have told him the proposal is feasible and some
patients would volunteer. He spoke at a meeting on ``AIDS at the
Millennium'' sponsored by Lemuel Shattuck Hospital and the
Massachusetts Medical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said in an interview that he got the idea of testing a
live-virus vaccine in cancer patients when his father was dying of
cancer four years ago. His father would have volunteered, Sullivan
said.
</P>
<P>
   An international group of physicians who specialize in AIDS care
have offered themselves as guinea pigs for a live-virus HIV
vaccine, but others have criticized their proposal as premature.
</P>
<P>
   Live but ``attenuated'' viruses, which have been modified to
make them harmless while stimulating a protective immune response,
have been highly effective against other diseases. But skeptics say
AIDS is different because HIV inserts its genes into the immune
cells of people it infects, perhaps doing damage that could take
years to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People turn their backs and say this is a crazy idea,''
Sullivan said. ``I think some people have made up their minds that
this approach is not going to work, but I would call that
scientific hubris.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan argued that human trials of a live attenuated HIV
vaccine, as a genetically crippled virus is called, should proceed
in case other vaccine strategies fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wait 20 years before we start looking seriously at a
live attenuated AIDS vaccine in humans, it will be 40 years before
we could deploy it,'' Sullivan added.
</P>
<P>
   It would take so long to develop a live HIV vaccine, Sullivan
and others said, because volunteers would have to be monitored for
years to make sure the disabled virus did not cause delayed immune
damage, which would be disastrous if such a vaccine were widely
deployed.
</P>
<P>
   One cause for concern comes from a Massachusetts patient of
Sullivan's and a handful of others in Australia who were
accidentally infected through blood transfusions by mutant strains
of HIV that were missing one gene, called ``nef.'' Though the
patients did not seem to suffer ill effects for years afterward,
recent studies have shown evidence of immune system damage.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of a live-virus vaccine point to evidence from
DesRosier's lab at the New England Regional Primate Center in
Southborough that an experimental live-virus vaccine protected
monkeys against infection by multiple strains of the natural simian
AIDS virus, called SIV.
</P>
<P>
   However, another Harvard researcher, Ruth Ruprecht, reported
last July that some monkeys sickened and died of immune-system
damage after getting a vaccine based on a live disabled SIV.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the AIDS virus he and DesRosiers propose to test
in cancer patients would lack four different genes, while earlier
live-virus vaccines lacked only one.
</P>
<P>
   Not all AIDS vaccine experts dismiss the proposal. ``We would
like to see safety work done on live attenuated HIV vaccines
because, if all other approaches fail, we believe we will have to
come back to a live attenuated vaccine, and the more data we have
the better,'' said Dr. Seth Berkley, president of the International
AIDS Vaccine Initiative in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
