<SLUG> BC-MA-HEALTH-PREMIUMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG COSTS BOOST HEALTH INSURANCE PREMIUMS FOR EMPLOYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts employers are facing the biggest
increases in health insurance premiums in almost five years as drug
costs skyrocket, America ages, and technology continues to crank
out better, costlier treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The rate hikes mirror a national trend of swelling health care
expenses that highlight the limits of managed care's promise to
contain costs.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, employers are reporting premiums will rise 4 percent to
15 percent for 1999, after several years of negligible or low
single-digit increases.
</P>
<P>
   Employees, who on average pay about 30 percent of the
overall &UR;  &LR; premium, will see their bills rise as employers, which
pick up the balance, pass along the higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever increases there are will be passed along to
everyone,'' said Kenneth E. Thorpe, professor of health policy at
Tulane University in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   While few observers believe there will be a return to the
spiraling costs of the late 1980s when average yearly premium
increases grew beyond 18 percent, many think the nation is entering
a new era of persistent health care inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Though not all 1999 contracts between employers and their
insurers are completed, the anecdotal evidence so far points to
some of the biggest increases in years.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid Corp. in Cambridge, whose 6,500 Massachusetts workers
saw no increases for the last two years, is experiencing a 5
percent jump in health care premiums for 1999. At Boston-based
Gillette Co., which has 5,510 employees in Massachusetts, premiums
are going up 4 percent to 8 percent in 1999, compared with a 4
percent increase in 1998 and a small reduction in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit, however, are smaller employers. Bull HN Information
Systems in Billerica, which has 500 employees in Massachusetts,
expects its premiums to spike 15 percent, more than double its 1998
increase. In 1997, premiums for Bull were flat compared with 1996
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a very large company, and our ability to influence
our rates is contained at best,'' said Cecile Wright, vice
president of human resources at Bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing increases anywhere from 5 percent to 13 percent,
or higher, and that's for large employers,'' said Susan Connolly, a
partner at William M. Mercer Inc., a benefits consulting firm in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, as managed care gained ascendancy as the
nation's dominant form of health insurance, costs took a dramatic
downward turn. Managed care insurers, while emphasizing preventive
care, eliminated redundant or unnecessary care, drove hospital
prices down, and slashed payments to physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Now, insurers have run out of places to cut, and costs are
starting to creep back up.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the nation, premiums are also surging anew. Oxford
Health Plans Inc. in Norwalk, Conn., this month said premiums for
employers its serves are expected to jump 9 percent on average.
Humana Inc. of Louisville, reported increases averaging 10 percent,
and Oakland, Calif.-based Kaiser Permanente, the nation's largest
HMO, said its 1999 rates would also rise substantially. Federal
employees, the largest single group of employees in the nation,
with over 9 million workers and dependents, are seeing a 12 percent
increase in the premium of their standard HMO policy in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Culprits behind the cost resurgence, according to the
Washington Business Group on Health, a research group funded by
large companies, include:
</P>
<P>
   --Rising pharmaceutical costs. Once a miniscule portion of
overall health care costs, drugs now take up more than 15 percent
of the average overall health care budget. That figure is rapidly
rising, thanks to a record number of new medications, many of which
are revolutionary but also expensive, such as Viagra, the
anti-impotence drug, and Prozac, an antidepressant. Thorpe of
Tulane estimates that about one-third of premium increases seen
next year is due to rising drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   --Advancing technology. Science continues to produce a dazzling
array of new technologies to treat everything from infertility to
brain tumors. As these treatments become standard, insurance
companies must pay for them, and pass along the cost in the form of
higher premiums.
</P>
<P>
   --Aging population. &UR;  &LR; As baby boomers enter their 40s and 50s,
the cost of their care grows. Medical expenditures for men 45 to 54
years old, for example, are 45 percent greater than for those
between 35 and 44, according to Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   --Insurance economics. Insurers have kept premiums low in the
past few years in bidding wars to win market share. But the
premiums have not kept up with medical inflation, and the result is
that 57 percent of health plans in America lost $768 million
combined in 1997, according to the Washington Business Group on
Health. Now the emphasis for HMOs is on profitability and higher
premiums. Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, for example, is expected to
increase premiums by an average of 6 percent to 8 percent in 1999,
after rate increases averaging just 2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   --Consumer demand. Gone are the days when patients passively
waited for their trusted doctors to issue orders. Patient
empowerment has turned people into savvy, aggressive consumers who
seek and demand the latest treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care's current inability to tame these forces point to a
new frontier for the industry, specialists say. Managed care, in
short, must live up to its name and manage care, not just cost.
That means devising more efficient and effective ways to treat and
manage costly illnesses such as heart disease, diabetes and asthma.
This will help bring costs down in the long run, health care
observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next phase of managed care has got to move from managing
cost to truly managing care,'' said Sally Coberly, director of
policy for the Washington Business Group. ``We need to treat people
in their totality, have processes in place to manage diseases.
That's where we can have a more lasting impact on costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, premiums are expected to continue their climb. This
year, however, a funny thing happened at the negotiating table _
employers didn't push back that hard, consultants said. One
possible reason: many expected even steeper increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are getting larger rates increases than they have in
the past, but they seemed to be accepting of that,'' said Steve
Sadowski of William M. Mercer, who has negotiated with HMOs on
behalf of employers for six years.
</P>
<P>
   At Polaroid, Bill Hubert, manager of benefits, is watching to
see if managed care can continue to deliver quality care without
letting prices get out of hand. ``Now we'll see how effective
managed care can be,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
