<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR PLANS TO TELL HOUSE PANEL OF PATTERN OF LIES BY CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth Starr plans to tell a
House Judiciary Committee hearing Thursday about repeated lies and
``misuse of presidential authority'' by President Clinton to cover
up his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In 58 pages of remarks prepared for the opening session of the
committee's impeachment inquiry, Starr accused Clinton of a
``pattern of obstruction of justice, false statements and misuse of
executive authority'' to undermine a federal grand jury
investigation and Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit against
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, the evidence suggests that the president repeatedly
used the machinery of government and the powers of his office to
conceal his relationship with Monica Lewinsky from the American
people, from the judicial process in the (Paula) Jones case and
from the grand jury,'' Starr says in the testimony delivered late
Wednesday to the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The White House issued a statement dismissing Starr's release as
a repeat of his earlier impeachment report ``in new wrapping
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr also is prepared to summarize his four-year criminal
investigation of the president and how prosecutors had drafted,
then decided against sending, a report to Congress a year ago
outlining possible impeachable offenses by Clinton stemming from
sworn testimony about his business dealings in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The report had detailed sworn testimony by Clinton that he knew
nothing about a fraudulent $300,000 loan from a federally backed
savings and loan run by David Hale, a former municipal judge in
Little Rock, Ark. Hale testified that Clinton urged him to make the
loan.
</P>
<P>
   In his prepared remarks, Starr says he and his deputies decided
against referring the incident to Congress after concluding ``it
would be inconsistent with the statutory standard because of the
difficulty of establishing the truth with a sufficient degree of
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said at the time ``there were still two outstanding
witnesses who might later corroborate _ or contradict'' the
allegations that Clinton lied about the loan. The witnesses are
former Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker, who was convicted in a related
case and sent to prison, and Clinton's former Whitewater business
partner Susan McDougal, who was jailed for contempt for refusing to
cooperate with Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was given the green light to go beyond the
Clinton-Lewinsky affair by committee Chairman Henry Hyde, who also
signaled a renewed interest among Republican committee members in
whether Clinton was involved in campaign fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hyde announced plans Wednesday to subpoena four
more witnesses, including Deputy White House Counsel Bruce Lindsey,
the president's closest confidant, and Robert S. Bennett, a private
lawyer who represented Clinton in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the panel will vote Thursday on whether to subpoena
Lindsey and Bennett, along with Daniel Gecker, attorney for
Kathleen Willey, and Democratic financier Nathan Landow, who had
contacts with Willey before she publicly accused Clinton of an
unwanted sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's announcement came hours after Clinton left on an economic
mission to Asia, which will keep him out of the country during the
first few days of televised hearings and debate by the deeply
divided Judiciary Committee. The hearings were set to begin at 10
a.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   The moves by Republicans to expand the investigation beyond the
Lewinsky affair _ and to limit Democrats' ability to challenge
Starr's investigation _ drew protests from committee Democrats and
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an impeachment in search of a crime,'' complained
James Jordan, spokesman for Democrats on the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters shortly before
the president departed that the Republicans appear to be on an
unconstitutional ``partisan adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart complained that Republicans are seeking to muzzle the
president's defenders while attempting to broaden their
investigation. ``They have rediscovered all of their old bad habits
and since they don't like where it's going they're going to try to
find something else,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who cautioned that he would tolerate no attacks on Starr,
said he has no plans to yield to Democratic complaints. ``The
Democrats want to stick to Monica Lewinsky. We want to look at
everything. That's the big difference,'' the Illinois Republican
told reporters after a strategy session with GOP colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Clinton's legal team, which is being allowed to
participate in Thursday's hearing, Hyde warned that no questions
would be allowed about controversies surrounding Starr's
investigation of the president, such as contacts with Jones'
lawyers and an inquiry into illegal leaks of grand jury
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Efforts to utilize these proceedings as a forum to inquire
about nongermane matters, such as investigations into the conduct
of the investigation, that are pending before other bodies, shall
not be permitted,'' Hyde wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hyde has written the Justice Department for a memo
that provides a detailed argument for appointing an independent
counsel to take over the criminal investigation of Democratic
fund-raising abuses. Attorney General Janet Reno previously refused
to provide the memo, written by former prosecutor Charles LaBella,
to congressional committees. Under threat of contempt, she allowed
key committee members to read the document.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who has been given two hours for his opening remarks,
plans to dispute claims by Clinton and many of his supporters that
his relationship with Lewinsky was a private affair and not the
proper subject for a special prosecutor to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating many of the 11 allegations that prompted the House to
launch the presidential impeachment investigation _ only the third
in the nation's history _ Starr said Clinton's behavior with the
former White House intern ``is not a private matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence ... suggests that the president ... misused his
authority and power as president and contravened his duty to
faithfully execute the laws,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also plans to draw parallels between the help Clinton and
his aides gave Lewinsky in her New York job search after learning
she was being subpoenaed in the Jones lawsuit and the financial aid
his supporters gave Webster Hubbell when he was under investigation
in the Whitewater case.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of a top presidential assistant, several wealthy
Democrats funneled $550,000 in consulting work to Hubbell after he
left his high-ranking post at the Justice Department. Hubbell, a
long-time friend of Clinton and former law partner of first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, has declined to cooperate with Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the $550,000 was given to Mr. Hubbell for little or no
work,'' Starr said. ``This rush of generosity obviously gives rise
to an inference that the money was essentially a gift. And if it
was a gift, why was it given? This money was given despite the fact
that Mr. Hubbell was under criminal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning that Jones' legal team wanted to question
Lewinsky, Clinton used White House aides and former U.N. Ambassador
Bill Richardson in an effort to find Lewinsky a job, Starr argued.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
