<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVENT SUED AS IT FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY PROTECTION
</P>
<P>
   Livent, the Broadway theater company, filed for bankruptcy
protection, just six months after the company was taken over by
Michael Ovitz, the former Hollywood talent agent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ovitz and his new management team filed a
lawsuit against the company's founders, Garth Drabinsky and Myron
Gottlieb, contending the two men fraudulently misled Ovitz into
investing in Livent by hiding the fact that the company was losing
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Livent's raising of the financial white flag underscores larger
questions about the future viability of a company that helped
define the outer reaches of theater extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL ECONOMY CONTRACTS BY 1.5 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Fanning widespread fears that Brazil is plunging into a
full-fledged recession, the government announced that the economy
contracted by 1.5 percent in the third quarter from the second
quarter and said that key indicators pointed toward an even more
pronounced slump over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS POST BROAD GAINS LATE
</P>
<P>
   Late-session surges drove stocks to broad gains as investors
more thoroughly digested the Federal Reserve's decision on Tuesday
to cut interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial average gained
54.83 points, to 9,041.11. The Nasdaq did even better, climbing
18.92 points, or just more than 1 percent, to 1,897.44. The S&AMP;P 500
rose 5.16 points, to 1,144.48.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina raised $1 billion in seven-year debt, extending a
bond-sale binge and proving it can still tap international markets.
</P>
<P>
   TIGHTER RULES SEEN FOR HEDGE FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. regulators tighten their scrutiny of hedge funds,
officials say they will likely require the often secretive funds to
reveal more about how much debt they use and the risks they take
with their money.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON'S STANCE ON CHEAP IMPORTS
</P>
<P>
   In the view of the Clinton administration, it is acceptable for
Russia and other countries to export their way to recovery as long
as those exports do not land here. Clinton is right to seek
protection from a deluge of temporarily cheap steel imports, but
there are good and bad ways to do that. So far the administration
has not chosen the best course of action.
</P>
<P>
   SALES FALL 4 PERCENT FOR GLAXO WELLCOME
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome, the world's second-largest drug maker, said that
its 1998 sales through Oct. 31 fell 4 percent, within market
forecasts, as increased sales of asthma drugs failed to offset
slowing growth for other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT UP 4.8 PERCENT FOR CAMPBELL SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup, which makes about 75 percent of the soup sold in
the United States, said that first-quarter profit rose 4.8 percent
because of cost cuts and higher-than-expected sales. Net income
rose to $264 million, or 58 cents a diluted share, matching
analysts' estimates. Campbell reduced spending, expanded overseas
and shed some businesses.
</P>
<P>
   SURGERY SET FOR CHIEF EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management said its chief executive, John Drury, was
scheduled to have a mass removed from his brain. But the company
said the operation was not life threatening and that Drury was
expected back at work within a week to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIED SIGNAL CASE IN LOWER COURT
</P>
<P>
   In an advance for Allied Signal, the company said a federal
appeals court had given jurisdiction over the company's attempt to
expand the board of AMP with its own directors back to a district
court judge, who is likely to lift a preliminary injunction he
imposed last month barring the board election.
</P>
</TEXT>
