<HEADER>
A8069 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-18 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THESE OLD WALLS COULD TALK ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Me and Gretz, we go way back. I was eight
days shy of my 10th birthday and Wayne Gretzky was not quite 19
when he first visited me. I remember it so well, this breeze of a
boy from Edmonton scoring a power-play goal with the Oilers down,
7-0, to break up goaltender Mario Lessard's shutout bid.
</P>
<P>
   He would collect two goals and an assist that night in the
Oilers' 9-3 loss. All told, I've seen 171 of his goals _ including
his most historic, on March 23, 1994 _ and 412 of his points. Only
Marcel Dionne was more prolific in my presence and he was around me
night in and night out for 12 years. Gretzky and I spent a ton of
time together between October of 1988 and February of 1996 but not
so much before or since.
</P>
<P>
   We had joy, we had fun, we had one Stanley Cup title run. But so
much for all of our seasons in the sun. The reality is, I'm getting
on in years and so is he. At 31, I'm absolutely ancient for a
sports facility. I'm so old, people think my columns are the work
of guys named Domitian and Vespasian.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, the crowned prince of puck, turns 38 in January. I'm
not suggesting there's a rocking chair calling his name but the
Kings' newest center, Olli Jokinen, was born the same year (1978)
Gretzky began his pro career with the Indianapolis Racers.
</P>
<P>
   Me and Gretz, we're both showing signs of wear, though I don't
mind admitting he has withstood the ravages of time a lot better
than I. It's no secret I'm well past my prime, or have you not
heard the Kings are leaving me next fall for a comely crib on the
other side of town? Talk about stealing from the cradle; my
replacement hasn't even been christened yet!
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Gretzky's New York Rangers are taking on the Kings
tonight and I couldn't be more melancholy. It's the 303rd
regular-season visit the game's greatest player will pay me. It's
also the last. Just seeing him set up behind the net or glide
across the ice, one skate resting atop the other, is going to bring
back enough memories to flood the surface.
</P>
<P>
   For one night, anyway, that won't be condensation forming
puddles on the ice. It'll be my tears.
</P>
<P>
   From that first time he graced me with his presence, on Dec.22,
1979, I've had a soft spot for Gretzky. Those first nine years he
spent with the Oilers, I made him feel so at home, it's little
wonder the day came when he actually was storing his sticks and
hanging up his skates under my roof.
</P>
<P>
   In 31 regular-season visits as an Oiler, Gretzky left 30 of them
with at least one point. In that span, I saw him pull out hat
tricks twice and collect more than three points four times on his
way to 26 goals and 68 points. All told, Gretzky has collected at
least one point in 258 of his 302 trips to see me.
</P>
<P>
   His sleight of hand has been a sight to behold. His right hook?
Well, that was another story. For sure, the Lady Byng was created
for fighters such as Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   When people think of me and Gretz they think of the 1982 Miracle
on Manchester that drained the life out of his Oilers or the goal
he scored 12 years later as a King to pass the king himself, Gordie
Howe. But one of my most vivid memories is of the night he and I
got caught in the middle of the worst fracas on ice that didn't
involve Russian ice dancer Pasha Grishuk.
</P>
<P>
   I saw the whole thing and believe me, I was wiping the blood off
my side boards for days. It happened on Feb.28, 1990, in a game _
understand, I use that term loosely _ against the Oilers that
produced 86 penalties totaling 356 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, a noted pacifist, entered the fray, sort of. He jumped
an Oilers skater to keep him from bruising Brian Benning.
</P>
<P>
   As I also recall, I was filled to the rafters that night.
Indeed, it was my fifth sellout in 12 days, my 25th of the season
and my 49th since the start of the 1988-89 season, Gretzky's first
with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   My stock soared in the NHL as soon as Oilers owner Peter
Pocklington traded Gretzky to the Kings along with Mike
Krushelnyski and Marty McSorley for Jimmy Carson, Martin Gelinas,
three first-round draft picks and $15 million in cash. Just like
that, I was no longer the poor man's Forum. A Montreal wannabee no
more, I proceeded to ride Gretzky's jersey shirttails all the way
to a place in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   Me and Gretz had many memorable moments. They'll have to raze me
before I forget Roy Orbison singing the national anthem in
Gretzky's first game as a King, on Oct.6, 1988, and Wayne then
going out and scoring on his first shot on his way to a four-point
debut.
</P>
<P>
   His seven-point night against Quebec in February of 1989 was a
kick and I can live the rest of my days off the energy that coursed
through my concourses during Games 3 and 4 of the 1993 Stanley Cup
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing compared to the night in 1994 when he notched his
802nd goal to break Howe's goal-scoring record. Hundreds of
photographs were snapped of me and Gretz and the puck during and
after that game against Vancouver, many of them in a closet-sized
room off the Kings' dressing room where players, movie stars and
minimum-wage workers streamed through to have their pictures taken
with The Accommodating One.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the photographs from that night have made it to the
Hockey Hall of Fame in Toronto. That makes me happy, knowing I'll
be hanging on hockey's hallowed walls long after my own have
crumbled and fallen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
