<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-RUEGAMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUEGAMER GETS READUY FOR POSSIBLY LAST GAME AS A DEVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the scariest sight on wheels since the Wizard of Oz
tornado scene. Grey Ruegamer. On a bike. In the locker-room shower.
Naked.
</P>
<P>
   Need more? Check out his freezer. You'll find a fish head tucked
under the Stouffer's.
</P>
<P>
   That's the free-spirited Ruegamer. Then there's the other side,
the one who enjoys working with special education children, the one
former teammate Kyle Murphy describes as a ``great guy and true
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder may have summed it up best when he
described the senior as ``complex, mean, smart, tender, obnoxious.
He's 14. He's 44.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many shades of Grey, but the one the Sun Devils will
miss most is the tough-nosed player on the football field. Unless
ASU beats Arizona and advances to a bowl, Nov. 27 will be
Ruegamer's last game in a Sun Devil uniform.
</P>
<P>
   His preference for the bizarre sometimes overshadows his
accomplishments: First team All-Pac-10 in 1997, Lombardi Award and
Outland Trophy candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He always plays hard, but this season his aggressiveness has
raised some eyebrows. Oregon Coach Mike Bellotti accused the Sun
Devils' offensive line of chop-blocking, and several of the plays
under question involved Ruegamer.
</P>
<P>
   Some have wondered if the center might feel the backlash in the
postseason, when coaches vote for the all-conference team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about what Pac-10 coaches think,'' he said.
``That stuff doesn't matter to me. I'm just (ticked) off because of
his accusation. It isn't intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything else about Ruegamer is. He often has crazy
bumpersticks or messages, like ``Maggotfest,'' taped to his helmet.
He'll walk around ASU's locker room wearing nothing but a glove in
a, well, odd place. Or he'll ride around naked on a bike to lighten
up a glum locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that one from Jake (Plummer),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He received some noteriety this summer when he spent a weekend
helping a friend of his mom's castrate sheep. The process was done
in the Basque tradition, which means teeth are used instead of a
scalpal because it is less painful to the animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more worried about the sheep than me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did about 200.
</P>
<P>
   There are still people walking around Tempe who believe
Ruegamer's mom is a buffet waitress at a Las Vegas casino.
</P>
<P>
   He started that story after growing tired of those who knew
nothing about his Nevada hometown and assumed he was raised in a
hotel. So he ran with it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, both parents are doctors. His father is a
veterinarian, his mother a Ph.D. Is she appalled by her son's
behavior?
</P>
<P>
   Are you kidding?
</P>
<P>
   ``She hunts mountain lions in her spare time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   A recent question-and-answer session with Ruegamer in the ASU
game program offered these tidbits:
</P>
<P>
   If you could live anywhere, where would you live?
</P>
<P>
   ``Underwater, on the ocean floor.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to switch places for a day with . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``A grizzly bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense. If there's one thing that defines Ruegamer, it's
his toughness. Credit his older brother Shane, his long-time
sparring partner growing up. When the boys were young, their
father, Alan, bought them boxing gloves so they would stop
wrestling in the house and breaking things.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'd cry, he'd start beating the hell out of me again,''
he said. ``He taught me a lot of things in the process of kicking
my (butt). He's actually great. So are my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane is now about six inches smaller now than the 6-foot-5,
305-pound Grey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' he said. ``I guess I mutated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruegamer makes no excuses for his behavior. ASU linebacker Joe
Cesta, Ruegamer's roommate, believes he ``does it for his own
enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ruegamer: ``I'm like a little kid. If I have too much
sugar, I get hyper. Sometimes I get incredibly bored. I could
entertain myself for hours on end just by creating things to amuse.
I don't see it as being that off the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruegamer stands out on and off the football field, and coaches
already are bemoaning the fact that he won't be back next season.
</P>
<P>
   He looks forward to his future, which likely will be in the NFL,
but he'll miss his experience at ASU and the relationship he's
developed with teammates and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade it,'' he said. ``Not many guys can say
they've been to the Rose Bowl. We've done so many good things here.
I've been fortunate to experience all these things college football
has to offer. I got to do a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   And he certainly did them his way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8076 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-MOORE-AZR &LR;      11-18 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-MOORE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MOORE OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - He has thought about the play a countless number
of times, rewinding it in his head, wishing there was something,
anything he could have done to make the outcome different.
</P>
<P>
   But each time Cardinals wide receiver Rob Moore replays the
closing seconds of last Sunday's game, the result always is the
same.
</P>
<P>
   He gets mauled in the right corner of the end zone by Dallas
cornerback Kevin Smith and quarterback Jake Plummer's pass falls
incomplete. Then, Moore looks for a pass-interference penalty, but
there is no call, and the Cardinals lose, 35-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thought I had was if I could have just squeezed it
a little more,'' he said. ``I thought it slipped out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The film showed otherwise. Smith knocked away the ball but not
until after a severe case of static cling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to expect to get calls like that,'' Moore said. ``But
when it starts happening time after time. . .Sure, it was
interference. But (for an official) to make that call, that's a
gutsy call.''
</P>
<P>
   The play was symbolic of Moore's season.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Moore led the NFL in receiving yards (1,584),
catches of at least 25 yards (20) and first-down grabs (68) in
making the NFC Pro Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Moore's production has dropped dramatically. He has
only 34 catches (down 23 from this time a year ago) for 487 yards,
a 14.3 average.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are simple. For much of the first half of the
season, he was slowed because of a nagging hamstring. He also has
played in an offense that has been one of the league's worst.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last month, in the middle of his slump, the ``New York
Times'' wrote that Moore, who is in the last year of his
$2.8-million-a-year contract, could be headed to the New York
Giants at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where they got that,'' said Moore, a Hempstead,
N.Y., native who came to the Cardinals in 1995 from the New York
Jets in a draft-day trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it didn't come from me. When I left there, (the New
York media) was saying that I was asking for too much money, that I
was demanding a trade. I heard so many things.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he's happy in the Valley of the Sun and could see
re-signing.
</P>
<P>
   `How can you beat this?'' he said of the weather. ``I got
married here. I had my (two) kids here. (Wide receiver Frank
Sanders) and I are like brothers. Guys like Aeneas (Williams) and
Anthony (Edwards) . . . I have an allegiance to so many players on
this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played with so many quarterbacks. Now, I look at Jake
(Plummer), and can't help but want to be part of his growth
process. He's so young but already doing things that takes people
years to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said he won't even think about his free-agent options
until the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an opportunity to get to the playoffs and that's
very important to me,'' Moore said. ``I've only been there once
before. We have a great chance to enjoy what that's like.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said he isn't upset about his production ``because we have
a lot more wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, 4-12 a year ago, are 5-5 and in the running for a
wild-card spot going into Sunday's game at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, Moore has had two of his three best
games this season. He had five catches for 107 yards in the 17-15
victory at Detroit on Nov. 1. Last Sunday, he had three receptions
for 77 yards, including a 57-yarder in the closing seconds that
gave the Cardinals first and goal at the 5.
</P>
<P>
   He was tackled from behind by safety Kenny Wheaton after it
appeared he would score or at least get out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed I didn't get into the end zone,'' Moore
said. ``I still think I was trying to do the right thing. I wasn't
thinking about the clock. I just ran out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are going to continue to try to get the ball to
Moore for big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a down-the-field receiver. He should be averaging 15 to
18 yards a catch,'' offensive coordinator Marc Trestman said. ``At
times, we've had him open, but he's been victim of some bad luck.
In (last Sunday's) Dallas game, we had him open on a go-route and
just missed him. In the first Dallas game, he beats (cornerback
Kevin) Smith by 20 yards, and we get sacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man of tremendous character, and I know things have not
gone exactly the way he has wanted this season, but he means so
much to us and we want him here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
