<HEADLINE>
PADRES' FINLEY DUE FOR VISIT ON MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Free agency in baseball is marked by plenty of ebb and
flow.
</P>
<P>
   One can wake up one day and be certain that the Diamondbacks
will sign left-hander  &UR; Randy Johnson. The next day, a completely
different feeling. The same thing with center fielder  &UR; Bernie
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the tide carried in right-hander  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre,
with Arizona making an offer. On Wednesday, team officials were
waiting for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears that another jewel will wash ashore Monday.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. said center fielder  &UR; Steve
Finley, who helped the San Diego Padres reach the World Series,
will visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the upper echelon as far as defensive outfielders are
concerned (Finley won National League Gold Gloves in 1995 and
1996). He's always been a solid hitter who happened to have an off
year last year (.249, 14 homers, 67 RBIs), but he was still the
everyday center fielder of a team that made it to the World
Series,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks were one of the first clubs to contact Finley
after the season, said Finley's agent,  &UR; Tommy Tanzer, and the
attention increased after the Los Angeles Dodgers signed
Diamondbacks center fielder  &UR; Devon White to a three-year, $12.4
million deal Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in what the Diamondbacks have to say. It is
an intriguing situation,'' Tanzer said. ``You wonder how extensive
their off-season moves will be. Could they bring in three top guys?
That's something you don't often see.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be that the Diamondbacks are focusing on Finley, 33,
because the tide might be taking Williams back toward the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are taking a long look at  &UR; Albert Belle and had
 &UR; Brian
 &UR; Jordan in for a visit Wednesday, but upon leaving his meeting,
Jordan said the team's No. 1 goal is to re-sign Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks still claim they have not made offers to
Williams and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will head to the West Coast in the next few days to
check out the Dodgers and Anaheim Angels. He could make a decision
on a new team by early next week, sources said. And Garagiola said
Stottlemyre continues to consider Arizona's offer. The team has not
disclosed details. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
