<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CIVIL-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: VAGUE WAIVERS IN LABOR CONTRACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Nov. 19: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When one of the Supreme Court's most conservative members,
Justice Antonin Scalia, writes a decision strengthening civil
rights enforcement, it is worth taking note. It happened this week
in a closely watched discrimination case from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The decision concerned a collective bargaining agreement between
the International Longshoremen's Association and the Port of
Charleston. Like most labor agreements these days, it contained a
clause requiring workplace disputes to be submitted to arbitration.
A federal appellate court interpreted the clause as stripping a
longshoreman, Caesar Wright, of his right to sue under the
Americans With Disabilities Act. Wright could not go to court with
his claim of discrimination, the court said, because his union had
effectively waived that right when it negotiated the arbitration
clause.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a unanimous Supreme Court has now rejected this
watering down of federal protection. Vaguely worded arbitration
clauses in labor contracts, the justices held, cannot bar access to
federal court by employees seeking to vindicate their rights under
federal civil rights laws. ``The right to a federal judicial forum
is of sufficient importance to be protected against
less-than-explicit union waiver'' of the right to go to court, said
Scalia, writing for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointingly, the court stopped short of finding that even an
explicit waiver would be unenforceable. But that may not matter for
most employees. Few labor agreements currently contain explicit
waivers of federal civil rights claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981118.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-REPUBS-NYT &LR;      11-18 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE REPUBLICAN LEADERS SET SAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Nov. 19: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first appearance of the new House Republican leaders
Wednesday suggested that the party has incorporated all the easy
parts of the message the public sent in the Nov. 3 elections.
``Teamwork'' and ``unity'' were the words of the day. There was no
mention of the social issues so dear to the hearts of the party's
right wing, and many nods to the importance of Social Security and
health care. Rep. Robert Livingston, who will be the new speaker,
announced that he regarded the party not as a ``big tent'' but a
``big ship'' that keeps moving steadily on course even when, on its
decks, the crew is going in all different directions.
</P>
<P>
   We can be pretty sure the incoming speaker has not been wasting
his time at the movies. In the year of ``Titanic,'' not a lot of
new leaders describe themselves as captains of really big ships
that keep forging ahead in one direction. Actually, Livingston
extended the metaphor to point to a specific type of ship, the
aircraft carrier, as an example of teamwork under the guidance of
the Constitution. In that context it is a heartening sign that he
is ready to take charge in a chaotic situation that calls for
strong leadership in the House.
</P>
<P>
   That institution has certainly appeared rudderless lately, and
this is precisely the moment when, among all branches of
government, it has to provide direction. As the House Judiciary
Committee struggles with the nation's most pressing political
crisis, Chairman Henry Hyde has been floundering desperately,
lurching first one way and then the other, without any apparent
plan. The House has the constitutional burden of judging President
Clinton and finding a punishment that fits the evidence, and as
Livingston has to see that the judiciary committee does not run
into the icebergs that Hyde seems not to notice.
</P>
<P>
   After the Republicans' leadership election, all the new officers
vowed to get behind the GOP ``agenda,'' but the makeup of the team
suggests that the Republicans have not figured out which way they
want to go. Dick Armey, a symbol of the surly approach that
Livingston wants to leave behind, survived a serious challenge to
keep his job as House majority leader. Another tough guy, Tom
DeLay, who was unchallenged in re-election as whip, was the point
man for former Speaker Newt Gingrich's assault on party reformers
on the campaign finance issue.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest news came when J.C. Watts of Oklahoma became the
first black Republican elected to a leadership role. Watts' strong
ties to the social conservatives and his personal popularity helped
win him the fourth spot, party conference chairman. But if the
Republicans were also sending a message of inclusion, it was a
commendable impulse both in terms of policy and politics. Watts is
the only black Republican in the House, and overwhelming black
support for Democratic candidates was a main reason for key
Republican losses in the election. Given the choice between writing
the black vote off or trying to win it, the party made the right
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Watts' new job involves communicating the party's message, and
his well-known talents as a public speaker should serve the party
well. But first, somebody is going to have to give him a message to
deliver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
