<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nostalgia the theme in Tenn. St. season finale
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A grand ol' time is expected in Nashville on Saturday
when Tennessee State plays its last regular-season game at historic
Hale Stadium, better known as ``The Hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers (8-2), hosting Texas Southern, won their first Ohio
Valley Conference title and clinched a berth in the Division I-AA
playoffs last week with a 46-44 victory over Murray State. The game
will be a homecoming of sorts for Texas Southern coach Bill Thomas,
a former player and coach at Tennessee State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be bringing back those guys who played in the
Hole, band members who performed there, Tiger Belles who ran track
there and even ushers who guided people to their seats,'' Tennessee
State third-year coach L.C. Cole said. ``It should be a memorable
day for everybody, including this football team. I didn't think
this kind of success would come so soon, but we came here with a
plan and everybody bought into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly quarterback Leon Murray, a 6-3, 205-pound junior
from Shreveport, and senior receiver Tyrone Butterfield, who
surpassed the 1,000-yard mark in receiving twice since transferring
from Michigan a couple of years ago. Against Murray State, Murray
completed 28 of 54 attempts for an OVC-record 491 yards and four
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine showdown
</P>
<P>
   As many as 70,000 people could be in Orlando this weekend as
Florida A&AMP;M (9-1) meets surprising Bethune-Cookman (8-1) in the
Citrus Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   After beating South Carolina State, North Carolina A&AMP;T and
Hampton on the road, Bethune has put itself in position to win the
MEAC title outright.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Wildcats' five-game victory streak should end,
they are assured a spot somewhere in postseason play _ in either
the I-AA playoffs or the McDonald's Heritage Bowl in Atlanta on
Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   For FAMU, tied with Bethune and Hampton in the MEAC, a victory
would almost assure one of the eight host spots in next week's
first round of I-AA playoffs, along with a share of the conference
title.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer Bowl set
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone College, which won the Central Intercollegiate
Athletic Association (CIAA) championship for the second year in a
row, will play in the Atlanta-based Pioneer Bowl again. The Blue
Bears (7-3) from Salisbury, N.C., will face SIAC champion Tuskegee
(9-1) Dec. 19 at Morris Brown's Herndon Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tuskegee won't end its regular season until Thanksgiving Day,
when it takes on Alabama State at the Cramton Bowl in the annual
Turkey Day Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk State coach Darnell Moore has become one of the first
casualities of the postseason. After compiling a five-year record
of 26-27, including a 2-9 mark in the team's first year as a member
of the MEAC, Moore's contract was not renewed. ... Jackson State,
which has led I-AA in attendance all but one year during the past
decade, is expected to draw a crowd of 55,000 Saturday when it
faces SWAC-rival Alcorn State in the annual Capital City Classic in
Memorial Stadium in Jackson, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S GAMES
</P>
<P>
   CIAA
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth City State at Johnson C. Smith, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MEAC
</P>
<P>
   Delta. State at Howard, 1 p.m.; Hampton at Morgan State, 1 p.m.;
S.C. State at N.C. A&AMP;T, 1:30 p.m.; Florida A&AMP;M at Bethune-Cookman,
8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SIAC
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky State at Illinois State, 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SWAC
</P>
<P>
   Jackson State at Alcorn State, 1 p.m.; Texas Southern at Tenn.
State, 1 p.m.; Alabama A&AMP;M at Ark.-Pine Bluff, 2 p.m.
</P>
