</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLEMSON-WEST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemson fires West in 2-8 season
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Clemson one defeat away from its worst season in
nearly a quarter-century, head coach Tommy West was abruptly fired
Wednesday amid speculation that his successor might be his one-time
boss: Danny Ford.
</P>
<P>
   West, in his fourth year as head coach, has three years left on
his contract and one game left to coach at Clemson: Saturday
night's season finale against arch-rival South Carolina. With
Clemson 2-8 overall _ and, at 1-7 in the ACC basement, already
assured of its worst finish in the conference _ a loss to the 1-9
Gamecocks would match the Tigers' worst record since going 2-9 in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised,'' said West, who was informed of his
firing Wednesday by Clemson athletics director Bobby Robinson, the
man who hired West in November, 1993. ``It really kind of caught me
off guard. I said if a decision's been made, I'd like to know. So I
was really caught off guard.'' Robinson told West that he was fired
but could coach Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my years at Clemson, I never enjoyed working with
anyone more,'' said Robinson who praised West's ``class, dignity
and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't meet our expectations as far as the won-loss
record,'' said Robinson. ``That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   West is 30-28 at Clemson. After a 5-6 debut, his next three
teams went to bowl games. But this year's Tigers, with a young,
inexperienced offensive line, have lost seven of their last eight
games, including the last four. Five of those losses were by seven
points or less. West informed his team at a meeting before
Wednesday's practice. ``Our players were in shock,'' he said. ``I
wanted them to hear it before anyone else told them. What effect
it's going to have on them (Saturday), I don't know.'' As for
West's successor, Robinson said, ``You'd like to get someone in as
fast as possible. But time is not as important as making sure we
get the best coach in America for Clemson football.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates include Tommy Bowden, whose Tulane team is 9-0
and who's become the hottest coaching commodity in the land. While
Tommy Tuberville of Ole Miss has also been mentioned, there is
growing support among older Clemson alumni and IPTAY boosters for
Ford, who took Clemson to the 1981 national championship.
</P>
<P>
   And what would West advise his successor? ``Don't have a losing
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
