<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson rests ankle but says, `I'm fine'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons running back Jamal Anderson, who is third in
the NFL with 1,066 rushing yards, did not practice Wednesday
because coach Dan Reeves decided it would be best if Anderson
rested his sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson suffered the injury in the first quarter of Sunday's
31-19 win over San Francisco, but finished the game with 31 rushes
for 100 yards and two TDs.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday, he wore a removable cast on his lower
left leg, but Wednesday he was in athletic shoes on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's listed as questionable on the injury report,
Anderson insists he'll play Sunday when Atlanta (8-2) meets the
Bears (3-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine, I'm fine,'' is all he said as he jogged off the
field Wednesday, with no apparent limp.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson spent nearly an hour in the training room Wednesday
morning wearing a boot that sends a mild electrical current into
the body to stimulate blood flow and expedite healing.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is second in the NFL with 11 touchdowns (Terrell Davis
has 17), tied with Barry Sanders for second-most 100-yard games
(Davis has eight), leads the NFL in third-and-1 rushes, converting
all seven of his tries to first downs, and is second in the NFC
behind Emmitt Smith (70) with 63 first downs.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, rookie Ken Oxendine (12 carries, 19 yards) and
9-year veteran Harold Green (14 carries, 31 yards) worked with the
first-team offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game plan wouldn't change (if Anderson didn't play),''
Reeves said. ``I think Ken gives us a chance with his running
instincts to get the job done, but I would rely too on Harold
because of his experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Other injury news
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver and kick returner Tim Dwight practiced Wednesday
for the first time since he strained a medial collateral knee
ligament Oct. 25 against the Jets, but he's still listed as
doubtful for Sunday's game. Reeves said Dwight was a little stiff.
... Cornerback Ronnie Bradford, who played a few snaps on punts
Sunday in his first action since straining an MCL Oct. 25, worked
part-time with the No. 1 defense Wednesday. There is a chance he
could replace Michael Booker, who has played well in three starts,
in the starting lineup against the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   No sellout likely
</P>
<P>
   Falcons president Taylor Smith talked with NFL officials
Wednesday about getting extra time to sell out Sunday's home game
against the Bears so that a local TV blackout could be lifted.
Also, general manager Harold Richardson and director of
marketing/sales Rob Jackson talked with Atlanta-area corporate
sponsors about guaranteeing to purchase the remaining tickets to
aid the process. League rules stipulate that home games must be
sold out by 1 p.m. the prior Thursday in order to be televised in
the local market. But with about 19,000 tickets still left for the
game, at an average price of $30 apiece, neither local corporations
or WAGA, Channel 5, the local Fox affiliate that would televise the
game, was willing to put up nearly $570,000 in order to guarantee
the sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Bad News Bears
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's practice was bizarre Wednesday as No. 3 quarterback
Moses Moreno, a rookie, took all the snaps with the No. 1 offense,
and the No. 1 tailback was James Allen, who began the season on the
practice squad. To top it off, offensive coordinator Matt
Cavanaugh, a 14-year backup quarterback in the NFL, ran the scout
team offense. Chicago quarterback Erik Kramer, who has missed the
last two games with shoulder tendinitis and a possible tear of the
rotator cuff, threw before practice but did not participate. Exams
have not revealed a tear, but Kramer, who Reeves and the Falcons
tried to sign as a free agent last year, keeps describing symptoms
matching a tear.
</P>
<P>
   Also, quarterback Steve Stenstrom did not practice because of a
strained non-throwing shoulder but said he'll be 100 percent by
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That left Moreno, a seventh-round draft choice out of Colorado
who has completed 1-of-2 passes for 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with first-round draft choice Curtis Enis, a running
back, out for the season with a torn ACL, Edgar Bennett has become
the starting tailback but missed Wednesday's practice with back
spasms. That left former Oklahoma star Allen, who has no carries as
a pro, working with Glyn Milburn at running back.
</P>
<P>
   Still a Falcon
</P>
<P>
   Running back Byron Hanspard, who tore the anterior cruciate
ligament and patella tendon in his knee in the final preseason
game, misses playing. But he said he's not suffering extra just
because his teammates are having so much fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a lot of my playing through Jamal,'' Hanspard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, at the beginning, everybody was trying to get used
to each other and feel things out. This year, we know each other,
we're happy with each other, we love each other. There's no, `I'm
the man,' or, `He's the man.' I don't see any cockiness in the
locker room. It's all `we' and no ``me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling, playing better
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Bob Whitfield is playing very well lately, and he
said it's reasonable to assume that when things are going so well
for the team, players pick up their individual games. Whitfield has
a reputation for being inconsistent, but lately he's been very
solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start winning, it changes your mentality and how you
look at the game, how you are at home, how you talk to your kids,''
he said. ``You start feeling like you're playing better. You want
to keep that roll, and you have that confidence that you're going
to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield's mother, Eartha, is feeling good, too. She cooks a
meal for the team at the beginning of every season. Friday, she's
doing it a second time, as the team has been invited over to
``Mama'' Whitfield's, about five minutes from team headquarters in
Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler leads the NFL with a 118.5 passer
rating in the fourth quarter, completing 22-of-31 passes (71
percent) for 386 yards, three touchdowns and two interceptions. ...
The Falcons worked out offensive linemen Steve Zahursky (6-foot-6,
310 pounds), who has been with the Jaguars, Steve Scifres (6-4,
300), who has been with the Cowboys and Panthers, and tight end Bob
Rosenthal (6-3, 240), who has been with the Raiders. ... Kicker
Morten Andersen, who scored seven points against the 49ers, has 401
points as a Falcon, passing kicker Norm Johnson (395) to move into
second place in franchise history. Kicker Mick Luckhurst leads with
558.
</P>
<P>
   Bears boys
</P>
<P>
   First-year defensive tackle Shawn Swayda, who was active in last
Sunday's game against the 49ers, was cut last year as a defensive
end by the Bears, who drafted him in the sixth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no resentment,'' he said. ``I'm sure they don't think
much of me. I didn't play well when I was there. I couldn't have
made any team last year. I wasn't ready to play. This year, I was
ready to play, and I don't think there's too many teams I wouldn't
have made. That's the way I look at it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
