<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurdles all but cleared for Holyfield vs. Lewis
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After eight weeks of conference calls and facing a
possible repeat of last year's nightmarish fizzled negotiations,
officials representing Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis finally
have reached an agreement in principle for a heavyweight title
unification March 13 at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a deal,'' said Milt Chwasky, an attorney representing
Lewis, whose camp resolved some final issues with promoter Don King
and pay-per-view distributor Time Warner late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executive Lou DiBella said, ``Other than some
signatures, there's nothing really stopping this now.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight, which officially will be announced Nov. 30 at a
Garden news conference, will unify Holyfield's WBA and IBF belts
and Lewis' WBC title. Holyfield will earn at least $20 million.
Lewis and his promoters will take in a total of $9.5 million,
although the boxer will end up with closer to $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The lone potential deal-breaker was a dispute over the payment
schedule of the $9.5 million. Dino Duva, one of Lewis' promoters,
even sent out a press release earlier in the week, charging King
with ``trickerations'' by and that he was changing the terms of a
deal. that had been verbally agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   Duva's move even upset Chwasky, who expressed surprise told a
reporter, ``Oh, (bleep),''when learning of the release from a
reporter. Holyfield's attorney, Jim Thomas, expressed relief that
felt relieved matters have been settled, but Thomas said of Duva,
``I get the feeling someone on Lennox's side doesn't want this
fight to happen. What good is going to come out of calling names?
We're trying to make a deal happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Training Tyson
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Brooks, Holyfield's assistant trainer, is close to
accepting a deal to become Mike Tyson's next trainer. It's But it's
not clear whether Brooks would leave Holyfield's camp immediately.
Technically, Brooks could train Tyson for his Jan. 16 comeback
against Francois Botha and then help trainer Don Turner prepare
Holyfield for the Lewis bout. Thomas said he hadn't discussed the
matter with Holyfield yet.
</P>
<P>
   King's return
</P>
<P>
   Don King will promote his first card in Atlanta since the
Holyfield-Vaughn Bean title fight with a program card Friday night
at the Atrium in Stone Mountain. Tickets, at $35 and $15, are
available are on sale at the Atrium box office or by calling
404-298-6546.
</P>
<P>
   The main event will pit Atlanta female boxer Isra Girgrah
against Angela Buchanan, who was knocked out in the third round by
Girgrah in April. Girgrah has not fought since, in part because of
management entanglements.
</P>
<P>
   But Girgrah's focus these days is primarily on women's champion
Christy Martin. The two fought last year, with Martin winning a
decision, but Girgrah has sought a rematch ever since. There is a
chance the two might may meet on the undercard of Holyfield-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is ever definite until the contract is signed, but
hopefully it will go through,'' Girgrah said. ``I want a rematch
with Christy, or fight somebody high in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
