u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ACCREPORT19-COX     11-18 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ACCREPORT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemson going into game with injury, defense concerns
 &HT;    By Norman Arey and Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CLEMSON vs. South Carolina, Saturday, 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers will play their season _ and head coach Tommy West's
_ finale with major injury concerns on defense. Cornerback Antwan
Edwards is still questionable with a pulled hamstring that kept him
out of the Georgia Tech game, and linebacker Chris Jones is on
crutches with a sprained ankle. Linebacker O.J. Childress, who has
played sparingly the last three games with a sprained knee, is
probable, defensive end Terry Bryant is doubtful with a sprained
ankle and defensive end Adrian Dingle is questionable, also with a
sprained knee.... Before his dismissal, West said the program was
better ``in every area'' than the one he inherited from Ken
Hatfield in 1993 _ from on-the-field performance to academic
progress to attendance.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE vs. North Carolina, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   When Duke hosts North Carolina, the Blue Devils will be trying
to snap a seven-game losing streak against the Tar Heels. One
reason UNC has been so dominant is that it has been able to run the
ball against Duke. Carolina has outrushed Duke 236.2 yards to 54.4
yards over the past five games. ``We consider this the biggest
football game of the year,'' said coach Fred Goldsmith, who never
has beaten UNC. . . . Tailback B.J. Hill had 124 yards rushing
against Maryland last week and broke Duke's freshman rushing record
with 701 yards. . . . Scottie Montgomery (58 catches) and Richmond
Flowers (46) rank third and fourth among ACC reception leaders. . .
. Duke ranks in the middle of the conference in total offense and
defense _ fifth in total offense (348 yards per game) and sixth in
total defense (354.2).
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE vs. Florida, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles are trying to prepare quarterback Marcus Outzen
for Florida's pass rush, but coach Bobby Bowden says it has been
difficult. ``We haven't even come close to facing a pass rush like
they've got,'' Bowden said. ``A lot of times you're worried about
assignments, and you think if you can get a body on the right guy,
you can beat him. But against Florida, you can get your body on the
right guy and still get beat.'' Bowden said Florida is FSU's
biggest rival. ``They don't have many players we haven't tried to
recruit and we don't have many that they haven't tried to get.''
Florida State returned to the top of the nation in total defense
this week. The Seminoles had dropped to second before holding Wake
Forest to 179 total yards in last week's 24-7 victory. . . . The
Seminoles lead the ACC with 38 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND vs. N.C. State, Saturday, 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-25 win over Duke last week not only snapped an 11-game
ACC losing streak, but it marked the most points the Terps scored
since a 52-0 win over Wake Forest in 1996.... Maryland picked off
an ACC single game-tying seven passes against Duke, three by
cornerback Cliff Cosby.... Quarterback Randall Jones came off the
bench to have the best game of his career, completing six of 13
passes for a personal-best 98 yards and two touchdowns. He became
the first Maryland quarterback in 20 years to rush for more than
100 yards with 115 yards.... Despite being second in the ACC in
rushing with 164.3 yards a game, the Terps are near the bottom
nationally in most other offensive categories: 97th in points
(18.1); 104th in total yards (278.1) and 106th in passing yards
(113.9).
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA at Duke, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   Coach Carl Torbush says his Tar Heels know that Duke is
dangerous. ``They've lost three games that they could have won,''
Torbush said. ``They're like us in that their record could be
better with a few breaks. This Duke team is the most physical
running football team of any Duke team I can remember. This is a
cross-town rivalry in the truest sense, and I think it'll be a
dogfight.'' . . . Receiver Na Brown is within one reception of the
school record of 155. . . . Junior cornerback Dre Bly is the ACC's
all-time interception leader with 19. . . . Freshman Rufus Brown
leads the Tar Heels with 385 yards rushing, which ranks 10th in the
ACC. . . . Quarterback Ronald Curry leads all ACC freshmen and is
seventh overall in the conference in total offense (139.7 yards per
game).
</P>
<P>
   N.C. STATE at Maryland, Saturday, 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Torry Holt's record-shattering season might be getting headline
attention, but the 6-3 Wolfpack needs a win Saturday to erase any
doubt about a bowl bid. With a loss they probably have to beat
North Carolina next week just to get any invitation. State has won
just once in its last five road games, and that was a 46-39
thriller at Clemson on Oct. 31.... Holt needs seven more receptions
to own the ACC single-season reception mark of 77; he already has
the single-season yardage record with 1,338. With 3,113 yards, Holt
needs 208 yards over the next two games to become the ACC careere
receiving-yardage leader. ... Tailback Rahshon Spikes, out since
hurting his shoulder in the Georgia Tech game Oct. 10, will play
Saturday. In his place, freshman Ray Robinson has rushed for a
team-high 664 yards.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA at Virginia Tech, Nov. 28
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers have this weekend off before closing out their
season against Virginia Tech. When the Cavs take the field on Nov.
28, coach George Welsh will be coaching his 300th Division I
football game. ``That's a lot of games _ that's my first thought,''
Welsh said. ``I never thought I'd be around this long. But some
guys have 300 wins and, to me, that's even more amazing.'' Welsh is
concerned that Virginia Tech has blocked so many kicks this season.
The Cavs will practice only twice this week before working a normal
week next week. ``I don't want to leave it on the field this week.
This is the 12th week of the season. You have to be very careful.''
. . . Virginia leads the ACC in rushing offense at 227.1 yards per
game, which is 10th nationally. Thomas Jones leads the ACC with
124.8 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   WAKE FOREST at Georgia Tech, Saturday, 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Demon Deacons coach Jim Caldwell said he thinks Desmond Clark,
the ACC's career receiving leader, will be ready to play Saturday
against Georgia Tech. Clark has missed two games because of a knee
injury. ``Desmond practiced earlier this week and looked good,''
Caldwell said. ``He tried to go last week, but he wasn't ready. But
he's much better this week.'' . . . Caldwell said it's important
for his 3-7 Deacons to finish the season positively. ``Our focus
has been good, even though our season hasn't gone as well as we
would have liked,'' he said. ``It's important for us to end the
season on a good note. We do a lot of recruiting in the Atlanta
area.'' . . . Wake ranks second in the conference in passing
offense (265.7 yards per game) but is next to last in passing
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
