<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to salvage any season
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A victory on college football's ``Rivalry Saturday''
is so big it can turn a good season into a great season. For
struggling teams, it can transform a bad season magically into
something much better.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe one game can make such a difference? Ask Auburn
defensive tackle Charles Dorsey.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a fun year at Auburn. The Tigers are 3-7. Their
head coach, Terry Bowden, quit at midseason. There is daily
speculation about who the new coach will be. Almost all the
headlines have been negative. But all the heartache Auburn has
endured this season, Dorsey said, will disappear if the Tigers can
find a way to beat archrival Alabama on ESPN Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we beat Alabama, people are going to forget about all the
hurt we've been through,'' Dorsey said. ``That's how big this one
game is.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan, this is the game you have to live with for an
entire year. If your team loses, you have to face the fans of the
other team at work, at church, at the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks here want us to win them all, but if we have to lose
one, they sure don't want it to be against Florida,'' said Florida
State coach Bobby Bowden, whose Seminoles host Florida on Saturday
(3:30 p.m., ABC). ``When you get a rivalry within one state, it
gets pretty intense.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of intense rivalry games will be played Saturday, while
others, such as Arkansas-Mississippi State, have major postseason
implications. Here are 10 of the best and what's at stake:
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2 Kansas State at No. 19 Missouri: Kansas State clinched a
berth in the Big 12 championship game with a victory over Nebraska,
but it needs a win over Missouri to keep alive any hope of
advancing to the Fiesta Bowl for the national title game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Southern California (7-3) at No. 3 UCLA (9-0): UCLA already
has clinched the Rose Bowl but needs to keep winning to stay in
contention for the Fiesta Bowl and the national championship. USC
has enough athletes to exploit the Bruins' bad defense and would
love to knock them out of the big game.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 4 Florida (9-1) at No. 5 Florida State (10-1): The winner
of this one not only gets bragging rights but also will be on the
doorstep to the Fiesta Bowl if any of the top three stumbles down
the stretch. Florida coach Steve Spurrier is winless in Tallahassee
in four trips.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 11 Michigan (8-2) at No. 7 Ohio State (9-1): Michigan has
won eight in a row since starting the season with two losses. If
they beat the Buckeyes for the ninth time in 11 years, the
Wolverines go back to the Rose Bowl. Ohio State goes to Pasadena if
it wins and if Wisconsin loses to Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   _ South Carolina (1-9) at Clemson (2-8): It is the worst
combined record for these two teams going into the game. Clemson's
Tommy West will be coaching his last game after being fired
Wednesday. South Carolina's Brad Scott is also under fire. Both
teams need something to salvage their respective seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Auburn (3-7) vs. Alabama (6-4): Alabama needs a win to cap off
a good comeback season under second-year coach Mike Dubose. Auburn
is playing for pride.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 9 Arkansas (8-1) at Mississippi State (6-3): The
Razorbacks can clinch the SEC West with a victory, while the
Bulldogs can pull into a first-place tie with Arkansas with a win.
</P>
<P>
   _ North Carolina (4-5) at Duke (4-6): It's a better rivalry in
basketball, but these two schools, separated by 12 miles, really
don't like each other. A win would keep the Tar Heels alive for a
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ Indiana (4-6) at Purdue (7-4): The game dates back to 1891,
and since 1925 they have played for the Old Oaken Bucket. The
Boilermakers are going to a bowl for the second year in a row,
thanks to quarterback Drew Brees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yale (5-4) at Harvard (4-5): This rivalry is the third-oldest
in college football, dating back to 1875. Yale can earn a share of
the Ivy League title
</P>
<P>
   with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
