<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGENOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC officials drop ball again
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Bobby Gaston had his way, people would never notice
the men who officiate football games for the SEC. No such luck this
week.
</P>
<P>
   SEC football officials are making news for a game that already
has been played _ Arkansas-Tennessee _ and a game that is about to
be played _ Florida-Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the SEC officiating crew made an incorrect ruling
in last week's Arkansas-Tennessee game when Arkansas punter Chris
Akins kicked the ball out of the back of the end zone after a snap
had gone over this head. Officials on the play awarded Tennessee a
safety, which cut the Arkansas lead to 24-22 with 2:56 left.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston said Wednesday that officials actually should have given
Tennessee the option of taking the ball where it was kicked plus a
half-the-distance penalty. That would have given Tennessee the ball
on the 5-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were entitled to an an option they didn't get,'' said
Gaston, who was in his car listening to the game on the radio when
he heard what happened. ``When I called both coaches on Monday,
neither was aware of the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Vols not come back and won 28-24, it would have been a
disastrous mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making any excuses, but in the heat of the moment I
might have missed the call, too,'' Gaston said. ``It was the first
time I had seen that.''
</P>
<P>
   SEC officials will be under scrutiny again Saturday when they
travel to Tallahassee to work the Florida-Florida State game. Two
years ago, Florida coach Steve Spurrier blistered the SEC crew,
which he claimed let Florida State beat up quarterback Danny
Wuerffel in a 24-21 loss.
</P>
<P>
   He carried his crusade against late hits all the way to the
Sugar Bowl, even making a video tape for the media. With a Big 12
crew working the game, Florida beat Florida State in a rematch
52-20.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's biggest advantage in Saturday's game is that the
Gators have a healthy quarterback in Doug Johnson. FSU will be
playing with backup Marcus Outzen. Spurrier has been low-key on the
topic this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all I need to say on the subject,'' Spurrier said.
``People know how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaston said he had discussed the topic this week with Florida
assistant Lawson Holland and that his officials will call the game
consistent with the rules. There will be an SEC technical advisor
at the game to talk to the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'll bring it up before the game,'' said Gaston.
``Steve knows we will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   COACHING BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Auburn continues search for a coach
</P>
<P>
   _ The coaching grapevine tells us Auburn's coaching search will
continue into next week and the school hopes to make a decision
either just before or just after the SEC Championship game Dec. 5.
Athletics director David Housel is mum on the interview process,
but it is known he talked with Temple coach Bobby Wallace on
Monday. We also believe that, despite his suggestions to the
contrary, Ole Miss coach Tommy Tuberville is still a very viable
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Auburn interim coach Bill Oliver will not return to the school
if he is not named head coach. That much we know. What we don't
know is where Oliver will land. He says he'll probably go fishing
and introduce himself to his wife. We think Florida coach Steve
Spurrier, a long-time admirer, will give Oliver a strong look if
his defensive coordinator, Bobby Stoops, gets a head-coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ole Miss officials are getting a little weary of Tuberville
getting involved in the coaching derby again this season. They gave
Tuberville's assistants healthy raises last year after he came
close to going to Arkansas. They also have drawn up some plans for
new facilities for the football program. Tuberville's name has been
linked with Auburn, South Carolina and even Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   _ After catching heat from the family of quarterback Michael
Bishop, Kansas State coach Bill Snyder finally let Bishop talk to
the media this week. He refused media access for most of the season
after Bishop made some ill-advised comments, but the family thought
it was hurting Bishop's chances at the Heisman Trophy. They were
right. Now it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   BOWL BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Keeping track of bowl situation
</P>
<P>
   _ If Miami wins the Big East championship, Florida might go to
the Orange Bowl, even if it doesn't beat Florida State. The Orange
Bowl wants the Gators because they have not been to the bowl since
Jan. 1, 1967, which was the last game as a college player for coach
Steve Spurrier. It was, coincidently, Bobby Dodd's last game as
Georgia Tech coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Tennessee wins the SEC championship and plays in the Fiesta
Bowl, the Sugar Bowl will get the first pick after the
national-title game is set. The Sugar Bowl's top game? Florida
State vs. 10-1 Notre Dame. That only happens if Kansas State is in
the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   _ That Florida appears headed to the Bowl Championship Series
improves the chances of Georgia getting into the Citrus Bowl
against Wisconsin, Ohio State or Michigan. The Bulldogs can
strengthen that position by beating both Ole Miss and Georgia Tech.
If Georgia loses one or both, the Citrus might be tempted to take
Kentucky and Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Arkansas (8-1) beats Mississippi State on Saturday, it will
do no worse than the Cotton Bowl on Jan. 1. Folks in Dallas would
love to match the Razorbacks with Texas (7-3), particularly if the
Longhorns can upset No. 6 Texas A&AMP;M next week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Gator Bowl's No. 1 game? Georgia Tech vs. Notre Dame. If
Notre Dame doesn't make it into the Bowl Championship Series, it in
effect becomes a Big East team and gets that slot.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   2012: The year Kansas State would reach the .500 mark in
all-time victories if it won every game between now and then.
</P>
<P>
   7.7: Millions of dollars in profit earned by Big Ten athletic
departments last season. The conference generated $403.2 million in
revenues and had $395.5 million in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   1982: The last year that Auburn and Alabama played and neither
team was ranked. It has happened only five times in the previous 61
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   .713: The NCAA record for pass completion percentage for a
single season. It was set in 1983 by Steve Young of BYU. Going into
Saturday's final regular-season game with New Mexico, Central
Florida's Daunte Culpepper has completed .738 of his passes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
