<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Work on Stone Mountain spillway nears end
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde and Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro anglers are wondering about the status of the
boat ramp at Stone Mountain Park's large lake, which has been
closed since September for work on the spillway near the dam. Bob
Cowhig, director of planning and construction for the Stone
Mountain Memorial Association, said work is about 60 days ahead of
schedule and the ramp should be back to normal well before the
initial prediction of mid-spring, maybe even in January.
</P>
<P>
   The ramp is closed because the water level is down to 6 feet; no
motors are allowed because the lower level could expose boaters to
dangerous structures above or just below the surface. Cowhig said
construction would be finished in about two weeks, weather
permitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The construction is about to be completed,'' Cowhig said.
``Once that's done, bring on the rain.'' Rain will help bring the
water level back to full pool.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ramp being closed, anglers are finding ways to wet a
line, either from the bank or from small boats and canoes carried
to the water. And some have been having good luck catching bass.
``I've talked to some fishermen who wanted to know if we could just
leave it the way it is,'' Cowhig joked.
</P>
<P>
   Hike on Foote
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened Len Foote Hike Inn lodge at Amicalola Falls
State Park will be showcased on tonight's ``Georgia Outdoors
Show,'' 7:30 on GPTV. The 21-room lodge, operated by the nonprofit
Appalachian Education and Recreation Services, is a five-mile hike
from the park. Reservations are required and accepted as much as 11
months in advance by calling 770-389-7275 and outside metro Atlanta
at 800-864-7275. Rates are $55 double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   State championship begins
</P>
<P>
   Another large field is expected for the 11th annual Georgia
State Bass Fishing Championship/Highland Marina Invitational this
weekend on West Point Lake near LaGrange. Tournament director
George Marovich says more than 500 men and women, all qualifying by
finishing in the top five in significant tournaments held on
Georgia lakes in the past year, will compete for about $50,000 in
cash and prizes. First place is guaranteed $15,000. Last year's
field of 256 boats (512 anglers from six states) was the largest
bass tournament on West Point. Practice rounds are today and
Friday, with competition beginning at safe light Saturday and
Sunday. For information, call 706-882-3437.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
