<HEADER>
A8255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-RACING-NOTES19-CO     11-18 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRL rules unlikely to attract CART
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The competition between the Indy Racing League and the
CART circuit appears likely to carry into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL announced new engine rules and new guidelines Tuesday
for its 3-year-old series. And although it made some changes in
engine dimensions, horsepower, even sound, the IRL stood fast about
the concept of teams owning their engines rather than leasing them
from manufacturers as CART does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a series, and we want additional competitors, but
we're going to stay with the principles developed by our founder,
Tony George,'' said Leo Mehl, executive director of the IRL. ``The
main issue is leasing. I've been told that (CART) will not budge on
that issue. There is no reason another group (such as CART) could
not take this basic program, which controls cost, controls speed,
and adapt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehl said CART drivers and teams would be welcome at
Indianapolis and all other IRL events, if their cars comply with
IRL rules.
</P>
<P>
   The split has kept most of the sport's best-known drivers, who
were under contract with CART, away from the Indianapolis 500.
Those missing from the showcase race included Al Unser Jr., Michael
Andretti and Bobby Rahal, who recently retired.
</P>
<P>
   Selwa leaving Panoz
</P>
<P>
   Jim Selwa, chief operating officer of Panoz Motor Sports since
1997, is leaving Panoz to pursue other interests in the automotive
industry. He will, however, remain with Panoz as a consultant.
Replacing Selwa is Tres Stephenson, former executive director of
Sebring International Raceway. International stars raced at Road
Atlanta during October's Petit Le Mans. Now, the grass-roots guys
take over, as the Sports Car Club of America has its American Road
Race of Champions, Friday-Sunday. For more information, call
770-455-7222.
</P>
<P>
   Drag racing
</P>
<P>
   Duluth's Warren Johnson and other NHRA leaders were honored
Tuesday for winning championships in their respective professional
categories at the 1998 NHRA Winston Drag Racing awards ceremony at
the Cerritos (Calif.) Center for the Performing Arts. Drag racing
fans in Georgia have known for weeks that Johnson sewed up another
Pro Stock crown, but they might be surprised to learn that Mike
Stryker, crew chief for Johnson's GM Goodwrench Pontiac Firebird,
was named the Parts America Mechanic of the Year for his efforts in
helping Johnson to a fourth Winston Pro Stock championship. ...
Mark Osborne, who beat Johnson in the Atlanta Nationals, will jump
from the seat of a Pro Stock car into that of a Pro Stock Truck in
the 1999 NHRA Winston Drag Racing Series, driving a Chevy S-10 Pro
Stock Truck for James Kessinger, owner of Kessinger Motorsports of
Lawrenceburg, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
