<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOLFE-LECTURE19-COX     11-18 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLFE-LECTURE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wolfe welcomed in Atlanta
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlantans welcomed Tom Wolfe warmly at Atlanta History
Center on Wednesday night, but not as warmly as he had feared.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``A Man in Full'' jokingly said that he half
expected to be greeted with a firebomb or at least a blowtorch
after several reviews of the novel portrayed him as a literary
Sherman burning Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The novel isn't pro-Atlanta, it isn't anti-Atlanta,'' Wolfe
told the predominantly white crowd of 500. ``I hope it is
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly ``Bo'' DuBose, president of the Atlanta History Center,
introduced Wolfe with these comments: ``If you look in the mirror
and you don't like what you see, don't blame the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were any disgruntled Atlantans in the audience, none
spoke up. Wolfe drew applause and laughter as he described a scene
at PlannersBanc with financially beleaguered protagonist Charlie
Croker at a ``workout'' session with bankers determined to recover
the half-billion dollars he owes them. And there was even more
laughter when Wolfe read a chapter set on Turpmtine, Croker's vast
South Georgia quail-shooting plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked afterward if he had shot any birds, Wolfe smiled and said
he had been relegated to the buckboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offered a chance to shoot, but I'm sure they were
relieved when I declined.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said he toured the plantations with friends Mack and Mary
Rose Taylor and was amazed at the luxuriousness he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living naively in the East, I thought the ultimate in
conspicuous consumption was flying a Gulfstream V private jet. And
since a lot of these plantations seemed to be owned by real estate
developers, I decided to use one in the novel. I originally set it
in New York, and had Charlie Croker flying back and forth to
Georgia, but that didn't work, so I moved it to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said he made a dozen trips to Atlanta for periods of five
or six days each beginning in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not consider myself an authority on Atlanta. Everything I
know about Atlanta I put in the book.''
</P>
<P>
   The author reiterated comments he made earlier this month about
the vibrancy of Atlanta as a setting for a novel. He cited the
multicultural area of Vietnamese, Asian and Hispanic immigrants
along Buford Highway as one example of how Atlanta is becoming an
international city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new and fascinating world,'' he said. ``Atlanta is one
of the most exciting cities in the country and a blueprint of what
cities will be like in the future _ edge cities where the
development occurs in places like Perimeter Mall and Cumberland
Mall. There should be 25 or 50 novels about Atlanta by now. What
are these novelists doing?''
</P>
<P>
   After the lecture and before a $600-a-plate black tie dinner to
benefit the Margaret Mitchell House, Wolfe fielded questions about
the book at a press conference and downplayed any hints of
controversy involving Mayor Bill Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   When one reporter asked if he was bothered by the fact that
Campbell had said he hadn't read the novel, Wolfe replied, ``That's
all right. There's not going to be a quiz.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe explained that the novel was not intended to be a roman a
clef.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is fictional, with as realistic a setting as I could
get,'' Wolfe said. ``Small details mean a lot. I was very upset
week before last when I learned something that was too late to put
in the book. I heard that one of the plantations I had visited had
a cage where a cougar was kept. It had a drain and all the cougar
did was eat, drink a lot of water and urinate. The cougar urine was
collected and spread around the perimeter of the plantation to keep
out the varmints such as foxes and other animals that killed quail.
That was a beautiful nugget of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe admitted that he has been surprised by all of the pre-and
post-publication hype surrounding the novel. Referring to a
question about Wolfe Watch _ a daily roundup of Tom Wolfe minutiae
in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution _ he laughed and said it made
him feel like the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a reporter at the New York Herald Tribune when the
Beatles first arrived in America in 1964,'' he said. ``All day long
we'd get these bulletins, `They're over Greenland now!' ...
`They're coming over Nova Scotia ...'
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Journal-Constitution, you made me feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe continues his march through Atlanta today, sharing a
morning meal with the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau and
lunch with members of the Piedmont Driving Club. At 7:30 p.m., he
heads to Borders Books &AMP; Music in Buckhead, where staffers are
bracing for a crowd of several thousand fans seeking to get an
autographed copy of ``A Man in Full.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Eldredge contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
