<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVIN: STREAK WAS GOOD, BUT WINNING MUCH BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A reluctant Michael Irvin walked out of the
Cowboys locker room yesterday and tried to set the record straight
about ``the streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Measuring his words carefully, the Cowboys receiver admitted his
disappointment over the no-catch performance Sunday in the team's
35-28 victory against the Arizona Cardinals. That performance
snapped his team-record streak of catching a pass in 117
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Although Irvin said he was ``OK'' with the end of the streak
because of the victory, he has mixed feelings about his diminishing
contributions to the offense because ``the personal battles are
important to all great players.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey shouldn't go out of his way to
talk to him about the end of the streak. Instead, he said Gailey
should remain focused on Sunday's matchup against the Seattle
Seahawks (5-5). Gailey said earlier this week, if he needed to, he
would talk to Irvin about his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan's concern needs to be Seattle, not Michael this or
Michael that,'' Irvin said. ``I don't want to make it an issue.
Maybe we can put it to rest. So we all can focus on Seattle. It's
behind us. We won the game. That's the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin has caught six passes in the past three games _ three
against the Philadelphia Eagles and New York Giants and none on
Sunday _ dropping him from fourth to 15th in the NFL, with 44
receptions.
</P>
<P>
   But Irvin said these frustrations pale in comparison to last
season's nightmarish 6-10 campaign, especially considering the
Cowboys (7-3) won the past three games and sit atop the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say it's nothing to me,'' said Irvin,
referring to losing the streak and not catching many passes.
``Because it is. If I said it's nothing, I'd be lying. But that's
still a Polaroid. The Mona Lisa is winning games. I'm not saying I
don't want to win the Polaroids. But I'm OK losing some of the
Polaroids. As long as I win the Mona Lisa. Now, I have a problem
with losing both. But I can deal with losing the Polaroids.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coaches say the biggest reason for Irvin's drop-off is
that opponents are going out of their way to take Irvin out of the
offense, forcing quarterback Troy Aikman to beat them with
receivers Billy Davis and Ernie Mills, who have combined for 49
receptions, 932 yards and six touchdowns this season.
</P>
<P>
   Although understanding of the strategy, Irvin believes he will
have to play a larger role if the Cowboys are to reach the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman agreed, but also said the Cowboys will throw the ball
where the defense dictates and won't force any passes to Irvin in
double coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receivers coach Dwain Painter said the coaches are doing
everything they can to make Irvin a playmaker again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has always been a big part of the game plan,'' Painter
said. ``We will continue working to get him the ball. The playbook
is very thick, and we keep adding yellow pages from the new plays.
We are definitely going to do more things to try to get him the
ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
