A8259 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-FISHING-OAKCREEK-     11-18 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-FISHING-OAKCREEK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWS ABOVE, TROUT BELOW  
 OAK CREEK RAIN BOWS LURK AMID RED ROCKS, FALL COLORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK CREEK, Ariz. - The Red Rock Country around Sedona is as much
a secret as the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, it seems, has either heard of it, seen pictures of it
or been there.
</P>
<P>
   New-Agers flock to the rock spires, expecting the planets or
something to line up just right, producing a religious rapture.
People with lots of money come to spend it. It's easy to pay $200 a
night at a Sedona resort.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Creek Canyon just to the north of the city is perhaps the
second-most-famous canyon in Arizona. With good reason.
</P>
<P>
   At the lower end of the canyon, the red formations are nothing
short of spectacular. As U.S. 89A rises through the canyon toward
Flagstaff, the reds turn more to whites as the limestone cap
becomes more evident.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Creek Canyon simply is one of the most beautiful places in
Arizona. It doesn't produce the awe of size, a quality that draws
millions to the Grand Canyon. It's more of a mix of Bryce and Zion
canyons in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   With all the ogling and hiking and rapturing, sometimes Oak
Creek itself doesn't get its just praise. It may be the most
beautiful creek in Arizona. It has everything from quiet stretches
on the flats to boulder-filled, tumbling stretches. And its
riparian vegetation is stunning, especially now that the leaves are
turning on its lower stretches.
</P>
<P>
   Slide Rock State Park midway through the canyon attracts huge
crowds to sun themselves or play in the water on the rock shelves.
</P>
<P>
   But we haven't talked about fishing. OK, anglers, think about
these beautiful surroundings plus catching a brown or rainbow
trout.
</P>
<P>
   Some big trout are taken from Oak Creek, but most are stockers
from the Arizona Game and Fish Department. The stream is stocked
twice a month until January, then resumes in March.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Thomas and Rick Verbalaitis, both fly-fisherman from
Phoenix, tackled the stream on Monday. Thomas is a veteran,
Verbalaitis a stranger to small-stream fly-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   A hike to the western fork of the creek can produce wild trout,
but Thomas and Verbalaitis decided to stay along the highway to
fish the main creek.
</P>
<P>
   At a local sporting goods store, they were told that the best
fishing had been toward the upper end of the creek. The operator
said to start just above Junipine Resort and head upstream.
</P>
<P>
   There is considerable private land along the stream. But finding
access points isn't a major problem. Several U.S. Forest Service
campgrounds offer access, as do spots where the road passes near
the stream. Except in the campgrounds, parking means a pullout from
the highway. Campgrounds charge a fee for gaining access.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't like fishing Canyon or some other smaller creeks,''
Thomas said. ``At Canyon, you can get access almost anywhere. And
it's more open water. You can make some long casts. Here, you make
short casts, and if you hook a fish, it has no place to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Verbalaitis fished a stretch of the creek where the
water tumbles over boulders into small pools. Thomas examined the
bottoms of submerged rocks to determine the aquatic trout food
available and began fishing with a No. 14 bead-head, squirrel-hair
nymph.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his casts were no more than 10 feet. He'd cast to the
top of a pool and allow the fly to float through. One trout struck
the fly, another the strike indicator.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting cold now, and the state's bumper crop of
grasshoppers has all but disappeared in higher country. Hopper
dry-fly patterns were good from spring through summer.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas switched to a No. 6 hopper pattern and got immediate
results. Both a brown and a rainbow struck the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Verbalaitis got two hard strikes on the hopper pattern before he
began having tackle problems.
</P>
<P>
   It was tranquil fishing. Pools were stacked one after another in
the boulders. The anglers moved slowly from pool to pool. The trout
weren't large, but they were there.
</P>
<P>
   The turning trees, the pines, the rock formations and the
crystal stream made this fishing a quality experience. The trout
only made it better. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached a 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-18-98 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
