<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBIN TO OFFENSIVE LINE STARTERS: STAY HEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The Cardinals got another scare on their
offensive line Wednesday when center  &UR; Aaron Graham woke up with
fluid on his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   He missed practice when sent for a magnetic resonance imaging
test. No structural damage was found. Graham is expected to play
Sunday when the Cardinals (5-5) visit the Washington Redskins
(2-8).
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals already have depth problems up front.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Matt Joyce, their first backup at both tackles and guards, had
a plate surgically implanted Tuesday into a broken bone in his
right hand. He'll be out at least two weeks. Rookie tackle  &UR; Anthony
Clement suffered a setback in his rehabilitation from surgery on a
herniated disk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starters have stayed intact since we got (left guard)
 &UR; Chris Dishman (strained neck) back, so that's encouraging,''
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said. ``But our depth is going down. That has
weakened us. I hope our starters stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was diagnosed with knee chondromalacia (roughness under
the knee that causes irritation) and is day-to-day. That he is not
seriously injured is the good news for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that with Graham out of Wednesday's workout,
 &UR; Allen
 &UR; DeGraffenreid was forced to spend most of his time as backup center
behind  &UR; Mike Devlin, who moved up to the first team.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches have to find a backup tackle and had hoped to give
DeGraffenreid, a tackle in college, a tryout Wednesday.
DeGraffenreid will get his audition this morning instead. If the
coaches like what they see, he'll become backup to  &UR; Lomas Brown on
the left side and
 &UR; James Dexter on the right.
</P>
<P>
   If the coaches aren't satisfied with DeGraffenreid's work at
tackle they plan to promote  &UR; Jon Clark from the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Clement initially projected to return for the Nov. 29 game at
Kansas City. Doctors won't clear him until he can work out without
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Clement on Wednesday said he believes he will make it back this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can run and do the drills, then I get so much pain I can't
continue,'' Clement said. ``I'll go easy for another week and then
we'll see.'' &QL; 
More injuries &QL; 
Two other key players _ starting outside linebacker  &UR; Tony McCombs
(toe) and backup middle linebacker/special teams contributor
 &UR; Mark &UR; Maddox (knee) _ did not practice.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs is listed as probable for the Washington game; Maddox
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the injuries, Tobin said the team's return to practice
after coming up short against Dallas went ``really well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players realize where we are,'' Tobin said. ``They were
bitterly disappointed after the Dallas game (a 35-28 loss). They're
young guys with better ability to bounce back than the coaches
sometimes.'' &QL; 
Volunteering information &QL; 
New practice-squad receiver  &UR; Andy McCullough, who was signed
Tuesday after quarterback  &UR; Corey Sauter was waived, said averaging
just under 20 yards a catch from quarterback  &UR; Peyton Manning last
season at Tennessee ``is something I can tell my kids, when I have
kids. How many players can say they caught passes from a
quarterback like that?''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough also will have some ugly stories for his kids about
the hazing of rookies by the Saints, which he suffered in training
camp before being waived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' McCullough said. ``I don't know what they
hit me with but I was hit by something. It just got out of hand. I
don't want to talk about it, but that's a chapter I can put in my
book someday.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mike Moten, a practice-squad lineman from Florida whose locker
is next to McCullough's, couldn't resist an opening jab at his new
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reminded him that we never lost to Tennessee,'' Moten said.
``I asked him to show me his SEC ring.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
