<HEADLINE>
TROJANS COULD TAKE THIS ONE, BY THE BYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The great debate at Spaulding and Howard Jones
fields this week is the impact of USC's bye last Saturday. While
UCLA was defeating Washington in Seattle, the Trojans were resting,
relaxing and spending extra time preparing for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, byes haven't done USC much good. They're 10-8-2
against UCLA after a bye, including the 1996 game, when they darted
to a 24-7 halftime lead before the Bruins rallied to win in double
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But this year may be different. The bye gave Trojans receiver R.
Jay Soward time to rest his sprained ankle, and it gave USC's
first-year coaches a chance to scrutinize video of the Bruins'
potent attack.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Dick Tomey is rooting for UCLA _ if the Bruins are
in the Fiesta Bowl, Arizona could play in the Rose _ but he doesn't
think the Bruins can overcome the bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very surprised,'' he said. ``It's a big advantage
to have a bye week late in the season against a rival who is
playing that week.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo believes the bye is an advantage for the
Trojans _ ``It's a huge thing in their favor'' _ but the players
aren't so sure. They believe bye weeks can ruin a team's momentum,
which the Trojans had after impressive victories over Washington
and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have a bye, sometimes it ruins our timing, sometimes
it doesn't,'' UCLA guard Andy Meyers said. ``Really, a bye is only
three days (off). I don't think it will affect the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pacific-10 teams are 6-2 following byes this season,
including Cal's victory over USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make the argument both ways,'' Bruins offensive tackle
Kris Farris said. ``I prefer the rest, but some people think it
makes you rusty. Last year, we had byes before the Arizona and
Washington games, and those were arguably the two best games we
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting a record: A capacity crowd of 90,000 is expected,
meaning UCLA will set a single-season attendance record and lead
the Pac-10 in attendance for the first time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The full house will boost UCLA's average to approximately
74,100. The school record is 69,812, set in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, Washington leads the league (71,356 per
game) but has no home games left.
</P>
<P>
   Scout stuff: Anticipation for the annual scout-team scrimmage
Wednesday afternoon was so high Toledo stopped practice to realign
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were thinking about the scrimmage, and I told them to
pick it up a little,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the intense, 15-minute scrimmage concluded without
a fight.
</P>
<P>
   More grades: UCLA's entering freshman football players (1994-97)
had an average high school grade-point average of 3.15 _ tops among
teams ranked in this week's Associated Press Top 25. Their average
SAT score (990) was second among top 25 teams, behind Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   The 3.15 and 990 numbers ranked second to Stanford in the
Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's four-year graduation rate for classes entering school
from 1988-91 was 57 percent _ fifth in the Pac-10 behind Stanford,
Oregon State, Oregon and USC.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Right tackle Brian Polak has not practiced this
week because of a sprained right knee and ankle. Asked if there's a
chance he won't play Saturday, Polak scoffed: ``No way.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Polak may not be fit to play every down. Josh Webb is
ready in reserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
