A8276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-N     11-18 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: MASS., R.I.)  
 ROLAND SAYS DEAL NEAR TO MOVE PATRIOTS TO HARTFORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, CONN. _ Gov. John Rowland of Connecticut said
Wednesday that only technicalities remained to be worked out in a
deal to build a stadium for the New England Patriots in downtown
Hartford. Connecticut's chances for luring the team seemed to
improve Wednesday afternoon when a Massachusetts legislator, who
had blocked money for a new stadium near Boston, said he would do
nothing to try to keep the team.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, a Patriots official said publicly for the
first time that a Hartford move could happen. ``There is not a deal
done, but I won't deny there's a possibility of it,'' said Stacey
James, the team's director of media relations.
</P>
<P>
   Officials involved in the negotiations said they hoped to hold a
celebratory ceremony with the Patriots owner, Robert Kraft, as soon
as Thursday. And a senior Democrat in the Connecticut legislature
said that Rowland, a Republican, had told him to expect an
announcement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rowland and other officials cautioned that the legal
and financial fine points were already taking longer than they had
expected and that objections from either side could derail the
project. ``Everything's still going in the right direction,''
Rowland said as he shuttled, tieless and in shirt sleeves, between
his office and the stadium war room he has set up at the Capitol.
``There's 18,000 little things that can go wrong. But we're all
very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, memories of previous failed deals with sports teams led
some local officials to preach caution. ``I'll believe it when I
see it,'' said Michael Peters, the mayor of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in a sign of optimism, Rowland delayed for a
second day his scheduled departure to New Orleans for the meeting
of the Republican Governors Association.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, Rowland summoned two dozen legislative and
business leaders to the executive residence, where he showed off
drawings of the proposed stadium and explained how it would be paid
for. The stadium would be part of a $350 million redevelopment
project that would include a convention center and a hotel, state
officials said. The state had already committed $300 million to
build a redevelopment project on the site, known as Adriaen's
Landing. Kraft would pay no money for the stadium, but would be
expected to help pay for another part of the project, possibly the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Thomas Finneran, speaker of the Massachusetts House,
was once again refusing to come to the aid of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes them special?'' Finneran asked at a news conference
outside his office. ``What makes them different? What makes them
entitled to a deal that goes beyond the bounds of anything that's
reasonable and quite frankly bullies and pillages the taxpayers?''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Senate has promised money to help build a new
stadium in Foxboro, where the Patriots now play, 30 miles south of
Boston. But a Massachusetts deal has been held up in the House, and
Finneran said he planned to do no more for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft proposed to spend $200 million for a new stadium near the
current one, and in return he wanted the state to pay $72 million
to buy land, build roads, and install lighting and other utility
lines. The Massachusetts Senate passed the package, but the House
would not approve more than $57 million, which killed the deal for
Kraft.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Greg Aiello, the National Football League's vice president of
public relations, said a change of playing site would require the
approval of 24 of the league's 31 clubs. ``The fact that the
Patriots would be staying in New England would be viewed as a
positive by the rest of the league,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A special session of the Connecticut Legislature would be called
next month to approve the project. ``We don't want to give
Massachusetts time to react,'' said a senior official involved in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   As sketched by legislative and administration officials, the
deal calls for a 65,000-seat open-air stadium with a grass surface.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would last for 30 years, and the stadium would be
paid for with the sale of bonds. State officials said that to pay
off the bonds, Kraft would pay the state a 10 percent cut of
tickets, concessions and parking.
</P>
</TEXT>
