<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-LAUTENBERG-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUTENBERG SAYS HE'LL SEEK 4TH TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Frank Lautenberg, a three-term New Jersey
Democrat who was widely thought to be considering retirement, said
Wednesday that he would run for re-election in 2000, mainly because
he believed that the Democrats would regain control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview from Jerusalem, where he is traveling on Senate
business, Lautenberg said the Democrats' unexpectedly strong
showing in the midterm elections had convinced him that his party
would pick up the five seats needed to take back the Senate in
2000. ``I think the Democrats have gained their credibility back,
despite the president's problems,'' he said. ``People believe we
know how to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, 74, said his decision to run again, which was first
reported in The Star-Ledger of Newark on Wednesday, was prompted by
reasoning that if the Democrats retake the Senate, he may have the
choice of becoming chairman of the Budget Committee or the
Environment and Public Works Committee, which has jurisdiction over
transportation programs, an area of interest to him.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg is the ranking minority member on the Budget
Committee, which would make him first in line to become chairman in
a Democratic-led Senate. And the Democrat who is ahead of him on
the Environment and Public Works Committee, Sen. Max Baucus of
Montana, may choose to become chairman of the Finance Committee
instead, Lautenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we've enjoyed in the past with legislative successes
could get even better,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   There is some skepticism among New Jersey politicians about
whether Lautenberg will really stay in the race. In both parties,
there is speculation that he is gearing up to do fund-raising just
so he can retire old campaign debts or that he made the
announcement simply to maintain his influence in the Senate and in
New Jersey political circles.
</P>
<P>
   But Lautenberg denied any such motivations. ``I've said I'm
going to run, and I intend to,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His announcement is likely to freeze campaign preparations by
several other Democrats, including Rep. Robert Menendez of Union
City, N.J., who has said that he would not challenge Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the senator's decision, some political analysts said,
some Republicans may abandon the idea of running for Senate and set
their sights on the 2001 race for governor instead. The Republicans
mentioned as possible Senate candidates include Jersey City Mayor
Bret Schundler, state Sen. William Gormley of Mays Landing and
Essex County Executive James Treffinger.
</P>
<P>
   In his first Senate campaign, in 1982, Lautenberg attacked his
Republican opponent, Rep. Millicent Fenwick, who was 72 at the
time, as being too old. Reminded of that Wednesday, the senator
said things were different in his case because he had seniority and
would not be struggling to find his way around the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty fit and aggressive,'' he said. ``My kids will tell
you I'm the one who tires them all out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
