A8282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SADDAM-NYT &LR;      11-18 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SADDAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UNSEATING SADDAM HUSSEIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Nov. 19: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weary of endless confrontations with Iraq, President Clinton,
Congress and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain are now rallying
around the idea of overthrowing Saddam Hussein. The thought is
certainly alluring. The installation of a democratic government in
Baghdad would probably eliminate the threat of Iraqi aggression.
Unfortunately, the only sure way to reach that goal is for American
troops to invade Iraq and capture Baghdad, a risky prospect few
Americans would support.
</P>
<P>
   Toppling foreign governments is no easy trick, and replacing
them with democratic leaders can be even harder. The American
record is not encouraging. The Central Intelligence Agency
engineered coups in Iran and Guatemala in the early 1950s,
consigning those two countries to years of corrupt, undemocratic
leadership. In Iraq, political disintegration and civil war could
easily follow a coup and prove as destabilizing to the Persian Gulf
region as the Saddam regime has.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is an especially difficult target for outside intervention
because opposition groups are weak and divided, state sanctions
against dissent are severe and Saddam has executed potential
antagonists in the Iraqi military and security services. A palace
coup seems unlikely, even in the face of sustained American aerial
bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is more likely to pursue a strategy of political and
military encirclement, depending heavily on Iraqi groups long
estranged from Baghdad. These include Kurdish guerrillas in the
north and Shiite forces in the south. One proposal is to assemble
and arm an opposition army under the protection of American
warplanes in a remote region of Iraq. The leaders of this group
would then establish an alternative Iraqi government that would be
recognized by Washington and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Even if feuding between opposition groups can be stilled long
enough to form such a united front, the next step would inevitably
involve a military offensive by this alliance against Baghdad. This
cannot hope to succeed without mechanized American ground forces
and air strikes. Absent that help, thousands of Iraqi rebel
soldiers would probably be slaughtered by Saddam's Republican
Guards.
</P>
<P>
   Other plans are no more appealing. The CIA has few reliable
friends in Baghdad and is in no position to encourage an
insurrection within Saddam's inner circle or to conduct a campaign
of sabotage against Iraqi utility plants and broadcast stations. A
CIA effort to kill the Iraqi leader would not only violate a
presidential ban on assassination but would also invite retaliation
against American leaders. Encouraging a popular rebellion by
beaming American radio broadcasts into Iraq would seem a futile
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and the Pentagon are well aware of all these
problems, and were openly skeptical about plotting against Saddam
until Clinton unexpectedly embraced the idea earlier this week. If
Clinton and members of Congress are serious about trying to
overthrow him, they need to level with the American people about
the potential financial and human costs. The project will not be
cheap or bloodless. Nor is it likely to succeed without an American
invasion and occupation of Iraq. Keeping Iraq isolated and
controlling its weapons of mass destruction through aggressive
inspection is an imperfect policy, but it is more practical than
anything else that has been proposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
