<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WILL NOT EASE CONSTRAINTS ON EMBASSY BOMB SUSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: All names are CQ) 
(mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge has refused to lift the highly
restrictive jail conditions placed on three defendants arrested
after the bombings of the U.S. embassies in Africa last August,
according to a court transcript made public Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Leonard Sand of U.S. District Court in Manhattan issued
his ruling after visiting the Metropolitan Correctional Center in
lower Manhattan on Tuesday, and making a personal inspection of the
secure unit where the three men have been held in virtual
isolation, with their communications to the outside world almost
entirely shut off.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the three men, arguing that the restrictions were
inhumane and unconstitutional, had asked Sand to lift them or at
least to grant their clients access to the jail's rooftop exercise
area and allow them to mingle with one other.
</P>
<P>
   But Sand, who had indicated earlier that he was concerned about
what he called ``the totality of all of these conditions,'' said he
had concluded after visiting the institution that the security
measures were legitimate, reasonable and taken in accord with due
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some of the precautions seem a little excessive, I think it
is because the objective is to accomplish something that is very
difficult to accomplish,'' Sand said, according to a transcript of
a hearing on Tuesday after his visit to the jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not paranoia on the government's part,'' the judge
added, citing the federal government's desire to prevent the
defendants from communicating with people outside the jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a realization,'' Sand said, ``based on past experience,
that there is a risk that persons who have engaged in conduct which
the defendants have been accused of engaging in have communicated
to their cohorts messages which have been detrimental to the
security and well-being of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In isolating the defendants, the government moved under a rarely
used federal rule that allows prison officials to limit an inmate's
contacts to prevent ``acts of violence and terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have not said publicly what concerns they may have
about the defendants' potential involvement in such acts, but the
rule allows the government to impose restrictions when officials
believe that there is ``a substantial risk'' that an inmate's
communications ``could result in death or serious bodily injury.''
</P>
<P>
   The three men have been indicted along with several others,
including Osama bin Laden, who prosecutors suspect was the
mastermind behind the embassy attacks and who remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said they are apprehensive about
potential acts of terrorism against Americans, particularly in
retaliation for the missile strikes that the United States launched
in August against bin Laden's camps in Afghanistan and a
pharmaceuticals plant in the Sudan, where officials suspected that
chemical weapons also were being manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   Sand agreed to a defense request to let the defendants call
their families three times a month each, instead of once a month.
</P>
<P>
   The three defendants include Mohammed Saddiq Odeh and Mohamed
Rashed Daoud al-'Owhali, who have each been charged with separate
counts of murder in the deaths of more than 200 people in the
attacks on the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   They have also been charged, along with the third man, Wadih el
Hage, in a broader conspiracy to kill Americans overseas. All three
men have pleaded not guilty to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Odeh and al-'Owhali declined to comment on the
ruling, while el Hage's lawyer did not reply to a message left with
his office requesting a comment. Prosecutors also refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers had argued in court Monday that the
restrictions should be lifted because they were causing
psychological damage to their clients and interfering with their
abilities to prepare their legal defense.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal prosecutor, Patrick Fitzgerald, argued against
removing the restrictions, including the one prohibiting the men
from the jail's roof.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the case of another suspected terrorist who, several
years ago, had tried, unsuccessfully, to escape from the roof.
</P>
</TEXT>
