<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK OFFICERS SENT TO TROUBLED PRECINCT SUE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than a year after Police Commissioner Howard
Safir announced he would put more black officers into the Brooklyn
police precinct where prosecutors charge that a Haitian immigrant
was beaten and sodomized, two black sergeants who were transferred
there have filed a federal suit alleging that the move violated
their civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The multimillion-dollar suit, filed Wednesday in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan, says the sergeants, Philip Tai and John
Robertson, suffered emotional distress and embarrassment after
their involuntary transfer to the 70th Precinct in Flatbush in
August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeants have not said they were mistreated by other
officers at the station house once they arrived there. Their
lawyer, Peter Blessinger, said the suit was filed because the
transfers were ordered solely because the sergeants are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other arenas, the police commissioner has said that race,
gender, religion and sexual orientation have no place in
assignments and transfers of police officers,'' he said. ``But
these sergeants were transferred based solely on race. If there's
nothing wrong with this, why not start transferring all the Jewish
officers to Williamsburg?''
</P>
<P>
   Blessinger said that several other black officers transferred
along with his clients to the 70th Precinct had filed similar
lawsuits against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector Michael Collins, a police spokesman, said that while
he could not comment on the specific suit, ``it is the police
commissioner's prerogative to transfer members of the service
according to the needs of the department.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir publicly announced his intent to transfer black officers,
particularly Haitian-Americans, to the 70th Precinct on Aug. 19,
1997, after four white officers were charged with attacking Abner
Louima in a police car after his arrest in a street brawl on Aug.
9, 1997, and later beating and sodomizing him at the station house.
The officers are facing federal civil rights charges in U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said he would transfer at least 10 minority officers into
the precinct, which was then 74 percent white, a move lauded at the
time as an effort by the department to establish a better rapport
with the large Caribbean community in Flatbush.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference then, the commissioner said: ``I think we
need to move some more Haitian police officers into the seven-o who
can relate to that portion of the community that is Haitian. We
need to move some additional African-American police officers into
the seven-o.''
</P>
<P>
   Those statements may have given Tai and Robertson the hook they
needed to sue the city, said Lance Liebman, a professor of labor
law at Columbia University Law School, noting that the Supreme
Court has ruled that personnel decisions must be race-neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the police commissioner decides that white officers are
particularly good on Madison Avenue and assigns them there,'' he
said, ``and that black officers are better in other places, my
prediction is that the court will say that this is not
satisfactory.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Noel Leader, a member of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who
Care, an organization of black officers, said he thought it was
good that the Police Department recognized that more black officers
were needed in minority communities, but added, ``The problem is
that they need to increase the number of African-American officers
across the board instead of just moving them around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
