<SLUG> BC-PYRAMID-FRAUD-PLEA-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUILTY PLEAS IN FRAUD AND PYRAMID SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Three officials of a small brokerage firm pleaded
guilty Wednesday to a securities fraud and pyramid scheme that
bilked more than 7,000 people of more than $120 million during a
10-year period.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, the three officials illegally sold
the municipal bonds and government securities of their clients and
kept the proceeds or used those bonds as collateral for personal
and commercial loans to benefit themselves and business ventures
that they had started.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they sold another type of security over and over
again in a pyramid scheme. These securities were backed by the
lease payments of government agencies on office equipment.
Officials illegally sold the same security several times, using the
proceeds of the most recent sales to make bogus interest payments
on the earlier sales, said Faith Hochberg, the U.S. attorney for
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money was used for major and minor purchases,
including a $21,000 backhoe, a new home, about $670,000 in men's
clothing for employees of the firm and $1 million payment to the
Resolution Trust Corp. for overcharges they made to the securities
account of the failed Elysian Federal Savings Bank in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas involved officials of the the firm, First
Interregional Equity Corp., based in Millburn, and its subsidiary,
First Interregional Advisors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the officials' illegal activities became clear
after March 1997, when agents from the FBI and IRS and Security and
Exchange Commission officers, armed with search warrants, raided
its offices and interrupted efforts by the conspirators to close
down the company and shred documents that outlined their
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendants lied to and stole from investors who were
family friends and elderly people, not nameless and faceless people
in the open market,'' Ms. Hochberg said. ``Every time they wanted
money for anything they stole it, and no customer was too close a
friend or too elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials who pleaded guilty were the firm's president,
Richard Goettlich, 42, of Mendham, who is the son of Herbert
Goettlich, the founder of First Interregional Equity Corp.; Anthony
Gianninoto, 50, of Califon, who was the company's treasurer and
controller; and Eileen Laine, 46, of Millburn, who supervised the
firm's data processing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, before U.S. District Court Judge Maryanne Trump
Barry, the three admitted to securities fraud, income tax evasion,
money laundering and conspiracy charges that carry penalties of up
to 20 years in prison. Sentencing is set for March 22. Ms. Hochberg
said the investigation was continuing to determine whether any of
the firm's other employees were involved in the complicated
schemes.
</P>
<P>
   The First Interregional case, in its use of unregistered
securities backed by equipment leasing contracts that are sold
multiple times, mirrors an even larger alleged pyramid scheme
involving the defunct Bennett Group of Syracuse, N.Y. That case is
slated to go to trial next month in the U.S. District Court for the
Southern District in Manhattan. That case, believed to be the
largest pyramid scheme in the country's history, is said to involve
more than $1 billion and 12,000 investors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As early as 1996, the SEC was investigating First Interregional,
said Andrew J. Geist, the associate regional director of the
agency, and they had been the object of fines and other sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the agency's on-premises examinations of First
Interregional in that year, according to court papers, Goettlich
had not only submitted false documentation but also bugged the
office and telephones being used by the examiners, all in an effort
to obstruct the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 5,400 people with claims against First Interregional
Equity Corp. for selling their securities have settled their
claims. But 1,750 people who had claims against First Interregional
Advisors Corp. for the leasing fraud have not seen any money yet.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Harrison Goldin, the bankruptcy trustee for First
Interregional Advisors Corp., said many of the investors they had
heard from were ``small, unsophisticated investors'' who were
solicited for the pyramid leasing scheme because they had done some
business in government securities with the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
