<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     11-18 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE scholars rarely if ever mentioned Weeb Ewbank's name when they
called the roll of great pro football coaches. But Weeb, short and
round with a face like Edmund Gwenn in Miracle on 34th Street, had
as many moments of pure bliss as any of them.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, he coached the Baltimore Colts, and Johnny Unitas,
when they outlasted the Giants in 1958, in the first sudden-death
game ever played. He coached the New York Jets, and Joe Namath,
when they shocked the Colts, and everyone else, in the third and
most historic of all Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The coach with the oddly lyrical name was too modest and decent
to gloat when his Jets won 16-7 over the team that had fired him a
few years earlier. In fact, what he had was a kind of out-of-body
experience.
</P>
<P>
   An injured Unitas had come off the Baltimore bench in the second
half, and he was passing on every down as the final seconds ticked
away, in a futile effort to rally the Colts. And on the New York
sideline, a few writers who had gathered for the countdown saw
Ewbank cup his hands and yell across the field, and across the
years:
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, John, no interceptions now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in time and space, Weeb wasn't aware that he was offering
encouragement to the quarterback of his former team, from an era
long gone.
</P>
<P>
   Weeb Ewbank died Tuesday, and it was a little odd to read the
accounts that said the cause of death was unknown. He was 91 and
had pushed the clock as far as it would go. He had retired from
coaching 25 years ago. In January, the Jets will celebrate the 30th
anniversary of their blockbuster Super Bowl win.
</P>
<P>
   Their coach made it to the Hall of Fame, even though his record
wouldn't impress you. He had one more victory than losses, 130 to
129, over 20 years. But he won championships in both leagues and
helped develop two of the great and distinctive quarterbacks the
game has known.
</P>
<P>
   Unitas was the classic model, with his crew cut and black
high-top shoes. Namath was a rebel in white sneakers, Broadway Joe,
with hair that was almost a national scandal, cascading down his
neck and over his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Joe and the Jets put the upstart AFL on equal footing with the
old guard, and paved the way for decades of incredible growth. They
were a raggedy bunch to have been the instruments of such change.
But they did it with Namath's showmanship and a cast of characters
that included 10 or 11 Texans, depending on how you counted them.
</P>
<P>
   The ``A'' list included John Elliott, Jim Hudson, Pete Lammons
and George Sauer, all of them ex-Longhorns. That group alone gave
the Jets a second identity: the University of Texas at Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were Don Maynard (Texas Western), Bake Turner (Texas
Tech), Curley Johnson (Houston), Winston Hill (Texas Southern),
Carl McAdams, who played at OU, and Sam Walton, no, not the one who
founded Wal-Mart. This Walton went to East Texas on a basketball
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott started out as a high jumper. Hill played tennis. And
those were the tackles.
</P>
<P>
   To Ewbank, Texans were larger than life, and faster. ``These
guys, these Texans,'' he would say, shaking his head. Maynard was
one of his favorites. Weeb called him ``The Human Crab,'' the kind
of guy ``who would kick in water,'' that being next to impossible
except for a really crabby guy.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard made it to the Hall of Fame as a wide receiver on legs a
sparrow would have rejected. ``Don told me he got hit on the leg
once,'' said Turner, ``and it swole up big as a broomstick.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Talamini qualified as Weeb's 11th Texan. The chunky
Kentuckian played eight years for the Oilers, was an All-Pro six
times and was traded when he asked to renegotiate his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ewbank tossed all those personalities into the blender and came
up with a championship team, which is what great coaches do. He was
not a comic, but his easy nature kept his players loose _ not that
Namath needed much help. The Colts had lost only one game all year.
They had a terror at tackle, Bubba Smith, and a driven young coach,
Don Shula.
</P>
<P>
   The story that defined the '69 Super Bowl had to do with
Namath's boast that the Jets would win, when almost no one thought
they could. On the morning of the game, Ewbank attended church in
Miami. Of course, church is where most coaches go to repent. But
after the services, as he moved through the receiving line, Weeb
complimented the minister on his sermon. Then, on a whim, he asked
a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me, Reverend,'' he said, ``who do you think will win the
big football game this afternoon?''
</P>
<P>
   According to Weeb, the minister cast his eyes upward and held
out his arms. With a gentle smile he said, ``Whomsoever the Lord
nameth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought right then,'' claimed Ewbank, ``that our chances
were pretty good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
