<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-18 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH19-COX     11-18 1568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starr report finds no impeachable offenses
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr will insist in
the House impeachment hearings today that President Clinton used
the ``machinery of government'' to obstruct justice by covering up
his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He will also argue that Clinton repeatedly threw up ``roadblocks
and hurdles'' that slowed the prosecutor's other investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But after recounting his allegations in the Lewinsky case, Starr
will disclose that he has found no evidence suggesting any
impeachable offenses in the FBI files controversy or the White
House travel office firings.
</P>
<P>
   He also will reveal that he had considered sending Congress an
impeachment referral in late 1997 on evidence that Clinton may have
known about an illegal government loan in the Whitewater land
development project that the the Clintons had invested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drafted a report,'' he said in his testimony, released
Wednesday evening. ``But we concluded that it would be inconsistent
with the statutory standard (of impeachment) because of the
difficulty of establishing the truth with a sufficient degree of
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   As Starr's prepared testimony for the House Judiciary
Committee's first hearing was made public Wednesday night, Rep.
Henry Hyde, chairman of the Judiciary Committee, announced that
Republicans would supboena four new witnesses in the investigation
of Clinton amid signs that the committee majority is now seeking to
broaden the inquiry far beyond the Lewinsky matter to show a larger
pattern of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's appearance before the committee will provide the nation
its first opportunity to hear the controversial prosecutor explain
the conduct of his investigation, which began four years ago and
has cost $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   And the text he delivered to Capitol Hill on Wednesday night
indicated that he will offer a strong defense of his office,
despite Democratic efforts to portray it as a ``partisan witch
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence suggests that the president repeatedly tried to
thwart the legal process in the Jones case and the grand jury
investigation,'' the Starr statement says. ``That is not a private
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence futher suggests that the president, in the course
of these efforts, misused his authority and power as president and
contravened his duty to faithfully execute the laws. That, too, is
not a private matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House dismissed Starr's statement as a repeat of his
earlier impeachament referral ``in new wrapping paper.'' ``The only
new thing in the statement is on page 46 and 47 in which he
declares the president is innocent in the FBI files and travel
office matters,'' it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Republican committee members had hoped that Starr's appearance
today would reinvigorate an impeachment process that many say has
lost its steam.
</P>
<P>
   But with more than two-thirds of the America saying they have
had enough of the Lewinsky scandal, Republicans outside the
Judiciary panel are leery of pushing forward with the impeachment
of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Hyde said his committee would take the inquiry
wherever ``the truth leads us'' and that his committee would ``talk
about anything that is credible and substantive'' including whether
Hubbell had accepted ``hush money'' in exchange for his silence.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said his committee would issue subpoenas for four new
witnesses to testify: Bruce Lindsey, a top presidential adviser and
longtime confidant of the president; Robert Bennett, the
president's personal attorney in the Paula Jones case; Daniel
Gecker, the former attorney for Kathleen Willey, a former White
House volunteer who claims the president made an unwanted sexual
advance on her in 1993; and Nathan Landow, a Maryland fund raiser
who committee investigators believe may have information about the
Willey case.
</P>
<P>
   The new witnesses were expected to be questioned first in
private depositions and the list may expand to include others.
Republicans would decide from the depositions whether to summon
them, or call additional witnesses, at public hearings. Gecker and
Landow could be called as early as next week, followed by Lindsey
and Bennett during the first week of December, GOP officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also showed a renewed interest in campaign
fund-raising allegations against the president. Hyde asked the
Justice Department for a prosecutor's memo that provided a detailed
argument for appointing an independent counsel to take over the
criminal investigation of fund-raising abuses in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is impeachment in search of a crime,'' said Jim Jordan,
the Democratic committee spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   The memo by Charles LaBella, former chief of the Justice
Department's campaign finance task force, contains grand jury
information which by law must be kept secret. But it is possible to
seek the release of the memo through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats viewed the new witnesses with suspicion and complained
that Hyde was attempting to violate attorney-client privilege by
seeking testimony from attorneys, not subjects of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinary that the chairman has unilaterally made
null and void 200 years of American jurisprudential precedence,''
Jordan said. ``The Democrats will not sit idly by and allow Mr.
Starr to offer up allegations and conspiracy theories for which he
has offered no evidence to this committee. Nor will he be permitted
to accomplish through innuendo or character assassination what he
has failed to prove in a court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing will open with statements from Hyde and Conyers,
followed by Starr's testimony. David Schippers, chief investigative
counsel, and his Democratic counterpoint, Abbe Lowell, will each be
given 30 minutes to address the committee. That will be followed by
questioning from members. The White House attorneys will be given
the final word, with 30 minutes to refute Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Starr will attempt to show that the president tried to keep
Lewinsky on his team by helping her get a job in New York after
realizing that she could become an adverse witness against the
president. For example, Starr will discuss how Vernon Jordan, the
president's close friend and golfing partner, interceded on
Lewinsky's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, knowing that a witness had just signed a false
affidavit, encouraged his friend to continue trying to find her a
job,'' Starr's testimony states. The White House has disputed this
version of the job placement for silence scheme, pointing out that
Lewinsky has testified that no one promised her a job for her
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``At bare minimum, the evidence suggests that the president's
job assistance stemmed from his desire to placate Ms. Lewinsky so
that she would not be tempted _ under the burden of an oath _ to
tell the truth about the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing other areas of his investigation, Starr noted that
``the pattern of obstruction of justice, false statements and
misuse of executive authority in the Lewinsky investigation did not
occur in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over the investigation of the Whitewater land deal
in August 1994, Starr said he has essentially become the
independent counsel of four other investigations: the suicide-death
of presidential aide Vincent Foster; the firing of the White House
Travel Office; misuse of FBI files; and the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Starr details on Hubbell's involvement with a
failed savings in loan in Arkansas known as the Madison Guaranty
Savings and Loan. Hubbell, a former law partner of Hillary Rodham
Clinton, did work for the savings and loan in 1985 and 1986 when he
and Clinton worked at the Rose Law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Starr contends that Rose may have assisted Madison in legal work
on a land development known as Castle Grande. the deal was
structured to avoid state banking regulations and involved
violations of federal criminal law, Starr states.
</P>
<P>
   As the criminal investigation was beginning in 1994, Starr said,
Hubbell received payments totalling nearly $550,000 from several
companies and individuals, many of whom were wealthy campaign
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the $550,000 was given to Mr. Hubbell for little or no
work,'' Starr said. ``This rush of generosity obviously gives rise
to an inference that the money was essentially a gift. And if it
was a gift, why was it given? This money was given despite the fact
that Mr. Hubbell was under criminal investigation for fraudulent
billing and was a key witness in the Madison Guaranty
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending his office, Starr states that his investigation has
resulted in the conviction of 14 people, including Hubbell;
Arkansas Governor Jim Guy Tucker and former Clinton business
partners Jim and Susan McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sum, this office has achieved a superb record in the courts
of law,'' stated Starr, who underlined the word law in an apparent
reference to the court of public opinion and spin doctors on
Capitol Hill. ``We go to court and not on the talk show circuit.
And our record shows that there is a bright line between courts and
polls. It leaves the polls to the politicians and spin doctors. We
are officers of the court who live in the world of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
