<HEADER>
A8305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOLFE-SCENE19-COX     11-18 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLFE-SCENE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sequins, Escada and gossip capture snazzy crowd
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton and Richard Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ These were, to say the least, Atlanta's heavy-hitters.
The 150 people who paid $600 a plate to attend a benefit dinner in
honor of author Tom Wolfe had one message for the man who lampoons
their like ``A Man in Full'' Essentially, they said: No hard
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd's attendance garnered a $90,000 donation toward the
refurbishment of the Margaret Mitchell House.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit-goers at the black tie affair _ including those
who've read some or all of ``A Man in Full'' _ were gracious hosts
to Wolfe, who says he's astounded at the feathers already ruffled.
They got all gussied up for their visitor from New York, they
laughed at his jokes, doted over his pretty wife (Sheila) and
toasted him roundly before the night was through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to a black-tie event in the middle of the week is not
one of my favorite pastimes,'' said CNN executive Pat Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she made a mad dash home to change from her
business clothes into a beaded black jacket by Zelda and a black
skirt she'd purchased in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Outfits worn by the women attending ranged from the elaborate to
elegant, matronly to modern. Standouts include: Star 94 morning
radio personality Vicki Locke, who wore a black sequined pantsuit;
chief Mitchell House fund-raiser Mary Rose Taylor wore an Escada
ensemble consisting of a gray velvet brocade jacket with olive
overtones, olive silk slacks, a semi-sheer blouse and olive
Ferragamo shoes; Atlanta Magazine publisher Susie Love wore a black
crepe suit with silver piping; philanthropist Melita Hayes wore a
black velvet cloak trimmed in multi-colored frizz that she
purchased at a wearable art fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to wear something else, but I changed my mind at
the last minute,'' Hayes said. ``It's a pretty snazzy crowd we've
got here; especially for a weeknight.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of snazzy: Wolfe stayed true to form by wearing an
off-white, double-breasted, three-piece suit with spectator shoes
that matched his blue-and-white poplin shirt and silk handkerchief.
His wife wore a pale blue, fringed, skirted suit by Christian Dior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is much more style-conscious than New York,'' observed
Wolfe, who deplores the sight of casually-dressed people in first
class airline seats. ``There's a little more propriety in dress
(here) than in New York, where all the barriers are down.''
</P>
<P>
   Although civility prevailed outwardly, some attendees were prone
to gossip amongst themselves at the lecture prior to the dinner.
Some of the comments overheard:
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I drove down to Charleston last weekend and we
read the book to each other as we went. We actually finished it. I
didn't know Charleston was such a drive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lunch with Wolfe and (developer) John Portman when he
was in town six years ago. After lunch, I was walking back with
John and he turns and says to me, 'I think I just met my match.'''
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``How far are you in the book? Answer: ``I read the
acknowledgements and had to take a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be me in the book. He's described me down to my
shoes. I have more hair though.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to love Georgia Tech football. I guess that alone was
worth giving him $30.''
</P>
<P>
   Man one: ``I'm 400 pages into it already. How far are you?'' Man
two: ``You're way ahead of me. Mine's back-ordered on Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like he wrote two books and stuck them together with
Scotch tape. It's pretty impausible that a real estate developer
would also own a food company. Charlie Croker, Please! People like
that don't exisit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could skip 10 pages and not miss the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense that Atlanta's real reaction to ``A Man in Full'' is
still in the offing was evoked by New York Times Atlanta bureau
chief Kevin Sack. Sack has been spending weeks shadowing Wolfe and
wondered how warmly he'd be received here. ``I don't think that the
city can judge whether it's an unkind portrayal or not until people
have had the chance to read the book.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
